{ This study will contain my personal annotations on the famous book by Bobby Fischer: "My 60 Memorable Games." You can use this study to learn from the games and view key variations. However, to get the most out of this study, I strongly suggest you follow along the actual book as well!

Throughout the annotations, Fischer's words will be put "in quotes," while my personal comments will be plain text. }
 *


[Event "New Jersey Open"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1957.09.02"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "James T Sherwin"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: French Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - James T Sherwin"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/ljj7OT6R"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Too little, too late" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 Nc6 4. g3 Nf6 (4... d5 5. Nbd2 Bd6 6. Bg2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nh4!? { "with chances for initiative" Fischer - Ivkov, 1966 }) (4... g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 f6 $10 { Having analyzed this position a lot (as I used to struggle with it as black myself), I feel like this is one of black's many tries for equality. }) 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nbd2 (7. e5 Nd5 8. Nbd2 f6 9. exf6 Nxf6 10. Re1 $16) 7... Rb8 (7... d5 8. Re1 b5 9. e5 Nd7 10. Nf1 b4 11. h4 a5 12. Bf4 a4 13. a3! $14 { Fischer's important improvement against Myagmarsuren, 1967. White won with a brilliant kingside attack and finished it with a queen sacrifice: https://lichess.org/study/YtBYXc3m/88AYWBz1 }) 8. Re1 d6 9. c3 b6!? (9... b5!? { "I had expected" } 10. d4 b4 11. e5 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. c4 $15 { "holds the advantage" yet stockfish disagrees and vastly prefers } (13. Ne4! bxc3 14. bxc3 Ndxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Nxe5 17. Bf4 f6 $10 { Although this looks much more like black is the slightly better one in this equal position })) 10. d4 { I've had this exact same position myself before as black, and b5 is always a key idea long term, but not before you optimize your pieces. } 10... Qc7? (10... Bb7 $10 { Qc7 next and black is fine. }) (10... cxd4 11. cxd4 d5 12. e5 Nd7 { Fischer prefers this line to the game, but this is clearly just a bad French after: } 13. Bf1! $16 { And white stops the c8 bishop from getting active. }) 11. e5?! { Rushed, but has the right idea. Black has to play precisely here to fully equalize. } (11. Nf1 Bb7? 12. d5! $16) 11... Nd5?? (11... dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 (12... Nd5!?) 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. h4 $10 { "with a bind" }) 12. exd6? (12. c4! Ndb4 13. exd6 Bxd6 14. Ne4 $16 { And white wins at least the exchange along the h2-b8 diagonal. } { [%cal Gc1f4,Gf4b8,Ge4d6] }) 12... Bxd6 13. Ne4 c4? { "releases pressure in the center and gives white a free hand to start operations on the kingside" } (13... Ba6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 $14) (13... cxd4?? 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. c4 Nf6 (15... Nc7 16. Bf4 Qd7 17. b4 $14) 16. Bf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4b8] }) 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Ng5 Nce7 (15... h6 16. Ne4 Qc7 $14 { A better try, but white's central control is king. }) 16. Qc2 Ng6 (16... f5? 17. Qe2 $18 { [%cal Ge2e6,Gg5e6] }) (16... g6 17. Ne4 $18 { These dark squared weaknesses... } { [%cal Ge4f6,Gc1h6] }) 17. h4 Nf6 { Apparently defending everything... } 18. Nxh7! { "tactics flow from a positionally superior game" } 18... Nxh7 (18... Kxh7?? 19. Bf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4b8,Gc2h7] }) 19. h5 Nh4! (19... Ne7?? 20. Bf4 $18) 20. Bf4 Qd8 21. gxh4 (21. Bxb8?? Nxg2 22. Kxg2 Bb7+ 23. f3 Qxb8 $19) 21... Rb7 22. h6! Qxh4 23. hxg7 Kxg7?? { "Suicidal. The last hope would have been" } (23... Rd8 24. Bg3 Qh6 25. Qe2 $16) 24. Re4 { [%cal Gf4e5,Ge4h4] } 24... Qh5 25. Re3! f5 26. Rh3 Qe8 27. Be5+ (27. Bh6+ Kg8 28. Bxf8 Qxf8 29. Bxb7 Bxb7 $18 { "I felt there was more in the offing" }) 27... Nf6 (27... Kg8?? 28. Rg3+ Kf7 29. Rg7#) 28. Qd2 { [%cal Gd2g5,Gg5h6] } 28... Kf7 29. Qg5 Qe7 30. Bxf6 Qxf6 31. Rh7+ Ke8 32. Qxf6 Rxh7 (32... Rxf6 33. Bxb7 Bxb7 34. Rxb7 $18 { Up a full rook }) 33. Bc6+ $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Rather than face the following crush: } 33... Bd7 34. Qxe6+ Kd8 35. Qd6 $18 { with mate to follow } 1-0


[Event "Portoroz Interzonal"]
[Site "Portoroz SLO"]
[Date "1958.08.16"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Bent Larsen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B77"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Dragon Variation, Yugoslav Attack, Czerniak Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Bent Larsen"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/9VZT1YpV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Slaying the dragon" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { The dragon! } 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. Bc4 { The main move: stopping ...d5 } (9. O-O-O d5 { In Fischer's day, this position was considered perfectly equal. Nowadays, people consider this a battleground for the entire variation. } 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bd4 e5 13. Bc5 $14) 9... Nxd4 (9... Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Bb3 Nxd4!? 12. Bxd4 b5 { The most topical line in the Yugoslav as of today. }) 10. Bxd4 Be6 11. Bb3 Qa5 (11... Bxb3? 12. cxb3!? { "Black cannot make any more progress against this particular pawn configuration." Just don't end up in an endgame and white's attack should win. }) 12. O-O-O b5 13. Kb1 { Always play Kb1 } 13... b4 14. Nd5 (14. Ne2?! Bxb3 15. cxb3 $10) (14. Bxe6! fxe6 15. Ne2 $14 { Shirov, A. - Santos Latasa, J., 1-0, World Rapid 2021, https://lichess.org/iN77ZnuC } { An improvement from Shirov in 2021. White keeps more pieces in the game for a stronger attack. }) 14... Bxd5 (14... Nxd5? 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. exd5 Bd7 $16 { The backward e pawn will be a target forever }) 15. Bxd5?! (15. exd5! Qb5 16. Rhe1 a5 17. Qe2 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 $10 { "Stronger. White abandons the attack and plays for pressure along the e-file instead as in Tal-Larsen, 1959" }) 15... Rac8? (15... Nxd5 16. Bxg7 Nc3+ 17. Bxc3 bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Rfc8 $10 { "After the game, Larsen explained he was playing for a win." This position would be a forced draw with the more active black rooks mattering more than the extra pawn. }) 16. Bb3! { "Pry open the h file. Sac, sac, mate!" } 16... Rc7 (16... Nd7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. h4 $14) 17. h4 Qb5 (17... h5 { "There's no satisfactory way to impede white's attack" and Fischer actually shows all of the following variations: } 18. g4! hxg4 (18... Rfc8 19. Rdg1 hxg4 20. h5 gxh5 21. fxg4 Nxe4 22. Qf4 e5 23. Qxe4 exd4 24. gxh5 Kh8 25. h6 Bf8 26. Rg7 $18) 19. h5 gxh5 (19... Nxh5 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. fxg4 Nf6 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Qh8#) 20. fxg4 hxg4 (20... Nxe4 21. Qe3 Bxd4 (21... Nf6 22. gxh5 e5 23. h6) 22. Qxe4 $18 { [%cal Gh1h5] }) 21. Rdg1 { Threatening Bxf6 and Rxg4! } 21... e5 22. Be3 Rd8 23. Bh6 $18 { [%cal Gd2g5] }) 18. h5 Rfc8 (18... gxh5 19. g4 hxg4 20. fxg4 Nxe4 21. Qh2 Ng5 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Rd5 $18) (18... Nxh5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. g4 Nf6 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. g5 Nh5 23. Rxh5 gxh5 24. g6! hxg6 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Rg1+ Qg5 28. Rxg5#) 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. g4 (20. Rh6!! { Stockfish shows another brilliant exchange sacrifice in order to pry open the black king's shelter. The threat is Rxg6 } { [%cal Rh6g6] } 20... Bxh6 (20... Kf8 21. Rdh1 $18) 21. Qxh6 { [%cal Gd1h1] } 21... Qh5 22. Qc1! $16 { Rh1 cannot be stopped, and the white attack continues. }) 20... a5 21. g5 Nh5 22. Rxh5 gxh5?? (22... Bxd4! 23. Qxd4 gxh5 24. g6 Qe5?? (24... Rc4! { The move Fischer and Larsen both missed. Black can equalize by giving back the exchange and allowing a perpetual: } 25. Qe3 fxg6 26. Qh6 Kf7 27. Qh7+ Kf6 $14 { Who could possibly play like this as black though? }) 25. gxf7+ Kh7 26. Qd3 $18 { "intending f4. Decisive" }) 23. g6! e5 (23... e6 24. gxf7+ Kxf7 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Rg1+ Kh7 27. Qg2 $18) 24. gxf7+ Kf8 25. Be3 d5 26. exd5 (26. Bxd5?? Rxc2 $10) 26... Rxf7 (26... a4 27. d6! axb3 28. dxc7 $18) 27. d6 Rf6 (27... Rd7 28. Bh6 $18) (27... Rxf3?? 28. d7 $18 { Mate cannot be stopped. } { [%cal Gd2d6] }) 28. Bg5 Qb7 29. Bxf6 Bxf6 30. d7 Rd8 31. Qd6+ $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (31. Qh6+ { Forced mate in 3 was better than the move Fischer played in the game! } 31... Bg7 (31... Ke7 32. Qh7+ Kf8 (32... Bg7 33. Qxg7#) 33. Qf7#) 32. Qd6#) 1-0


[Event "Portoroz Interzonal"]
[Site "Portoroz SLO"]
[Date "1958.08.27"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Tigran Vartanovich Petrosian"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A16"]
[Opening "English Opening: Anglo-Indian Defense, Queen's Knight Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Tigran Vartanovich Petrosian - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/kgI95ZmE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Bear Hug" }
1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O Nc6 7. d3 (7. d4 e5 $10 { A sideline in the KID }) 7... Nh5 8. d4 e5 9. d5 Ne7 10. e4 f5 (10... c5!?) 11. exf5 gxf5 12. Nxe5 { [%cal Gd1h5] } (12. Ng5! { This move would have in essence refuted black's entire setup... Getting in Ne6 and forcing Bxe6 is an idea that Kramnik pioneered starting in the 90s. } 12... Nf6 13. Qb3 h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 $16) 12... Nxg3 { Desperado } 13. hxg3 (13. fxg3 dxe5 { An interesting alternative. }) 13... Bxe5? (13... dxe5! $14 { "keeping a fluid pawn center, offers more play" - apparently he was unnecessarily worried about c5 and a potential passed d6 pawn. }) 14. f4 Bg7 15. Be3 Bd7 16. Bd4!? (16. Kf2 Kh8 17. Qd3 Ng8 18. Rh1 Rf7 19. Rae1 Re7 20. Bf3 $16 { Slow play is probably even better than in the game. While the bishop on g7 is a monster. It's also temporarily blocked by this knight on c3. Don't trade pieces when you have a space advantage! }) 16... Ng6 17. Re1? { "a careless transposition" } 17... Rf7? (17... Bxd4+ 18. Qxd4 h5 $10 { "h4 is unstoppable, so black can exchange his isolated h pawn for white's g pawn and the game would be dead equal." }) 18. Bf3 { Stopping ...h5 for good } 18... Qf8 19. Kf2 Re8 20. Rxe8 Qxe8 21. Bxg7 Rxg7 22. Qd4 b6 23. Rh1 (23. b4!? { "poses more immediate problems for black" } { [%cal Gc4c5] }) 23... a5 24. Nd1 Qf8 25. Ne3 (25. Bh5! { "the rook can't move because Bxg6 hxg6 allows a check on h8" }) 25... Rf7 26. b3 Qg7 27. Qxg7+ Kxg7 { Trading the queens makes it easier for black to play with less space } 28. a3 Rf8 { The e file is irrelevant for either rook because all of the infiltration squares are covered. } 29. Be2 Ne7 30. Bd3 h6 31. Rh5 (31. b4? axb4 32. axb4 Ra8 { White hands over the a file for no reason. }) 31... Be8 (31... Kg6?! 32. g4! Kg7 33. Bxf5) 32. Rh2 (32. Nxf5+? Nxf5 33. Rxf5 Rh8! { Black wins an exchange at least! } { [%cal Ge8g6] }) 32... Bd7 33. Rh1 Rh8 34. Nc2! { "Headed for an even stronger post on d4. I was amazed during the game. Each time Petrosian achieved a good position, he managed to maneuver into a better one." } 34... Kf6 35. Nd4 Kg7 36. Be2 Ng8 (36... Ra8 37. Bh5 { This infiltration doesn't actually get anywhere as long as black remains flexible. } 37... Rb8 38. Re1 Kf6 39. Ne6? c6 $10) 37. b4! { Now white doesn't allow the black rook to dominate the a file! } 37... Nf6 38. Bd3 (38. bxa5 Ne4+ 39. Kg2 bxa5 40. Rb1 Nc5 $10 { still no infiltration squares on this file either! }) 38... axb4 39. axb4 Kg6?! (39... Ra8! 40. Nxf5+ Bxf5 41. Bxf5 $10 { Unnoticed by Fischer or Petrosian: this endgame gives black a lot of drawing chances because of the activity of the black rook, and the closed nature on the queenside. If the kingside pawns get traded, it's an immediate draw. So the knight stays near the kingside and stops any infiltration. }) 40. Ra1 Ng4+ 41. Ke2 Re8+ 42. Kd2 Nf6 43. Ra6 Rb8 44. Ra7 Rc8 45. c5! bxc5 (45... Nxd5?? 46. c6! Be8 47. Bxf5+ $18) 46. bxc5 dxc5 47. Nf3 Kf7 48. Ne5+ Ke7 49. Nxd7 Nxd7 50. Bxf5 Rf8! 51. g4 (51. Bxd7 Kxd7 52. Ke3 Kd6 53. Ra6+ Kxd5 54. Rxh6 Re8+ 55. Kf3 c4 $10) 51... Kd6 { Fischer thinks that this was the losing move... Stockfish disagrees! } (51... Nf6 52. Be6 Nxd5! 53. Bxd5 Rxf4 $10 { Forcing a drawn endgame of B+R vs R. }) 52. Bxd7 Kxd7 53. Ke3 Re8+ 54. Kf3 Kd6 55. Ra6+ Kxd5 56. Rxh6 c4? (56... Re1! { Stopping Rh1 is necessary: } 57. f5 c4 58. f6 c3 59. Rh5+ Kd4 60. Rh2 Rf1+ 61. Rf2 Rxf2+ 62. Kxf2 c2 63. f7 c1=Q 64. f8=Q $10) 57. Rh1! (57. Rh7 { Petrosian believes that this move instead of Rh1 should win. Hilariously, Rh1 also won... } 57... c6? { Petrosian's line is flawed: } (57... Re1! 58. Rxc7 Rc1 59. g5 { This is the only way to make progress, but sadly our rook is too close to the black king: } 59... Kd6 60. Rc8 Kd7 61. Rc5 Kd6 $10 { So Petrosian's line was actually flawed as well! }) 58. Rd7+ Kc5 59. Rd1 c3 60. g5 Kc4 61. g6 c2 62. Rc1 Kc3 63. f5 Rg8 64. Kf4 Kd2 65. Rxc2+ Kxc2 66. Kg5 { [%cal Gf5f8] } 66... c5 67. f6 c4 68. f7 Rf8 69. g7 Rxf7 70. g8=Q $18) 57... c3 58. g5?? (58. f5 Kd4 (58... c5 59. Rc1! Kd4 60. f6 Kd3 61. g5 Kd2 62. Rxc3 Kxc3 63. g6! $18) 59. f6 c2 60. g5 Kc3 61. f7 Rd8 62. Ke4 Rd1 63. f8=Q Rxh1 64. Qf3+! Kd2 65. Qxh1 c1=Q 66. Qxc1+ Kxc1 67. g6 $18 { The actual way to win! No wonder both Fischer and Petrosian didn't evaluate this endgame correctly both during and after the game... }) 58... c5! 59. Rd1+ (59. f5 c2 60. f6 (60. Rc1 Re5 61. Kg4 Re2 62. g6 Ke5 $10) 60... Re5 61. Kf4 Ke6! $10) (59. Rc1 Kd4 60. g6 Re3+ 61. Kg4 Re2 62. f5 Rg2+ 63. Kh5 Ke5 $10 { The key idea in this endgame that both players missed: with the black rook on the 2nd rank, the c2 pawn is defended, so black has time to activate their king in order to deal with the two connected passed pawns on f5/g6. If the black king defends the c3 pawn instead, the black rook is in front of the passed pawns, they push forward anyway, gaining tempi on the rook. }) 59... Kc4 60. g6 c2 61. Rc1 Kd3 62. f5 Rg8! { Freezing the pawns again gains another valuable tempo. } 63. Kf4 Kd2 64. Rxc2+ Kxc2 65. Kg5 c4 66. f6 c3 67. f7 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 67... Rxg6+ 68. Kxg6 Kb2 69. f8=Q c2 { The queen vs c pawn endgame is always drawn due to stalemate tricks: } 70. Qb4+ Ka1 71. Qc3+ Kb1 72. Qb3+ Ka1! 73. Qxc2 $10 { Stalemate } 1/2-1/2


