{ "Tact and tactics" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. O-O (8. Bg5 O-O { The safest way to prevent the queenside bind: } (8... Nbd7 9. a4! b6?! { Trying to stop a5 here doesn't work: } (9... h6 10. Bh4 Qc7 11. a5 b5! 12. axb6 Nxb6 13. O-O O-O { Not optimal, but black has prevented a serious queenside bind. }) 10. Nd2! $16 { [%cal Gd2c4] }) 9. a4 Be6 10. a5 Nxe4! 11. Bxe7 Nxc3 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. Bxd6 Rd8 14. Bxb8 Nxe2 15. Kxe2 Raxb8 $10) 8... O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. f3 (10. a4 Qc7 11. a5 Nbd7 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bf5 14. c4 Bg6 15. Kh1 Rac8 16. Qd2 Qd8 17. Rac1 h6 18. f4 exf4 19. Bxf4 Bg5 $10 { Smyslov - Gligoric, 1962 }) 10... Qc7 (10... d5?! { "premature" } 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 14. Rfd1 $14) 11. Qe1 Nbd7 12. Rd1 b5 13. Rd2 (13. a3 Nb6 14. Bxb6 (14. Kh1 Nc4 15. Bc1 $17) 14... Qxb6+ 15. Kh1 $17) 13... Nb6 (13... b4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. Qf2 { "with play against white's backward c-pawn" } { [%csl Gc2][%cal Gc7c2,Gf5c2] }) 14. Qf2 Rab8 (14... Nc4! 15. Bxc4 bxc4 16. Bb6 (16. Nc1 Rab8 $17 { [%cal Gb8b2] }) 16... Qc8 17. Na5 Nd7! $17 { The knight on a5 is trapped if the b6 bishop retreats. Otherwise Rb8 wins at least a pawn. }) 15. Bxb6 (15. Na5?? d5! 16. exd5 Nbxd5 { [%cal Gc7a5] } 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Nb3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 a5 $19 { Black will kick away this knight and play Bc5 winning material. The queenside threats are too quick. } { [%cal Ga5a4] }) 15... Rxb6 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Bd7 18. f4 Bf6?! (18... f5 19. c3 Bf6?! 20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Nc5 $15 { The weakened e6 square is relevant here } { [%cal Gc5e6] }) (18... Rbb8! $17 { Objectively best. Black prepares a5-a4 again and is not worried about f5-f6 or fxe5 dxe5, activating black's pieces for him. }) 19. c3 Rbb8 20. fxe5 Bxe5 (20... dxe5? 21. d6! { "white has active play" }) 21. Nd4 g6 { [%cal Gd4f5,Gg6f5] } 22. a3 (22. Bf3 b4 { Not yet an actual concern: } 23. cxb4 Rxb4 24. Nc6 $10) 22... a5 23. Kh1?! (23. Bf3 { "should again be played. White starts drifting." }) 23... b4 24. cxb4 (24. axb4 axb4 25. c4 b3 $15 { [%csl Gc4] }) 24... axb4 25. Rc2 Qb6 26. Nc6 bxa3 27. Qxb6 Rxb6 28. bxa3 Ra8 29. Nxe5 (29. Ra2! Rb2 30. Rxb2 Bxb2 31. Bb5! { [%cal Ga3a4] } 31... Rxa3 32. Ne7+ Kf8 33. Nxg6+ hxg6 34. Bxd7 { "with a draw in view" }) 29... dxe5 30. Rc3 (30. Rc7 Rd6 $15 { [%cal Gd6d5,Ga8a3] }) 30... Rb2 (30... Kg7! { Most accurate. It gets out of the way of an eventual pin on the f7 pawn in combination with Bc4, and allows for possible defense with Rf6. Get your king up in the endgame! }) 31. Rc7 Bf5 32. g4 (32. Bc4 Rc2! 33. d6 Rxc4 34. Rxc4 Bd3 35. Rfc1 Bxc4 36. Rxc4 Rxa3 37. g4 Kg7 38. g5! $15 { White has a little hope here that at least the black king cannot win the d pawn immediately as in the game. }) 32... Be4+ 33. Bf3 Bd3 34. d6 (34. Rd1 e4 35. Bg2 Rd8 36. Rc5 Kg7! { Going for the d pawn. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Gd8d5] } 37. g5? (37. Kg1 f5 38. gxf5 gxf5 $17 { "The two center passed pawns should win" }) 37... h6 38. h4 hxg5 39. hxg5 Rh8+ 40. Kg1 Rh5 $17) 34... Rd8! 35. Re1 Rxd6 (35... e4! 36. Bxe4 Rb1! 37. Rxb1 Bxe4+ 38. Kg1 Bxb1 $19 { Najdorf chided Fischer after the game for missing this line! }) 36. Rxe5 (36. Re7 Rf6 37. Bd5 e4 38. Bxe4 Bxe4+ 39. R7xe4 Rff2 $19) 36... Rf6 37. Re3 Rxf3 38. Rxf3 Be4 39. Rxf7 Rf2! { Winning the rook - not just restoring material equality... } 40. Rf8+ Kg7 { 0-1 White resigns. } { The game could have continued like this: } 41. Rf7+ (41. Rf4 Bd5 $19 { And we will be able to win both rooks, trading into a trivially won endgame. }) 41... Kh6 $19 0-1


