{ "A small oversight" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Nf1 { One of the mainlines in the Chigorin, Ruy Lopez } 13... Rfe8 (13... Nc4 14. b3 Nb6 { More common } 15. Ne3 c4 16. Ba3 $10) 14. Ne3 { [%cal Ge3f5] } 14... g6 15. dxe5?! { "bares the hole on d5." Personally, this feels like you're letting black off the hook by releasing tension too quickly. } (15. Bd2!? Bf8 16. Rc1 Bg7 (16... Nc6? 17. d5 Na5 $16 { And the knight is out of play, while having lost time. }) 17. b4 exd4! (17... Nc6?? 18. Nd5! Nxd5 19. exd5 Ne7 20. dxc5 Nxd5 (20... dxc5 21. Be3 $16 { [%cal Ge3c5] }) 21. Bb3 Nf6 22. cxd6 Qxd6 23. Ng5! { [%cal Gg5f7,Gb3f7] } 23... Rf8 24. Be3 { [%cal Ge3c5] } 24... Qxd1 25. Rexd1 h6 26. Ne4 Nxe4 27. Rxd7 Rac8 28. c4 Ng5 $18 { Fischer-Rinaldo, 1957 }) 18. cxd4 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Nc4 20. Nxc4 bxc4 $10) 15... dxe5 16. Nh2 Rad8 17. Qf3 Be6 (17... h5?? 18. Qg3 Bf8 19. Nf5 $16 { [%cal Gc1g5] }) 18. Nhg4 Nxg4 19. hxg4! { The knight is bound for the d5 hole - let's not get distracted putting it on g4 instead! } 19... Qc6 20. g5 $146 (20. Qg3!? Nc4 21. Nf5! { A novelty from Fischer's era. White retains a slight advantage here. } 21... gxf5 22. gxf5+ Kh8 23. fxe6 Qxe6 $14) 20... Nc4 (20... Bxg5!? 21. Nd5 Bxc1 22. Nf6+ Kh8! (22... Kg7? 23. Nxe8+ $16 { [%cal Ge8g7] }) 23. Raxc1 (23. Nxe8 Bg5! 24. Nf6 $10 { "Black has good play for the exchange" }) 23... Rf8 24. Qg3 Qc7! 25. Qg5 Kg7 { "White can force a draw with Nh5+ or try for more with f4 or Re3." Engine only sees a draw. }) 21. Ng4 { The point of the novelty. White avoids the knight trade. } 21... Bxg4 22. Qxg4 { The d5 square is no longer of key importance. Now white can possibly attack on the h file. } 22... Nb6 { "To prevent a4!" Chapter 11 shows 22...f6: https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/mQxAqOWy#44 } 23. g3 c4 (23... Nd7?! 24. a4 b4? (24... c4!? 25. Kg2?! (25. axb5 axb5 26. Kg2 Nc5 $10) 25... b4 26. cxb4 Bxb4 27. Rh1 Nf8 $15 { Limiting the bishop pair ensures that white's caveman attack won't lead to a quick KO. }) 25. cxb4 cxb4 26. Bb3 $16 { [%cal Gb3g8] }) 24. Kg2 Nd7 25. Rh1 Nf8 26. b4 (26. b3 b4! 27. cxb4 c3! { Again the bishops have no open diagonals. }) 26... Qe6! (26... cxb3?! 27. Bxb3 { [%cal Gb3g8] } 27... Qxc3?? 28. Be3 Rd7 (28... Ba3 29. Rxh7 Nxh7 30. Rh1 Qc6 31. Qh4 Kf8 32. Qxh7 $18) 29. Rxh7! Nxh7 30. Qxd7 $18) (26... a5!? 27. a3 Ra8 $10) 27. Qe2 a5 28. bxa5 Qa6 29. Be3 Qxa5 30. a4 Ra8?! (30... Qxc3 31. axb5 $10) 31. axb5 Qxb5 32. Rhb1! { By not committing on the kingside, Fischer is able to reroute his pieces to the queenside and now begin to hunt for weaknesses everywhere, utilizing the bishop pair in an open position. } 32... Qc6 33. Rb6 Qc7 34. Rba6 Rxa6 35. Rxa6 Rc8 36. Qg4 (36. Ra7 Qd8 37. Qd1 { [%cal Ga7e7] } 37... Ne6 38. Qxd8+ Bxd8 39. f4! Rb8 { [%cal Gb8b2] } 40. Ra2 Kg7 41. Kf3 $16 { Most precise play. White retains winning chances once the position opens up. } { [%cal Ga2a5,Ga5e5] }) 36... Ne6 (36... Bc5 37. Bxc5 Qxc5 38. Ba4 Rc7! $10 { Practically forced. Black needs the resource Ra7 in order to trade off the active rook and equalize. } { [%cal Gc7a7] }) 37. Ba4 Rb8 38. Rc6 Qd8?? (38... Qd7! 39. Kh2 Rb1 40. Rb6 (40. Rxc4?? Qd3 41. Rc8+ Kg7 42. Qh4 Bxg5! 43. Bxg5 Nxg5 44. Qxg5 Qxe4! $19 { [%cal Gb1h1] }) 40... Qd3 41. Rxb1 Qxb1 42. Bd7 Nd8 $10 { [%cal Gb1d3] }) 39. Rxe6! Qc8 (39... fxe6? 40. Qxe6+ Kg7 41. Qxe5+ Kf7 42. Bc6 $18 { [%cal Gc6d5] }) 40. Bd7!! { 1-0 Black resigns. } { The small detail overlooked. Black resigned rather than deal with the discovery on the undefended queen: } 40... Qxd7 41. Rxg6+ $18 { [%cal Gg4d7] } 1-0


