{ "Pride goeth" }
1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. d5 Nbd7 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 a6?! { "This slow system has never been refuted" until modern times! } { Granda Zuniga, Julio E - Valdes, Leonardo, 1-0, Andorra op 30th, 2012, https://lichess.org/1c7VAgNL } (9... g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. h4 (11. Nd2 Nf4 12. O-O $10 { [%cal Gf4e2] }) 11... g4 $10 { Kramnik, Vladimir - Kasparov, Garry, 1-0, Linares 12th, 1994, https://lichess.org/IilTd9pb }) 10. Nd2 Qe8 11. g4!? Nh7 12. Qc2 Ng5? { [%cal Gg5h3,Gh3f4] } 13. h3! { Stopping Nh3 rerouting to f4! } 13... Nc5 14. O-O-O Bd7 15. f3 Na4 (15... b5! 16. b4 Nb7 $14) 16. Nxa4 Bxa4 17. b3 Bd7 18. Bf2 { Preparing h4 } 18... c5! 19. h4 (19. dxc6? bxc6 20. Nb1 d5! $17 { [%cal Gc8c1] }) 19... Nh7 20. Be3 b5 21. Nb1 (21. Bd3 { Fischer believed this would be better for white, as f5 is stopped, but actually black plays a quick queenside attack with the following: } 21... b4! 22. Nf1 a5 23. Qd2 a4 24. Bxh6 axb3 25. axb3 Ra3 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Bc2 $10) (21. h5 Ng5 (21... g5 22. a3! $16 { Black cannot break through on the queenside. But how does white break through on the kingside? }) 22. Bxg5 hxg5 23. a3! $16 { White will eventually break through on the kingside }) 21... f5 (21... Nf6!? 22. g5 (22. h5 g5 23. a3 $10) 22... Nh5 23. gxh6 Bf6 24. Rdg1 b4! $17) 22. gxf5 gxf5 23. exf5 Bxf5 24. Qd2 e4! 25. Rdg1?! (25. Bxh6? e3! { [%cal Gd2e3,Ge8e5] } 26. Bxe3 (26. Qxe3 Qe5 { [%cal Gg7h6] } 27. Qxe5?? Bxh6+! 28. Kb2 dxe5 $19) 26... Bxb1 27. Kxb1 Qe5 28. Rdg1 Qa1+ 29. Kc2 Qxa2+ 30. Kd1 Qxb3+ 31. Ke1 $13) (25. Rhg1! exf3 26. Bxh6 Ra7 27. Bxf3 Bxb1 28. Rde1 Qd8 29. Kxb1 Rxf3 30. Bxg7 Rxg7 31. Rxg7+ Kxg7 32. Qg2+ $16 { The difference between the two rook moves is revealed! Qg6 is impossible. } { [%cal Ge8g6] }) 25... exf3 26. Bxh6 (26. Rxg7+ Kxg7 27. Bxh6+ Kh8 28. Bxf8 Qxf8 29. Bxf3 Bxb1 30. Qc3+ Qf6 31. Qxf6+ Nxf6 32. Kxb1 $14) 26... Ra7 27. Bxg7 (27. Bxf3 Bxb1 28. Kxb1 Rxf3 29. Bxg7 Rxg7 30. Rxg7+ Kxg7 31. Qg2+ Qg6+! { The difference between Rhg1 and Rdg1 on move 25 is revealed! Black is completely winning in this line. }) 27... Rxg7 28. Rxg7+ Kxg7 29. Bd3?? (29. Qc3+ Qe5 30. Rg1+ Kh8 31. Qxe5+ dxe5 32. Bxf3 Bxb1 33. Kxb1 Rxf3 34. b4!! { The brilliant liquidating move that both sides missed! } 34... cxb4 (34... bxc4 35. bxc5 $10 { [%cal Gc5c8,Gd5d8] }) 35. c5 $10 { [%cal Gc5c8,Gd5d8] }) 29... bxc4 30. Rg1+ Kh8 31. Qc3+ (31. bxc4 f2 32. Rf1 Bxd3 33. Qxd3 Qe1+ 34. Kc2 Rf4 35. Nd2 Rd4 $19) 31... Qe5 32. Qxe5+ dxe5 33. Bxf5 Rxf5 34. bxc4 (34. d6 Nf6 35. Nd2 f2 36. Rf1 c3! 37. Nc4 e4 38. Ne3 Rf3 39. Nc4 Ng4 { [%cal Gg4f2] } 40. d7 Rd3 $18 { [%cal Gd3d8] }) 34... Nf6 35. Nd2 f2 36. Rh1 e4? (36... Rf4 37. Kd1 Nh5 38. Nf1 Re4 { [%cal Ge4e1] } 39. Nd2 Rd4! 40. Rf1 e4 41. Rxf2 e3 $19 { The computer line that seals the deal. }) 37. Kd1?? (37. Nf1 Ng4 38. Kd2 Rf3 39. d6 Rd3+ 40. Ke2 Rxd6 41. Ne3! $10 { White had a miraculous draw that Fischer didn't appreciate even in the post-mortem. }) 37... e3 38. Nf1 Re5 39. Ke2 Nh5 { Ng3 will break the blockade if the knight moves. Nf4 will break the blockade if the rook moves. } { [%cal Gh5g3,Gh5f4] } 40. Kf3 (40. Rh3?? Nf4+ { [%cal Gf4h3,Gf4e2] }) (40. Nxe3 Ng3+ 41. Kxf2 Nxh1+ 42. Kf3 Kg7 $19 { The engine line is equally hopeless. }) 40... e2! $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { Fischer finds the other way to break the blockade if the king moves. "One of the black pawns must reincarnate." } 0-1


