{ "Meat and potatoes" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 cxd4 (12... Rd8 13. Nf1 d5? { Keres' old way of playing. } 14. dxe5 Nxe4 (14... dxe4 15. N1d2! exf3 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qxf3 Be6 18. Ne4!) 15. Qe2 Bb7 16. Ne3 $18 { [%cal Ge3d5] }) 13. cxd4 Bb7?! (13... Nc6 14. Nb3 a5 15. Be3 a4 16. Nbd2 { Modern mainline }) 14. Nf1 (14. d5! { Blunting the bishop now that it has committed to b7 is the modern way to go: } { Shirov, Alexei - Timman, Jan H, 1-0, Belgrade Investbank, 1995, https://lichess.org/IKNthYAP }) 14... Rac8 15. Bd3 Nc6 (15... d5! $10) 16. Ne3 Rfe8? (16... Nxd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Nf5 Rfe8 19. Bg5! $14 { [%cal Ge7f8,Gg5e7] }) 17. Nf5? { "A superficial plan" } (17. d5! Nb4 18. Bb1 a5 { [%cal Gb7a6] } 19. Qe2 { [%cal Gf6d7] } 19... Qb6?? { [%csl Gd7] } (19... Qd7 20. a3 Na6 21. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3a6] } 21... Rc5 22. Rb1 $18 { b4 cannot be stopped, and the b pawn is falling. } { [%cal Gb2b4] }) 20. Nf5 Bf8 21. a3 Na6 22. Be3 $18 { The queen cannot maintain the defense of the b pawn. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ge2b5] }) 17... Bf8? (17... Nxd4 18. N3xd4 exd4 19. Bg5 Bd8 $14) 18. Bg5 Nd7 19. Rc1 Qb8 (19... exd4! { Black needs to play actively to get out of this pin - not as he does in the game. } 20. N3xd4 Qb6 21. Nxc6 Bxc6 22. Bb1 $16 { [%cal Gd1d6,Gf5d6] }) 20. Bb1 Nxd4 21. N3xd4 Rxc1 22. Bxc1 exd4 23. Nh6+! (23. Qxd4 Nc5 24. b4 Ne6 25. Qd3 { [%cal Gd3g3] } 25... g6 26. Nh6+ Bxh6 27. Bxh6 $16 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gd3c3,Gc3g7] }) 23... gxh6 24. Qg4+ Kh8 25. Qxd7 Bd5! { Rerouting to defend the weakened kingside. } 26. Qf5 Re5 27. Qf3 f5!? 28. Bf4 Re8 29. Qh5 Bxe4 30. f3 Bc6 31. Rc1! (31. Rxe8? Bxe8 32. Qxf5?? Bg6 $19) 31... Bd7 32. Bxh6 (32. Bxf5 Bxf5 33. Qxf5 $16 { An alternative line where white remains in the driver seat }) 32... Re6 33. Bxf8?! { Never trade. Now black's weakened kingside is that much harder to attack. } (33. Bf4?! Qe8! 34. Qh4 Rg6 $14) (33. Bd2! { Stopping any shenanigans on the e file for good. } 33... Qe8 34. Qxf5 Re1+ 35. Rxe1 $18 { [%cal Ge1e8] }) 33... Qxf8 { [%cal Gh5f5,Ge6e1] } 34. Qh4 (34. Bxf5?? Rh6 $18) 34... Qf6 (34... Qg7? 35. Rc7 Re2?? 36. Qd8+ Re8 37. Rxd7 Rxd8 38. Rxd8+ { [%cal Gg7g8] } 38... Qg8 39. Rxg8+ Kxg8 40. Bxf5 $18) 35. Qxf6+ Rxf6 36. Kf2?! { "Losing a vital tempo" } (36. Rc7! Be6 37. b3! $14 Bf7 38. Ra7 { Fischer thought this position was close to winning for white, but black does have a devious defense: } 38... f4! 39. Rxa6 Re6 { [%cal Gb1e4] } 40. Kf2 (40. Be4 Kg7 41. Bd5 Re3 42. Bxf7 Kxf7 43. Rxd6 d3 44. a4 $10) 40... Bg6 41. Bxg6 hxg6 42. a4 d3! { All rook endgames are drawn. } 43. axb5 d2 44. Ra1 Re3 45. Rd1 Rxb3 46. Rxd2 Rxb5 47. Rxd6 $10) 36... Kg7 37. Rc7 Rf7 38. Ke2 (38. Ra7 Bc8 $10) 38... f4 39. Ra7 Kf6?! (39... Bc8 40. Rxf7+ Kxf7 41. Bxh7 Be6 42. a3 Kg7 43. Bc2 Bc4+ 44. Kd2 $10) 40. Rxa6 Re7+ 41. Kf2 Be6?? { Activity is crucial in the endgame, but this is not the way to get it done. } (41... Bf5!! 42. Bxf5 Kxf5 43. Rxd6 Ke5 44. Rb6 d3 45. Rxb5+ Kd6! 46. Rb8 Re2+ 47. Kf1 Kc5 { White is up 2 pawns, but black's activity fully compensates. This was a better version of the game - keeping the bishops on the board benefits white, as the d1 queening square is easier to guard. }) 42. Rxd6 Ke5 43. Rc6 Bd5 44. Rh6 Rc7 45. Rh5+ Kd6 46. Rh6+ Ke5 47. Rh5+ (47. Rb6?? Rc1 48. Bxh7 Bc4 $15 { [%cal Gc1f1] }) 47... Kd6 48. Rf5? (48. b3! Rc1 49. Be4 Bxe4 50. fxe4 Rc2+ 51. Kf3 Rxa2 52. Rxb5 $18 { [%cal Gb3b7,Gb6b7] }) (48. Rxh7? Rc1 49. Bd3 Bc4 $10) 48... Rc1 49. Bd3 Rd1 (49... Bc4? 50. Rxf4! Bxd3 51. Rxd4+ $18 { [%cal Gd4d3] }) 50. Ke2 Rg1 51. Kf2 Rd1 52. Ke2 Rg1 53. Rg5 Bxa2 (53... Ra1!? 54. Bxh7 Bc4+ 55. Kd2 Rxa2 56. Kc2 b4 $10) 54. Bxb5 Rb1 55. Kd3 h6? (55... Rxb2 56. Kxd4 Bb1! $10 { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gb1h7] }) 56. Rh5 Rxb2 57. Kxd4 Rxg2 58. Rxh6+ { It's not that we're up a pawn. White's better here because white's pieces are all now more active than black's. However, exchanging bishops ends in a theoretically drawn position. Exchanging rooks is also drawn if black's king can stay on the f6 blockading square. } 58... Ke7 59. Ke4 Rg5 60. Ba6 Bf7?! (60... Bb1+! 61. Kxf4 Rf5+ 62. Kg4 Rf6 63. Rxf6 Kxf6 $10 { Keres' adjournment analysis... he forgot it over the board. }) 61. Bc8! (61. Kxf4 Rh5 $10 { The rook trade is forced. }) 61... Rg6 62. Rh7 Kf8 63. Bg4 Rg7 64. Rh6 Rg6 65. Rxg6 Bxg6+ 66. Kxf4 Kg7 67. Kg5! { Black could not reach the f6 square in time, so white is winning. } 67... Bd3 68. f4 Be4 69. h4 Bd3 70. h5 Be4 71. h6+ Kh8 72. Bf5 Bd5 73. Bg6 Be6 74. Kf6 Bc4 { [%csl Gh6,Gh8] } 75. Kg5 Be6 76. Bh5 Kh7 77. Bg4 Bc4 (77... Bxg4 78. Kxg4 Kxh6 79. Kf5 $18) 78. f5 Bf7 79. Bh5 Bc4 80. Bg6+ Kg8 (80... Kh8 81. f6 Ba2 82. Kf4 Bb3 83. Ke5 Ba2 84. Kd6 Bb3 85. Ke7 Ba2 86. Bf7 Bb1 87. Bh5 Ba2 88. Bg4 { [%cal Gg4e6] } 88... Bg8 89. Be6 Bh7 90. f7 $18) 81. f6 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


