{ "Something new" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 Bd7 7. Bb3 g6 8. f3 Na5 9. Bg5 Bg7 10. Qd2 h6 11. Be3 Rc8 12. O-O-O Nc4 13. Qe2 (13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. g4 { Simple and good. }) 13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 O-O 15. g4 Qa5? (15... Qb6! $10 { With the threat of e5 winning a piece, white has to waste further tempi... there is no attack. } { [%cal Ge7e5] }) 16. h4 (16. Nd5? Nxd5 17. exd5 $17 { Hilariously this is what Gligoric expected, completely forgetting about a kingside attack. Wow. Chess has improved a lot over the past 60 years. }) 16... e6 (16... h5 { An alternative approach to avoid white playing h5. } 17. g5 Ne8 18. f4! { Huebner liked this for black. Fischer liked this for white. But Kasparov shows the following line: } 18... Bg4?! (18... e5! { SF recommendation finds something nice here for black: } 19. Nde2 exf4 20. Nxf4 Kh7 (20... Bxc3?? 21. Nxg6! $16 { [%csl Gf8] }) 21. Ncd5 Qc5 22. Qxc5 dxc5 23. Ne7 Rd8 24. c3 $14) (18... e6?! 19. f5 exf5 20. exf5 Bxf5 21. Nxf5 Qxf5 22. Nd5 $16) 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. f5! Bxd1 21. Rxd1 Bxd4 (21... Kh7 22. fxg6+ fxg6 23. Ne6 $18) 22. Qxd4 Kh7 23. Nf4 $18 { [%cal Gb3f7,Gf4g6] }) 17. Nde2! { [%cal Ge2c3] } (17. g5!? { More to the point. Rxc3 is not yet a real issue. }) 17... Rc6? (17... Ne8 { Stops g5 and h5 because without the fork, there's no way to forceably open up the kingside files. }) 18. g5 hxg5 19. hxg5 Nh5 20. f4 Rfc8 21. Kb1 (21. f5?! exf5 22. Nd5?! Qxa2!! 23. Bxa2 Rxc2+ 24. Kb1 Rxb2+ $19 { Now kids, we know to always play Kb1. }) 21... Qb6 22. Qf3 Rc5 23. Qd3? (23. f5!? exf5 24. Rxh5 gxh5 25. Qxh5 Be6 26. g6! Qc7 27. Nd4 Bxb3 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. axb3 f4 30. Nf5 Bf6 31. g7+ Bxg7 32. Qxg7+ $18) (23. Rxh5! { The correct way forward. Fischer doesn't even discuss this move in his post-mortem... } 23... gxh5 24. Qxh5 Kf8 (24... d5 25. g6 fxg6 26. Qxg6 Rf8 27. exd5 exd5 28. Qg2 Rf7 29. Nxd5 $18 { There are many ways to win from here }) 25. f5 Ke8 26. Qh7 Bf8 27. g6 fxg6 28. fxg6 $18 { [%cal Gg6g7] }) 23... Bxc3? (23... a5 { Engines say this move gives black enough counterplay a la Anand - Carlsen, 2008. But white feels like they are still in the driver seat. }) 24. Nxc3 Nxf4 25. Qf3! Nh5 26. Rxh5 gxh5 27. Qxh5 { Always sacrifice the exchange. } 27... Be8 28. Qh6 (28. Rh1 Kf8 { No need to let the king run at all. }) 28... Rxc3 29. bxc3 Rxc3 (29... Qe3 30. Rh1 Qxc3 31. g6 Qg7 32. Qh2 { We still have a strong attack in every variation. }) 30. g6! (30. Rh1? Qd4 { [%cal Gd4h8] }) 30... fxg6 31. Rh1 Qd4 (31... Kf7 32. Qh7+ Kf6 33. Qh8+ Kg5 (33... Ke7 34. Rh7+ Bf7 35. Qxc3 $18) 34. Qh4#) 32. Qh7+ $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } (32. Bxe6+ { A faster mate! } 32... Bf7 33. Qh7+ Kf8 34. Qxf7#) 32... Kf8 33. Rf1+ Bf7 34. Qxf7# 1-0


