{ "Too many cooks" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 Qc7 (8... h6 9. Bh4 g5!? { The argentine gambit was revived by Fischer for a time for finding one specific move. Nowadays there's better alternatives... } 10. fxg5 Nfd7 11. Nxe6 (11. Qh5! { An improvement! } 11... Ne5 12. Bg3 $16 { Radulov, Ivan - Inkiov, Ventzislav, 1-0, BUL-ch, 1976, https://lichess.org/nyqo8God }) 11... fxe6 12. Qh5+ Kf8 13. Bb5 Rh7 $10 { Fischer's novelty }) 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. Be2!? (10. g4 { My personal recommendation }) 10... b5 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 (11... Bxf6? 12. Bxb5! { Once the bishop no longer defends d6, this sacrifice gets 3 pawns for the piece and a huge initiative. } 12... axb5 13. Ndxb5 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gb5d6,Gd1d6] }) 12. e5 Bb7 13. exf6!? { The novelty of the game - a queen sacrifice! } (13. Qg3?! dxe5 14. fxe5 Nd7 15. Qxg7 Qxe5 $17) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxf6 (14... Rc8 15. fxe7 Qxe7?? (15... b4 $10) 16. Nf5! $18) 15. Bxa8 d5 { Trapping the bishop. White will be down a rook+knight against queen+pawn unless white finds something immediate. } { [%csl Ga8] } (15... Qc4! { Not discussed by Fischer. } 16. Ne4 Qxa2! $19 { Probably Fischer didn't even consider this line as it's ridiculous to get this greedy while you have no development. }) 16. Bxd5 (16. Bc6+ Kf8 17. Nce2 Ke7 $10 { Another way to regain the piece. } { [%cal Gh8c8] }) 16... Bxd4! (16... Qxf4+? 17. Kb1 Bxd4 18. Bc6+! Ke7 19. Ne2 $16) 17. Rxd4 exd5 18. Nxd5 Qc5 19. Re1+ Kf8 20. c3 { "White seems to have fair prospects, but a queen is a queen!" } 20... h5! (20... g6 21. g4 (21. f5!? gxf5 $10) 21... Kg7 22. g5 h6 23. h4 hxg5 24. fxg5? (24. hxg5 $10 { Better for white, but lets the black rook out. }) 24... Rd8? (24... b4! { Not mentioned by Fischer. Black retains an edge by opening up the white king. }) 25. Nf6 Rxd4 26. Re8 Rd8 27. Rxd8 Qe3+ { Perpetual check }) 21. f5 (21. Nb4 { A Kotov recommendation that Fischer refuted: } 21... g6! 22. Nxa6 Qc6 $19 { [%csl Gg2,Ga6] }) (21. Re5 { A Zagoryansky recommendation } 21... g6 22. f5! { But Fischer continued the line to show black is doing great here: } 22... Kg7 23. f6+ Kh6! 24. g4 b4 $19) 21... Rh6! 22. f6?! (22. Red1!? Kg8 $15 { "Keres should just try to maintain the status quo" }) (22. Rde4?! Kg8 23. Re8+?? Kh7 24. Rd8 Rd6! $19 { "Neutralizes any threats" of doubling on the 8th rank } 25. Re5?? Qg1+! 26. Kc2 Rxd8 $19) (22. a3!? { The engine recommendation also maintains the status quo, stopping b4. }) 22... gxf6 23. Nf4 h4 24. Rd8+? { "Continuing the "attack" where there is none. The defensive Re2 was in order" } 24... Kg7 25. Ree8? Qg1+ 26. Kd2 Qf2+ 27. Ne2 Rg6! $19 { Black avoids any perpetual check and is now winning. } 28. g3 f5 (28... hxg3 29. h4 f5! $19) 29. Rg8+ Kf6 30. Rxg6+ fxg6 31. gxh4 Qxh2? (31... Qxh4! { "The winning method" } 32. Rd6+ Kf7 33. h3 Qh6+! { Forces the white king to some square where we can now safely take the h3 pawn and give a follow-up check. } (33... Qxh3?? 34. Rxg6 { [%cal Ge2f4,Gf4g6,Gf4h3] } 34... Kxg6 35. Nf4+ $18) 34. Kd1 Qxh3 35. Rxg6?? Qf1+ $19 { [%cal Gf7g6] }) 32. Rd4! { "Now Black has to win the game all over again" } 32... Qh1 33. Kc2 Ke5 (33... Qg2! 34. Kd2 a5 35. a3 Ke5 { Zugzwang! } 36. Ke1 Qh1+ 37. Kd2 Qb1! $19) 34. a4 (34. Nc1!? { Possibly a fortress } { [%cal Gc1d3] }) (34. Nf4?? Qh2+ 35. Kd1 Qxf4 36. Rxf4 Kxf4 $19 37. b3 Kg3 38. a4 f4 { [%cal Gd1e1,Ge1f1] } 39. axb5 axb5 40. c4 Kg2 41. c5 f3 42. c6 f2 43. c7 f1=Q+) 34... Qf1 35. Nc1 Qg2+ 36. Kb3?? (36. Kd1! bxa4 37. Nd3+ Kf6 38. Rxa4 a5 39. Rd4 $10 { Keres gets his fortress after all! }) 36... bxa4+! 37. Ka3 (37. Rxa4 Qd2 38. Na2 (38. Ra5+ Kf4 39. Na2 Kg4 $19 { [%cal Gf5f4,Gf4f3,Gf3f2,Gf2f1] }) 38... f4! $19) 37... Qc2 38. Nd3+ Kf6 39. Nc5 Qc1 (39... Qe2! 40. Rxa4 Qe7 { [%cal Ge7a3] } 41. b4 f4 $19 { The engine line. White is completely tied up on the queenside, and the f pawn is unstoppable. }) 40. Rxa4 Qe3 41. Nxa6 { The sealed move during the adjournment. Fischer had mainly focused instead on breaking this fortress: } (41. Rd4 f4 42. Nd3 f3 43. Kb3 Kg7 44. Ka3 Qe2 45. Kb3 Qd1+ 46. Kc4 (46. Ka3 a5 47. Ka2 a4 48. Nf2 Qb3+ 49. Ka1 a3 $19) 46... a5 47. Kb5 a4 48. Ka5 Qb3 49. Ka6 a3 50. bxa3 Qxa3+ 51. Kb5 Qxc3 $19) 41... f4 42. Rd4 Kf5! (42... f3 43. Nc5 f2 44. Ne4+ Qxe4 45. Rxe4 f1=Q $10 { A fortress. }) 43. Nb4 Qe7! { The same pin we saw in the engine line on move 39...Qe2. "Two passed pawns become irresistible" } 44. Kb3 Qxh4 45. Nd3 g5 46. c4 Qg3 47. c5 f3 48. Kc4 f2 49. Nxf2 Qxf2 50. c6 Qxb2 51. Kc5 Qc3+ 52. Kd5 g4 53. Rc4 Qe5# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } 0-1


