{ "Four queens" }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nf6 6. d3 (6. d4 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Qxd4 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. Be3 $10) 6... e6 7. g3 Bb4 8. Bd2 d4 9. Nb1 Bxd2+ (9... Qb6 { Keres and Benko both tried this move tempting white to weaken with b3 (the best move). But here the queen is misplaced so white will keep an edge: } 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bg2 a5 12. a3 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Qc5 14. Qd1 h5 $14) 10. Nxd2 e5 11. Bg2 c5 12. O-O Nc6 13. Qe2 Qe7 (13... g5!? { Played in an earlier round between Petrosian and Fischer: } 14. Nf3 (14. c3! { Fischer's new prep: } 14... Qe7 15. Nf3 h6 16. cxd4! Nxd4 (16... exd4 17. e5! O-O-O 18. Rfe1 $18) (16... cxd4 $14 { [%cal Gc1c8,Gb1b8] }) 17. Nxd4 cxd4 18. Rac1!) 14... h6 15. h4 Rg8 16. a3 Qe7 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Qd2 Nd7 19. c3 O-O-O 20. cxd4 exd4 $15) 14. f4 O-O-O 15. a3 Ne8 (15... Nd7 { "also playable" } 16. b4 f6 17. Nc4? b5! 18. Na5 Nxa5 19. bxa5 $15) 16. b4 cxb4? { [%cal Gf4e5] } (16... f6 17. b5 Na5 18. Nb3 Nxb3 19. cxb3 Kb8 20. a4 $10 { A safer choice from black }) 17. Nc4?? (17. axb4! Nc7 (17... Qxb4 18. Rfb1 Qe7 19. fxe5 { Fischer doesn't even mention this line, but here white gets a much more favorable version of the correct lines. }) 18. fxe5! { Black's center collapses, relative to the game. }) (17. fxe5 bxa3 18. Nc4 b5! { Fischer missed the precise follow-up here: } 19. Nxa3 Nc7 20. Qg4+ Qe6 $15) 17... f6 18. fxe5 fxe5 19. axb4 Nc7 20. Na5 Nb5! { Nxb4, opening up lines, is not the way to go. } 21. Nxc6 bxc6 22. Rf2 (22. Ra6 Kb7 23. Rfa1 Rhf8 { [%cal Ge2d1,Gd1b1,Gb1b3,Gb3c4] } (23... Rc8 24. c4 dxc3 { [%cal Gd3d4] } 25. Qa2 Kb8 26. Qc4 Rhd8) 24. c4 dxc3 25. Qa2 Kb8 26. Rxc6 Rc8 { [%cal Gc8c3] } 27. Qc4 Rxc6 28. Qxc6 Nd4 $19 { [%cal Gc3c2] }) 22... g6 { This b5 knight is a hero - stopping everything on the a file, b file, and c file. } { [%csl Gb5] } 23. h4 Kb7 24. h5 Qxb4!? (24... Rhf8 $17 25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Raf1 Qxb4! $17) 25. Rf7+ Kb6 26. Qf2 { Petrosian is really breaking the Yuspov mantra: "Thou shalt not allow counterplay" } 26... a5 27. c4 Nc3 28. Rf1? (28. Qf6!? Rdf8 (28... Qc5 29. Qg7! Ka6! { [%cal Gc5a7,Gf7a7] } 30. Ra7+ Qxa7 31. Rxa5+ Kxa5 32. Qxa7+ Kb4 33. Qb6+ Ka3 34. c5 { "White's c pawn is dangerous" }) 29. Qxe5 Rxf7 30. Qxh8 { "It's difficult for black in view of his exposed king" }) 28... a4! 29. Qf6 Qc5? (29... Qd6 30. Qg7 Rdg8 31. Rb7+ Kc5 $19) 30. Rxh7 Rdf8 31. Qxg6 Rxh7 32. Qxh7 Rxf1+ 33. Bxf1 a3 34. h6 a2 35. Qg8 a1=Q 36. h7 Qd6 37. h8=Q { Four queens on the board! } 37... Qa7?? (37... Qe1 38. Qd8+ (38. g4?? Ne2+ 39. Kg2 Qg3+ 40. Kh1 Qg1#) 38... Qxd8 39. Qxd8+ Ka6 { Perpetual check would be white's best here. Ne2+ is hard to stop. }) 38. g4! Kc5 39. Qf8 (39. g5 $16 { [%cal Gg5g6,Gg6g7,Gg7g8] }) 39... Qae7 40. Qa8 Kb4! { Slippery king! } 41. Qh2 Kb3! 42. Qa1 (42. c5! Qxc5!? 43. Qg8+ { There's no way to block this check conveniently, so white truly has some winning chances. } 43... Ka3 44. Qc2 $16 { [%cal Gc2b3,Gg8b3,Gg8a8] }) 42... Qa3! { Black is successful in trading off a queen which ensures his king is not getting mated. The resulting good knight vs bad bishop endgame is much less clear. } 43. Qxa3+ Kxa3 44. Qh6 Qf7 45. Kg2 Kb3 46. Qd2 Qh7 47. Kg3 Qxe4! 48. Qf2? (48. dxe4?? Nxe4+ 49. Kh4 Nxd2 50. g5 Nxf1 51. g6 d3 52. g7 d2 53. g8=Q d1=Q $19) 48... Qh1 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Fischer offered the draw, which was accepted. However, black has a nagging edge after blockading the g pawn and attempting to push through his own passed d pawn, as in this sample variation: } 49. Qf3 Qh6 50. Bg2? c5 51. Bf1 Nb1 52. Qf5 Qe3+ 53. Qf3?? Qxf3+ 54. Kxf3 Nd2+ 55. Ke2 Nxf1 56. Kxf1 e4! 57. dxe4 d3 58. Ke1 Kc2 $19 1/2-1/2


