{ "A very near miss" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Bb3 b5 (7... Nbd7 8. f4 Nc5 $10 { The modern way to handle this opening. }) 8. f4 (8. O-O { [%cal Gb8d7,Gb3e6] }) 8... b4 9. Na4 Nxe4 10. O-O g6? (10... Bb7 { Fischer believed this to be correct, but actually it's black who's about to die after: } 11. f5! e5 12. Ne6 fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. fxg6 $18) (10... Nf6 11. g4! { Novelty, that the engine finds. g5 is coming whether or not black wants it. }) 11. f5! gxf5 12. Nxf5! Rg8 13. Bd5!! Ra7 (13... exd5 14. Qxd5 Bxf5 15. Rxf5 Ra7 16. Qxe4+ Re7 17. Qxb4 Re2 18. g3 $18) 14. Bxe4 (14. Be3! exd5 15. Bxa7 Qg5 16. Ne3 $16) 14... exf5 15. Bxf5 Re7 16. Bxc8 Qxc8 17. Bf4? (17. c3! Qb7 18. Rf2 Rg6 19. Bf4 { An improvement on the game. }) (17. Qxd6?? Rxg2+ 18. Kxg2 Re2+ $19 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8d6] }) 17... Qc6! { [%cal Gc6a4,Gc6g2] } 18. Qf3 Qxa4! { Greedy, and correct! Tal finds an extremely tight defense: } (18... Qxf3 { The line Fischer expected. } 19. Rxf3 Re2 20. Rf2 Rxf2 21. Kxf2 { "White has a slight edge after a3 because of black's disconnected pawns." }) 19. Bxd6 Qc6 20. Bxb8 Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Qxb8 22. Qc6+?! (22. Rae1 { The move all annotators believed was winning for white. Even Tal was sure he was lost. However, Fischer finds the correct way forward: } 22... Kd8! { Avoiding Qxf7+ } 23. Rd1+! Kc7! 24. Qf4+! Kb7! 25. Rd6! Qc7 26. Qxb4+ Kc8! 27. Rxa6 Qb7! 28. Qxb7+ Kxb7 29. Raf6 Rg7 $10 { After a sequence of only moves, this should be drawn. The bishop is an equal match for all of white's pawns. }) 22... Rd7 23. Rae1+ Be7 (23... Kd8?? 24. Rxf7! Be7 25. Rfxe7 Rxe7 26. Rd1+! $18) 24. Rxf7? Kxf7 25. Qe6+ Kf8! (25... Kg7?? 26. Qxd7 $18 { [%cal Ge1e7] }) 26. Qxd7 (26. Rf1+?? Kg7 27. Rf7+ Kh8 28. Qxd7 Rd8!! { [%cal Gd8d1] } 29. Qg4 Qe5 $19 { [%cal Ge5e1,Ge5h8] }) 26... Qd6 27. Qb7 Rg6 { Now that black has consolidated, white is the one who must fight for the draw. } 28. c3 a5 29. Qc8+ (29. cxb4 Qxb4 30. Qf3+ Kg7 31. Qe2 Bd6 $19 { Fischer thought there was a draw here, but I don't see it. }) 29... Kg7 30. Qc4 Bd8 { [%csl Gh2][%cal Gd8c7,Gd6h2] } 31. cxb4 axb4 32. g3 (32. Qe4!? Bc7 33. Qe7+ Kg8 34. Qe8+ Qf8 35. Qe4 { Fischer thought he had another draw here. This one seems technically possible, but after: } 35... Rf6 36. Qg4+ Kh8 37. Qd4 Qd6 38. Re8+ Kg7 39. Qg4+ Rg6 $19 { Black finds a way to consolidate. }) 32... Qc6+ 33. Re4 Qxc4 34. Rxc4 Rb6! (34... Be7? 35. a3! bxa3 36. bxa3 Bxa3 $10) 35. Kg2 (35. a3? b3! { Keeping pawns on the board ensures that black retains winning chances! }) 35... Kf6 36. Kf3 Ke5 37. Ke3 Bg5+ 38. Ke2 Kd5 39. Kd3 Bf6 40. Rc2 Be5 41. Re2 Rf6 42. Rc2 Rf3+ 43. Ke2 Rf7 44. Kd3 Bd4 45. a3 (45. Re2!? Rf3+ 46. Kc2 Kc4 { Black makes continued progress. }) (45. b3!? Rf3+ 46. Ke2 Rf2+ 47. Kd3 Rxc2 48. Kxc2 Ke4 $19 { [%cal Ge4f3,Gf3g2,Gg2h2] }) 45... b3 46. Rc8 Bxb2 47. Rd8+ Kc6 48. Rb8 Rf3+ 49. Kc4 Rc3+! { Black keeps the b pawn! } 50. Kb4 Kc7 51. Rb5 Ba1 { [%cal Gb3b2,Gb2b1] } 52. a4 b2 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } 53. Kxc3 b1=Q+ $19 { This same idea is similar to the final position of chapter 32. } { [%cal Ga1c3] } 0-1


