{ "Theoretical scuffle" }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bg4 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nxd4 11. Bb5+ Nxb5 12. Qc6+ Ke7 13. Qxb5 Nxc3?! (13... Qd7 { The correct alternative, known to modern players as a safe drawing line for black: } 14. Nxd5+ Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 $10) 14. bxc3 Qd7 15. Rb1! $146 { Fischer's innovation that Benko had shown it to Fischer a few months before the game. "As horrible as white's pawn structure may be, black cannot exploit it because he'll be unable to develop his kingside normally. It's the little quirks like this that could make life difficult for a chess machine." Little did you know Fischer... little did you know. SF 13 finds this move Rb1 to be best. } 15... Rd8 (15... Qxb5 16. Rxb5 a6 17. Bg5+ f6 18. Rb7+ Kd6 19. Be3 Ke5! $10 { The point of a6. Neither player saw this modern line. }) 16. Be3 Qxb5 17. Rxb5 Rd7 18. Ke2! { "White will win the a pawn at leisure" } 18... f6 19. Rd1 Rxd1 20. Kxd1 Kd7 21. Rb8! Kc6 22. Bxa7 g5 23. a4 Bg7 24. Rb6+ Kd5 25. Rb7 Bf8 26. Rb8 { Black can't untangle, but Fischer didn't yet figure out how to get the most out of this bind. } 26... Bg7 27. Rb5+ Kc6 28. Rb6+ Kd5 29. a5 f5 30. Bb8 { [%cal Ga5a6,Ga6a7,Ga7a8] } 30... Rc8 31. a6 Rxc3 32. Rb5+ Kc4 (32... Kc6 33. Ra5 Bd4 { Euwe showed Fischer this position after the game and asked what his move would be: } 34. Be5?? (34. a7 Bxa7 35. Rxa7 $16 { But it still takes work to win. }) (34. Ke2 $16) 34... Rc5! 35. Ra4 (35. Rxc5+ Bxc5) 35... Rxe5 36. Rxd4 Ra5 $10) 33. Rb7 Bd4 34. Rc7+ Kd3 35. Rxc3+ Kxc3 (35... Bxc3 36. a7 $18) 36. Be5! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Why even let black sacrifice the bishop for the pawn? } 1-0


