{ "A queen for the king" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. e5 { Unnecessary. Better is to transpose to the mainlines with f3 or Nf3, etc } 5... Ne8 6. f4 d6 7. Be3 c5 8. dxc5 Nc6! 9. cxd6 exd6 10. Ne4 (10. exd6 Nxd6 11. c5 { [%cal Gd8e7] } 11... Qe8! 12. Qe2 (12. cxd6 Qxe3+ 13. Qe2 Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qxc3+ $19) 12... Nc4! $19) (10. Nf3 Bg4 11. Be2 { Modern theory. White maintains a partial center, but black has near full compensation. }) 10... Bf5! 11. Ng3? (11. Nxd6 Nxd6 12. Qxd6 Qxd6 13. exd6 Bxb2 14. Rd1 Nb4! { [%cal Gf5c2] } 15. Kf2! { "Black is better but white has drawing resources" } (15. Nf3 Bc2 16. Rd2 Bc3 $15)) 11... Be6 12. Nf3 Qc7 (12... dxe5 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14. Bc5 exf4 { With a winning endgame for black. "I wanted to fracture him in the middle game." }) 13. Qb1 (13. Be2 dxe5 14. Bc5 Qa5+ 15. b4 Nxb4 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 17. O-O exf4 18. Ne4 Bf5 $19 { 2 pawns for the exchange and extremely active pieces, black is winning. } { [%csl Ga1][%cal Gf5e4,Gg7a1] }) (13. Qc2 dxe5 14. f5 gxf5 15. Nxf5 Nb4 16. Qb3 (16. Qb1 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Nd6 18. Qb1 Nxc4 19. Ng5 f5 20. Ne6 Qc6 21. Bxc4 Qxc4 22. Nxf8 Rxf8 $19 { [%cal Gb4c2,Gc4f1] }) 16... Bxf5 17. Qxb4 Nf6 $17 { [%cal Gf6g4] }) 13... dxe5 14. f5 e4! 15. fxe6 (15. Qxe4 gxf5 16. Nxf5?? (16. Qf4 Qxf4 17. Bxf4 Bxb2 $17) 16... Qa5+ $19 { [%cal Ga5f5] }) 15... exf3 16. gxf3 f5 { [%cal Gf5f4] } 17. f4 Nf6 18. Be2 Rfe8 19. Kf2 Rxe6 20. Re1 Rae8 21. Bf3 { I love how all of both player's moves recently have been so logical, and yet black's beastly lead in development naturally led to a brilliant tactic that Fischer saw and his opponent did not. Tactics rise from a superior position, indeed. } { [%cal Ge6e3] } 21... Rxe3! 22. Rxe3 Rxe3 23. Kxe3 Qxf4+!! { 0-1 White resigns. } 24. Kxf4 (24. Kf2 Ng4+ 25. Kg2 Ne3+ 26. Kf2 Nd4 27. Qh1 Ng4+ 28. Kg2 Qxf3+ 29. Kh3 Nf2+ 30. Kh4 Bf6#) 24... Bh6# 0-1


