{ "No holds barred" }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Ba5?! { This line in the Winawer doesn't have a great reputation, but Tal is Tal. } 6. b4! cxd4 7. Qg4 Ne7 (7... dxc3?? 8. Qxg7 $18 { [%cal Gg7h8] }) 8. bxa5 dxc3 9. Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qxh7 Nbc6 11. Nf3 { Shirov, Alexei - Akopian, Vladimir, 1-0, Merida, 2000, https://lichess.org/AYyrO46i } 11... Qc7 12. Bb5?! { Maybe a bit harsh to call this dubious, but there is a better alternative: } (12. Bf4! Bd7 13. a6! { Not yet discovered in Fischer's time } (13. Be2? O-O-O 14. Qd3?! (14. O-O Nf5 15. Bd3 { White should allow the perpetual "check" on his queen. } { [%cal Gg8h8,Gd8g8,Gd8f8] }) 14... Qxa5 15. O-O Rg4 16. Bg3 Nf5 $15 { Unzicker - Duckstein, 1959 }) 13... b6 14. Bg3 O-O-O 15. Bd3 Rh8 16. Qxf7 Rdf8 17. Qg7 Rhg8 18. Qh6 $18) 12... Bd7 13. O-O { [%cal Gb5c6,Gd7c6] } 13... O-O-O (13... Nxe5! { Petrosian's suggestion after the game is actually correct. } 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 16. Qd3 Qf5! { A move Fischer didn't even consider } 17. Rd1 Qxd3 18. Rxd3 e5 19. Rxc3 $15 { While white is up a pawn, it's a doubled a pawn. White's pieces lack a lot of harmony and these central pawns are quite annoying. }) 14. Bg5? (14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Qxf7 d4 16. Qxe6+ Kb8 17. Ng5 { Fischer thought this was completely over for black, but Stockfish finds the following idea: } 17... Ba4! 18. Ra2?? (18. Qf6 Rgf8 19. Qg7 Rg8 20. Qf6 $10 { With a perpetual on the queen. White cannot allow Bxc2 where there are two connected passed pawns running. Black cannot allow Ne6 winning a clean exchange. }) 18... Bb5! 19. Rd1 Bc4 $19 { [%cal Gc4a2,Gc4e6] }) (14. Re1 $14 { Overprotecting e5 and preparing Fischer's move is best. }) 14... Nxe5! { "Settling off a dazzling array of fireworks" } 15. Nxe5 Bxb5 (15... Qxe5 16. Bxe7 Rh8 17. Rfe1 (17. Rae1 Qb8 18. Bxd7+ Kxd7 19. Bd6!! $10 { A brilliant defense that Fischer missed. } { [%cal Gh7f7] }) 17... Qxe1+ 18. Rxe1 Rxh7 19. Bxd8 Kxd8 20. Bxd7 Kxd7 21. Re3 d4 22. Re4 e5 23. Rxe5 $10 { "bails white out" }) 16. Nxf7 Bxf1 (16... Rdf8 17. Rfb1 Bc6 18. Nd6+! Qxd6 19. Qxe7 Qxe7 20. Bxe7 Rf5 $15 { After d4, it's clear that black's bishop is awesome and white's bishop is not in this opposite color bishop ending. With the rooks still on the board, black can still play for a win. }) 17. Nxd8 Rxg5 18. Nxe6 Rxg2+ 19. Kh1 (19. Kxf1? Rxh2! 20. Qf7 Rh1+ 21. Kg2 Qh2+ 22. Kf3 $10 { You don't want to have this position against Tal... }) 19... Qe5 (19... Qc4 20. Qxe7 Rg1+!! 21. Kxg1 Qg4+ 22. Kxf1 Qc4+ $10 { With an amazing perpetual on the shelter-less king. }) 20. Rxf1 Qxe6 21. Kxg2 Qg4+ $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


