{ "Asking for trouble" }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. a4 (7. Qg4 Qc7 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 { The modern way to play this position. } 10. Qd3!? { A Huschenbeth novelty that should not be underestimated } 10... Qxe5+ 11. Ne2 dxc3 $14) 7... Qc7 (7... Nbc6 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bd7 10. Bb5!? { The modern main line. Fischer doesn't mention this, so presumably it was unknown in the 1960s. }) 8. Nf3 b6 9. Bb5+! Bd7 10. Bd3 { Stops black's main idea of eliminating white's good bishop with Ba6 } 10... Nbc6 11. O-O c4 { Fischer doesn't comment on this move, but it's positionally very questionable. Black really wants to be playing Na5->c4, putting the knight on a beautiful outpost. By depriving himself of this option and releasing central tension, black gives white the go ahead for a direct kingside assault, making O-O impossible. } (11... O-O?? 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Ng5+ Kg6 (13... Kg8 14. Qh5 $18 { [%cal Gh5h7] }) 14. h4 $18 { Greek gifts are in the air... } { [%cal Gh4h5] }) (11... h6! 12. Re1 { The main way to play in modern times. }) 12. Be2 f6 13. Ba3! fxe5 (13... O-O 14. Re1 { Black should look for a safer game. }) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Re1 N7c6?? (15... N5c6 16. Ng5 O-O! (16... h6?? 17. Bh5+ g6 18. Bxg6+ Nxg6 19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. Rxe6+ Kf7 21. Qxd5 $18) 17. Bg4 { [%cal Gg4e6,Gg5e6,Ge1e6] } 17... Rf6 $14 { The engine line. Black sacrifices the exchange to avoid the alternative kingside crushes. } (17... Qf4!? 18. Bxe6+ Bxe6 19. Nxe6 Qxf2+ 20. Kh1 Rf6 (20... Rf5 { [%cal Gf5d5] } 21. Re2! Qh4 22. Nd4 Rh5 (22... Nxd4? 23. Bxe7 Nxe2 24. Bxh4 $18) 23. Nf3 $18) 21. Nc7 { [%cal Ga3e7,Ge1e7] } 21... Raf8 (21... Nf5!? { The engine line is still lost, but requires precise play from both players } 22. Qxd5+ Kh8 23. Re6!! { Defending against Ng3+ hxg3 Rh6# } 23... Ne3 24. Rxf6! Qxf6 25. Qd2! { [%cal Gd2c3,Gd2c2,Gd2f2] } 25... Nf1 26. Qd6 Rc8 27. Qxf6 gxf6 28. Rxf1 Rxc7 29. Rxf6 $18) 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Qxd5+ Kh8 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. Qxc6 $18)) 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. f4?? (17. Bh5+! { A rare tactical oversight from Fischer. This simple win isn't even mentioned in the book at all. } 17... g6 18. Qd4 { [%cal Gd4h8] } 18... gxh5 19. Rxe5 O-O-O 20. a5! $18) 17... Nc6 18. Bg4 O-O-O 19. Bxe6 Bxe6 20. Rxe6 Rd7 21. f5 { Threatening f6 "which gets a grip on the f file" } { [%cal Gf5f6] } 21... Nd8 22. Re3 Qf4 23. Rf3 (23. Qe2 Qxf5 24. Rf1 Qg6 { Perhaps sacrificing the f pawn in order to fully coordinate was an easier way forward. }) 23... Qe4 24. a5! Nc6?! (24... b5!? 25. a6! { Preventing Rb7 to defend the b5 pawn. } { [%cal Gd7b7] } 25... Re8 26. Qb1! { White crashes through on the queenside immediately. } { [%cal Gb1b5] }) 25. axb6 axb6 26. Qb1! { White is already crashing through on the a and b files. } 26... Kc7 (26... Kb7?? 27. Bc5 $18 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gb1b6] }) (26... Rb7 27. Bc1! $18 { [%cal Gc1e3,Ge3b6] }) 27. Bc1!! { The winning move. The bishop puts on its best impression of a billiard ball in order to reposition to the correct diagonals. } { [%cal Gc1f4,Gc1e3,Ge3b6,Gf4b8] } 27... Qe1+ (27... Ne5 28. Bf4 Re8 29. Qb5 $18 { A crush similar to the game. } { [%cal Rb5d7,Rb5b6,Ra1a7,Rf4c7] }) 28. Rf1 Qxc3 29. Bf4+ Kb7 30. Qb5 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%cal Gb5a6] } 1-0


