{ "Sheer pyrotechnics" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 (4... exd5 { "leads to the kind of wood pushing that always bored me." Tell that to more than a century of d4-d5 players, Fischer. }) 5. Nf3 c5 6. e3 (6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O $10 { Tal made some improvement in this line in the 60s, so I don't believe Fischer was well equipped to go down this road just yet. }) 6... Nc6 7. Bd3 (7. Bc4 cxd4 8. exd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 a6 $10 (10... b6? 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bb5 $14 { Botvinnik-Alekhine, 1938 had white pushing for an advantage. })) 7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a3 cxd4 10. exd4 $10 { We reach a tabiya IQP position. White must play for the initiative, using the space advantage afforded by the d4 pawn. If black can stop any kingside attack and trade pieces, this d4 pawn is more of a weakness than a strength. } 10... Nf6 11. Bc2 { [%cal Gd1d3,Gd3h7] } 11... b6 12. Qd3 Bb7 13. Bg5 g6 14. Rfe1 Re8? (14... Rc8! 15. h4 Na5 16. Ne5 Nd5 17. Nxd5?? Qxd5 $17 { [%cal Gb7g2] }) 15. h4! Rc8 16. Rac1 (16. Ba4! { [%cal Ga4e8] } 16... a6 17. b4 b5 18. Bb3 { d5 is going to hurt black. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } 18... Qd6 19. Rad1 $16 { This knight on c6 is horribly misplaced. }) 16... Nd5 17. Ne4 f5 18. Nc3 Bxg5 19. Nxg5! (19. hxg5 Nxc3 20. bxc3 Na5 $10 { Fischer committed this "ugly positional move" f5 in order to create a alight squared blockade on the now hanging pawns. } { [%cal Ga5c4,Gc8c4,Gd8d5] }) 19... Nf4 (19... Nxc3 20. bxc3 Na5 21. Ba4 Re7 22. Qg3 { [%cal Gh4h5,Gg3e5,Ge1e6,Gg5e6] } 22... Bd5 23. Nh3 $16 { The same ideas don't work. } { [%cal Gh3f4,Gf4d5,Gf4e6,Gh4h5] }) 20. Qe3 Qxd4 21. Nb5!! { White threatens to win an exchange with Nd6. } 21... Qxe3 22. fxe3 Nxg2! 23. Kxg2 Nd4+ 24. Be4 Bxe4+ 25. Nxe4 Nxb5 26. Nf6+ Kf7 27. Nxe8 Rxe8 28. a4! { A necessary final move in order to infiltrate on the 7th and actually prove the rook is better than the knight+2 pawns. } 28... Nd6 29. Rc7+ Kf6 (29... Re7 30. Rec1 $16 a5 31. R1c6 $18 { [%cal Ge7c7,Gc6c7,Gf7f6,Gc7c6] }) 30. Rec1! { Keeping control of the c file is more important than pawn grabbing! } (30. Rxa7? Rc8 $10 { [%cal Gc8c2] }) (30. Rxh7? Rc8 $10) 30... h6 31. Rxa7 Ne4 32. Ra6 Rd8! { Activate the pieces! } 33. Rc2?? { Ironic how the first move that makes our pieces less active in order to defend one of the pawns immediately loses the majority of the advantage. } (33. Rxb6 Rd2+ 34. Kg1 g5 35. hxg5+ hxg5 36. Rcc6 g4 37. Rxe6+ Kg5 38. Rh6 f4 { Fischer believed this was a drawn position. Stockfish disagrees: } 39. exf4+ Kxf4 40. Rb4 Kg3 (40... Kf3 41. Rb3+ Kf4 42. Rh8 Nc5 (42... g3 43. Rh4+ Ke5 44. Rb5+ $18) 43. Rf8+! $18) 41. Rb3+ Kf4 42. Rh8 Ng5 { [%cal Gg5f3] } 43. Rf8+ $18 { White is just in time to prevent black from creating mate threats. }) 33... Rd3 (33... Rd6! $10 { Possibly a missed opportunity. Fischer doesn't even mention this idea. }) 34. Rxb6 Rxe3 35. a5 f4 36. Rf2?? (36. Kf1 f3 37. Rb4! { Preventing this mating idea of Rd3, white can push on for a win! } 37... f2 38. Rxf2+ Nxf2 39. Kxf2 { and with our rook behind the passed a pawn, white should still be winning. } 39... Re5 40. Ra4 Rb5 41. b4! $18 { [%cal Ga5a6,Ga6a7,Ga7a8] }) (36. a6?? f3+ 37. Kf1 Rd3! { [%cal Gd3d1] } 38. Ke1 Re3+ 39. Kf1 Rd3 $10) 36... Nxf2 37. Kxf2 Re4 38. b4 { Similar to the other position reached after 36. Kf1, but white's rook is misplaced and black has the extra f pawn! Now the position is simply drawn with best play, but white is the one pushing... } 38... Re3 39. a6 Ra3 40. Rc6?? (40. b5 g5 41. hxg5+ hxg5 42. Rb8 g4 43. Rf8+ Ke5 44. b6 Ra2+ $10 (44... Rxa6?? 45. b7! $18)) 40... g5! 41. hxg5+ hxg5 42. b5 g4 43. Rc8 Kf5 44. b6 g3+! 45. Ke1 Ra1+ 46. Ke2 g2 47. Rf8+ Ke4 48. Rxf4+ Kxf4 49. b7 g1=Q (49... Ke4!! 50. b8=Q Ra2+ 51. Ke1 g1=Q#) 50. b8=Q+ Kf5 51. Qf8+ Ke4 52. Qa8+ Kd4 53. Qd8+ Kc4 54. Qd3+ Kc5 55. Qc3+ Kd6 56. Qd2+ Ke5 57. Qb2+ Kf5 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } 58. Qb5+ Kf6 59. Qb2+ e5 $19 { No more checks, and black emerges up a full rook. } 0-1


