{ "A peccable draw" }
1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Nd3 (10. Be3 f5 11. f3 f4 12. Bf2 { The fully approved modern way forward. This was well tested at the time too, but some middlegame subtleties hadn't been discovered. }) 10... f5 11. exf5 (11. f3 f4! { Starts the kingside attack and white no longer has the key bishop defending and attacking, from f2. } { [%cal Gc1d2,Gd2e1,Ge1f2] } 12. Bd2 g5 13. b4 { [%cal Gc4c5] }) 11... Nxf5?! { Fischer wants to play Nd4, but giving up the e4 square is something taught to every Russian schoolboy. } { [%cal Gf5d4] } (11... gxf5 12. f4 e4 13. Ne1 $10 { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3] }) 12. f3 Nd4 13. Ne4 b6 { Playing "against white's thematic break c5" } 14. Bg5 (14. b4?! a5! { [%csl Ga5] } 15. b5 { The queenside remains closed. } (15. bxa5 Rxa5 { [%cal Gc4c5,Gb6c5,Gd6c5] } 16. Bd2 Ra3! { The queenside remains closed! })) (14. Bd2?! a5!) 14... Qe8 15. Bd2 (15. Qd2 { Avoids the h6 move, kicking us back, but after: } 15... a5 { white cannot play b4 (and therefore c5) because we can no longer move the a pawn due to Nb3, forking. }) 15... a5! { Stopping b4 means that black gets all the fun on the kingside, whereas white gets nothing going on the queenside. } 16. Re1 Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 h6 18. b3 g5 19. a3 Qg6 20. b4 Nf6 21. bxa5? (21. Ndf2 { Best according to Fischer, but his follow-up was lackluster: } { [%cal Gg5g4] } 21... Nh5 (21... Nxe4! 22. Nxe4 (22. fxe4 g4!) 22... g4!) 22. bxa5 Nf4 23. Qd1 bxa5 24. Rc1 Bd7 25. g4 h5 26. h3 hxg4 27. hxg4 Kf7 28. Bxf4 gxf4 29. c5 { White can break through immediately on the queenside and center in this variation. }) 21... g4 22. Ndf2 (22. axb6?? gxf3 23. Qxf3 (23. Nxf6+ Bxf6 24. Qxf3 e4 25. Qxe4 Bf5 $19) 23... Nxe4 24. Qxe4 Bf5 $19 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gf5d3] }) 22... gxf3 23. Qxf3 Nh5 (23... Nxd5? 24. Qg3 $10) 24. Qe3 bxa5 { "Finally" recapturing! } 25. Rac1 Bf5 26. c5 (26. g3?? Rf7 $17 { [%cal Ga8f8] }) 26... Nf4 27. Qg3?? (27. Qf3! Nxd5 28. cxd6 cxd6 29. Rc6! Rad8 30. Qb3! { White has sufficient counterplay here for equality. }) 27... Bxe4 28. Rxe4 Qxe4! 29. Nxe4 Ne2+ 30. Kh1 Nxg3+ 31. hxg3 Ra6 { Stopping an eventual Rc6 infiltration. } 32. cxd6 cxd6 33. a4 { White has a firm light square blockade. Black will only be able to make progress if we can break through somewhere. } { [%csl Ge4,Gd5,Ge6,Gf5,Gg4,Gh5,Gc6,Gb5][%cal Gg3g4] } 33... Rf7 34. g4 Bf8 35. Kh2 Kh7 36. Rc8! { Stopping the f7 rook from infiltratign on the b file. } 36... Rb6 (36... Rf1 37. Rc6! Rxc6 38. dxc6 Be7 39. c7 Rf8 40. Bxa5 d5! $19 { Probably Fischer didn't want to allow this "counterplay" but once the light squared blockade is destroyed, black has to be winning with the extra exchange. }) 37. Ra8 (37. Bxa5?? Ra6! { [%cal Ga6a4] }) 37... Rb3 { Fischer finally infiltrates. } 38. Bxa5 Rf4 { [%cal Gf4g4,Gf4e4] } (38... Re3 39. Ng3 Rd3! { Another way forward. } { [%cal Gd3d5] }) 39. Bc7 Rxe4 40. Rxf8 Rd3! 41. Rf6 Rxg4 42. Rxd6 Rg7? (42... Rd2! 43. Rd7+ Kg6 44. Bxe5 Rgxg2+ 45. Kh3 Rg5 $19 { If everything gets traded, the h pawn is now passed. } { [%cal Gg5d5,Gd2d5] } 46. Bf4 Rd3+ 47. Kh2 Rf5 { [%cal Gf5f2,Gd3d1] }) 43. Rc6! Rxd5 (43... Rd2?? 44. Bxe5 Rgxg2+ 45. Kh3 Rg5 46. Bf4 Rd3+ 47. Kh2 Rh5+ 48. Kg2 Rdxd5 49. Rc7+! Kg6 50. Rc6+! $10) 44. Rc2 e4 45. a5 Rd3 46. Bf4 Rf7 47. g3 e3?? { The drawing move! } { [%cal Ge3e2,Ge2e1,Gf7e7] } (47... Ra3 48. Rc6 Re7 49. Rxh6+ Kg7 50. Rb6 (50. Ra6 e3 { [%cal Ge3e2,Ge2e1] } 51. Bd6 Ra2+ 52. Kh3 Re4 $19 { [%cal Ge3e2,Ge2e1] }) 50... Rxa5 $17 { Black retains winning chances by keeping this passed pawn alive. The e pawn ends up being more important than the h pawn. }) 48. Rc1 (48. Kg2 { An easy draw that Reshevsky didn't have time to see. } 48... Rxf4? 49. Rc7+! $10 (49. gxf4?? Rd2+ 50. Rxd2 exd2 $19 { [%cal Gd2d1] })) 48... Re7 49. Re1 Ra3 50. Re2 Kg6 51. Kg2 (51. Bd6!? Rd7 52. Bxa3 Rd2 53. Rg2!! e2 54. Bb4 e1=Q 55. Bxd2 $10 { And now white has to hold this insane fortress (which is drawn). Much easier is to keep the previous fortress alive as in the game. }) 51... Rxa5 52. Rxe3 Ra2+ 53. Kf3?? (53. Kh3! Rxe3 54. Bxe3 h5 55. Bf4 Ra1 56. Bc7 Kf5 57. Bf4 Rb1 58. Bc7 Rh1+ 59. Kg2 Rc1 60. Bf4 Ra1 61. Kh3 $10) 53... Rb7?? (53... Rxe3+ 54. Bxe3 h5 55. Ke4 (55. g4 h4! $19 { Fischer gives many variations here proving that you can keep the pawn alive and eventually win this as black. }) 55... Kf6 56. Bf4 Ra4+ 57. Kf3 Kf5! $19 { With the white king on h3, black could not make further progress. Here, however, black is forceably going to be able to play Kg4 and break through with h4, when the bishop is on f4, destabilizing. } { [%cal Ga4a3] }) 54. Re6+ Kf5 55. Re5+ Kf6 56. Rd5 Rb3+ 57. Kg4 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { White's fortress cannot be broken. } 1/2-1/2


