{ "A lyrical performance" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Nd3 (10. f3 f5 11. Be3 f4 12. Bf2 g5 { "black's kingside attack has practically been worked out to a forced mate!" and yet 50 years later this is definitely the mainline, and both engines and super GMs prefer white's position tremendously. }) 10... f5 11. exf5 Nxf5?! { See chapter 29 for a further exploration of this variation. The e4 square is going to hurt. } 12. f3 Nf6 13. Nf2 Nd4 14. Nfe4 Nh5 { "White has the c5 lever; black has the dynamic break with g5-g4. Chances are roughly even." Personally, I prefer white because play in the center is usually more reliable than a dynamic kingside pawn break (while you're castled kingside too!) } 15. Bg5 Qd7 16. g3 h6 (16... c5?! 17. Nb5 Nxb5 18. cxb5 { Tal - Gligoric from a later round in this exact tournament got here instead, where white achieved a bind on the queenside. }) 17. Be3 c5?! (17... Qe7 { More prudent. Taking on d4 with the bishop is going to lose a lot of the dark squares in white's camp: } 18. Bxd4? exd4 19. Nb5 Bf5 20. Qd3 Nf6 21. Nxd4 Nxe4 22. Nxf5 gxf5 23. fxe4 fxe4 $10) 18. Bxd4 (18. Qd2! { An improvement on the game. First we force black to make a slight kingside weakness before taking the pawn. } 18... Kh7 (18... g5 19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Nb5 Qe7 21. Nbxd6 Bh3 22. Rfe1) 19. Bxd4 exd4 20. Nb5 Qe7 21. Nbxd6 Bh3 22. Rfe1 Be5 23. Nb5) 18... exd4 19. Nb5 a6?! (19... Qe7 20. Nbxd6 Bh3 21. Re1) 20. Nbxd6 d3! 21. Qxd3 (21. Bxd3 Bd4+ 22. Kh1?! (22. Rf2! Bxf2+ 23. Kxf2 $16 { Up two pawns, sacrificing the exchange seems like a smart idea to quell any further kingside attack. Now white can focus on promoting the d5 pawn. }) 22... Nxg3+ 23. Nxg3 Qxd6 24. Qc2 Bh3 $14 { Black's pieces spring to life! }) 21... Bd4+ 22. Kg2? (22. Rf2! { Again, the way forward. Sacrificing the exchange quells any further kingside attack and white can hope to safely play with the passed pawn in the center. }) 22... Nxg3! { An attack fully on the dark squares. Notice how this entire combination starts after white gets rid of their primary defender with Bxd4. } 23. Nxc8! (23. hxg3?? Qh3#) (23. Nxg3 Qxd6) 23... Nxf1! 24. Nb6 Qc7! 25. Rxf1 (25. Nxa8?? Qxh2+ 26. Kxf1 Qg1#) 25... Qxb6 26. b4! { Counterattacking on the queenside is perfectly well timed. } 26... Qxb4 (26... cxb4?? 27. c5! Bxc5 28. Nxc5 Qxc5 29. Qxg6+ Kh8 30. Qxh6+ Kg8 31. Kh1! $18 { [%cal Gf1g1] }) 27. Rb1 Qa5 28. Nxc5! (28. Rxb7? Rf7! { Black expels the active rook immediately and retains a good game. }) 28... Qxc5 29. Qxg6+ Bg7 30. Rxb7 { White's down a full rook now, but the active pieces remaining ensure that it's enough for a draw. Black is the one who has to be careful here to avoid getting mated. } 30... Qd4! 31. Bd3 Rf4! 32. Qe6+ Kh8 33. Qg6 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { A draw by repetition. Black has to repeat with Kg8 to avoid getting mated on the weakened light squares. } 1/2-1/2


