[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Tigran Vartanovich Petrosian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/h7rbJrnr"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The sincerest form of flattery" }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 (5. Ng5!? { A lot of theory in this line was developed after Fischer during Kasparov's reign. It looks ridiculous, but there are a lot of tricks based around e6/f7 sacrifices and is currently regarded as white's best try in this variation. } 5... Ngf6 6. Bd3 e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 (7... h6? 8. Nxe6 fxe6 9. Bg6+ $16) 8. Qe2 h6 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Qc7 11. Qg4 $14 { The modern main line. }) 5... Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bc4 Bf5 8. Qe2 e6 9. Bg5 Bg4! { Reducing white's attacking prospects before they even begin. } (9... Be7 10. O-O-O h6 (10... b5!? 11. Bb3 a5 $15) 11. Bh4 Ne4? 12. g4! Bh7 13. Bg3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Qc7 15. Ne5 Bd6 { Tal - Fuster, 1958 gave white the initiative after a few normal looking moves from black. }) 10. O-O-O Be7 11. h3 (11. Kb1 Nd5 12. Bc1? b5! (12... O-O 13. h3 $10 (13. Bd3 Qb6 { [%cal Gd5c3] } 14. Ka1 $15)) 13. Bb3 a5 $17) 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nd5! { "Forces an exchange of bishops" } 13. Bxe7 (13. Bd2 Bg5! $10) 13... Qxe7 { This position is very dry. If white can force something through, it'll be by taking a huge space advantage on both sides of the board and utilizing the bishop to control both flanks simultaneously. Kasparov - Anand, 2003 showcases how to convert this space advantage into a win. } 14. Kb1 Rd8 (14... O-O-O!? $10) 15. Qe4 b5 { Petrosian hasn't castled long for a reason! } 16. Bd3 a5 17. c3 Qd6 18. g3 (18. Rhe1 Qf4 19. Qxf4 Nxf4 20. Be4 $10 { Fischer wanted to keep the queens on the board. }) 18... b4 19. c4 { Forced, but now the d pawn is a potential weakness, so white can't go all-out on the kingside. } 19... Nf6 20. Qe5?! (20. Qe2 O-O (20... Qxd4?? 21. Bg6! $18 { [%cal Ge2e8,Gd1d8] }) 21. Bc2?! (21. Qe3 a4 22. Rhe1 $10) 21... c5! 22. dxc5 Qxc5 $15 { Black has the more active pieces and white's bishop is partially blocked by his pawns. }) 20... c5 (20... Qxe5!? 21. dxe5 Nd7 22. f4 Nc5 $10 { "A drawn ending" but honestly black is the one fighting. }) 21. Qg5!? (21. Qxc5 Qxc5 22. dxc5 Rc8 $10 { Transposes to the game, but Fischer wanted more... }) 21... h6! { Petrosian calls Fischer's bluff! } 22. Qxc5 (22. Qxg7 Ke7!! 23. dxc5 Qxc5 (23... Qc6 24. Bg6 Rdf8 25. Rhe1 $10 (25. Bxf7?? Qe4+!! 26. Ka1 Rh7 $19)) 24. Rhe1 Qg5! $10 (24... Rdg8?? 25. Rxe6+!! Kxe6 26. Re1+ $18) 25. Rxe6+? Kxe6 26. Re1+ Kd6 27. Qxf7 $15 { Black is slightly better, but white is down a full rook with almost complete compensation so in a practical game, this is extremely hard to win. }) 22... Qxc5 23. dxc5 Ke7 24. c6 Rd6 25. Rhe1 Rxc6 26. Re5 Ra8 27. Be4 { Petrosian offered a draw, but Fischer refused it because he saw Tal standing there excitedly "since a drawn result would practically clinch first place for him. So I refused - not because I thought white has anything in the position, but because I didn't want to give Tal the satisfaction!" } (27. Rb5 Ra7 $10 { [%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5] }) 27... Rd6?! (27... Nxe4 28. Rxe4 $10) 28. Bxa8! (28. Rxd6?! Kxd6 29. Rxe6+ fxe6 30. Bxa8 Kc5 31. b3 Nd7 32. Kc2 Kd4 $10) 28... Rxd1+ 29. Kc2 Rf1 30. Rxa5 Rxf2+ 31. Kb3 Rh2?! (31... Nd7!? { The engine suggestion. Black covers the 7th rank and can march his king up the board to start to prevent the c pawn from getting out of hand. } 32. c5! $14 { Stopping Kd6 gives white a slight pull }) 32. c5! Kd8 33. Rb5 (33. Ra7? Nd7 34. c6 Nb6 $14 { Similar to the other engine line mentioned. }) 33... Rxh3 (33... Nd7?? 34. c6! $18 { And Nb6 and Ne5 are both covered. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gd7c5,Gd7e5,Rb5e5,Rb5b6] }) 34. Rb8+ Kc7 35. Rb7+ Kc6 { Petrosian knew this was lost, but wanted to end the game immediately rather than suffer on. } (35... Kc8 36. Rxf7 Rxg3+ 37. Kxb4 $18 { Both players knew this was hopeless. }) 36. Kc4! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Discovered checkmate is unstoppable! } 1-0


