{ "The moral victor" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 (5. Nb5!? { The main way to play if you enjoy going for Maroczy binds (which Fischer did enjoy) }) 5... Qc7 6. g3 Nf6?! { Top players don't play this anymore - because of this very game, which highlights the refutation. } (6... a6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O $10 { Theory. }) 7. Ndb5! Qb8 8. Bf4 Ne5?? (8... e5 9. Bg5 a6 10. Bxf6 axb5 11. Bg5 $16 { The engine still finds a way forward here, but nobody has yet to play into this risky line with: } 11... Bb4!? (11... b4? 12. Nd5 $16) 12. Bxb5 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 d6 $14 { Black is down a pawn, but has some compensation due to white's terrible queenside. }) 9. Be2! (9. Bg2 a6 10. Qd4 d6 11. O-O-O axb5 12. Bxe5 Ng4 $16) 9... Bc5 (9... a6?? 10. Qd4! d6 11. O-O-O axb5 12. Bxe5 $18 { Notice the difference between having the bishop on e2 instead of "the natural" g2 square. }) (9... Ng8!? 10. Qd4 f6 11. O-O-O a6 12. Nd6+ Qxd6 13. Qxd6 Bxd6 14. Rxd6 $18 { Tal's suggestion for improvement. But let's be real - white is crushing it here with the active pieces and bishop pair. }) 10. Bxe5! Qxe5 11. f4 Qb8 12. e5! a6 (12... Ng8? 13. Ne4 $18 { [%cal Gb5d6,Ge4d6] }) 13. exf6 axb5 14. fxg7 (14. Ne4! Bf8 15. Qd4 $18) 14... Rg8 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Qd4 Ra4 (16... Qc7!? { Finally getting some activity for the queen... }) 17. Nf6+! Bxf6 18. Qxf6 Qc7 19. O-O-O! Rxa2 20. Kb1 { Always play Kb1. Now we can safely compare white's king to black's king and the disparity in king safety is the only thing worth discussing in this position. } 20... Ra6 (20... Ra5? 21. Bh5 d5 22. Rxd5! exd5 23. Re1+ $18) 21. Bxb5?! (21. Bh5! d6 22. Rhe1 Qe7 23. Qh6 Kd7 24. Qxh7 $18 { Fischer's improvement. Black can immediately resign. }) 21... Rb6 22. Bd3 e5! { Tal finds a way to activate his pieces even in such a dire position. } 23. fxe5!! (23. Qxe5+?! Qxe5 24. fxe5 Rxg7 $16 { Some drawing chances. But "in top-flight chess, you have to drive your advantage home unmercifully." }) 23... Rxf6 24. exf6 { [%cal Gd3h7] } 24... Qc5!? (24... Qb6 25. Rhf1 $18) (24... Kd8 25. Bxh7 Qe5 26. Rhf1 Rxg7 27. fxg7 Qxg7 $18 { The engine recommendation. Also hopeless for black. }) 25. Bxh7 Qg5! 26. Bxg8 Qxf6 27. Rhf1 Qxg7 28. Bxf7+ Kd8 { Transposes to the engine line mentioned earlier, but white is up a further pawn. } 29. Be6 Qh6 30. Bxd7 Bxd7 31. Rf7 Qxh2 32. Rdxd7+! { Doubling on the 7th ensures a "quick" resignation. Much better than keeping white's own back rank defended. } 32... Ke8 33. Rde7+ Kd8 34. Rd7+ Kc8 35. Rc7+ Kd8 36. Rfd7+ Ke8 37. Rd1 (37. Rxb7 { With more time on the clock, Fischer would have surely gone in for this: } 37... Qxg3 38. Re7+ Kd8 39. Rbd7+ Kc8 40. b3 $18) 37... b5 (37... Qxg3 38. Rxb7 $18) 38. Rb7 Qh5 39. g4! { Now Fischer imagines all the possible staircase mates on Tal's barren king. } 39... Qh3 (39... Qxg4 40. Rh1 { [%cal Gh1h8] } 40... Qd4 41. Rh8+! Qxh8 42. Rb8+ Kd7 43. Rxh8 $18) 40. g5 Qf3 41. Re1+ Kf8 42. Rxb5 Kg7 43. Rb6 { Cut the king off and then go for mate again. } 43... Qg3 44. Rd1 Qc7 45. Rdd6 Qc8 46. b3 Kh7 47. Ra6! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { There is no defense to Ra7+ Kg8 Rdd7, without losing the queen. } 1-0


