[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The drawing master" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 exd4? { Extremely risky to try and hold on to this pawn with the e file fully open. } (7... d5 8. dxe5 Be6 $10 { The main line. }) 8. Re1 d5 9. Nc3! { [%cal Gc3d5,Gc3e4] } 9... Be6 (9... dxc3?? 10. Bxd5 Bb7 11. Bxe4! Qxd1?? 12. Bxc6+ Kd8 13. Rxd1+ $18) 10. Nxe4 dxe4 11. Rxe4 { Black's lack in development has caught up to him. } { [%cal Be4e8,Bb3f7] } 11... Be7 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Nxd4! $146 (13. Rxe6 Qd5 14. Qe2 O-O 15. Rxe7 Nxe7 16. Qxe7 Rae8 17. Qxc7 Rf7! 18. Qg3 Rxf3!! 19. gxf3 Re1+ 20. Kg2 Qc4 { [%cal Gc4f1] } 21. Kh3 (21. Qb8+ Kf7 22. b3 Qf1+ 23. Kg3 $16 { A possible engine improvement. }) 21... Qe6+ 22. Qg4 Qc6 $10 { A known drawing line. }) 13... O-O 14. Qg4 Nxd4 15. Rxd4 Qc8 16. Re4 Rf6 (16... e5!? $10 { Kovalev, Vladislav - Kocheev, Aleksandr, 1/2-1/2, Minsk op, 2013, https://lichess.org/NMwnKZri }) 17. Be3 (17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Be5 Bxe5 19. Rxe5 $14) (17. Bg5?? Rg6 18. h4 h6 19. Qh5 Qe8!! 20. Bxe7 Rxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Qxh5 $19) 17... Qd7 18. Rd1 Qc6 19. Bd4 Rg6 20. Qe2 Rd8 21. g3 { White's positions are well coordinated against the accessible e6 weakness, but black doesn't have two weaknesses yet. Fischer needs to open a second flank if he wants a win. } 21... Qd5? (21... Rd6 $14) 22. Re1! c5 (22... Qxa2? 23. b3 { [%cal Be1a1] } 23... Qa3 24. Rxe6 $18) 23. Bc3 Rd6 (23... b4 24. Be5 $16 { As in the game but with more weaknesses. }) 24. Be5 Rd8 25. Bf4 { Preventing the queen trade with Qd2, white is directly winning the e pawn now. } 25... c4 (25... Kf7 26. b3 $16) 26. Rxe6 Rxe6 27. Qxe6+ Qxe6 28. Rxe6 Bf6 29. Rxa6 Rd1+ 30. Kg2 Bxb2?? (30... Rb1! 31. b3 (31. a4!? Rxb2 32. axb5 Rxb5 33. Rc6 c3 34. Re6 Kf7 35. Re2 { White maintains winning chances by marching the king to d3 in order to capture on c3. }) 31... Rb2 { Black possibly has a draw with these active pieces. } 32. bxc4 bxc4 33. Kf3 Rxc2 34. Be3! c3 35. Ke4 Kf7 36. Kd3 Rb2 37. g4! { [%cal Gg4g5] } 37... h6 38. h4! $16 { The way to break through is distract the bishop from the c pawn, prevent the rook from getting behind the passed a pawn, and then push through. }) 31. Rb6 Ra1 32. Rxb5 Rxa2 33. Rc5 Ra4 34. Be5 Bxe5 35. Rxe5 Ra2 36. Re2 Kf7 37. Kf3 Kf6 38. Ke4 g5 39. Kd4 Kf5 40. f3 (40. Kxc4 Kg4 41. Kb3 $18 { Just get on with it. Black's active king is on the wrong side of the board to prevent the c pawn from queening. }) 40... c3! 41. Rf2?! { Fischer is unnecessarily trying to hold everything together instead of just winning. Curious, since his main advantage of his opponents was his ability to play the board objectively and calculate accurately. } (41. Kxc3 Ra3+ 42. Kd4 Rxf3 43. c4 $18 { Same idea. }) 41... Ra3 42. Kc4 h5 43. Kb4 Ra8 44. f4 (44. Kxc3 h4 $18 { Much more critical than the previous lines, but should still be winning. }) 44... Ke4! 45. fxg5 (45. Kxc3 Ke3 46. Rf1 Ke2 47. Rc1 gxf4 48. gxf4 $16 { Now white's pieces look ridiculous... although it's still enough for a win. Barely. }) 45... Ke3! { Trifunovic has clearly seen Capablanca's games - king activity is crucial in the endgame. Get your king up in the endgame! } 46. Rg2 Kd4 (46... Rc8 47. h4 Kf3 48. Rg1 Kf2 49. Rd1 Kxg3 50. Rd4 $18) 47. Re2 Rb8+ 48. Ka4 Rg8 49. h4 Rf8 50. Re7 (50. g4! hxg4 51. Rg2 Rf4 52. g6! $18) 50... Rf3 51. Rd7+ Kc5 52. Rc7+ Kd4 53. Rd7+ Kc4 54. Rc7+ Kd4 55. Kb3 Rxg3 56. Rd7+ Ke4 57. Rh7 Kd4 58. Rxh5 { Finally Fischer coordinates his pieces and re-prepares to win with the passed kingside pawns. } 58... Rg1 59. Rh8 Rb1+ 60. Ka4 Ra1+ 61. Kb5 Rb1+ 62. Kc6 Rg1 63. Rd8+ Kc4 64. Re8 { [%cal Ge8e4] } 64... Kb4 (64... Kd4 65. Rd8+ Kc4 66. Kd6 { Also progress. }) 65. Kd5 Rd1+ 66. Ke6 Re1+ 67. Kf7 Rf1+ 68. Kg6 Rf2 69. h5 Rxc2 70. h6 Rh2 71. h7 c2 72. Rc8! (72. h8=Q?? Rxh8 73. Rxh8 c1=Q $10) 72... Kb3 73. Kg7 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Now after h8=Q, we can recapture with the king. It took Fischer a long time to activate his king, but notice that as soon as he did, the game ended almost immediately afterwards. } 1-0


[Event "Stockholm Interzonal"]
[Site "Stockholm SWE"]
[Date "1962.03.04"]
[Round "22"]
[White "Mario Bertok"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D59"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Tartakower Defense, Makogonov Exchange Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Mario Bertok - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/tijuPd76"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Hanging pawns unhung" }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 { A trendy move - prevents Bg5 and therefore avoids some dull main lines in the QGD. } (3... Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 c6 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. Qc2 O-O 9. Nge2 $14 { Often, the knight finds a good square on e2 instead of f3. Now white can play for the f3-e4 pawn break. }) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 { The Tartakower. Interesting how 2 years after Fischer wrote this book, he played the white side of this exact position for the first time in his life in his WCC match against Spassky. } 8. cxd5 (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 c5 11. Qe2 Ne4 $10 { Another way to play this position as white. Fischer had this position against Petrosian in the 1959 Candidates before. }) 8... Nxd5 (8... exd5?! 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. f4 $14) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Be2 (11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4!? { Fischer, Robert James - Spassky, Boris V, 1-0, World Championship 28th, 1972, https://lichess.org/rWrwdkZw } { The famous to-be-referenced Fischer - Spassky game. }) 11... Be6 12. O-O c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 { Hanging pawns structure is reached. In this case, it's not bad for black as the "pawns will exert a tremendously cramping influence on white's future development." } 14. Qa4 Qb7 { This move was actually a key improvement on the Fischer - Spassky game. Interesting how Fischer already knew the idea from the reverse side of the position! } 15. Qa3 Nd7 16. Ne1 { "What else is there?" } (16. b3 a5 $15 { If Qb4 can be maintained, then black's pawns will start marching. } { [%cal Gb7b4] }) 16... a5 17. Nd3 c4 18. Nf4 Rfb8! { Fischer has utilized the Capablanca maneuver with the hanging pawns. c4!? gives up the d4 square, but black argues that this hole is completely meaningless when compared to the pressure on the backwards b pawn. } 19. Rab1 (19. e4! Qxb2 20. Qxb2 Rxb2 21. exd5?? (21. Rfb1 Rab8 $17) 21... Bf5!! { Threatening g5, removing the defender of the bishop, and stopping Rab1 trading my active rook. } 22. Bf3 (22. Bxc4? Rb4! { [%cal Bb4f4] } 23. Rac1 Nb6 $19) 22... g5 23. d6 Ra6 24. Nd5 Bd3 $19 { [%cal Ra6d6] }) (19. Nxe6?! fxe6 20. Bg4 Ra6 $17 21. b3 Qb4 22. Qxb4 axb4! $17 { Black's passed pawns will start rolling. }) (19. Bf3? Nf6 20. Rfd1 Qxb2 21. Qxb2 Rxb2 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Bxd5 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 c3! 25. Rc5? c2 26. Rc1 Rd8! $19 { [%cal Gd8d1] }) 19... Bf5! 20. Rbd1 Nf6 { Fischer keeps proving with every move that the backwards b pawn is more important than the backwards d pawn. If black wins the b pawn, the c4 pawn queens. If white wins the d pawn, nothing has really changed. } 21. Rd2 g5! { "Practically forcing the win of a piece" } 22. Nxd5 (22. Nh3? Ne4 23. Rdd1 Qxb2 $17 { [%cal Gb2e2,Gb2a3] }) 22... Nxd5 23. Bxc4 (23. Bf3 Bd3 $17 24. Qc5 Qb4! { [%cal Rb4d2] } 25. Qxb4 Nxb4 26. Bxa8 Bxf1 27. Kxf1 Rxa8 28. a3 Nd3 { A sample line showing how black wins a piece. }) 23... Be6 24. Rfd1 Nxe3! { [%cal Re3g2,Rb7g2] } 25. Qxe3 Bxc4 { Black is up a piece for a pawn, and the queenside pressure is still there. Black is winning. } 26. h4 Re8 27. Qg3 Qe7 28. b3 Be6 29. f4 g4! { No more attack, and black is fully consolidated. } 30. h5 Qc5+ 31. Rf2 Bf5 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


[Event "Stockholm Interzonal"]
[Site "Stockholm SWE"]
[Date "1962.03.03"]
[Round "21"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Julio Bolbochan"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B90"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation, Adams Attack"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Julio Bolbochan"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/cQi4MwjG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "A brilliant cadenza" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3!? { This move has become fashionable since Michael Adams started deploying it in the 1980s to get people out of theory. } 6... Nc6 (6... e5 7. Nde2 Be6?! 8. g4! { Justifying white's h3 move. }) 7. g4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 e5 9. Qd3 Be7?! (9... Be6 { "More accurate" }) 10. g5! Nd7 11. Be3 Nc5 (11... Bxg5 12. Bxg5 Qxg5 13. Qxd6 $14 { [%cal Gc3d5,Ga1d1] }) 12. Qd2 { Black keeps attacking the queen, but its awkward placement on c5 ensures that it's black who will be losing time next. White's pieces are perfectly setup to take advantage of the d5 hole. } 12... Be6 13. O-O-O O-O 14. f3 Rc8 15. Kb1 { Always play Kb1. "Amateurs are always puzzled by this apparent loss of time. Actually it is a handy defensive move, getting out of the pin on the c-file which could become annoying after …b5-b4. One never knows when lightning will strike!" } 15... Nd7 { The knight reroutes to b6 and possibly c4 because it was hitting nothing on c5. } 16. h4 b5 17. Bh3! Bxh3?! { Black should be trying to keep more control over d5. This move simply trades black's good bishop for white's bishop in a way that gives white maximum control over d5. } (17... Nb6 18. Bxb6! Qxb6 19. Nd5 { [%cal Rh3c8] } 19... Qd8 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Qxd6 $16 { By refuting the move Bolbochan wanted to play, Fischer causes his opponent to panic. }) 18. Rxh3 Nb6 19. Bxb6! Qxb6 20. Nd5 { Fischer obtains the beautiful knight on d5 against the terrible bishop on e7 game that he had been striving for the past 10 moves. The position is now strategically won, and white needs only coordinate his pieces on the kingside to break through. } 20... Qd8 21. f4 { If f5 is played, black is 100% dead. } (21. Nxe7+? Qxe7 22. Qxd6?? Rfd8! $19 { Don't get greedy! }) 21... exf4 22. Qxf4 Qd7 23. Qf5 Rcd8 (23... Qxf5?? 24. Nxe7+ Kh8 25. exf5 $18) 24. Ra3! { The bishop is dead on e7, so rather than bust open the kingside with an all-out h5-g6, Fischer calmly refocuses his efforts by probing both sides of the board. } { [%cal Ra3a6] } 24... Qa7 25. Rc3 (25. Nf6+ Bxf6 (25... gxf6?? 26. gxf6 Kh8 27. Qg5 Rg8 28. fxe7! $18) 26. gxf6 g6 27. Qf4 Kh8 { Tempting, and technically winning, but there's no immediate breakthrough here either. Better practically to keep the amazing knight. }) 25... g6 26. Qg4 Qd7 27. Qf3 Qe6 28. Rc7 Rde8 (28... Rd7? 29. Nf4! { Trapping the queen }) 29. Nf4 Qe5 30. Rd5 Qh8 31. a3 { Preparing Ra7 where black cannot defend any of these queenside pawns. } 31... h6 32. gxh6 Qxh6 33. h5 Bg5 (33... g5!? 34. Ne2 $18 { White maintains "a winning bind" } { [%cal Ge2g3,Gg3f5,Ge2d4,Gd4f5] }) (33... gxh5?? 34. Rxe7 Rxe7 35. Qg3+ Kh7 36. Rxh5 $18) 34. hxg6! fxg6 (34... Bxf4 35. gxf7+ Rxf7 36. Rxf7 Kxf7 37. Rh5! $18 { And the bishop is won next with a completely open king. }) 35. Qb3! { [%cal Bb3g8] } 35... Rxf4 (35... Kh8 36. Nxg6+ Qxg6 37. Rxg5! Qxg5? (37... Rf1+ 38. Ka2 Qxg5 (38... Qe6 39. c4! { No queen trade! } 39... bxc4 40. Rh5+ Kg8 41. Qg3+ Kf8 42. Qg7# $18) 39. Qh3+ Kg8 40. Qxf1 $18 { Keeping up the initiative and regaining the material. }) 38. Qh3+ Kg8 39. Qh7# { The major pieces have successfully infiltrated! }) 36. Re5+ Kf8 37. Rxe8+ $18 { And black resigned rather than get mated as follows: } 37... Kxe8 38. Qe6+ Kf8 39. Qc8+ Bd8 40. Qxd8# 1-0


[Event "Stockholm Interzonal"]
