[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Viktor Korchnoi"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C91"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed, Bogoljubow Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Viktor Korchnoi"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/tbk1A9e4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Gaston and Alphonse" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 (8. d4! { The anti-Marshall } 8... d6 9. c3 { Transposing to the game. }) 8... d6 (8... d5!? { With the game's move order, Korchnoi had a chance to enter the Marshall. However, he was known for going up a pawn and holding on to it for dear life, asking his opponent to prove the compensation. Therefore, it makes sense he wouldn't go for this pawn sac as black. }) 9. d4 { Fischer willingly enters the Yates. In recent times, this is typically only done to avoid the Marshall gambit } (9. h3 { The main move }) 9... Bg4 10. Be3 exd4 11. cxd4 Na5 12. Bc2 Nc4 13. Bc1 c5 14. b3 { Fischer is playing approved theory even to this day! } 14... Na5?! (14... Nb6 { "Korchnoi thinks this move completely equalizes" but Fischer believes that white keeps a small pull as in this Pietzsch game: } 15. Nbd2 cxd4 (15... Rc8!? { Ding's move possibly improves... }) 16. h3 Bh5 17. g4 Bg6 18. Nxd4 { Although winrates are not so impressive after: } 18... Rc8 $10 { Baron, Ta - Van Foreest, Lucas, 0-1, 9th Batavia GM 2017, https://lichess.org/UXxCSHJQ }) 15. d5! { [%cal Ga5c4,Ga5c6] } 15... Nd7 (15... Nxe4?? 16. Rxe4 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6a1] } 18. Nc3 b4 19. Bb2 bxc3 20. Bxc3 Bxc3 21. Qxc3 $16 { "White has a big advantage" }) 16. Nbd2 Bf6 17. Rb1 c4 (17... Ne5 18. h3 Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 c4 21. b4 Nb7 $14 { Reminiscent of Karpov - Unzicker, 1974 - the knight on b7 is completely dominated by the b4 and e5 pawns. }) 18. h3 (18. b4?? c3! { And the knight on a5 will not be dominated after all! }) 18... Bxf3 (18... Bh5 19. g4 Bg6 20. bxc4 Nxc4 21. Nxc4 bxc4 22. Nd4 $16 { [%cal Gd4f5] }) 19. Nxf3 cxb3 20. axb3 Qc7 21. Be3 { Both players thought white didn't have much in this position, but SF14 is unconvinced by black's setup... } 21... Bc3 22. Re2 b4 23. Nd4 Rfe8 24. Nf5 { Knife f5! The knee-jerk reaction of Bf8 here is not possible with the bishop on c3! } 24... Nb7 25. Bd4! { Further hitting the kingside dark squares now that the bishop has left the king's defense. } 25... g6 (25... Bxd4 26. Qxd4 Nf6 27. Qxb4 Nc5 28. Qd4 $18 { Attacking on the kingside will be so easy without the dark squared bishop. }) 26. Nh6+ Kf8 27. Rc1 Rac8 28. Bd3? { [%cal Bc1c7] } (28. Re3! $16 { Korchnoi's improvement for white. After Bxc3 bxc3, the c pawn will be lost. } { [%cal Re3c3] }) 28... Qa5? (28... Qd8!? 29. Bxa6 Bxd4 30. Rxc8 Qxc8 31. Qxd4 Qc1+ 32. Kh2 Qxh6 33. Bxb7 Qf4+ 34. g3 $10 { With a probably draw }) 29. Rec2 { Fischer dominates the c file, and still has possible kingside breakthroughs. } 29... Ne5? 30. Bf1?! (30. Bxe5! Rxe5 31. Qf3 Re7 (31... Qc7 32. Rxc3 bxc3 33. Rxc3! $18 { [%cal Rf3f7,Bc3c8] }) 32. e5! dxe5 33. Qf6! $18 { Both players missed this sequence of only moves where white is completely winning. } { [%cal Gf6h8] } 33... e4?? 34. Rxc3! Rxc3 35. Qh8#) 30... Nc5! { "Sacrifices a pawn for the moment, but black's pieces have excellent activity." -Korchnoi } 31. Bxc3 bxc3 32. Rxc3 Kg7 33. Ng4 Nxg4 34. Qxg4 (34. hxg4!? Rxe4 35. Rc4 Rxc4 36. Rxc4 { Threatening b4 with a pin and a fork } { [%cal Rb3b4] } 36... Qd8 37. b4 Nd7 38. Qa1+ Kg8 39. Qxa6 Rxc4 40. Qxc4 $14 { Best play. White wins a pawn, but has to convert this endgame where black will maintain a good knight on c5 or e5 forever if white plays inaccurately. }) 34... Rb8 35. Rf3! Nxe4 36. Qf4 f5 37. Re3 Re5 38. Rc6 Rbe8?! { Played in time pressure, Korchnoi overlooked Fischer's response. That being said, his suggestion is not so clear either... } (38... g5!? 39. Qf3 Rbe8 40. Rxa6 Qxd5 41. b4 { An unclear position for both sides. }) 39. Rxd6! Qa1?? (39... Nxd6?? 40. Rxe5 $18) (39... g5! { Insane, but forced. } 40. Rd7+ Kg6 41. Qf3 Qb6 { With the threat of Nxf2! } 42. Qe2!? (42. Re2! $16 { The engine line just calmly defends against the Nxf2 threat and says there's no problems for white at all... }) (42. Rxe4!? { Korchnoi's suggestion, with white having at least a draw: } 42... Rxe4 43. g4 Rf4 (43... f4?? 44. Bd3 $18) 44. gxf5+ Kh6 45. Rxh7+ Kxh7 46. Qh5+ Kg7 47. Qxg5+ Kf7 48. Qxf4 $10) 42... Nxf2 43. Rxe5 $10 { Fischer's suggestion, with an eventual draw. }) 40. Rxa6 { Fischer's now up 2 pawns and has the move. } 40... Qd4 41. Rd3 Qb2 42. d6 g5 43. Qe3 f4 44. Qa7+ $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Korchnoi did not want to see the following crush: } 44... Kf8 45. d7 Rd8 46. Qb6 Ke7 47. Qxd8+ Kxd8 48. Ra8+! $18 { [%cal Gd7d8] } 1-0


