{ "Only a draw" }
1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 d6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O Nc6 6. c3 e5 { Reaching a typical reversed Botvinnik English. } 7. d3 Nge7 8. a3 { Going for b4, a pawn break that isn't called for in this position. } 8... O-O (8... a5? 9. a4! { And now the b5 square is white's forever. } { [%cal Gb1a3,Ga3b5] }) 9. b4 b6 10. f4 exf4! { "Abandoning the center to play against white's shaky pawn structure." This is fully justified because black is the one who is better developed, and a3-b4 has accomplished nothing except weaken the long diagonal. } 11. gxf4 d5! 12. e5?! (12. exd5? Nxd5 13. c4 Bxa1 14. Bxd5 Nd4 15. Bxa8?? Bg4! $19) 12... Bg4 (12... Nf5!?) 13. h3 Bxe2? { Don't trade the bishop pair away! } (13... Be6 14. Ng3 Qd7 15. Kh2 f6! { A better way forward } 16. d4 fxe5 17. fxe5 Rxf1 18. Bxf1 (18. Qxf1? cxd4 19. cxd4 Nxd4 $19) 18... cxd4 19. cxd4 Nxe5! 20. dxe5? Bxe5 $19 { Black has more diagonals than white, and with Nf5 coming, black is completely killing white. } { [%cal Be5h2,Be6h3,Be5a1] }) 14. Qxe2 f6 15. b5! (15. e6? f5! { The weak e pawn will be won later. }) 15... Na5 16. Nd2 fxe5 17. fxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Nxf1 Nb3 19. Rb1 Nxc1 20. Rxc1 Qc7! { The point of all these trades. Black will target the e5 pawn. Better yet was keeping all of the tension earlier though and simply murdering the weak white king. } 21. Re1 (21. d4?? cxd4 $19 { [%cal Rc7c1] }) 21... Rd8 22. Nh2 d4 23. cxd4 cxd4 24. Nf3 (24. Ng4! { Stopping Fischer's follow-up was called for. } 24... Nf5 25. Qe4 $15) 24... Bh6! { The bishop will be stronger on f4 or e3 than on g7 now that the d4 pawn is fixed there. } 25. Qa2+ Kh8 26. Qe6 Nd5?! (26... Nf5! 27. Qf6+ Bg7 28. Qe6 Rf8 $17 { Black is only momentarily inconvenienced by this check. Black will soon play Bh6-e3 again and infiltrate on the dark squares. }) 27. Nh2 Ne3 28. Bc6! { "The black queen must coordinate with the e3 knight for it to be really meaningful." } 28... Rf8 29. Nf3 Bf4 30. Nxd4 Bxe5 31. Nf3 Bd4! 32. Rxe3 (32. Nxd4?? Qg3+ 33. Kh1 Qxe1+ $19) 32... Bxe3+ 33. Qxe3 Qg3+ 34. Kf1 Qxh3+ 35. Ke1 Qf5 { Fischer willingly goes in for the endgame where the rook and pawn are slightly better than the two pieces. In a middlegame, this would be suicide, but there are a lot of open files for the rook to run circles around the pieces here that black should still be the one pushing. } 36. d4 Kg7 37. Kf2! { The kingside pawns are the scary ones. } { [%cal Gh7h1,Gg6g1] } 37... h5 38. Kg3 Qg4+ 39. Kh2 Rf4? (39... Qf4+ 40. Qxf4 Rxf4 41. Kg3 g5!? 42. d5! $10) 40. Qe7+? (40. Qe5+ Kh7 41. Ng5+ Kh6 42. Nh3! $16 { A key defensive maneuver Keres missed just before the adjournment. Here, black's king is just as vulnerable as white's king, and the pawns are firmly blockaded. }) 40... Kh6 41. Qe2 Qf5 42. Qe3 g5 43. Kg2 Rg4+ 44. Kf2 Rf4 45. Kg2 { Fischer starts fishing for Keres to go wrong with some "exploratory checks" } 45... Qc2+ 46. Kh1 (46. Kg3?? Rg4+ 47. Kh3 Qg2#) 46... Qb1+ 47. Kh2 Qa2+ 48. Kh3 Qf7 49. Kh2 Qf6 { Hinting at g4, where Nh4 (blockading) is impossible. } 50. Kg2 Kg7 51. Kg3 h4+ 52. Kg2 Rg4+ (52... g4?? 53. Nxh4!) 53. Kh1 Rg3 54. Qe4 g4 55. Nh2 Qg5 56. Nf1?! { Keres misses a draw just before the second adjournment. } (56. Qe5+! Qxe5 57. dxe5 Kf7 58. Bd7 $10) 56... Rh3+ (56... Rxa3!? 57. Qe6! { The only drawing move, and not a move that Fischer considered. } (57. d5?! g3 58. Bd7 Ra1! { Gaining a tempo as opposed to the game. })) 57. Kg1 Rxa3 58. d5 g3 59. Bd7 Ra1 60. Bf5 { Threatens d6, where Qc5+ is not possible. } 60... Qf6 61. Qf4 Re1 62. d6 Re5 63. Qg4+! (63. d7?? Rxf5 64. Qxf5 Qxf5 65. d8=Q Qf2+ 66. Kh1 Qxf1#) 63... Kf8 64. d7! { Now white will queen with check if the bishop is taken. } 64... Rd5 65. Kg2 Rxd7 66. Bxd7 Qf2+ 67. Kh3 { White has managed to get his king up in the endgame, at all costs. } 67... Qxf1+ 68. Kxh4 g2 69. Qb4+ Kf7 70. Qb3+ Kg7 71. Qg3+ Kh7 72. Qe5!! { Not stopping Fischer from queening, but going for his own counterplay instead. } (72. Bf5+?? Qxf5 73. Qxg2 Qf4+ 74. Qg4 Qxg4+ 75. Kxg4 Kg6 $19) 72... Qh1+ (72... Qf2+ 73. Kh3 g1=Q 74. Bf5+ Kh6 75. Qf6+ Kh5 76. Bg6+ Qxg6 77. Qg5+!! Qxg5 $10 { A miraculous stalemate that Keres had cooked up. }) 73. Bh3 Qxh3+ (73... g1=Q 74. Qh5+ Kg7 75. Qg6+!! Qxg6 $10 { Another nice stalemate }) 74. Kxh3 g1=Q 75. Qe7+ Kh8 76. Qf8+ Kh7 77. Qf7+ $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { It's a draw by perpetual check, because the only try for an advantage is still drawn too: } 77... Qg7 78. Qxg7+ Kxg7 79. Kg3 { Distant opposition! } 79... Kf7 80. Kf3 Ke7 81. Ke3 Kd6 82. Kd4 $10 1/2-1/2


[Event "Curacao Candidates"]
[Site "Willemstad CUW"]
[Date "1962.05.12"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Paul Keres"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C96"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed, Keres Defense"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Paul Keres"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/48T6nXQo"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Detective story" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 (8. h3?! Na5!) 8... O-O (8... Bg4?! 9. h3 Bh5 10. d3 $16) 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Nd7!? $146 { Keres' novelty! Literally creating the Keres defense this very game! } (11... Qc7 { The main move }) 12. dxc5 (12. Nbd2 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Nb3 (14. d5 Nb4 15. Bb1 a5 16. a3 Na6 17. b4 { Main line Keres defense. }) 14... a5 15. Be3 a4 16. Nbd2 { The same maneuver from the main line Chigorin is also OK }) 12... dxc5 13. Nbd2 Qc7 (13... c4!? 14. Nf1 Bb7 15. Ne3) 14. Nf1 Nb6?! 15. Ne3 Rd8 16. Qe2 Be6?! { A natural move, controlling d5, but Fischer shows that it actually doesn't! } (16... Bf8 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 f6 $14 { The engine line. White has only a small plus, but from a practical perspective this already shows that black's play hasn't made much sense... }) 17. Nd5! { Fischer jumps in in order to open up his bishops and pursue a kingside attack, now that all of black's pieces have abandoned the kingside. This is reminiscent of another Fischer games from this book: https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/JPVykOGY#37 } 17... Nxd5 18. exd5 Bxd5 19. Nxe5 Ra7 (19... Bd6?? 20. Qd3! Bxe5 21. Qxh7+ Kf8 22. f4! $18) 20. Bf4 Qb6 21. Rad1 { Threatening Rxd5 Rxd5 Qe4, winning! } 21... g6 22. Ng4! { Now Fischer focuses in on the kingside dark squared weaknesses. } { [%cal Bg4f6,Bg4h6] } 22... Nc4 23. Bh6 Be6 (23... Nxb2?? 24. Rxd5 Rxd5 25. Be4 Rd8 26. Qxb2 f5 27. c4 $18) 24. Bb3 Qb8 { Desperately trying to defend the dark squares (e5 in this case) } 25. Rxd8+ Bxd8 (25... Qxd8?? 26. Bxc4 bxc4 27. Qe5 $18) 26. Bxc4 bxc4 (26... Bxc4?? 27. Qe8#) 27. Qxc4! Qd6 (27... Bxc4?? 28. Re8#) 28. Qa4 { [%cal Ga4e8] } 28... Qe7 29. Nf6+! Kh8 30. Nd5 Qd7 31. Qe4! { Fischer keeps revisiting the same themes: weak back rank, weak dark squares near the king, and a vulnerable queen on top of it all. } 31... Qd6 { Again covering e5 } 32. Nf4 (32. c4 $18 { "Also good" }) 32... Re7 33. Bg5 (33. Bf8! $18 { Won immediately, but Fischer was content with his plusses in the endgame. }) 33... Re8 34. Bxd8 Rxd8 35. Nxe6 Qxe6 36. Qxe6 fxe6 37. Rxe6 Rd1+ 38. Kh2 Rd2 39. Rb6! (39. Rxa6?! Rxb2 40. Kg3 Rc2 41. Ra3 $14 { You have to play actively in the endgame! }) 39... Rxf2 40. Rb7! Rf6 41. Kg3 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Keres resigned at the adjournment because (1) his king is trapped on the back rank forever, (2) he's down a pawn, (3) his rook is passively defending the a6 pawn. Fischer gives the following as a possible continuation. } 41... Kg8 42. b4 cxb4 43. cxb4 Rd6 44. a4 Rd3+ 45. Kh2 Ra3 46. a5 Ra4 47. Kg3 $18 { And the white king marches up the board to c5 and wins. } { [%cal Gg3e5,Ge5c5] } 1-0


[Event "Varna ol (Men) fin-A"]
[Site "Varna BUL"]
[Date "1962.10.07"]
[Round "10.1"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D98"]
[Opening "Grünfeld Defense: Russian Variation, Smyslov Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Mikhail Botvinnik - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/V1yAIgMC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The confrontation" }
1. c4 g6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 O-O 7. e4 Bg4 (7... Nc6!? { Byrne's provocative Nc6 is also a good choice against the Russian. }) (7... a6!? 8. Be2 b5 9. Qb3 c5 10. dxc5 Be6 11. Qc2 Nbd7 { One modern line. }) 8. Be3 Nfd7 9. Be2 Nc6 10. Rd1 Nb6 11. Qc5 { This exact position was often contested in the 1986 Karpov - Kasparov WCC } 11... Qd6 12. h3 (12. e5!? { Karpov, Anatoly - Kasparov, Garry, 1-0, World Championship 33th-KK3, 1986, https://lichess.org/DBDtEJe8 }) 12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 Rfd8 14. d5 { Like a true hypermodernist, Fischer is tempting the pawns forward and seeking to take advantage of the gaps left behind. } (14. e5 Qxc5 15. dxc5 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Nd7 17. f4 g5! 18. fxg5 Bxe5 $10) 14... Ne5 15. Nb5 (15. f4?! Nec4 16. Bxc4 Qxc5 17. Bxc5 Nxc4 18. e5 Nxb2 19. Rd4 f6! $15) 15... Qf6?! { Although at the time Fischer was convinced this was an excellent move, there is in fact better: } (15... Qxc5 16. Bxc5 c6 17. Nc7 Rab8 18. Bxe7 Rd7 19. d6 Nc8 20. Ne8! Nxe7 21. Nxg7 Kxg7?? (21... Nd5!! 22. exd5 Rxd6 23. dxc6 Rxd1+ 24. Kxd1 Rd8+ 25. Kc2 Nxc6 $10 { The engine improvement Fischer didn't analyze! }) 22. f4 $18) 16. f4 Ned7 17. e5 Qxf4! { Botvinnik had prepared the following two lines against Smyslov for their WCC match, but he didn't figure on this following desperado! } (17... Qf5? 18. Qb4 a5 19. Qd4 $16 { The threat of Bg4 is nearly impossible to parry. }) (17... Qh4?? 18. Qc2 g5 19. Rd4! $18 { The black queen will be sidelines }) 18. Bxf4 (18. Qxb6?? Qe4! { [%cal Ge4h1,Ra7b6] } 19. f3 Qh4+ 20. Bf2 Qb4+! $19 { [%cal Ra7b6] }) 18... Nxc5 19. Nxc7 Rac8 20. d6 exd6 21. exd6 Bxb2 { Black is up a pawn, but white has the bishop pair, more active pieces, and a scary d6 pawn. The position is roughly level. } 22. O-O Nbd7 23. Rd5 b6 24. Bf3? { "Feeble play" -Botvinnik } (24. Bc4 Ne6 25. Bg3 Ndc5 26. Re1 { White's pieces maintain their active posts, and white is still slightly better. }) 24... Ne6! 25. Nxe6?! (25. Bg3 Nf6 26. Rb5 $10) 25... fxe6 26. Rd3 Nc5 27. Re3 e5! 28. Bxe5 Bxe5 29. Rxe5 Rxd6 { Simple and strong. Now we're in a simplified endgame where black is simply up a pawn and white has no more lead in activity. } 30. Re7 Rd7 31. Rxd7 (31. Rfe1 Rcc7! $17 { Flushes white's active rook off the 7th rank. }) 31... Nxd7 32. Bg4?! { Pointless since there's no inconvenience due to this move. } (32. Rd1!? Rc7 33. Rd3 Kf7 34. Ra3 $17 { White can keep some activity here, so the win is not so simple. }) 32... Rc7 33. Re1 (33. Bxd7?? Rxd7 $19 { A lost rook and pawn endgame, with Rd2 coming. }) 33... Kf7 34. Kg2 Nc5 35. Re3 Re7 36. Rf3+ Kg7 37. Rc3 { Black was threatening h5, trapping the bishop. } 37... Re4 (37... Re1 38. Bf3 { Botvinnik thought this was a better way forward from black, but Fischer said that the bishop on f3 was just as good as on c2. Engine slightly agrees with Fischer. }) 38. Bd1 Rd4 39. Bc2 Kf6 40. Kf3 Kg5 41. Kg3 Ne4+?? { Never trade. The hardest scenario to win is this rook endgame; just because white could not allow the rook endgame before doesn't mean this one is exactly the same. If Fischer kept his active knight on the board, white was nearly in zugzwang. Fischer stands by this move. } 42. Bxe4 Rxe4 43. Ra3?? (43. Rc7 Ra4 44. Rxh7 Rxa2 45. h4+ $10 { Transposes to the game - a draw. }) 43... Re7?? (43... a5! 44. Rb3 Rb4! 45. Rxb4?? axb4 $19 { This is a won king and pawn endgame. }) 44. Rf3 Rc7 45. a4 Rc5 { Sadly, transposing to the other line offers nothing for black. Fischer's previous mistake cannot be overcome. } 46. Rf7 Ra5 47. Rxh7 Rxa4 48. h4+ Kf5 49. Rf7+ Ke5 50. Rg7 Ra1 51. Kf3 b5?! { Throws the rest of the game away. Now, it's a clear draw. } (51... Kf6!? { Black can still play on here, although it's not genuine progress. }) 52. h5! Ra3+ 53. Kg2 gxh5 54. Rg5+ Kd6 55. Rxb5 h4 { The h pawn is firmly blockaded, and with the a3 rook in front of the passed a pawn, black needs his king on the queenside in order to make any progress. With the mutual passed pawns though, this means black has nothing more than a draw. } 56. f4 Kc6 57. Rb8 h3+ 58. Kh2 a5 59. f5 Kc7 60. Rb5 Kd6 61. f6 Ke6 62. Rb6+ Kf7 63. Ra6 Kg6 64. Rc6 a4 65. Ra6 Kf7 66. Rc6 Rd3 67. Ra6 a3 68. Kg1 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Fischer chided himself for the amount of mistakes he made this game. Regardless, beating Botvinnik in a technical endgame is always going to be insanely difficult... } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Varna ol (Men) fin-A"]
[Site "Varna BUL"]
[Date "1962.09.28"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Miguel Najdorf"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B90"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation, Adams Attack"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Miguel Najdorf"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/y2i6gF9K"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The Najdorf variation" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 b5 7. Nd5?! (7. a4!? { A better version of the game: white first weakens the queenside pawn structure before doing the maneuver he wants to do: Nd5 } 7... b4 8. Nd5 $14) 7... Bb7?! (7... e6! 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. c4 { Fischer thought this would be good for white, but missed the following key move: } 9... d5! { It's bizarre Fischer didn't see this move as this is identical to the concept he himself used in Chapter 26 against Lombardy. } 10. exd5 exd5 11. cxd5?? Bb4+ $19) 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 9. c4!? (9. Bd3!? Nd7 { "Tenable" for black, but the engine is not convinced: } 10. Qh5 $16) 9... bxc4? (9... Bxe4 10. cxb5 Bg7? (10... e5 { Practically forced, although it requires seeing this variation: } 11. Ne2 d5 12. Ng3 Bg6 13. Be2 h5 14. h4 $14 { White is slightly better because black's center cannot be maintained forever. White's king will stand better than black's. }) 11. Qg4 Bg6 12. f4 f5 13. Nxf5 $16) 10. Bxc4 Bxe4 (10... Qa5+? 11. Bd2 Qe5 12. Qb3! Qxe4+ 13. Kd1 $18 { "White has a very strong attack" }) 11. O-O d5 12. Re1 (12. Bb3! { Better than the game. } 12... e6 13. Re1 Bc5 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Rxe4 dxe4 16. Qh5+ Ke7 17. Qxc5+ Qd6 18. Qc4 $18) 12... e5?? (12... Bxg2!! { The only saving move. } 13. Kxg2 dxc4 14. Qf3 Nd7 15. Nf5 Rg8+ 16. Kh1 e6 17. Qc6 { Fischer stopped calculating here, thinking that Rxe6+ was the game-winning threat, but he missed the subtle: } 17... e5! $10 { The game could continue: } 18. Be3 Rc8 19. Qxa6 Nc5 20. Qb5+ Qd7 21. a4 Qxb5 22. axb5 Kd7 23. Bxc5 Bxc5 24. Ra6 $10) (12... Rg8?? 13. Rxe4 dxe4 14. Qh5 { [%cal Gh5f7,Gc4f7] } 14... Rg6 15. Qxh7 { [%cal Gh7f7,Gc4f7] } 15... e6 16. Be3 $18) (12... e6?? 13. Qh5 Bg6 14. Qxd5 Qxd5 15. Bxd5 Ra7 16. Bf4 $18) (12... dxc4?? 13. Rxe4 Qd5 14. Qf3 e6 { Fischer believed this was the best try for black, but white would be better. In fact this is completely lost due to: } 15. Bf4! Bc5 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rd1 Qc6 18. Bd6!! $18 { [%cal Ge4e6,Bf3a8] }) 13. Qa4+ (13. Rxe4!? dxe4 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Bb5 axb5 16. Qxa8 exd4 17. Qxb8+ Ke7 { The game is still won though: } { [%cal Gb2b3,Gd4d3,Gd3d2] } 18. a4 Bg7 (18... bxa4 19. b3! $18) 19. Qg3 $18 { [%cal Rg3g7,Ga4b5] }) 13... Nd7?? (13... Qd7 14. Bb5 axb5 15. Qxa8 Bd6 16. Rxe4! dxe4 17. Qxe4 $18 { Nf5 next, and white's bind on the light squares cannot be disturbed. Najdorf had to try this though... }) 14. Rxe4! dxe4 15. Nf5! { Black is effectively out of ideas on how to finish development. The king will die in the center. } 15... Bc5 (15... Rg8?? 16. Qb3 $18) (15... Rb8 { The best engine move doesn't help: } 16. Be3 $18 { Again, black is out of further developing moves... }) 16. Ng7+ Ke7 (16... Kf8 17. Bh6 Kg8 18. Qb3 $18 { "Murder" }) 17. Nf5+ Ke8 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. fxe3 { Honestly just toying with Najdorf now. Black has no moves! } 19... Qb6 20. Rd1 { The Morphy move finishes off the game. All pieces are now ready to reach their maximum potential: } 20... Ra7 21. Rd6 Qd8 22. Qb3 Qc7 23. Bxf7+ Kd8 24. Be6 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


