[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/yGj47axt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "A bright cameo" }
1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd8 { "A hypermodern approach championed by Bronstein".... and later John Bartholomew! } 4. d4 g6 5. Bf4 (5. Nf3!? Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 $14 { Caruana, F. - Duda, J., 1-0, GCT Blitz Paris 2019, https://lichess.org/J3wfABVq }) 5... Bg7 6. Qd2! { "Ignoring the 'threat'" and stopping Nh6->f5, pressuring the d4 pawn. } 6... Nf6! (6... Qxd4? 7. Qxd4 Bxd4 8. Nd5 Bb6 9. Bxc7! Nf6 (9... Bxc7?? 10. Nxc7+ $18 { [%cal Gc7a8,Gc7e8] }) 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. O-O-O $16 { The threat of mate ensures that white will be up a pawn and have the bishop pair in this ending. }) (6... Bxd4?? 7. O-O-O Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Nd5! { [%cal Gf4c7,Gd5c7] } 9... Bb6 10. Nf3 e6 11. Rhe1 $18) 7. O-O-O c6 8. Bh6 O-O? { Castling into the attack. Black is essentially in a bad Pirc. } (8... Bxh6 9. Qxh6 Be6 $14 { Black should seek to castle queenside instead. }) 9. h4 Qa5 10. h5 { This attack is identical to that against the dragon. Black has none of the normal counterplay against white's king because the b/c files remain closed. } 10... gxh5 { Black is trying to desperately keep the h file closed. } (10... Rd8 11. hxg6 fxg6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14. Nf3 $18 { [%cal Gf3g5] }) (10... Nxh5? 11. Be2 Nf6 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Qh6+ Kg8 14. Ne4 Nbd7 15. Ng5 $18) 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Nge2 Rd8 13. g4 Nf8 (13... Nxg4 14. Rdg1 $18 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg1g8] }) 14. gxh5 Ne6 15. Rdg1 Kh8 16. Bxg7+ Nxg7 17. Qh6 Rg8 (17... Ne6?? 18. Nf4 $18 { [%cal Gf4g6,Gh6h7,Gh6g7,Gf4e6] }) 18. Rg5 Qd8 19. Rhg1 Nf5? (19... Qf8 { Fischer expected his opponent to play the best move after which he had prepared this "prettier finish" } 20. d5! cxd5 (20... Bd7 21. d6! Nf5 22. Qxf8 Raxf8 23. Bxf5 Bxf5 24. dxe7 Rb8 25. Rxf5 $18) 21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Qxh7#) 20. Bxf5 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Robatsch blunders a piece here because he didn't consider all the possible checks, captures, and threats in the positions... } 20... Bxf5 { is impossible due to: } (20... Rxg5 { also gets mated: } 21. Rxg5 Bxf5 22. Qg7#) 21. Rxg8+ Qxg8 (21... Nxg8 22. Qg7#) 22. Rxg8+ $18 1-0


[Event "Varna ol (Men) fin-A"]
[Site "Varna BUL"]
[Date "1962.10.04"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Wolfgang Unzicker"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B92"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation, Opocensky Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Wolfgang Unzicker - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/6FYLkvgH"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Playing by ear" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e5 { "Black's expectation in this Najdorf variation is that his control of important squares, with possibilities of queenside expansion, will more than compensate for the slight weakness of his backward d pawn." } 7. Nb3 Be6?! { I have found this move-order to be slightly inaccurate when compared to the main line. } (7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Be6 10. f4 exf4 11. Bxf4 $10 { White's bishop has moved twice in the opening. }) 8. O-O (8. f4! Qc7 (8... Be7 9. f5 Bd7 $14) 9. g4 $16 { This variation is known to give white a slight pull. }) 8... Nbd7 9. f4 Qc7 10. f5 Bc4 11. a4 Be7 (11... Rc8? 12. a5 Be7? (12... d5! $10) 13. Bxc4 Qxc4 14. Ra4 Qc7 15. Be3 h6 16. Kh1 O-O $14 { "with a bind" }) 12. Be3 O-O 13. a5?! (13. g4 { "The critical alternative" } 13... d5! 14. exd5 { Forced: } (14. g5? Bxb3 15. gxf6 Nxf6 16. cxb3 d4 $19) (14. Nxd5?! Nxd5 15. exd5 Nf6 16. d6? Bxd6 17. Bxc4 Qxc4 18. Qxd6?? Qxg4+! 19. Kh1 Qe4+ 20. Kg1 Qxe3+ $19) 14... Nb6! { The Giri maneuver (a la https://lichess.org/study/WotymApK/nqKvzBcN ) taking full control over d5 and c4, fully equalizes. }) 13... b5! 14. axb6 Nxb6 { [%cal Gb6d5,Gf6d5,Gd6d5] } 15. Bxb6 { Fischer gives this move a ? and states that Geller found the right line in 1962: } (15. Kh1!? Rfc8 16. Bxb6 Qxb6 17. Bxc4 Rxc4 18. Qe2 Rb4 (18... Rac8!? 19. Ra2 Bd8 20. Rfa1 Qb7 { Black can play on here. }) 19. Ra2! h6 20. Rfa1 Bf8 21. Rxa6 Rxa6 22. Rxa6 Qb7 23. Na5 Qc7 24. Nb3 Qb7 $10) 15... Qxb6+ 16. Kh1 Bb5 { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gb5c6] } 17. Bxb5?! (17. Bd3! Bc6 18. Na5! Bb5 19. Nb3 $10) 17... axb5! { Now the "weakness" on the a file has become an asset to further attack the center. } 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Qxd5 { Fischer has willingly walked into a good knight vs bad bishop position, but he recognizes that it's simply not feasible to teleport the knight from the sad b3 square to the strong d5 outpost. A good knight is only good if it can reach the perfect outpost squares! } 19... Ra4! { Compare the activity of black's and white's pieces with a previous game in this book: https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/cQi4MwjG#39 } 20. c3 (20. Rxa4?? bxa4 21. Nd2 Qxb2) 20... Qa6 21. h3 Rc8 22. Rfe1 h6 23. Kh2 Bg5 24. g3? Qa7! { Fischer has activated all of his pieces and fully infiltrates on the dark squares. The knight on b3 remains a bystander. } 25. Kg2 Ra2! { [%cal Ga2b2] } 26. Kf1 Rxc3! $19 { Unzicker immediately resigned here, with this "good knight" still on its passive b3 roost. Black did not want to face the following brutal attack: } 27. Rxa2 (27. bxc3?? Qf2#) 27... Rf3+ 28. Ke2 Rf2+ 29. Kd3 Qxa2 30. Ra1 Qxb2 31. Ra8+ Kh7 $19 0-1


[Event "US Championship"]
