{ "Shock treatment"

The game was a skittles game played at Fine's home in NYC. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4!? { The Evans gambit! } 4... Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 exd4 (6... d6!? 7. Qb3 (7. O-O?! Bb6 { The Lasker defense is also well-respected for black. }) 7... Qd7 { Tartakower's methodology scores reasonably well for black. }) 7. O-O dxc3? { It's well-known that you can't keep taking pawns, opening up lines for white's pieces to attack your centralized king... } (7... Nge7!? 8. Ng5 d5 9. Nxf7 (9. exd5 Ne5 10. Qxd4 $10) 9... Kxf7 10. exd5 Ne5 11. Bb3 dxc3 12. d6+ Ke8 13. dxe7 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bd7 $10) 8. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3f7] } 8... Qe7? (8... Qf6 9. e5 Qg6 10. Nxc3 Nge7 11. Ba3 $10 { Chigorin thought this was still playable for black. Engine agrees. }) 9. Nxc3 Nf6?? (9... Bxc3 10. Qxc3 Nf6 (10... f6 11. Ba3 d6 12. Bd5 Bd7 (12... Qd7 $16) 13. Rab1 O-O-O?? 14. Nd4! $18) 11. Ba3 d6 12. e5 Ne4 13. Qc2 Nxe5?? 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Rfe1! $18 { [%cal Gf2f3] }) 10. Nd5! Nxd5 11. exd5 { The open e file with all of black's most important pieces on it beckons to Fischer... } 11... Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Bb2! { Gaining tempo on the queen in order to put a piece on the e file at all costs is the way forward. } 13... Qg5 14. h4! { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gb2g7] } 14... Qxh4 (14... Qh6? 15. Qa3 $18 { [%cal Ra3a5,Ra3e7,Gf1e1] }) (14... Qg4? 15. Rfe1+ Kd8 { Keeping the bishop around to defend e7 leads to a beautiful checkmate: } (15... Bxe1 16. Rxe1+ Kd8 17. Qe3 Qxh4 18. g3! { Qe7# is unstoppable! }) 16. Qe3 Bb4 17. Qh6!! gxh6 (17... f6?? 18. Bxf6+ $18) 18. Bf6+ Be7 19. Bxe7+ Ke8 20. Bg5+ Kf8 21. Bxh6+ Qg7 22. Re8+!! Kxe8 23. Bxg7 $18 { [%cal Ga1e1] }) 15. Bxg7 Rg8 16. Rfe1+ Kd8 (16... Bxe1 17. Rxe1+ Kd8 18. Qg3! $18 { The same mate }) 17. Qg3 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Rather than take the queen sacrifice, Fine resigned. The beautiful mate is: } 17... Qxg3 18. Bf6# 1-0


