[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Ghosts" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 (5... Nxd5? 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 { The Fried liver! }) 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 h6 9. Nh3!? { The first time this move had been played by a GM in 70 years! Originally by Steinitz, it fell out of fashion after the 1891 Steinitz - Chigorin match, where white lost. Since Fischer's time, it has now been revitalized and is in fact one of the trendy ways to play for an advantage in this opening! } 9... Bc5!? (9... Bd6!? 10. d3 (10. d4? Qc7 $15) 10... O-O 11. Nc3 { Aronian, L. - Ding Liren, 1-0, Tata Steel India Blitz, 2019, https://lichess.org/g7uohoTx }) 10. O-O (10. d3!? O-O 11. Nc3 Re8 12. O-O Bxh3?! (12... Nb7 $10) 13. gxh3 Qd7 14. Bg4 Nxg4 15. hxg4 $14 { Fischer - Radoicich, 1963 }) 10... O-O 11. d3 Bxh3 12. gxh3 Qd7 13. Bf3! (13. Bg4?! Nxg4 14. hxg4 f5 $15 { "gives fair attacking chances" }) 13... Qxh3 { "Black regains the pawn, but I have faith in my two bishops." } 14. Nd2 Rad8 15. Bg2 Qf5?! (15... Qh4? 16. Qf3! $16 { The engine line is much better than Fischer's. } (16. Nf3?? Qh5 17. Qe1 { [%cal Ge1e5] } 17... Rfe8!! 18. Qxa5 e4!! 19. dxe4?? Bxf2+ 20. Rxf2 Qxa5 $19)) (15... Qe6 $10 { The best square. Black still has to contend with the two bishops, but at least his queen is out of danger. }) 16. Qe1? (16. Rb1! { [%cal Rb2b4] } 16... Nb7 17. Qf3 Nd6 18. Qxf5 Nxf5 19. Nc4 $16) 16... Rfe8 17. Ne4 Bb6 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Kh1 c5! { Rerouting the knight to d4. } 20. Qc3 Nc6 21. f4 Nd4! 22. Qc4 Qg6 (22... Qe6 23. Qa4 Qg4! $19 { Fischer missed this move! The queen will remain actively posted on g4 and/or h4, and black has a strong attack against Fischer's unsafe king. Meanwhile, white's queen is in Siberia! } (23... Qd7? 24. Qxd7 Rxd7 25. c3 Nc2 26. Bc6 $18)) 23. c3 Nf5? (23... Nc2! 24. Rb1 exf4 { [%cal Gc2e3] } 25. Be4 Rxe4! 26. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 27. dxe4 g5 $17 { Both players missed this chance for black to get a huge kingside pawn majority in exchange for the exchange. White has a tough time untangling with this untouchable knight controlling many key squares. }) 24. fxe5 Rxe5 25. Bf4 Re2 (25... Ne3 26. Bxe3 Rxe3 $10) 26. Be4 Rxb2?? { Fischer was sad that his opponent made this terrible blunder instead of playing the interesting: } (26... Re8! { [%cal Re8e4] } 27. Bf3 (27. Rg1? Qh5 28. Raf1 Ne3! 29. Qb5 { [%cal Gb5e8] } 29... Rxe4? { Fischer only analyzed this forcing line: } (29... Re7! { Black can play quietly though and keep all of his threats! } 30. Bf3 Qh4 31. Bxe2 Nxf1 32. Bxf1 Qxf4 $19 { Fischer misevaluated these further complications. Black has a winning line. }) 30. dxe4 Nxf1 31. Qe8+ Kh7 32. Rxg7+! Kxg7 33. Be5+ Qxe5 34. Qxe5+ f6 35. Qe7+ Kg6 36. Qe8+?? (36. Qe6! { No escaping the perpetual here! }) 36... Kg5 $19 { Black escapes the perpetual in the most forcing line. }) 27... Rxb2 28. Rae1 Rxe1 29. Rxe1 $15 { But white retains a strong bishop pair. }) 27. Be5 { Rxf5 cannot be stopped. } 27... Re8 28. Rxf5 Rxe5 29. Rxe5 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } 1-0


