{ "Romp" }
1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. f4 Nf6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Bd3 { This is the final round of Fischer's infamous 11-0 US Championship win in 1963-64, an unmatched feat to this very day. Benko plays into this though by going for the slightly dubious Pirc defense, allowing his opponent to pull off a further brilliancy to cap off his amazing tournament. } 6... Bg4? (6... Na6!? 7. e5 Nd7! $10 { There are some amazing lines in this variation, but it's supposed to be equal. } (7... dxe5 8. fxe5 Nd5 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $14 { Fischer thought this was fine for black, but the center can be maintained with c4+d5 and Qe2. })) 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nc6 9. Be3 e5 10. dxe5! dxe5 11. f5 { "Already threatening to obtain a winning bind with g4-g5" } 11... gxf5 (11... Nd4 12. Qf2 c5 13. g4 b5 14. g5 b4 $16 { This is black's best try, but white's play seems a bit easier than black's in this crazy position... }) 12. Qxf5 (12. exf5? e4! 13. Nxe4 Ne5 $14 { Thou shalt not allow counterplay! }) 12... Nd4 13. Qf2 (13. Qxe5!? Ng4 14. Qxg7+ Kxg7 15. hxg4 { Fischer was tempted to play into this queen sacrifice line, but couldn't find the refutation over the board to: } 15... Nc6? 16. O-O-O Re8 { But actually white keeps a strong bind on the position and can slowly start an attack on the open h and f files anyway. } 17. Bb5 Qe7 18. Rh5 $16) 13... Ne8 14. O-O (14. O-O-O!? Nd6 15. h4 c5 16. h5 b5 17. h6 Bf6 18. Nd5 $18 { Fischer wanted to keep the attack clean, but this is actually squeaky clean. }) 14... Nd6 15. Qg3 Kh8 (15... f5! 16. Bh6 Qf6 17. Bxg7 Qxg7 18. Qxg7+ Kxg7 19. exf5 N6xf5 20. Rae1 Rae8 21. Ne4 $16 { Best play, but white has a great game, playing against the weak IKP. }) 16. Qg4 { Now f5 is stopped forever. } 16... c6?! { "Too passive" } (16... c5! { With c4 coming, black gets some counterplay: } 17. b3 b5 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. Nxb5 Nxb5 20. Bxb5 $16) 17. Qh5 Qe8?? (17... b5?? 18. Bxd4 exd4 19. e5 $18 { [%cal Gh5h7,Gd3h7] }) (17... Ne6! $16 { Essential. Black needs to keep the dark squares near his king safely defended, and keep the e4 pawn under lock and key. }) 18. Bxd4! exd4 19. Rf6!! { A brilliant move. Fischer simply prevents Benko's one defensive idea at all costs, and h7 can no longer be defended. } (19. e5?? f5! { By threatening the queen trade, black has just enough to hold here. }) 19... Kg8 (19... dxc3?? 20. e5 $18 { [%cal Gh5h7,Gd3h7] }) (19... Bxf6?? 20. e5 $18 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gh5h7] }) (19... Nf5?? 20. Qxf5 $18 { [%cal Ge4e5,Gd3h7] }) 20. e5 h6 21. Ne2! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Fischer simply removes the threat on his knight and now there's no stopping Rxd6. Rather than deal with this endgame down a piece, Benko threw in the towel. } (21. Rxd6!? Qxe5 22. Qxe5 Bxe5 23. Ne4! Bxd6 24. Nxd6 $18 { Even here, the two pieces for the rook should have won the game, but Fischer instead finished with style. }) 21... Nb5?? (21... Bxf6?? 22. Qxh6 $18 { [%cal Gh6h7] }) 22. Qf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5h7] } 1-0


[Event "US Championship 1963/64"]
