{ "The Indian sign?" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Nc6?! 13. dxc5?! (13. d5 Nd8 $14 { Honestly not a great line for black because this knight will be dead for a while. }) 13... dxc5 { White will be giving up the center in order to plant pieces on the d5 and f5 squares. } 14. Nf1 { [%cal Gf1e3,Ge3d5,Ge3f5] } 14... Rd8 15. Qe2 Nh5 16. g3 { By killing the black knights, Fischer is hoping to claim that the kingside weaknesses he's created is irrelevant when faced with the active pieces he is about to get. Objectively, this is still probably equal. } (16. a4 Rb8 17. axb5 axb5 18. g3! $14 { A better way forward, following Fischer - Eliskases 1960. }) 16... g6 (16... Nf6 17. a4 b4 $10) (16... Bxh3? 17. Ng5 Bxg5 (17... Bxf1 18. Qxh5 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 f6 20. Bxf6! Rf8 21. Bxg7 Qxg7 22. Rxf1 $18) 18. Bxg5 f6 19. Be3 $16 { [%cal Ge2h5,Ge3c5] }) 17. h4 $146 { Fischer's improvement on Bronstein - Reshevsky, 1960. } 17... Be6 18. Ne3 f6? (18... Rac8 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. hxg5 Nd4!! 21. cxd4 cxd4 $10 { Black regains the piece and has fully justified the placement of all his pieces. The dark squared weaknesses on the kingside (and open h file) do not lead to an attack. } { [%cal Gc7c2,Gd4e3] }) 19. Nd5! { A move striving for the initative. This is reminiscent of another Fischer games from this book: https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/48T6nXQo#33 } 19... Qb7 (19... Bxd5? 20. exd5 Rxd5 21. a4 { [%csl Gb5] } 21... Rb8 22. axb5 axb5 23. c4 Nd4 24. Nxd4 Rxd4 25. cxb5 $16 { White has regained the pawn and has every light square forever. }) 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 { "White has the two bishops - or a 'half point' advantage." } 21. Nh2! { Fischer has time to reposition his worst-placed piece. The knight will reach a beautiful outpost on d5 just as its predecessor did! } { [%cal Gh2g4,Gg4e3,Ge3d5] } 21... Ng7 { [%cal Gc5c4,Gg7e6,Ge6c5] } 22. Ng4 c4 23. Qf3 { [%cal Rf3f6,Rg4f6] } 23... Bxg4 { Now white has the bishop pair against the knight pair, and should seek to blow up the board, with b3+f4+h5. } (23... Rf8 24. Ne3 $16 { By first deflecting the rook from the d file, this knight reposition is all the more powerful. }) 24. Qxg4 Ne6 25. h5 (25. Be3 Nc5?? 26. Bxc5 Qxc5 27. Qe6+ Kg7 28. Rad1 $16 { "penetrates decisively" }) 25... Kh8!? (25... g5? 26. Be3 { A better version of the other line. }) (25... Kg7 { The human move gets refuted with similar ideas. } 26. Be3! $16 (26. hxg6?! hxg6 27. Be3 Rh8 28. Rad1 { f4+f5 is coming, but there was better. })) 26. Kg2 (26. hxg6?! Rg8! $16 { Black's idea. As always, keeping the tension is preferable. }) 26... g5 (26... Rg8 { Black cannot maintain the tension forever. So g5 is going to have to be played eventually. } 27. Rh1 gxh5? (27... g5!?) 28. Qxh5 Nf4+ 29. Bxf4 exf4 30. e5 $18 { [%cal Gc2h7,Gh5h7] }) 27. Be3 Nf4+! 28. Kh2! (28. gxf4?? gxf4 $10 { [%cal Gd8g8,Gg8g2] }) 28... Nd3 29. Bxd3 cxd3?? { But Fischer hasn't over-committed to a kingside attack, meaning he has time to reposition his pieces to the center and collect this weak c3 pawn. } (29... Rxd3! 30. Red1 Rad8 31. Rxd3 cxd3 (31... Rxd3?? 32. Qc8+ Nd8 33. Qxa6 $18 { [%csl Rd1,Rd2,Rd3,Rd4,Rd5][%cal Gc3d4,Ge4d5,Ge3d2] }) 32. Rd1 Rd7 33. Rd2 $16 { Bc5! coming with "a winning bind" } { [%cal Ge3c5,Ge7c5,Gg4d7] }) 30. Red1 Rd7 31. Rd2 Na5 32. b3 Qd6 (32... Nb7 33. Rad1 Rad8 34. Bb6 Re8 35. Rxd3 Rxd3 36. Rxd3 $18 { The normal way to win the pawn. }) 33. Rad1 Re8 34. Rxd3 Qxd3 35. Qxd7! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { But the game simply wins with pizzazz. The x-ray attack on d7 means that white is fully up a pawn with no counterplay for black. } (35. Rxd3 Rxd3 36. Bc5 $18 { Also completely winning. }) 1-0


[Event "US Championship 1963/64"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1963.12.18"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Robert Eugene Byrne"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E60"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Fianchetto Variation, Immediate Fianchetto"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert Eugene Byrne - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/MYWxGe0b"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The brilliancy prize" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 (2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Nc3 { The Jobava London. } 4... cxd4 5. exd4 a6 { [%cal Gc3b5,Ra6b5] } 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Ne5! $14 { Black should not allow Nxc6 bxc6, because white is quick to blockade the c6 pawn with Na4->c5. }) 2... g6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nc3 Bg7 { This game starts with a symmetric Gruenfeld - the calmest of variations for white. } 7. e3?! (7. Nf3 O-O 8. Ne5! { An idea used to prove an advantage in a critical variation of the Jobava London (see the beginning variation for more) } 8... Bf5 (8... Nc6?! 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Bf5 $14 { [%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5] }) 9. O-O Ne4 10. Qb3 Nc6 11. Qxd5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qxd5 13. Bxd5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Bxe5 $10 { Benko - Fischer, 1962. }) 7... O-O 8. Nge2 Nc6 9. O-O b6 10. b3 (10. Nf4 e6 11. b3 Ba6 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Rc1 $10 { With perfect symmetry, Stahlberg - Flohr, 1937 was a quick draw. }) 10... Ba6 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Qd2 e5! { Fischer is arguing that the IQP is irrelevant, since opening up the bishop pair against white's slightly poorly placed pieces is more important. } (12... e6 $10 { "would probably lead to a draw" }) 13. dxe5 Nxe5 { White's best placed piece is the g2 bishop, defending the light squares around the king and attacking black's weak IQP. However, every other piece is slightly worse than black's corresponding pieces. That leads Fischer to start looking for tactics... } { [%csl Gg2] } 14. Rfd1? (14. Rad1! Ne4 (14... Qc8!! { In response to Averbakh's "refutation" to his original analysis, Fischer finally found the following move (SF14 approved!) } 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Rd8 17. f4 Rxd5 18. Qxd5 Bb7 19. Qd2 Qc6 20. Qd5 Qxd5 21. Rxd5 Bxd5 22. fxe5 Bxe5 $15 { An insane line! }) 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Bxe4 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 Nc4! { [%cal Re8e4] } 18. Bxa8 Nxd2 19. Rd1 Nc4?! 20. bxc4? (20. Bc6! Nxa3 21. Bxe8 Bxe2 22. Rd7 $18 { Averbakh found this hole in Fischer's original analysis of the "correct play." }) 20... Rxa8 $15 { "with a big endgame advantage." }) (14. Nf4? Bxf1 15. Rxf1 Ne4! 16. Nxe4 dxe4 $19 { There is no exchange sac in this position either. }) 14... Nd3!! { The original octopus knight! With the bishop on a6 firmly cementing this knight on d3, it is safely hitting everything in white's position, and absolutely dominating the d file as well. Black threatens Ne4, fully cementing the knight on d3 forever. } { [%cal Rd3f2,Rd3e1,Rd3c1,Rd3b2] } 15. Qc2? (15. Nd4? Ne4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bb2 Rc8 $19) (15. Nf4 { The best engine line still gets white nowhere. } 15... Ne4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rab1 Rc8 18. Nxd3? Bc3! 19. Qe2 Bxd3 $19) 15... Nxf2!! { "The complete justification for this sac does not become apparent until white resigns!" } 16. Kxf2 Ng4+ 17. Kg1 Nxe3! { A second octopus knight enters the field. } { [%cal Re3g2,Re3d1,Re3c2] } 18. Qd2 Nxg2!! { Fischer correctly recognizes that the rook on d1 is irrelevant when compared to the key defender of white's king. Now the bishop pair will swarm into the position against the naked king on g2. } (18... Nxd1?? 19. Rxd1 $10) 19. Kxg2 d4! { A key clearance sacrifice of the long diagonal } { [%cal Rb7g2] } 20. Nxd4 Bb7+ 21. Kf1 (21. Kg1 Bxd4+ 22. Qxd4 Re1+! 23. Kf2 Qxd4+ 24. Rxd4 Rxa1 25. Rd7 Rc8 26. Rxb7 Rxc3 27. Rb8+ Kg7 28. Bb2 Rxa2! $19 { "equally hopeless" }) (21. Kf2 Qd7 22. Rac1 Qh3 23. Nf3 Bh6! { [%cal Rh6e3,Re3c1] } 24. Qd3 Be3+ 25. Qxe3 Rxe3 26. Kxe3 Re8+ 27. Kf2 Qf5! $19 { "finis!" } { [%cal Rb7f3,Rf5f3] }) 21... Qd7 $19 { Fisher was disappointed that Byrne resigned here rather than play out the brilliant finish: } 22. Qf2 Qh3+ 23. Kg1 Re1+!! 24. Rxe1 (24. Qxe1?? Qg2#) 24... Bxd4! $19 { Unstoppable mate on g2 coming. } { [%cal Rh3g2,Rb7g2] } 0-1


