{ "A complex trap" }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 (6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 $10 { The more modern way to approach this line. The pawn being on h5 means that an eventual g4-g5 pawn break hits with greater effect. }) 6... Nf6 7. h4 h6 8. Bd3 (8. Ne5 Bh7 9. Bc4 e6 10. Qe2 Nd5! $10 (10... Qxd4?? 11. Nxf7! Kxf7 12. Qxe6+ Kg6 13. h5#)) 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 e6 10. Bd2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O Qc7 12. c4 O-O-O 13. Bc3 { While this exact position isn't theory, the ideas that white and black are using occur in many of the main lines of the classical Caro Kann. } 13... Qf4+? { "The start of a faulty concept" } (13... Bd6 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 c5 16. d5 exd5 17. Qxd5 Nf6 18. Qf5+ Qd7 19. Qxd7+ Rxd7 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Rhe1 $10 { White can hope for a slight pull in this endgame, but with the bishop against knight, it should be level. }) 14. Kb1 Nc5?? 15. Qc2 Nce4 16. Ne5! { A clear refutation to Steinmeyer's idea. Now the queen is trapped behind enemy lines. } 16... Nxf2 (16... Nxg3?? 17. fxg3 Qxg3 18. Rd3 Qf4 19. Rf3 Qe4 20. Nxf7 $18) (16... Nxc3+? 17. bxc3! Rg8 18. Rd3! h5 19. Rf3 Qh6 20. Nxf7 $18) (16... Re8 17. Nxf7 Rg8 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Ne5 $18) 17. Rdf1! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Black resigned, admitting that his entire concept was fundamentally flawed. White wins an exchange at least in the main line. } 17... Qxg3 18. Rxf2 Qe3 (18... Bd6 19. Rf3 $18 { Trapping the queen. }) 19. Re2 Qf4 20. Nxf7 $18 { With this game, Fischer won the 1963-64 US Championship 11-0. } 1-0


