[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Squeeze play" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 { "long abandoned" - and yet Carlsen uses it as his main weapon to avoid theory in the Ruy Lopez. } 5... d6 (5... Bc5 6. c3 b5 7. Bc2 O-O 8. O-O d5 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. h3 h6 11. d4 exd4 $10 { Anderssen - Morphy, 1858 }) 6. c3 Be7 7. Nbd2 O-O 8. Nf1 { By making this maneuver before castling, white saves a move having to avoid a later Re1. } 8... b5 9. Bb3 d5! { Black is trying to prove that white cannot keep his king in the center forever. } 10. Qe2 dxe4?! (10... d4! 11. Ng3 a5! $15 { By keeping the tension and the space advantage, black can seek play on all sides of the board in order to claim a slight advantage. } (11... dxc3?! 12. bxc3 b4 13. Bd2 $14 { Fischer's suggestions indeed give white the advantage. })) 11. dxe4 Be6?! (11... Re8 12. Ng5 Rf8 13. Nf3 $10 { A potential quick draw. }) 12. Bxe6 fxe6 { Smyslov is banking that the active play on the d and f files will make up for his structural weakness. That evaluation is misguided. } 13. Ng3 { Temporarily misplaced, but white needs to castle before regrouping to attack the double isolated e pawns. } 13... Qd7 14. O-O Rad8 15. a4 Qd3! 16. Qxd3 Rxd3 { With the queens off the board, black's weaknesses are hard to attack. } 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ra6! (18. Re1 Bc5! 19. Ra6 Rd6 $10 { This reorganization of black's pieces would have been quite convenient. }) 18... Rd6 { [%cal Re7c5] } 19. Kh1 (19. Re1?! { A careless move by white would allow a favorable series of exchanges: } 19... Nd4! 20. Rxd6 Nxf3+ 21. gxf3 cxd6 $10) 19... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7c5,Rc5a6] } 20. Be3 { [%cal Re3c5] } 20... Rd8 (20... b4! $10 { Weakening white's queenside pawn structure gives black some much-needed activity. }) 21. h3?! (21. b4! $16 { Stopping black's plan is more important than giving up the c3/c4 squares. }) 21... h6 (21... b4! $10) 22. Rfa1 Ndb8 23. Ra8 Rd1+ 24. Kh2 Rxa1 25. Rxa1 Nd7?! (25... b4 26. cxb4 Bxb4 27. Nf1 { Black needs this pawn break in order to achieve some freedom for his pieces. }) 26. b4! Kf7 (26... Nb6 27. Bxb6! cxb6 $16) 27. Nf1 Bd6 (27... Ke8 28. g3 Nb6 29. Bxb6 cxb6 30. Ne1 $14 { Black has to accept this endgame if he wants any chance anymore... but I think it's easy to see why Smyslov rejected this. These pawns look ridiculous. } { [%cal Re1d3] }) 28. g3 { [%cal Rd6h2] } 28... Nf6 29. N1d2 Ke7 30. Ra6! Nb8 31. Ra5! c6 { "By forcing c6, we take away another breathing space from black's pieces" } 32. Kg2 Nbd7 33. Kf1 Rc8 34. Ne1 Ne8 (34... c5 35. Rxb5 cxb4 36. cxb4 $18 { Amazingly, there's no route for black to get behind this passed pawn. } { [%cal Rd2b3,Re1c2,Rd2b1,Gb4b8] }) 35. Nd3 Nc7 { Preparing Ra8, trading pieces. } 36. c4! bxc4 (36... Ra8?? 37. c5 Rxa5 38. cxd6+ Kxd6 39. bxa5 $18) (36... Kd8 37. c5 Be7 38. Nf3 Bf6 $18 { White's pieces are all perfect, active, and attacking black's weaknesses, where-as black is choking in his lack of space. }) 37. Nxc4 { [%cal Rc4e5,Rd3e5,Ra5e5] } 37... Nb5 38. Ra6 { Stopping Ra8 again. } 38... Kf6 39. Bc1 { [%cal Gc1b2,Rb2f6] } 39... Bb8 40. Bb2 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 40... c5 41. Nb6! Nxb6 42. Rxb6 c4 43. Nc5 c3 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Smyslov, lacking all mobility due to his lack of space, does not have enough with this single passed pawn. Fischer believes the game could have continued: } 44. Bc1 Nd4 45. Nd7+ Ke7 46. Nxb8 Nb3 47. Rb7+ Kd8 48. Rd7+ Ke8 49. Rxg7 Nxc1?? 50. Rg8+ Ke7 51. Rxc8 $18 1-0


[Event "USA-ch"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1965.12.27"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Nicolas Rossolimo"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C12"]
[Opening "French Defense: McCutcheon Variation, Lasker Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
