[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/PYpx21ia"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Peekabooo strategy" }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 (3... Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4 { A mainline Winawer, showcasing the pawn structure that arises from the McCutcheon. }) 4. Bg5 Bb4 5. e5 h6 6. Bd2 Bxc3 7. bxc3 Ne4 8. Qg4 g6 9. Bd3 Nxd2 10. Kxd2 c5 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Qf4 Qc7? (12... Qa5 13. Rhb1 $10 { Modern theory } { [%cal Gc5d4] }) 13. h4 { Horvath, Adam - Kraai, Jesse, 1-0, Hotel Irottko GM, 2000, https://lichess.org/KXjBQsAp } (13. dxc5! $16) 13... f5 14. g4 (14. exf6?? Qxf4+ $19 { This move would have been good positionally.... but oh no my queen! }) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 Ne7? { Black is trying to support his kingside pawns, when really he needs to be counterattacking white's tender queenside structure. } { [%cal Ge7f5,Ge7g6] } (15... Bd7 { Rossolimo's recommendation, but Fischer liked: } 16. gxf5 gxf5 17. Rhg1 O-O-O 18. Rg6 $10 { Black's king reaches safety in this line, so the slightly active pieces aren't enough to do anything scary. }) 16. gxf5 exf5 17. Bb5+! Kf8 (17... Bd7 18. Bxd7+ Qxd7 19. e6! Qxe6 20. Rhe1 $16 { White's king is perfectly safe in the center where-as black's king is nearly checkmated. }) (17... Kd8 18. Bd3 Be6 $16 { "It's hard to get at the black king" now that black has clogged the e file. There should be some sort of breakthrough on the c or b file though with precise play. }) 18. Bd3 { "Mission accomplished" } 18... Be6 19. Ng1! { [%cal Rf4g6,Rf4e6,Rf4d5,Gg1h3,Gh3f4] } 19... Kf7 20. Nh3 Rac8 21. Rhg1?? (21. Ke2! Qc3 22. Rab1 b6 23. Rb3 Qc7 24. h5! $18 { The precise way to implement Fischer's plan in the game. }) 21... b6?? (21... Qc3+! 22. Ke3 Rc6 23. Rab1 Rb6! 24. Rxb6 axb6 $14 { By distracting white's pieces to the queenside (and trading a pair of rooks), black lessens the kingside pressure and reminds white that the fight should also take place on the side of the board where black has a larger presence: the queenside. }) 22. h5! Qc3+ (22... g5?? 23. Nxg5+ hxg5 24. Qxg5 $18 { [%cal Gg5f6,Gg5g7] }) 23. Ke2 Nc6 (23... Rcg8!? 24. hxg6+ Rxg6 25. Qh4 $18 { Threatening either Qf6+ or Ng5+ depending on what black does. }) 24. hxg6+ Kg7 { Notice how throughout all the following sidelines (and indeed the main game), the knight reaches f4, which breaks black's light squared blockade and opens the floodgate for white's pieces to infiltrate to the weakened black king. } (24... Ke7 25. Qh4+ Kd7 26. Rad1! Nxd4+?? (26... Qxd4 27. Nf4! $18 { [%cal Rf4e6,Rf4d5,Rf4g6] }) 27. Qxd4 Qxd4 28. Bb5+ $18 { [%cal Gd1d4] }) 25. Rad1! (25. Qh4 Nxd4+ 26. Kf1 Qxa1+ 27. Kg2 Qc3 28. Nf4 $18 { Going straight at the black king, even down a rook (with check!) also wins. Fischer follows Yusupov's maxim: "thou shalt not allow counterplay." }) 25... Nxd4+ (25... Qxd4 26. Kf1! Qxe5 (26... Qxf4 27. Nxf4 Rhe8 28. Nxe6+ Rxe6 29. Bxf5 $18) 27. Re1 Qxf4 28. Nxf4 Bd7 29. Nh5+ Kg8 30. g7 Rh7 31. Nf6+ Kf7 32. Nxh7 $18) 26. Kf1 Rhe8 27. Rg3 (27. Qh4? { Rushes things } 27... Nf3 28. Qf6+ Kg8 29. Bxf5 Nh2+ 30. Kg2 Qf3+ 31. Kxh2 Qxf5 { Black is almost out of the woods here, but there's one move that Fischer missed: } 32. Nf4!! $18 { And white maintains the initiative or two connected passed pawns on the 6th rank. }) 27... Nc6 28. Qh4 Nxe5 29. Nf4 { The knight reaches its dream square, breaking the light square blockade, and the game immediately ends. } 29... Ng4 30. Nxe6+ Rxe6 31. Bxf5 Qc4+ 32. Kg1! $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Fischer avoids the last trick, and there is no stopping either Qxg4 or Bxe6, completely winning. } (32. Kg2?? Ne3+ 33. fxe3 Qxh4 $19) (32. Rgd3?? Ne3+ 33. fxe3 Qxh4 $19) 1-0


[Event "Second Piatigorsky Cup"]
[Site "Santa Monica, CA USA"]
[Date "1966.08.03"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Lajos Portisch"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E45"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: St. Petersburg Variation, Fischer Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Lajos Portisch - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/pAGKUZNa"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Black magic" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 { Fischer rarely played the Nimzo-Indian, so he must have prepared a special line against Portisch... } 4. e3 (4. Bg5?! h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 (6. e3 cxd4 7. exd4 O-O 8. Bd3 d5 $10) 6... d6 7. e3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 e5 $10) 4... b6 5. Ne2 (5. Bd3 Bb7 6. Nf3 $10 { White doesn't quite get everything they want - the knight on f3 is misplaced, and the c3 knight has less protection. }) 5... Ba6 6. Ng3 (6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 d5 8. b3 O-O $14) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d5 8. Qf3 (8. cxd5 Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Qxd5 $10 { The threat of Qc4+ means that white doesn't have time for f3+Kf2 yet. }) 8... O-O 9. e4!? dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 Qd7! (11... Nd7 12. Bd3 Nf6 13. Qh4 $14 { White has "the two bishops and a beautiful development despite the doubled pawns." Fischer loved his bishops, so I can definitely see how he would not be a fan of this position. }) 12. Ba3 (12. Qxa8? Nc6 13. Qxf8+ Kxf8 $19 { Black gets a huge lead in development and a lot of targets. }) (12. Bd3!? f5 13. Qe2 Nc6 $10 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ra5c4,Ra6c4] }) 12... Re8 13. Bd3 f5 14. Qxa8? (14. Qe2 Nc6 $15 { Portisch should have accepted he's not better anymore. } { [%cal Gc6a5,Ra5c4,Ra6c4,Gd7c6,Rc6c4] }) 14... Nc6 15. Qxe8+ Qxe8 16. O-O Na5 17. Rae1 (17. Rfe1 Bxc4 18. Bxf5?? Qa4! $19) 17... Bxc4 (17... Qa4! 18. Bb4 Bxc4 19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Rxe6 a5 21. Be7 Nd2 22. Rfe1 Ne4 23. f3 Qxa2 $18 { Fischer only saw this winning continuation in his post-mortem. } { [%cal Ga2e6,Ga2f2] }) 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Bc1 c5 20. dxc5 bxc5 21. Bf4 h6 22. Re2 (22. h4? e5! 23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24. f4 Nf3+! 25. gxf3 Qa4 $18 { [%cal Ga4a2,Ga4f4] }) 22... g5 23. Be5 Qd8 24. Rfe1 Kf7 25. h3 f4 { Fischer has placed all of his pawns on dark squares to (a) defend themselves and (b) blunt this bishop from accessing any targets. With the active queen and dominant knight, the weak queenside pawns will be eventual food for a roaming queen. } 26. Kh2 a6 27. Re4 Qd5 { "The queen is boss." } 28. h4? Ne3! 29. R1xe3 (29. f3?! Qd2 { [%cal Rd2e1] } 30. Rg1?? Qf2! $19 { [%cal Rf2h4] }) 29... fxe3 30. Rxe3 Qxa2 31. Rf3+ Ke8 { No more dark squared bishop checks to worry about. The queen is obviously better than the bishop+rook, which cannot coordinate to stop the passed a and soon-to-be passed c pawn. } 32. Bg7 Qc4 33. hxg5 hxg5 34. Rf8+ Kd7 35. Ra8 Kc6 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%cal Ga6a1] } 0-1


[Event "Second Piatigorsky Cup"]
[Site "Santa Monica, CA USA"]
[Date "1966.08.11"]
[Round "16"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Miguel Najdorf"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B44"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Taimanov Variation, Szén Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Miguel Najdorf"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/LvsMFdli"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Najdorf's night off from the Najdorf" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Najdorf avoids the Najdorf variation! } (2... d6 { He lost with this move earlier against Fischer: https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/y2i6gF9K }) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nb5 { The move I play as well, but theoretically should be equal. } (5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 $10 { The main theoretical battleground of this opening starts here }) 5... d6 6. Bf4!? (6. c4 Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 $10 { Not the easiest Maroczy bind to play. }) 6... e5 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Bg5 { Going into the Sveshnikov, down a tempo cannot be best play from white. } 8... Be6 9. N1c3 a6 10. Bxf6?! gxf6 11. Na3 Nd4! (11... d5!! $15 $146 { Fischer, Robert James - Petrosian, Tigran V, 1-0, Candidates final, 1971, https://lichess.org/ANomu9GL } { Petrosian's novelty is not yet mentioned in this book. Fischer won a brilliant game in the Candidates 1971 match, but was worse out of the opening. }) 12. Bc4 (12. Nc4 { If: } 12... Rc8 (12... f5! $17 $146 { Fischer missed the best move in his annotations, and Taimanov uncorked it in their Candidates match in 1971. Again, Fischer won a brilliant game but was worse out of the opening. } { Fischer, Robert James - Taimanov, Mark E, 1-0, Candidates qf3, 1971, https://lichess.org/KPdmwLee }) 13. Ne3 Bh6? 14. Bd3 Rg8 $16 { Fischer does not appreciate the subtleties of these positions and his notes have several holes that both Petrosian, Taimanov, and future players of this line as black have filled. }) 12... b5?! (12... d5! { Black can immediately strike in the center, punishing Fischer for misplacing his pieces and wasting tempi in the opening: } 13. Nxd5 (13. exd5? Bxa3 14. bxa3 Qa5 15. Qd2 Rc8 16. Bd3 Bxd5 $19) 13... Rc8! 14. Ne3 Bxa3 15. Bxe6 Qa5+ 16. Kf1 fxe6 $17) 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Ne2 (14. O-O?? b4 $19) 14... Nc6 15. Ng3 { "If black's central pawn mass can be restrained, then it becomes merely a fixed target subject to constant pressure." } 15... Qd7 (15... h5! { The type of move that people would find immediately in 2021 (post Alphazero), but never in 1965. } { [%cal Gh5h4] } 16. Nxh5 Kf7 { Where black has opened up the h file for his rook, and after d5, all of his pawns will start pushing in the center, creating a terrible bind. } { [%cal Gd6d5] }) 16. c4 Nd4 (16... bxc4? 17. Nxc4 $16 { [%cal Gc4b6,Rb6d7,Rb6a8,Gc4e3,Be3d5,Be3f5] }) 17. O-O { Black needs to both maintain the tension with the c pawn and stop himself from pushing the central pawns. If black's king could get to safety, these pawns could start marching. But as-is, white's got a firm grip on the light squares, and so is better. } 17... b4? (17... Rc8 $14 { Keeping the tension is preferable. }) 18. Nc2 Nxc2 19. Qxc2 h5 20. Rfd1? (20. h4 $16 { Fixing the target on h5 to be taken later. }) 20... h4 21. Nf1 Rg8? (21... h3 22. g3 Qc6 $14 { "with reasonable play" } 23. a3?! b3! { The difference between this variation and the game } 24. Qxb3? Qxe4 $17 { [%cal Ge4g2] }) 22. a3! h3 23. g3 bxa3 (23... Qc6? 24. axb4 $18) 24. Rxa3 Qc6 25. Qe2 { White's pieces are all active, except for the knight on f1. Black's pieces are all at home, watching TV. } 25... f5? { You cannot open the center when your king has nowhere safe to run to. } 26. c5! Qxe4 (26... dxc5? 27. Qh5+ Ke7 28. Rad3 fxe4 29. R3d2 $18 { [%cal Gf1e3] }) (26... Qxc5? 27. Qh5+ Kd7 28. exf5 $18) (26... Kf7!? 27. Ne3 Qxe4 28. cxd6 $16) 27. Qxe4? (27. Qh5+! Ke7 28. cxd6+ Kf6 29. Ne3 f4 30. f3! Qb7 31. Nc4 $18 { A very scary line, where white is completely winning at the end of it. No wonder Fischer didn't even see this after the post-mortem. }) 27... fxe4 28. cxd6 { This position is good for white because black's pawns are a mess, but this would be even better for white if the queens were on the board to better take advantage of black's unsafe king. The mate on g2 can always have been stopped with Ne3. } 28... Bh6 29. Ra5 Kd7 30. Rxe5 Bg7 31. Rxe4 Bxb2 32. Ne3 a5 { Fischer thinks that his opponent could have resigned in this position, but I think it's still a game until the blockade of the passed d pawn can be kicked away. } 33. Nc4! { [%cal Gc4b6,Gc4e5,Re5d7,Rb6d7] } 33... Rgb8! { Stopping Nb6+ and maintaining the blockade. } 34. Rh4! { [%cal Gh4h7,Rh7d7] } (34. Ne5+?? Bxe5 35. Rxe5 a4 $10) 34... Kc6 35. Rh7 Bd4 36. Rc7+ Kd5 37. d7 { The blockade has been lifted and now it's clear that white is crushing it. } 37... a4 38. Nb6+ (38. Rc8 Rxc8 39. Nb6+ Kc5 40. dxc8=Q+? (40. Rc1+!! { The zwischenzug that breaks all further resistance. } 40... Kxb6 41. Rxc8 $18 { [%cal Gd7d8] }) 40... Rxc8 41. Nxc8 a3 $18 { "with some practical chances," but white should still be winning with best play. }) 38... Rxb6 39. Rc8 Rd6 40. Rxa8 Rxd7 41. Rxa4 { Instead Fischer opts for this line which prolongs the game, but avoids any possibilities of venom. } 41... e5 42. Kf1 Rb7 43. f4 Ke6 44. fxe5 Rf7+ 45. Ke2 Rf2+ 46. Kd3 Bxe5 47. Re1 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Fischer sets up a winning king and pawn endgame. Najdorf resigned rather than play it out: } 47... Rf5 48. Ra5 Kf6 49. Rexe5 Rxe5 50. Rxe5 Kxe5 51. Ke3 Kf5 52. Kd4 (52. Kf3 { Going for the h pawn immediately does not work though } 52... Kg5 53. g4?? Kh4 54. Kf4 $10 { Stalemate! }) 52... Kg5 53. Ke5 Kg4 54. Ke4 Kg5 55. Kf3 Kf5 56. g4+ $18 { [%cal Gf3g3,Gg3h3] } 1-0


