[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Jacek B Bednarski"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/xqV429uI"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The price of incaution" }
1. e4 c5 (1... e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. fxe5 Nxe4 5. d3? Qh4+?! (5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 d4 $15) 6. g3 Nxg3 7. Nf3! $10 { This line in the Vienna parallels the game: look at move 12. }) 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 { Taking up the Fischer variation again } 6... e6 7. Bb3 Nbd7 { [%cal Gd7c5,Rc5b3] } 8. f4 Nc5 9. f5 Nfxe4? { "Playing with fire" } (9... Be7! { The correct way forward. } 10. Qf3 e5 (10... O-O!? 11. Be3 $10) 11. Nde2 Nxb3 12. axb3 b5 $10 13. Nxb5!? (13. Bg5 Bb7 $10) 13... d5! $10) 10. fxe6 Qh4+?? (10... Bxe6 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe6 Qh4+! 13. g3 Nxg3 14. Bg5! Qe4+ 15. Kd2! Nxh1 16. Nc7+ Kd7 17. Nxa8 { Fischer thought this position was winning for white, but in fact, there's a follow-up check! } 17... Qg2+! 18. Kc1 (18. Kc3!? Qxg5 19. Qxh1? Qe3+ 20. Kc4 $17) 18... Qxg5+ 19. Kb1 Nf2 $17) 11. g3 Nxg3 12. Nf3! { A classic twist that arises in several positions, such as in the Vienna line, given above. } 12... Qh5 13. exf7+ Kd8 14. Rg1 Nf5 15. Nd5 { Black's attack has backfired, as now white's pieces are ready to attack the naked black king! } 15... Qxf7 (15... h6? 16. Nf4 $18 { Traps the queen }) 16. Bg5+ Ke8 17. Qe2+ (17. Nf6+ gxf6 18. Bxf7+ $18 { At this point, Fischer is winning the queen, but he clearly wants more... }) 17... Be6 18. Nf4 Kd7 19. O-O-O { The Morphy move. Now every single white piece is attacking the centralized black monarch. Ne5+ is threatened. } 19... Qe8 (19... Nxb3+ 20. axb3 Qe8 21. Rge1 Bg8 22. Qd3 $18) (19... Bxb3 20. Ne5+ Kc7 21. Nxf7 Bxf7 $18 { Black's best try is terrible. He's obviously busted at this point. }) 20. Bxe6+ Nxe6 21. Qe4! { [%cal Ge4b7,Ge4f5] } 21... g6 22. Nxe6 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Bednarski resigned rather than play out the following variation: } 22... Qxe6 23. Qxb7+ Ke8 24. Rge1 $18 1-0


[Event "Havana ol (Men) fin-A"]
[Site "Havana CUB"]
