[Round "8.1"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Svetozar Gligoric"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation, Gligoric Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Svetozar Gligoric"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/lAq2Nz5G"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The Fischer continuation" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 { Fischer rarely played the exchange Ruy Lopez. He played this line against Portisch a few rounds earlier and thought he should repeat it against Gligoric too. } 4... dxc6 5. O-O f6 (5... Bg4!? 6. h3 h5 $10 { A famous fishing pole trap introduced by Alapin. }) 6. d4 Bg4 (6... exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 $10 { Fischer saw a previous game with Portisch in this line. }) 7. c3 exd4 8. cxd4 Qd7 (8... c5!? 9. d5 Bd6 $10 { Gligoric himself had recommended this line after playing in Hastings 1965, but had forgotten it when playing Fischer only one year later! }) 9. h3 Be6! (9... Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Qxd4? 11. Rd1 Qc4 12. Bf4 $16 { Don't get greedy! }) (9... Bh5!? 10. Ne5!? Bxd1 11. Nxd7 Kxd7 12. Rxd1 $14) 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Bf4 Ne7?! (11... g5 { "The critical line" } 12. Bg3 h5 13. d5! h4 (13... cxd5?? 14. Rc1! Bd6 (14... dxe4?? { leads to another fantastic win: } 15. Na4! { [%cal Ga4b6,Rb6d7,Rb6c8] } 15... Kb8 16. Rxc7!! Qxd1 17. Rc8+!! Kxc8 (17... Ka7 18. Bb8+ Ka8 19. Nb6#) 18. Nb6#) 15. Na4 Kb8 16. Nc5 Bxc5 (16... Qe7?? { Fischer analyzed this blunder out to a win for white without commenting on the best play. } 17. Nxa6+ bxa6 18. Nd4 { [%cal Rc6e7,Rc6b8,Gd4c6] } 18... Bd7 19. Qb3+ Ka7 20. Rxc7+!! Bxc7 21. Bxc7 Bb5 22. Nc6+! Bxc6 (22... Ka8 23. Nxe7 $18) 23. Qb6+ Ka8 24. Qxa6#) 17. Rxc5 dxe4 18. Qc2 $16) 14. Bh2 Bxh3 15. gxh3 Qxh3 16. Kh1 Bd6 17. e5! Bxe5 18. Nxe5 fxe5 $10 { Mary, Patrick - Mehlhorn, Wolfgang, 1/2-1/2, CL/2012/C11, https://lichess.org/EdAMkXzc }) 12. Rc1 Ng6 13. Bg3 Bd6 14. Na4 Bxg3? { "Yielding the c5 square permanently to the knight" } (14... Kb8 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Rxc5 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Re1 $16) 15. fxg3 Kb8 16. Nc5 Qd6 17. Qa4 Ka7?? (17... Bc8!? { "Always play Bf8" -Ben Finegold. When you're castling queenside, that translate to Bc8! } 18. Rc3 Nf8 $14 { "black might have hung on" }) (17... Qxg3?? 18. Nxe6 $18) 18. Nxa6! Bxh3 (18... bxa6 19. Rxc6 $18 { [%cal Ga4a6,Rc6d6] }) 19. e5! Nxe5 (19... fxe5 20. Nc5+ Kb8 21. Rc3 $18 { The knight on c5 controls the d7 escape square, so Rh8 is going to be mate. } { [%cal Gc3a3] }) 20. dxe5 fxe5 21. Nc5+ Kb8 22. gxh3 e4 { Gligoric maintains his desperate ploy to distract Fischer from the simple mate of Rc3->a3+Qh8#, but it has cost him too much material. } { [%cal Rd6g3] } 23. Nxe4 { [%cal Be4g3] } 23... Qe7 24. Rc3 b5 25. Qc2 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Fischer has consolidated and is now 2 pieces ahead. There are no more tricks in the position, so Gligoric resigned. } 1-0


[Event "Monte Carlo"]
[Site "Monte Carlo MNC"]
[Date "1967.03.28"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Bent Larsen"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E97"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Orthodox Variation, Aronin-Taimanov Defense"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Bent Larsen - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/GAtXHpAV"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Change of pace" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Be2 O-O 6. Nf3 e5 7. O-O Nc6 8. Be3!? (8. d5 Ne7 9. Ne1 Nd7 10. Nd3 f5 11. Bd2 { The main line that Fischer had expected, and he had prepared the following line: } 11... c5!? 12. f3 (12. Rb1!?) 12... f4 $14 { where black is playing with a cramped setup, but solid. }) 8... Re8?! (8... Ng4 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bc1 $10 { The main line is still definitely the way to go here as black. }) 9. dxe5! (9. d5?! Nd4 $10) 9... dxe5 10. Qxd8 (10. h3!? { A modern improvement in this line. }) 10... Nxd8 { Trying to get a new position - interestingly this became the main line in the 1990s. } (10... Rxd8 11. Bg5 Rd7 (11... Rf8 $10 { "solves all black's problems" }) 12. Bd1! $14 { Benko's invention: activating the bishop on a4 where it now pins the c6 knight. } { [%cal Gd1a4] }) 11. Nb5 Ne6 12. Ng5 Re7 13. Rfd1 (13. Nxe6 Bxe6 14. f3 c6 15. Nc3 $10 { Reshevsky - Fischer, 1966 }) 13... b6! $146 { Fischer had prepared this novelty "a long time ago" } (13... c6!? { Reshevsky - Fischer followed this line, but Larsen had prepared the following novelty (engine approved!): } 14. Nxa7! Bd7 (14... Rxa7?? 15. Nxe6 $18) 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. f3 Rd7! $10 { "Black has fair play for the pawn" }) 14. c5?! (14. Rac1!?) (14. a4!? { The new main move is interesting as well. }) 14... Nxc5 (14... bxc5? 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Bxc5 Rd7 17. f3 $16) 15. Rd8+ Bf8 16. Nxa7 Rxa7 (16... Bb7?! 17. Rxa8 Bxa8 18. f3 $14 { The knight is misplaced on a7, but not trapped: } 18... c6? 19. Nc8! Rb7 20. Rd1 $16) 17. Rxc8 { The dust has settled, and Fischer firmly believes that his position is perfectly equal. With play on the open a and possibly d files, it's believable. White can't really play Bxc5 and expect to get anywhere because the newly weakened dark squares ensure the ending will always be better for black (even down a pawn) } 17... Kg7 18. f3 Ne8 (18... Re8!? 19. Rxe8 Nxe8 20. a3 $10 { Possibly Fischer believed this would get black nowhere, but to my eyes, this seems like black has quickly untangled and can soon pressure the queenside. There are no weaknesses in black's position. }) 19. a3 Nd6 20. Rd8 (20. Rb8 Nd7 21. Rd8 Nb7 22. Rc8 Nd6 $10 { Since there is this draw by repetition, it's clear that Larsen wants to win this game too. }) 20... h6 21. Nh3 Ne6 22. Rb8 Re8 23. Rxe8 Nxe8 { We reach a similar position to that one reached in note 18. } 24. Bb5?! { Larsen tries to prevent Bc5, taking full control of the dark squares, but this is only short-lived. } (24. Nf2 Bc5 25. Bxc5 Nxc5 26. Nd3 $10 { At least here, white's knight is not marooned on the side of the board. }) 24... Nd6 25. Bf1 Nb7 26. Nf2 Bc5 27. Bxc5 Nbxc5 28. Rd1 h5! { Fischer has full control of the dark squares (f4 and d4 in particular), so now he begins prophylaxis against white's pieces. } (28... Nd4?! 29. Ng4 { [%cal Rg4e5] } 29... f6 30. f4! $10) 29. Rd5 (29. Nd3! Nxd3 30. Bxd3 Nd4 31. Kf2 $15 { A good knight - bad bishop ending. With the active pieces though, white should not yet be lost. }) 29... Kf6 30. h4 Ke7! 31. Bc4 (31. Rxe5?? c6 $19 { [%cal Gc5d7,Rd7e5] }) 31... c6 32. Rd2 Nd4! { Well-timed as always, Fischer jumps into to the central outpost and avoids any of the danger that could have hurt his coordination after b4. } (32... Ra8? 33. b4 Nb7 34. Ra2 $10) 33. Kf1 f5 34. b4? (34. exf5?! Nxf5 $17 { This fork ensures that black wins the h pawn. } { [%cal Gf5e3,Re3c4,Re3f1,Rf5h4] }) 34... b5! 35. Bg8 (35. bxc5?? bxc4 $19 { [%cal Gc4c3,Gc3c2,Gc2c1,Ra7a3] }) (35. Bxb5?? Ncb3 $19 { [%cal Rc6b5,Rb3d2] }) 35... fxe4 { "Fixing white with another weakness" } 36. fxe4 (36. bxc5? e3 37. Rxd4 exd4 38. Nd3 Rxa3 39. Ke2 Rc3 $19 { Three passed pawns should be enough to win. }) 36... Nd7 37. Rd3 Ra6 { With the c6 pawn protected, Nc2 is a big threat. } { [%cal Gd4c2,Rc2a3,Ra6a3,Ba6c6] } 38. Rc3 c5! { Larsen was low on time and got confused by this surprising pawn break. } (38... Ra8! { It's even stronger to prepare this pawn break further! } 39. Ba2 (39. Bh7?? Kf7 $19 { [%cal Gf7g7,Gg7h7] }) 39... c5! 40. bxc5 b4 41. Rc4 b3 42. Bb1 Rxa3 $19) 39. g4?? (39. bxc5 b4! 40. Rc1 (40. axb4?? Ra1+ $19) 40... Nf6! 41. Ba2 b3! 42. Bb1 Ng4 $19 { Fischer had not fully seen this position yet, but his intuition that lines like this would be strong for black was perfectly correct. The b3 pawn is much stronger than the blockaded c5 and a3 pawns. }) 39... c4 { Now it's too easy. Black maintains the strong passed pawn without any of the possible counterplay. } 40. gxh5 gxh5 41. Bd5 Nf6 42. Rg3 Nxd5 43. exd5 Rf6 44. Kg2 Nf5 45. Rh3 Rg6+ 46. Kf3 Nd4+ 47. Ke3 (47. Ke4?! Kd6 { Zugzwang. Rg2 is the threat, but if: } 48. Rh2 Rg3 $19 { [%cal Gg3a3] }) 47... Rg2 48. Rh1 Kd6 49. Ne4+ Kxd5 50. Nc3+ Ke6 51. Rc1 Rh2 52. a4 Rh3+ (52... bxa4 { The most straightforward move is equally winning, but why allow this b pawn to move at all and have to calculate this line? } 53. b5! (53. Nxa4?? Re2#) 53... a3 54. b6 a2 55. b7 Rb2 56. b8=Q Rxb8 57. Nxa2 Rb3+ 58. Ke4?? (58. Kf2 Rb2+ $19 { [%cal Gb2a2] }) 58... Ne2 $19 { [%cal Ge2g3] }) 53. Kf2 (53. Ke4?? Nf5! $19 { [%cal Gh3e3] }) 53... Nb3 54. Kg2 Nxc1 55. Kxh3 bxa4 56. Nxa4 Ne2 57. b5 c3 58. b6 c2 59. Nc5+ Kd5 60. Nb3 (60. b7 c1=Q 61. b8=Q Qh1#) (60. Nd3 Nf4+ 61. Nxf4+ exf4 62. b7 c1=Q 63. b8=Q Qh1#) 60... Kc6 61. Kg2 Kxb6 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { Larsen finally resigned, as there's no stopping c1=Q next, winning a knight. } { [%cal Gc2c1] } 0-1


[Event "Skopje"]
[Site "Skopje YUG"]
[Date "1967.08.08"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Efim Geller"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B89"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Sozin Attack, Main Line"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Efim Geller"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/1s2JojbR"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Flawed masterpiece" }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bc4 e6 (6... Qb6!? 7. Nb3 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 Qc7 10. f4 O-O 11. Bd3 $10 { Fischer - Saidy, 1967. Not an easy game for either side. }) 7. Be3 Be7 8. Bb3 O-O 9. Qe2 (9. Qd2? Ng4 $15 { Black easily nabs the most important piece for white. } { [%cal Gg4e3] }) 9... Qa5 (9... a6!? 10. O-O-O Qc7 $14 { Anand, Viswanathan - Salov, Valery, 1-0, Dos Hermanas, 1997, https://lichess.org/dQJYCryv } { There is a lot of theory in this main line, but white has a decent win rate. } { [%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] }) 10. O-O-O Nxd4 (10... Bd7?! 11. Ndb5! { [%cal Gb5d6] } 11... Ne8 12. Bf4 a6? (12... Ne5! 13. Kb1 a6 14. Nd4 $14) 13. Nxd6 Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Nxd6 15. Rxd6 Qg5+ 16. Qd2 Qxg2 17. Rd1 Be8 18. Qf4 $16 { "with good pressure" }) 11. Bxd4 Bd7 12. Kb1 { Now Bxf6 is a threat, winning the d6 pawn or shattering black's kingside protection. } 12... Bc6 (12... Rad8!? 13. g4! (13. Qe3? b5! 14. a3 b4 15. axb4 Qxb4 16. Bxa7 Qb7 17. Qb6 Qa8 18. f3 $19 { Fischer thought this position was fine for white, but he simply overlooked how strong the a file pressure is after Rc8->c6->a6, winning the bishop on a7 or mating. }) 13... b5 14. g5 Ne8 15. h4) 13. f4 Rad8 14. Rhf1 { From this position, Fischer calculated the ensuing sacrifice. } (14. g4!? { [%cal Gg4g5] }) (14. f5!? exf5 15. exf5 Rfe8 16. Qf2 { "with positional pressure" }) 14... b5 15. f5! b4 16. fxe6 bxc3 17. exf7+?! (17. Rxf6! { The winning exchange sacrifice! Fischer doesn't even mention this move in his post-mortem, instead blaming the follow-up. Let's see how it wins: } 17... gxf6?? (17... Bxf6! 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. e7 Qe5 20. exd8=Q Rxd8 21. Qc4! { [%cal Rc4f7,Rc4c6] } 21... Bxe4 22. Qxf7+ Kh8 23. Qc7 $18 { Geller's king is much more vulnerable than white's in this final position, and Fischer rules the light squares. }) 18. exf7+ Rxf7! (18... Kh8?? 19. Qg4 Rb8 20. Bxc3 Qd8 { [%cal Bd8f6] } 21. Be6! { to prevent black from counter-sacrificing the exchange. } 21... Ba4 (21... a5 22. Rd3 { The winning rook lift will not be denied. } { [%cal Gd3h3] }) 22. Rd5 $18 { The winning rook lift! } { [%cal Gd5h5,Gh5h7] }) 19. Bxf7+ Kxf7 20. Qc4+ d5 21. Qxc6 $18) 17... Kh8 { Stockfish 13 is convinced that this position is equal, but in fact Fischer shows there's a win here that the engine only sees once you start playing down the line... } 18. Rf5! Qb4 (18... Qc7?? 19. Rdf1 { [%cal Gf5f6] } 19... Nd7?? (19... Bxe4 20. Bxf6 Bxf5 (20... Bxf6 21. Qxe4 $18) 21. Bxe7 $18) 20. Rh5! $18 { [%cal Gh5h7] }) 19. Qf1!! { It took Fischer 45 minutes to find this move! Rxf6 is threatened. } 19... Nxe4! (19... Nd7!? 20. Rh5! { [%cal Gh5h7] } 20... Ne5 (20... Nf6 21. Rh6! $18) 21. Qf5 h6 22. Qg6!! Nxg6?? (22... Rxf7 23. Bxe5 $18) 23. Rxh6#) (19... Ng4!? 20. Bxc3 Qb7 21. Qf4 Ne5 $18 { "with three pawns for the piece and a winning attack" }) 20. a3?? (20. Qf4!! { Fischer found this win a few hours after the game had ended... } 20... cxb2 (20... d5!? 21. Qe5 Nf6 22. Rxf6 Bxf6 23. Qxf6! gxf6 24. Bxf6#) (20... Nd2+ 21. Rxd2 cxd2 22. c3!! Qxb3 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Qg4+ Kh8 25. Qd4+ Bf6 26. Qxf6#) 21. Rh5 { [%cal Gd4g7] } 21... Nc3+ (21... Bf6 22. Qf5 h6 23. Rxh6+! gxh6 24. Qg6! { And Qxh6# is unstoppable. }) (21... Nf6 22. Rh6! Rxf7 23. Bxf7 Be4 24. Rh3 d5 $18 { The attack is over, but white is up enough material now. }) 22. Kxb2 Nxd1+ (22... Rxf7 23. Qxf7 Nxd1+ 24. Kb1!! Qxd4 25. Rxh7+! Kxh7 26. Qh5#) 23. Kc1 Rxf7 24. Bxf7 { And there's no answer to the threat of Rxh7+ Kxh7 Qf5+, mating. } 24... Bg5 25. Qxg5 Qxd4 26. Qxd8+) 20... Qb7! 21. Qf4?? (21. Rh5!? { A more accurate try! } 21... Qd7! { Controlling the f5 square should hold. White needs to bail out with a perpetual check: } (21... Ba4?? 22. Qf5! Ng5 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Rxg5+ Bxg5 25. Qxg5+ Kh8 26. Qf6#) 22. Bxg7+ Kxg7 23. Qf4 { [%cal Gf4h6] } 23... d5 24. Qh6+ Kxf7 25. Qxh7+ Ke8 26. Qg6+ Rf7 27. Qg8+ $10) 21... Ba4!! 22. Qg4 (22. Qh6!? Bf6! 23. Rxf6 Bxb3 $19) 22... Bf6! 23. Rxf6 Bxb3! $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { Fischer resigned as there's simply no way to prevent Ba2+ with Qxb2# to follow. The game could have ended with: } 24. cxb3 Nxf6! $19 { And now white's attack is over, and black's is just getting started. } 0-1


[Event "Skopje"]
[Site "Skopje YUG"]
[Date "1967.08.28"]
[Round "16"]
[White "Ratmir Kholmov"]
[Black "Robert James Fischer"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A49"]
[Opening "Indian Defense: Przepiorka Variation"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Ratmir Kholmov - Robert James Fischer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/ErDGMlqE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "The erring bishop" }
1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. O-O d6 6. Nc3 { "A straightforward but essentially passive development of the knight." } 6... Nbd7 7. b3?! { "This system is characterized by symmetry and drawing tendencies," but Fischer needed a win as black in this game in order to secure first place in the tournament. } 7... e5 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. e4 Re8 10. Ba3 c6 11. Bd6?! Qa5 12. Qd3? (12. b4 Qa3 13. Nb1 Qb2 14. Nbd2! Re6 15. Rb1 Qa3 16. Bc7 Ne8 17. Bd8 $10 { Hilariously, there's no way to trap the bishop. With this sequence, white had a save. }) 12... Re6! { Fischer is winning either a pawn or two pieces for the rook by force now. } 13. b4 (13. Ne2 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Rxd6 $19) 13... Qa3 14. Bc7 Qxb4 (14... Ne8 15. Ba5 b6 16. Rab1 bxa5?? (16... Rd6! { There's a simple way out of these complications. } 17. Qc4 Ba6! 18. Qxa6 Qxc3 $19) 17. Rb3! Nc5 18. bxc5 Qxc5 19. Rfb1 $10 { In these complications, white is doing just alright. }) 15. Rab1 Qe7 (15... Qf8?? 16. Ng5! Re8 17. Bd6 $16) 16. Rfd1 (16. Ng5?? Nc5! $19) 16... Ne8 17. Ba5 Rd6 18. Qe2 Rxd1+ 19. Qxd1 Bf8! { Preparing Qa3 which cannot be kicked away with Bb4. } 20. Nd2 (20. Bb4!? Qf6 21. Bxf8 Nxf8 $19 { Now black would be up a clean pawn for nothing. } { [%cal Gf8e6,Ge6d4] }) 20... Qa3! { [%cal Ra3a5,Ra3c3,Ra3a2] } 21. Nc4 Qc5 22. Bf1 b5 23. Nd2 (23. Bb4? Qd4! { And you cannot save both the knight and bishop. } 24. Qxd4 exd4 $18 { [%cal Gb5c4,Gd4c3] }) 23... Qa3! { White cannot escape the loss of material again. } 24. Nb3 Nc5 25. Bxb5 { "Desperation" } (25. Nxc5 Qxa5 $19 { [%cal Ra5c3,Rf8c5] }) 25... cxb5 26. Nxb5 Qa4 27. Nxc5 (27. Qd5? Qxe4! { Defends the rook and trades queens into a won endgame. }) 27... Qxa5 28. Qd5 Rb8 29. a4 Bh3 30. Qxe5 Rc8 31. Nd3 Qxa4 32. Ne1 a6 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { Kholmov resigned because the knight is trapped: } 33. Na7!? (33. Nd4 Bg7 $19 { [%cal Rg7d4] }) (33. Nc3 Qc4 $19 { [%cal Rc4c3,Rc4f1] }) 33... Rc7 34. Ra1 Qd7 35. Rxa6 Rxa7 36. Rxa7 Qxa7 37. Qxe8 Qa1! $19 0-1


[Event "Sousse Interzonal"]
[Site "Sousse TUN"]
[Date "1967.10.24"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Leonid Stein"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C92"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed, Flohr System"]
[StudyName "Fischer's My 60 Memorable Games"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Leonid Stein"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/miI3fn8S/OoK9Yx5j"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "When champions meet" }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 { The Zaitsev! At the time, this was a rare side line. Indeed, this only reached fame after Zaitsev (Karpov's second) picked it up in the 80s. } 10. d4 Na5?! { Mixing ideas between the Zaitsev and Chigorin doesn't make sense here... } (10... Re8! 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a4 h6 { If white wants to play Nf1->g3, then the e pawn needs more direct protection. } 13. Bc2 exd4! 14. cxd4 Nb4! 15. Bb1 $10 { Kasparov, Garry - Karpov, Anatoly, 1-0, World Championship 35th-KK5, 1990, https://lichess.org/hHn19S4m }) 11. Bc2 Nc4 (11... exd4? 12. cxd4 d5 13. e5 Ne4 14. Nc3 f5 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxe4 18. Rxe4 c5 19. d5 $16) 12. b3 Nb6 13. Nbd2 Nbd7 14. b4! { Stein was preparing c5 with his last move, but Fischer now is ready to shut down the queenside expansion. } 14... exd4?! 15. cxd4 a5 16. bxa5 c5 { Stein refuses to play passively, and willingly sacrifices a pawn in order to continue the struggle in the center. } 17. e5?! (17. Bb2 Qxa5 18. a4 b4 19. Nc4 $18 { Cirich - Robatsch, 1967, where white went on to win. }) 17... dxe5 18. dxe5 Nd5 19. Ne4 Nb4 20. Bb1 { By forcing the bishop to retreat to b1, white's rook on a1 is further hemmed in. } 20... Rxa5 21. Qe2 (21. Nfg5! { [%cal Gd1h5] } 21... g6? (21... Bxe4 22. Bxe4 Bxg5 23. Bxg5 Qxg5 24. Qxd7 $16 { Clearly white's coordination is better than black's. }) 22. Nxf7 Rxf7 23. e6 $18) 21... Nb6?? { As soon as the knight leaves the king's defense, all of the previous lines are that much stronger for Fischer. } 22. Nfg5! Bxe4 (22... h6? 23. Nh7 Re8?? 24. Nhf6+ gxf6 25. Qg4+ Kh8 26. Nd6 Bxd6 27. Qf5 $18) (22... g6? 23. Nxh7! Kxh7 24. Nd6 Bxd6 25. Qh5+ Kg8 26. Bxg6 $18) 23. Qxe4 { [%cal Rb1h7] } 23... g6 24. Qh4! h5 25. Qg3! { Threatening Ne6! We can see how quickly the attack comes now that 3 pieces have left the defense of black's kings. Ironically, even though this wasn't a Zaitsev proper, this attack has all the makings of the main line Zaitsev with the killer bishops sitting on b1 and c1. } 25... Nc4 26. Nf3? (26. e6! f5 27. Nf7 Rxf7 28. exf7+ Kxf7 29. Bxf5 gxf5 30. Bh6!! { The brilliant move that Fischer had missed. The attack rages on the dark squares and e file. } 30... Qg8?? (30... Bf6 31. Rad1! Qb6 32. Rd7+ $18) 31. Rxe7+) 26... Kg7 27. Qf4 { Again preparing a final assault on the dark squares. } 27... Rh8 28. e6! { Finally Fischer finds the break through. } 28... f5 29. Bxf5 Qf8 (29... gxf5?? 30. Qg3+ Kf8 (30... Kh7 31. Ng5+ Bxg5 32. Bxg5 Qd3 33. Qc7+ Kg6 34. Qf7+ Kxg5 35. Qg7+ Kf4 36. Rad1! $18) 31. Qg6 Qe8 32. Bh6+ Rxh6 33. Qxh6+ Kg8 34. Ng5! Bxg5 35. Qxg5+ Kh8 36. Qh6+ Kg8 37. e7 $18) 30. Be4? (30. Nh4!! { Littlewood's analysis shows this was a game-ending move: } 30... Bxh4 31. Qxh4 Qxf5 32. Qe7+ Kg8 33. Qd8+ Kg7 34. Qc7+ Kg8 35. e7 $18 { [%cal Ge7e8] }) 30... Qxf4 31. Bxf4 Re8 32. Rad1 Ra6 33. Rd7 Rxe6 34. Ng5 Rf6 35. Bf3 Rxf4 36. Ne6+ Kf6 37. Nxf4 Ne5 38. Rb7 Bd6 39. Kf1 { "Put an end to all effective resistance" by stopping the threat of Nxf3+. } 39... Nc2 (39... Nxf3?? 40. Rxe8 Nd2+ 41. Ke2 Bxf4 42. Rf8+ Kg5 43. Rxf4 Kxf4 44. Kxd2 $18) 40. Re4 Nd4 { The next few moves are just Fischer's active pieces running rampant over all Stein's unprotected minor pieces and unprotected king. Even in an endgame, Fischer proves that king safety is an important asset. } 41. Rb6 Rd8 42. Nd5+ Kf5 43. Ne3+ Ke6 44. Be2 Kd7 45. Bxb5+ Nxb5 46. Rxb5 Kc6 47. a4 Bc7 48. Ke2 g5 49. g3 Ra8 50. Rb2 Rf8 51. f4 gxf4 52. gxf4 Nf7 53. Re6+ Nd6 54. f5 Ra8 55. Rd2 Rxa4 56. f6 $18 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Stein resigned because there's no way to stop this f pawn without giving up a piece. For instance: } 56... Kd7 (56... Rf4? 57. Nd5! Rf5 (57... Ra4 58. f7 $18) 58. Ne7+ $18 { [%cal Re7c6,Re7f5] }) 57. Re7+ Kc6 58. f7 Nxf7 59. Rxf7 $18 1-0


