his move if he were playing. } 29... Qxd6 (29... Qb7? 30. Qxe6+ Kh8 31. Qg6 $16 { You can't give up the pawn. White has active options here with e6 or Rf7 coming and everything defended on the queenside. }) 30. exd6 $16 { I wasn't convinced during the game that the d6 pawn was an asset. I thought it was more of a liability since if the DSB can target it, then it's almost sure to drop. However, this turns out to just not be possible and indeed this position is great for white. } 30... Rf8!? { This move, preparing Bf6 to trade off the DSBs, concerned me during the game. } (30... Bh4!? 31. Rf3! $16 { No Bg3 for you! }) (30... Rc6!? $16 { Doesn't even threaten the pawn since Be5 is a skewer. }) (30... Re8?! 31. Be5 $16 { The passed d pawn is practically impossible to attack. }) 31. Rxf8+! Rxf8 32. Nd3 { The knight is heading to c5, so black has to snap it off right now. } 32... Bxd3 33. cxd3 $16 { We actually have a similar position to the game on move 40, but white even keeps the DSB around. With Bc5 always an option, indeed the pawn remains an asset. Qd6 has been justified. }) (29. Qxa4?! { I didn't consider this move for more than a second. } 29... Bh4 30. Rfd2 Ra8 $17 { My queen is dangerously low on squares and a2 is less defended than b2. It's not a good idea to allow the queenside to open up this much. }) 29... Bh4! { "Forcing" g3. } { [%clk 0:53:00] } (29... Be7?! 30. Qh3! $14 { A new option available to white that I wanted to play since e6 is a juicy weakness. In a game of tempi, this one could be crucial. }) 30. g3 { [%clk 0:12:00] } 30... Be7 { [%clk 0:53:00] } 31. Qe3 { Now my queen cannot go to the h3 square. Probably black has a draw in hand by constantly attacking my queen, but I assumed my opponent who is 300 points higher rated than me wouldn't go for it. } { [%clk 0:12:00] } 31... Rf8?! { Black takes the f file, but with one less rook on the board, threats against my king are not so serious anymore. During the game, I was instantly much happier with my position and only now started playing for a real advantage. } { [%clk 0:52:00] } (31... Bg5!? { Theoretically, black has a draw in hand I suppose? } 32. Qa3 (32. Qc3?! $15 { I'm not sure this is an improvement for white. The batteries along the c file are scary. }) 32... Be7 $10) (31... Rb7!? { I assumed my opponent would double rooks on the b file and try to kill me somehow. } 32. Nd3 Rcb8 { Maybe there are no threats though. } 33. Ka1!? $14 (33. Nf4? Rxb2+!! 34. Bxb2 a3 $19)) 32. Rxf8+ { [%clk 0:12:00] } 32... Rxf8 { [%clk 0:51:00] } 33. Nd3 { If my knight gets to f4, it's hitting everything. } { [%cal Gd3f4,Gf4g6,Gf4e6] [%clk 0:12:00] } 33... a3!? { Essentially forcing b3. } { [%clk 0:37:00] } (33... Bg5! { My opponent saw this but didn't want to allow Nf4. } 34. Nf4!? { The move my opponent was scared of. } (34. Qe2? { My planned response was refuted during the post-mortem. } 34... Bxa2+! 35. Kxa2 Qc4+ 36. Kb1 Qxd4 $15 { Black is the one who holds all the cards now and isn't even down material. }) (34. Qg1!? $10 { So perhaps this is the only way to play for an advantage as white? Doubtful. }) 34... Bxf4! { My counter-intuitive suggestion to him during the post-mortem is quite strong. } 35. gxf4 Rf5 $10 { Black is still down the pawn, but their activity ensures at least a draw. I wasn't sure if I wanted to allow this during the game. Indeed, black's heavy piece activity compensates for the missing pawn. }) 34. b3 { [%clk 0:12:00] } 34... Bxd3 { [%clk 0:37:00] } 35. Qxd3 { My opponent was happy because my knight was no longer getting to f4. I was happy because my pieces are finally coordinated. } { [%clk 0:12:00] } 35... Bc5? { My opponent thought it was smart now to trade off the bishops. Although we would be entering a heavy-piece "endgame," white is practically playing a heavy-piece middlegame due to the thorn pawn on a3. Black's king has no such king-safety issues.
However, I believe this is the decisive mistake of the game! During the game, I wasn't sure if I was truly winning yet, but I was happy to find the next move. } { [%clk 0:37:00] } (35... Rf5!? 36. g4 Rf4 $14 { A more prudent way for black to play. Even though white is up a pawn, black's piece activity is almost enough to claim equality. }) 36. Qc3! { The queens are getting traded off by force! We're not going to be in a heavy-piece middlegame after all. Rather, we will be in a clear endgame where white is up a pawn. } { [%clk 0:10:00] } 36... Bb6!? { The bishops will stay on the board now, but white gets the better of this endgame after } { [%clk 0:35:00] } (36... Rc8!? 37. Bxc5 Qxc5 38. Qxc5 Rxc5 39. Rd3! { Preventing Rc3 and preparing b4 to win the a3 pawn! I saw this line before committing to Qc3. } (39. Rd4?! Rc3 40. Ra4 Rxg3 41. Rxa3 $16 { Down a tempo compared to the other line starting with Rd3. Probably white still wins the race. }) 39... d4!? (39... Rb5!? 40. Rd4! Rc5 41. Ra4 Rc3 42. Rxa3 Rxg3 $16 { The a or b pawn should win significantly faster than any of black's pawns. }) (39... Ra5?! { Too passive. }) 40. b4! Rxe5!? (40... Rb5?! 41. Rxd4 $16) 41. Rxa3 $16 { The b pawn will queen. } { [%cal Ga3b3,Gb4b8] }) 37. Qxc7 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 37... Bxc7 { [%clk 0:35:00] } 38. Bc5! { Hitting the all-important a3 pawn with tempo on the rook. } { [%clk 0:09:00] } 38... Rf5!? { My opponent seeks activity. If he can play Bxe5 and Rxh5, then there's a real race on our hands. } { [%clk 0:33:00] } (38... Ra8!? { The only real alternative, but this is just too passive. } 39. Bd6!? { White no longer has to force things since black is not even attempting to race us. But this move works just as well as in the game too. } 39... Bxd6 40. exd6 Rd8 41. c4! Rxd6 42. c5 Rc6 43. b4 $18 { I saw this line during the game. I assume it's winning with Rd3->a3 to follow. } { [%cal Gd1d3,Gd3a3] }) (38... Rf3!? { The other way to play is similar to the game continuation. } 39. Bxa3 Rxg3?! (39... Bxe5!? 40. Bc5! $16 { The a and b pawns are too strong here. } { [%cal Gb3b4] }) 40. Bd6! Bxd6 41. exd6 Kf7 42. c4!! Ke8 43. c5 Kd7 44. Rc1! $18 { Practically identical to the game. }) 39. Bxa3 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 39... Rxh5? { But with this move order, it's too easy. I saw to the end of the game from this position. } { [%clk 0:31:00] } (39... Bxe5!? { The only serious try. } 40. Bc5! { I wasn't sure if I would play this way during the game or not, but after analyzing, it's just so clearly winning. The passed queenside pawns simply march up the board. Moreover, black's rook is dominated by my bishop, since Ra7 and Rf8 are both controlled. } (40. Bb2?! { My other candidate move during the game is probably also winning. But it is not as clinical as Bc5. } 40... Bxb2 41. Kxb2 Kf7!? (41... Rxh5?! { Now the king is not inside the square of the a pawn. } 42. a4 Kf7 43. a5 d4 44. a6! Ra5 45. Ra1 $18) 42. a4 Ke7 43. a5 Kd6 44. a6 Kc7 45. Ra1 Kb8 46. b4! d4 47. Kb3 Rxh5 48. Kc4 $18 { Black's pawns haven't even started to race yet. White is winning. } { [%cal Gb4b5,Gb5b6,Ga6a7,Gb6b7] }) 40... Bxg3 41. a4 Rxh5?! (41... Bb8!? 42. a5 d4 43. b4 $18 { White still marches on here. } { [%cal Ga5a6,Ga6a7] } 43... Rf7!? { Prevents a7, but not everything else. } 44. Rxd4 $18 { [%cal Gd4d8,Ga5a6,Ga6a7] }) 42. a5 Bb8 43. a6 $18 { [%cal Ga6a7] }) 40. Bd6! { Damned if you do - damned if you don't. The tempo on this loose c7 bishop kills black. } { [%clk 0:09:00] } 40... Bxd6!? { Entering a lost rook and pawn endgame. But there was no other option. } { [%clk 0:18:00] } (40... Bb6!? 41. c4! dxc4 42. bxc4 { c5 is coming with tempo. c7 is already defended. There is no way to prevent promotion since black's rook is so sidelined. } 42... Kf7!? (42... Bf2?! 43. c5 Bxg3 44. c6 Rh4 45. c7 Rc4 46. Rc1 $18) 43. c5 Ba5 44. c6 Ke8 45. c7 Kd7 46. Bb4+ Kxc7 47. Bxa5+ $18) (40... Ba5!? { Tempting me into the b4+a4 moves. But white can stick their head in the ground and continue the same way: } 41. c4! $18 (41. b4!? Bb6 42. a4 $18 { The win is slower, since now black's bishop can somewhat prevent these pawns from queening instantly. But in all races, white clearly wins. })) 41. exd6 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 41... Kf7 { [%clk 0:18:00] } 42. c4!! { The key move. the d pawn is a strength rather than a weakness. } { [%clk 0:09:00] } 42... Ke8 { [%clk 0:17:00] } (42... dxc4?? 43. d7 $18 { Rooks belong behind passed pawns! }) 43. c5! { The threat is c6, getting two connected passed pawns on the 6th rank. } { [%clk 0:09:00] } 43... Kd7!? { [%clk 0:16:00] } (43... d4!? 44. c6 (44. Rc1?! d3 45. c6 d2 46. Rd1 Rc5 $16 { Less clear than the other line. Probably also winning. }) 44... Rc5 45. Rc1 Rxc1+ 46. Kxc1 e5 47. b4 $18 { White's king can control both of black's passed pawns. Black's king cannot control all four of white's. }) 44. Rc1! { c6+ is once more threatened. } { [%clk 0:08:00] } 44... Rf5!? { Black controls the f file so that white's rook doesn't have as many options. } { [%clk 0:11:00] } (44... Kc6!? { Prevents both pawns for one turn, but white has even more. } 45. b4! d4 46. b5+! Kxb5!? (46... Kd7!? 47. c6+! Kc8 (47... Kxd6? 48. c7 $18) 48. d7+ Kc7 49. b6+! Kd8 50. c7+ Kxd7 51. c8=Q+ $18 { Tempo tempo tempo tempo. }) 47. c6 Rc5 48. Rxc5+ Kxc5 49. c7 $18) (44... d4!? { The other main candidate move I was calculating for my opponent back on move 40. } 45. c6+! Kc8 (45... Kxd6?? 46. c7 Rc5 47. Rxc5 Kxc5 48. c8=Q+ $18) 46. Rf1! Rf5 { The only move to prevent Rf8#. } 47. Rxf5! exf5 48. a4! $18 { Entering the same winning king and pawn endgame we had in the game. I saw this position was winning before I played Bd6 on move 40. }) 45. c6+ { [%clk 0:08:00] } 45... Kc8 { Black's intended defense. The rook and two pawns cannot directly win because the rook cannot coordinate on an open file with the white. Or can it? } { [%clk 0:11:00] } (45... Kxd6?? 46. c7 Rf8 47. c8=Q Rxc8 48. Rxc8 $18 { An easily winning endgame. }) 46. Rc5! { The threat is Ra5, with mate threats! } { [%clk 0:06:00] } 46... d4!? { The only option left to prevent Ra5. But I had already calculated this king and pawn endgame earlier via a different move order. } { [%clk 0:09:00] } (46... Rf8!? { Passive defense equally does not work. } 47. Ra5 Kb8 48. c7+ Kb7 49. Rb5+ Kc8!? (49... Kc6!? 50. Rb8 $18) (49... Ka7!? 50. d7 $18) 50. Rb8+ Kd7 51. Rxf8 $18) 47. Rxf5 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 47... exf5 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 48. a4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 48... f4 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 49. gxf4 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 49... h5 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 50. a5 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 50... h4 { [%clk 0:09:00] } 51. a6 $18 { My opponent resigned in this position. The finish is immediate in every variation. } { [%clk 0:05:00] } 51... Kb8!? (51... h3!? 52. a7 h2 53. a8=R# { Black is once again, one tempo too slow. }) 52. d7! Kc7 53. d8=Q+ Kxd8 54. a7 h3 55. a8=Q+ $18 1-0


