{ A repeat opponent. Last time, my 45 year old opponent blundered in the opening of the Bg5 Najdorf. He told me afterwards that he had taken nearly 20 years off of competitive chess then, so I was surprised and happy to find out that it wasn't a one-off tournament for him and that he was back for real. }
1. e4 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 1... c5 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 2... e6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 3. d4 { [%clk 1:30:00] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 4... a6 { [%clk 1:31:00] } 5. a3!? { A rare option, more typically played after Nc3 Qc7, a3 - but one that has some venom. } { [%clk 1:24:00] } 5... Nf6 { [%clk 1:30:00] } (5... Qc7!? 6. Nc3 (6. c4! { But I don't like allowing this line if I can avoid it. }) 6... b5 $10 { Arguably this is the most precise move order for black to play. The knight on f6 can sometimes be a target to a fast f4+e5. }) 6. Nc3 { [%clk 1:24:00] } 6... Qc7 { Preventing e5. On a low level, white simply prevents Bb4. But on a high level, the thematic f4-e5 push becomes stronger if black does not develop precisely. In particular, a fast b5+Bb7 might be called for. } { [%clk 1:30:00] } 7. g3 { Played after a further 3 minute think. During the game, it was now clear to me that he was just trying to get a position. } { [%clk 1:21:00] } (7. f4!? { Critical, now that the knight has committed to f6. }) 7... b5 { [%clk 1:28:00] } 8. Bg2 { [%clk 1:20:00] } 8... Bb7 { [%clk 1:28:00] } 9. O-O { A quick e5 can be played if black is not careful. } { [%clk 1:20:00] } (9. e5? { Too early } 9... Qxe5+ $19) 9... d6 { Preventing e5 in all lines. I'm going for a normal Scheveningen setup. } { [%clk 1:27:00] } 10. Be3?! { The bishop is almost always misplaced on this square. } { [%clk 1:18:00] } (10. f4 Nbd7 11. g4!? { Had my attention during the game. } (11. Qe2!? Be7 12. Bd2!? O-O 13. Rae1 $10 { Bd2 is more circumspect based on white's setup. }) 11... h6!? 12. Qe2!? (12. h4?! Be7 13. g5 hxg5 14. hxg5 Nh5 $15 { As long as my rook is on the h file this shouldn't bother me. If I had to castle early though... }) 12... Be7 13. Bd2 Rc8 14. Rae1 $13 { You can't pay me to castle kingside here. }) 10... Nbd7 { [%clk 1:25:00] } 11. Qe2 { [%clk 1:10:00] } (11. f4? Nc5! { Amazingly, it's not possible to defend the e pawn. } 12. Re1!? (12. Qf3?! Ncxe4 $17) (12. e5?! Bxg2 13. exf6 Bxf1 $17) 12... Ncxe4! 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 $17) 11... Be7 { [%clk 1:23:00] } 12. f4 { [%clk 1:08:00] } 12... O-O { [%clk 1:17:00] } 13. Rae1?! { With the bishop on e3, it makes more sense to place this rook on d1 instead now. } { [%clk 1:06:00] } (13. Rad1!? $10 { Perhaps black is still for choice here, but the game should definitely be close to equal. }) (13. g4!? { This is playable now already too. Black has some options though. } 13... Nc5!? { The tempo on e4 forces white's hand. } (13... d5!? { Thematic: counter-attack in the center when white tries to attack on the flank. } 14. e5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 $10 { The e pawn is hard to track down so black should have resources here. But this doesn't really refute white's setup. }) 14. Bd2 d5!? (14... g6!? 15. g5 Nh5 $10 { I was also trying to judge this line during the game. As long as the immediate Bf3, f5, or e5 don't lead anywhere, black should be fine here too. }) 15. e5 Nfe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 $10 { Probably a cleaner version than the other line. }) 13... Rfe8 { [%clk 1:12:00] } 14. Bf2?! { White threatens e5 as well as further prep work for g4-g5. But this is another slow move. I knew I had to be better if I just played with some pizazz. } { [%clk 0:49:00] } (14. g4! { The only critical move. At some point you have to play it. } 14... Nc5 15. Bd2 { Perhaps g6 is again playable here, but justifying the rook on e8 means that d5 is preferred. } 15... d5 16. e5 Nfe4 $10) 14... e5! { Preventing e5 and killing many of white's pieces. } { [%clk 1:10:00] } 15. Nf5 { [%clk 0:40:00] } 15... Bf8 { [%clk 1:09:00] } 16. fxe5 { [%clk 0:37:00] } 16... dxe5!? { [%clk 1:07:00] } (16... Nxe5?! { Loosens f6 and doesn't cover d4. Now I have to be alert for Nh6+ ideas. } 17. Bd4 $10 { This position isn't so comfortable for black, although there are surely resources here as well. }) 17. h3?! { After another long think, my opponent played this complete lemon. Further confirmation that I'm better. White has now played a third weird move, and I simply have the textbook Scheveningen structure. Moreover, I have more than double my opponent's clock with this solid position.
However, there are some issues lurking. I want to keep pieces on the board in order to make in-roads on the queenside. However, trading pieces would make my king potentially safer. For instance, my d7 knight is clearly passive, but moving it allows Nh6+ tricks. During the game, I failed to overcome my issues. } { [%clk 0:23:00] } (17. Be3!? $15 { Just get on with it. What is h3 even about? }) (17. g4!? $15 { The other way to just get on with it. I really don't know what white was thinking. }) 17... Rac8 { The most normal square for the rook. The only issue is that in some lines Nd6 can now land with a huge family fork. } { [%clk 0:56:00] } (17... g6?! 18. Ne3 $10 { I didn't want to weaken my king unnecessarily, leading to a position similar to the previous round, especially since I'm just inviting the knight closer to the d5 outpost. }) (17... Bxa3?! { This never seemed like a pawn I wanted to grab for several reasons. } 18. bxa3!? { Reason 1. } (18. Nd5!? Bxd5 19. exd5 Bd6 $10 { Reason 2: I've lost the bishop pair and for what? }) (18. Nxb5?! axb5 19. bxa3 Rxa3 $15 { Reason 3: huge simplifications leave my kingside looking more suspicious. } 20. Qxb5? Ba6! $17 { At least if white grabs the pawn, black has some positives we can point to. We're most likely going to be winning the exchange too. }) 18... Qxc3 { Do I really want to weaken all the dark squares (such as d6?) this much? } 19. Rd1!? { Preparing Nd6. Rac8 piling on pressure to c2 is not playable due to Nd6. } (19. Nd6!? { Also immediately playable. } 19... Reb8 $10 { Ugly. })) (17... b4!? 18. axb4 Bxb4 $15 { Perhaps this is an alternative idea for black? The rook on the a file can be justified by playing a5+Ba6 right now. }) 18. Be3 { I knew this was coming. But now that I reached this position, how much better is black actually? The longer I thought on this position, the less active my position looked. Both Nh6+ and Bg5 are extremely annoying moves, restricting my d7 and f6 knight. If I do nothing, g4-g5 is coming to kick away my main kingside defender. The center is open and my pieces are on the optimal squares, but I need to get the initiative right here right now before white does something drastic to me on the kingside. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } 18... b4!? { [%clk 0:42:00] } (18... g6? { Now this is too late. } 19. Nh6+ $16 { I can't give up my DSB but I also can't leave the knight here on h6. }) (18... Qc4!? { A candidate during the game. If I could force white's queen to move and I could achieve b4+Qxb4, my queen is extremely active on the queenside. } 19. Qxc4! (19. Qf2?! b4 20. axb4 Qxb4 21. Rb1 $15 { I would have loved to play a position like this. }) 19... Rxc4 20. Rd1 $10 { But this didn't seem convincing to me. Once more, Nd6 is coming to ruin the fun. }) (18... Bxa3?! { Potentially more interesting because I have more firepower against the c2 pawn. Potentially less interesting because all of my pieces get forked by Nd6. } 19. bxa3 Qxc3 20. Nd6! Qxc2?! (20... Re6!? 21. Nxc8 Qxc8 $14 { With Rc6 coming, this is an interesting exchange sac I didn't consider during the game. I don't really believe in this position though simply because my knights remain superfluous and in the long term white's bishop pair should prove to be an advantage. }) 21. Qxc2 Rxc2 22. Nxe8 Nxe8 $16 { The bishop pair more than compensates for the extra pawns black snagged. }) (18... Bc5?! { I spent far too long on this move. Trades are good in that now my king is less likely to come under fire. But my queenside play completely stalls here. } 19. g4! Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 h6?! (20... Qc5!? 21. Qxc5 Rxc5 22. g5 Nh5 $14 { I was not a fan of how much white was pushing black around. }) 21. g5! $16 { White is the one creating all the threats and I haven't done anything constructive on the queenside. }) 19. axb4 { [%clk 0:20:00] } 19... Bxb4 { [%clk 0:42:00] } 20. Bd2 { I've loosened the queenside, but white has everything defended, my king is slightly weaker than theirs, and my bishop on b4 is tactically loose due to Nd5 and/or Nb5 jumps. This is a critical position, as I need to find a further way to make progress or the game can quickly change. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } 20... Bf8?! { Too slow. After spending 10 minutes looking for something incisive, I ultimately couldn't keep my nerve maintaining the loose bishop on b4. Now the trend of the game begins to turn. } { [%clk 0:32:00] } (20... Qb6+!? 21. Kh2 Nc5!? $10 { An improvement on the type of plan I was going for during the game. Now that Nh6+ is ruled out, my knight on c5 can finally get to a better spot. Either d4 or e4 are great squares for it. } (21... a5?! $10 { During the game, I thought about this move order to threaten Ba6, but (1) there is Nd5 or Na4 to consider here, and (2) there are many options available to white to avoid losing the exchange. Do I really want to soften up the light squares like this? This is probably the best I have though, meaning that my overall evaluation of black crushing white for the last few moves was extremely optimistic. })) (20... a5?! 21. Nb5! Qb6+ (21... Qxc2!? { Looks like it hangs a fork on d6 but actually doesn't. } 22. Bxb4 Qxe2 23. Rxe2 axb4 24. Nbd6 Ba6! $10) 22. Be3! $10 { I couldn't find a satisfactory response here during the game. Ba6 is not coming after all. }) (20... Bxc3! { During the game and analysis, I thought that giving up the bishop pair here accomplishes nothing. } 21. Bxc3 $10 { During the post-mortem, my opponent thought that this was a good way forward for black, since now the e4 pawn is more of a weakness. I didn't agree as now the bishop pair should destroy me. } 21... Re6! (21... Bc6?! { The point that I was focused on. But white has several good options here. } 22. Qxa6!? $14 { There's nothing going on here for black. } (22. Qe3!? Bb5 23. Rf2 $10 { This was the other option I saw during the game where black isn't really doing anything. Nd6 will soon be an issue. })) 22. Qe3 h6! $15 { But this Stockfish continuation is instructive. Both of white's bishops are hemmed in. Meanwhile, black has the easy plan of ganging up on e4 with Nc5. In reality, this position shows ways for black to make progress. } { [%cal Gd7c5,Rc5e4,Rf6e4,Rb7e4] }) (20... Nf8?! { It would be great if I could simply reroute this passive knight to the dream d4 square. But tactically this is quite suspicious. } 21. Nh6+! { The annoying resource white always has hanging over my head. } 21... Kh8 22. Nd5!? (22. Rxf6?! { I didn't want to even allow this type of sacrifice. In analysis though, I don't think it crushes me, and so I should be fine to allow it. } 22... gxf6 23. Qh5 Ng6 24. Nf5) 22... Bxd5! (22... Nxd5? 23. Nxf7+ Kg8 24. exd5 $16) 23. exd5!? (23. Bxb4? Bc4 $17) 23... Bxd2 24. Qxd2 $13) (20... Re6?! $10 { Overprotects f6, thus allowing Nf8. But now I've taken away the e6 square! So this once more doesn't help my d7 knight. }) 21. Kh2 { My opponent has simple, easy moves to improve his position. Meanwhile I cannot find an effective way to untangle my superfluous knights. } { [%clk 0:19:00] } 21... Qb6?! { Note: I am not threatening b2 since Rb1 wins my LSB. The purpose of Qb6 is to overprotect f6, so that on a good day I could actually move my d7 knight somewhere without allowing Nh6+. And yet, where exactly am I moving d7? Nf8->e6->d4 would be great, but I just blocked that route with my last move. Nb6->c4 would be great but I blocked that too. My coordination is falling apart. } { [%clk 0:27:00] } (21... Qc4!? { Endgames will give me better chances since I can poke and prod the c and b files without worrying about getting blasted off the board on the kingside. } 22. Qe3!? $14 (22. Qxc4?! Rxc4 $10)) 22. b3! { I was happy to see this move during the game because I thought it meant my opponent had lost a tempo (Qxb2 was never a threat anyway). However, his idea to put the knight from f5 on c4 is actually genius. } { [%clk 0:18:00] } 22... g6?! { Seemingly kicking the knight away from my kingside now that the DSB is overworked protecting c3 and h6. Yet in reality I'm kicking the knight where it wants to go. } { [%clk 0:24:00] } (22... a5!? { I need to go for Ba6 in order to do anything here. } 23. Na4! { This move scared me off during the game. Where does my queen even move? } (23. Ne3? Ba6 24. Nc4 Bxc4 25. bxc4 Qc6 $17 { [%cal Gc6c4] }) 23... Qc7 24. c4! $14 { Now my queenside play has 100% backfired. }) (22... Bb4!? { Now that the knight is weakened, wasting time but returning to this square is certainly playable. } 23. Na4!? { Snap judgement during the game was that I was worried about this move with fancy threats against b4 and d6. But during analysis, everything is totally fine for black and the knight on a4 is reasonably misplaced. } (23. Nd5?! { I didn't spend time trying to refute this during the game, but it is indeed suboptimal for white. } 23... Bxd5 24. Bxb4!? (24. exd5? Rxc2! $17) 24... Qxb4 25. exd5) 23... Qa5 24. Bxb4 Qxb4 25. Rd1 Re6 $10) (22... Qe6!? $10 { Stockfish's recommendation. The queen is out of range of the knights, while also protecting against Nd5. g6 is now actually on the cards. }) 23. Ne3 { I still was under the illusion that white was playing to get a grip on the d5 square. } { [%clk 0:17:00] } (23. Nh6+! Bxh6 24. Na4! Qc7 25. Bxh6 { I had calculated this line during the game on my opponent's turn and was sad to see the outcome. However, I didn't look one ply deeper. } 25... Qxc2! { Black shouldn't be much worse here if at all. The lack of DSB though is really felt. } 26. Qf3 $14) 23... Bg7 { Now that the bishop protects f6 and vacates f8, I can play Nf8->e6->d4. But I have lost way too many tempi to pull off this pipe dream. } { [%clk 0:21:00] } (23... a5!? 24. Nc4 Qd4 $16 { Maybe this is still annoying for white to deal with. My queen is strong but also potentially trapped? Not sure how to evaluate this mess. }) 24. Nc4! { Only now did I realize how strong white's position was. My queenside play is a distant memory, all of white's minor pieces are contributing, and I have lost so many tempi going back and forth across the board that it's ridiculous. White is already practically winning. } { [%clk 0:17:00] } 24... Qc7?! { Runs into further tempi. I've accomplished literally nothing in the last 7 moves except moving my bishop and queen back and forth. At this point, black is almost busted. } { [%clk 0:20:00] } (24... Rxc4? { If bxc4 was forced, I probably would have played this move just to eliminate this beastly knight. } 25. Qxc4! $18 { But sadly there are no issues for white here. This is simply the cleanest exchange you've ever seen. }) (24... Qe6!? { Prevents Nd5 for the time being, but gets in the way of my d7 knight's future. If Nd5 does land and I cannot capture the resulting pawn on d5, I'm also losing another tempo. } 25. Rd1 $16 { Not the only move for white. Meanwhile, what is black's next constructive plan? }) 25. Qf2 { [%clk 0:16:00] } 25... Nf8 { I don't know if there's a save anymore, but I was desperately trying to achieve Nd4. } { [%clk 0:17:00] } (25... a5?! { I even thought about this desperate move to try to get in Ba6 to challenge the knight, but now I lose the dark squares in my position. } 26. Nb5! Qb8 27. Nbd6 $18) 26. Bg5! { First gaining a tempo on the f6 knight... } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 26... Nh5 { [%clk 0:17:00] } 27. Nd5! { Then landing the eagle on d5. My knight on f8 never gets the chance to land on d4 after all. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } (27. Be3? { Obviously white would not need to make this retreating move but just to show my idea: } 27... Ne6 { At least here I could have some hope. } 28. Nd5 Bxd5 29. exd5 Nd4 $16 { The knight on d4 is strong so I don't have to resign just yet. }) 27... Bxd5 { [%clk 0:17:00] } 28. exd5 { d6 is an insanely massive threat. My queen is actually about to be trapped. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 28... f6 { A real feels-bad move. I know I'm at least losing a pawn here as soon as g4 lands. But what else to do? d6 was a massive threat. } { [%clk 0:16:00] } (28... a5?? { Or any other nothing move. } 29. d6! Qd7 { The only move to defend f7. } (29... Qb8?? 30. Qxf7+ $18) 30. Nb6 $18 { Splat. }) 29. Be3!? { [%clk 0:14:00] } (29. d6!? Qb8 30. Be3 Nd7 $18 { Black doesn't resign just yet. But this is certainly lost just as the game is. }) 29... Nd7 { Blockading the passed d pawn. The position is just yikes. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 30. d6 { [%clk 0:08:00] } 30... Qb8 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 31. g4 { Wins a pawn. Why not? } { [%clk 0:08:00] } 31... Nf4 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 32. Bxf4 { [%clk 0:08:00] } 32... exf4 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 33. Qxf4 { [%clk 0:08:00] } 33... Rc5 { [%clk 0:11:00] } (33... Bf8! { Perhaps I would have found this combative move if I had more time on the clock. } 34. Bd5+ Kh8 $16 { White's pieces are strong but also barely defending d6. If I could just get rid of that pawn I'd only be worse, rather than lost. }) 34. Qd2! { Behind the passed pawn. White is also threatening to trade rooks and reconquer the e file. A nice move that shows my opponent has good technique. } { [%clk 0:06:00] } 34... Ne5 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 35. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 35... Rcxe5 { I no longer have the blockade on the d pawn but also I no longer have to worry about it essentially being a connected passed pawn. } { [%clk 0:10:00] } 36. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 36... Rxe5 { [%clk 0:10:00] } 37. Kh1 { White escapes my tricks and now I know I'm going to resign soon. } { [%clk 0:06:00] } (37. d7?? Rd5+ 38. Qf4 Qxf4+ 39. Rxf4 Rxd7 $10 { My main trick. }) (37. Re1?? Rxe1 38. Qxe1 Qxd6+ $10 { My other trick. }) 37... Qd8 { [%clk 0:08:00] } 38. d7 { My bishop and queen are completely useless. I figured though that since there are chances for an OCB endgame, I shouldn't resign just yet. The main goal: activate the bishop in order to get at white's king. } { [%clk 0:05:00] } 38... f5!? { My king will be weak, but at least so too will white's. } { [%clk 0:08:00] } (38... Bf8? { But also where is this bishop going anyway? } 39. Rxf6! Qxf6 40. d8=Q $18) 39. gxf5 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 39... gxf5 { [%clk 0:07:00] } 40. Qd3 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 40... Re7! { Activity! d7 is the real target. Who cares about f5? } { [%clk 0:06:00] } 41. Rd1! { [%clk 0:05:00] } (41. Qxf5? Qxd7 $14) (41. Bc6!? f4!? $18 { Be5 and Rg7 are coming to create some grief around white's king. }) 41... f4 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 42. c4 { Good technique. If white gets in c7, then I have to sacrifice a queen. } { [%clk 0:05:00] } (42. Qxa6?! Be5 $18 { f3 is perhaps coming, with vague threats around white's king. }) (42. Qc4+! Kh8 43. Qc8 $18 { The cleanest finish. }) 42... Kh8 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 43. c5 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 43... Be5 { [%clk 0:06:00] } 44. c6 { [%clk 0:05:00] } 44... Rg7 { f3 is perhaps threatened, with vague threats around white's king. } { [%clk 0:06:00] } 45. Qd5 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 45... Bc7 { [%clk 0:06:00] } (45... f3?! 46. Bxf3 Qg5 { If only d8=Q didn't come with check... } 47. d8=Q+ $18) 46. Re1! { Threatening Re8+. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 46... Re7 { [%clk 0:05:00] } (46... Rg8?! 47. Qd4+ $18) 47. Qd4+! $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { Finally I resigned. After Kg8, Bd5+ essentially mates me.
This game stung. As black, I had a great position and so much extra time on the clock on move 18. But the position was hard for me to figure out and I ended up making passive half-moves that simply passed the advantage to my opponent. I'm extremely unhappy with nearly all the middlegame decisions I made during the game.
After the game, my opponent and I went out to eat poke together. We only talked about the game for a few minutes over lunch. However, I found out that he is an extremely active online player, not someone who was essentially retired for 20 years as I had previously thought. That revelation made me feel much better about getting so thoroughly outplayed this game. } { [%clk 0:04:00] } 1-0


