[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Welcome to another instructive study by NoseKnowsAll. This interactive study is for players 1500-2200 lichess, taking you through an important middlegame strategical concept: weak color complexes. Let's see how we can use a weak color complex to launch a strong attack on the kingside or center! Importantly, we'll also learn how to use weak color complexes as the basis of positionally maneuvering as well.

Throughout this study, I will also provide general middlegame tips that these positions showcase. Whenever this general advice occurs, I'll write it just like this:

PRO TIP: The more pieces available that can infiltrate a weakened color complex, the more serious the pawn structure deficiency becomes.

Please check out my other middlegame strategy studies as well:
* Knights | How to dominate your opponents! https://lichess.org/study/kI8ikTU4
* Bishops | Slice through the opposition! https://lichess.org/study/kNn68T8l
* Rooks | Infiltrate for activity! https://lichess.org/study/U7tTRtdj
* Always sacrifice the exchange! https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE

If you find this study useful, please heart it and share it with any friends! }
 *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: What is a weak color complex?"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "What is a weak color complex?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/6br1inHb"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "4k3/1p3p2/2p1p1p1/3p3p/3PP3/2P2P2/1P4PP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ In the current position, black has weak dark squares across the board because all of their pawns are on light squares. Meanwhile, white does not have these same issues because not all their pawns are on the same color. Therefore, white's king has several easy routes into black's camp, but black's king does not have the same options.

We say that black has a weak dark square complex. } { [%csl Gd6,Gf6,Ge5,Gg5,Gc5,Gb6,Gh6] }
1. Kf2 { However, without the presence of more pieces on the board to fix black's pawns permanently on dark squares and/or infiltrate via the weakened squares, a weak color complex is not a killer issue. } 1... Ke7 2. Ke3 g5! $10 { Partially repairing the weakened dark squares on the kingside ensures that white's king cannot infiltrate into the position. The position is equal.
PRO TIP: If the pawn structure is not fixed, the side with a weak color complex often has the opportunity to repair their weaknesses by judiciously placing pawns on the other color. } *


