[ChapterName "Color complex: Minor pieces, minor problems"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/lUTYacTv"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2b1k3/1p3pn1/2p1p1p1/2Np3p/3PP3/2P2PB1/1P4PP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ Revisiting this same position but adding a few minor pieces into the mix accentuates how uncomfortable black's weak dark squares are. White's bishop is a monster, knifing into black's queenside. White's knight, on a powerful dark square, reaches far into black's camp. Black's inactive pieces are hopelessly trapped, and white should play to maintain dark square superiority. }
1. Be5! { The bishop assumes the most powerful outpost on the board, attacking a dominated knight, and further limiting black's ability to place pawns on dark squares. } 1... Kf8 2. Na4! { Rerouting to jump further into black's weakened dark squares. Black's strength on the light square color complex is irrelevant when all of white's threats hit on the other color. } 2... Bd7 (2... b5?! 3. Nb6 Bb7 { Another way for black to lose horrendously on the dark squares: } 4. Nd7+ Kg8 5. Nf6+! Kf8?? 6. Bd6# { An aesthetic finish! The two minor pieces land with a thud on two important dark squares with mate! }) 3. Nb6 Be8 4. Bf6! { All of black's pawns are now fixed on light squares permanently. Black cannot move a muscle to regain control of the dark squares. } 4... Kg8 5. Kf2 { Finally, white's king prepares to infiltrate via the dark squares. As opposed to the previous chapter, black will be unable to prevent his advance. } 5... Kh7 6. Ke3 Kg8 7. Kf4 Kh7 8. Ke5 Kg8 9. Kd6 $18 { White will win the bishop on e8 and the game.
PRO TIP: Placing pawns on the color of your own bishop limits the piece's scope, potentially turning it into a bad bishop: https://lichess.org/study/kNn68T8l/467VfNtg.
In this example, both of black's minor pieces were hopelessly blocked in by their own pawn chain. Don't let this happen to you! } { [%cal Gd6e7] } *


