[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2brk3/1p2qpn1/2p1p1p1/2Np3p/3PP3/2P1QPB1/RP4PP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ Adding major pieces that can also infiltrate on the weakened dark squares pushes black's defensive task from the improbable to the impossible. }
1. Qh6! { Black's dark squares prove immediately fatal when the queen is able to infiltrate into the position. } 1... Qf8 (1... Kf8?? 2. Qh8# { Oh no, my king! }) (1... f6? 2. Qxg6+ $18 { Wins one pawn, and more will fall next. }) 2. Bc7 { White traps the rook, but the real knockout comes after further infiltrating with the rest of the army.
PRO TIP: The more pieces available that can infiltrate a weakened color complex, the more serious the pawn structure deficiency becomes. } 2... Ke7 3. Bxd8+ Kxd8 4. Ra8! { Next the rook enters.
Bishops, knights, queens, and kings can see color and therefore are all affected by weak color complexes. But note how the rook controls an equal number of light and dark squares no matter where it goes. So rooks are essentially "color-blind." } 4... Kc7 5. Qf4+! { And finally the queen returns to the most important dark square diagonal. Black is busted. } 5... Qd6? { A valiant effort to defend some of the dark squares, but there are already many ways to win. } 6. Rxc8+! { Cleanest. White wins the full queen on d6 next. } 6... Kxc8 7. Qxd6 $18 { Checkmate is the next goal.
White surely had an advantage from the start of this chapter due to their space advantage and piece mobility, so the specific continuation was not crucial. They key point to understand is that the end comes swiftly for black if/when white's major pieces infiltrate via black's dark squares. } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Exercise 1: Knockout blow on the dark squares"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
