[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Weakening the kingside"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/rOYrJWrd"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3q1rk1/1bpn1ppp/1b1p1n2/1p2pNB1/3PP3/1BP2N1P/1P3PP1/Q3R1K1 b - - 1 20"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ White is clearly building up pieces on the kingside for some sort of attack. But notice how there's no immediate breakthrough on g7 (only attacked once) or h7 (solidly defended by the f6 knight). Black plays the next move to kick out the pesky f5 knight, but this move shows they did not appreciate the kingside dark square weaknesses it creates. }
20... g6?? { With the dark squared bishop in Siberia on b6, there is just no way to ever repair the dark square weaknesses created on the kingside. f6 and h6 in particular are now horribly weak. Moreover, black can now never play h6 to defend the g5 dark square too. } { [%csl Rb6] } (20... exd4 21. cxd4 Qa8 $14 { Better play from black. Without queens on the board, it is harder to convert white's kingside aspirations into something tangible. }) 21. Nh6+ { Infiltrating to the newly available dark square. } 21... Kg7 22. Qc1! { Further attacking the weakened dark squares on the kingside. The immediate threat is Ng4 and Bh6+ infiltrating further. } 22... Qa8?? { Getting out of the brutal pin, but fatally weakening the dark squares on the kingside. Black gets destroyed immediately. } (22... c5 $16 { Counter-attacking in the center is probably black's best chance at this point. But the kingside dark squares remain chronically weak. }) 23. Bxf6+! Nxf6 24. Nf5+! { Notice how the knight is a piece that controls the opposite color it is currently on. So planting this knight back on f5 (a light square) directly attacks all the weakened dark squares from black's most recent mistakes. } { [%csl Ge7,Gg7,Gh6] } 24... gxf5 { Taking the knight is losing, but what other choices are there? } (24... Kh8 { The only alternative also loses to } 25. Qh6! { More dark square infiltration! } 25... Rg8 26. Ng5! $18 { Too many threats here as well. } { [%cal Gg5f7,Gh6h7,Gg5h7] }) 25. Qg5+ { Dark square infiltration! } 25... Kh8 26. Qxf6+ { Dark square infiltration! } 26... Kg8 27. Ng5 $18 { Dark square infiltration! Black resigned since Qh6 and Qxh7# is unstoppable.
There are two major points to take away from this game:
PRO TIP: Do not weaken your kingside unnecessarily if you're being attacked.
PRO TIP: Weakening the dark squares near your king without a dark squared bishop around to protect them can end in disaster. } { [%cal Gf6h6,Gh6h7] } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Sac-sac mate"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[White "NoseKnowsAll"]
[Black "ljorge60"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Sac-sac mate"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/tgVrSxch"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1rbqr1k1/3nppbp/2pp1np1/7P/pp1PP1P1/4BPN1/PPPQ4/1K1R1BNR w - - 1 14"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ Now let's look at one of my games!

I have set up for a 150 attack, similar to the Yugoslav attack against the Sicilian Dragon. Fischer famously said that to beat the Dragon, "play h4-h5, and then sac-sac-mate."

However, to be more precise, we break down the kingside by first removing the dark square bishop and then checkmating black on those dark squares. Let's see it in action. }
14. Bh6 { Step 1: Remove the key dark square defender. } 14... b3 { Black wants to stir up trouble against my king, but there's a simple remedy to this fork on my a and c pawns. } (14... Bh8!? { Resilient, but doesn't actually deal with the threats on the h file. } 15. hxg6 fxg6 16. g5 $18 { And the knight has nowhere to go. }) 15. cxb3! axb3 16. a3! { The queenside remains closed, so I can fully commit to the sac-sac mate attack on the kingside. My king is now completely safe from any queenside counterplay. } 16... Nf8 17. Bxg7 { Step 1 complete. } 17... Kxg7 18. hxg6 { Step 2: open the h file for the major pieces. } 18... fxg6! { The best recapture. Now at least the fatally weak h8 square is inaccessible to white's major pieces. } (18... hxg6?? { A simple way to go down without a fight. } 19. Qh6+ Kg8 20. Qh8# { Notice how every forward move lands on a dark square! }) 19. Qh6+ { Step 3: infiltrate on the newly weakened dark squares. } 19... Kg8 20. N1e2 { As Yasser Seirawan would say, "bringing more boys to the party." As soon as my knights and light squared bishop join the fray, black should be mated. } (20. g5! $18 { Wins a clean piece. But at this point, I could already see how the weakened dark squares would prove fatal. I played directly for mate. }) 20... Be6 21. Nf4 { A new piece enters on the dark squares near black's king. } 21... Bf7 { After identifying that the weakened dark squares are the key targets to attack, g7 in particular should be our focus, since it is currently impossible for black to defend it with a piece. } 22. Nf5!! { Hitting the key g7 square! Qg7# can only be prevented by taking this knight, which opens the g file, giving white's rooks direct access to this all-important g7 square. } { [%csl Gg7] } 22... gxf5 23. gxf5 e5?! { A losing move in a hopeless position. But what else was there to do? } 24. Bc4!! { My checkmating attack revolves around the dark squares. In fact, this bishop is irrelevant and the only purpose of this move is to get my final rook into the game with tempo. } 24... Bxc4 25. Rdg1+ { With all of my pieces attacking black's king, and g7 terminally weak (and now exposed!), I was confident that white would be winning from this position without calculating a specific variation beyond this point. } 25... Ng6 26. Rxg6+! { Keeping the files open. Now the h8 square is also an accessible weak square. } (26. fxg6 { Winning too, but now g7 can be defended. } 26... Rb7 27. gxh7+ Kh8 28. Ng6#! { A move I didn't see during the game. }) 26... hxg6 (26... Kf7 27. Qg7# { Dark square infiltration. }) (26... Kh8 27. Qg7# { Dark square infiltration. }) 27. Qxg6+ Kf8 28. Ne6+! { The final piece targets the fatally weakened dark squares. } 28... Bxe6 (28... Ke7 29. Qg7#) 29. fxe6 { Black is up a rook and a knight, but the attack has already broken through. The position is forced mate no matter what black plays. } 29... Rxe6 (29... Ke7 30. Qf7#) 30. Rh8+ Ke7 31. Qg7# { A fitting end. White checkmates black with both major pieces landing on the important dark squares that were the focus of this attack! } 1-0


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Exercise 3: Yugoslav destruction"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[White "Artemiev_Student"]
[Black "Mercurial_09"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "Exercise 3: Yugoslav destruction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/6VkLbgOl"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3q1r2/5pkp/r1p1p1p1/p2p3n/4P3/2N2P2/PPPQ2P1/2KR3R w - - 0 16"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this 5+0 lichess blitz game, white has sacrificed the h pawn in the Yugoslav attack.

It's our turn to take over. What is the cleanest path to victory? }
16. g4! (16. Rxh5?? $17 { An interesting idea, but this sacrifice is highly unclear in this position since we have already traded so many pieces. } 16... gxh5 17. Rh1 h4! $17 { Black should have no problems at all here since the g file remains closed. }) 16... Nf6 { Ng3 directly lost the knight to Qh6+ Kf6, Qh4+. } (16... Ng3 17. Qh6+ Kf6 18. Qh4+ $18 { Just as hopeless. }) 17. Qh6+ (17. e5? { Premature, after Ng8! black defends some of the weakened dark squares. }) 17... Kg8 { Nice job so far! Using the open h file and weakened dark squares, we've infiltrated with the heavy pieces on the kingside.
Only one more precise move is needed to seal the deal. } 18. e5! { Exactly! The knight cannot safely move anywhere without allowing Qxh7#. } (18. g5?? { A common mistake in the Yugoslav attack. After Nh5! the h file remains closed, and the attack is going nowhere. } 18... Nh5 19. Rxh5 $13) *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: Exercise 4: Tactical infiltration"]
[Date "2009.06.25"]
[White "Vladimir Akopian"]
[Black "Joel Lautier"]
[Result "*"]
