[ChapterName "Exercise 4: Tactical infiltration"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/O9dXDP8b"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1bq1bppp/p7/2p5/N3p3/1P6/PBP1QPPP/3RR1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Here we have a more recent game where black has a weakened pawn structure in exchange for the bishop pair.

Are there any targets on the kingside that black is hard pressed to defend? }
1. Qg4! g6 { Defending mate with Bf6 would have lost the bishop to Bxf6, so black is forced into making this weakening move. } (1... f6? 2. Rd7 Qc8 3. Nb6 $18 { Loses just as in the game except now we also have a weakened 7th rank we can use as well. }) (1... Bf6?? 2. Bxf6 $18 { The g pawn is pinned. }) 2. Rd7 (2. Qd7?! { Another good move since the queen cannot be captured without losing a bishop. But is there a point after Rfc8? } 2... Rfc8 (2... Qxd7?? 3. Rxd7 $18 { [%cal Gd7e7,Gd7b7] }) 3. Nb6! { The only real way forward. } 3... Qxb6 4. Qxe7 $16 { With Qe5 next, white is still in the driver's seat. }) 2... Qc8 { Lautier is desperate to defend his dark squared bishop for fear of the famous "death by dark square" strategy! This tricky pin temporarily prevents us from snacking on the e7 bishop. } 3. Nb6! { Exactly! The queen cannot maintain this pin, and so black will be losing the important dark squared bishop next. In the game, Akopian finished brilliantly after Qc6 with Nd5! winning a clean piece since Bd8??, Rxd8! Rfxd8, Ne7+ leads to instant destruction on the dark squares. } (3. Rxe7?? { Oh no, our queen! } 3... Qxg4 $19) (3. Red1!? $18 { Also strong, but we're still not threatening to take out this dark squared bishop unless we next play the move played in the game. }) (3. Qh3!? $18 { Also strong, but we really want to capture the e7 bishop and keep queens on the board. }) *


[Event "1944 Georgian Championship"]
