[ChapterName "Exercise 5: Slay the dragon"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/utD9f5DK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r4rk1/pp2ppbp/3p2p1/5P2/3BP1n1/2N5/PqP1Q2P/3R1RK1 w - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Another dragon! This time we're facing against a 15 year old Tigran Petrosian, soon to become a master, and 20 years before he becomes world champion.

Let's teach Petrosian a lesson on the importance of the dark squared bishop in the dragon! }
17. f6! { A beautiful interference shot! Now that the bishops are not staring at each other, the knight on g4 is truly hanging. } (17. Qxg4?? { This was surely what Petrosian had calculated. Now after Bxd4+ Rxd4, the c3 knight is hanging, and black is winning. } 17... Bxd4+ 18. Rxd4 Qxc3 $19) (17. Bxg7?? { After Kxg7, we still have to deal with the fact that our c3 knight is hanging. } 17... Kxg7 18. Qxg4 Qxc3 $19) (17. e5?? { After Nxe5, black has just won another pawn and has no issues in his position. } 17... Nxe5 $17) 17... Bxf6 { The only way for black to maintain the tension between the bishops. } (17... Nxf6!? { This interesting alternative also loses: } 18. Nd5! Qxa2 19. Nxe7+ Kh8 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Rxf6 $18 { Another way for white to break through on the dark squares. }) (17... exf6? 18. Qxg4 $18) 18. Rxf6! (18. Bxf6?? { After Nxf6, black is up 3 pawns and keeps his safe king. } 18... Nxf6 $19) (18. Qxg4?? { This was surely what Petrosian had calculated. Now after Bxd4+ Rxd4, the c3 knight is hanging, and black is winning. }) (18. Nd5?? { After Bxd4+, Rxd4 Qxd4+, everything collapses with check. } 18... Bxd4+ 19. Rxd4 Qxd4+ $19) 18... Nxf6 { Sacrificing the exchange leaves white with the only dark squared bishop on the board. Now finish Petrosian off! } 19. Nd5 { Brilliantly done! The black queen is attacked and cannot defend e7. After e7 drops, black will soon lose the knight on f6 next with a ferocious attack on the dark squares. Petrosian resigned and allowed his opponent a miniature rather than limp along for another few moves.
Hilariously, Petrosian himself became famous for his exchange sacrifices later in his career. No doubt this exchange sacrifice left a strong impression on him! } *


[Event "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!: An important Stonewall idea"]
[Date "2023.03.28"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Light and Dark Squares | Master color complex strategy!"]
[ChapterName "An important Stonewall idea"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/IV54dIxt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pp4pp/2pbpn2/3p1p2/2PP4/1P3NP1/P3PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2023.03.28"]
[UTCTime "14:12:15"]

{ Weak color complexes create positional ideas as well.

In the Stonewall Dutch, black builds a strong fortification on the central light squares, in exchange for having a poor c8 bishop, and potentially weak dark squares. If black is not careful in this position, they can quickly end up positionally worse by making the next move carelessly. }
7... O-O?! { A normal developing move, but it misses white's main idea. } (7... Qe7! $10 { Black should first prevent white's main idea before castling. }) 8. Ba3! { Trading off black's main defender of the dark squares ensures that white will have good control over the weakened dark squares across the board. e5, c5, and f4 in particular are the most central squares soon under white's control.
Notice how white is using their understanding of good and bad bishops ( https://lichess.org/study/kNn68T8l/467VfNtg ) to make favorable trades. } 8... Bxa3 { PRO TIP: Understanding the pawn structure of your openings will help you identify exactly which piece trades are beneficial or harmful to your position! } 9. Nxa3 $14 { Maneuvering this a3 knight to d3 (which can then jump to all the important central dark squares) takes time, but gives white a good game.
The following moves are not forced, but there is one more follow-up idea in this position worth seeing. } 9... Qe7 10. Nc2 Nbd7 11. Qc1 Ne4 12. Qa3! $14 { Not the only idea, but certainly one that continues the dark square strategy! If the queens are traded, then white inches that much closer to a dream good knight (on e5) vs bad bishop (on c8) endgame. If the queens are not traded, then black must cede further control of the dark squares to white. } *


