[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/T3ixjwmg/rzpEeuuM"]
[FEN "r3kn1r/p1q1npp1/4p3/1p1pP1Np/b1pP3P/2P3PB/2PB1P2/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a huge space advantage, a safe king, and the bishop pair. However, black is up a pawn with a solid position. The only real issue in black's position is that every single fixed pawn is stuck on a light square, and he's missing his dark squared bishop. }
1. Bc1! { Always retreat! Stein correctly recognizes that he needs to activate his bad bishop previously stuck behind the central pawn chain. } 1... g6 { Without a dark squared bishop, black can never challenge white's dark squared bishop, which can poke and prod the dark squares along any diagonal it wants. } 2. Ba3 { The previously inactive bishop now breathes fire along the uncontested a3-f8 diagonal. } { [%cal Ba3f8] } 2... Nh7 { PRO TIP: When you are being attacked, trade pieces. Attacks with less pieces are less likely to succeed. } 3. Nf3! $16 { Just as we should not trade active bishops for inactive bishops, we do not trade the active knight on g5 for the passive knight on h7.
Stein is clearly better and can launch an attack on Schweber's king no matter which side of the board he ends up residing, as in the game: https://lichess.org/ztgf1ASG#41 } *


