[FEN "r2q1rk1/1p2ppbp/2bp1np1/p7/2PBP3/2N2P2/PP1QB1PP/2R2RK1 b - - 1 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We arrive at a common position in the accelerated dragon, Maroczy bind variation. Black is cramped for space, but has good play on the queenside and center. Black's next move may be surprising. }
13... Nd7! { Has black gone insane? Surely trading the dark squared bishops means black's king will be permanently weakened?
Incorrect! Nd7 is perfectly correct because (1) white has no pieces that can even attack the kingside, and (2) white will actually be the one left with weakened dark squares in the center! Let's see how this works: } 14. Bxg7?! (14. Be3! $14 { Keeping this important dark square defender alive is necessary if white wants to claim an advantage in this position. }) 14... Kxg7 15. Rfd1 (15. Qd4+ f6 $10 { With Qb6 coming next to trade the queens, it should be clear that black is not weak on the kingside dark squares. }) 15... Qb6+ { Further infiltrating the weakened dark squares. } 16. Qd4+?! { Trading one of the few remaining pieces that can control the dark squares cannot be correct. } (16. Kh1 { A better try. } 16... Nc5 $10 { But white's terrible light squared bishop remains a problem piece. } { [%csl Gc5,Re2] }) 16... Qxd4+ 17. Rxd4 Nc5 $15 { Look at how terrible white's light squared bishop is. Compare it to how strong black's knight is on the (dark squared!) outpost c5. The center of the board is swiss cheese on the dark squares.
To fully appreciate how bad this position is for white, enjoy GM Milos Pavlovic's smooth conversion of this position here: https://lichess.org/eQ9o4949/black#33 } { [%csl Gc5,Re2] } *


