[FEN "q1r3k1/1b1nbpp1/r2p1n1p/p3pP2/NpP1P3/1B4N1/PPR1QBPP/4R1K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

1. Qd3? { In a tough position, Anand played Qd3, a careless move that misses our positional threat. What did Anand overlook? } (1. h3 $15 { Would have been a better way to prepare Qd3. }) 1... Ng4! $17 (1... Nc5!? { A very different idea than what Ivanchuk had in mind, but also strong. This knight must be captured, after which the open d file proves dangerous for white. } 2. Nxc5 dxc5 3. Ba4 Rd8 $15) 2. Nf1 { Exactly! this simple move wins the dark squared bishop - the most important piece in white's position based on the pawn structure. } (2. Nh5!! { Trading off one knight means that white has potential for a kingside attack, since black is missing a key defensive piece. This amazing defensive resource was missed by both players during the game. } 2... Nxf2 3. Rxf2 Nf6 4. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $15) 2... Nxf2 $17 (2... Ndf6! $17 { Ivanchuk's move in the game is great as well since white's bishop isn't yet able to avoid being traded. Play Nxf2 instead for the solution. } 3. Bg3? Bxe4 $19) (2... Bg5?! $17 { This move allows Bg3, when white can keep his dark squared bishop. }) 3. Rxf2 $17 { After winning the most important defender, Ivanchuk went on to win a brilliant game on the newly weakened dark squares: https://lichess.org/ioWi7jGv/black#46 } *


