1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 { Exchange French... } 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Bd3 Ne7 6. O-O Bf5 (6... Nbc6 7. c3 Bg4 { I was toying with this line as a way to keep life in the position. But I didn't want to lose a second game in one day. So I decided to prove why the exchange French is slightly better for black and grind my young opponent in an endgame. }) 7. Re1 O-O 8. Bg5 f6 9. Bh4 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Qd7 11. Bg3 Nf5 12. Bxd6 Nxd6 13. Nbd2 { It's clear this position is equal, but I came up with a few ideas to avoid it being a dead draw. Idea #1: Don't trade all the rooks. } 13... Nc6 14. c3 a5 15. Re2 Rfe8 16. Rae1 Rxe2 17. Rxe2 Re8?! { Welp. So long for that idea. } (17... Qf5! { Trading the queens however, allows Kf7 to be played, and black keeps the winning chances. At the time I did not appreciate this. White's rook cannot infiltrate on the e file. }) 18. Rxe8+ Qxe8 19. Qe3?! Qxe3 20. fxe3 { Yawn. After mass exchanges, I started to realize that it's technically possible for black to win this endgame. e3 is a weakness, and I have both the e4 and c4 holes as good outposts for my knights. Now it just became a game of ensuring my knights stayed active. } 20... a4 { With the idea of focusing in on c4. } 21. Kf2 Kf7 22. b3 axb3 (22... b5 23. bxa4 bxa4 24. Ne1 Nb5 { [%csl Gc3] } 25. c4 dxc4 (25... Na3! 26. cxd5 Nb4 $15 { but this was completely missed during the game }) 26. Nxc4 Nc3 { [%csl Ga2] } 27. a3 $10 { I saw this far and thought it was probably drawn. In fact I was correct. }) 23. axb3 b5!? { Permanently gives up c5, but I saw that white couldn't get there in time. } 24. b4? { Black should have tried to get in c4. Now it's almost as if black is just up a pawn because of how useless the e pawn is. } (24. Ne1 { [%cal Ge1d3,Gd3c5] } 24... Ne4+! { [%csl Gc3,Gf2] } 25. Nxe4 dxe4 { And white's knight will remain worse than black's. }) (24. Ke2 b4 (24... Ke6 25. Kd3 Kf5 $10) 25. c4 dxc4 26. bxc4 { At least I have a passed pawn with which I can possibly convert into a win. However, white's central majority ends up being more important. Misevaluated. }) 24... Ne7 { Immediately keying in on the weakened outpost. } 25. Nb1 Nec8 26. Ke2 Nb6 27. Kd3 g5 28. Nbd2 (28. g4?? { I saw that g4 (freezing my kingside majority) could not be played here. } 28... Ne4 $16 { [%csl Gf2,Gc3] }) 28... Na4 29. g4 { But i forgot to check here... } 29... Ne4!? { A super committal move that takes us deep into the endgame, with black a pawn up. } (29... Kg6 30. h3 h5 { This was my original, main idea. I couldn't get the thought out of my head that I should win a pawn and try to deal with a slightly inactive piece, though, and I went for that instead. In fact, this is better. } 31. Nh2 f5! 32. Ndf3 fxg4 33. Ne5+ Kh6 34. hxg4 h4 $17) 30. Nxe4 dxe4+ 31. Kxe4 Nxc3+ 32. Kf5 Nd5 33. Ke4 (33. e4 Ne3# { Wouldn't this have been nice? }) 33... Nxb4 { This was as far as I saw. But now my knight and king are less active than white's. I need to be careful here to avoid losing back the pawn. } 34. d5 Na6?! { The knight is now offsides. I thought I could make progress here, but it's not the way forward. } (34... c5! 35. dxc6 Nxc6 36. Kd5 Nb4+ 37. Kc5 Nd3+ 38. Kxb5 Nf2 $19 { I didn't see that I would win the pawn back. } { [%cal Gf2g4,Gf2h3] }) (34... Ke7? 35. Nd4 $10) 35. Kd4 (35. Nd4 Nc5+ 36. Kf5 b4) 35... Ke7 36. Nd2! b4 (36... Kd6? 37. Ne4+ $10) 37. Nc4 Kd7 38. e4 c5+ 39. dxc6+ Kxc6 40. e5 fxe5+ 41. Kxe5?? { I had reached time control, but I was almost certain that I was losing in this study-like endgame because white would sacrifice the knight for my b pawn, and his king would mop up on the kingside. } (41. Nxe5+ Kb5 42. Nf7 h6 43. Nxh6 Nc5 44. Nf7 Ne6+ 45. Kd3 Ka4 46. Kc2 Ka3 47. Kb1 Kb3 $17 { A very interesting line that shows best play. Practically, nobody would want to play white like this though with such passive pieces. }) 41... Kb5?! { The beginning of the wrong idea. } (41... Kc5 { Best play. } 42. Nd2 (42. Nb2 b3 43. Kf5 Kd4 44. Nd1 Kd3 45. Kxg5 Kd2 46. Nb2 Nc5 47. Nc4+ Kc3 48. Na3 Ne4+ 49. Kh6 b2 50. Kxh7 Kb3 51. Nb1 Ka2 $19 { [%csl Gc3,Gd2,Ga3] }) 42... Nb8!! { This sets up the winning idea - the pawn is in the perfect spot. All I need to do is get the king more active, but stop one pesky check on c5. } 43. Kf5 (43. Ke4 { [%cal Gb8d7] }) 43... Kd4 44. Kxg5 Nd7 { [%csl Gc5] } 45. h4 Kc3 46. Ne4+ { [%csl Gc5] } (46. Nb1+ Kc2 { [%csl Gd2,Gc3,Ga3] }) 46... Kd3 $19 { [%csl Gd2,Gc3,Gc5] } 47. Nd6 b3 48. Nb5 b2 49. Na3 Nb6 50. Kh6 Nc4 51. Nb1 Kc2 { [%csl Gd2,Gc3,Ga3] } 52. Kxh7 Kxb1 53. g5 Ka2 54. g6 b1=Q $19) 42. Nd2 { [%cal Gc5c4,Gb3a5] } 42... Nc5?! 43. Kf5 Ka4?? { Ka4 throws away the win. By going this way around the pawn, I set myself up for a brutal check that I had earlier missed. } (43... h6!! { This sets up one more winning idea. Getting the king to d4 is always key here. } 44. Kg6 Kc6 45. Kxh6 Kd5 46. Kxg5 (46. Kg7 Kd4 47. h4 (47. Kg6 Kd3 48. Nb1 Kc2) 47... gxh4 48. g5 $19) 46... Ne4+ $19) 44. Kxg5 Ne4+?? (44... Ka3 45. Kh6 Kb2 { [%cal Gb2c2] } 46. Nc4+ Kc3 47. Na5 Nd7 48. g5 { [%cal Gd7f6] } (48. Kxh7 Nf6+ { [%cal Gf6g4,Gg4h2] }) 48... Nf8 49. Kg7 (49. h4 Ng6 { [%cal Gg6h4] } 50. h5 Nf4 { [%cal Gf4h5] } 51. g6 hxg6 52. hxg6 Nxg6 { [%cal Gb4b3] }) 49... Ne6+ { [%cal Ge6g5] } 50. Kh6 $10 { Amazingly, this is a draw. } 50... Nf8 51. h4 Ng6 $10 { During the game I figured playing passively like this would be hopeless. }) 45. Nxe4 { [%cal Gb4b3] } 45... b3 46. Nc5+ (46. Nc3+ Kb4 47. Nb1 b2 48. Kf4 Kb3 49. Nd2+ Kc2 { And even here this is not a draw either. }) (46. Nd2 b2 47. Kf4 Kb4 48. g5 Kc3 { I thought I had a draw here, but in actual fact white is still winning. } 49. Ke3 $18) 46... Kb4 47. Nxb3 Kxb3 { Black resigns.
After the game, I found out that my young opponent rated 1700 is actually an endgame wizard. He often beats master players at the Seattle chess club by trading everything down until he gets to an endgame. Technically it worked on me too, but sadly I had the win before letting it slip away... } 1-0


