1. e4 e6 { A French! This time as white! } 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 Qb6 8. Na4 Qa5+ 9. c3 cxd4 10. b4 Qc7 (10... Nxb4 11. cxb4 Bxb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 O-O { [%csl Gb7,Gd5,Gd4] } 14. Bd3 b5 15. Nb2 Nb6 16. O-O Nc4 { After the game, my opponent and I had discussed how this is the mainline that we knew. He said that he scored poorly with it, so didn't play it in the game. Regardless, it was here that I showed him this Bxh7 line. } 17. Bxh7+ Kxh7 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Nf3 f6 20. Nh4 $16 Qd8 21. Nd3 Nd2 22. Ng6 Nxf1 23. exf6 Rxf6 (23... gxf6 24. Rxf1 Kg7 25. Rf3) 24. Qh8+ Kf7 25. Nde5#) 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 { This was a new position for me. But I was content with my bishop locking down the queenside, and I envisioned ways to force through a kingside attack. } 12... Be7 13. Bd3 (13. Qg4 O-O 14. Bd3 f5 { I wasn't sure how I liked this line, so I instead tried to remain flexible. }) 13... O-O 14. Qh5! g6 (14... f5 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Bxf6 Rxf6 17. Qxh7+ { This line shows that f5 doesn't work. So, instead g6 must be played. Except this ensures dark squared weaknesses around his king and discourages the f6 break. }) 15. Qe2 b6 { After successfully probing for a weakness I really wanted to play h4. } 16. O-O (16. h4!? a5 17. h5 axb4 18. hxg6 fxg6 (18... hxg6?? 19. Qg4 $18) 19. Rxh7 { I saw this position, but felt that black was going to be fine here because he had broken down my queenside, and my king is no safer than his. } { [%csl Ga4] } 19... Rf7? { The defense I was most scared of. } (19... Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg7 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Qh7#) 20. Bxg6! Rxh7 21. Bxh7+ Kxh7 22. Qh5+ Kg7 23. O-O-O Rxa4 24. Rd3 $18 { The unbelievable continuation I did not see during the game. White is simply winning down two pieces. }) 16... f6 17. a3 fxe5 18. fxe5 Bb7?! { I could see the makings of an attack. All I was missing was the knight on a4. } 19. Qg4! { The only way to defend e6 is by trading rooks. } 19... Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Nf8 { I was sure there was a breakthrough, but thought 25 minutes before finding: } 21. Qf4! { There is no way to defend the f7 square! } { [%csl Gg5,Gh4,Gd8,Bf7][%cal Gf4f8] } 21... Bc6! { My opponent finds the best defense! Amazingly, there is no breakthrough involving Qf7+. So instead of rolling the dice on a position I couldn't crack, I started a long maneuver to get the last piece involved in the attack. } (21... Qd7 22. Qf7+ Kh8 23. Be3!! { I had found this move after the defensive move I thought was forced from my opponent (21...Qd7) } 23... Qxa4 (23... g5 24. Qh5 $18) (23... Bh4 24. g3 Qxf7 25. Rxf7 $18) 24. Bh6 $18 { [%cal Gf7g7,Gh6g7] }) 22. Nb2 (22. Qf7+ Kh8 23. Be3 Be8) 22... Be8?! { A slight inaccuracy based on what happens later in the game. } 23. Nd1 Qd8 24. Ne3 Bc6 25. Ng4 { The knight lands on g4 with too many threats! } 25... Qe8 26. Nf6+ (26. Nh6+ Kh8 27. h4 Rc8 28. h5 Rc7 { There were too many defensive resources, so I couldn't calculate everything here. Instead, I went with the mantra of "simple is good." } 29. Nf7+ Kg8 30. Nd6! Bxd6 (30... Qb8 31. Qf7+ Kh8 32. h6! $18) 31. exd6 { [%cal Gd4g7] } 31... Rf7 32. Qe5 Rxf1+ 33. Bxf1 Qd7 $18) 26... Bxf6 27. exf6 Qf7 { The queen must blockade the pawn or let the dark squared bishop destroy the king. } 28. Qd6 Bb7 29. a4 Nd7 30. Bb5 { A picture-perfect position. I thought that black was completely helpless, but my opponent surprised me with: } 30... e5! (30... Rd8 31. Qc7 $18) (30... Bc8 31. Bc6 Rb8 32. Bxd7 Bxd7 33. Qxb8+ $18) 31. Bxe5?! (31. Bxd7 Rd8 { I thought black was getting out of this, but missed the continuation: } 32. Qxe5 Rxd7 33. Re1 { threatening Qb8+ winning the queen } { [%cal Ge5b8] } 33... Bc8 34. Qe8+ Qf8 35. f7+ Rxf7 36. Qe5!! $18) 31... Nxe5 32. Qxe5 a6 33. Bd3 (33. Bd7!! { I was very low on time, so I missed another brilliant shot with Bd7 to deflect the queen from blockading. } { [%csl Ge6] } 33... Qxd7 34. f7+ Kf8 35. Qh8+ Ke7 36. f8=Q+ $18) 33... Re8 34. Qd4 Re6 35. c4 Rd6 (35... dxc4 36. Bxc4 $18 { [%cal Gc4g8] }) 36. c5 bxc5 37. bxc5 Rc6 38. a5 Rc7 { I was considering g4-g5 and h4 in order to cement that passed pawn, but I was down to seconds before hitting the time control. } 39. Qe3 Rc6 40. Qd4 Rc7 41. Rb1 Rc6 { Even after the time control, I miss-evaluated this tactic. So again, "simple is good" } 42. Rf1 (42. Rxb7 Qxb7 43. Qxd5+ Kf8 44. Qd8+ Kf7 45. Bc4+ Re6 46. Bxe6+ Kxe6 { Up two pawns, but with a very shaky king position. If only there was a way to trade queens... } { [%csl Ge7,Gd6] } 47. Qb6+ { Unfortunately, I only saw Qe7+ and Qd6+ in that final position, so I avoided this altogether. } 47... Qxb6 48. axb6 $18) 42... Rc7 43. h3 Rc6 44. g4 Bc8 45. Kg2 h5 46. Bxg6! { Finally a tactic that I could clearly visualize! } 46... Qxg6 47. f7+ Kh7 { I wanted to promote to a knight, just for the novelty of it. But I could clearly see the unavoidable mate after getting a new queen... } { [%cal Gf7f8] } (47... Qxf7 48. Rxf7 Kxf7 49. Qxd5+ Re6 50. Qxh5+ $18) (47... Kf8 48. Qh8+ $18) 48. f8=Q { [%cal Gf8h8] } (48. f8=N+ Kg8 { The move I wanted to play... but I saw to mate in the other line. }) 48... Qc2+ 49. Rf2 $18 { My opponent flipped over his king rather than sacrifice pieces to delay the mate. } { [%cal Gf8h8] } 1-0


