1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 Be7 5. Nc3 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 { [%cal Gd5c4,Gc8a6,Gc8b7] } 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bd3?! { While the bishop often is placed on d3 to attack the king and enable the e4 break, moving the bishop 3 times in the opening allows black to instantly equalize with the freeing c5 break. } 11... c5 12. Rc1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 (13. exd4!?) 13... Nc5 14. f4?! { [%csl Ge3] } (14. Bb1! Rc8 15. Qc2 { [%cal Gh4f6,Gc2h7] } 15... g6 { I thought here I was only equal. }) 14... Nd5 { Rather than immediately snapping up the bishop pair, I decide to enter complications where my opponent has many chances to go wrong, and I am pushing for a solid advantage. } 15. Bxe7 (15. Nxd5?? Qxd5! { [%cal Gd5g2,Ge7h4] }) 15... Qxe7 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] } 16. Nxd5 (16. Qe2 Nxd3 $15 { Only now I can take the bishop - once the queen has already moved. }) 16... Bxd5 17. f5?? Qg5! { [%cal Gg5g2,Gg5e3] } 18. Rf2 { My opponent finds the only move that doesn't immediately lose a piece. The computer suggested line here seemed messy to me, so I decided to avoid any counterplay on the open g file. } 18... Qxe3 (18... Bxg2 19. Rxg2 Qxe3+ 20. Kh1 Nxd3 { I was scared of this line, but in fact was seeing ghosts here, as Qg4 can be met with Nf2+. } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gd1g4,Gc1g1] }) 19. Bb1 { [%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] } 19... Ne4 { [%csl Gc3] } (19... Rad8?! 20. Rc3!) (19... Be4? 20. Rc3! { I was frustrated that I didn't quite have time to get my rook on the d file to win the knight. }) 20. Bxe4 Qxe4! { Taking with the queen gives up on the loose d4 knight, but ensures everything is well protected. } (20... Bxe4?! 21. Rc3!) 21. f6!? { An interesting try from my opponent to try and stir up trouble against my king. I took a long time before taking this pawn. The other moves I was considering didn't seem as appealing. } 21... gxf6 (21... Rac8 22. fxg7 Rfd8) (21... g6 22. Qd2 Kh7 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gc1c7] }) 22. Qd2 Rac8 23. Re1 { Keeping both rooks on the board is crucial if black wants to have a successful attack. } 23... Qh4 { [%cal Gf2f4] } (23... Qg6?? 24. Re3 { [%cal Ge3g3] } 24... Kh7 25. Rg3 Qh5 26. Rxf6) 24. Re3 { [%cal Gf2f4,Ge3g3] } (24. Nf5! exf5 25. Qxd5 { I wasn't sure if I was going to be able to win this game, but I figured - at least I have some shelter from the diagonal checks. } { [%csl Ge1] }) 24... Kh7! 25. Rg3 (25. Qd3+ f5 26. Nxf5 Rc1+ { [%cal Gd3h7] } 27. Rf1 Rxf1+ 28. Kxf1 Qf4+ { Black is OK. }) 25... Rg8! 26. Rf4 Qh5 27. Rxf6 Rxg3 28. hxg3 Kg7 { Finding these only-moves on the defense was taking a lot of time off my clock. I was now down to one minute or so. } 29. Qf4?? e5! 30. Rf5 (30. Nf5+?? Kxf6! { No fear! }) 30... exf4?? (30... Qd1+ { I told myself I wouldn't miss any checks... but with so little time on the clock, and tired from my long defense, I started to fall apart. } 31. Qf1 Qxd4+ 32. Kh2 Rc2 $19) 31. Rxh5 fxg3! 32. Ne2 (32. Rxd5?? Rc1#) 32... Bxa2 33. Nxg3 Rc5 { This endgame is clearly winning if only I could trade off the rooks, I would basically be able to premove... } 34. Rh4 Be6 35. Ra4 Rb5 { In general it's not good to trade pawns. But with so little time, I was trying to be practical. We trade pawns and I push my b pawn to victory. From this point on, I even stopped notating the game because we both had so little time left on the clock (<20 seconds, with a 10 second delay). And we all know how bad I am at blitz. } 36. b4 Bb3 37. Rxa7 Rxb4 38. Kf2 Be6 39. Ke3 Rb3+ 40. Kf4 b5 41. Ne2 { [%cal Ge2d4,Gd4e6,Gd4b3] } 41... Kf6 42. Nd4 Rb2 43. g4 b4 44. Rb7 b3 45. Rb6 Rd2?? { I missed my opponent's threat on b3... } { [%cal Gd2b2] } (45... Rb1 46. Kg3 Kg7 47. Rb7 b2! 48. Nxe6+ Kf6 49. Nf4 Rg1+ 50. Kf3 b1=Q $19 { If only I had time to calculate. }) 46. Nxe6 (46. Nxb3?? Rb2 $19) (46. Rxb3?? Rxd4+ $19) 46... fxe6 47. Rxb3 { I could instantly tell that this was a draw, but I refused to let my opponent have it with so little time on both of our clocks. I'm still the one pushing. } 47... Rd4+ 48. Kg3 e5 49. Rb6+ Kg5 50. Rb5?? { And he blunders right back. } 50... Rxg4+ 51. Kf3 Rf4+ 52. Ke3 Kf5 53. Ra5 h5 54. Ke2 h4 55. Ra8 Rb4 56. Rf8+ Ke4 57. Rh8 Rb2+ 58. Ke1 Kf3?? { Down to approximately 5 seconds, I missed my opponent's threat on the h pawn. We now enter a drawn philidor position. But can my opponent prove it? } { [%cal Ge5e4,Ge4e3,Gb2b1] } (58... Rh2 $19) 59. Rxh4 e4 60. Rh3+ Kg4 61. Rh1?? Rg2 (61... Rb1+ $19) 62. Kd1 Kf3 63. Rh3+ Kf2 64. Rh4?? (64. Kd2! { The only drawing move! White stops black from pushing the e pawn. }) 64... Rg1+ 65. Kd2 e3+ 66. Kd3 Rd1+ 67. Ke4 e2 68. Rh2+ Ke1?? (68... Kf1! 69. Rh1+ Kg2 $19) 69. Ke3 $10 { My opponent offered me a draw and I accepted it with 2 seconds on the clock. } 1/2-1/2


