1. e4 c5 { My first OTB Sicilian! } 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 { I enter the Prins to try and get a Maroczy bind structure and avoid any special Najdorf/Dragon theory. } 5... a6 6. c4 e5 7. Nc2 Be7 8. Nc3 Be6 9. Be3 Nbd7 10. Qd2 Rc8 11. Nd5 { I wanted to avoid play b3 just in case it was important not to loosen the c3 knight being x-rayed by the rook after a possible b5 or d5 break. } 11... Bxd5 12. cxd5 Nb6 { An interesting try. Again I wanted to avoid b3. So rather than make a committal pawn move, or developing the f1 bishop which is intended to take out this knight in only one move, I stayed flexible. } { [%cal Gb6c4] } 13. Rc1 Nc4?! (13... Qc7!? { Black should say, "two can play at that game" at which point, white is almost obliged to play b3 so that he can develop his bishop and finally castle. }) 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. O-O O-O 16. b3 { I finally relented and played b3 once I knew that the only move for black was full retreat. } { [%csl Gd4,Gb4,Ga4,Gc3,Gc2,Gc5,Gc6,Gc7] } (16. Na3!? { [%csl Gd6] } 16... Ra4 17. Nc4 Rxa2 { I was sure this position was winning for white somehow. But I couldn't calculate exactly how the rook would be trapped. With the computer anlaysis, it's obvious. } 18. Qc2 { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gc2b3] } 18... Qe8 19. Na3 $18 { [%cal Gc2b3] }) 16... Rc8 17. Na3 { [%cal Ga3c4] } 17... b5 { [%csl Gc6] } 18. Nc2! { Once black weakens the c6 square, white immediately pounces. } { [%cal Gc2b4,Gb4c6] } 18... Nd7 { [%csl Gc5] } (18... a5!? 19. Na3! { [%csl Gb5,Gc4] } 19... a4!? (19... Rb8 20. Rc6 { Black can't hope to hold this position. Nc4 must be allowed finally. }) 20. Nxb5 axb3 21. axb3 Rb8 22. Na7 Rxb3 23. Nc6 { I saw this far down the line and decided that even though white is not up material. The better bishop, better knight, and better queen are enough to have the advantage. }) 19. Nb4 Nb8 { A sad move to have to make. At this point, I decided it best to trade so that I can get a passed pawn. } (19... Nc5!? 20. Bxc5?? (20. Nc6!) 20... dxc5 21. Nxa6 Qb6 $19) 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Rc1 Qb7 22. Nc6 Nxc6 (22... h6!? { An interesting try. Black is not obliged to take the knight and create the passed c pawn. }) (22... Rc8?? 23. Nxe7+ { Black cannot add more pressure to the knight. }) 23. dxc6 Qc7 { [%cal Gd2d5] } 24. a4! { White wants a pawn on a5 to ensure the bishop can land on b6 and remove the blockader. } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Ge3b6] } (24. Qf2 Bd8 { I didn't see how this was helping white's cause, but it's clear that it's better to demote the bishop before the rook gets on the a or b file. }) (24. Qd5 { [%cal Ga2a4,Gd2a5] } 24... Rb8 { I didn't see how to actually win this. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf3f4,Ge5f4,Ge3f4] } 25. a4 bxa4 26. bxa4 a5 { [%cal Ge3d2,Ge7d8] }) 24... bxa4 25. bxa4 a5 { Necessary to avoid Bb6. } { [%cal Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gh5h6] } 26. Qd3?! { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ga6b7] } (26. Qd5 Rb8 { I saw this position. While white is clearly better in every conceivable way, I failed to find any real breakthrough. } 27. f4! Bf6 28. Bd2! { [%cal Gd2a5] } 28... Bd8?! (28... exf4 29. Bxa5 Qa7+ 30. Kh1 { [%cal Gc6c7] } 30... g6 31. c7 Rc8 32. Qxd6 $18) 29. fxe5 dxe5 { White can make more progress by creating a second weakness! }) 26... Rb8 27. Qa6 { [%csl Gd5,Ga6] } 27... h6 28. h3 (28. Bd2 Bd8 { I had improved all of my pieces as best as I could, but I couldn't find any breakthrough... }) 28... Bg5 29. Bxg5 hxg5 30. Kh2 { Out of ideas on how to dislodge the queen, I decide to play the waiting game. } 30... f6?! { Already my opponent messes up. Never play f6... } 31. Qc4+ { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gg8f8] } 31... Qf7?? 32. c7! { Without realizing it, my opponent has allowed the c pawn to move on. The rest of the game is an easy conversion. } 32... Rc8 33. Qc6 { [%csl Gd6] } 33... Qe7 34. Qb7 { [%cal Gb7c8] } 34... Qd7 35. Qd5+ Kf8 36. Qxa5 Ke7 37. Qb5? (37. Qa7 { Obviously better than what I played. } { [%cal Ga4a5,Ga5a6,Ga7b7,Ga6a7,Ga7a8] }) 37... Rxc7 { Oof. Now I have to win this queen and pawn endgame. Thankfully, my king is super safe and black's king can never really aid in the defense of the passed a pawn. } (37... Qxb5?? 38. axb5 Kd7 39. b6 g6 40. b7 { I saw this position, and was comfortable trading queens. Unfortunately, it's built upon a blunder. }) 38. Rxc7 Qxc7 39. a5 Kd8 40. a6 Kc8?? (40... g6!? 41. Qd5 { White has too many threats. } { [%cal Ga6a7,Ga7a8,Gd5g8] }) 41. Qe8+ $18 { My opponent resigned rather than see the following variation on the board. } 41... Qd8 42. Qxd8+ Kxd8 43. a7 1-0


