1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 a6 6. Nf3 c5 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Qd2 { We've entered the mainline classical French, but opponent doesn't quite know what to do. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Gb7b5,Gc5d4] } 8... g6?! { [%cal Gf7f6] } (8... b5 { Just getting on with the queenside expansion is best here. My opponent was worried about f5 for white here for unknown reasons. } 9. f5? (9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O-O { [%csl Gc5,Gg7][%cal Gg7g6] }) 9... Be7 10. O-O-O cxd4 11. Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] } 11... O-O $17) 9. dxc5 Bxc5 (9... Nxc5 10. Qf2! $16) 10. Be2 { I was struggling on how best to "punish" the one inaccuracy from my opponent. So I calmy developed instead of hastily castling into a queenside attack. } { [%csl Gg7,Gc5] } (10. O-O-O b5 { Scary, but white should be fine here too. }) 10... Qb6?! { [%cal Gb7b5] } (10... b5 { Again my opponent is scared of expanding with b5. }) 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. O-O-O { [%cal Gb7b5] } 12... Nb6? { Again! Here I started realizing that the only way I would lose to my opponent is if I go for a kingside attack, but end up getting mated first. So instead of going for murky waters with the typical g4-f5 break, I decided to trade everything and aim for a good knight vs bad bishop endgame. } { [%csl Gc8] } 13. Nd4 Nxd4 (13... O-O? 14. Nb3 Qb4 15. a3 Qe7 16. h4 $16) 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Rxd4 { [%csl Ge2,Gb6] } 15... O-O 16. g4 Nd7 { [%cal Gf7f6] } (16... Bd7?? { [%cal Gc3b5,Ge2b5,Gb4b5] } 17. Rb4! { The knight is trapped, and black loses a pawn by force. } { [%csl Gb7] }) 17. g5 b5 18. h4 Bb7 19. Rh3 { I wanted to get off the long diagonal, and I saw possibilities of swinging along the 3rd rank, but ultimately this move wasn't best. } { [%cal Gh3a3] } 19... Rac8 20. Kd2?! (20. Ne4?! dxe4 21. Rxd7 Bd5 { I was unconvinced here because black's bishop is finally active. }) (20. Nd1! Nc5 21. Ne3 Ne4 22. Ng4! $16 { The correct way forward, and an idea I didn't see at all during the game. My knight on c3 wasn't optimized, but when it lands on f6, it will land with a thud. }) 20... Rfe8 21. a4?! { Hasty. Once I saw that black was just waiting, I should have prepped this move with Rg3, so that the Rg1-Ra1 maneuver hits faster. } (21. Nd1! { Again, the same maneuver works. } { [%cal Gd1e3,Ge3g4] }) 21... bxa4 22. Rxa4 Rc6 23. Rg3?! { Planning to double on the a file, but avoiding the mined h1 square opposite black's LSB. This maneuver is so slow though... } { [%cal Gg3g1,Gg1a1] } (23. Rb4 Nc5 (23... Rc7?! 24. Na4! $16 { And my h3 rook can swing to the queenside immediately. } { [%cal Gh3c3,Gh3b3,Gh3a3] }) 24. Na4! Ne4+ 25. Ke3 Rc7 26. Bd3 $16 { Since I've opened up the LSB a little bit, I already need to play precisely to prove any advantage. }) 23... Rec8 24. Rg1 Nb6? (24... Nc5! 25. Rd4 Ne4+ 26. Nxe4 Rxc2+ 27. Ke3 dxe4 28. Rb4 { I was sure I was worse in this position. If only I had one extra move, Rc1 would have stopped everything... }) 25. Rd4 Nc4+ 26. Bxc4 Rxc4 (26... dxc4? { Opens up her bishop, but actually activates my knight and kills both her rooks. } 27. Ne4! $18) 27. Rxc4 Rxc4 28. Ne2 { Black is on the precipice of disaster, but didn't realize how dire this endgame would be. I felt that the only tries for black were Rb4 or Re4. } { [%cal Ge2f4,Ge2d4,Gc2c3] } 28... Kf8? (28... Rb4 29. Rb1? (29. b3 $14 { Necessary, but a move that doesn't fit with my plans. }) 29... Bc6! 30. c3 Re4! $15 { Black stays active. } { [%cal Ge2f4,Ge2d4] }) (28... Re4 29. Rg3! Bc6 30. b3 Bb5 31. Re3! { Black cannot maintain their active rook, with proper play. }) 29. c3 Rc8?! 30. Ra1 Ra8 31. Ra5 { Now black is doomed to a passive defense in this good knight vs bad bishop endgame. The only question is, will white be able to break through? } 31... Ke7 32. Nd4 Kd7 33. b4 (33. Ke3 Kc7 34. h5 Kb6 35. Ra1 { White can go for immediate kingside play instead of maximing the queenside position of the pieces as I did. }) 33... Kc7 34. Kd3 Kb6 35. Nb3 Rc8 36. Nc5 Rc7 (36... Rh8! 37. Kd4 h6 { Black needs to avoid passivity! }) 37. Kd4 Re7 38. Na4+ (38. Ra2 { This is actually the correct time to prepare the h5 pawn break. }) 38... Kc7 39. Kc5 Rd7 40. Nb6 Rd8 { I've maximized my piece placement, but where is the final breakthrough? After analysis, however, it is clear that I should undo my last few moves since d4 from black will be able to come soon and I'm playing with fire having my king barely defending the knight. } 41. Ra2 Re8 42. h5! Re7 43. c4?! { It's necessary to open up a second weakness for white to actually get anywhere, so I thought now was the time to strike with c4 (gaining access to the d6 square), but I overlooked one resource my opponent had... } (43. Rh2! { The cleanest approach that I didn't see. I can simply open the h file and infiltrate on h7. Black can't stop this. } { [%cal Gc7d8] } 43... Re8 44. hxg6 hxg6 45. Rh7 Re7 46. Rh8 $18 { In retrospect, it's so obvious... Now black has two accessible weaknesses. }) 43... dxc4 44. Nxc4 (44. hxg6! { This was the decisive mistake in the game. Had I foreseen what would happen, this would have assured victory... } 44... fxg6 45. Nxc4 Rf7 46. Rh2 $18) 44... Rd7 (44... Bd5?? 45. hxg6 fxg6 46. Rxa6 Kb7 { [%cal Ge7c7,Gc7c4] } 47. Rb6+ Ka7 48. Nd6 Rc7+ 49. Kb5 $18 { I made sure this wasn't possible for black. }) 45. Nd6 gxh5! { Black suddenly gets counterplay with their passed pawn! And the game is suddenly unclear. } { [%cal Gb7f3] } 46. Ra3 { [%csl Gf3] } (46. Rh2 Bf3 $10) (46. Nxb7!? Kxb7 47. Rh2 a5! 48. Rxh5 a4! 49. Rxh7 Rc7+ 50. Kd6 a3 51. Rh2 { White should still be winning this, but I didn't want to calculate another possibly drawn rook endgame. } 51... Kb6) (46. Rc2 { An engine line and the only line that truly keeps an advantage. } 46... Bf3 47. b5!! axb5 48. Kxb5+ Kb8 49. Kb6 $18 { The h pawn is irrelevant if white can actually breakthrough to black's king. } { [%cal Gc2c8] }) 46... Bg2 { The only move, but expected. } { [%csl Gh3] } 47. Rg3 (47. Rxa6?? { [%cal Ga6a2,Gh5h4,Gh4h3,Gh3h2,Ga2g2,Gh2h1] } 47... h4 48. b5 h3 49. b6+ Kd8 $19 { [%cal Ga6a8,Ga8e8] }) 47... Bf1 { Again the only move, but expected. } { [%csl Gh5] } 48. Ne8+ { [%cal Gc7d8,Gc7b7] } 48... Kb7 $10 { Draw offered and accepted. } 49. Nf6?! { If I want to play on here, I have to do some suspicious stuff: } { [%cal Gd7d5] } (49. Nd6+ $10 { The grandmaster draw. }) 49... h4 (49... Rc7+ 50. Kd6 h4 51. Rg4! h3 52. Rh4 { Amazingly white has some play here. I didn't see any of this during the game. } 52... Rc2 { With best play, white could possibly still be winning this. } 53. Rxh7 h2 54. Rxf7+ Kb6 55. Rh7 $16) 50. Rg1 (50. Rg4! { Transposing to the other line is best. }) 50... Rd1 { This variation scared me because for the first time this game, I was seeing variations where I was losing. } { [%cal Gg1g4,Gh4h3,Gg4h4] } 1/2-1/2


