{ Welcome to another instructive study by NoseKnowsAll. This interactive study is for newer players <1900 lichess, taking you through the games of one of the most important chess players of all time: Paul Morphy. Born in the 19th century, Morphy exploded onto the chess scene by essentially dominating every opponent he ever faced in the US and Europe from 1850-1860. He was so ahead of his time that he often gave his opponents piece odds or played them while blindfolded just to make the games more interesting.

As we go through his games, we'll learn about opening principles, middlegame strategy, and endgame fundamentals. We'll enjoy the dazzling tactical fireworks that set Morphy apart. While his games are often spectacular, the emphasis of this study will be on instructive value for beginners. My goal with the annotations is to explain many of the fundamental chess concepts that his games showcase. I will start from the most basic opening principles so every beginner can follow along.

I will walk you through many of Morphy's moves. After reading my annotations on the side, play the move marked by the arrow. However, I will also leave you to try to "guess the move" for some of Morphy's most instructive or beautiful moves. If you ever get stuck, click the "view the solution" button below the board, and then spend some time determining why that move was played. Were there threats you missed? Was there a strategic concept you didn't apply? That position is precisely where you're most likely to learn something new!

Throughout this study, I will provide general tips that Morphy's games showcase. These tips will mostly but not always relate to the current theme. Whenever this general advice occurs, I'll write it just like this:

PRO TIP: The best threat is often one that also improves the worst placed piece.

If you find this study useful, please heart it and share it with any friends! }
 *


