[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Part I: Fundamentals

Collections of Morphy games are organized into "chapters." The first three chapters will cover some of the most fundamental aspects of chess strategy: opening principles, blasting open the position when you have a lead in development, and how to thwart an opponent obsessed with moving their queen all over the board.

We will start with the most accessible collection of games, chosen for how instructive and easy to follow they are. These chapters are for players who are just starting to learn about chess strategy.

However, I will assume you know basic chess terminology like file, rank, pin, fork, etc. If this is not the case, I suggest you first play through the basics at https://lichess.org/learn before returning to this study.

Fair warning: This study is the length of a book, and so it is not designed to be completed in only one sitting. The best way to get the most out of this study is to take your time reading the annotations and truly put yourself in Morphy's shoes when trying to guess the move! Please return to make further progress as you have more time.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------

Chapter I: Opening principles

In these first games, Morphy will teach us the opening principles and the benefits of following them. In particular, every move in the opening should develop a piece, control the center, or get our king to safety. The best moves often accomplish multiple of these concepts simultaneously!

Hopefully anybody who just knows the rules of chess will be able to follow along!

Now without further ado, let's dive into our first Morphy game! }
 *


[Event "Paris"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Duke Karl / Count Isouard"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "The Opera Game"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/hfjeDaU2"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This is arguably Morphy's most famous game. Against two amateurs in an opera booth, Morphy shows his opponents the power of development and how to generate threats by bringing in the reserves at every opportunity. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 { Paul Morphy always started the game with 1. e4, which controls the center and prepares to develop the light squared bishop (LSB) and queen.
He was an expert at attacking chess, starting as early as move 1. The open games arising from 1. e4 particularly suit this style, and we will see his prowess time and time again from both sides of this position. } 1... e5 { A good response from black, for all the same reasons. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 { Developing a piece simply means bringing it off the back rank. In this case, the knight on g1 wasn't participating in the fight yet, but from f3 it is defended and controlling squares in the center. Therefore, it is now a productive piece.
The first of many threats in this game. White develops a new piece, controls the center, and threatens to win the e5 pawn. } 2... d6 { The Philidor defense. Playable, but passive. Black is merely responding to white's threat. In contrast to white's last move, black does not develop a piece.
Nc6 (developing a piece while defending against the threat) instead is more reliable. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 3. d4 { Striking in the center and seeking to develop the dark squared bishop (DSB) soon too. e5 is once again threatened.
This brings us to our first lesson that Morphy teaches us.
PRO TIP: Every move in the opening should seek to develop a piece, control the center, or get the king to safety. The best moves may in fact do several of these simultaneously!
Throughout this study, I will highlight many lessons that Morphy's game teach us, writing them succinctly as PRO TIPs. These tips will mostly but not always relate to the current theme of the chapter. } (3. Nc3!? { A reasonable move, developing the knight and controlling the center. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Bc4!? { The other principled developing move. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Bb5+? $15 { A bad check. After c6, we have to move the bishop again. Meanwhile, black is one move closer to taking over the center with d5. }) 3... Bg4?! { Black "defends" e5 by pinning white's knight. Unfortunately, this pin is easy to escape. } { [%cal Gd4e5] } 4. dxe5 { Resolving the tension in the center is only smart right now because white is threatening to win e5 next.
If black simply recaptures the pawn, white will be dominating after trading queens (escaping the pin on the knight with tempo!) and then playing Nxe5. } 4... Bxf3 { Black moves a developed piece a second time, while developing Morphy's army for him. This transaction means that black is losing "time" or dropping a "tempo."
However, this move is seemingly necessary since recapturing on e5 simply lost the pawn.
This is the first position where you must guess the move. What should white play? } (4... dxe5? 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nxe5 $16 { Up a pawn with tempo on the bishop and f7. White is practically winning already. }) (4... Nc6!? { Black has a gambit in this position worth exploring. } 5. exd6 Bxd6 $16) 5. Qxf3 { Of course we should recapture and develop a new piece. Note that the recapture gxf3 doesn't develop a piece - pawns aren't pieces! } (5. gxf3?! $14 { A worse recapture, since this move does not develop a piece. Note that pawns aren't pieces! }) 5... dxe5 { Since chess is a turn based game, it takes time to develop the pieces. Every move not spent on developing, controlling the center, or getting your king to safety is equivalent to throwing away time in the battle to coordinate your army and dictate the fight.
In this position, we can already say that white is ahead two tempi: one because the queen is already developed, and one because it is white to move. } 6. Bc4! { Developing a new piece while threatening checkmate! Once more, Morphy creates threats while developing.
PRO TIP: Developing quickly is crucial. Do not move a piece multiple times in the opening if instead you can bring out more pieces to participate in the fight. } (6. Nc3!? $14 { Not a bad move as this develops a piece and controls the center. Can you instead play a move that develops a piece and generates a threat? }) (6. Be3!? $14 { Not a bad move as this develops a piece and controls the center. Can you also find a move that develops a piece and generates a threat? }) (6. Bd2?! $14 { The bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file in case we put a rook on d1. }) (6. Bg5?? { Hangs a bishop. } 6... Qxg5 $19) (6. Bb5+?! $14 { An empty check that simply asks black to develop with Nd7 or regain the tempo with c6. After either of these moves, you have not truly gained a tempo. }) (6. Be2?! $14 { A half-developing move that does not improve the bishop in any meaningful way. }) (6. Bd3?! $14 { A half-developing move that does not improve the bishop in any meaningful way. }) 6... Nf6 { Black develops and defends against white's threat. } { [%cal Gf3b3] } 7. Qb3! { The only "hard" move of the game. Morphy moves his queen a second time, a seemingly unprincipled option.
"Doesn't this move lose time?" Only if black can ignore white's threats! By generating a double attack against f7 and b7 (Bxf7+ being the more important threat), white will get the move back. Indeed, Morphy is already winning a pawn should he choose to take it. } 7... Qe7!? { Black directly defends f7 by developing a piece. Unfortunately, this move blocks in black's dark squared bishop (DSB), slowing down any chances of castling. To finish development the queen needs to move again, and so this move ultimately loses time.
PRO TIP: Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing. To keep up with your opponent, you need to develop your entire army as soon as possible. It's not good enough to only develop some of your pieces!
Should we get greedy and capture on b7? } 8. Nc3! { An excellent move! Morphy develops a new piece with an eye on the center. Morphy rejects the greedy Qxb7 option and instead plays for piece activity and trusts in his lead in development. } (8. Qxb7?! { A greedy move that does in fact win a pawn. However, after Qb4+, we are trading queens and the damage is only limited to one pawn. Morphy plays for a larger advantage by not being greedy. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 $16) (8. O-O?! $16 { A developing move that proves you understand the opening principles. Unfortunately, the rook on f1 doesn't immediately win any awards, so it's better to leave queenside castling available in the long term. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (8. Bg5? $14 { A developing move, but one that backfires just as black's earlier pin with Bg4 did. Unfortunately, because black can get out of the pin with Qb4+, this move looks silly. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Nc3 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nbd7 $14) (8. Nd2? $14 { Develops a piece, but blocks in the DSB on c1. Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing! }) (8. Bd2?! $14 { Develops a piece and takes the sting out of Qb4+. But the bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file in case we put a rook on d1. }) 8... c6 { Black defends b7 directly, but again isn't developing a new piece.
White is already ahead two tempi by counting the developed pieces. Importantly though, white is actually up a third tempo, since black's queen must first move again to develop the DSB. White's lead in development is reaching epic proportions. } (8... Qb4? { This move no longer comes with check and is therefore ineffective. } 9. Bxf7+ $18) 9. Bg5 { PRO TIP: You must develop all the pieces, not just play with a few. GM Yasser Seirawan calls this "bringing all the boys to the party!"
Playing with all of the pieces against an opponent who is not developing is like playing a game with more players on the field. The team with more players in the action simply can do more. } (9. Be3!? $16 { An equally strong move. Play Bg5 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Bd2?! { The bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file in case we put a rook on d1. }) (9. O-O?! $14 { Gets the king to safety, and is therefore principled. However, the rook on f1 is not participating yet. There is a stronger developing move that sets up queenside castling instead. }) 9... b5? { The losing move. Black has played one too many unprincipled moves, and Morphy can now translate his massive lead in development into a direct assault against black's king. } { [%cal Gc3b5] } 10. Nxb5! cxb5 { [%cal Gc4b5] } 11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 { White has sacrificed the knight for two pawns. But more importantly, white has opened lines towards black's king and placed the LSB on a killer diagonal with tempo.
We say that white is down a piece. But is that really true? Until black's DSB or h8 rook contribute to the fight, black is not truly up a piece. In fact, the traffic jam in black's position means it's more reasonable to say that black is down a rook!
Getting those pieces into the game requires time. With his flawless execution of the remainder of this game, Morphy does not give his opponent that time.
How do we crank up the pressure further? } 12. O-O-O! { Bringing all the boys to the party! This is a great multipurpose move that both develops a rook and gets the king to safety (away from the action happening in the center of the board). Notice how kingside castling would have been inferior, as that only safeguards the king.
We typically say that white has "finished development" (and therefore entered the middlegame) when the rooks are connected and the king is safe. Therefore, we can see that Morphy is already well into the middlegame here while black is at least 3 moves away from escaping the opening.
This position is a picture-perfect showcase of development. } (12. O-O?! $16 { Gets the king to safety, and is therefore principled. However, the rook on f1 is not participating yet. There is a multipurpose move that accomplishes more! }) (12. Rd1?! $16 { Develops the rook to an open file, and is therefore principled. However, the king remains in the center. There is a multipurpose move that accomplishes more! }) (12. Bxf6?! $16 { Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) (12. Bxd7+? $17 { Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) 12... Rd8 { Black is scrambling to defend d7, but they are out of time. If only we could bring our final piece into play with tempo... } { [%cal Gd1d7] } 13. Rxd7! { An excellent shot! This exchange sacrifice is all about bringing in the reserves with tempo. In that sense, Rxd7 is a developing move. The final piece (the rook on h1) is now ready to join the attack with deadly effect. } 13... Rxd7 { This specific recapture was forced if black didn't want to lose a queen. Now let's bring the last piece into the attack. } 14. Rd1! { The final piece joins the attack and renews the threat to d7. Every single move Morphy plays brings more forces to the fight, generating threats whenever possible.
Notice how black's king is still stuck in the center, black's DSB cannot develop, and the rook on h8 is a passive bystander to the slaughter occurring in the center. We say that "white is down a rook." But I would argue that black is actually the one down a piece, since neither the DSB nor rook will get a chance to play at all. } { [%csl Rf8,Rh8] } 14... Qe6 { Black tries to trade queens and develop the DSB, but it's far too little too late.
At this point, nearly every move is winning for white. Can you find Morphy's artistic finish? } 15. Bxd7+ (15. Qxe6+?! { A forcing check and indeed a winning move because the rook on d7 will soon be lost. But why trade queens in the middle of a checkmating attack? Can you find Morphy's finish instead? } 15... fxe6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rxd7 $18) (15. Bxf6?! $18 { A forcing capture and indeed a winning move. d7 drops next. But Morphy's win is much more aesthetic starting with a more forcing check. }) 15... Nxd7 { Another recapture that is forced if black wants to keep their queen. What is the final blow? } 16. Qb8+!! { Yes! This brilliant queen sacrifice kicks off a mate in 2. } 16... Nxb8 { Black's move is yet again forced, allowing the beautiful finish. } 17. Rd8# { Morphy was as much an artist as a chess player! This checkmating pattern with the bishop and rook is known as "the opera mate" due to this very game.
The Opera Game is as beautiful as it is instructive. Indeed, this game alone teaches several fundamental strategic concepts. With every move, Morphy developed a new piece as rapidly as possible, generating threats along the way. Meanwhile black neglected development and king safety. Their inaccurate play got brutally punished by white's fully mobilized army.
I believe this game is so fundamental to every player's chess knowledge that we will revisit it later in more detail once we have a deeper chess vocabulary and broader chess understanding. } 1-0


[Event "Casual Game"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1850.??.??"]
[White "James McConnell"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C02"]
[Opening "French Defense: Advance Variation"]
