{ From Morphy's most famous game, we now turn to an overlooked masterpiece. Once more we will see Morphy precisely follow the opening principles, while mercilessly punishing an opponent who breaks them. }
1. e4 { [%cal Ge7e6] } 1... e6 { Morphy was a lifelong lover of the open game that arises from 1. e4 e5. With both colors he time and time again showed his mastery of the sharp tactics that arose.
Therefore it is unclear why in this casual game he played the French defense, which often leads to closed centers and slow maneuvering of the pieces. Indeed, this is Morphy's only recorded game playing the black pieces in the French. Regardless, this game shows that Morphy was as much a master of closed positions as he was open ones. } 2. d4 { [%cal Gd7d5] } 2... d5 { The point of the French: black challenges white's e4 pawn and uncontested central control on move 2. } 3. e5!? { A strong move, which cramps black's position, shuts down any dreams of activity for black's LSB, and prevents black's kingside knight from developing to its favorite square: f6.
Yet we should notice that this is not a developing move and could translate into a loss of time! } { [%cal Gc7c5] } 3... c5 { Again, Morphy strikes at white's center. } 4. c3 { White correctly defends their center with a pawn. With the pawn chain secure, white is hoping for an eventual kingside attack, utilizing the e5 pawn to its fullest. We shall examine many such attacks in Chapter VII: The e5 lance pawn.
However, white is once again not playing a developing move!
How can black crank up the pressure against white's center? } 4... Nc6 { Even though Morphy is playing black, this (completely standard) opening has already given him a slight lead in development! } (4... Qb6!? $10 { Somewhat interchangeable with the game continuation. How else can you develop and attack d4? }) 5. f4?! { White further cements their center, but this poor move fails to appreciate that tempo is still important in closed positions. Nf3 first, developing and defending d4, would have led to a standard advanced French position. } (5. Nf3 $10) 5... Qb6! { Development with a threat! This is an excellent multipurpose move since it develops while eyeing both d4 and b2.
It is instructive how both sides correctly keep the tension between the c and d pawns. White does not want to capture away from the center with dxc5, since that loses time while black's army develops with Bxc5. Likewise, black does not want to pull the trigger with cxd4, because white's cxd4 opens the c3 square to the b1 knight. Both captures lose time. } (5... cxd4?! $15 { We will soon discuss why neither side should release the tension. }) (5... Nge7?! $10 { Oh no, my c5 pawn! }) (5... Nh6!? $15 { Equally good to the game continuation. First pressure the d pawn instead. }) 6. Nf3 { A good move, developing and defending d4. } 6... Bd7 { This move in of itself is an ineffective developing move since the LSB stands just as well on c8 as d7. However, developing this bishop off the back rank clears the c8 square for a rook. Indeed, this move is more about claiming the c file than developing the bishop. } (6... Nh6!? $15 { Equally good. Play Bd7 first instead for the game continuation. }) (6... Be7?! $10 { A loss of tempo. When white plays dxc5 we will have to move this bishop again to recapture. }) (6... Nge7? $14 { Blocks in the DSB. Now when dxc5 is played, we would have to move our queen a second time (and to the more vulnerable c5 square!), thus losing time. }) 7. a3?! { White wishes they could develop the DSB, but that simply hangs b2. a3 prepares b4, when next the DSB can develop without hanging the b pawn. If that sounds complicated, it is because it is. Ultimately, this is just a poor move that loses more time.
A better move was Qb3, developing and seeking to relieve pressure on white's pawn chain with a queen trade. } (7. Qb3! $10) 7... Nh6! { A star move, highlighting Morphy's keen understanding of this French position. From f5, the knight will return to the center of the board with tempo since Nf5 hits d4 yet again.
There is a common phrase "knights on the rim are dim," which suggests knights should be developed to the center rather than the edge of the board. It's true that centralized knights influence more squares and more important squares than sidelined knights. However, knights on the rim that have a path back to the center can be great. Indeed, this h6 knight is one move away from becoming black's best piece! } (7... Be7?! $15 { A loss of tempo. When white plays dxc5 we will have to move this bishop again to recapture. }) (7... Nge7? $14 { Blocks in the DSB. Now when dxc5 is played, we would have to move our queen a second time (and to the more vulnerable c5 square!), thus losing time. }) (7... Rc8!? $15 { A reasonable alternative. However, there is a more important piece to develop before focusing on the heavy pieces. We want to develop with threats, and claiming the c file doesn't immediately generate any. }) (7... O-O-O? $14 { The king is not any safer on the queenside, nor is the rook any better on d8. It's not a good idea to consider such a move. }) (7... cxd4?! { All the same reasons that both sides should keep the tension still applies. } 8. cxd4 $15) 8. b4?! { White influences the c5 pawn but still isn't developing the pieces.
What is the best response? } 8... cxd4 { Yes! We capture towards the center to finally convert d4 into a tangible weakness. Notice how Morphy kept the tension in this position until white lost several tempi to force his hand.
Let's consider the other moves black should not have played last move:
* After cxb4?! axb4, we would have only developed white's rook for them.
* After c4?, the position would be closed, and we would have just killed the effectiveness of both our c6 knight and queen by forever removing d4 as a target. In general, we want more active pieces, not less active ones! } (8... c4? { A horrible move! Now that d4 is no longer a target, both of our knights (and queen!) have just lost their job. As we will see in countless Morphy examples, you must open the position when you have a lead in development, not close it! }) (8... cxb4?! { After axb4, we are only developing white's rook for them. }) 9. cxd4 { White maintains their center, but the disparity in development should already be worrying... } (9. Nxd4 a5 $17 { White has less central control. Although this might have been the lesser evil. }) 9... Rc8 { Arguably Nf5 was the more precise move, but there is no reason to criticize this fine developing move that places a rook on the only open file. } (9... Nf5! $17 { Great move! This is more precise and slightly more logical than Morphy's move. Play Rc8 first for the game continuation. }) (9... Be7?! $15 { We can call this a half-developing move. The bishop is not any better on e7 than f8. There are more important moves to make first before we should resort to this lame option. }) 10. Bb2 Nf5 (10... Be7?! $15 { We can call this a half-developing move. The bishop is not any better on e7 than f8. There are more important moves to make first before we should resort to this lame option. }) 11. Qd3?! { Every black piece is playing. Morphy has a lead in development with 5 pieces out to white's 3 and is therefore up three tempi because it is black to move. Moreover, white's last move just put the queen on a vulnerable square. If only there was some way to open up the position... } { [%cal Gf8b4] } 11... Bxb4+! { Blasting open the position, identical to the sacrifice from the Opera Game.
I may not spell out exactly why every line works for Morphy throughout this study. However, the annotations explaining the tactics behind the scene will always include those details. To see the full annotations, click the "Analysis Board" button at the end of the game. } 12. axb4 { [%cal Gc6b4] } 12... Nxb4! { Morphy's lead in development directly translates to an attack, as his pieces flood the center, each improving with tempo.
PRO TIP: One of the main ways to increase a lead in development is to improve your pieces while making threats. If your opponent has to play a suboptimal or non-developing move to deal with your threat, then your move is said to have "gained time." } 13. Qd2 { [%cal Gc8c2] } 13... Rc2! { Our rook on c8 was useful, controlling the c file. But now on c2 it is optimally placed, raking across the 2nd rank. Morphy is at least regaining the sacrificed piece with interest.
PRO TIP: The best threat is often one that also improves the worst placed piece. } 14. Qd1 { White plays the only available move with the queen, sadly returning her to her original square.
Can you believe that black is technically down a bishop in this position? I would argue that counting the pieces doing anything constructive points us to a new material count: black is up a rook and a knight! Almost all of white's pieces remain at home watching TV, so of course black is winning in a variety of ways.
Can you put the game away with one more move? } 14... Ne3! $19 { Trapping the queen! Morphy recognizes that it's better to win a queen with Ne3 than recapture his sacrificed piece with Rxb2.
Just as in the Opera Game, Morphy sought to make every developing move one that came with a threat. Meanwhile, white lost time with unnecessary pawn moves instead of developing their pieces, ultimately allowing Morphy's lead in development to directly translate into an attack. } (14... Rxb2!? $19 { A clean option. Black regains all the sacrificed material with interest. Yet Morphy found an even more crushing move. }) (14... O-O?! $19 { Hilariously even this slow but solid option is completely winning for black. Kudos for seeking to develop all of your pieces! Play for a crushing attack instead. }) 0-1


[Event "1st American Chess Congress"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.11.04"]
[Round "4.7"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Louis Paulsen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B40"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Paulsen-Basman Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Don't hang your stuff"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/ERigB1R6"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This next game is less satisfying than the previous two but no less instructive. Against one of the top US players, Morphy provides a reminder of the most fundamental chess skill: you cannot give your opponent free stuff, and you must be alert for when your opponent gives you free stuff.

PRO TIP: You can play the most principled chess in the world, but you will lose the game if you hang a queen. More fundamental than all the principles in the world is the skill of taking free pieces and not giving away free pieces! } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 { Bobby Fischer, 100 years after this game was played, famously said that 1. e4 is "best by test." Indeed, this principled move that takes the center and seeks to develop the LSB and queen remains the most common move even to this day in both professional and amateur play. } 1... c5 { The Sicilian defense. Black doesn't yet develop, but this c pawn now prevents white from fully owning the center with 2. d4. It is therefore a principled response to 1. e4. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 e6 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 3. d4 { 3. d4, entering the Open Sicilian, opens the center and prepares rapid development. The Open Sicilian remains the best way for white to get an advantage against the sharp Sicilian defense to this day. } 3... cxd4 { Of course. The point of the Sicilian was to prevent white from dominating the center. Therefore, when white plays d4, this capture is logical to avoid being overruled. } 4. Nxd4 { White is only up one tempo if you count the developed pieces. But black still needs to make another pawn move (or two!) to open up a route into the game for the LSB. On the other hand, white's pieces have many central options, and in particular both bishops have free diagonals.
This is one of the main benefits of playing the Open Sicilian: white attains a sizable lead in development in practically every variation. } (4. Qxd4?! { A worse recapture. After Nc6, developing a piece, we will have to move the queen again. Therefore, this move loses time. }) 4... Bc5 { An off-beat line in the Open Sicilian. Nc6 is more reliable. } { [%cal Gc1e3] } 5. Be3 { A principled developing move, but not the only option for white. } 5... Qb6 { The position is already critical. Black threatens b2, and there is no way to develop a piece and defend it. } 6. Nc3!? { A classic response to black's supposed threat: ignore it! Morphy argues that black does not have the right to create threats due to their poor development. "If you want to waste more time snagging a useless pawn, be my guest!"
We will explore this concept further in Chapter V: Active defense. } (6. Na3!? { A great way to develop and ignore black's threat to b2. Qxb2?? is met with Nab5, when there is no way to avoid the queen getting trapped or the fork on c7. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. } 6... Qxb2? 7. Nab5! Bb4+ 8. Ke2 $18 Na6?! (8... Nf6!? 9. Nc7+ $18) 9. a3! Be7 10. Rb1 Qa2 11. Nb3! Nf6 12. Ra1 Qb2 13. Bd4 $18) (6. b4!? { In the style of the Evans Gambit. This bizarre move does have a point since Bxb4+ c3 overprotects d4 with tempo on the bishop. However, such a gambit is less principled than other options available to white here. } 6... Bxb4+ 7. c3 Bc5 8. Nd2 $16) (6. Qd2?! { A developing move, but how does this move address the threat to b2? } 6... Qxb2 7. Qc3?? (7. Nb3! $14) 7... Bb4 $19) (6. Bc4?! { A logical developing move, but how does this move address the threat to b2? } 6... Nc6! 7. c3 Nf6 8. O-O Nxe4 $15) (6. Be2?! { A logical developing move, but how does this move address the threat to b2? } 6... Qxb2 $15) (6. Bd3?? { Oh no, your knight! } 6... Bxd4 $19) (6. Bb5? $15 { A highly suspicious move. On this square, the bishop is attacked once and defended once, so it is a loose piece. Moreover, the defender on d4 can be removed.
How are you dealing with Bxd4? How about e5? How about Nc6? Don't set yourself up for failure with such a move! Don't hang your stuff. }) (6. Qc1?? { Oh no, your knight! This move is unprincipled as well as tactically flawed. } 6... Bxd4 $19) (6. b3? { A poor choice that should never cross your mind. The sole reason for playing this move is to avoid losing material. Unfortunately, not only does this move lose time, it also weakens our queenside and makes normal moves like Nc3 significantly weaker (since the knight would be loose). Passive defense is almost never the way forward. } 6... Nf6 $15) 6... Qxb2?? { A horrible blunder by Paulsen. White already has three pieces developed, but the LSB, queen, and now a1 rook can immediately swing into action too. Meanwhile, black only has two pieces developed, a queen uncoordinated with any other piece, and no other pieces remotely ready to join the action.
Not only is this greedy pawn grab unprincipled (white already has a lead in development, so wasting time with the queen and opening up a file for white's rook is suicidal), it also unsurprisingly fails tactically.
PRO TIP: When you have a huge lead in development in an open position, and your opponent plays several unprincipled moves, you should be looking for ways to punish them!
Nc6 instead, developing and creating a threat on the d4 knight, was the correct way to play. } (6... Nc6 $10) 7. Ndb5! { A simple forcing move. White threatens Nc7+ winning the exchange, Bxc5 winning a piece, and Rb1 trapping the queen. There is no defense. } (7. Ncb5!? { A sensible option, threatening Rb1 and Nc7+, but there's a flaw! What are you doing in response to Bb4+? } 7... Bb4+ 8. Ke2!! $16 { White retains all the previous threats, but now we have to play a position with our king on e2. }) (7. Na4?! { A sensible option, threatening the queen and bishop, but there's a flaw! What are you doing in response to Bb4+? } 7... Bb4+! 8. Ke2! $16 { White still maintains the lead in development, but now we have to play a position with our king on e2. Still, this position is good for white if we can fix our kingside. }) (7. Rb1?? { Oh no your knight! } 7... Qxc3+ $19) (7. Nce2? $17 { Too passive. You're just responding to black's threat. }) (7. Qd2?? { A desirable developing move if it didn't hang the rook on a1 with check! } 7... Qxa1+ $19) 7... Bxe3 (7... Bb4!? 8. Bd4! $18) 8. Rb1! { And just like that, the queen is trapped! } (8. fxe3? { Keep your eye on the prize! The queen was the true target here. } 8... Qb4!? 9. Nc7+ Kd8 10. Qd2!! Kxc7?? 11. Nd5+! exd5 12. Qxb4 $18 { White still has tactics that make this line work out well. But this is not the simple solution we were looking for. }) (8. Nc7+?? { A typical mistake when calculating. This intermediate check does not win the exchange because our knight on c3 is also hanging and we have not recaptured the bishop! When you are playing forcing moves, don't forget to calculate your opponent's forcing moves as well! } 8... Kd8 $19) 8... Qxb1 9. Nxb1 $18 { The game ( https://lichess.org/nFqj4t4b#17 ) ended on move 26 but black, down a queen, never had a chance.
This is not the last time we will see Morphy's opponents miss his forcing moves that directly win material. However, I believe it's worth highlighting how crucial of a skill it is to play a game of chess without hanging something.
In fact, the best way to improve at nearly all levels is to stop hanging free stuff and always capture the opponent's free stuff. At the lowest levels, this means working on your board vision and consistently having a strong understanding of what squares and pieces are defended or under attack. At higher levels, this means working on tactics problems that improve both your pattern recognition and calculation abilities. } (9. Qxb1!? $18 { Equally good. Play Nxb1 for the game continuation. }) 1-0


[Event "1st American Chess Congress"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.10.13"]
[Round "2.1"]
[White "Alexander Beaufort Meek"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
