[ECO "C65"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Anti-Berlin Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Meek development"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/0TDH5pLP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We return from our brief foray into tactics to see how opening principles apply in a slow-building position. Even when there are no fireworks on the board, adhering to the principles of rapid development, central control, and king safety will net dividends.

Morphy's opponent is Alexander Meek, a US judge and clear underdog to Morphy. This game was played in round 2 of the 1st American Chess Congress, Morphy's breakout tournament that catapulted him to international fame. }
1. e4 { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Ruy Lopez or "Spanish" was less common in the Romantic Era since it was more positional than the sharper alternatives like the Evans and King's Gambit. } { [%cal Gg8f6] } 3... Nf6 { Both a very old and very new move. Kramnik popularized this option in the 21st century, famously defending the "Berlin endgame" that arises after O-O Nxe4 in his 2000 WCC match against Kasparov. } 4. d3 { White defends the e pawn directly. Is Bxc6 followed by Nxe5 a threat?
How best to react to this threat? } (4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $10 { The Berlin endgame }) 4... Bc5! { A nice developing move that defends against white's threat to the e pawn by essentially ignoring it!
Bc5 is another example of "active defense," a concept to be explored in Chapter V. } (4... d6?! $14 { Directly defending against white's threat is not so precise since now we have blocked our DSB inside the pawn chain. }) (4... Bd6?! $14 { A playable alternative, but you will have to work extremely hard to move this bishop again in order to develop the LSB. Let's not lose tempo! }) (4... Qe7?! { You are blocking in your DSB, similar to black's play in the Opera Game. We want to emulate Morphy's play, not his opponent's play! } 5. O-O $14) 5. c3 { I may not lay out in the words why every line works for Morphy. However, the annotations explaining the tactics behind the scene will always include those details. To see the full annotations, click the "Analysis Board" button at the end of the game.
This exact variation has returned to prominence in top level chess in the last decade because white players have struggled to find ways to fight for an advantage in the more forcing lines leading to the Berlin endgame.
While this is a fine move, controlling black's knight and DSB, we should appreciate that it is not a developing move and thus white's first loss of time. } (5. O-O!? $10) (5. Bxc6!? dxc6 6. Nxe5?? Qd4 $19) 5... d6 { Morphy directly defends e5 only now that the DSB is outside the pawn chain. } (5... O-O!? { These days, this is a common option as well. The point is that after Bxc6 bxc6!, Nxe5!? d5! black has full compensation for the pawn due to the lead in development and opening of the center.
Play d6 instead for the game continuation. } 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. Nxe5 d5 $10) (5... d5!? $10 { A sharp move that equalizes the game according to modern theory. Play d6 instead for the game continuation. }) 6. b4 { Gaining space on the queenside with tempo on our bishop. But yet again this isn't a developing move... } 6... Bb6 (6... Bxf2+?? { Oh no, your bishop! We have nowhere close to enough pieces for this sacrifice to work out. After reading through Chapter IV, perhaps you will have a better sense of when such a sacrifice is reasonable. } 7. Kxf2 Ng4+ 8. Kg1 $18 { There is no follow-up. }) 7. a4 { White tries to trap our bishop with a5. Yet again, not a developing move. } 7... a6 (7... a5!? $15 { My personal preference for dealing with white's queenside pawn storm because it employs the rook. Play a6 instead for the game continuation. }) (7... Ng4?! $14 { A one move threat that is dealt with by O-O. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! }) 8. Bc4?! { Wasting time with the bishop. By move 8, white has only developed two pieces. } (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O $10 { Correct play. White gets on with development ASAP. }) 8... Be6!? { Developing and challenging white's best piece. One of several fine developing moves in this position. } (8... O-O!? $10 { An equally fine developing move. Play Be6 for the game continuation. }) (8... Ne7!? { A high-class positional move. The knight is better placed on g6 than dominated on c6. Play a more direct developing move instead for the game continuation. }) (8... Bg4?! { We do not want to capture on f3, and after h3 Bh5?! our bishop is doing nothing except getting kicked around.
In e4-e5 games, pinning with Bg4 or Bg5 is often overrated unless you can follow-up with more pressure on the pinned knight. }) 9. Bxe6 fxe6 { The doubled pawns are more of an asset than a liability. Firstly, an e6 pawn covers the important d5 and f5 outposts that white commonly uses in the previous structure. Secondly, recapturing on e6 is actually a developing move! Now a rook on f8 will stand well on the half-open f file. } 10. O-O O-O 11. Ng5?! { A one-move threat that is easily parried by developing. While this is a poor move, white will not lose the game in the next 5 moves like Morphy's previous opponents because their center is stable and king is safe. Regardless, these inaccuracies add up to giving black the better position.
PRO TIP: Do not make threats that can be conveniently parried by moves your opponent wants to make anyway. Essentially, you are forcing your opponent to play good moves! } 11... Qe7!? { Note that the knight on g5 is not coordinated with any other piece and therefore can next be kicked back with h6. Making two moves with the knight to force black to develop their pieces translates to a clear loss of two tempi. } (11... Qd7!? { Equally strong. The queen has slightly less options from d7 than e7 though. }) (11... Qe8!? $10 { Equally strong. The queen remains in the way of the rooks from e8 than on e7. }) (11... Re8? $14 { Demoting your rook from a half-open file to a closed file just to defend against white's threat? Morphy would never play such a passive move. }) (11... Qc8?! $14 { Demoting your queen purely to defend against white's threat? Morphy would never play such a passive move. }) 12. Kh1?! { Another ridiculous loss of time. White wants to get in f4, but again refuses to develop a piece. } { [%cal Gh7h6] } (12. Nd2 $10 { Clearly the best move. Developing a piece. }) (12. Qb3!? Rae8 $10) 12... h6 13. Nh3 { Black has a fully developed army and therefore is in the middlegame, while half the white pieces are at home watching TV. Black must clearly have the advantage based on development alone.
How best can we press the advantage? } 13... d5! $15 { Yes! Taking the center is the most principled choice.
PRO TIP: The best way to refute unprincipled play is to play the most principled chess conceivable. We will repeatedly see Morphy refute his opponents by centralizing his pieces and following the opening principles, not by playing outlandish or esoteric plans/moves.
This game ( https://lichess.org/2LYKfGAg/black#26 ) continued to move 29, but the remainder of the game is less instructive. In this position, Morphy has already finished development, taken over the center, and centralized his pieces. Meanwhile white is doing who knows what with their knight and refusing to develop the queenside. Black is already clearly in control. } (13... Rad8!? $15 { A reasonable alternative, placing a rook on a soon-to-be important file. Yet this file is only relevant if you follow-up with the move Morphy plays in the game. }) (13... Rf7!? $10 { Preparing to double on the f file makes sense, but isn't the strongest plan. }) (13... Ba7!? $10 { A thematic maneuver typical of this position. Black retreats the bishop to avoid getting hit with a5 with tempo at a later date.
Morphy doesn't mess around in positions by playing such subtle moves. He is full steam ahead! }) 0-1


[Event "Casual game"]
