{ In one of his first ever recorded games, a 10 year old Morphy takes on his father. Once more we will see the opening principles in action, and how to decisively finish off an opponent who doesn't develop their pieces. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 { The King's Gambit was a mainstay during the Romantic era of chess (1830s-1880s, including Morphy's time), as it had a reputation for creating fireworks on the board. Indeed this will not be the last King's Gambit we will see Morphy play with either color.
f4 itself is positionally motivated: if white can remove black's e5 pawn with a flank pawn, then white can dominate the center with both e4+d4. The problem is that touching the f pawn is fraught with danger since the king is now weakened, especially along the e1-h4 diagonal, at an early stage of the game. } 2... exf4 { As opposed to the Queen's gambit (1. d4 d5 2. c4), accepting this gambit is the most accurate way to play. Black should welcome a chance to weaken white's king at such an early stage! White will need to work hard to conveniently recapture this pawn by developing a piece.
Note though that this capture takes away from the center and clearly loses a tempo. There is a clear trade-off for winning this pawn. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 { Judit Polgar's favorite variation when she picked up the King's Gambit in the 1980s. } 3... Qh4+!? { The obvious downside to white's play: black immediately pounces on the weakened diagonal towards white's king and forces white's king to move. This annoying check though may be overrated as Nf3 is soon to come, regaining a tempo on the queen. } { [%cal Ge1f1] } 4. Kf1 Bc5?! { Black reveals that he is an amateur. This move threatens mate in 1, but Alonzo has clearly not learned the lesson we have from the previous game. Do not make threats that can be conveniently parried by moves your opponent wants to make anyway!
In fact, black's activity has reached the maximum it will ever reach again this game. } 5. d4! { Taking the center with e4+d4 is one of the main plans of the King's Gambit. Indeed, white would have played this move anyway if black had done absolutely nothing last move. Forcing white to play such a productive move with tempo shows that black did not bother to calculate even a single ply deep before playing Bc5... } (5. Qe2?! $15 { Let's take the fight to black! Not passively defend against their threats. }) (5. Qe1?! $17 { Let's take the fight to black! Not passively defend against their threats. }) (5. Nh3? $17 { Let's take the fight to black! Not passively defend against their threats. }) (5. Qf3? $17 { Let's take the fight to black! Not passively defend against their threats. }) (5. g3? { After fxg3 your entire kingside is wrecked. This is no way to defend. } 5... fxg3 6. Nf3?? g2+ 7. Kxg2 Qf2+ 8. Kh3 d5#) 5... Bb6 6. Nf3 (6. Nc3!? $14 { Equally good. But we 100% know where our kingside knight belongs, while it's still unclear if this is the best square for the queenside knight. }) 6... Qe7 { We should briefly take stock of the position out of the opening. White has the perfect center, and has gained a tempo by kicking black's queen backwards. White is already better. } 7. Nc3 { Simply developing and defending e4. Moreover, the idea of Nd5 has been introduced, further centralizing while gaining tempo against black's queen.
The tempting Bxf4, regaining the sacrificed pawn, is going nowhere. } (7. Bxf4?! { Positionally desirable. But did you see your e4 pawn was hanging? } 7... Qxe4 8. Qd2! $16) (7. Qd3?! $14 { Is this really the dream square for our queen? Unclear. }) (7. Qe2?! $10 { Is this really the dream square for our queen? Unclear. }) (7. Nbd2? $15 { Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing. }) (7. Kf2? $15 { It is a bad idea to align your king opposite their bishop. Focus on developing other pieces instead - the rook can wait. }) (7. Qe1?! $15 { Defends the e pawn but is otherwise putting the queen on a suboptimal square. }) (7. Bd3?! $10 { We should not be interested in losing a tempo just to defend this pawn! }) (7. Bd5? { We should not be interested in losing a tempo just to defend this pawn! } 7... c6 $10) (7. e5?! $10 { We should not be interested in losing a tempo just to defend this pawn! }) 7... Nf6 { [%cal Gd1d3] } (7... g5? 8. Nd5 $18) 8. Qd3? { Developing and defending the e pawn. At face value, this is a reasonable move.
However, a more experienced Morphy would have first looked at his available active options and found e5! Black's knight didn't have any square to go to except g8, after which white would have had a monstrous position. } (8. e5! { Excellent job improving over Morphy's play! This thematic central thrust kicks black's knight back to its starting square. } 8... Ng8 { Sad, but necessary. } (8... d5? 9. exf6 $18) (8... Ng4?! 9. Bxf4 $16 { [%cal Gh2h3] }) (8... Nh5? 9. g4! fxg3 10. Kg2 $18 { Some classic King's gambit action. Nd5 and Ng5 are massive threats that will wreck black's haphazardly placed pieces. }) 9. Bxf4 $16) (8. Bxf4?! $14 { Reasonable, since Nxe4 is suicidal. But there is much better in the position. }) 8... c6?! { Another soft move that does not develop a piece. d6, holding up white's center and preparing to develop the LSB, was significantly stronger. } 9. Bxf4 { White develops the last minor piece and regains the sacrificed pawn. This central control and piece constellation is the dream of any King's Gambit player.
The only "issue" in white's position is the king. It should be emphasized though that there is no issue in terms of king safety - what black piece can possibly hurt the king on f1? The true issue is that white's rook on h1 remains locked out of the game as long as the king remains on f1. } (9. e5!? { A reasonable alternative since the knight again doesn't have a good square to go to. Did you see that black had prepared the thematic counterpunch d5? That move would give the knight the e4 square if possible. } 9... d5! 10. exf6 Qxf6! (10... dxc4?? 11. fxg7!! (11. fxe7?? cxd3 $17) 11... Rg8 12. Qxh7! $18) 11. Bb3 O-O $16 { Black is down a piece, but their pawn chain kills both the knight on c3 and bishop on b3. Winning this position still takes a lot of work. }) 9... d5!? { The only move to prevent getting run over by e5. But this move sacrifices a pawn and opens the position for white's pieces. } (9... O-O?! 10. e5! Ne8 11. Bg5 $18 { Too pathetic a position to play. Not to mention the queen is trapped. } 11... Qb4 12. a3 Qxb2 13. Ra2 $18) 10. exd5 { We shall see many later examples exploring the benefits of opening up the position when ahead in development. } 10... O-O { A nice sequence by black from a bad position. Black has successfully castled and avoided their knight getting kicked around by e5... at the cost of a pawn. } { [%cal Gd5d6] } 11. d6 { Opens up the LSB with tempo. } 11... Qd8 { The only square that does not block in any of the remaining pieces. Now that the dust has settled, it's obvious that black's earlier Qh4+ has backfired. After three moves, the queen has done nothing but return to her home square. } 12. Re1! { The Morphy move! Before starting decisive action against black's king, Morphy first "brings all the boys to the party," as GM Yasser Seirawan says. } (12. Rd1?! $16 { A developing move. But the rook is clearly more active on the e file than on the d file. }) (12. Kf2!? { Seeking to get the h1 rook into the game is reasonable. Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. } 12... Nh5! $16 { An awkward move to meet for just one move. }) 12... Re8 { White is up four tempi in this open position. There are many ways to execute an attack from such a monstrous position. } { [%cal Gf3g5] } 13. Ng5 { f7 is a massive target. The most direct knockout was Bxf7+, but Morphy's Ng5 here ends the game just as quickly. } (13. Bxf7+!? Kxf7 14. Qc4+ Kf8 15. Ng5 Rxe1+ 16. Kxe1 Qd7 17. Rf1 $18 { Nh7+ is a decisive threat. }) (13. Kf2?! $18 { A fine move to connect the rooks. Morphy accomplishes the same thing in the game but one tempo faster. }) 13... Rxe1+ 14. Kxe1 Qe8+ { [%cal Ge1d2] } 15. Kd2 Be6 { Yes, white's king has been checked around a few times this game. But all of white's pieces are working, and the king is no less safe on d2 than on b1 or c1 as if he had originally castled queenside. In fact, black's king is the monarch coming under fire by all of white's pieces!
PRO TIP: King safety is exclusively measured by how easily the king can come under fire. The square the king resides on, the number of pawns sheltering the king, or the amount of times the king has been checked are not determining factors for how safe a king is. } 16. Re1! { The Morphy move, bringing all the boys to the party! } (16. Rf1?! { A reasonable square for the rook, eyeing f7. Unfortunately, with Bxc4 black is able to trade pieces and relieve the pressure to f7. }) (16. Nxe6?! $18 { Cashing in slightly too early. This bishop can instead be hit a third time by developing the last piece! }) (16. Bxe6?! $18 { Cashing in slightly too early. This bishop can instead be hit a third time by developing the last piece! }) 16... Nbd7?! { Black finally develops their queenside, but it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games. } { [%cal Gg5e6] } 17. Nxe6 { One of many knockouts. My personal favorite, Nxf7, was as flashy as it was strong. } (17. Nxf7! { A nice KO move as well since the bishop on e6 is pinned and therefore will be lost next move. Play Nxe6 instead for the game continuation. } 17... Kxf7 18. Rxe6 $18) 17... fxe6 { [%cal Ge1e6] } 18. Rxe6 $18 { Black resigned in this position. The queen is under fire, and any queen move besides Qf7 hangs mate-in-1 to Re8 double checkmate! Unfortunately, Qf7 only prolongs the inevitable because Re7 both pins and wins the queen.
Hopefully you are starting to see a pattern in Morphy's games. Every move he plays in the opening develops a piece, controls the center, or gets the king to safety. While developing, he creates threats and gains tempi whenever possible. Finally, Morphy utilizes all of his pieces to take down an opponent who has failed to adequately develop their pieces.
Sometimes chess is that easy. } 1-0


