{ NN, or "no name," is a common name given to players of recorded games whose names have been lost to history. Since Morphy was so much stronger than most of his opponents, he offered many players material odds before the game. In this game, he was so confident against this unnamed player that he offered to start the game down the a1 rook.

Those odds are easily surmounted this game, as once more Morphy plays principled chess and his opponent doesn't. } { [%csl Ra1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 { I will soon stop extolling the virtues of 1. e4. Morphy played 1. e4 in every single game in this study, and indeed in the vast majority of his recorded games. } 1... e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 { The Italian game in modern times is chosen as a way to keep tension in the position and maneuver slowly in the middlegame. In the Romantic Era, the Italian was played to dynamically crush black out of the opening on the weak f7 square. } 3... Bc5 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 4. b4!? { Our first Evans gambit, but certainly not our last. Morphy was the world's leading authority on this opening (assuming he had a rook still on a1!), and played it throughout his career.
White sacrifices the b pawn to open up lines, force black to lose another tempo with their bishop, and build up a strong center with c3+d4. } 4... Bxb4 { Black is forced to waste a tempo with the bishop. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 Ba5 { Black is forced to waste another tempo with the bishop, while white builds a strong center. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 6. d4 { Visually, white's center and development look healthy. However, we cannot ignore the fact that white has sacrificed a pawn (and indeed started this game down a rook). So white very much has something to prove in order to avoid the missing material becoming the most relevant factor in the position. } 6... exd4 { Black calls white's bluff. If the c pawn cannot recapture on d4 due to the pin, what center is white building anyway? } 7. O-O! { Yes! We simply develop and get out of the pin. If black wants to waste all their tempi taking free pawns and opening up white's pieces, we should allow them. } (7. Nxd4? $19 { We certainly don't want to play this recapture, trading pieces and removing all hope of building up the ideal pawn center. }) (7. Qb3!? $19 { A common move in the Evans to continue focusing in on f7. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) 7... Nf6 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 8. Ba3 { As we play through many Evans Gambit games, we will see the bishop arrive on a3 in many lines. An important recurring theme is that Ba3 prevents black from castling kingside. } 8... Bb6?! { Moving the bishop again loses an unnecessary tempo. } { [%cal Gd1b3] } (8... d6 $19) 9. Qb3! { Threatening f7 with mate! Even though white is down a rook, Morphy is playing with all of his pieces, while black's rooks and LSB remain trapped on their starting squares. } (9. cxd4!? $19 { A very reasonable alternative. Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) 9... d5? { Black attempts to forceably shut down the diagonal towards f7.
Unfortunately, this move opens up the center in a position where black's king is stuck there. Next chapter, we will deeply explore why such a move should therefore be avoided like the plague. } (9... d6! $17 { Shutting down the DSB long enough for black to castle kingside was the best way forward. At least now Bxf7+ isn't mate. } 10. e5!? (10. Bxf7+!? Kf8 $19) 10... O-O! $19) 10. exd5 { We shall see many later examples exploring the benefits of opening up the position when ahead in development. Here, black is doing it to themselves. } (10. Bxd5? { A huge mistake. After Nxd5, black achieves a soothing trade. White achieves nothing by allowing this trade instead of recapturing on d5 with the pawn at first. } 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 $17) 10... Na5? { A move that operates under the delusion that black will get a chance to snap off the LSB. If black had calculated one ply deep they would have seen that two different checks in the position completely wreck black's position.
Ne7, clogging the a3-f8 diagonal and e file before the king dies in the center was more circumspect. } 11. Re1+ { A typical Morphy - NN position. White is playing with all the pieces, while black has repeatedly lost time straight out of the opening. } (11. Bb5+!? { Another extremely strong check since black does not have a good way to block. } 11... Bd7 12. Re1+ $18 { Equally crushing. }) (11. Qa4+? { Escapes the tempo against the queen, but after Qd7! both our queen and LSB are still under fire. There is no strong way to continue the attack. } 11... Qd7 12. Re1+!? (12. Bb5!? c6 13. dxc6 bxc6 $19) 12... Kd8 $19 { We should not have given black's king the d8 square. }) 11... Be6 { Sadly, this move is forced since the king was trapped in a kill box. Kd7 got mated after Ne5+. } { [%cal Gd5e6] } (11... Kd7?? 12. Ne5+! Ke8 13. Qb5+ c6 14. dxc6! { Bxf7#, c7+, and cxb7+ are all decisive threats. }) 12. dxe6!! { A true double exclamation mark, Morphy sacrifices the queen. } 12... Nxb3? { The obvious choice, and yet a losing move. Nxc4 had to be tried to avoid getting mated.
This study is designed for lower rated players learning the basics of strategy, so I will not ask you to find Morphy's deepest sacrifices such as the queen sacrifice kicking off with dxe6. However, knowing that this position is now forced mate, can you calculate the mate-in-6 from this position before playing the first move of the sequence?
Once you think you have it, kick off the mate with exf7+! } { [%cal Ge6f7] } (12... Nxc4!? 13. exf7+ Kxf7 14. Re5! $16 { Preventing Qd5. Now Qxc4+ is a deadly threat. }) 13. exf7+ Kd7 { PRO TIP: Checkmate ends the game. You do not get a prize for capturing all of your opponent's material if your king is the one who ends up mated. } { [%cal Gc4e6] } 14. Be6+ { This important check prevents the king running away to safety via c8. In Chapter IV: King hunt, we shall see many examples where preventing the king from slipping away is the prime concern. } 14... Kc6 { Only legal move... } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 15. Ne5+ Kb5 { Only legal move... } { [%cal Ge6c4] } 16. Bc4+! Ka5 { Now that the position has simplified, I know that you can find the finishing mate in 2! } 17. Bb4+ (17. Nc6+ { Prolongs the game by one move. Don't get fancy. } 17... bxc6 18. Bb4+ Ka4 19. axb3#) 17... Ka4 { Only legal move... } 18. axb3# { Morphy finishes this absolute smack down with a nice pawn checkmate. Hilariously, had he not given rook odds to his opponent, this finish would have been a double checkmate!
I have taken to calling positions in my own games where one side is developing the pieces while the other side wastes a lot of time doing nothing "Morphy - NN positions." One key point of this study is to help you recognize similarities between your own games and Morphy's games.
Sometimes harnessing righteous indignation at an opponent repeatedly making unprincipled moves is enough to exclaim, "They don't deserve to get away with this!" Morphy's games should provide guidance for when an opponent has broken too many principles, and serve as inspiration for how to refute unprincipled play. Once inspired, it's your job to channel your inner Morphy and play the sacrifices necessary to punish such an opponent. } 1-0


