{ Now let's summarize this chapter on opening principles while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board.

* Every move in the opening should seek to develop a piece, control the center, or get the king to safety. The best moves may in fact do several of these simultaneously! } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e6 { * Developing quickly is crucial. Do not move a piece multiple times in the opening if instead you can bring out more pieces to participate in the fight. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 2. d4 c5?! { * Bring all the boys to the party! You must develop all the pieces, not just play with a few.
* Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } 3. d5 e5?! { * One of the main ways to increase a lead in development is to improve your pieces while making threats. If your opponent has to play a suboptimal or non-developing move to deal with your threat, then your move is said to have "gained time." } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 4. f4 d6 { * A lead in development in an open position can often lead to a direct attack.
* When you have a huge lead in development in an open position, and your opponent plays several unprincipled moves, you should be looking for ways to punish them! } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 5. Nf3 Bg4 { * King safety is exclusively measured by how easily the king can come under fire. } { [%cal Gf4e5] } 6. fxe5 Bxf3? { * You can play the most principled chess in the world, but you will lose the game if you hang a queen. More fundamental than all the principles in the world is the skill of taking free pieces and not giving away free pieces! } { [%cal Gd1f3] } 7. Qxf3 dxe5 { * The best way to refute unprincipled play is to play the most principled chess conceivable. } { [%cal Gf1b5] } 8. Bb5+ Nd7 { * Do not make threats that can be conveniently parried by moves your opponent wants to make anyway. Essentially, you are forcing your opponent to play good moves! } { [%cal Gb1c3] } 9. Nc3 Nf6 { * The best threat is often one that also improves the worst placed piece. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } 10. Bg5 Be7? { * Checkmate ends the game. You do not get a prize for capturing all of your opponent's material if your king is the one who ends up mated. } { [%cal Gd5d6] } 11. d6! Bxd6 { * One key point of this study is to help you recognize similarities between your own games and Morphy's games. } { [%cal Ge1c1] } 12. O-O-O $18 { Black resigned in this position because Morphy is already winning a piece.
We will continue to see the opening principles exemplified across dozens of upcoming Morphy games. However, if you want more resources taking you through the opening principles, please check out:
* ChessDojo's Opening principles https://youtu.be/ENApnb0HuPU?si=TOsFto-2uK-3jHeP
* ChessNetwork's Beginning to master series https://youtu.be/pOjzvVVrxWw?si=c4BeOP92ZL3rMIJt
* Chessbrah's Habits series https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLUjxDD7HNNThftJtE0OIRFRMMFf6AV_69
* Dr. Can's Chess Clinic https://youtu.be/wNedhSZ_yzY
* ChessCoach Andras' course https://www.chessable.com/chess-principles-reloaded-development/course/50567/ } 1-0


