{ Chapter II: Blast open the position

This next chapter still focuses on the opening principles, but the difficulty increases. Morphy's opponents will not implode under the slightest pressure, so we will be exploring a new concept: opening up the position when you have a lead in development.

PRO TIP: When you have a lead in development, blast open the position. Sometimes this means a pawn break. Sometimes this means a sacrifice. Your developed pieces will only be able to generate game-winning threats once you open up lines for them. }
 *


[Event "Odds game"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1869.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Charles Maurian"]
[Result "1-0"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Keep your friends close"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/iiAf3eMf"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Morphy in this game plays his lifelong friend, Charles Maurian. Since Morphy was significantly stronger, they only played games where Morphy spotted a knight. Across 15 years and 75 knight-odds games, Morphy scored roughly 50%.

Since Morphy is already down a knight, he has to play hyper-aggressively to ensure his piece play is more relevant than his material deficit. Therefore, we should not dwell on his opening choices. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 { A King's Gambit of sorts. } 2... exf4!? { Black plays the most ambitious response like the previous player who faced off against Morphy's King's Gambit. Again, this is a loss of time. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 3. Nf3 { Assuming white still had both knights, this would be the main move in the King's Gambit - cutting out Qh4+ and controlling squares in the center. } 3... g5?! { Black is seemingly setting up to hold onto the f pawn for a while. Developing the pieces instead should be a much higher priority - especially when black is already up a knight! } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 4. Bc4 g4?! { So much for defending f4... Black ambitiously tries to kick the f3 knight around to argue that g4 isn't a loss of tempo. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 5. d4!! gxf3 { Morphy is not at all interested in slowing down his development, knight be damned! Now white is down two knights, but by move 6 has all the pieces open and ready to develop. Counting the tempi, white has the move, a developed LSB, an open DSB, and an eventual half-open file for the f1 rook. Meanwhile, black has only opened up the DSB. White is already up three tempi. } 6. Qxf3 { Recapturing while developing should typically be a top candidate move. } (6. O-O!? $19 { An equally interesting option. Play Qxf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. gxf3? { Not developing a piece? Perhaps you should revisit Chapter I. } 6... Qh4+ $19) (6. Bxf4?! $19 { The wrong recapture. Unfortunately we don't have a great response to f2+. } 6... f2+! (6... fxg2? 7. Bxf7+!! Kxf7? (7... Ke7! 8. Bg5+ Nf6 9. Rg1 Kxf7 10. e5 $17) 8. Qh5+ $10 { White has at least a perpetual check. }) 7. Kxf2 Qf6 8. g3 d6 $19) 6... d6?! { Black is still not developing the pieces! } 7. O-O (7. Bxf4!? $19 { Equally good. Play O-O first instead for the game continuation. }) (7. Qxf4?! $19 { The pawn is incidental. More important is gaining a critical lead in development. }) (7. Rf1?! $19 { A worse version of the game continuation. Why not safeguard the king simultaneously? }) 7... Be6?! { The first developing move from black forces Morphy to make a move he was already considering. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } 8. d5 { Of course we are not interested in trades since we are already down two pieces. Therefore, avoiding the trade with tempo is logical. Unfortunately, this move blocks in white's LSB on its current diagonal. The board is open though, so this may not last...
The deeper point behind d5 will only be appreciated later. } 8... Bc8 { Black is setting up the pieces for the next game... Frankly, ridiculous. } 9. Bxf4 { Developing a piece and regaining the pawn. White is now up five tempi and is playing against an opponent whose pieces are all at home watching TV. The fact that black is up two knights may soon be irrelevant if they do not contribute meaningfully to the game!
The most instructive aspect of Bxf4 to note for this chapter is that the f file is further opened while white's heavy pieces are already breathing down to f7. } (9. Qxf4?! $19 { A worse way to recapture the pawn. We should look to develop all the pieces! }) 9... Qd7? { Black overprotects f7 in order to avoid any shenanigans on the f file. But this move does not catch up in the tempo war, since it is now harder to develop the queenside.
This is the most instructive position of the game, where Morphy now teaches us how to properly convert an advantage in time into a decisive attack. } (9... Nd7! $19 { Clearly better, as this holds up e5 from white for a little bit. } 10. Bxd6!? Qf6! $19) 10. e5! { Yes! This simple pawn break will forceably open up the e file. White's heavy pieces and DSB all open up as soon as this trade of pawns (either on d6 or e5) occurs.
PRO TIP: When your opponent's king is stuck in the center, you should look for a pawn break (a pawn move that introduces tension with an opponent's pawn) that open up files or diagonals towards the king. Indeed, a timely central pawn break is the most common way to open up the position.
If we reconsider the moves leading up to this position, we can now appreciate the genius behind Morphy's earlier d5 move. Yes, it gained a tempo on the bishop on e6, but more importantly it fixed the d6 pawn! Once fixed, d6 became a hook that the e5 pawn break could exploit to open up lines.
Note that if white's d pawn instead remained on d4 here, black could respond to e5 with d5, seeking to keep the central files closed and the black king safer. } (10. Rae1?! $17 { Fantastic intuition playing the Morphy move here. This is indeed the most logical developing move, opposite the king. However, now is the moment to strike! }) 10... Qg4 { Black is desperate to trade queens and develop the remaining pieces... } 11. Qe3! { Of course we don't want to trade queens when (1) we're in the middle of an attack and (2) black's king is stuck in the center! Moreover, this specific queen move x-rays black's king, thus generating more threats in the position.
PRO TIP: The primary factor both sides should evaluate when considering a queen trade is king safety. The reason is simple: it becomes significantly harder to execute an attack and take advantage of an unsafe king once the queens come off the board. So, if your king is safe while your opponent's king is not, do not queen trade! If your king is running all over the board while your opponent's king is free from danger, do everything in your power to queen trade! } (11. Qc3!? $15 { Equally good, eyeing the rook on h8. Play Qe3 instead for the game continuation. }) (11. Qf2?! $15 { A reasonable option as well, eyeing f7. Play Qe3 instead for the game continuation. }) (11. Qb3? $17 { Good job avoiding the queen trade. But your queen is not doing anything particularly useful on this square. }) (11. Qe4?! $17 { Good job avoiding the queen trade. This is a worse version of the game continuation, since the queens being opposite each other means we just pinned our own DSB. }) (11. Qd3? $17 { Good job avoiding the queen trade. But your queen is not doing anything particularly useful on this square. }) (11. Qa3? $19 { Good job avoiding the queen trade. But your queen is about to get kicked around after dxe5! }) (11. Qxg4? $19 { Trading queens and developing black's army for them? Not a chance! Did you forget white was down two pieces? }) (11. Rae1? $17 { The Morphy move. But we don't want a queen trade while down two pieces! }) 11... Be7?! { Black is desperate to safeguard their king along the e file. But it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } (11... Ne7 $17) 12. exd6 (12. Rae1!? $15 { Nice job playing the Morphy move. Morphy first played exd6 to open up the e file while Bxd6 was illegal. }) 12... cxd6 { The e file opens up. Black's king is in the crosshairs. } 13. Rae1! { The Morphy move! The final piece enters the attack, and threats along the e file materialize. } (13. Qc3!? $14 { The engine move. Be2 is coming next, kicking the queen around. Morphy's moves are much more direct and aimed at the king. }) (13. Bxd6? $17 { You just hung your c4 bishop for little compensation! }) (13. Bb5+? $17 { An empty check that only asks your opponent to develop. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! }) 13... h5? { Simply unexplainable. Black once more insists on not developing the pieces. Morphy does not give his friend another chance. } (13... Kd8! $15 { and pray }) 14. Bxd6!? { Morphy temporarily sacrifices a third piece (the LSB) in order to break through decisively on the e and f files. } (14. Qc3!? $16 { The engine move. Both c8 and h8 are in the queen's crosshairs. Play Bxd6 instead for the game continuation. }) (14. Bb5+!? { Too fancy. The king is already vulnerable on the e file. } 14... Kd8 15. Qc3! Rh7 16. Bxd6 $18) 14... Qd7? { Black retreats the queen to defend e7. Of course such a passive move must be refuted. } { [%cal Gd6e7] } (14... Qxc4 15. Bxe7 Qxd5! $16 { Some life is left in the position, although Morphy's opponent would not be able to survive this attack. }) 15. Bxe7 (15. Bb5? $18 { Switch up your move order to more decisively break through! }) 15... Nxe7 { Black resigned after the next move. How did Morphy put away his opponent? } 16. Bb5! $18 { Excellent tactical vision! The bishop is immune due to the mate on e7. Therefore the only move that doesn't resign is Nc6. Regardless, after dxc6 bxc6, Bxc6! the queen is still lost.
The key point of this game worth remembering is that the earlier pawn breaks (10. e5, and to a lesser extent 2. f4) opened the position when white had a lead in development. With open lines, white's extra firepower could successfully overwhelm black's sleeping army. } (16. d6?! $18 { An interesting options to open up the LSB. Not decisive enough! }) 1-0


[Event "Bishops | Slice through the opposition!: Morphy showing off bishop mastery"]
[Site "https://lichess.org/G6WVWnci"]
[Date "1849.??.??"]
