[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ A young Paul Morphy plays against his father in 1849. Let's see another example of him translating a lead in development into a crushing attack through the use of sacrifices that open the center. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 4. b4!? { The fearsome Evans Gambit was a favorite of the Romantic Era. Last time we saw this line, white was missing the rook on a1. In this game, that rook plays a decisive role in the attack. } 4... Bxb4 { The point of the Evans is to build a large center while gaining time against black's bishop. } 5. c3 Bc5 6. d4 { Exactly. White now has a strong center, with tempo.
There are many aspects of a chess position that determine its evaluation, time and material being the two easiest to understand. One useful rule of thumb allows us to relate these two aspects to each other.
PRO TIP: Three tempi are typically worth one pawn. Indeed, most opening gambits that sacrifice a pawn, such as the Evans Gambit, get exactly three tempi in exchange for the material! } 6... exd4 7. cxd4 (7. O-O!? $10 { Starting with this developing move is most precise. Play cxd4 instead for the game continuation. }) 7... Bb6 { White has successfully achieved a strong center. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 8. O-O { In exchange for a single pawn, white has a huge lead in development and owns the center. White needs three moves to finish development vs black's five. But since black must also spend a tempo or two to address white's threats in the position, the opening gambit has been largely successful. } 8... Na5?! { This poor move is no longer played because the knight on the side of the board aims at nothing after Morphy's next move. } (8... d6 $10 { Much more normal. Black hurries to develop. }) 9. Bd3 { "No bishop for you!" The LSB can later participate in an attack. Meanwhile, the sidelined knight on a5 owes white a tempo just to get back into the game, so Bd3 does not ultimately lose a tempo. } (9. Be2?! $10 { Blocking the e file is less precise. We want to later use that file towards black's king with a timely Re1! }) (9. Bb3? $15 { Don't let black justify the sidelined knight by taking your bishop!
It is also worth mentioning that your rook does not truly improve after Nxb3 axb3. With the bishop on b6 conveniently defending a7, your rook does not pressure black in any way on the a file. }) (9. Bd5? $15 { Running into Ne7 with tempo is not smart. }) (9. Bb5?! $10 { What is the bishop even doing on this square? }) (9. Bxf7+?! { It's a bit too crazy to go in for this bishop sacrifice with only one other piece developed. However, this is still an interesting sacrifice kicking off a king hunt similar to those we will explore in Chapter IV. Stay tuned to understand this more! } 9... Kxf7 10. Ng5+! (10. Ne5+? Kf8 11. Qh5 Qe8 $17) 10... Kf8 11. e5! h6! 12. Qf3+ Nf6! 13. Ba3+ d6 14. Ne4 Bxd4! 15. exf6 Bxa1 16. Nbc3 g6! 17. Rxa1 Be6 $15) 9... d5? { Black thinks he is playing in a principled manner - after white's LSB has been kicked back, black can "safely" strike at white's center.
The issue with this logic is that black has moved the DSB four times and the knight twice, and is therefore behind in development. Moreover, black will be unable to recapture on d5 with a pawn, thus securing a center of their own. This leads to another fundamental opening principle...
PRO TIP: Do not open the position when you are behind in development. Opening up the center before you are castled is especially unwise. } (9... d6 10. Nc3 Ne7 11. h3 O-O $10 { Black has castled to safety, but white retains full compensation for the pawn. }) 10. exd5 (10. Nc3!? $16 { Developing and ready to recapture on e4 with the knight. A sensible move. Play exd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Re1!? $16 { Putting the rook opposite black's king is smart. Play exd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Ba3!? $16 { Developing and preventing black from castling kingside. A good move. Play exd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Bg5?! $14 { You are forcing your opponent to develop with Ne7. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! }) 10... Qxd5 { Correct! We should open the position since white has a lead in development.
Note: this last recapture has not developed black's army for them. In fact, the queen is a poor piece to develop early since she can often be attacked by white's pieces as they develop to natural squares. We will revisit this concept in detail next chapter. } 11. Ba3! { Morphy keys in on the problem in black's position: the centralized king! Activating the bishop on a3 controls f8: the black king's escape square, ensuring that a future check on the e file will be devastating.
Of course our d4 pawn is not actually hanging unless black wants to lose the queen. } (11. Nc3!? $16 { The most natural move and equally good to the game continuation. Develop the DSB to its optimal square first for the game continuation. }) (11. Re1+!? $16 { A natural move and equally good to the game continuation. Develop the DSB to its optimal square first for the game continuation. }) 11... Be6 { Black hurries to close the e file and castle, but that flimsy defense will only last for so long... } (11... Bxd4?? 12. Nxd4 Qxd4?? 13. Bb5+ Nc6 14. Qxd4 $18 { Free queen }) 12. Nc3! { After playing through this many Morphy games, this developing move with tempo on black's queen should be screaming out to be played. If this hasn't been a top candidate move ever since black played Qxd5, please play through the games in the first chapter again. } (12. Re1?! { A sensible developing move, yet after O-O-O, we don't have a knockout. Develop with tempo instead! } 12... O-O-O $14) 12... Qd7 { We arrive at the most instructive moment of the game.
Black has partially opened up the e file for us with the earlier rushed d5? But the bishop on e6 does a reasonable job of keeping the position only partially open. But black is only one move away from castling queenside to safety...
What explosive move did Morphy play that convincingly opens up the e and d files towards black's king? } 13. d5! { An excellent move! Morphy removes the blockade on the e file to continue opening up lines and diagonals towards black's king.
PRO TIP: Once you have attained a decisive development disparity, you should be looking for forcing moves, tactical shots, and general fireworks to open the position and go after your opponent. The decisive development disparity (DDD, pronounced "triple-D") moment occurs when there are king safety issues while the gap in development will not get any larger.
Consider the previous position closely for instance. White did not have a useful developing move besides Re1, but after black castled queenside, does that rook have an impactful purpose? Meanwhile, black has many ways to catch up in development. Therefore, white should act now! Later action once black is less behind in development and has a safer king will hit with less oomph.
The exact DDD moment is not always obvious. Therefore, we will revisit this concept many times across several games in order to better appreciate the nuances of when to strike. } (13. Ne5? $10 { Oh no, your d pawn! This move would be natural and strong if it didn't hang d4. }) (13. Re1?! $14 { A normal move, but you're letting black off the hook by queenside castling! }) (13. Bb5?! $16 { A forcing move, but after c6, we have not accomplished anything active. }) 13... Bxd5 14. Nxd5 { The one-two punch of d5 is complete. The e file has been ripped open while black's king remains in the center. } (14. Re1+? $16 { The bishop can directly return to e6 now, and you have not succeeded in opening up the e file. }) (14. Qe2+? $16 { The bishop can directly return to e6 now, and you have not succeeded in opening up the e file. }) (14. Bb5!? $18 { A fine move that tries to generate threats while white has a lead in development. Play Nxd5 instead for the game continuation. }) 14... Qxd5 { With the LSB taken off the board, at the mere cost of a (second) pawn, Morphy has ensured the e and d files will remain open forever. Black is now assuredly lost due to all the open lines.
We arrive at another decisive development disparity (DDD) moment. If black gets time to castle queenside and then play Nf6, white will not have anything special.
Morphy's next move is as beautiful as it is unnecessary. In such a dominant position, nearly every move is winning. } { [%cal Gd3b5] } 15. Bb5+!! { A crushing blow whose purpose is purely to draw the queen away from the king's defense. } (15. Re1+!? $18 { Also winning, but now white has to contend with Kd8. } 15... Kd8 16. Be4! Qxd1? 17. Raxd1+ Kc8 18. Bf5+ Kb8 19. Rd8#) 15... Qxb5 { Forced. } (15... c6?! 16. Qxd5 $18 { And the pawn is pinned. }) 16. Re1+ { The Morphy move, bringing all the boys to the party! } 16... Ne7 { The point of Bb5+ is revealed. Black was forced to block on e7, thus losing the piece right back.
Before taking the free knight on e7 though, Morphy plays a final finesse that further draws the queen away from the defense. } { [%cal Ga1b1] } 17. Rb1!? { A further Morphy move! } 17... Qa6? { Black's queen is banished to Siberia. White now has forced mate in several variations. Morphy, ever the artist, dispatches his father with the most elegant option. } { [%cal Ge1e7] } (17... Qd7!? 18. Rxe7+ Qxe7 19. Bxe7 Kxe7 20. Qd5 $18 { Up a queen against black's poorly placed pieces, Morphy would surely convert this position. }) 18. Rxe7+ Kf8 { Black's king is forced to walk into discovered checks... } { [%cal Gd1d5] } 19. Qd5! { Going for style points, Morphy saves his discovered check by creating an even bigger threat: Qxf7#.
Of course, there were many winning continuations from such a crushing position. Every white piece is better than every black piece. } 19... Qc4 { X-ray defense of f7 ends up insufficient. } { [%cal Ge7f7] } 20. Rxf7+ Kg8 { In true Morphy style, he finds a beautiful finish to cap off a beautiful game. What's the stylish mate-in-1 that ends the game? } 21. Rf8#! { What an aesthetic double checkmate!
The specifics of how black's king got executed need not be remembered. More important is understanding how and when to open up the position. In this game, both black's d5? and white's d5! opened up the position when white had a lead in development. } (21. Rxg7+?? { Did you recognize that Kxg7 is playable? }) 1-0


[Event "Blindfold simul, 3b"]
[Site "Havana CUB"]
[Date "1864.02.16"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Felix Sicre"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C41"]
[Opening "Philidor Defense: Morphy Gambit"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Simple is good"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/noCm0GtM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ During the US Civil War, years after Morphy had played his last competitive match, he fled the US for France. During his voyage, he stopped in Cuba, where he played a blindfold simul against 3 local players. That is to say, he was not looking at any of the boards going on at the same time, while his competitors each had a chess board in front of them and were only focused on their game. Apparently, Morphy made this event more challenging by eating dinner and having animated discussions with other patrons simultaneously too!

This is the most instructive of those three simultaneous games. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 d6 { We have seen the Philidor defense before in the Opera Game. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 3. d4 { As before, Morphy claims the center when it is offered. } 3... exd4 { An improvement over the Opera Game. Black does not allow white to maintain the strong center.
Rather than using this game to learn any new concepts, let's use this game to reinforce the opening principles. Moreover, I'm confident you'll spot the moment when there is no obvious developing move and immediate action to open the position is required.
You're now on your own. When you play a move that is as strong as Morphy's choice, I will let you know. Give yourself full credit, and move on by making the move Morphy played instead. Good luck! } 4. Bc4!? { Possibly inviting a gambit, Morphy develops the LSB to the best diagonal and prepares to kingside castle next. } (4. Nxd4!? $14 { Recapturing with Nxd4 is the most sensible option, improving the knight and recapturing the pawn. Play Bc4 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. Qxd4!? $10 { Qxd4 is equally playable, although you need to have a response planned for black responding with Nc6, developing with tempo. I would not recommend this option. }) (4. c3?! $10 { It's too early to sacrifice a pawn. Black hasn't done anything wrong, and so white will only be up two tempi for the pawn. }) (4. Bg5?! $10 { An ineffective threat. After Be7 you are simply offering a trade. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! }) 4... h6?! { A poor move that wastes time for no benefit. Black wanted to play Nf6, but was afraid of Ng5?! with pressure on f7. Those fears are unfounded though since such an early attack by white is unprincipled. In that line, f7 can be conveniently defended with the thematic d5! counterattack in the center. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } (4... Nf6! 5. Ng5?! d5 $10) 5. c3!? { Morphy decides the best way to punish his opponent's slow play is to gambit a pawn for faster development.
We have already seen the rule of thumb that a pawn is worth three tempi. Since white is already up three tempi, this pawn sacrifice is fully justified.
Normal moves like O-O or Nxd4 are just as good for white as well. } (5. Nxd4!? $14) (5. O-O!? $14) 5... c6?! { c6 controls some squares from the bishop, but is an otherwise unproductive move. Black already lags in development by 3 moves and is just losing more time...
Black is making enough provocative moves that your mindset should transition from "white has a comfortable position" to "how do I punish this play?" } (5... dxc3!? 6. Nxc3 $14) 6. O-O! { Morphy hurries to castle and does not bother recapturing the pawn yet again.
Punishing slow play does not require immediate action. As discussed last chapter, the correct way to punish unprincipled play is to play the most principled chess conceivable. In this case, Morphy chooses to increase white's lead in development by simply castling.
Immediate action is only required at the DDD moment - the moment when black's king safety remains an issue and white has no obvious developing moves that increase white's lead in development. } (6. Qb3! $14 { Great job developing with a threat to f7. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (6. cxd4?! $14 { A reasonable recapture, but now black gets their share of the center with d5! }) (6. Nxd4?! $14 { A reasonable recapture, but now c6 is slightly more justified since it controls squares from both the bishop and knight. }) (6. Qxd4! $14 { Now that Nc6 is off the cards, recapturing with the queen is the most sensible recapture since it develops a new piece. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (6. Bf4?! $10 { Not the most important piece to develop. From f4 the bishop is a target (to g5, Ng6, or Qf6) as well. }) (6. Bd2? $10 { A half-developing move that should not cross your mind. }) (6. Nbd2? $15 { Blocks all of your pieces. The knight is going nowhere next. }) (6. Bxf7+?? $19 { Such drastic measures are completely uncalled for? Is this the DDD moment? No way - white has many sensible developing moves left. }) 6... dxc3?! { Losing more time. This greedy capture develops our army for us. } 7. Qb3!? { A classic Morphy move, developing with a threat to f7. } (7. Nxc3!? $16 { Simply recapturing and developing is a great move. Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) (7. Re1?! $14 { It's not obvious the rook belongs on e1. }) (7. Bxf7+! $16 { Yes even this bishop sacrifice is playable since after Kxf7, Ne5! starts sending the king all over the board. From such a dominant position, you shouldn't sacrifice unless you can calculate the entire variation though.
Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) 7... Qc7 { Developing and defending the threat. Black justifies the earlier c6 move. } (7... cxb2? 8. Bxf7+! Kd7 9. Bxb2 $18 { Black's king is the only piece developed? No chance of survival. }) 8. Nxc3 { Simply recapturing and developing is an easy move. } (8. Qxc3?! $14 { A poor recapture. Now the knight on b1 looks silly. We should be developing a new piece and recapturing instead in order to gain time. }) (8. bxc3? $15 { The worst recapture. Your knight on b1 is crying. }) 8... g5?! { Covering f4, the best square for white's DSB. But black is losing even more time! Such a move betrays a total disregard for the opening principles. The correct mindset should now be: "Black MUST lose this game! How do I punish them?"
Controlling some useful squares while behind in development by five tempi is like turning off the lights when your house is on fire. } 9. Be3 { Continuing the theme of this game: the best way to refute unprincipled play is to play the most principled chess conceivable.
White is not yet fully developed and there is no better square for the DSB than e3. After playing through 9 Morphy games, Be3 should now be an easy move for you to make. } (9. Re1!? $16 { A fine move. Play Be3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. e5!? { Seeking to open up the position makes sense, but what are you doing after black responds by closing the center with d5? } 9... d5?! 10. Bxd5!! cxd5 11. Nxd5 Qd8 12. Rd1! Be7 13. Be3 Nc6 14. Rac1 $16 { A typical Morphy - NN position. But are you comfortable playing in such a manner when there are easy moves still available to white? }) (9. Rd1!? $16 { Is this the best square for the rook? }) (9. Bd2?! $16 { A half-developing move that should not enter your thoughts. }) (9. Bxg5? { Not the worst way to try to punish black's play. But opening up the h file for black's rook will surely backfire. Meanwhile, white has sensible developing moves left that aren't sacrifices. } 9... hxg5 10. Nxg5?? d5! $19 { h2 is threatened. }) (9. Nxg5?? $19 { An unnecessary sacrifice that barely improves white's pieces while opening up black's rook. }) (9. h3?! $16 { A waste of a move. Not only was black not previously threatening g4 or Bg4, but h3 in fact makes your king less safe. You have just given your opponent a hook to bite at in the future. To explore this concept further, see Chapter VI: Opposite sides castling. }) 9... Bg7 { Which pieces are not yet playing? } 10. Rac1 { Placing a rook opposite the queen can only be beneficial to white. A hallmark of Morphy's play is that he brings all his pieces to bare before launching decisive attacks. } (10. Rad1!? $16 { Equally fine. Play Rac1 for the game continuation. }) (10. Rfd1!? $16 { Equally fine. Play Rac1 for the game continuation. }) (10. Rfe1!? $16 { Equally fine. Play Rac1 for the game continuation. }) (10. Rae1?! $16 { A poor move. Now the f1 rook is trapped. Remember to avoid blocking your other pieces when you develop your army! }) (10. Rfc1?! $16 { A poor move. Now the a1 rook is trapped. Remember to avoid blocking your other pieces when you develop your army! }) (10. e5?! $16 { Seeking to open up the position makes sense, but what are you doing after black responds by closing the center with d5? } 10... d5 11. Bxd5! cxd5 12. Nxd5 Qd8 13. Rad1 $16 { A typical Morphy - NN position. But are you comfortable playing in such a manner when there are easy moves still available to white? }) (10. Nd4?! $16 { A fine centralizing move. But developing either of white's two rooks first brings more force to the fight. }) 10... Bxc3? { "You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move!" as IM Mio Perunovic would say. Why black would ever consider trading their best piece for a dominated knight is beyond me.
The chess gods do not abide such provocative play. It is now up to us to smite black for their chess sins and prove there is justice in the world! } 11. Qxc3 { Recapturing with a threat on h8.
PRO TIP: Don't get fancy - recapture your pieces! If you don't get in the habit of recapturing when your opponent captures your pieces, you will run out of pieces quickly. The exception to recapturing is when your threats are truly more important, such as Morphy's earlier Qb3. } (11. bxc3? $16 { A bad recapture. Now the rook on c1 looks silly. }) (11. Rxc3?! $16 { A suboptimal recapture since there is no immediate threat created by this move. If we want to punish our opponent, we need to gain as much time as possible! }) 11... Rh7 { Can you believe that black was one of the best Cuban players at the time? Let's just say that black is certainly not putting together a Capablanca masterpiece this game! } 12. e5! { Yes! This is the decisive development disparity (DDD) moment. White already has an overwhelming lead in development and a safer king, but the heavy pieces will not accomplish anything decisive until we open up the center!
The only line you need to calculate before playing this pawn break is what happens if black tries to close the center with d5. Indeed, d5 falls flat because the c pawn is pinned - Bxd5 is there, winning a free pawn and opening the position anyway. } (12. Rfd1?! $16 { I won't fault you for making this move. Please note though that it completely lacks punch by generating no threats. }) (12. Rfe1?! $16 { I won't fault you for making this move. Please note though that it completely lacks punch by generating no threats. }) (12. Bd3!? $16 { Opens the heavy pieces on the c file and prepares e5. Reasonable option! Play e5 first instead for the game continuation. }) (12. Bxg5! { A winning sacrifice since after hxg5 Nxg5 hits both f7 and h7. Black is busted here too. Play e5, blasting open the center, instead for the game continuation. } 12... hxg5 13. Nxg5 d5? (13... Rg7?? 14. Qxg7 $18) (13... Rh5?! 14. Bxf7+ $18) (13... Rh6!? 14. Bxf7+ $18) 14. Nxh7 $18) 12... Nd7 { Black desperately tries to keep the center closed. } { [%cal Gc4d3] } (12... d5!? 13. Bxd5 $16) (12... dxe5? { Opening up the center is the fastest way to die. } 13. Nxe5 Be6 14. Bc5 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Rcd1 Qc7 17. Rfe1 $18 { Splat. Black is never getting out of this one. }) (12... Be6!? 13. exd6 Qd7! 14. Ne5!? (14. Bd3!? Bf5? 15. Qe5+ $18) 14... Qxd6 15. Rcd1 Qe7 16. Rfe1 $18) 13. Bd3 { f7 is a well-defended target, so Morphy reroutes the bishop (with tempo!) while opening the heavy pieces on the c file instead.
The direct exd6 would have been more on-theme for this chapter on blasting open the center. Indeed, exd6 is just as crushing as the game continuation. } (13. exd6!? { Equally good. Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. } 13... Qd8 14. Bd3 Nf8 15. Bxh7 Nxh7 16. Qg7 $18) 13... Nf8 { Black's rook was trapped due to the threat of exd6. The game is already long gone. } { [%cal Ge5d6] } 14. exd6 { After a brief interlude, Morphy opens the center. } 14... Qd8 { The e5 pawn break was successful, and the position has opened up further. Black correctly does not recapture on d6 in a desperate attempt to prevent the center from fully opening.
How to continue the game? } (14... Qxd6?! 15. Rcd1 $18) 15. Rfe1! { The Morphy move! All of white's pieces are now playing against black's back-rank fest. The end is nigh. } (15. Bxh7?! $18 { It is a shame to capture this rook. The LSB is raking across the board, while the h7 rook is passively defending with two legal moves. }) (15. Rfd1!? $18 { Opposite the queen and equally winning. Play Rfe1 for the game continuation. }) 15... Be6 { The rest of this game is no longer interesting because Morphy has a lead in development, the safer king, and is already winning the exchange whenever he desires. We will play through the rest of the moves, but please note that every legal move is winning in such a dominant position. Morphy's conversion is just one of many. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 16. Ne5 Nf6 { [%cal Gd3h7] } 17. Bxh7 N8xh7 { Morphy is now up the exchange, with a continued attack. } { [%cal Ge3c5] } 18. Bc5!? { I would have preferred d7+ first, opening up the center further at the cost of an irrelevant pawn. d7 is both the best move and the most thematic option for this chapter. } (18. d7+! $18 { In my opinion, the best move. } 18... Nxd7!? { One line just to show the point: } 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Qh8+ Nf8 21. Rcd1 Qc7 22. Bc5 $18 { Splat goes the defense. }) 18... Nd7 { [%cal Ge5g4] } 19. Ng4!? { Of course nearly every move wins, and some knockouts were quite flashy including Nxf7! Kxf7, Rxe6!
Ng4 showcases the difference between Morphy when he was first bursting onto the international scene, and Morphy when he was semi-retired. Having played earlier high-stakes matches where unnecessary complications and sacrifices backfired, Morphy now plays with more restraint. Indeed, Ng4 seeks to win without any fireworks - black cannot move a muscle.
PRO TIP: Sometimes simple is good. Especially when you're in a dominant position, do not complicate the position. } (19. Nxf7! Kxf7 20. Rxe6! Kxe6!? 21. Qb3+ Kf6 22. Bd4+ Kg6 23. Qd3+ Kf7 24. Qxh7+ $18) 19... b6 { [%cal Gc3g7] } 20. Qg7 Nhf8 { [%cal Gc5d4] } 21. Bd4 $18 { The threats on h6, f6, and c6 are too much for black to handle. Black's king is never escaping the center, so now is as good a time as any to resign.
Black in this game disregarded the opening principles and quickly got a horrible position. How did Morphy punish this bad play? By keeping it simple!
He developed the pieces, one by one. He broke open the center at the DDD moment (once he had a decisive lead in development). He won material by snagging the exchange. He used his superior pieces to swarm black's king. Nothing flashy and nothing that required deep calculation. Sometimes, simple is good!
It goes without saying that Morphy won all three of his games in this blindfold simul! } 1-0


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "London ENG"]
[Date "1858.06.23"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Thomas Inglis Hampton"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C51"]
