{ In a perfect world, every developing move also comes with a threat the opponent has to respond to. However, in reality, many positions offer no such multipurpose moves. In this game against an amateur, Morphy shows us a deeper look into the trade-off between gaining time by developing and creating threats. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { [%cal Gb2b4] } 4. b4!? { Another game. Another Evans Gambit.
This is the first threat Morphy makes this game that is not a developing move. It is also a fully sound pawn sacrifice!
What is the justification for such a claim? Firstly, white will win at least two tempi on the bishop after Bxb4, c3 Banywhere. Secondly, while black is losing tempi moving the bishop all over the board (unprincipled but necessary!), white is building up a strong center (principled!). Finally, white is opening a diagonal for the DSB to develop to b2 or a3 in many lines, making this somewhat of a developing move as well.
Are all those points enough to justify a non-developing pawn sacrifice? Maybe. Objectively, white is doing fine in the Evans Gambit, but so too is black. Do not get the impression that this opening wins by force. } 4... Bxb4 { The first of many undesirable moves black is forced to make. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 { Preparation for building a broad center with d4 next, a threat, and a developing move (since white's queen often develops to b3 in the Evans Gambit). It is hard to imagine a better multipurpose move! } 5... Bc5 { One of many options available to black's bishop. Throughout this study Morphy will face several of these options. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 6. O-O (6. d4! { More precise than the game continuation, although this game will transpose to this line. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. } 6... exd4 7. O-O! d6 8. cxd4 Bb6 $10 { Transposes to the game. }) 6... d6 { Black plays well, developing the LSB and defending the e pawn. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 7. d4 { Following through with the point of the Evans Gambit. White has achieved the dream center (with further tempo on the bishop). } 7... exd4 { Black chooses to give up the center in order to remain up a pawn. } (7... Bb6 { The most dependable option. } 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8!? (9... Kxd8?! 10. Bxf7 $14) 10. Nxe5 $10) 8. cxd4 Bb6 { If black has time to simply develop the rest of their army and consolidate, then white's central pawn mass is not worth black's extra pawn.
Is now the moment to strike in the center? } 9. Nc3! { Correct! White has easy developing moves that still need to be played. White does not have a tangible lead in development that on its own justifies opening the center at all costs. } (9. d5?! { Closes down our bishop. This threat doesn't gain time because after Na5 we have to spend a move retreating the bishop, losing a tempo right back. } 9... Na5 10. Bd3!? $10 (10. Bb2!? Nf6 (10... Nxc4? 11. Bxg7 $16) 11. Bd3 $10)) (9. e5?! { A thematic strike in the Evans, seeking to blast open the position. But white doesn't have enough development for such a move. After d5! the center is closed with tempo. } 9... d5! 10. Bb5 Ne7 $15) (9. Ba3?! { Good job not budging in the center. However, this move is poorly timed because the bishop does nothing on its own from a3. } 9... Bg4! $15 { White's center is still tender. }) (9. Re1!? $10 { Good job not budging in the center. The rook coming to e1 does not pack the same punch as developing another piece though. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. h3!? $10 { A horrible "bunny ears" move that you should avoid at all costs. Unfortunately, this unprincipled move is an interesting option played by some top players nowadays, simply because Bg4, pressuring the center, is so annoying. }) (9. Qb3?! { Thematic, as you are developing with a threat. Unfortunately, after Na5! taking on f7 loses a piece since the queen cannot escape the knight's attack while defending the loose bishop on f7. } 9... Na5! 10. Bxf7+? Kf8 $17) (9. Bg5?! { Thematic, as you are developing with a threat. Unfortunately, after Nge7 (developing!), there is no way to continue pushing our slight advantage in development. Perhaps the bishop is not as strong on g5 as on another square... } 9... Nge7 10. Nc3 O-O $10) (9. Bb2!? { Good job not budging in the center. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. } 9... Nf6 10. d5!? $10 (10. e5?! dxe5 11. Ba3 $17 { Down a tempo from the game. })) (9. Ng5?! { f7 is a weakness in this opening, but this move forces black to develop and defend with Nh6. Meanwhile, we are wasting time and undefending our center! } 9... Nh6 $15) 9... Nf6? { Black develops and prepares to castle.
Is now the moment to strike in the center? } 10. e5! { Yes! Several signs point to e5 being the correct move.
Most importantly, black is one move away from castling, and white has no developing moves that interfere with that simple plan. Yes, white has a slight lead in development (needing two moves to connect the rooks to black's three), but certainly not a decisive lead.
If white had not gambited a pawn earlier, there is an argument to be made that white's uncontested center is a dependable enough advantage, and so there is no need to seek complications. However, since white is already down a pawn, there is the impetus to generate active play. e5 is a step in that direction.
Thirdly, white's king has safely evacuated the center. Blowing open the center while the opponent is the only one with their king stuck in the center can often pay dividends.
Lastly, there is a specific flaw to black's last move. A knight on f6 creates a pawn forking opportunity with e5. Without a knight on f6, e5 can be met with d5, keeping the position closed. With a knight on f6, black cannot respond to e5 with d5, and so the position will open.
In conclusion, this threat opens the position at the DDD moment. If white casually develops, black can castle the king and develop the pieces naturally. This threat interferes with black's plan. } (10. Ba3? { A logical developing move, trying to play e5 next. Unfortunately, after O-O, black is doing alright. Switch the move order instead! } 10... O-O 11. e5!? Nh5! $10 (11... dxe5? $16)) (10. Re1? { A logical developing move. But after O-O, black is doing alright. } 10... O-O $10) (10. d5? { Forcing issues is correct. But after Ne7, black will still be able to castle next. } 10... Ne7 { Importantly, white does not have the development to meaningfully follow-up with e5. } 11. e5?! dxe5 12. Ba3 O-O $15) (10. Qb3? { You are practically forcing black to castle! Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 10... O-O $15) (10. Nd5?! { This move doesn't even create a threat, since f6 is already defended. This is not a way to blow open the position. } 10... Nxd5! (10... O-O?! 11. Bg5 $14) 11. exd5 Ne7 $17) (10. Bg5? { A logical developing move, but after h6, did we really want to take on f6? This pin isn't annoying for black unless black is already castled. } 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 $15) (10. Bxf7+?? $17 { Oh no, your bishop! Now is the time to strike, but there is no follow-up after Kxf7. White just doesn't have enough pieces. }) 10... dxe5 { The most logical try, even though the center opens.
We will revisit this position and explore what happens when black tries the thematic counterstrike d5 instead in a later game this chapter.
Another instructive moment. Is now the moment to further open the center? } 11. Ba3! { Exactly! There is no need to further open the position. Opening the e file towards black's king would be great, but we do not want to open the d file and offer a queen trade in the middle of an attack.
Morphy prevents black from castling kingside by developing a piece. e5+Ba3 is the one-two punch to ensure that white's lead in development is not fleeting. It will be felt now that black's king remains stuck in the center.
PRO TIP: The opening principles (developing, center, king safety) apply to your opponents too. Playing moves that prevent your opponent from making the principled moves they want to is a winning strategy as well! } (11. dxe5? { No, it is not correct to further open the center. You just gave your opponent an opportunity to queen trade and kill your attack before it got off the ground! } 11... Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Ng4 $17) (11. Nxe5? { We don't care about recapturing the pawn! After Nxe5? Nxe5!, dxe5 Qxd1!, Rxd1 you just gave your opponent an opportunity to queen trade and kill your attack before it got off the ground! } 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ng4 $17) (11. Qb3? { You are forcing your opponent to castle! Don't force your opponent to make good moves. } 11... O-O $17) (11. Ng5? { You are forcing your opponent to castle! Don't force your opponent to make good moves. } 11... O-O $17) (11. Bxf7+? { A candidate idea, but white does not yet have the crushing lead in development to justify this sacrifice. } 11... Kxf7 12. Qb3+ Ke8! 13. dxe5 Ng4 14. Bg5 Qd3 15. Rad1 Qg6 $17) 11... Bg4 { A nice move from black. Rather than getting greedy and opening the center fully with exd4, they develop a piece. "If you won't let me castle kingside, I will try to castle queenside!"
Is now the moment to further open the center? } (11... Be6? 12. d5! $18) (11... e4? 12. Qb3! Qd7 13. Rae1 $18) 12. Qb3! { Correct! White is not interested in a queen trade, so dxe5 remains off the table.
Once more, Morphy increases his lead in development by developing with a threat. In contrast to just two moves ago, white is now the one who has easy developing moves that increase the pressure. Black struggles to come up with a move that defends against white's threat to f7 since the convenient response of kingside castling remains illegal. } (12. dxe5? $17 { No, it is not correct to further open the center. Moreover, the pawn is irrelevant. You just allowed your opponent the opportunity to queen trade and kill the attack before it got off the ground! }) (12. Nxe5?? $19 { "Oh no my queen!" A nice bait, but after Nxe5 Nxe5, your queen is still hanging and you have just lost a piece for nothing. } 12... Nxe5 $17) (12. Bxf7+?? $19 { Too crazy, even though I like how you are considering forcing moves. Unfortunately, white does not have enough of a lead in development to justify such a piece sacrifice. } 12... Kxf7 13. Qb3+ Nd5! 14. Nxd5?! (14. Qxd5+!? Qxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxf3 $19) 14... Be6! $19) (12. h3? { Too slow. After Bxf3 Qxf3 Qxd4!, black gains a tempo on the unprotected LSB and is only one move away from castling queenside. } 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxd4! 14. Ba6!! { The engine finds some sort of brilliant mess here, but black is still fine when the dust settles. } 14... e4! 15. Nxe4! Nxe4 16. Bxb7! Ne5! 17. Qxe4 Qxe4 18. Bxe4 O-O-O $10) (12. Qa4? { Threatening d5 is reasonable, yet black has a convenient response in Bxf3 gxf3, Qd7! Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 12... Bxf3! 13. gxf3 Qd7! $17 { Black is escaping queenside now, and we have nothing for our two sacrificed pawns. }) 12... Bh5?! { Qd7 (developing and defending!) was a more principled defensive try, but Morphy had no doubt calculated its refutation: Nxe5! Check the analysis board at the end of this game to see this beautiful refutation.
In contrast, black's Bh5?! does not develop a new piece and therefore gives white several crushing options.
Is now the moment to further open the center? } (12... Qd7!? { The best defensive try. } 13. Nxe5! Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nh5 15. Rad1! Bxd1 16. Rxd1 Qf5 17. Ne4!! { Nf6+, finishing the destruction in the center, is the game-winning threat. } 17... Rd8!? (17... Qxe4?! 18. Bxf7#) 18. Nf6+!! Qxf6 { Sadly, necessary. } (18... Nxf6?! 19. Bxf7#) 19. exf6 Rxd1+ 20. Qxd1 $18) (12... Na5?! 13. Bxf7+ Kd7 14. Qc2 $18 { In contrast to the earlier Qb3 line, black does not have pressure against the f7 bishop. }) 13. dxe5 { Yes! Opening up the center with tempo on f6 once more prevents black from making the developing moves they so desperately need.
This is yet another example of Morphy adhering to the concept that you should open up the position when you have a lead in development. } (13. Rfe1 $18 { Principled and strong. Play dxe5 for the game continuation. }) (13. Rae1 $18 { Principled and strong. Play dxe5 for the game continuation. }) (13. Nxe5 $18 { Centralizing the knight with further tempo on f7. A great move. Play dxe5 for the game continuation. }) (13. Rad1 $18 { Nice! A classic Morphy move. Play dxe5 for the game continuation. }) (13. Rfd1 $18 { Nice! A classic Morphy move. Play dxe5 for the game continuation. }) 13... Ng4 (13... Na5!? 14. Qa4+ Qd7 15. Bb5! c6 16. Rad1! cxb5!? 17. Nxb5! $18 { [%cal Gd1d7,Gb5c7,Gb5d6,Ge5f6] }) 14. Rad1! { The Morphy move! At this point, your hand should be itching to bring the last piece into the fight with tempo, even before your brain fully absorbs the position. } (14. e6! $18 { Excellent job opening up the position further. Play the Morphy move first for the game continuation. }) (14. Rfd1?! $18 { The worse rook to develop with tempo because now f2 is falling in many lines. }) (14. Rfe1? { Oh no, your f pawn! } 14... Nxf2!? (14... Bxf2+?! 15. Kh1 Bxe1 16. Qxb7! $18) 15. Kf1! $16) (14. Rae1!? $18 { Not a bad square for the rook, although placing the rook on the d file is much more natural. }) 14... Qc8 { With all of white's pieces in the attack (except the f1 rook, which is at least serving a useful role defending f2), black's king hopelessly trapped in the center, and black's pieces scattered to the sides of the board, white is clearly winning.
How do you finish off the game fastest? } (14... Nd4? 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Qxb7!? c5 17. Bxc5! $18 { [%cal Gd1d4,Gb7a8,Gc4b5] }) 15. e6! { Continuing the theme of the chapter. White is massively ahead in development, so opening the center is necessary to crush black's king.
I'm reasonably confident that Morphy played e6 without calculating a single variation. For all the reasons we have been discussing, it has to be correct. } (15. Nd5?! $18 { A solid, centralizing move. But one that comes with no threat. Find a more direct finish. }) (15. Ne4?! $18 { A solid, centralizing move. But one that comes with no threat. Find a more direct finish. }) (15. Ng5? $16 { Further pressure on f7. But after Qf5, black has further defense. Don't force your opponent to make good moves. }) (15. Rfe1?? $16 { Oh no! You hung f2! } 15... Bxf2+ 16. Kh1 Bxe1 17. Ne4 $16) (15. h3?! $18 { Black's knight has to retreat to h6, which conveniently defends the f7 weakness. Winning, but not in a very direct manner. }) (15. Nb5? $18 { The knight does nothing on b5. Find a more direct finish. }) 15... f6 { Black, of course, cannot allow the center to open. But now the e6 pawn is a thorn in black's position, covering two critical squares around black's king.
Morphy's finish is as boring as it is ruthless. } { [%cal Gb3b5] } (15... fxe6? 16. Bxe6 $18) 16. Qb5!? { One of the less violent ways to win, attacking the bishop on h5. Rd7 would have been my preference. } (16. Rd7! { My personal preference for ending the game. Rxg7 and Nd5 are deadly follow-ups. Black is lost. Play Qb5 instead for the game continuation. } 16... Bg6!? 17. Nd5 Nge5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5? (18... fxe5!? 19. Rxg7 $18) 19. Re7+! Kf8 20. Rxc7+! $18) 16... Bg6?! { The threat to h5 is parried but now Morphy uncorks a much more serious threat. } { [%cal Gc4d5] } 17. Bd5! $18 { The c6 knight cannot be defended a second time, and so white wins at least a pawn. More important than winning a pawn however is that this pawn drops with checkmate!
Since there is no satisfactory defense in this position, black resigned. However, let's play out a few more moves just to see how the game could have ended. } 17... a6!? { One of many unsatisfactory defenses.
How do you finish off black? } 18. Bxc6+! (18. Qxc6+!! { Adding insult to injury, this fantastic queen sacrifice is as crushing as it is unnecessary. Congratulations on spotting this beautiful mate-in-4. Play Bxc6+ instead for the game continuation. } 18... bxc6 19. Bxc6+ Qd7 20. Bxd7+ Kd8 21. e7# { A finish reminiscent of the Evergreen Game, played by none other than Morphy's foil, Adolf Anderssen: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evergreen_Game }) 18... bxc6 19. Qxc6+ Qd7 { A sad day for black. There wasn't even a way to postpone the finish for even two moves. } 20. Qxd7# { This will not be the last game where Morphy takes a time-out from developing as rapidly as possible in order to generate a threat that provokes a weakness, undevelops an opponent's piece, takes over the center, or forces an opponent to defend in some undesirable way.
There is no hard and fast rule determining when a threat is stronger than a developing move. However, I hope that this example at least provides a few guidelines of what to look for when choosing between these two options. When you have a lead in development, keep your eye out for the DDD moment!
Another important takeaway is that Morphy does not make threats that can be conveniently defended, for instance by the opponent developing a piece to a good square. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 1-0


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.09.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Paul Journoud"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B21"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Morphy Gambit"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Tempo fiend"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/l1PmGO1g"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this game, Morphy faces off against one of the leading French masters.

Try to identify the DDD moment(s) this game to determine when to blast open the position. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 c5 { The Sicilian defense } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 2. d4 { Morphy's preferred move order to reach the Open Sicilian is less common today. There is no real independent value to playing this move order, especially because it allows black one extra option that we see in the game. Nf3 first is overwhelmingly more common. } 2... cxd4 { Black plays the Sicilian to prevent white claiming a broad center. Therefore, when white plays d4, this capture is logical to avoid being overruled. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 3. Nf3 { By transposition, Morphy is willing to play the Open Sicilian. Black should play e6, d6, Nc6, or g6 as they would after the normal move order: 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 to take us back into the main lines.
The fiery Smith-Morra gambit kicking off with 3. c3 instead was not developed for another hundred years. } (3. c3 { The Smith-Morra gambit was unknown for another hundred years }) 3... e5!? { "Oh no my e pawn!" Morphy's move order has allowed this off-beat variation. Black is now decidedly up a pawn.
However, white is on move (=> one tempo), has already developed the kingside knight (=> two tempi), and both bishops are ready to fly into action compared to only black's DSB (=> three tempi). This is another example of the rule of thumb that a pawn is worth three tempi. The position is equal.
How best to justify this pawn sac? } 4. Bc4 { Preparing to castle kingside while placing the LSB on the best diagonal, newly weakened by black's e5. } (4. Nxe5?? { Loose pieces drop off! Black has Qa5+ and you just lost a knight! } 4... Qa5+ $19 { [%cal Ga5e5] }) (4. c3! $10 { Give yourself credit for such a move. Theory today states that this is the optimal way to play. Play Bc4 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. Be2?! $15 { Too passive. We're down a pawn - we need to play the most active moves possible. }) (4. Bg5?! { A poor threat. After black responds with Be7, we are simply offering trades and developing black's army for them. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 4... Be7 5. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15) 4... Be7?! { "Half-developing moves" are moves that technically develop a piece, but place that piece on a square where it accomplishes nothing besides being off the back rank. In essence, the piece is developed, but passive.
PRO TIP: Don't play half-developing moves when there are more active options available instead. Active pieces win games. Passive pieces lose ground.
In this position, Be7 is a half-developing move. Yes, the bishop is developed. But is it doing anything useful from e7? Moreover, this move doesn't control the center in any meaningful way.
Nc6, developing and defending the center, is more principled. } 5. c3! { When you're ahead in development, open the position!
This move also has the happy side effect of blocking the a5-e1 diagonal towards white's king, thus introducing Nxe5 as a threat.
Is this the DDD moment? Almost. Besides O-O (an equally strong option), white had no flexible developing move free from drawbacks. c3 was therefore the best choice either this move or next. } (5. O-O!? $14 { A fine option too. Play c3 for the game continuation. }) (5. Nbd2? $16 { Blocks your queen and DSB. To develop efficiently you cannot block your own pieces! }) (5. Bd2? $17 { An equally bad half-developing move. To develop efficiently you cannot block your own pieces! }) (5. Nxe5?? $19 { Loose pieces drop off! Black has Qa5+ and you just lost a knight! }) 5... d6?! { Black directly defends e5, but this is a poor move for several reasons. Firstly, the d4 pawn is now ripe for the taking, further blasting open the position. Secondly, Nc6 was available, developing and defending. Thirdly, black clearly misses Morphy's next move, which has no counter. } (5... Nc6! 6. Qb3!? Na5! $10) 6. Qb3! { Developing with a threat! Typically such a move is desirable because it gains time - black has to waste time defending in an undesirable way. However in this position, white is just winning f7. There's simply no move that defends against the threat of Bxf7! } (6. cxd4! $16 { Simple and good. We regain the sacrificed pawn, have better control of the center, and open up Nc3 as a new option. Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. O-O?! $14 { A logical developing move. But white can already strike while the iron is hot. Find a developing move that comes with a threat instead. }) (6. Bxf7+?? $19 { Way too soon. There is no follow-up for such a sacrifice. }) (6. Qa4+? { An empty check. After Nc6, you are just forcing your opponent to make a good move. } 6... Nc6 $10) 6... dxc3?! { Black's position is bad but this horrible move deserves a double question mark for how unprincipled it is!
PRO TIP: When you are behind in development, every move you make should be focused on catching up in development and avoiding the position opening up before all your pieces are playing. For the logicians out there, this tip is nothing more than the inverse of what you should do when you are ahead in development. } 7. Bxf7+ (7. Nxc3?! $16 { Inconsistent. Take the free pawn with check first! }) 7... Kf8 8. Nxc3 { If this move was not one of your first candidates, please revisit the previous chapter. Multipurpose developing moves are the backbone of how to get a lead in development. } (8. Qxc3?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 8... Kxf7 $19) (8. bxc3? $10 { A bad way to recapture. Your knight on b1 is now crying because you robbed her of her favorite square. }) 8... Nc6 { From such a passive position, black does not deserve to be able to generate any threats. Yet black's threat of Na5, after which there is no queen move that also defends the LSB, is real. This threat forces an atypical move by Morphy. } { [%cal Gf7g8] } 9. Bxg8!? { We have repeatedly seen that Morphy was an unapologetic tempo fiend.
Morphy is not interested in wasting a tempo to deal with black's threat of Na5. He prefers trading off the bishop for the knight on g8 just to get the move back and further his lead in development. } (9. a3!? { Arguably the best move. White gives their queen the a2 square and now Na5 doesn't do anything productive for black. This isn't in Morphy's style though. }) 9... Rxg8 { Notice that Rxg8 is not a developing move. Thus, Bxg8 regained a tempo. } 10. O-O { As before, punishing black's slow play requires patience. White still has necessary developing moves before it is time to strike. } (10. Be3!? $16 { Great job developing the bishop to a good square. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Nd5!? $16 { Great job placing this knight on the dream outpost. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Bd2?! $14 { The bishop does nothing from d2. }) (10. Bg5?? $19 { Oh no, your bishop! }) 10... Qe8? { Another non-developing move. White's lead in development has reached its peak, and so it's time to strike. } { [%cal Gf3g5] } 11. Ng5! { Threatening Nh7#! This was not the only good move for white, but Morphy is consistent in his quest to develop as fast as possible or create threats. } 11... Bxg5 12. Bxg5 Be6 { Black is desperate to catch up on development before white can land a knockout blow, but it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } 13. Nd5! { Excellent! A great multipurpose move that brings the knight into the center while dealing with black's threat.
PRO TIP: Parrying your opponent's threats with a constructive move that you wanted to play anyway is often an excellent response. It's best to avoid losing time when possible. We will see Morphy play many such moves throughout this study, while his opponents will often fail to find these themselves.
This concept is deeply explored in Chapter V: Active defense. } (13. Qxb7?! $16 { An unnecessary pawn to grab. After Rb8 our queen is merely getting sidelined. }) (13. Qa3?! $16 { Not a horrible move, escaping the threat while also generating a threat of your own. But there are more direct options available for white that play in the center. }) 13... h6 { An instructive position to analyze. It is worth spending time here. No hints from me! } 14. f4!! { A fantastic move! Blowing open the f file in every variation brings the rook into the game in the fight against black's king!
This is one more example of a concept we have already seen. Once you reach the DDD moment, you should be looking for forcing moves, tactical shots, and general fireworks - especially those that blast open the position further.
As an aside, we will later explore the concept of a "hook" (a pawn one can latch onto with a pawn break in order to open up lines) in Chapter VI of this study. This e5 pawn is a prime example of a hook. } (14. Be3? $16 { This retreat is of course "fine," in that white retains an edge. But white already has fireworks available. }) (14. Qf3+? { An empty check that only encourages Qf7, a developing move. } 14... Qf7 15. Qa3! $16 { Miraculously, white keeps an edge even here }) (14. Nc7?? { A forward move, but tactically flawed. After Bxb3, Nxe8 Kxe8, black is up a piece. Both bishops are hanging in that position. However, whether we save ours or capture theirs, black will copy us and remain up a piece.
In a DDD moment, we should not necessarily consider all forcing moves. Rather, we should focus on forcing moves that generate threats around black's king. } 14... Bxb3 15. Nxe8 Kxe8 16. Be3!? (16. axb3!? hxg5 $19) 16... Be6 $19) (14. Bxh6?? { Why are you opening up black's horrible rook on g8? This move does not blast open the position towards black's king, it blasts open the position towards ours! } 14... gxh6 15. Nf6 Bxb3 16. Nxe8 Kxe8 17. axb3 $19) (14. Qxb7? { Once more, capturing on b7 lacks any follow-up. After Rb8, our queen is merely sidelined. } 14... Rb8 15. Qc7 hxg5 16. f4!! $16 { Amazingly there is still some juice here. } 16... exf4?! 17. Nxf4! gxf4 18. Rxf4+ Bf7 19. Raf1 Ne5 20. Qxd6+ Qe7 21. Qxb8+ Qe8 22. Qxe8+ Kxe8 23. Rf5 $18) 14... Qd7?! { Of course hxg5 would have been met with fxg5+, where black's king dies on the open f file. Regardless, Qd7 does nothing to slow down white's attack. Bf7, blocking the f file, was more prudent, albeit still hopeless. } (14... hxg5 15. fxg5+ Bf7 16. g6 $18) (14... Bf7 15. fxe5 hxg5 16. Nc7 $18) 15. fxe5+ Ke8 { White's pieces are swarming black's king. Many wins exist in this position, but Morphy's continuation is the most precise. } { [%cal Gd5c7] } 16. Nc7+! { Deflecting the queen from the defense of the bishop. } 16... Qxc7 17. Qxe6+ $18 { exd6 is coming next, further opening lines to the king. Black's king remains caught in a kill box in the center of the board.
As we have just seen, stronger opponents don't just roll over and resign. They force us to play more precisely. The principled moves that build up the position require effort. The opponent's threats require attention. The killing blows require calculation.
As we progress through this study and the games get more difficult, more time and effort will be spent on the variations that make Morphy's moves work. This is not to say that the principles we have been discussing become less important. Rather, they form a foundation for determining which candidate moves are most desirable. The act of choosing the specific candidate move to play each move though will require calculating more precise variations. } 1-0


