{ Morphy's opponent this game was another top French player at the time. In this game, we revisit the Evans Gambit line played previously against Thomas Hampton, where black is once again lost by move 9. This time, however, Morphy's opponent complicates the conversion.

Previously we discussed the fine line between forcing matters with threats and building up the position by developing. This time we will discuss the Evans Gambit in detail and appreciate how Morphy uses the initiative to convert a winning attack. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 { Best by test. } 1... e5 { This will be the last game I provide arrows for the Evans Gambit opening moves. You've seen it enough, I expect you to have already memorized it! } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { Nf6 is another, good, developing move. It prevents the Evans Gambit but allows Ng5, going for the Fried Liver Attack.
Against the Evans, black wins a pawn at the cost of being behind in development. Against Ng5, black sacrifices a pawn but gets a lead in development. Black chooses Bc5 or Nf6 depending on which middlegame they prefer. } { [%cal Gb2b4] } (3... Nf6!? 4. Ng5!? d5! 5. exd5 Na5! (5... Nxd5? { Allowing the fried liver. Do not allow this as black! } 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 $16) 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 $10) 4. b4!? { The return of the Evans Gambit.
One side effect of playing through Morphy's games is acquiring a sense for where the pieces belong for maximum effect in both the Evans and King's Gambit.
PRO TIP: One of the best ways to learn how to play an opening is to play through many master games in that opening. You're sure to pick up on typical early middlegame plans for both colors, the most effective squares for your pieces, and the most critical variations worth understanding. } 4... Bxb4 { Nxb4 is also playable, but less flexible. White plays the same way with c3+d4, and so black has to allow the variation we get in the game. There are other defenses more dependable than the game continuation, so why limit options unnecessarily? } 5. c3 { As before, building a broad center (with tempo!) with c3+d4 is the main point of the Evans. } 5... Bc5!? { Be7, Ba5, Bd6, and Bc5 are all playable, although they have different flavors.
The most solid, but boring, retreat is Be7. After d4 Na5! black gains a valuable tempo on the LSB. Black next will give back the pawn and castle ASAP, trying to play an equal endgame.
The most fiery option is Ba5, which seems to prevent d4. However d4 is still playable, at the cost of a second pawn. No matter if black accepts or rejects that second pawn, sharp variations are inevitable because white must justify their material deficit with active moves.
Bd6 is an attempt to hold up the fireworks until after black castles. While playable, blocking in the d pawn (and therefore LSB) limits black's defensive capabilities considerably.
The least common option is Bc5. After d4 exd4, O-O! white fights for the initiative. Black must stay on their toes to equalize. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } (5... Be7!? { The boring, solid retreat. } 6. d4 Na5 7. Be2!? (7. Bd3!? d6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 $10) 7... d6 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Bxd8 10. Nxe5 $10) (5... Ba5!? { Fiery play } 6. d4 d6!? (6... exd4!? 7. O-O! Nge7 $13) 7. Qb3!? (7. O-O Bb6!? $10 { The normal move order to reach the Lasker defense. }) 7... Qd7 $10) (5... Bd6!? { Solid, but perhaps pushing their luck. } 6. d4 Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 $10) 6. O-O?! { Objectively, d4 first is more precise than O-O, although they transpose in this game.
A good way to remember the correct move order: d4 first is always correct against every bishop retreat. If black captures on d4 with exd4, then O-O! is a good way to sacrifice more material but pick up a raging attack. Black should typically not accept the second pawn, in which case we can transpose to the game if black's bishop is on c5. } (6. d4! $14 { Objectively more precise than the game continuation because black is forced to capture on d4. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) 6... d6 { What is the point of the Evans Gambit? } 7. d4 exd4?! { Black holds onto their extra pawn by giving up the center. This capture would have been forced if white had played 6. d4 rather than 6. O-O.
Instead of exd4, Bb6! would have transposed to the Lasker defense, a solid way to treat the Evans. Black gives up the e pawn but quickly catches up in development, while white has to spend time recapturing the sacrificed pawns.
We will play through a dozen Evans Gambits throughout this study. I only bring up these opening subtleties because I believe it's worth knowing which move orders are optimal according to modern theory in case Morphy inspires you to pick up this opening yourself. } (7... Bb6! 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Nf6 $10) 8. cxd4 Bb6 { I have included all of the Evans Gambit main lines we just discussed in this game's PGN. To view the different variations, click "Analysis board" after completing this game.
Amazingly, we transpose to one of the modern main lines in the Evans Gambit... in 1858.
We have seen this position in a previous game. Is now the moment to strike in the center? } 9. Nc3 { Correct. White does not have a tangible lead in development that on its own justifies opening the center at all costs. } (9. d5?! { Closes down our bishop. This threat doesn't gain time because after Na5 we have to spend a move retreating the bishop, losing the time right back. } 9... Na5 10. Bd3 $10) (9. e5?! { A thematic strike in the Evans, seeking to blast open the position. But white doesn't have enough development for such a move. After d5! the center is closed with tempo. } 9... d5! 10. Bb5 Ne7 $15) (9. Ba3?! { Good job not budging in the center. However, this move is poorly timed because the bishop does nothing on its own from a3. } 9... Bg4! $15) (9. Re1!? $10 { Good job not budging in the center. The rook coming to e1 does not pack the same punch as developing another piece though. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. h3!? $10 { A horrible "bunny ears" move that you should avoid at all costs. Unfortunately, this unprincipled move is an interesting option played by some top players nowadays, simply because Bg4, pressuring the center, is so annoying. }) (9. Bb2!? $10 { Good job not budging in the center. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Qb3?! { Thematic, as you are developing with a threat. Unfortunately, after Na5! taking on f7 loses a piece since the queen cannot escape the knight's attack while defending the loose bishop on f7. } 9... Na5! 10. Bxf7+? Kf8 $17) (9. Bg5?! { Thematic, as you are developing with a threat. Unfortunately, after Nge7 (developing!), there is no way to continue pushing our slight advantage in development. Perhaps the bishop is not as strong on g5 as on another square... } 9... Nge7 $15) (9. Ng5?! { f7 is a weakness in this opening, but this move forces black to develop and defend with Nh6. Meanwhile, we are wasting time and undefending our center! } 9... Nh6 $15) 9... Nf6? { We have already seen that this natural move is a fatal mistake. Bg4 instead is the most dependable move to play according to modern theory. } (9... Bg4! 10. Bb5!? Bd7! $10) 10. e5! { Blasting open the position at the DDD moment! } 10... d5? { In a previous game, we saw how Morphy refuted dxe5 with Ba3! Now we will explore black's attempt with d5. In both cases, white already has a winning position.
What concept applies to this position? } (10... dxe5!? 11. Ba3! $16) 11. exf6! { Exactly! We have a lead in development and a safe king, while our opponent doesn't have their king castled nor have enough development to keep up with us. We should therefore seek to open up the position so that our advantage in time is felt more directly. } (11. Bb3? $16 { Reasonable, since black now has to move the knight somewhere, this hanging d5. But we don't care about a silly pawn! Look for better. } 11... Ne4 12. Nxd5 O-O $16) (11. Ba3?! $16 { Logical development of the DSB to prevent castling. There is a more forcing way to accomplish this though kicking off with exf6 instead. }) (11. Bg5? $16 { A worse version of the immediate exf6, since after gxf6 black now gains a tempo on our bishop. }) 11... dxc4 { Black's move is forced to avoid losing a piece. What's the one-two punch that prevents black from castling forever? } 12. fxg7 (12. Re1+! $18 { Equally good. Take on g7 first before playing this move. }) (12. d5?! { Not actually a forcing move since after Qxf6, hitting our knight on c3, white has to blink first. } 12... Qxf6! $16) (12. Ba3?! $18 { A fine way to prevent black from castling kingside. However, there is a more forcing way to accomplish the same thing. }) 12... Rg8 { Correct again! Black is now never castling kingside.
The factors that determine a chess position's evaluation broadly fall under two categories: static and dynamic.
Static advantages are those that persist and don't depend on the move-by-move variations. Examples include extra material and a better pawn structure.
Dynamic advantages are those that are time-dependent in that they will disappear if not utilized immediately. Use it or lose it! Examples include a lead in development, a king stuck in the center, or more active pieces.
Throughout these last two chapters, we have been exploring how Morphy fights for dynamic advantages and then utilizes them to destroy his opponents. Indeed, once again, this position has opened up, black's king is stuck in the center, and white has a slight lead in development. These dynamic factors dominate any trivial concerns about static factors, and so white must be much better.
PRO TIP: Dynamic advantages are often more important than static advantages, especially when they involve king safety concerns. You can have all the material in the world - you still lose the game if your king gets mated! } 13. Re1+ (13. d5!? $18 { Equally good. Play Re1+ first for the game continuation. }) (13. Ne4!? $18 { A nice centralizing move that admittedly doesn't have a killer threat. Play Re1+ for the game continuation. }) (13. Bg5?! { After f6, black gets the move back and can now keep their king relatively safe on f7. Note that this move doesn't gain a tempo! } 13... f6! $16) (13. Ba3? { Black's king isn't castling kingside anymore, so this bishop is now on the wrong diagonal. } 13... Qf6 $14) (13. Qe2+!? { Reasonable, only because Qe7 will now be met with Qxc4. Play Re1+ instead for the game continuation. } 13... Qe7 14. Qxc4 $16) 13... Be6 { Black walks into an obvious pawn fork, but is relying on a trick.
Have you noticed that Morphy has been dictating play this game? Ever since he achieved the e5 pawn break, every move has been a forcing move that black has had to defend. White is moving forward while black is trying to tread water. White has what is known as the "initiative."
PRO TIP: One of the most common ways to push a dynamic advantage is to gain the initiative. In an open position, when you have more active pieces that can naturally generate threats, using the initiative forces a less active opponent backwards or passive. } 14. d5! (14. Bg5!? { The Morphy move. Play d5 instead for the game continuation. }) 14... Qf6 { This is black's planned defense, although it is doomed to fail.
PRO TIP: The side with the less active pieces usually cannot seek dynamic counterplay - dynamics favor the side with more active pieces.
In this position every forcing move is winning for white. Morphy's choice is principled and on-theme for this chapter: he finishes development while further opening the center. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } 15. Bg5!? { A true Morphy - NN position. All of white's pieces are developed with tempo, the position is opening up, and black's king is stuck in the center of the board. } 15... Qxc3 { Forced, if black does not want to go down a piece for nothing. } 16. dxe6 (16. dxc6?! $16 { This capture doesn't open up the position to black's king as much as the other capture. }) 16... Qd3 { Black would of course love to trade queens to avoid their king dying in the center. We already know white should avoid this very queen trade and open the center instead. } 17. exf7+ Kxf7 { Black will pay the price for not evacuating the king out of the center before the position exploded. Besides king safety being a primary concern, black not castling means the rooks remain bystanders to the ongoing slaughter. } { [%cal Ge1e7] } 18. Re7+! { The rook is immune because the knight is overworked defending e7 and the royal fork on e5.
As Fischer famously said, "tactics flow from a superior position." } 18... Kg6 { [%cal Gd1e1] } (18... Nxe7? 19. Ne5+ $18) 19. Qe1 { After nine consecutive forcing moves, Morphy takes time out to keep the queens on the board before the king hunt continues in earnest. Note that the rook remains immune due to the same knight fork.
Qe6+ is white's immediate threat. } 19... Qd5 { Black defends against Qe6+. The black queen is not better placed on d5 though. } 20. Rd1! { The Morphy move! Of course we bring our last piece into the fight with tempo. Classic multipurpose move.
Once more, we see that Morphy grabs hold of the initiative when possible. He does not make aimless threats. Rather, he makes threats that improve his position. Having such options is a consequence of white's initiative. } (20. Qb1+?! { After Qd3 the best you can do is repeat with Qe1. } 20... Qd3 21. Qe1 $18) (20. Qc3!? $18 { A good move, coordinating on f6 with the DSB. Play Rd1 for the game continuation. }) (20. Qe6+?? $10 { Trading queens in the middle of a large attack is the worst way to kill your own initiative! }) (20. Re6+? { An empty check that allows the king to slip away after Kxg7. } 20... Kxg7 $16) (20. Nh4+?? { Oh no your bishop! } 20... Kxg5 21. Re6 $16) 20... Nd4 { There was no queen move that prevented Qe6+, so blocking with the knight that wasn't doing anything is as good a defensive attempt as any.
This is yet another example of the DDD moment. All of white's pieces are in the action. Meanwhile, black has many desirable moves that would catch up in development. If black gets a move to bring either rook into the game, trade off a piece or two to relieve the pressure, or otherwise neutralize white's lead in development, then white will have no tangible advantage.
If only black had time! White's decisive dynamic advantage can already be converted into a decisive static advantage, simply by winning material. } { [%cal Gd1d4] } 21. Rxd4! { PRO TIP: Sacrificing to remove a key defender should be a foundational tool in your toolkit of how to push the initiative. Kasparov famously described this operation as "an equal exchange. I can exchange one attacking piece for one defensive piece. But I have enough pieces to mate him." https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SMe-hvCwTRo
Rxd4 is just one finish of many. Black's king has been stuck in a kill box for several moves now. } 21... Bxd4 { Black's king is now critically weak. Can you finish them off? } 22. Qb1+! (22. Nxd4?! $18 { Winning. But why are we trading our strong knight for a bishop that is doing nothing? }) (22. Re6+?? $14 { Forces Kxg7. Why are you forcing your opponent to make a good move? }) (22. Qe6+?? $15 { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Why are you trading queens in the middle of a winning attack? }) (22. Qe4+?? { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Of course we are not interested in trading queens in the middle of our mating attack. } 22... Qxe4 23. Rxe4 $19) 22... Qf5 { Of course Kh5 dropped h7 with check, so this sad move had to played. } (22... Kh5?! 23. Qxh7+ Kg4 24. h3#) 23. Nh4+ { Nice fork! White will now end up a decisive amount of material. Moreover, black's king remains on the chopping block. } (23. Re6+!? $18 { Also a nice move that wins the queen. Play Nh4+ instead for the game continuation. }) (23. Qxf5+?? $17 { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Don't trade queens when you can instead directly win their queen! }) 23... Kxg5 24. Qxf5+ (24. Nxf5!? $18 { Also playable and completely winning, but the other capture is more in the spirit of Morphy's forcing play. }) 24... Kh6 { Of course, Kxh4 was met with g3#. On h6, black's king is desperately short on squares and he cannot escape back up the board. If only we could bring in one more attacker... } (24... Kxh4?! 25. g3#) 25. g4! { The g pawn joins the fight, setting up Qh5#. Black is helpless to prevent it.
Even in a completely winning position, Morphy continues making threats and pushing his initiative! } (25. Nf3! $18 { Full credit if you found this move - threatening Qg5#. Play g4 instead for the game continuation. }) (25. Re6+! { Full credit if you found that after Kxg7 white has Re7+ crashing through to h7. Play g4 instead for the game continuation. } 25... Kxg7 26. Re7+ Kh8 27. Rxh7#) 25... Bxf2+ { A spite check that accomplishes nothing. } 26. Kg2 $18 { Black resigned because there is no longer a way to prevent Qh5#, even for a move.
After achieving e5 early in this game, Morphy gained the initiative. He strung together an impressive 16 consecutive forcing moves, culminating in winning black's queen in the middle of a mating attack. The only time that black momentarily prevented Morphy from pushing his agenda was the silly spite check one move before resigning.
I have included all of the Evans Gambit main lines in this game's PGN. To view the different variations, click "Analysis board." That will turn off the guess-the-move overlay, so you can flip through the opening variations at your leisure. } (26. Kxf2?! $18 { There's no reason to capture this bishop and allow Rf8. Find another safe square instead. }) (26. Kh1!? $18 { Equally winning. Morphy played Kg2 instead. }) (26. Kf1!? $18 { Equally winning. Morphy played Kg2 instead. }) (26. Qxf2?! $18 { Obviously still winning. But don't demote your queen in the middle of a mating attack. You're only prolonging the finish. }) 1-0


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.10.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Theodore Lichtenhein"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C51"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, McDonnell Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
