{ This game was played just before Morphy's meteoric rise in the US scene. Here, Morphy faces off against the indisputable #3 player in the US in a casual game outside of the 1st American Chess Congress.

Since Lichtenhein is much stronger than most of Morphy's opponents so far, he puts up much stiffer resistance, even after finding himself in a losing position. Therefore, this game will be a step up in difficulty compared the previous games.

We will revisit the same Evans Gambit line again. Even down a tempo, white's initiative remains fearsome. No arrows in the opening this time. You know what to do! }
1. e4 e5 { It's worth repeating two terms introduced last game since they are so fundamental: statics and dynamics. These two categories encompass the factors that determine a chess position's evaluation.
Static advantages are those that persist and don't depend on the move-by-move variations. Examples include extra material and a better pawn structure.
Dynamic advantages are those that are time-dependent in that they will disappear if not utilized immediately. Use it or lose it! Examples include a lead in development, a king stuck in the center, or more active pieces. } 2. Nf3 (2. f4!? $15 { Morphy opts for the Evans Gambit this game. }) 2... Nc6 { Developing and defending. The best move. } 3. Bc4 (3. Bb5!? $10 { Morphy opts for the Evans Gambit this game. }) 3... Bc5 { How do you kick off the Evans Gambit? } 4. b4!? { The Evans Gambit is back! Once more we will see this opening fits Morphy's dynamic style. } (4. c3!? $10 { Morphy opts for the Evans Gambit this game. }) 4... Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 { The least common bishop retreat these days. } 6. O-O?! { As previously mentioned, d4! exd4 O-O! is the most precise way to continue against every bishop retreat. } (6. d4! $14 { As previously mentioned, d4! exd4 O-O! is the most precise way to continue against every bishop retreat. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) 6... Nf6?! { A new move relative to lines we discussed last game. This natural developing move has the same issue as Nf6 last game: black loses the center and therefore can get blown off the board! } 7. d4! { Yes. The point of the Evans Gambit is to take the center with tempo! } 7... exd4? { The logical continuation of black's play to avoid losing a pawn or further time. But we will repeatedly see that giving up the center (with tempo!) is a poor way to continue against the Evans unless black achieves some soothing piece trades as well. } 8. cxd4 Bb6 { We already know that one of the opening principles is to play in the center. Great - Morphy has successfully done so. His pieces control central squares and he has the strong pawn duo on e4 and d4. But what is the point of owning the center?
PRO TIP: Owning the center has both static and dynamic advantages. Statically, the center is strong because it robs your opponent's pieces of central squares, carves out space for your pieces to comfortably sit behind, and grants your pieces more mobility and maneuverability. Dynamically, the center is strong because at any moment the center can push forward, scattering your opponent's pieces to the wind.
Which is more important this game, the static or dynamic advantage of Morphy's center? } 9. e5! { Yes, the dynamic potential of an unchecked center should be used! The knight cannot jump to a central square (Ne4? Qe2!, hitting the knight and aligning with black's king is lights out), so either black must sideline the knight or play the thematic counterstrike d5. } (9. d5!? $16 { The right type of move. The knight gets kicked around and cannot jump towards the center. Unfortunately, after Na5 black regains a crucial tempo against your LSB, and so this move doesn't flat out win. There is stronger. }) (9. Ba3!? $16 { Preventing castling and developing a piece. Nice idea! Play e5 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Re1? $10 { Developing a piece, but now black can safely castle. }) (9. Bg5? $10 { Prevents castling due to the threat of e5. But what are you doing in response to h6? There are more forcing ways to prevent black from castling. }) 9... d5!? { A thematic response to white playing e5 in the Italian. Black refuses to budge with the knight and instead counterattacks the bishop on c4. If the bishop reacts, black has successfully played a center-focused developing move with tempo while also carving out e4 as a safe square for the knight. If the knight is captured, then black in turn captures white's bishop to restore material equality. This is a useful response to remember!
Unfortunately, there is a flaw in black's play - their king remains in the center! } (9... Ne4 10. Qe2! $18) (9... Ng4 10. Bg5 f6 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Re1+ Kf8 13. Bf4 $16) 10. exf6! (10. Bb5? { After Ne4, there is nothing wrong with black's position. } 10... Ne4 $10) (10. Ba3?? $17 { Prevents kingside castling, but black can still castle queenside. When the board is on fire, you can't afford niceties like this. What are the most forcing moves available for both sides? }) 10... dxc4 { So far, we have just traded pieces. What is the true problem with black's play? } 11. fxg7! (11. Re1+!? $18 { Equally good. Play fxg7 first for the game continuation. }) (11. d5?! $14 { Similar idea to last game. But after Qxf6, we again have problems on the diagonal - the a1 rook is loose. }) (11. Ba3? { Be6 + Qd7 is coming next. Black can still castle queenside! } 11... Be6 12. fxg7 Rg8 13. Nc3 Qf6! 14. Re1 O-O-O $19) 11... Rg8 { Exactly! Black's king is stuck in the center, so we should seek to open the position.
Does this position make you feel deja vu? It should! We reached the same position last game, but white's knight had already developed to c3. Since black played d5 in one move this game as opposed to two (d6-d5) last game, we are down a tempo compared to last game.
Regardless, the evaluation remains similar between the two positions. White has a lead in development, black's king is stuck in the center, and with proper play white can generate an initiative while preventing black from solving their king safety issues.
Time remains of the essence! } 12. Re1+ { There is no move more principled than developing the rook with check to the fully open file opposite black's king.
PRO TIP: When debating between several candidate moves, play the most adaptable option first. That is, you should start with the move that improves your position across the widest range of futures. Then, when it's time to play less clear candidates, you give yourself more flexibility to respond to your opponent. Maybe you play them as originally planned, maybe you play them in a different move order, or maybe you respond to your opponent with a different move altogether.
For instance, in this position, white's rook should end up on e1 in every variation. Meanwhile, white's DSB has options - it could play to a3, f4, or g5. Starting with the adaptable Re1 allows Morphy the flexibility to respond to black's play with the optimal bishop move later this game.
Please note that this tip is a rule of thumb and should NOT be followed religiously. If you believe one of your candidate moves is stronger than the others, play it! This rule of thumb is simply a helpful heuristic to be used when debating between seemingly equally strong candidates. } (12. d5! { Kicking the knight from its central post is equally strong. Play Re1+ instead for the game continuation. } 12... Ne7 13. Re1 $16) (12. Bg5?! { After f6, black gets the move back and can now keep their king relatively safe on f7. Note that this move doesn't gain a tempo! } 12... f6! $14) (12. Nc3?! $16 { In general, it is important to develop the pieces. However, in a DDD moment like this, we want to prioritize threats or developing moves with tempo, in order to prevent black's pieces from getting in the game. }) (12. Ba3? { Black's king isn't castling kingside anymore, so this bishop is now on the wrong diagonal. } 12... Be6 $17) (12. Qe2+? $10 { The queen is not better placed on e2 than on d1. Moreover, you are forcing black to develop with Be6. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! }) 12... Ne7!? { Blocking the check with Be6 instead would have lost to the same attack as last game, kicking off with d5! By starting with Re1, Morphy maintained the flexibility to play with a d5 thrust and not develop the DSB after all. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } (12... Be6!? 13. d5! Qf6!? { Like last game. } 14. dxe6 Rd8! (14... Qxa1?? 15. Qd7#) 15. Qc2 Qxa1? (15... Nd4!? 16. exf7+ Kxf7 17. Qxc4+ Kxg7 18. Nbd2 $18) 16. exf7+ Kxf7 17. Ng5+ Kf6 18. Re6+ Kxg7 19. Qxh7+ Kf8 20. Qf7#) 13. Bg5 { Now that f6 has been ruled out, this developing move comes with tempo and can't simply be kicked back. } 13... Be6 { A sensible move. Black develops and blocks the e file. Black only needs two moves to evacuate the king to the queenside and relative safety. Time remains of the essence. } 14. Nc3! { Once more we see a hallmark of Morphy's style: all the pieces are brought into the fight before decisive action is taken. } (14. Na3?! $16 { The knight is developed, but perhaps sidelined from a3 or b5. There is a more principled option. }) (14. Nbd2!? $16 { The knight is developed, but Nc3 is the more principled option. }) (14. Rxe6?! { Now is not the time to strike, even though this exchange sacrifice is still not worse for white. White still needs to finish development first. } 14... fxe6 15. Nc3 Rxg7 $10) (14. d5?? { A forcing move, but after Qxd5, white achieves nothing. } 14... Qxd5 15. Qc1!? $10 (15. Qxd5? Nxd5! $17)) (14. Qc2?! $16 { Is developing the queen the most adaptable option? We don't yet know where she belongs, but we certainly know where the b1 knight belongs! }) (14. Qa4+?! { Is developing the queen the most adaptable option? We don't yet know where she belongs, but we certainly know where the b1 knight belongs! } 14... Qd7 15. Qa3 $16) (14. Qd2?! $16 { Is developing the queen the most adaptable option? We don't yet know where she belongs, but we certainly know where the b1 knight belongs! }) 14... Ba5?! { Black attacks the c3 knight and pins it to the e1 rook. But when behind in development, moving the DSB yet again is horribly unprincipled. This should not be a candidate move! To make matters worse, Morphy proves this move does not even pin the knight after all.
Black just needs two moves to play Qd7 and O-O-O, fixing all king safety issues. Meanwhile white has a fully developed army and has already opened the center.
This position is yet another DDD moment! Time to strike! } { [%cal Gc3e4] } 15. Ne4! { Threatening Nf6# while simultaneously preventing the black queen from developing anywhere. Talk about a dynamic option! } 15... Rxg7 { [%cal Ge4f6] } 16. Nf6+ Kf8 { Black is certainly never castling now! How do you continue the initiative? } 17. Re5! { Getting out of Bxe1 by improving the rook with tempo against the loose bishop? Now that's a multipurpose move!
I hope you calculated the refutation to Nc6, black's developing move that simultaneously hits white's rook and defends the bishop on a5. That's right, Nxh7+ is a discovery that wins black's queen! } (17. Bh6?! { Sacrificing the exchange on e1 in order to win the exchange on g7? You're just trading pieces! } 17... Bxe1 18. Qxe1 Nf5 19. Bxg7+ Kxg7 20. Nh5+ $16) (17. Rxe6! { A reasonable exchange sacrifice. Following up with Ne5! keeps the initiative for white. Play Re5 instead for the game continuation. } 17... fxe6 18. Ne5! Bc3!? (18... Rxg5!? 19. Nxh7+ Kg7 20. Nxg5 $18) 19. Ned7+! Kf7 20. Qh5+ Rg6 21. Ne5+! Kf8 22. Bh6+ Rxh6 23. Qf7#) (17. Re4!? $18 { A nice rook lift. Play Re5 instead for the game continuation. }) (17. Re2?! $16 { If you're going to spend a tempo saving this rook, you should simultaneously threaten something so as to maintain the initiative! }) (17. Re3?! $16 { If you're going to spend a tempo saving this rook, you should simultaneously threaten something so as to maintain the initiative! }) (17. Rf1? $14 { Morphy would never play such a passive move. }) (17. Ne5? $10 { Your rook on e1 is hit. What does this move threaten? }) (17. Nh4? $10 { Your rook on e1 is hit. What does this move threaten? }) (17. d5? $14 { Your rook on e1 is hit. This move only threatens the bishop if you are willing to exchange queens. }) 17... c6 { A sad move to make. Black is purely defending against white's threats now. } (17... Nc6? 18. Nxh7+! Rxh7 19. Bxd8 $18) 18. Bh6 { A winning pin. White wins at least the exchange.
PRO TIP: You can learn all the chess strategy there is to learn... but the skill of spotting basic tactics for you and your opponent will always be the most important deciding factor in your games. } 18... Nf5 { Black tries to out-tactic Morphy. The DSB on h6 and knight on f6 are both attacked simultaneously. } { [%cal Ge5e6] } 19. Rxe6!? { This is not the only move from such a dominant position, and the continuation is quite complicated. Morphy, ever the artist, has planned a pretty follow-up.
Bxg7, immediately snagging the exchange, was potentially simpler. And simple is good. } (19. Bxg7+!? { Simple. The follow-up Nh5+ saves the knight and everything is defended. } 19... Kxg7 20. Nh5+ $16) (19. Nxh7+! { A crushing move that requires a lot of calculation in order to justify. See the annotations afterwards to see how white crushes black in every line. } 19... Kg8 20. Bxg7?! { Simple, but not as strong as the alternative. } (20. Bg5! { Even stronger according to the engine. The point is that black's queen actually has no safe squares while still defending the DSB on a5. } 20... Qc7!? (20... Qb6!? 21. Nf6+ Kh8 22. Rb1! Qa6 23. g4! Nd6 24. Qf1! $18) (20... Qc8!? { or any other queen move that doesn't defend the DSB... } 21. Nf6+ Kh8 22. Rxa5 $18) 21. Nf6+ Kh8 22. g4! Nd6 23. Qf1! $18 { [%cal Gf1h3] }) 20... Kxh7 21. Rxe6! fxe6 22. Be5 $16 { With a dominant position, even though white is not up any material. }) (19. Bg5! { Preparing for the Nxh7 discovered check. Just as in the game, the pieces defend themselves due to the various knight forks in the position. } 19... Bc7!? (19... Rxg5? 20. Nxg5 Qxf6?? 21. Nxh7+ Kg7 22. Nxf6 $18) 20. Rxe6 fxe6 21. Nxh7+! Rxh7 22. Bxd8 $18) (19. Qc1?? $10 { Oh no, your knight on f6. }) 19... fxe6 { [%cal Gf3g5] } 20. Ng5 { A pretty position! Every white piece is seemingly hanging, but the pieces all defend each other due to the various forks in the position. This is certainly a "don't try this at home" way to play chess though - one miscalculation and you lose a piece! } 20... Ke7! { Morphy's opponent finds a fantastic defensive move in a difficult position. Now all three of white's minor pieces are truly attacked.
There is only one move in the position to keep an advantage. Can you find it? } 21. Bxg7! { Winning the exchange for real, while temporarily defending the knight on f6. Good tactical vision. } (21. Nxe6?? { An interesting try, but the knight is able to be captured! After Kxe6 Bxg7 Nxg7, black is up material and there are no longer enough attackers to justify such a sacrifice. } 21... Kxe6 22. Bxg7 Nxg7 $19) (21. Nfxh7?? { Oh no your bishop! } 21... Nxh6 $19) (21. Ngxh7?? { Oh no your bishop! } 21... Nxh6 $19) (21. Nfe4?? { Oh no your bishop! } 21... Nxh6 $19) (21. Nge4?? { Oh no your bishop! } 21... Nxh6 $19) 21... Nxg7 { [%cal Gd1f3] } 22. Qf3 { Developing the queen and defending the f6 knight. The fireworks are mostly over now and white's pieces are no longer all hanging.
Oh no, my d pawn? } 22... Qxd4? { Black was surely counting on the threats of both Qxf6 and Qxa1 to win a tempo here after Qxd4. But dynamics favor the side with more active pieces.
Moreover, we have already seen examples where opening the position while behind in development is a good way to get yourself in trouble. While this is a tactical position where precise calculation is required, we should not forget that Qxd4 does not pass this rule of thumb. Therefore, Qxd4 should be treated as suspect without any calculation at all.
Precise calculation confirms this. Let's refute black with our next move! } 23. Rd1! { The Morphy move! Once this move lands on the board, it's easier to see that Qxf6 would now lose the queen to Rd7+! Short calculations such as this line are critical to being able to prove the principled, desirable moves are playable.
With all of white's pieces playing, and black's king still in the center, black is finally lost. } (23. Rb1?! { Tactically defending the knight due to Rxb7+. Excellent tactical vision! This move does not come with tempo though, whereas the game continuation does. } 23... Bb6! (23... Qxf6?? 24. Rxb7+ $18) 24. Nfxh7 $16) (23. Re1?? { Oh no, your rook! } 23... Bxe1 $19) (23. Rc1?? { Oh no, your knight! } 23... Qxf6 24. Qa3+ Ke8 25. Qxa5 Qf5! $17) (23. Qd1?? { Your knight is still hanging after the queen trade... } 23... Qxd1+ 24. Rxd1 Kxf6 $19) (23. Nd5+?? { Just hangs a knight after cxd5. } 23... cxd5 $19) (23. Ng8+? { A tricky option. But after Rxg8 we can't quite win yet because our rook on a1 is still hanging with back rank mate. } 23... Rxg8 24. Rd1! (24. Qf7+?? Kd6 25. Qxg8?? Qxa1#) 24... Qxd1+! 25. Qxd1 Rd8 $16) (23. Rf1?? { Oh no, your knight! } 23... Qxf6 24. Qa3+ Ke8 25. Qxa5 Qf5! $17) (23. Qa3+?? { Oh no, your knight! } 23... Kxf6 24. Qxa5?? Qxa1+ 25. Qe1 Qxe1#) 23... Bd2 { What else to do? Black was relying on Qxf6 working. Once that idea falls through, blocking the attack on the queen remains one of the few options left.
The game ends abruptly. } { [%cal Gf6g8] } (23... Qxf6? 24. Rd7+! Kxd7 25. Qxf6 $18) 24. Ng8+! { Tactically opens up the f file for the queen. } 24... Rxg8 { Forced if you don't want to lose to Ne4... } { [%cal Gf3f7] } 25. Qf7+! Kd8 { [%cal Gg5f3] } 26. Nf3! $18 { Morphy wants a bigger prize than the rook (with check)! Nxd4, winning a queen, and Rxd2, simultaneously winning a piece and the queen, are new threats. With no defense, black resigns.
Against tougher opposition, Morphy once more shows us the importance of precise calculation. Yes, Lichtenhein was objectively lost after missing the DDD moment and allowing the position to open while his king was stuck in the center. But converting the "win" into a win required Morphy's precise calculation abilities.
PRO TIP: The secret to good technique is good calculation! When Grandmasters say, "the rest is a matter of technique," that conversion still requires precise calculation. Few things are harder in chess than winning a "won" game! } 1-0


