{ Morphy's opponent in this game was the secretary of the NY Chess Club, but a vastly inferior player to Morphy. Rather than not play him, Morphy offered him knight odds to make the game more competitive.

As before with knight-odds games, we shouldn't focus on the specific moves played in the opening. Morphy is down a knight, and so must play hyper-aggressively to ensure his piece play is more relevant than his material deficit.

The benefit of analyzing such games though is that we get to see how Morphy throws caution to the wind in order to grab the initiative. Dynamic chess at its finest! } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { Morphy opts for an Evans Gambit-type game here. } 2. Nf3 (2. f4!? $19 { The King's Gambit is another good option if you start down a knight. In this game, Morphy opts for an Evans Gambit with Nf3. }) 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 { The Evans Gambit... down a knight! } 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O (6. d4! $17 { Good memory! d4 first remains more precise than Morphy's option even in a knight-odds game. Play O-O first for the game continuation. }) 6... Nf6?! { Loses a pawn or the center (with tempo!). We have already seen this mistake before, but in that game white still had their knight on b1. } 7. d4 exd4?! { Giving up the center is less important than giving up a pawn. Black is already up a piece, so should not be greedy! } 8. cxd4 Bb6 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 9. Ba3!? { Down a knight, Morphy goes for broke trying to prevent black from castling to safety. } (9. e5! { As in our previous game, this is a consistent approach to kicking black around or blasting open the center. Play Ba3 instead for the game continuation. } 9... O-O! 10. exf6 Qxf6 $17) 9... d6 { Black shuts the door on the DSB. Given one more move, black is ready to castle... } 10. e5! { Yes! This is the DDD moment! Nearly all of white's pieces are developed, and stirring up trouble immediately is necessary to prevent black from castling to safety. } (10. d5? { Gains a tempo. But after Ne7, black is still castling next move. } 10... Ne7 11. e5 Ng4 $19) (10. Qb3? { After O-O, f7 is adequately defended. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! } 10... O-O 11. Ng5!? Nxd4! 12. Nxf7 Nxb3 13. Nxd8+ Kh8 14. axb3 Rxd8 $19) (10. Ng5? { After O-O, f7 is adequately defended. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! } 10... O-O $19) 10... dxe5? { Black fails to prioritize king safety and development over material concerns. Ne4, centralizing the knight, followed by O-O was the best way to play. Even immediately castling, hanging the knight on f6, gives black some stability, two extra pawns, and a safe king.
In contrast, capturing on e5 decisively opens up the dark square diagonal for white's sniper bishop on a3. The center is slightly more opened for the heavy pieces too. This move is entirely too greedy. } (10... Ne4! 11. exd6 O-O 12. dxc7 Qxc7 13. Bxf8 Kxf8 $19) (10... O-O!? 11. exf6 Qxf6 $17) 11. Qb3! { Development with a threat! How exactly can black defend f7 now that castling has been ruled out?
We have seen many Evans Gambits now where this light square battery towards f7 is strong. Keep this piece constellation in mind for your own games. } (11. dxe5? { Allowing a queen trade in the middle of a blistering attack? You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! } 11... Qxd1 12. Raxd1 Ng4 $19) (11. Nxe5? { Allowing a queen trade in the middle of a blistering attack? You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! } 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Ng4 $19) (11. Re1? { Developing the rook, but this move lacks urgency. Black can develop the LSB to e6 and then quickly castle queenside. } 11... Be6 12. Bxe6 fxe6 $19 { [%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] }) (11. Ng5?! { A reasonable move, improving the knight and hitting f7. Unfortunately, black has Nd5, shutting down the attack on f7, followed by Be6 with harmonious development. This move lacks the necessary punch. } 11... Nd5 12. Qb3 Be6 $19) 11... Qd7?! { Further blocking in the development of the queenside. We have already seen the importance of avoiding moves that prevent the rest of the pieces from developing as early as the first game of the first chapter.
Black needs to be willing to part with some material in order to ease the pressure. Be6 instead would have lost a pawn with check to Bxe6 fxe6 Qxe6+ and is certainly not pretty. But at least in that line black is actually developing some pieces! } (11... Be6! 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qxe6+ Ne7 14. Nxe5 Rf8 15. Rfe1 Ng8 $10 { Disgusting to play in such a way, but at least black should hold. }) 12. dxe5 { Thematic. dxe5 opens up lines for the pieces, while recapturing with tempo. At this point in the study, I hope this capture was one of your top candidate moves.
Starting now, Morphy once more showcases how to use the initiative. Every single move from now until the end of the game is a forcing move in some way: either a check, capture, or threat. } (12. Nxe5! { Better the game continuation, although you had to see that Nxd4 can be met with Qg3! Play dxe5 instead for the game continuation. } 12... Nxd4! (12... Nxe5?! 13. dxe5 $16) 13. Qg3! $16 { Probably the move that Morphy missed. The threats of Nxd7, Qxg7, and Rfe1 are too much for black to handle. }) (12. Rae1? { Tempting, but after e4 black keeps the center closed. } 12... e4! $17) (12. Rad1?! { It is tempting to align with black's queen. Good instincts. Open the position up first for the game continuation. } 12... Na5! 13. Qb4 Nxc4 14. dxe5 c5! 15. Qxc4 Qe6! $17) (12. Rfe1? { Tempting, but after e4 black keeps the center closed. } 12... e4! $17) (12. Rfd1?! { It is tempting to align with black's queen. Good instincts. Open the position up first for the game continuation. } 12... Na5! 13. Qb4 Nxc4 14. dxe5 c5! 15. Qxc4 Qe6! $17) 12... Ne4 13. Rad1!? { Bringing all the boys to the party with tempo. } (13. e6! $15 { I love this move - blasting open the position while you have a lead in development and black's king remains in the center! Full credit for this move. Instead, bring all the boys to the party with Rad1 for the game continuation. }) (13. Rfd1? $19 { Oh no, your f2 pawn! }) (13. Rae1!? $15 { A logical way to bring all the boys to the party too. Play Rad1 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Rfe1?? { Oh no, your f2 pawn! } 13... Bxf2+! $19) 13... Nd4? { Morphy built up his position so far by developing his pieces to active squares, castling his king to safety, and seeking to open the position before black could castle. In contrast, black weakened their position by opening up the center and creating tension between the two armies while half of black's army is at home watching TV.
Dynamics favor the side with the more active pieces. There is already a tactical shot for white. Good luck! } (13... Qf5! $17) 14. Nxd4 (14. Rxd4?! { Similar to the game continuation but less forcing. Switch the move order instead! } 14... Bxd4 15. Nxd4 Nd2! $16 { The difference. Qxd4 is not forced. }) (14. e6? { It's tempting to blast open the position. But black's last move threatened your queen! In reality e6 does nothing but allow a queen trade - not something white wants to do. } 14... Nxb3 15. exd7+ Bxd7 16. Bxf7+! Kxf7 17. Rxd7+ Kg6 18. axb3 $15) 14... Bxd4 { Equal piece trades are usually bad for the side looking for dynamic play. With less pieces on the board, there is less firepower available to create threats. So why did Morphy play this way?
PRO TIP: Nothing beats a good move. The principles are concepts to help guide your thinking, not rules to be followed blindly. If you calculate a move wins, you should play it, regardless of if it breaks a principle or rule of thumb. Please double check your calculations before playing such a move though, as unprincipled play often backfires as we repeatedly see from Morphy's opponents!
The justification for trading these knights is purely based on calculation. Morphy sees a forcing continuation that wins f7 and forces black's king onto the dangerous d file. } 15. Rxd4! (15. Bxf7+?? { We don't want to sacrifice a piece in order to win a piece! Please recalculate your line after black responds with Qxf7. } 15... Qxf7 16. Qxf7+ Kxf7 17. Rxd4 Nc3 $19) (15. e6?! { Black has enough defenders on e6. There are more drastic measures available to white that break through to f7 successfully. } 15... fxe6 16. Bb2! Nc5 17. Qc2 e5 18. Rfe1 $16 { White had better but this does visually look like a Morphy - NN position. }) (15. Qd3? { Tempting. Yet after Nc3!, black holds the position together because of a timely check on e2. Look for moves that are more forcing! } 15... Nc3 16. Qxd4? (16. e6!? $10) 16... Qxd4 17. Rxd4 Be6! $17 { Ne2+ hangs over white, so there is no way to win material. }) 15... Qxd4 { Yes! The queen was overworked trying to defend both d4 and f7. Morphy is content to end up down a full rook just to keep the initiative going.
PRO TIP: The initiative is nothing more than the physical manifestation of one player championing their dynamic advantage. A good clue that you have the initiative is when your opponent has to abandon their plans in order to react to yours. } 16. Bxf7+ Kd8 { The king is forced to step onto the dangerous d file. White's DSB on a3 is certainly earning his rent money this game covering both f8 and e7! } 17. Rd1 { The Morphy move! Black deserves to lose immediately, but finds a few nice defensive moves from this difficult position to prolong the struggle. } 17... Nd2! { Punch, counterpunch! Not only does this move block the d file, it also threatens white's queen. Meanwhile, black still remains up a rook. What to do now? } 18. Qc2! { Nice job refusing to bow to black's threats. We're not interested in simply moving the queen anywhere and letting black wrestle the initiative from us. Qc2 saves the queen while introducing Rxd2 as a game-winning threat! } (18. Qb4?? { Oh no, your rook! Black has Nf3+ in the air, with a discovered check on your rook. } 18... Nf3+! 19. gxf3 Qxd1+ $19 { Who is pinning whom? }) (18. Rxd2?? { A forcing move, but there is no follow-up after black recaptures. Typically we want to pile pressure on pinned pieces, not trade them off immediately. } 18... Qxd2 $19) 18... Bd7! { Black blocks the d file, keeping the losses down to only a knight. } { [%cal Ge5e6] } 19. e6!? { Rather than cash in on the free knight, Morphy is interested in more! He wants to blast open the position even further. Dynamic chess at its finest. } 19... Ba4 { Punch, counterpunch. Punch, counterpunch. To Perrin's credit, he also refuses to roll over and die when faced with Morphy's blistering attack.
Unfortunately, we have already discussed how dynamic chess favors the side with the more active pieces. Black simply cannot keep up with white's threats in this position with both rooks stuck at home watching TV! } 20. Rxd2 { The beginning of a winning simplification. } (20. Qxd2!? $18 { An equally good simplification. Play Rxd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (20. e7+!? $18 { Another way to win. Play Rxd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (20. Qxa4?? $19 { Oh no, your queen! }) 20... Bxc2 { Forced. } 21. Rxd4+ (21. e7+!? $18 { Play Rxd4+ first instead for the game continuation. }) 21... Kc8 { White has ended up in an endgame down the exchange. Was Morphy's combination faulty? } 22. e7! { Excellent job. Black has no way to prevent e8=Q next, and so they are not truly up the exchange. In fact, white will be up a piece once the dust settles. } (22. Rd2? { A one-move threat. You are just forcing the bishop to g6, where it wants to go anyway. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 22... Bg6 23. f4!? $14) (22. Rc4? { A one-move threat. You are just forcing the bishop to g6, where it wants to go anyway. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 22... Bg6 23. Bd6 c6 $14) 22... b6 { Importantly, Ba4 to prevent the pawn from queening would have been met with Rxa4. } (22... Ba4?! 23. Rxa4 $18) 23. e8=Q+ (23. Rd8+?? { The king and rook cover the d8 square! } 23... Rxd8 24. exd8=Q+ Kxd8 $19) 23... Rxe8 24. Bxe8 { The dust has settled and white is now up a piece.
PRO TIP: All-out attacks need not end in checkmate. Often the attacking side is able to win a decisive amount of material instead. Indeed this is one example of a broader reality in chess. Dynamic advantages often are cashed in and transformed into static advantages, and vice versa. } 24... Kb7 { Morphy's next move cleanly simplifies the game further. } 25. Bc6+! Kxc6 { The bishop must be captured, attracting the king to the vulnerable c6 square. What is the point of the bishop sacrifice? } 26. Rc4+ { The secret to good technique is good calculation! These simple 3-ply tactics form the backbone of any chess player's arsenal to convert a winning position into a win. } 26... Kb5 27. Rxc2 $18 { After a nice fight, and out of respect for his opponent, Perrin resigned this position rather than ask Morphy to prove the win. If you are curious to see how to convert from here, check out one of my OTB games where I had a similar position: https://lichess.org/study/Pz8V86EC/zzD4Xpkz#61
To utilize the initiative, white did not just play a random sequence of forcing moves. Morphy chose forcing moves that improved white's position or forced black to somehow worsen their position.
It's worth noting that even when you do everything right and achieve a crushing position, your opponent always has resources. They get to play too. Still, the initiative is a useful tool to keep them on their back foot and force through your agenda. } 1-0


[Event "Odds Game (Nb1)"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Denis Julien"]
