[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ There is a lot to unpack from this chapter. Knowing when to make a threat vs develop a piece... appreciating the DDD moments when they show up... mastering the initiative... calculating precisely in order to knockout your opponent... Indeed, mastering many of these fundamental skills will take time across hundreds of your own games.

We will continue to hone these skills throughout the rest of the Morphy games. Now let's summarize this chapter on blasting open the position while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board.

* When you have a lead in development, blast open the position. Your developed pieces will only be able to generate game-winning threats once you open up lines for them. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { * When your opponent's king is stuck in the center, you should look for a pawn break (a pawn move that introduces tension with an opponent's pawn) that open up files or diagonals towards the king. Indeed, a timely central pawn break is the most common way to open up the position. } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 exf4 { * Once you have attained a decisive development disparity, you should be looking for forcing moves, tactical shots, and general fireworks to open the position and go after your opponent. The decisive development disparity (DDD, pronounced "triple-D") moment occurs when there are king safety issues while the gap in development will not get any larger. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 3. Nf3 g5 { * Do not open the position when you are behind in development. Opening up the center before you are castled is especially unwise. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 4. Bc4 Bg7 { * The factors that determine a chess position's evaluation broadly fall under two categories: static and dynamic.
Static advantages are those that persist and don't depend on the move-by-move variations. Examples include extra material and a better pawn structure.
Dynamic advantages are those that are time-dependent in that they will disappear if not utilized immediately. Use it or lose it! Examples include a lead in development, a king stuck in the center, or more active pieces. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 5. O-O h6 { * Dynamic advantages are often more important than static advantages, especially when they involve king safety concerns. You can have all the material in the world - you still lose the game if your king gets mated! } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 6. c3 d6 { * The side with the less active pieces usually cannot seek dynamic counterplay - dynamics favor the side with more active pieces. } { [%cal Gd1b3] } 7. Qb3 Qe7 { * Owning the center has both static and dynamic advantages. Statically, the center is strong because it robs your opponent's pieces of central squares, carves out space for your pieces to comfortably sit behind, and grants your pieces more mobility and maneuverability. Dynamically, the center is strong because at any moment the center can push forward, scattering your opponent's pieces to the wind. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 8. d4 c6 { * One of the most common ways to push a dynamic advantage is to gain the initiative. In an open position, when you have more active pieces that can naturally generate threats, using the initiative forces a less active opponent backwards or passive.
* The initiative is nothing more than the physical manifestation of one player championing their dynamic advantage. } { [%cal Gc1d2] } 9. Bd2 Nd7 { * Sacrificing to remove a key defender should be a foundational tool in your toolkit of how to push the initiative. } { [%cal Ga1e1] } 10. Rae1 Nb6 { * The opening principles (developing, center, king safety) apply to your opponents too. Playing moves that prevent your opponent from making the principled moves they want to is a winning strategy as well! } { [%cal Gc4d3] } 11. Bd3 Bg4 { * Morphy does not make threats that can be conveniently defended, for instance by the opponent developing a piece to a good square. Don't force your opponent to make good moves!
* Parrying your opponent's threats with a constructive move that you wanted to play anyway is often an excellent response. It's best to avoid losing time when possible. } { [%cal Ga2a4] } 12. a4 Bxf3 { * When debating between several candidate moves, play the most adaptable option first. That is, you should start with the move that improves your position across the widest range of futures. Then, when it's time to play less clear candidates, you give yourself more flexibility to respond to your opponent. } { [%cal Gf1f3] } 13. Rxf3 Nd7?! { * Three tempi are typically worth one pawn.
* Don't play half-developing moves when there are more active options available instead. Active pieces win games. Passive pieces lose ground. } { [%cal Gb3b7] } 14. Qxb7 Rb8 { * Sometimes simple is good. Especially when you're in a dominant position, do not complicate the position. } { [%cal Gb7c6] } 15. Qxc6 Rxb2 { * Don't get fancy - recapture your pieces! If you don't get in the habit of recapturing when your opponent captures your pieces, you will run out of pieces quickly. The exception to recapturing is when your threats are truly more important. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } 16. e5!? Rxd2?? { * One of the best ways to learn how to play an opening is to play through many master games in that opening. } { [%cal Gc6c8] } (16... dxe5! 17. Bc1 Rb6! $17 { White is attacking with all the pieces but there is no immediate win. }) 17. Qc8+ Qd8 { * The primary factor both sides should evaluate when considering a queen trade is king safety. The reason is simple: it becomes significantly harder to execute an attack and take advantage of an unsafe king once the queens come off the board. } { [%cal Ge5d6] } 18. exd6+ Be5 { * You can learn all the chess strategy there is to learn... but the skill of spotting basic tactics for you and your opponent will always be the most important deciding factor in your games. } { [%cal Ge1e5] } 19. Rxe5+ Nxe5 { * The secret to good technique is good calculation! When Grandmasters say, "the rest is a matter of technique," that conversion still requires precise calculation. } { [%cal Gd3b5] } 20. Bb5+ $18 { (Black resigned in this position... let's continue making moves to see why) } 20... Nd7 { * Nothing beats a good move. The principles are concepts to help guide your thinking, not rules to be followed blindly. If you calculate a move wins, you should play it, regardless of if it breaks a principle or rule of thumb. } { [%cal Gb5d7] } 21. Bxd7+ Kf8 { * Stronger opponents don't just roll over and resign. They force us to play more precisely. The principled moves that build up the position require effort. The opponent's threats require attention. The killing blows require calculation. } { [%cal Gc8d8] } 22. Qxd8+ $18 { * All-out attacks need not end in checkmate. Often the attacking side is able to win a decisive amount of material instead.
For more resources taking you through moments where a lead in development justifies blasting open the position, check out:
* ChessCoach Andras https://youtu.be/WjZlziodyUk
* Marc Esserman https://youtu.be/supEFUS4Zg8
* John Bartholomew https://youtu.be/DA5HRUGT8ek
* Daniel Naroditsky https://youtu.be/5o8LUjvHFZA
* John Bartholomew https://youtu.be/HQk9UaXya1g
* Jesse Kraai's course https://www.chessable.com/mastering-time-in-chess/course/277570/ } 1-0


