{ Chapter III: Thwart a wild queen

This next chapter will focus on how to punish an opponent who is obsessed with creating threats by moving their queen all over the board.

Beginners are often enamored moving the queen out early because she can attack so many different things. Likewise, beginners are scared of early queen moves because you have to have a firm grip on the board to avoid losing unnecessary material to her.

However, Morphy will show us that developing the queen early is often overrated since she can be attacked by the other side's pieces as they develop to natural squares. Therefore, time is the crucial reason that makes early queen moves a poor choice! }
 *


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1849.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "James McConnell"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C40"]
[Opening "King's Pawn Game: McConnell Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Keeping a grip on the board"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/ad2INDUm"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We join a game between a 12 year old Morphy and his family friend growing up in New Orleans. James McConnell shows himself to be a true amateur this game by obsessing about moving his queen as much as possible. }
1. e4 { Best by test. That's right, no more arrows for Morphy's first move - I know you already know it! } 1... e5 2. Nf3 (2. f4!? $15 { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (2. Bc4!? $10 { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) 2... Qf6?! { Black develops and defends the e5 pawn. On the surface, this appears to be a sensible option. "The queen is the strongest piece, right? So why shouldn't I bring out my strongest piece as soon as possible?"
It is precisely because the queen is the most valuable piece that this logic backfires.
PRO TIP: Don't develop your queen early. If your opponent's pieces can make normal improving moves while attacking her, you have to respond to those threats, thus losing time. } { [%cal Gb1c3] } 3. Nc3 { A developing move that white might make regardless of black's queen position. Note that Morphy prioritizes this specific developing move because Nd5 soon would centralize the knight with tempo on black's queen. } 3... c6?! { Not a developing move. Black was already feeling the heat of Nd5, a double-attack on the queen and c7.
Stopping this threat with c6 though falls for a sunk-cost fallacy. Black tries to justify the queen's position and avoid losing time with the queen by instead losing time with the pawn... } 4. d4! { Yes! This central pawn break is desirable even if the queen wasn't on f6. But because of the queen's poor position, the newly introduced "threat" to develop the DSB to g5 with tempo makes this move even stronger.
Note how energetically Morphy is playing. White does not currently have a lead in development yet, but the promise of gaining tempi against black's queen all but guarantees that white will have a lead in development soon. } (4. Bc4!? $16 { A logical developing move. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. d3?! $14 { Why are you blocking in your LSB? White has the right to claim more from this d pawn due to black's poor play. }) (4. Be2?! $14 { A half-developing move. This does not try to punish black's play in any way. }) 4... exd4?! { Another step in the wrong direction. We have already seen that it is not correct to open the position while behind in development. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } (4... d6!? 5. Bg5 Qg6 6. dxe5 $16) 5. e5!? { Bg5 first would have been more principled. After Bg5 Qg6!? Qxd4, white has four pieces out to black's one.
With e5, Morphy hopes to later use this pawn to spearhead an attack. This move comes with a threat but doesn't maximize white's lead in development. } (5. Bg5! { The strongest move. A developing move with tempo on the queen! } 5... Qg6 6. Qxd4 $16) 5... Qg6? { Again, black places the queen on a square that can be attacked by white's pieces. If she is relying on the pressure on g2 to prevent any LSB developing move, she will be in for a rude awakening... } 6. Bd3! { Yes! Further tempo against the queen. White should not be scared of dropping g2 because white already has a massive lead in development and welcomes more open lines and more tempi against the queen. } (6. Qxd4!? $16 { Excellent job developing and recapturing the pawn. Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. Nxd4!? $14 { Improving the knight and recapturing the pawn is a reasonable choice, although it does not seek to punish black's wild queen "strategy." Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. Nh4? { We do not want to make aimless threats against the queen. Only gain a tempo on her if you are somehow improving the position. Is the knight better on h4 than on f3? } 6... Qe6 $10) 6... Qxg2 { Black doubles down on their wild queen "strategy" by snagging the g pawn with tempo on white's rook. } 7. Rg1! { Nice counterattack! White develops the rook to a newly open file with tempo.
Beginners find many reasons to be afraid of positions like this as white: "I'm scared I'll lose something to this wild queen", "Now I can't castle kingside", or "I don't like losing pawns".
Morphy will show us how to quell these concerns throughout the games in this chapter. Let us use this game to discuss this first fear of black's queen becoming Pac-Man and eating all of our pieces.
PRO TIP: Having a grip on the board is a fundamental skill to improving as a chess player. By having a grip on the board, I mean constantly tracking which pieces are defended or not, which pieces are attacked by the opponent, what squares are under our control, and what checks are in the position. This grip on the position is sometimes called "board vision."
Morphy was a master at board vision, even blindfolded. In this position, he clearly knew that all of his pieces and pawns were defended. With a firm grip on the board, fears about what the g2 queen will capture next are replaced with confidence that black's queen is all bark and no bite. The queen on g2 is more of a liability than an asset. } (7. Rf1?? { A horribly passive move that also loses tactically: your knight on c3 is still hanging. You just lost your grip on the board! } 7... dxc3 $19) 7... Qh3 { We have already seen how a pawn is often worth three tempi. Here, white already has four pieces out to black's one, many open lines for the pieces, and further promise to gain even more tempi against black's wild queen.
The evaluation is no longer "equal." The evaluation is no longer "white is better." The evaluation is "white is completely winning - how do I crush this guy?" } 8. Rg3 { The rook is better placed and defended on g3. Again, with a firm grip on the board, Morphy sees that retreating the queen is black's only option.
For the rest of this game, Morphy takes over the initiative. White's lead in development is too massive. } (8. Nxd4?! { A free pawn, but Morphy was not interested in losing h2. } 8... Qxh2 9. Nf3 Qh3 $16) (8. Ne4!? $16 { A nice centralizing move. The e4 knight pairs well with the e5 pawn. Play Rg3 instead for the game continuation. }) (8. Bf1? $14 { We only want to gain tempo on the queen with improving moves. Is the bishop better placed on f1 than d3? }) (8. Ne2?? { Oh no, your f3 knight. } 8... Qxf3 $19) (8. Na4? $10 { Respond to black's threat while sidelining the knight? There is no world where this is a good move! }) (8. Ng5? { A one-move threat against black's queen. After Qxh2 with tempo on white's rook, the knight needs to return to f3. Remember - we only want to gain tempo on the queen with improving moves! }) (8. Nb1? $15 { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Morphy would never passively retreat his knight like this. }) 8... Qh5 { Morphy wants to win the d4 pawn without hanging either h2 or e5. In this position, he comes up with a forcing sequence against black's queen to make that a reality. } { [%cal Gg3g5] } 9. Rg5 Qh3 { [%cal Gd3f1] } 10. Bf1 { A firm grip on the board allows us to see that black's queen must retreat to the e6 square. } 10... Qe6 { [%cal Gf3d4] } 11. Nxd4 Qe7 { Tempo, tempo, tempo. Once more, Morphy ensures that all of his pieces are defended and that he controls any active square black's queen could jump to.
PRO TIP: Don't make aimless threats against a wild queen. You should focus on threats that simultaneously improve your position. } { [%cal Gc3e4] } 12. Ne4 h6?! { Black tries to force white to react to a threat in a position where black is behind in development by five tempi? Not likely to work out for black. We already know that the dynamics will favor white due to Morphy's lead in development. } { [%cal Gd4f5] } 13. Nf5?? { A rare Morphy blunder?? We can excuse him this time because he played this casual game while only 12 years old. But this blunder is a direct consequence of Morphy losing his grip on the board.
PRO TIP: Before getting excited and playing an attacking move, due your due diligence! Take a few seconds to confirm you are not missing a crucial check, capture, or threat in the position. Keeping a grip on the board requires constantly refreshing which squares are under your control in the position and which are not.
Before clicking "Next," can you find a winning move for black? } (13. Nd6+! $18 { An improvement over Morphy! Nice job coordinating your pieces with tempo. } 13... Kd8 14. Rf5 g6?! 15. Nxf7+ $18) (13. Rf5! $18 { An improvement over Morphy! Nice job coordinating your pieces with tempo. }) 13... Qe6?? { Whew. Black is only human and slips up too. Qb4+ would have been a double attack: the knight on e4 and the rook on g5 were both hanging.
After Morphy's opponent fails to capitalize on Morphy's rare blunder, the rest of the game is smooth sailing given white's massive lead in development. } { [%cal Gf5d6] } (13... Qb4+! $19 { Both the e4 knight and g5 rook are hanging. Black wins at least a piece. }) 14. Nfd6+ Bxd6 15. Nxd6+ (15. exd6?? { Oh no, your knight! } 15... Qxe4+ $19) 15... Kd8 { At this point, black's king is on the run, their queen is the only piece developed, and their queenside is not developing for the foreseeable future.
Keep using the initiative to blow black off the board! } 16. Bc4 (16. Bh3?! $18 { Oh no your bishop! }) (16. Rxg7?? $16 { You just lost your grip on the board! This rook is undefended, and after Qxe5+ will be picked off next. }) (16. Qg4? { We have already seen that king safety is the determining factor behind whether or not we should queen trade. Let's kill black's king instead of offering such a lame trade! } 16... hxg5 17. Qxe6 fxe6 18. Nf7+ Kc7 19. Nxh8 $14) (16. Qh5? { A tactically suspicious move. Are you really pinning the h pawn? } 16... hxg5 17. Qxh8 Qxe5+ 18. Be3 Qxd6 19. Qxg8+ Kc7 $14) (16. Rh5?! $16 { Fine, but not a move that furthers the initiative. Look for better. }) (16. Rf5!? $18 { Probably the best square for the rook if we had to move it. Play Bc4 instead for the game continuation. }) 16... Qe7 { White's pieces continue to swarm black's position with tempo. Keep up the initiative! } 17. Nxf7+ (17. Rxg7?? $16 { You just lost your grip on the board! This rook is undefended, and after Qxe5+ will be picked off next. }) 17... Kc7 { Black's king tries to vacate towards the queenside where there are less white pieces swarming the position. Morphy shows his opponent that there is no safe haven there either. } { [%cal Gd1d6] } 18. Qd6+!! { The principles are concepts to help guide your thinking, not rules to be followed blindly. Of course, Qd6+ offers a queen trade in the middle of a blistering attack and is therefore unprincipled.
But nothing beats a good move! Morphy calculated a forced mate in 5 from this position kicking off with this queen trade. } 18... Qxd6 { Knowing that this position is now forced mate, can you calculate the mate in 5 from this position? } 19. exd6+ (19. Nxd6?? { You lost your grip on the board! Your rook has been attacked for many moves. This recapture does not create any threat that overrides black's ability to take your rook. } 19... hxg5 $17) 19... Kb6 { Only legal move... } { [%cal Gc1e3] } 20. Be3+ c5 { Only legal move... } { [%cal Ge3c5] } 21. Bxc5+ (21. Rxc5! { Also a nice move similar to those we will explore later in Chapter VI: King Hunt. Black's king is not allowed a retreat square! } 21... Na6!? 22. Nd8! Nxc5 (22... h5 23. Rb5#) 23. b4! h5 24. Bxc5#) 21... Ka5 { Kc6 would have been met with Nd8#! } { [%cal Gg5g3] } (21... Kc6!? 22. Nd8#) 22. Rg3! { Only now that Morphy has set up a mating net does he retreat his rook! White can pre-move Ra3# next. } 22... b5 23. Ra3# { Ever the artist, Morphy finds an aesthetic mate to cap off a nice king hunt.
Black made way too many queen moves and never prioritized developing the rest of their army this game. In this final position, note that all of black's pieces are at home watching TV. Indeed, the furthest "developed" piece is the king!
In just one game, Morphy shows us how to punish an opponent who is overexcited about moving their queen. You need a basic understanding of time, a firm grip on the board, a strong desire to find improving moves with tempo against the queen, and a good sense of using the initiative. } 1-0


[Event "Paris"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1863.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Jules Arnous de Riviere"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C51"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, Morphy Attack"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Ping-pong"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/jT5dqnig"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ After playing through one of Morphy's first recorded games, let us now turn to one of his last. In this game, an already retired Morphy plays a casual match against a French master in Paris. Once again, we see how Morphy crushes an opponent who is trigger-happy with their queen.

No arrows in the opening! We revisit the Evans Gambit line we have already seen several times this study. }
1. e4 e5 { Now for move 2 of the Evans. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { Now for move 3 of the Evans. } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { Now kick off the Evans! } 4. b4 Bxb4 { What is the point of the Evans? } 5. c3 Bc5 6. O-O!? { We have already seen time and time again that d4! exd4 O-O! first is the most precise way to play. } (6. d4! $14 { Slightly more precise than Morphy's continuation: O-O. After d4 exd4, O-O!, white will either enter a true gambit or play cxd4 next achieving a broad center. }) 6... d6 7. d4 exd4 8. cxd4 Bb6 { We have seen this position several times before. Is now the time to strike? } 9. Nc3 { Correct. We need to still develop the pieces before we have the right to blow open the position due to a lead in development. } 9... Qf6? { Previously, we have seen that Nf6 was a mistake that was well met by e5! blowing open the position. Bg4 remains the most dependable option for black. In this game, black tries Qf6, developing the queen prematurely.
How best to continue? } (9... Bg4 $10) 10. Nd5! { Centralizing the knight with tempo on the queen. This is exactly the type of time-gaining move that proves the "rule": don't develop the queen early. } (10. e5! { A beautiful concept. Even with the queen on f6 (instead of a knight), opening up the position immediately works out well for white! Play Nd5 instead for the game continuation. } 10... dxe5 11. Nd5! Qd8 { White is crushing. One sample line: } 12. Bg5!? f6 13. Nxe5! fxg5?? 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Nxg6 $18) (10. Be3?! $14 { Playable, but passive. Why develop and defend when you can develop and attack? }) (10. Bg5?! { It's principled to develop with tempo on the queen. Unfortunately, after Qg6, the queen is now out of range of white's pieces for good, and the combination of h6 and Bh3 are coming. This is a fine move, but there is better. Find another move that gains time against the queen instead. } 10... Qg6 $14) 10... Qg6?! { A further step in the wrong direction. Black's queen remains developed, but also remains within range of white's knights.
Black should have admitted their earlier mistake and retreated the queen to d8, where she is out of reach of all of white's pieces. } { [%cal Gd5f4] } (10... Qd8 $16) 11. Nf4 { Tagging the queen again. From d5, the knight is on its best square but doesn't control the center. From f4, the knight better controls the center. Is Nf4 then strictly an improvement for white? Not really. Rb1 or Re1, just developing the rooks, were equally strong. } 11... Qf6 { This was the only square that avoided losing the queen. Qf6 also pressures the d4 pawn, limiting white's options. Finally, Qf6 is also a tacit draw offer from black. "Do you want to repeat the position three times, Mr. Morphy?" } 12. e5! { Fantastic! This is the DDD moment. White had to act immediately so as to avoid losing time defending d4. Meanwhile, white has a massive lead in development, and black's king remains stuck in the center.
As we have seen before, e5 comes with a fork on the d pawn and piece on f6, so the position will open in every line. } (12. Nd5!? $16 { Of course, this move remains fine as long as we don't repeat one more time. }) (12. Re1!? { A reasonable developing move. But what are you doing about Nxd4? } 12... Nxd4 13. e5! Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 dxe5 15. Bb2! $16) (12. Ba3?? { Oh no, your knight! } 12... Qxf4 $19) (12. Bb2?? { Oh no, your knight! } 12... Qxf4 $19) (12. Be3?! { A reasonable developing move to defend the center. But do we need to defend the center? Black doesn't deserve to be able to make a threat we have to respond to.
White is the one with the more active pieces! Let's use those pieces to grab the initiative. } 12... Nge7 $14) (12. Rb1?! { A reasonable developing move. But what are you doing about Nxd4? } 12... Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qb3 $16) (12. Nh5!? $16 { Of course, this move remains fine as long as we don't repeat the position three times after black plays Qg6. }) 12... dxe5 { Black captures on e5, opening the center slightly. } { [%cal Gd4e5] } 13. dxe5 { Recapturing with tempo. Of course, the e pawn is immune to capture due to an eventual pin on the e file, winning their queen.
White had several good moves instead of this immediate recapture now that the position has opened. Indeed, white's massive lead in development and black's unsafe king ensure that any dynamic complications should work out for white. } (13. Re1!? Nge7 14. dxe5 $16) 13... Qf5?! { Once more, the queen is on an accessible square. This is almost an inevitability though with white's pieces swarming the center.
How best to push the initiative? No hints this move! } 14. e6! { Another DDD moment! The e file remains closed to white's heavy pieces until we open the center fully. } (14. Bd3!? { Tempo on the queen, but is this improving the bishop? After Qd7, for instance, how would you make progress? } 14... Qd7 15. e6! $16) (14. Qe2!? $16 { A sensible developing move that deserves full credit. Not what Morphy played. }) (14. Re1?! { A developing move, but after Be6 our rook looks silly on the e file. } 14... Be6 $16) (14. Ba3?? { Oh no, your knight! } 14... Qxf4 $19) (14. Qb3? { Not a threat on f7 because f7 is already defended. This move just walks into a Na5 fork. } 14... Na5 $14) (14. Rb1?? { Oh no, your rook! } 14... Qxb1 $15) (14. Qd5? { Directly walks into Nge7 with tempo. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! } 14... Nge7 15. Qd1 $14) (14. Nh4?! $16 { Doesn't really improve the position, since our knight is just sidelined on h4 after the queen moves. }) (14. Bb2?? { Oh no, your knight! } 14... Qxf4 $19) (14. Nd4?? { Oh no, your knight! } 14... Bxd4 $19) 14... f6 { Keeping the center closed must be the best option for black. Unfortunately, black's kingside knight is now deprived of its favorite square: f6. } { [%cal Gf3h4] } 15. Nh4 { Not the only option. Indeed, this move gains tempo on the queen but potentially misplaces the knight on h4. The point of this move (beyond gaining a tempo on black's queen) is actually about developing white's queen to h5 now that f6 has weakened the e8-h5 diagonal towards black's king.
Remember: we should not make aimless threats against a wild queen. Focus on threats that simultaneously improve the position. } 15... Qc5 { This poor queen has already been ping-ponged across the board while Morphy improves his position. However, for once, black is the one making a threat!
White would love to play Be3, developing with further tempo against this queen. But black's attack on the undefended LSB on c4 supposedly prevents white from playing such a move. } 16. Be3!! { "Oh no, my bishop!" Morphy saw that Qxc4? is met with Qh5+! g6, Nhxg6! absolutely destroying black's king shelter and simultaneously winning material. Calculating such a line truly requires a firm grip of the board!
PRO TIP: When your opponent supposedly prevents you from making a move you want to make, ask yourself the Shankland question: "What if I do it anyway?" This question, popularized by US Chess Champion, GM Sam Shankland, reminds you to push past first impressions and possibly refute your opponent's faux threat. Pushing your own agenda instead of bowing to your opponent's threats is how you take the initiative.
Now look beyond the tactics that prove this move is not refuted by Qxc4. Be3 is nothing more than a developing move with further tempo against black's queen. Morphy continues improving the position with tempo! } (16. Ba3!! $18 { Sick move. Even more fantastic than Morphy's move! Play Be3 for the game continuation. }) (16. Re1?? { Oh no, my f2 pawn! } 16... Qxf2+ 17. Kh1 Qxh4 $10) (16. Bb2?! $16 { A nice idea. Find the same idea but with tempo. }) (16. Bd2? $16 { What does this half-developing move even accomplish? }) (16. Rb1?!) 16... Qg5 { Black's poor queen continues to be ping-ponged around the board by white's pieces. } { [%cal Gh4f3] } (16... Qxc4?! 17. Qh5+ g6!? (17... Kd8?! 18. Rad1+ $18) (17... Kf8?? 18. Qf7#) (17... Ke7?? 18. Qf7+ Kd6 19. Rad1+ $18) 18. Nhxg6 $18) 17. Nf3!? Qa5?! { Another volley of ping-pong. } { [%cal Ge3b6] } (17... Qf5! 18. Nh4 Qg5 19. Nd5!! { The real way to make progress. } 19... Qxh4 20. Bxb6! cxb6 21. Nc7+ $18 { With a deadly fork. }) 18. Bxb6 Qxb6?! { Developing the rook with axb6 would have been more natural and stronger than the game continuation. However, axb6 allows Nd5 with an unavoidable fork on c7.
Black's Qxb6 avoids losing c7, at the cost of two more tempi with the queen. Black is behind so many tempi that such greed is simply inconceivable. } (18... axb6!? 19. Nd5 Kf8 20. Nxc7 Nge7 $18 { Black can at least kick around here. }) 19. Nd5 { The most adaptable move in the position. In every line, we want our knight centralized on d5. Bonus points because it comes with tempo on their queen and pressures c7.
Perhaps our rook will develop to the b file. Perhaps it will remain useful on the a file. Likewise, our queen has many options. Because it is not clear yet where they would be optimally placed, we should start with the more adaptable Nd5. We will develop the remaining pieces once we have more information. } (19. Rb1!? $18 { A fine move. Play Nd5 instead for the game continuation. }) 19... Qa5 { The only square to prevent the fork on c7. } { [%cal Gf3d2] } 20. Nd2!? { Not the only way to win. The threat is Nb3, fatally kicking the queen away from the fork on c7. } 20... Nd4 { Black desperately "prevents" Nb3. } { [%cal Gd2b3] } 21. Nb3! { Morphy asks the Shankland question again! "What if I do it anyway?"
Once you ask the Shankland question, you quickly realize that black has not prevented Nb3. In fact, white would love to activate the rook with tempo on the queen after Nxb3 axb3. } 21... Nxb3 { Forced. } 22. axb3! { The poor queen is now getting ping-ponged by white's major pieces too... } (22. Qxb3?! $18 { Develops the queen, but there is a more forcing recapture. }) (22. Bxb3?! $16 { There is a more forcing recapture. }) 22... Qc5 { Black is doing everything they can to defend against Nxc7. But losing a million tempi with the queen has consequences.
Practically every active move for white now wins. Black simply has no developed army that can contest white's deadly threats to the king. } { [%cal Gd1h5] } 23. Qh5+ { Morphy's idea with this last check is to align his queen opposite black's. The actual threat now is Nf6+, winning the queen. } 23... Kd8 { With Kd8, black escapes the fire only to end up in the frying pan. } 24. Rad1 $18 { Bringing the boys to the party! Every discovered check is both winning the queen and checkmating the king. Black resigned rather than prolong the inevitable here in a position that is technically a forced mate in 10.
Notice how in the final position, every white piece is contributing. Meanwhile, every black piece is sitting at home watching TV.
This is the ultimate price for bringing the queen out too early: the opponent gets free tempi and the initiative. Morphy developed his entire army with tempo against the queen, while black never had a chance to breathe or the time for their army to contribute. } (24. Rfd1!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Rad1 instead for the game continuation. }) (24. e7+? $16 { Develops black's knight while not improving the position. }) (24. Qf7!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Rad1 instead for the game continuation. }) 1-0


[Event "Odds Game (Ra1)"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Alphonse Perrin"]
[Result "1-0"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "I have two knights. Ones for each of ya."]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/Fs5PohiF"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Morphy's opponent this game was an amateur player from New York. In fact, we already saw Morphy crush his older brother in "Fighting for the initiative" ( https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/BXNQYmeL ) while down a knight. Since the younger brother was even weaker, Morphy spotted him a full rook.

We know the drill: immediate aggression is called for to avoid white being "just" down a rook.

This game is a step up in difficulty from the last two. } { [%csl Ra1] }
1. e4 { Best by test... in odds games! } 1... e5 2. f4 (2. Nf3!? { Play f4 instead for the game continuation. }) 2... exf4 { The King's Gambit... accepted? Black is already up a rook. There is no need to get greedy and lose time in the opening! } 3. Nf3 (3. Bc4!? { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Nh3!? { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. h4? $19 { A horrible move that wastes time purely to avoid Qh4. We should be playing good moves, not bad ones. }) 3... d5! { An excellent choice by black. d5 develops and strikes in the center before white has a lead in development. } { [%cal Ge4d5] } 4. exd5 Qxd5?! { A first step in the wrong direction. Of course, the correct choice was Nf6, so that the knight could recapture the pawn without losing a tempo. } 5. Nc3 { Developing with a threat. Textbook Morphy play. } (5. Bc4?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 5... Qxc4 $19) (5. d4!? { Another reasonable way to play. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (5. Qe2+? $19 { A poor check because black can conveniently block this check while developing. All you are accomplishing is blocking your LSB. }) (5. c4? { Not a developing move. This one-move threat against the queen does not improve our position, and so should be avoided even if it gains a tempo. } 5... Qe4+ 6. Be2 Qxb1 $19) 5... Qe6+?! { A second step in the wrong direction. The queen could have avoided further tempi on d8, a5, or h5 instead. } { [%cal Ge1f2] } 6. Kf2 { It might feel like black's check has achieved something by taking away white's castling rights. However, white should not fear losing castling rights by moving the king. What is the true point behind castling? Castling is all about getting the king to safety and developing the heavy pieces.
We have already seen that king safety is exclusively measured by how easily the king can come under fire. In this position, with so many bodyguards around the king on f2 (and a potential d4 pawn to block any checks on the diagonal), the king on f2 is totally safe!
Moreover, this king move is actually a developing move for white's h1 rook. White already threatens Bb5+ followed by Re1, winning the queen!
Therefore, black has once again lost a tempo with the queen. Kf2 was an improving move, while Qe6 was not. } 6... Qf6?! { Another queen move? On f6 it still runs into an eventual Nd5 or Ne4. } 7. Bc4 { The eventual tempi against black's queen with Nd5 or Ne4 are inevitable, but white still has many pieces not playing yet that must be developed first.
PRO TIP: Punishing a wild queen does not mean hyper-fixating on her, going out of your way to attack her, or attempting to trap her with every move. The correct way to punish a wild queen is to gain a few tempi on her, giving you a lead in development. It's already a success to play normal, principled chess, up a few tempi. } (7. d4!? $19 { Equally good to the game. Play Bc4 for the game continuation. }) (7. Ne4?! { This move hits harder after white has more development. } 7... Qb6+ 8. d4 Be6 $19) (7. Nd5?! { This move hits harder after white has more development. } 7... Qd6! $19) (7. Qe1+?! $19 { An unnecessary check that doesn't improve white's position. }) (7. Qe2+? $19 { Blocking in the LSB? White has much stronger developing moves. }) (7. Bb5+?! $19 { After c6, the bishop will just get kicked backwards. }) (7. Bd3? $19 { There is no reason to block the d pawn, making it harder to eventually develop the DSB. }) (7. Be2? $19 { A passive, half-developing move. The only purpose of this move is to block the e file from white's pieces! }) 7... c6?! { Black prevents Nd5 but falls even further behind in development. } 8. Ne4 { Centralizing the knight with tempo on the queen should be a prime candidate move. Yet Re1+ improved a piece not yet playing with check. Re1+ was the more adaptable candidate move, and indeed was slightly stronger.
Ne4 at least has the benefit of being perfectly on-theme for this chapter! } (8. Re1+! $17 { A better move than Morphy's. Indeed, this is the most adaptable move in the position. }) 8... Qf5?! { The queen was hit, but once more black chooses a suboptimal square. Placing the king and queen a knight's fork distance away from each other walks into tactics.
Black should have admitted their mistake and retreated the queen to d8, where at least she is out of range of white's pieces. Losing four tempi with the queen for nothing is depressing, but nevertheless the lesser evil. } (8... Qd8!? $19) 9. Re1 (9. d4!? $17 { Equally playable because the knight is taboo. Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. d3!? $17 { Developing the DSB is sensible. Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Nd4?! $19 { You're playing with the pretty pieces here. A hallmark of Morphy's play is that he involves all of the pieces when attacking. }) 9... Be6 { Black desperately blocks the e file to avoid a killer discovered check. At first glance, this move appears to come with a threat on the c4 bishop too. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 10. d4 { "Oh no, my bishop!" Of course the LSB should not be captured as long as white has a discovered check on the open e file. Nd6+ is a royal fork that black must prevent at all costs.
This is another example of Morphy asking the Shankland question, "what if I do it anyway?" } 10... Be7 { Black shores up the e file even further, but Morphy spots a cute idea. } { [%cal Gf3g5] } (10... Bxc4?? 11. Nd6+ Kd8 12. Nxf5 $18) 11. Nfg5! { "Oh no, my knight!" Morphy now is "hanging" two minor pieces. Neither can be taken without allowing the royal fork Nd6+.
Once you look past the spectacular tactics that Morphy is relying on, it's worth noting that white's last few moves by themselves are nothing spectacular. White is simply improving the position of the pieces and starting to generate threats. Such improving moves are fundamental to gaining the initiative. } 11... Nd7 { Black, to their credit, ignores both of the hanging pieces, and gets on with developing. Black is only one move away from castling queenside to safety... } { [%cal Gg5f7] } (11... Bxg5?? 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. Nxf5 $18) (11... Bxc4?? 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. Nxf5 $18) 12. Nxf7! { "Oh no, my everything!" This is an inspired sacrifice, even though black has a way to bail out. The main point is that every capture on f7 walks into a deadly combination of Nd6+ and Bxe6. Another crucial point is that for one move, black's king is prevented from castling queenside.
Indeed, we have repeatedly seen that a sacrifice is a foundational tool in pushing the initiative. } 12... Ngf6? { Finally, black cracks while rushing to evacuate the king to the kingside. Check the PGN at the end of the game by clicking "Analysis board" to see how black could have fended off Morphy's attack.
What tactic did black miss? } (12... Qxf7! { The best capture, even though it looks scary. } 13. Nd6+ Bxd6 14. Bxe6 Qf6! $19 { Unfortunately white's best discovery only wins a piece. Black has too much material here to be afraid of anything. }) (12... Bxf7?? 13. Nd6+ Kd8 14. Nxf5 $18) (12... Kxf7?! 13. Nd6+! Bxd6 14. Bxe6+ Qxe6 15. Rxe6 Kxe6 16. Qg4+ Kf7 17. Qxd7+ Be7 $17 { Black should not allow such a line, even though they have a lot of material for the queen. This is simply more counterplay than white deserves. }) 13. Nfd6+! { "I have two knights. Ones for each of ya!" The royal fork cannot be denied. } (13. Ned6+! $18 { Excellent job! Instead, fork the king and queen with the other knight first for the game continuation. }) (13. Bxe6?? { A tempting move, but Nxe4+ is a brutal in-betweener. Suddenly all of white's pieces actually are hanging. You must keep a grip on the board at all times! } 13... Nxe4+ 14. Kg1 Qxe6 $19) 13... Kf8 { Black admits they are losing the queen and decides to leave the DSB on the board to better safeguard the king. } (13... Bxd6!? 14. Nxd6+ $18) 14. Nxf5 { PRO TIP: At the right moment, a dynamic advantage should be transformed into a decisive static advantage. In this game, Morphy accomplishes this simply by winning the queen in exchange for most of white's active pieces.
In positions where there are no such juicy prizes, transforming a dynamic advantage into a static advantage such as a better pawn structure or more space can be worthwhile too. } 14... Nxe4+ { Black inserts an unnecessary in-between check. } 15. Rxe4 Bxf5 { The dust has settled, and white now has a material advantage. However, white's lead in development remains the most important imbalance in the position. Put yourself in black's shoes: how do you even connect the rooks or get the king to safety?
Rather than sit back and enjoy his static advantage (material), Morphy continues using his remaining dynamic advantage (lead in development + initiative) to immediately go after the king. } { [%cal Gd1h5] } 16. Qh5! g6? { The losing move from a bad position. Morphy now finishes off the game with a sequence of checks. } { [%cal Gh5h6] } (16... Bg6!? 17. Rxf4+ $18) 17. Qh6+ Ke8 { Only legal move... } { [%cal Ge4e7] } 18. Rxe7+! { One last dynamic sacrifice rids the black king of the only defender of the dark squares. } 18... Kxe7 { [%cal Gh6g7] } 19. Qg7+ Kd6 { Black did not want to step back to the 8th rank and lose both rooks with check. But walking up the board directly walks into a mate in 2. } (19... Kd8 20. Qxh8+ $18) 20. Bxf4+ { Death by dark square. Nicely spotted. } 20... Ne5 21. Bxe5# { "I have two bishops. Ones for each of ya!"
The difficulty of each move this game was much higher than the previous two examples. Yet the principles remain the same. Morphy repeatedly took advantage of black's ridiculous queen moves either directly (by improving a piece with tempo on the queen) or indirectly (by improving a piece due to a tactic available because of black's queen position). } (21. dxe5+? $18 { Gives up the c5 square to the black king! }) (21. Qxe5+? $18 { Gives up the d7 square to the black king! }) 1-0


[Event "Anderssen - Morphy"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.12.25"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B01"]
[Opening "Scandinavian Defense: Anderssen Counterattack"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "A suspicious Scandinavian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/RorxIHYm"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We join one of the most serious matches Morphy ever played. In 1858 he faced off against Europe's top player in a first-to-7-wins match. Adolf Anderssen was arguably the #1 player in the world prior to Morphy's meteoric rise.

Therefore, it is all the more impressive that Morphy won this match 7-2, while recovering from both an illness and the leeching the doctors of the day administered to him. This crushing victory cemented Morphy's status as the undisputed best player in the world.

Morphy is already leading the match 4-1 at the time of this game. Anderssen, disliking the previous positions he got in 1. e4 e5, decides to shake things up to avoid theory. }
1. e4 d5!? { The Scandinavian defense. In modern times, this opening is a favorite of IM John Bartholomew. } 2. exd5 { Capturing on d5 is the only way for white to avoid losing time. } (2. e5?! $10 { Loses time. Now black is in a French but hasn't wasted a tempo on e6. }) (2. Nc3?! $10 { Loses time. After d4, there is no good square for the knight. }) (2. d3?! $10 { Allows a queen trade after the pawns are exchanged. That can't be the most white can get from this opening. }) (2. Bd3?! { Loses time with the bishop after black takes on e4. } 2... dxe4 3. Bxe4 Nf6 $15) (2. f3? $15 { A horribly weakening of your kingside for no reason! }) (2. Qe2? $17 { Developing your queen early in a chapter all about punishing players who develop their queen early? You're kidding, right? }) (2. Qf3? $17 { Developing your queen early in a chapter all about punishing players who develop their queen early? You're kidding, right? }) (2. Bb5+?! { An empty check. Walking into c6 means we're immediately losing the tempo back. } 2... c6 3. Bd3 dxe4 4. Bxe4 Nf6 $15) 2... Qxd5 { The Scandinavian defense is already somewhat suspicious since black is moving their queen into the center of the board where she will be attacked while white develops naturally. If black doesn't follow-up precisely, it is easy to end up worse at an early stage. } 3. Nc3 { This is the main move to take advantage of black's opening choice. Simple chess: develop with tempo. } (3. Nf3!? $10 { A principled option. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. d4!? $10 { A principled option. Play Nc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Qf3?! $15 { Not a principled option. We want to gain time against the queen, not offer a trade. After Nf6, white has nothing special. } 3... Nf6 $10) (3. c4?! { Unprincipled. Only make threats against the queen with moves that simultaneously improve your position! This move doesn't develop a piece, and in fact only creates weaknesses in white's position. } 3... Qe4+ $15) 3... Qa5 { A good move. This is one of the safest squares for the queen. It is hard for white to develop and attack the queen on a5. } 4. d4 { Staking a claim in the center and preparing to develop the DSB. Morphy continues to play principled chess. } (4. Nf3!? $14 { Equally principled. Play d4 for the game continuation. }) (4. Bc4!? $14 { Equally principled. Play d4 for the game continuation. }) (4. b4!? { A fun gambit that tries to take advantage of black's queen position. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. } 4... Qxb4 5. Rb1 Qd6 $10) (4. Be2?! $10 { A half-developing move with the bishop? Morphy would never. }) (4. Bb5+?! $10 { After c6, this move simply loses time. }) 4... e5?! { We have seen many examples showing that black should not open the center when behind in development. Therefore, e5 is somewhat suspicious. } { [%cal Gd4e5] } 5. dxe5 Qxe5+ { The 3rd queen move... } 6. Be2 { Blocking the check and developing. As soon as white plays Nf3, Morphy will gain another tempo on the queen. } (6. Nge2?! $10 { Don't block the LSB. Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing! }) (6. Qe2!? $14 { Fine, since after the queen trade, white gets to recapture and develop. Play Be2 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. Be3!? $14 { Developing and blocking the check. Play Be2 instead for the game continuation. }) 6... Bb4 { Aggressive intentions from black. Anderssen claims that Nf3 has been prevented because c3 falls with check.
Which side should be favored if we enter dynamic complications? } 7. Nf3! { Yes! Another example of the Shankland question! White will lose a pawn on c3, but Morphy is not worried about losing this pawn if he gets speedy development with tempo. } (7. Bd2!? $10 { A fine move if you prefer to play solidly. Look for better! }) (7. Qd3!? $10 { A fine move if you prefer to play solidly. Look for better! }) (7. Qd2? $15 { Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing! }) (7. Qd5?? { Oh no, your queen! } 7... Qxd5 $19) 7... Bxc3+ { Following through with their threat is forced if black does not want to fall dangerously behind in development for nothing. } 8. bxc3 Qxc3+ { The 4th queen move... } 9. Bd2 Qc5 { The 5th queen move.
Black needs four more moves to finish development compared to our one. Moreover, we will likely gain even more time against black's centrally placed queen while both sides finish deploying their armies. Since three tempi is often worth a pawn, white shouldn't be worried about being down a pawn in this position.
In fact, only white can be better. In exchange for the b pawn, white got every piece working, all coming out with tempo against black's queen. If black doesn't play perfectly for the next few moves, it is easy to get immediately crushed by the threats that white's developed army can now generate. } 10. Rb1 (10. O-O!? $14 { Just as good as the game continuation. Play Rb1 first for the game continuation. }) (10. Be3?! $10 { A desirable move with tempo on the queen. But did you lose your grip on your board?
Black is able to regain the tempo with any queen check. Your king is still in the center! }) 10... Nc6 { Finally, black has a tempo to start catching up on development. Anderssen, a strong player, jumps at the opportunity.
This specific developing move prevents Bb4, making the queen on c5 more reliable. } 11. O-O { Morphy essentially finishes development, while black's pieces remain on the back rank. } (11. Rb5!? $14 { A fine improving move with tempo. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (11. Be3?! $10 { A desirable move with tempo on the queen. But did you lose your grip on your board?
Black is able to regain the tempo with any queen check. Your king is still in the center! }) (11. Qc1?! $10 { This is not really a developing move. The queen does not stand better on c1 than d1. }) 11... Nf6 { Further development by black. Unfortunately, there is no way to keep black's king stuck in the center, and so white's lead in development will not translate into a crushing attack. At best, white is slightly better. } { [%cal Gd2f4] } 12. Bf4?! { A logical move that improves the DSB and attacks the c7 pawn. But this sells the position short because white has to move the bishop several times just to regain the material.
Rb5 would have been better, improving the rook with tempo on the queen. } (12. Rb5! { Even better than Morphy's move. Black's queen doesn't have any safe square on such an open board since Qe7 runs into an eventual Re1 and Qd6 runs into an eventual Rd1. } 12... Qd6!? (12... Qe7!? 13. Re1 $14) 13. Qa1 O-O 14. Rd1 $14) 12... O-O! { Black correctly recognizes that this is the moment to focus on development and not bend over backwards trying to defend the extra pawn.
PRO TIP: If you are ahead in material but behind in development, you have the option of returning the extra material in exchange for catching up in development. This transaction is nothing more than transforming a static advantage to a dynamic one.
We will explore this concept further in Chapter V: Active defense. } 13. Bxc7!? { White has regained the sacrificed material, but it has already cost white two tempi. Moreover, this bishop is now opposite black's queen and is thus tactically vulnerable.
There were more dynamic options available for white earlier. } (13. Rb5!? $10 { Also fine. Play Bxc7 for the game continuation. }) 13... Nd4! { Black jumps at the opportunity for more soothing piece trades. } { [%cal Gd1d4] } 14. Qxd4 Qxc7 { Material is now level, and white no longer has a lead in development. Statically and dynamically, the position is balanced, so the evaluation should be equal. } { [%cal Ge2d3] } 15. Bd3 Bg4 { Black has essentially caught up in development. But now Morphy generates a kingside attack out of thin air using the fact that more of his pieces are able to reach the kingside. } { [%cal Gf3g5] } 16. Ng5 { Nxh7 is the immediate threat, taking advantage of the overloaded knight on f6. } 16... Rfd8 { A developing move with tempo against white's queen. Certainly on-theme for this chapter! But it is unclear if this is a useful tempo for black because (1) white immediately gets the tempo back by attacking b7, and (2) now the f7 pawn is more sensitive. } { [%cal Gd4b4] } 17. Qb4 { Staying active!
The pressure against b7 is too much for Anderssen to handle. In this position, he cracks. } 17... Bc8? { "You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move!" Bc8 is just too pathetic to even be a candidate move. Literally any move that sacrificed the b pawn for activity would have been stronger than this passive, retreating move. Our newly acquired dynamic advantage ensures that we must be clearly better.
The obvious way to defend b7 was b6. But both players saw that b6 would have been met with Nxh7!, since the knight on f6 was still overloaded defending both h7 and g4.
The best option for black was h6, kicking the knight away, followed by sacrificing the b7 pawn for activity. } (17... h6! { The only way to remain in the game. } 18. Ne4 Nd7! 19. Qxb7 Qxb7 20. Rxb7 Ne5 $10 { Black's pieces are active enough to compensate for the missing pawn. }) (17... b6?! 18. Nxh7! Nxh7 19. Qxg4 $14) 18. Rfe1 { The Morphy move! Now all of white's pieces are playing.
The immediate threat is Re7. Black does not have time for h6. } (18. Rfd1? { The rook is not doing anything on the d file because at best white will be offering a rook trade. }) (18. Bc4!? { Equally strong as the game continuation. The threat to f7 is hard to parry since Rd7 clogs up all of black's pieces. Play Rfe1 instead for the game continuation. } 18... Rd7 19. Rfd1 $16) (18. Qh4? { A forcing move. However, after h6, your knight will get kicked back while the pressure on h7 is dealt with. You must improve all of your pieces first before launching such an attack. } 18... h6 19. Ne4 $10) (18. Bxh7+?? { Oh no, your bishop! We need more pieces in the attack before such a sacrifice could work out. } 18... Nxh7 19. Qh4!? (19. Nxh7!? Kxh7 20. Qh4+ Kg8 $19) 19... Nxg5 $19) (18. Nxh7?? { Oh no, your knight! We need more pieces in the attack before such a sacrifice could work out. } 18... Nxh7 19. Qh4 Nf6 $19) 18... a5 { Black is lashing out while also trying to get the a8 rook into the game via an eventual Ra5.
But it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } { [%cal Gb4e7] } (18... Rd7?? 19. Re8+!! Nxe8 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. Qf8#) 19. Qe7!? Qxe7 20. Rxe7 { Even in the endgame, white maintains the initiative. } 20... Nd5? { The losing move. Anderssen is simultaneously hanging f7 and h7, but is relying on tricks to carry him through these complications. We already know from previous examples that black should not have the right to pull off dynamic moves from such a passive position. } (20... Rd4! { The best option. Both Nxf7 and Rxf7 are tactically prevented while black is simply improving the rook. } 21. h3 $14 (21. Rxf7? h6 { [%cal Gh6g5,Gg8f7] } 22. Nf3 Rxd3! 23. Rxf6! Rc3! $10) (21. Nxf7? Nd5! $17 { [%cal Gd5e7,Gg8f7] })) 21. Bxh7+! { Yes! First the h pawn is removed with check. Next, the f7 pawn is free to capture. } (21. Nxf7? { Black's pressure on e7 means we are just trading pieces. White has much stronger. } 21... Nxe7 22. Nxd8 $16) (21. Rxf7?? { After h6 both your knight on g5 and rook on f7 are hit. White loses a piece. } 21... h6 $19) (21. Nxh7?? { Oh no, your rook! } 21... Nxe7 $19) (21. Re5? $10 { We are not interested in passively responding to black's threat. Push the initiative! }) (21. Re4?? { Nc3 is a massive fork! } 21... Nc3 $19) (21. Re2?? { Nc3 is a massive fork! } 21... Nc3 $19) (21. Ree1? $15 { We are not interested in passively responding to black's threat. Push the initiative! }) 21... Kh8 (21... Kf8?? 22. Rxf7+ Ke8 23. Re1+ Ne7 24. Rexe7#) 22. Rxf7 (22. Nxf7+?? $19 { Oh no, your bishop! }) 22... Nc3 { Black is now flailing, down two pawns. Morphy's continuation is convincing. } 23. Re1! { Yes! Activating the last piece. We do not want to bend over backwards defending a2. } (23. Ra1? $16 { Too passive. Moreover, a2 can still be captured due to our back rank weakness. }) (23. Rb2?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rb3?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rb4?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rb5?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rb6?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rbxb7?? { Oh no, your back rank! } 23... Rd1#) (23. Rf1?! $16 { Too passive. There is a clearly better square available to this rook... }) 23... Nxa2 { The knight is now hopelessly offsides. White is attacking with every piece. } { [%cal Gf7f4] } 24. Rf4 { Relocating to the h file. } 24... Ra6 { Finally, black's queenside rook participates. Too little too late. } { [%cal Gh7d3] } 25. Bd3 $18 { The bishop is saved, and now the threats of Rh4+, Nf7+, Bxa6, and Bc4 each win the game. Rather than sacrifice a piece just to prolong the game, Anderssen resigned.
This game was a more advanced (but also more realistic) example of thwarting the wild queen. With their early queen moves, black fell behind in development by four tempi in exchange for a pawn. While this gave Morphy some dynamic chances, the best he could find was regaining the lost material. Importantly, black's king was never in danger in the opening, and so the position remained roughly balanced.
PRO TIP: Keep a level head when attempting to refute a player obsessed with moving their queen. Early queen moves might lose a few tempi to your pieces as you make active, improving moves. But gaining a tempo or two in the opening doesn't mean you have the right to immediately checkmate your opponent. It's up to you to accurately evaluate what your dynamic compensation is worth, and press this dynamic advantage accordingly. } 1-0


