{ Now let's summarize this chapter on thwarting a wild queen while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board. }
1. e4 { * Don't develop your queen early. If your opponent's pieces can make normal improving moves while attacking her, you have to respond to those threats, thus losing time. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { * The ultimate price for bringing the queen out too early is that the opponent gets free tempi and the initiative. } { [%cal Gb8c6] } 2... Nc6 3. d4 { * Don't make aimless threats against a wild queen. You should focus on threats that simultaneously improve your position. } { [%cal Ge5d4] } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { * Punishing a wild queen does not mean hyper-fixating on her, going out of your way to attack her, or attempting to trap her with every move. The correct way to punish a wild queen is to gain a few tempi on her, giving you a lead in development. It's already a success to play normal, principled chess, up a few tempi. } { [%cal Gf8c5] } 4... Bc5 5. Ng5 { * Keep a level head when attempting to refute a player obsessed with moving their queen. Early queen moves might lose a few tempi to your pieces as you make active, improving moves. But gaining a tempo or two in the opening doesn't mean you have the right to immediately checkmate your opponent. } { [%cal Gg8h6] } 5... Nh6 6. Nxf7 { * Having a grip on the board is a fundamental skill to improving as a chess player. By having a grip on the board, I mean constantly tracking which pieces are defended or not, which pieces are attacked by the opponent, what squares are under our control, and what checks are in the position. This grip on the position is sometimes called "board vision." } { [%cal Gh6f7] } 6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ { * Before getting excited and playing an attacking move, due your due diligence! Take a few seconds to confirm you are not missing a crucial check, capture, or threat in the position. Keeping a grip on the board requires constantly refreshing which squares are under your control in the position and which are not. } { [%cal Ge8f7] } 7... Kxf7 8. Qh5+ { * When your opponent supposedly prevents you from making a move you want to make, ask yourself the Shankland question: "What if I do it anyway?" This question reminds you to push past first impressions and possibly refute your opponent's faux threat. Pushing your own agenda instead of bowing to your opponent's threats is how you take the initiative. } { [%cal Gg7g6] } 8... g6 9. Qxc5 { * If you are ahead in material but behind in development, you have the option of returning the extra material in exchange for catching up in development. This transaction is nothing more than transforming a static advantage to a dynamic one. } { [%cal Gd7d6] } 9... d6 10. Qb5 { * At the right moment, a dynamic advantage should be transformed into a decisive static advantage. } { [%cal Gh8e8] } 10... Re8 11. Qb3+?! { (Please enjoy the rest of this unannotated Morphy miniature. It's about to get spicy!) } { [%cal Gd6d5] } 11... d5 12. f3 { [%cal Gc6a5] } 12... Na5 13. Qd3? { [%cal Gd5e4] } 13... dxe4 14. fxe4 { [%cal Gd8h4] } 14... Qh4+! 15. g3 { [%cal Ge8e4] } 15... Rxe4+!? 16. Kf2 { [%cal Gh4e7] } 16... Qe7? (16... Qf6+! { Even stronger than the game continuation! } 17. Qf3 Bg4 18. Qxf6+ Kxf6 19. Rf1 Kg7 20. h4 Re2+ 21. Kg1 Bh3 $19) 17. Nd2?? { [%cal Ge4e3] } 17... Re3! 18. Qb5 { [%cal Gc7c6] } 18... c6!! 19. Qf1 { [%cal Gc8h3] } 19... Bh3!! 20. Qd1 { [%cal Ga8f8] } 20... Rf8! 21. Nf3 { [%cal Gf7e8] } 21... Ke8! $19 { For more resources exploring how to refute an opponent obsessed with moving their queen, check out:
* ChessCoach Andras https://youtu.be/HTpxmDTEhIc
* Chess Vibes https://youtu.be/Y9-xotChwmE
* Daniel Naroditsky https://youtu.be/HiCeU8tIh0U
* GothamChess https://youtu.be/cY9zitJFglc
* John Bartholomew https://youtu.be/U2huVf1l4UE&t=2093 } 0-1


