{ Now that we have more chess terminology and understanding of dynamic play, it's time to revisit the Opera Game. I believe this game is so fundamental that it is worth seeing it a second time with deeper explanations.

No arrows this time! Now that you have seen so many Morphy beat downs, I'm confident you can find all the moves with limited guidance by me. }
1. e4 e5 { In the first viewing we focused mainly on development and time. While those are crucially important takeaways from this game, this viewing we will focus mainly on dynamism and when Morphy makes a threat vs when he develops. } 2. Nf3 { The first of many threats in this game. White develops a piece, controls the center, and threatens to win the e5 pawn. Game after game, multipurpose moves like these set the groundwork for Morphy's dynamic advantage. } (2. f4!? $15 { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (2. Bc4!? $10 { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) 2... d6 { A first loss of time. Nc6 (developing a piece while defending the threat) instead is more reliable. } 3. d4 { Development with a threat. Not only does Morphy take over the center and prepare to develop the DSB with this move, but he is also threatening to capture on e5 twice. } (3. Bc4!? $14 { The other principled developing move. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Nc3!? $14 { A reasonable move, developing the knight and controlling the center. Play d4 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Bb5+? $15 { A bad check. After c6, we have to move the bishop again. Meanwhile, black is one move closer to taking over the center with d5.
I would hope that after reviewing three chapters of Morphy games you would no longer think of such moves! }) (3. d3?! $10 { Blocks in the LSB for no reason. Why would you play such a passive move? }) (3. Be2?! $10 { This half-developing move barely improves the LSB. }) 3... Bg4?! { Black "defends" e5 by pinning white's knight. However, they failed to address the Shankland question: "What if Morphy captures on e5 anyway?" } 4. dxe5 { Exactly! Either black immediately recaptures on e5, losing a pawn to Qxd8+ Kxd8, Nxe5; or black has to capture first on f3, losing further time out of the opening. } 4... Bxf3 { Black chooses the lesser evil: a second bishop move loses time while developing Morphy's army for him. } (4... dxe5? 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 6. Nxe5 $16 { Up a pawn with tempo on the bishop and f7. White is practically winning already. }) 5. Qxf3 { Recapturing and developing a new piece.
We have witnessed the pain Morphy repeatedly inflicted on his opponents last chapter for developing their queen too early. So it's perfectly valid to question why white is happy to develop this queen before any other piece.
White's queen is only poorly placed if she can be conveniently attacked by black's pieces as they make natural improving moves. What black piece can attack the queen on f3? The LSB has already been traded off the board. The f file is closed to the heavy pieces. So she is only misplaced if black can quickly play Nd4 to gain a tempo on the queen.
Since Morphy ensures Nd4 is never a possibility in this game, the queen on f3 is an asset, not a liability. } (5. gxf3?! $14 { A worse recapture, since this move does not develop a piece. }) 5... dxe5 { After a brief interlude, black restores material equality. } 6. Bc4! { Developing with tempo - mate in 1 is a pretty big threat! Due to black's passive play, Morphy already grabs the initiative. } (6. Nc3!? $14 { Not a bad move as this develops a piece and controls the center. Can you instead play a move that develops a piece and generates a threat? }) (6. Be3!? $14 { Not a bad move as this develops a piece and controls the center. Can you instead play a move that develops a piece and generates a threat? }) (6. Bd2?! $14 { The bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file in case we put a rook on d1. }) (6. Bg5?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 6... Qxg5 $19) (6. Bb5+?! $14 { An empty check that simply asks black to develop with Nd7 or regain the tempo with c6. After either of these moves, you have not truly gained a tempo. }) (6. Qb3!? $14 { You are mixing up the move order from the game. Developing a new piece with tempo is more principled than this otherwise high-level move. }) (6. Be2?! $14 { A half-developing move that does not improve the bishop in any way. }) (6. Bd3?! $14 { A half-developing move that does not improve the bishop in any way. }) 6... Nf6 { Black develops and defends against white's threat on f7. } { [%cal Gf3b3] } 7. Qb3! { "Another queen move? Surely the fool playing white needs to study Morphy games to better learn the opening principles!" While the negatives of this second queen move should already be apparent, we cannot ignore its positives.
Firstly, there is a direct threat to both f7 (Bxf7+ is a mate-in-2 threat) and b7 (Qxb7 attacks a loose rook). Secondly, black has no convenient developing move to defend against these threats. In fact, the threat against f7 can only be defended by Qe7, further delaying black's ability to castle kingside. Thirdly, the queen on b3 attacks more squares (and is thus more active!) than she did on f3. Fourthly, the queen on b3 is just as inaccessible to black's pieces as she was on f3.
With so many positives, Qb3 is in fact the objectively best move.
Remember, nothing beats a good move! The principles are concepts to help guide a player's thinking, not rules to be followed blindly. Strong players, guided by clear calculation, know when to play the best move, regardless of general principles it may break. } 7... Qe7!? { A nice defensive move from a rotten position. Black directly defends f7 with this move, while simultaneously preparing a queen trade with Qb4+. If white takes on b7, the damage is limited to only a single pawn.
However, the queen on e7 blocks in black's DSB. Black will now need to invest further time to develop the DSB. The ultimate consequence of blocking in the kingside pieces is that black's dream of castling kingside to safety will remain just that: a dream.
Should we secure a static advantage by capturing on b7? } 8. Nc3! { A dynamic choice! Morphy develops a new piece while preventing black's threat to trade queens with Qb4+. He rejects the greedy Qxb7 option, which secures a static advantage in the form of an extra pawn, and instead trusts in his lead in development. } (8. Qxb7?! { A greedy move that does in fact win a pawn, securing a static advantage for the long term. However, after Qb4+, we are trading queens and the damage is only limited to one pawn. Morphy plays for a larger advantage by trusting in his dynamic opportunities. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Nxd2 $16) (8. O-O?! $16 { A developing move, but the rook on f1 lacks dynamic potential. In a perfect world, Morphy would rather castle queenside because a rook on d1 is immediately active. }) (8. Bg5? { A developing move, but you didn't answer the Shankland question: "What if they play Qb4+ anyway?" Qb4+ gets out of the pin, forces a queen trade, and doesn't lose any of the pawns. } 8... Qb4+ 9. Nc3 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nbd7 $14) (8. Nd2? $14 { Develops a piece, but blocks in the DSB on c1. Avoid playing moves that prevent the rest of your pieces from developing! }) (8. Bd2?! $14 { A half-developing move to take the sting out of Qb4+ should be avoided. The bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file in case we put a rook on d1. }) 8... c6 { Black defends b7 directly, but again isn't developing a new piece. Counting the tempi, we see that white is up three tempi: one for having three pieces developed to black's two, one for being on move, and one that black owes to open up a diagonal for black's DSB.
Is this the moment to strike? } (8... Qb4? { This move no longer comes with check and is therefore ineffective. } 9. Bxf7+ $18) 9. Bg5 { Correct. This is not the moment to strike, since (1) we still have active developing moves to make, and (2) black is not yet able to evacuate the king from the center.
For the record, h6 is the only move worth calculating before playing Bg5. This turns out to be well met by Bxf6 though. Because black's queen must defend b7 to prevent black losing a rook, Bxf6 forces gxf6, when black is only losing time and creating weaknesses in the position. } (9. Be3!? $16 { An equally strong move. Play Bg5 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Bd2?! $14 { The bishop on d2 is not any better than on c1. Moreover, this blocks our d file for when we put a rook on d1. }) (9. O-O?! $14 { Gets the king to safety, and is therefore principled. However, the rook on f1 is not participating yet. There is a stronger developing move that sets up queenside castling instead. }) (9. f4!? $16 { With white's lead in development, this central strike is tempting. But this position is not truly the DDD moment since white still needs to develop the DSB and rooks for this central strike to hit with the desired force. Play Bg5 instead for the game continuation. }) 9... b5? { Another non-developing move? Black attempts to solve their coordination issues with this dynamic, lashing-out move. However, we have repeatedly seen that dynamic complications favor the side with the more active pieces.
If white responds to this threat by passively retreating the LSB, then black's last move successfully gains a tempo they can use to catch up in development. Therefore, at this exact moment, white's lead in development is at its maximum. Moreover, black's king remains stuck in the center, while white's king is ready to castle in either direction.
Putting all of these clues together, we see that this is the DDD moment. The position screams for a dynamic solution.
How best to use your active pieces? } (9... h6!? 10. Bxf6 gxf6 (10... Qxf6?? 11. Qxb7 $18) 11. O-O-O $16) 10. Nxb5! { Excellent job finding this dynamic option!
We now have the understanding to appreciate why such a sacrifice works.
Firstly, black doesn't deserve to be able to generate real threats with all of their pieces on the back rank and their king still three moves away from castling. With white's active pieces, we should be looking to take the initiative and not bow to black's threats.
Moreover, at the DDD moment, we should be looking for forcing moves, tactical shots, and general fireworks to open the position and go after the opponent. Nxb5 is all of the above!
Finally, we know that sacrifices that remove a key defender are crucial moves to keep the initiative. There were many possible sacrifices in the position. By specifically playing Nxb5, Morphy removes black's queenside pawns, turning the previously dormant LSB into a verifiable monster along the a4-e8 diagonal. } (10. Bxb5? { When sacrificing on b5, what piece do you want to end up with on b5 once the dust settles? Neither the knight nor queen landing on b5 lands with a killer threat. } 10... cxb5 11. Nd5!? (11. Qxb5+?! Qd7! 12. Qxe5+ Be7 $15) (11. Nxb5? Nc6 $17) 11... Qb7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Nxf6+ $10) (10. Qxb5?? $19 { Oh no, your queen! There is no compensation for such a sacrifice. }) (10. Bxf6?! { There is no need to cash out on this pin right now. What is your next move? } 10... Qxf6 11. Nxb5 cxb5 12. Bxb5+ Nc6! $16 { A new option available to black they don't have in the game. }) (10. Bxf7+?? { After the queen recaptures on f7, there is no follow-up. Your dynamic solution must somehow improve your pieces! } 10... Qxf7 $19) (10. O-O-O?? { After bxc4, white's knight and queen remain somewhat shut out of the game. This isn't a way to get compensation for a piece sacrifice. } 10... bxc4 11. Qxc4 Qe6! $19) (10. Nd5?? { A clever idea, as cxd5 is met with Bxb5+, similar to the game. Unfortunately, black can ignore this threat to their queen and insert bxc4, winning a piece while attacking your queen! } 10... bxc4!! 11. Nxe7 cxb3 12. Nf5 $19) (10. Bd3? $10 { Black's horribly passive pieces do not give them the right to grab the initiative. Look for a refutation to black's last move. }) (10. Be2? $10 { Black's horribly passive pieces do not give them the right to grab the initiative. Look for a refutation to black's last move. }) (10. Bf1? $15 { Black's horribly passive pieces do not give them the right to grab the initiative. Look for a refutation to black's last move. }) 10... cxb5 { Black must recapture if they don't want to go down without a fight.
PRO TIP: If your opponent is crushing you and decides to sacrifice material to put you away, you should often take the material. The reasoning is simple: it's better to be lost but up a knight than to just be lost! At least now your opponent must play accurately to prove their dynamic compensation is enough to win the game. There's a chance they fail and you swindle a draw or win. } 11. Bxb5+ (11. Qxb5+?? { After Qd7, black is untangling or trading queens. Neither option is what white is looking for! } 11... Qd7 12. Qxe5+ Be7 13. Rd1 Nc6! $10) 11... Nbd7 { Morphy has opened lines towards black's king and placed the LSB on a killer diagonal with tempo.
Having played through dozens of Morphy games, I hope the next move is screaming out to be played. } 12. O-O-O! { Bringing all the boys to the party! This is another great multipurpose move that both develops a rook and gets the king to safety (away from the action happening in the center of the board). Notice how kingside castling would have been inferior, as that only safeguards the king.
The direct threat is Bxd7+, winning a queen, because the knight on f6 is pinned. So Morphy's move is once again a developing move with a threat. } (12. O-O?! $16 { Gets the king to safety, and is therefore principled. However, the rook on f1 is not participating yet. There is a multipurpose move that accomplishes more! }) (12. Rd1?! $16 { Develops the rook to an open file, and is therefore principled. However, the king remains in the center. There is a multipurpose move that accomplishes more! }) (12. Bxf6?! $16 { Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) (12. Bxd7+? $17 { Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) 12... Rd8 { White clearly has the initiative here as black scrambles to defend d7. If only we could bring our final piece into play with tempo... } 13. Rxd7! { An excellent exchange sacrifice! But how can we find such moves in our own games?
Firstly, black remains desperately tied up by the pins in the position, but can soon escape them with Qe6 and Be7. So time is of the essence. Just as in a DDD moment, we should be looking for tactical shots.
Secondly, this exchange sacrifice brings in the reserves with tempo. In that sense, Rxd7 is a developing move. The final piece (the rook on h1) is now ready to join the attack with deadly effect.
Lastly, and most importantly, we should trust concrete calculations. The dominant LSB is crushing black here, and Morphy no doubt was looking for variations that accentuate its strength. Calculating Rxd7 Rxd7 Rd1, does black have a move to save the d7 rook? } (13. Bxf6?! $16 { Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) (13. Qa4?! $16 { Piling up further on the pinned knight is a strong choice. But it costs a tempo to make this move. Morphy instead finds a way to bring all of the boys to the party with tempo. }) (13. Bxd7+? $14 { Giving away the pride and joy of white's position for what? Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) 13... Rxd7 { This specific recapture was forced if black didn't want to lose a queen (again, the f6 knight is pinned). Now let's bring the last piece into the attack. } 14. Rd1 { The Morphy move! The final piece joins the attack and renews the threat to d7.
Notice how black's king is stuck in the center, DSB cannot develop, and rook on h8 is a passive bystander to the slaughter occurring in the center. A strong player does not bother counting material in such a position. White's massive dynamic advantage means we must be winning. } (14. Bxd7+? $14 { Giving away the pride and joy of white's position for what? Capturing a pinned piece is often a poor choice unless you are getting something tangible in return. Instead, you should pile more pressure on those pinned pieces! }) 14... Qe6 { Black tries to trade queens and develop the DSB, but it is too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games...
At this point, nearly every move is winning for white. Can you find Morphy's artistic finish? } 15. Bxd7+ { White's entire strategy had been to pile up pressure on the pinned piece on d7, accentuating the strength of the LSB... and now Morphy throws that all away by capturing the pinned piece with the monster bishop?
Unprincipled, but nothing beats a good move! Morphy surely calculated to the end of the game before playing this capture. } (15. Qxe6+!? { A forcing move, and one that is winning. After fxe6 Bxf6! removes the last defender of the d7 rook. White will enter a winning endgame.
Morphy finds a more convincing finish instead. } 15... fxe6 16. Bxf6! gxf6 17. Rxd7 $18) (15. Bxf6!? { A forcing capture that wins material in every variation.
Morphy finds a more artistic finish instead. } 15... Bd6! (15... gxf6!? 16. Bxd7+ Qxd7 17. Rxd7 $18) 16. Bxd7+ Qxd7 17. Bxg7 $18) (15. Rxd7!? { Also winning, but less clear. After Nxd7, what is your follow up? } 15... Nxd7 16. Qc3! $18 { Qc8+ will not be denied. }) 15... Nxd7 { Another recapture that is forced if black wants to keep their queen. What is the final blow? } 16. Qb8+!! Nxb8 { Black's move is yet again forced, allowing the beautiful finish. } 17. Rd8# { This game is truly the gift that keeps on giving.
On a first walkthrough, we explained Morphy's moves through the lens of development, time, and attack. On this second walkthrough, we focused more on utilizing the initiative, precise calculation, and when the principles should be followed or rejected. Indeed, I encourage you to revisit this game when you are a stronger player so that you can peel back even more layers on it.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
That wraps up Part I of this study, where we analyze Morphy's most accessible games. Indeed, the fundamentals that these games have taught us will be used throughout the rest of the study.
When you are ready, head to Part II of this study. The games will be more involved, but the concepts will be no less foundational.
In case you haven't yet, please like this study and share with your friends if you have enjoyed this study so far! } 1-0


