{ Chapter IV: King hunt

This next chapter will focus on attacking games where the king is forced out from behind his defenses. We will develop an intuition for hunting down a lonesome king walking up the board to his doom. In particular, when should we sacrifice? When can we afford a quiet move?

PRO TIP: In the middle of a king hunt, focus on forcing moves that prevent the king from escaping back to safety. If the king is forced up the board towards your army, you have a good chance of weaving mating nets. }
 *


[Event "Odds game (Ra1)"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1850.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "NN"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Morphy - NN"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/R1Wp7WMc"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Another game against the infamous NN. Morphy spots his opponent a full rook on move one.

This game was supposedly played while Morphy was eleven years old. However, there is some controversy that this game was actually played by Wilhelm Steinitz, the first official world champion and arguably best player in the world starting in the 1870s, and misattributed to Morphy after the fact.

Regardless, this rook-odds game is a model game, showing how to refute black in the Fried Liver Attack, even down a rook! } { [%csl Ra1] }
1. e4 e5 { This game starts as an Italian. } 2. Nf3 (2. f4!? $15 { Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) 2... Nc6 { Any player who plays the white side of the Italian and black side of 1... e5 would do well to memorize this game.
What move enters the Italian? } 3. Bc4 Nf6 { Every other game that has reached this position continued with Bc5, avoiding white's next move. Black instead opts for Nf6 this game, entering the so-called "Two Knights Defense."
Both moves are objectively sound for black and indeed transpose to each other if white plays d3+c3 or c3+d3. } { [%cal Gf3g5] } 4. Ng5!? { Morphy has another idea in mind with this early knight attack. He is immediately targeting f7, the soft spot in black's position.
PRO TIP: The commonly repeated phrase, "don't move the same piece twice in the opening," is overrated advice. In fact, there are many situations where moving a piece twice is objectively best. As we have seen in Chapter I, the correct advice should be: "don't lose time in the opening."
Let's consider a few instances of when that superficial phrase fails: Firstly, when your piece is threatened, you must move it again to avoid losing material. Secondly, generating a threat is more important than simple development in some critical positions, like a DDD moment. Indeed, moving an already developed piece again may be the best way to blow open the position. Thirdly, improving your piece to its best square may take several moves. In closed positions, you should look to optimize your pieces right out of the opening; knights are particularly slow to reach their optimal square.
Returning to this game, we can consider the positives and negatives of Ng5 in particular. Generating the threat to f7 avoids a loss of a tempo, even if it costs time to move the knight a second time in the first place. Indeed, this position is an example of the second instance above when moving a piece twice is justified. } 4... d5! { An excellent move! Black simultaneously challenges white's center, develops a piece (the LSB and queen), and prevents white's threat to capture f7. In the next chapter, we shall see that this is textbook "active defense."
Unfortunately, in this game we shall soon see that black played this move for the wrong reasons. } { [%cal Ge4d5] } (4... Bc5?! $17 { The Traxler is another way to play, although we won't discuss it here. }) (4... h6?? 5. Nxf7! $18) 5. exd5 { Capturing with the pawn is the only way to avoid losing a tempo, justifying white's budding attack. } (5. Bxd5? Nxd5 6. exd5 Qxd5 $19) 5... Nxd5? { This obvious recapture is a known mistake. Much stronger and safer is Na5, sidelining the knight but at least regaining a tempo.
With Nxd5, black enters the "Fried Liver Attack." In fact, if white still had a rook on a1, this position already is winning for white after the game continuation. } { [%cal Gg5f7] } (5... Na5! 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 $19 { The main line for black. }) 6. Nxf7! { This knight sacrifice was known to opening theory long before Morphy's time, but this position should still be studied by every chess player today. Indeed, kicking off a king hunt with this sacrifice is the entire point behind the earlier Ng5.
PRO TIP: A king hunt is defined by your opponent's king running for his life to avoid checkmate. It often starts with a timely sacrifice to force your opponent's king to walk up the board closer to your pieces.
In normal positions, most sacrifices on f7 are nonsense because they lack any follow-up. In contrast, the follow-up here fully justifies this sacrifice. Let's explore this follow-up as we play through the forcing continuation. } 6... Kxf7 { Capturing this knight, which forked the queen and rook, is forced. Unfortunately for black, their king is now opposite our bishop, allowing us a brutal continuation! } { [%cal Gd1f3] } 7. Qf3+! { This check is the one-two punch punch behind Nxf7. Black's d5 knight is both attacked and pinned, so the only way for black to respond to our check while saving their knight is Ke6. } 7... Ke6 { Black is up a knight (and a rook from move one!), but their position is unenviable. Their king is one of their furthest developed pieces and also playing a critical role holding together the knight on d5.
While white currently only has two pieces developed, the key to our follow-up is that all of our pieces can develop with tempo. Indeed, black is already under a vicious attack.
This is a classic example showcasing the interplay between statics and dynamics. } 8. Nc3! { Opening principles 101: develop with a threat! } (8. d4? { This move doesn't actually open the position. After Nxd4, black is simply centralizing their knight with tempo. } 8... Nxd4 $19) (8. O-O?! $19 { Desirable, but not forcing enough. We are down a knight and rook! We need dynamic moves now! }) 8... Ne7 { Either Nb4 or Ne7 is necessary to defend d5. In either case, black is losing yet another tempo... } 9. O-O { We need more pieces in the attack. In particular, our three attackers (knight, bishop, and queen) are already stymied by black's three defenders (two knights and queen). Since black's king is not yet able to escape the center, we can afford a slow move to bring in the reserves.
After O-O, our rook can play a decisive role in case the e file opens up. } (9. d4! $17 { Nice job blasting the center open. Indeed, this is close to a DDD moment. Play O-O first for the game continuation. }) (9. d3? $19 { Slow and simple development is not going to cut it. We're down a knight and rook. We must be on the hunt for a king! }) 9... c6 { A solid, albeit slow move. Black finally solidifies the d5 knight for good. But the true purpose of this move is to create an escape route back to safety for the black king.
PRO TIP: If your king is exposed, ensure that it is only temporary! King safety issues can be fatal. Not only does checkmate end the game, but an exposed king underlies many tactical motifs. Therefore, at the earliest opportunity, you should bring your king to safety before your opponent can execute a decisive king hunt.
Black's king is not out of the center yet though. How best to continue the king hunt? } 10. d4! { Exactly! This is a classic DDD moment. Our lead in development has reached its relative maximum, while black is not yet playing with all of their pieces. We must open up the center before black's king can run away. } (10. Re1?! $17 { The right idea, but a bit slow. Can you switch the move order to make Re1 land with larger effect? }) (10. d3? $19 { Slow and simple development is not going to cut it. We're down a knight and rook. We must be on the hunt for a king! }) (10. Qh3+? { This check forces black's king towards c7, where he wants to go anyway. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 10... Kd6 $19) (10. Qg4+? { This check forces black's king towards c7, where he wants to go anyway. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 10... Kd6 $19) 10... exd4?? { Frankly, ridiculous. We have already seen in Chapter II how opening up the position when you are behind in development is suicidal. The same logic applies to this position.
Moreover, in the opening, we are taught to develop ASAP, control the center, and get your king to safety. In this position, black has failed all of the above.
The rest of this game is a one-sided affair since now all of white's pieces can join the attack with tempo. } 11. Re1+ { Time and time again, we see that the best forcing moves are those that simultaneously improve the worst placed piece. White already has a raging initiative, and the rest of this king hunt plays itself. } 11... Kd7 { Black's king is desperate to escape the center and find relative shelter on c7 or b8. Don't give him a chance to breathe! } 12. Nxd5 { Exactly. This is the beginning of a forcing line that brings in all of our pieces with tempo. Importantly, by forcing matters, black's king is not given any time to run away. } (12. Bxd5!? $17 { Just as good. Play Nxd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (12. Bf4? { This move tries to cut the king, but after the simple Nxf4, all you are doing is trading pieces, giving black's king time to escape. } 12... Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Qc7 $19) (12. Ne4!? { Nice job finding this centralizing move, since Kc7 can now be met with Qg3+. Play Nxd5 instead for the game continuation. } 12... Kc7?! 13. Qg3+! Kb6 14. Qb3+ Kc7 15. Qg3+ Kd7 $15 { Black is up a knight and rook, so shouldn't want a draw, but this move is hard to play since once again black's king is forced towards the center. The king hunt continues. }) 12... Nxd5 { Recapturing with the pawn would not have changed anything. } (12... cxd5!? 13. Bxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5+ $16 { Transposes to the game. }) 13. Bxd5 cxd5?! { Recapturing the piece is an automatic decision. However, black is up so much material, they could have cut their losses and prioritized escaping the center instead. Black should have returned the piece with Kc7, after which their king slips away and they remain up a rook. } (13... Kc7! 14. Qg3+!? Bd6 15. Qxg7+ Bd7 $19) 14. Qxd5+ Kc7? { A classic Morphy - NN position. All of Morphy's pieces are developed and attacking. Meanwhile, all of NN's pieces are at home watching TV, while the most developed piece is their king!
There are many checks in this position, but only one continues the king hunt. } (14... Bd6! 15. Bf4 Qf6 16. Qb5+ Kc7 17. Qc5+ Kd8 18. Bxd6 Be6! $15) 15. Bf4+! { PRO TIP: In the middle of a king hunt, focus on forcing moves that prevent the king from escaping back to safety. If the king is forced up the board towards your army, you have a good chance of weaving mating nets.
This specific check prevents Kb8 (and as we shall soon see Bd6). If black is forced to run up the board with Kb6, we can be sure that there will be a good follow-up. } (15. Qc5+?? { Oh no, your queen! } 15... Bxc5 $19) (15. Qc4+? { An empty check that only encourages black's king to run away. } 15... Kb8 16. Bf4+ Bd6 $19) 15... Bd6? { The only move that doesn't lose a queen. Unfortunately for black, it loses a king! } (15... Kb6? 16. Qxd8+! $18 { The strong follow-up that doesn't even need to be calculated before playing Bf4+. }) (15... Qd6!! 16. Qc5+! Kd7 17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. Qxd4 $16 { White is up a queen and two pawns for two bishops and a rook. Under normal circumstances, black should be doing fine. But with black's king exposed and pieces undeveloped, white is better. We shall explore similar positions in Part III. }) 16. Qc5+! { A beautiful cross-pin! After their last move, black's bishop no longer defends c5, and so this devastating check is now both playable and strong. } (16. Bxd6+?? { A forcing move, but after Qxd6, there is no way to deflect the king from defending the queen. Black survives in every variation. } 16... Qxd6 $19) (16. Re7+?? { Oh no, your rook! The bishop may be pinned, but the queen is not. This check does not deflect the queen from defending any crucial squares (like d6 for instance), and should therefore be easy to discard. }) 16... Kb8 { Kd7 was mated by Qxd6#. Kb8 prolongs the struggle an extra move. } 17. Qxd6+! (17. Bxd6+!? $18 { Also mating, but this move order lacks artistic flair. }) 17... Qxd6 18. Bxd6# { Morphy, ever the artist, mates with the lone bishop.
This game showcases what happens when black plays the most obvious moves in response to the Fried Liver Attack. Indeed, it doesn't end well for them!
Since the missing rook on a1 never contributed to this mating attack, this game is well worth memorizing. As white, you should attempt to execute the same vicious king hunt. As black, you should understand why you are avoiding the Fried Liver. If you do enter it, this is a prime example of not opening up the position while your king is in the center! } 1-0


[Event "Odds game (Ra1)"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1850.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Alonzo Morphy"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "O-O#"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/biks4wRd"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/1NBQKBNR w Kkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ A 13 year old Morphy was already much too strong for his father. Therefore, he spotted his father a full rook in order to make this game more interesting.

This game again features the Fried Liver Attack... down a rook. } { [%csl Ra1] }
1. e4 e5 { The Italian continues with 2. Nf3. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { The Italian continues with 3. Bc4. } 3. Bc4 Nf6 { Our second Two Knights Defense. The Evans Gambit is not an option, but the early knight attack is!
The Fried Liver continues with 4. Ng5. } 4. Ng5!? d5! { The only way to avoid catastrophe on f7. The Fried Liver continues with 5. exd5. } 5. exd5 Nxd5? { A critical mistake. Black now enters the Fried Liver.
Na5 was the solid move that kills white's fun. Meanwhile, black remains up a rook.
Do you remember the point of the Fried Liver? } (5... Na5! 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3!? $19) 6. Nxf7! Kxf7 { The beginning of the king hunt. Black's king is drawn out to a vulnerable square. } 7. Qf3+! (7. Qh5+? { A poor check. Black is happy to escape to relative safety with Kg8. } 7... Kg8 $19) (7. Nc3? { A forcing move, but black has no problems after Be6. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 7... Be6! $19) 7... Ke6 { Exactly! Black must defend the knight on d5 and escape the check. Because the d5 knight is pinned, the only option is bringing the king up in the opening.
Even up a rook and a knight, black should already be feeling uncomfortable. } (7... Qf6! { Not playable if you're not already up a rook on move 1. But why not sacrifice d5 and at least get on with development? } 8. Bxd5+ Be6 $19) 8. Nc3 { Development with a threat! } (8. d4? { This move doesn't actually open the position. After Nxd4, black is simply centralizing their knight with tempo. } 8... Nxd4 $19) (8. O-O? $19 { Desirable, but not forcing enough. We are down a knight and rook! We need dynamic moves now! }) 8... Nd4?! { Black goes on the offensive rather than defend d5 with either Ne7 or Nb4. } (8... Nb4!? $19 { The main line of the fried liver is much stronger here. Black defends the knight and therefore remains up a rook. }) (8... Ne7!? $19 { The main line of the fried liver is much stronger here. Black defends the knight and therefore remains up a rook. }) 9. Bxd5+ (9. Qxd5+? { We cannot afford to trade queens while down so much material! } 9... Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Kd6 $19) (9. Nxd5?? { Oh no, your queen! } 9... Nxf3+! 10. gxf3 Qxd5 11. Bxd5+ Kxd5 $19) 9... Kd6 { This is arguably the most instructive position in this game.
Yes, black's king is on the run. But our queen is under attack, c2 is hanging with check, and black's king is only two moves away from safety after c6+Kc7.
With black's king seemingly slipping out of our grasp, how do we continue the king hunt? } 10. Qf7!! { An excellent move that showcases a deep understanding of how to conduct a king hunt. Black's king is cut off from retreating to safety.
PRO TIP: "Cutting" the king off from safety is the top priority in a king hunt. As long as their king is forced to run up the board towards your army, even at the cost of more material, good things will happen.
The main line to calculate is c6?? Ne4#! Black's king is not escaping the center today! } (10. Qd3? { Saves the queen and defends c2. Yet after c6, Banywhere, and Kc7, black's king is finally safe and they remain up a rook. } 10... c6 11. Be4 Kc7 $19) (10. Qg3?! { Keeping pressure on e5 doesn't prevent black's plan of c6+Kc7. Even if they hang the e pawn with check, blocking on d6 with their queen is fine for them. White has no attack. } 10... c6 11. Be4 Kc7 12. Qxe5+ Qd6! $19) (10. Nb5+? { A tempting check, but black's knight on d4 covers this square. Did you lose your grip on the board? } 10... Nxb5 $19) 10... Be6?? { A sensible, but losing move. This move is sensible because they are developing while preventing Ne4+ from mating. Yet their king remains cut off from safety. Therefore, their king must walk further up the board in response to our forcing moves. This is a king-hunter's dream!
Better would have been Qe7, giving their king the d7 square (relative safety, given his current residence!) in response to any checks. } (10... Qe7! { Ugly, but at least black has the d7 square to retreat to. } 11. Ne4+ Kd7 $19 { White continues attacking with all the pieces, but black has mostly extricated their king from the dangerous center of the board. }) (10... c6?? 11. Ne4#) 11. Bxe6 (11. Ne4+?? { This tempting check forces black's king further up the board. But after Kxd5, we have no more pieces to attack with! } 11... Kxd5 12. c4+ Kxe4 13. Qf3+ Nxf3+ $19) 11... Nxe6 { For the second time this game, black's king is a crucial defender of an otherwise loose knight.
PRO TIP: The king is the worst defender. Because the opponent must respond to any check in the position, the king can easily be overworked or deflected while defending a piece.
Keep up the king hunt with forcing moves! } 12. Ne4+! { An important follow-up before black has time to develop more pieces. Now, Black's king cannot safely defend their knight unless he walks deeper into white's territory. } (12. Nb5+? { A worse version of the game. After Kc6, black wins a tempo on this knight, while not having to commit up the board. } 12... Kc6 13. Qxe6+ Kxb5 14. a4+ Ka5 { This position might be tempting if white had more pieces in the game. With only the queen cutting off the king, there is no way to continue the king hunt. } 15. d3 Bb4+! $19 { "No Bd2+ for you!" } (15... c6!? 16. Bd2+ Kb6 17. a5+ Kc7 $19 { Black's king escapes to safety. })) 12... Kd5?! { Walking further into the belly of the beast.
Black remains up a rook, even though neither is participating in this game at all. Therefore, it would have been better to part ways with their knight and instead develop with Kc6 Qxe6+ Bd6. In that line, black has returned all their extra material, but at least is not getting mated.
How can we continue the king hunt? } (12... Kc6! 13. Qxe6+ Bd6 $14) 13. c4+! { Dragging the king deeper into white's camp. Yes, white's knight is undefended, but black's king is leading the charge with no way back to safety now. } (13. Nc3+? { After Kd6, black's king is not driven further up the board. In fact, he is one move away from Qe7+Kd7, escaping to safety. } 13... Kd6 14. Ne4+ Kd5?! (14... Kc6! $14) 15. c4+! $18 { At least white can seemingly repeat the position. }) 13... Kxe4 { Black accepts the "free" piece, but at what cost? } (13... Kc6?! { Now it is too late for Kc6. White has one more attacker, and so white wins after the following forcing line: } 14. Qxe6+ Bd6 15. Qd5+ Kd7 (15... Kb6?? 16. Qb5#) 16. c5! $18) (13... Kd4?! 14. Qf3! $18 { b3+Bb2# is almost unstoppable. }) 14. Qxe6 { Black's king is once again cut. Kf4 walks into d3#. Kd4 doesn't escape either after d3! } (14. Qf3+? { You must calculate 3-ply before pulling the trigger on such a move. We don't have enough pieces in the attack to justify not recapturing. After Kd4, black is threatening both Kxc4 and Kc5, escaping. } 14... Kd4 15. Qc3+!? (15. Qe3+!? Kxc4 $19) 15... Kc5 $19) 14... Qd4?! { Rather than accomplish anything active, this queen move takes away one more square from the black king. Regardless, black's position was dire. } (14... Kd3!? 15. Qg4! $18 { Cut the king! The threat is Kd1+Re1+Re3#. }) (14... Kf4?? 15. d3#!) (14... Kd4?! 15. d3! Kxd3 16. O-O $18 { All of white's remaining pieces will mate the king. } { [%cal Gc1e3,Gf1d1] }) 15. Qg4+ { Another forcing move that prevents the king from running up the board! } (15. Ke2!! $18 { This move is also mating. Yet what are you playing in response to Qd3+? } 15... Qd3+!? { The only try. But now white's rook gets into the game too. } (15... Qxf2+!? 16. Kxf2 Rd8 $18) 16. Kd1! { The point of white's two-step was to vacate the e file for the rook! } 16... Kf4 17. Re1 { Bringing all the boys to the party! Re4+!! is the threat. } 17... Be7!? 18. Re4+!! Kg5!? (18... Qxe4!? 19. d3+! Qe3 20. Bxe3#) (18... Kxe4!? 19. Qg4#) 19. Qxe7+ Kh6 20. Rh4+ Kg6 21. Rg4+ Kf5 22. Rg5+ Kf4 23. Qxe5# { A successful king hunt! }) (15. d3+?! { Not the most precise. Qxd3 is mated by Qg4#. But after Kxd3, black's king is dangerously placed but also threatening to escape via e4 or c4 at every opportunity. } 15... Kxd3 16. O-O! Kc2!? 17. Be3! Qd3 18. Qxe5! { Cutting the king again! Rc1# is unstoppable. } 18... Qxf1+! 19. Kxf1 $16 { White has restored material equality and keeps a raging attack. }) (15. f3+?? { After Kd3, black is always threatening to escape via c4 and c2. We need more firepower! } 15... Kd3 $19) (15. O-O?! { Prepares Re1+, but our king helped weave mating nets in the center, whereas on g1 it serves no active role. } 15... Kd3! 16. c5!! $16 { Qb3+ is threatened, and white keeps an advantage. }) (15. Kd1! $18 { A nice move to prepare Re1+, bringing more boys to the party, while still controlling some squares around black's king. Play Qg4+ instead for the game continuation. }) 15... Kd3 { Black is desperate to play Kxc4 and escape towards the queenside. } 16. Qe2+! { PRO TIP: A strong grip on the board is necessary to successfully hunt your opponent's king. At every point, you need to clearly visualize which squares around their king you control. If you miss even a single escape route, your opponent's king may slip away and your king hunt will end in failure. } (16. Qf3+?? { You lost your grip on the board! After Kxc4, black's king is escaping to safety. } 16... Kxc4 17. b3+ Kc5 18. Qxb7 { Cutting the king! At least white has a draw here: } 18... Qd5! 19. Ba3+! Kd4 20. Bb2+ Kc5 21. Ba3+ $10) (16. b3?? { Oh no, your queen! } 16... Qxg4 $19) 16... Kc2 { Black's king is forced even further into the belly of the beast... } 17. d3+ (17. Qd1+! { Also mating since Kd3 doesn't escape after Qb3+ Ke4, Qf3#. Play d3+ instead for the game continuation. } 17... Kd3 18. Qb3+ Ke4 19. Qf3#) (17. O-O?? { A tempting move, but white has no way to continue the attack after Qd3! } 17... Qd3 18. Qd1+ Kb1! 19. b4!? Rd8 $10) 17... Kxc1?! { Black scores a touchdown with their king, but our two remaining pieces are enough to mate. } (17... Kb1!? { The better try. } 18. O-O! Kxa2!? (18... Bc5!? 19. Be3+ Kxa2 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Qc2! $18 { Black's king is once again cut. The queen and rook can easily weave a mating net. }) 19. Qc2! $18 { There is no way to prevent b3+, mating. }) 18. O-O#! { How often do you get the opportunity to castle with checkmate? Such beauty is only reserved for the craziest king hunts.
At every moment, our goal was to bring the king closer and closer towards our army, lying in wait. Forcing moves were preferred, but even quiet moves that cut the king led to success.
As long as king safety remains the primary concern, material (statics) and sometimes even time (dynamics) can take a back seat in the evaluation of a position. } (18. Qd1+! { Also mating, albeit less artistic. } 18... Kxb2 19. Qb3+ Kc1 20. Ke2#) 1-0


[Event "Anderssen - Morphy"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.12.27"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Adolf Anderssen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ECO "B44"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Taimanov Variation, Szén Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Claustrophobia"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/N9tMegUQ"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Round 10 of the titanic match between Morphy and Anderssen. Having just won a game against Morphy with 1. a3!?, Anderssen was looking to continue the struggle in lesser known theoretical waters with black as well.

Anderssen was a strong opponent for Morphy. Therefore, this king hunt will not be a one-sided affair like the last games. Morphy will have to balance attack and defense in order to successfully drag black's king out. }
1. e4 c5 { The Sicilian was rarely played in the 1800s, since it doesn't develop the pieces as soon as possible. Regardless, this asymmetric way to hold up white's control of the center remains one of the main ways to play for a win against 1. e4 even today. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 2. d4 cxd4 { The point of the Sicilian was to prevent white from dominating the center. So when white plays d4, this capture is logical to avoid being overruled. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 3. Nf3 { Morphy once more allows gambit play. e5 is playable, holding onto the d pawn for good, as in "Tempo fiend" ( https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/l1PmGO1g ), even if it is not necessarily best. } 3... Nc6 { Anderssen is not interested in entering a gambit against Morphy. This sensible developing move brings the position back into an Open Sicilian. } 4. Nxd4 { Of course moving the knight a second time does not break any opening principles. White has not lost time in this position because black had to "waste" a tempo with cxd4.
The knight on d4 is centralized and active. Meanwhile, all of white's pieces (especially the bishops) are ready to develop to active squares next. If anyone has a lead in development in this position, it can only be white. } (4. Qxd4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 4... Nxd4 $19) 4... e6 { The Taimanov variation of the Open Sicilian rose to prominence in the middle of the 20th century as a key fighting ground in the Sicilian. } { [%cal Gd4b5] } 5. Nb5!? { The first moment in the game that should give us pause. White is now clearly losing a tempo with this knight, with the justification that Nd6+ (winning the DSB) is an important positional threat.
Is it though?
The finer details behind the interplay between time and positional considerations is beyond this study. Yet I will leave you with the following statistic: in modern times, masters play Nc3 (developing and controlling the center) more than 10x as often as Nb5. } 5... d6 { Black correctly prevents Nd6+ (the queen now lends support to d6), while further controlling the center. } { [%cal Gc1f4] } 6. Bf4 e5 { Black once more denies white access to d6 while gaining time. In contrast to his usual style, in this game Morphy is arguing on behalf of subtle strategic aims while disregarding the loss of tempo. } 7. Be3 { The battleground has been set. White has the d file: the d6 pawn is a target and the d5 square is a strong post for a piece. Black has a strong center and the potential to gain even more time against white's pieces.
Objectively speaking, this position is equal. } (7. Bg5?? { This bishop can be successfully captured. After Qxg5 Nc7+ Kd8 Nxa8, the knight on a8 is trapped and will inevitably be lost, leading to an imbalance of two pieces for the rook. Black is better. } 7... Qxg5 8. Nc7+ Kd8 9. Nxa8 Nf6 10. Nc3 Nd4! 11. Qd3 d5! $17) (7. Bg3?! $10 { On this square, our bishop is biting on granite. }) (7. Bd2?! $15 { We should never be interested in this half-developing move. The bishop interferes with many of our pieces. }) (7. Bc1?! $15 { Frankly, ridiculous. }) 7... f5?! { Breaking down white's center makes sense. Unfortunately, as we shall see in the game, weakening black's king to do so is a recipe for disaster.
Nf6, developing and attacking white's center, was significantly stronger. } { [%cal Gb1c3] } (7... Nf6!? 8. N1c3 a6 9. Na3 $10 { The main way to play this position. Only after white has committed a knight to c3 should the b5 knight be banished to the side of the board. }) 8. N1c3 f4 { Black weakens their king and wastes two tempi trying to push back our bishop? No way! } (8... a6!? 9. Nd5! axb5 10. Bb6 $16 { White wins the exchange. }) (8... Nf6!? 9. Bg5! $16 { With full control over d5. }) 9. Nd5! { The first of many precise moves! The fork on c7, winning the rook on a8, cannot be prevented. Therefore, white essentially wins the exchange in every line. White already has the initiative.
Presumably, Anderssen missed this move during the game. } (9. Qh5+? { An empty check. After g6, both the queen and bishop are attacked. White loses a piece. } 9... g6 $19) (9. Nc7+?? $19 { A losing check. After Qxc7, white simply hangs a knight. }) 9... fxe3 { Black snags the piece while they can. What else is there? } (9... Kf7!? { Prevents the fork, but at what cost? } 10. Bd2 Nf6 11. Nxf6 Qxf6 12. Nc7 Rb8 13. Bc4+ Kg6 $16 { Another king hunt in the making. }) (9... Rb8?! 10. Bc4! Nf6 11. Ndc7+! Ke7 12. Nd5+ Ke8!? (12... Nxd5?! 13. Qxd5 $16 { The light squares are falling apart. Black's king is ready to go for a journey. }) 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Bxa7 Nxa7 15. Nxa7 $16) 10. Nbc7+ { PRO TIP: An important skill in chess is following through with your plans. "If you say A, you should next say B!" If you suddenly get distracted and play C instead, you won't ultimately accomplish your goals.
Rather than changing your mind in the middle of executing a (hopefully short!) plan, it is better to calculate the ramifications of your different plans before committing to one. With that framework, your calculations should not branch too broadly. In your calculations, your moves are simply following through with your plans; your opponent's moves are any and all forcing sequences that attempt to refute those plans. If they cannot easily frustrate your plan, go ahead and play the first move.
The point of Nd5 last move was to threaten a fork on c7. Therefore, following through with this fork on the king and rook is the only coherent follow-up. } (10. Ndc7+?! { The worse check. Leaving the knight on d5 gives us more flexibility in the long term, so the more adaptable move is Nbc7+. } 10... Ke7 11. Nd5+ Kf7 12. Qf3+ Nf6 $17) 10... Kf7 { The beginning of a brutal king hunt. } 11. Qf3+!? { Rather than simply win the exchange with Nxa8, Morphy sets his eyes on the bigger prize: black's king. Morphy was never a materialist, so kicking off a king hunt was actually Morphy's plan the entire time. } (11. Nxa8!? { This simple recapture is best. Morphy probably didn't want to allow exf2+ when his king is slightly exposed.
Instead he opts for more complications with Qf3+. } 11... exf2+ 12. Kxf2 $16) (11. Bc4?! { A logical continuation. Yet what are you doing after exf2+? } 11... exf2+! 12. Kxf2 Rb8! { Amazingly, there is no deadly discovered check! } 13. Nf4+!? d5!! 14. Bxd5+ Ke7 $19) (11. Qh5+? { A worse version of the game. After g6 (the only legal move!), black's king will find some shelter on g7. } 11... g6 12. Qf3+ Kg7 $17) (11. fxe3!? { Can we really afford a time out to recapture on f3 and open the f file towards black's king? Impressively, the answer is yes! Play Qf3+ instead for the game continuation. } 11... Rb8 12. Qf3+ Nf6 13. Bc4 Na5! 14. Nxf6+ Nxc4 15. Nfe8+! Kg6!? (15... Kg8? 16. O-O { Black's king is not escaping. } 16... Qe7 17. Qg3 $18 { The threat of Nf6+! cannot be prevented. }) 16. O-O $10 { The king hunt continues. }) 11... Nf6 { Thankfully, black can block this check, rather than run their king further up the board to g6, begging to get mated. Still, white has a lot of attackers in this position that can actualize a king hunt. } (11... Kg6? $16 { Now black's king is surely going to get hunted down. }) 12. Bc4 { Development with a threat! As always, Morphy brings all of his pieces into the attack.
PRO TIP: The difference between a sacrifice that kicks off a successful king hunt, and an ineffective sacrifice that simply forces your opponent's king to move is the follow-up. An imprecise rule of thumb is that you should have 3/4 of the following after sacrificing: (1) you have enough developed pieces to create decisive threats, (2) your opponent must respond with further king moves, losing more time, (3) you can bring in more attackers with tempo, and/or (4) your opponent's king is cut off from safety. } (12. Nxa8? { Now this capture is ill-timed. After Nd4, black kicks our queen away and retakes the initiative. } 12... Nd4! 13. Qd1 (13. Qxe3?? Nxc2+ $19) 13... Bg4! 14. f3 Nxd5 15. exd5 Bxf3! 16. gxf3?? Qh4# { Who is attacking whom? }) (12. Nxf6!? { Not a bad move, since Bc4+ will hit next. Switch the move order instead for the game continuation. } 12... Nd4 13. Bc4+ d5! $10 { Transposes to the game. }) 12... Nd4 { Another example of "active defense," a concept we will fully explore next chapter. Black ignores the discovered check and improves their knight with tempo instead. } (12... Bg4?? 13. Nxf6+! d5 14. Nxg4+ $18) 13. Nxf6+ { We are winning a full knight with check. What could go wrong? } 13... d5!! { A fantastic resource! All of white's minor pieces want to use the d5 square, so this tricky interference shot forces one of our pieces to step on the toes of the others. } (13... Ke7? 14. Nfd5+ Kd7 15. Qf7+ Be7 16. O-O-O! { The Morphy move! } 16... Rf8 17. Rxd4!! Rxf7 18. Bb5# { Another successful king hunt! }) 14. Bxd5+ (14. Nfxd5+?? { Oh no, your queen! } 14... Nxf3+ $19) 14... Kg6? { The losing move, but defending this position after Ke7 against Morphy was probably a hopeless task too.
This is a DDD moment. Black only needs to recapture on f6 and play h6 for their king to find shelter on h7. To make matters worse, our queen is also already attacked. If there is no way to break through right here and right now, there might not be a second chance. } (14... Ke7! 15. Qh5!? (15. Ng8+!? Kd6 16. Nb5+ Nxb5 17. O-O-O $10) 15... gxf6 16. Qf7+ Kd6 17. Nxa8 Nxc2+ 18. Ke2 $10 { A line Tartakower showed to be drawn more than a century ago. }) 15. Qh5+! (15. Qg3+! { Another winning option. Play Qh5+ instead for the game continuation. } 15... Kxf6 16. fxe3 $18 { Rf1+ is winning, as in the game. }) (15. Bf7+?? { A useless check. After Kxf7, there is no follow-up. } 15... Kxf7 $19) 15... Kxf6 { Black has snapped off our knight, emerging up a piece again. But the king still has no protection, while almost all of the squares around him are covered by our pieces. He is no doubt feeling claustrophobia in this position.
How best to continue? } 16. fxe3! { Excellent job! This is one of several winning options, all of which revolve around opening up the position towards black's king. } (16. Qf7+? { The most tempting move, yet amazingly there is no follow-up after Kg5. Surprisingly, white has no pieces to control the dark squares on the kingside. } 16... Kg5 17. c3 $15 (17. h4+? Kh6 $19 { Black is safe. })) (16. Qh4+?? { After g5! there is no follow-up. } 16... g5 $19) (16. Ne8+?? { A tempting move, but black can capture this knight! When our queen recaptures on e8, she is undefended, ultimately falling after Bb4+. } 16... Qxe8! 17. Qxe8 Bb4+! 18. c3 Rxe8 $19) (16. f4! $18 { Equally winning. The threats of fxe5+, Qxe5+, and Qg5+ are all crushing. Play fxe3 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. O-O! $16 { Nicely done! Placing the rook opposite black's king puts him under further heat. Moreover, Ne8+ is now a deadly threat. Play fxe3 instead for the game continuation. } 16... e2 17. Ne8+! { Now this move works! } 17... Ke7?! (17... Qxe8!? 18. Qxe8 exf1=Q+ 19. Kxf1 $18) 18. Qf7#) (16. Nxa8!? $16 { We're now able to snag the exchange successfully. Black cannot afford to do the same against us with Nxc2+ since their king is too vulnerable. Play for mate instead. } 16... Nxc2+ 17. Ke2 Nxa1 18. f4! $18) (16. h4!? { The duel threats of Qg5# and Qf7# are crushing. Play fxe3 for the game continuation. } 16... g6!? 17. Qg5+ Kg7 18. Qxe5+ Kh6 19. Qxd4 $18) (16. O-O-O? { Connecting the rooks doesn't bring more firepower into the attack against black's king. After Qxc7, there is no follow-up. } 16... Qxc7 $19) (16. Rf1?! $16 { A worse version of O-O, albeit still better for white. Play fxe3 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. Qxe5+?? { Oh no, your queen! } 16... Kxe5 $19) (16. Qf5+?? { Oh no, your queen! } 16... Bxf5 $19) 16... Nxc2+ { A spite check. Black can neither prevent nor take the sting out of Rf1+. } (16... Qxc7!? 17. O-O+ Ke7 18. Rf7+ Kd8 19. Rxc7 $18 { White has won material and keeps a raging attack. }) 17. Ke2 $18 { Morphy avoids the final trick (Kd1?? Bg4+!!), so Anderssen resigns. Black's king has no means of escaping the kill box Morphy's pieces have set up. Rf1+ is still coming next, with deadly effect. In contrast, white's king is not under attack from any of black's pieces.
In this game, White possessed all four preconditions for a successful king hunt. White had enough developed pieces to create decisive threats, black had to respond with further king moves (losing more time), white brought in more attackers with tempo, and black's king was cut off from safety. Even so, it took a good grip on the board and the Morphy mindset to bring home the win. } (17. Kd2!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Ke2 instead for the game continuation. }) (17. Kd1?? { Oh no, your queen! After Bg4+! your queen is attracted to a forking square. Ne3+ is a savage continuation. } 17... Bg4+!! 18. Qxg4 Nxe3+! $19) (17. Kf2? { We want to use the f file to attack black's king. Why are you preventing your own rook from using the file? } 17... Qxc7 $17) (17. Kf1? { We want to use the f file to attack black's king. Why are you preventing your own rook from using the file? } 17... Qxc7 $17) 1-0


