{ Now let's summarize this chapter on king hunts while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { * A king hunt is defined by your opponent's king running for his life to avoid checkmate. It often starts with a timely sacrifice to force your opponent's king to walk up the board closer to your pieces. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { * In the middle of a king hunt, focus on forcing moves that prevent the king from escaping back to safety. If the king is forced up the board towards your army, you have a good chance of weaving mating nets. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { * "Cutting" the king off from safety is the top priority in a king hunt. As long as their king is forced to run up the board towards your army, even at the cost of more material, good things will happen. } { [%cal Gb2b4] } 4. b4 Bxb4 { * The difference between a sacrifice that kicks off a successful king hunt, and an ineffective sacrifice that simply forces their king to move is the follow-up. An imprecise rule of thumb is that you should have 3/4 of the following after sacrificing: (1) you have enough developed pieces to create decisive threats, (2) your opponent must respond with further king moves, losing more time (3) you can bring in more attackers with tempo, (4) your opponent's king is cut off from safety. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 Bc5 { * A strong grip on the board is necessary to successfully hunt your opponent's king. At every point, you need to clearly visualize which squares around their king you control. If you miss even a single escape route, your opponent's king may slip away and your king hunt will end in failure. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 6. O-O d6 { * If your king is exposed, ensure that it is only temporary! King safety issues can be fatal. Not only does checkmate end the game, but an exposed king underlies many tactical motifs. Therefore, at the earliest opportunity, you should bring your king to safety before your opponent can execute a decisive king hunt. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 7. d4 Bb6 { * The commonly repeated phrase, "don't move the same piece twice in the opening," is overrated advice. In fact, there are many situations where moving a piece twice is objectively best. As we have seen in Chapter I, the correct advice should be: "don't lose time in the opening."
Let's consider a few instances of when that superficial phrase fails: Firstly, when your piece is threatened, you must move it again to avoid losing material. Secondly, generating a threat is more important than simple development in some critical positions, like a DDD moment. Indeed, moving an already developed piece again may be the best way to blow open the position. Thirdly, improving your piece to its best square may take several moves. In closed positions, you should look to optimize your pieces right out of the opening; knights are particularly slow to reach their optimal square. } { [%cal Gd4e5] } 8. dxe5 dxe5 { * The king is the worst defender. Because the opponent must respond to any check in the position, the king can easily be overworked or deflected while defending a piece. } { [%cal Gd1b3] } 9. Qb3 Qf6 { * An important skill in chess is following through with your plans. "If you say A, you should next say B!" If you suddenly get distracted and play C instead, you won't ultimately accomplish your goals.
Rather than changing your mind in the middle of executing a (hopefully short!) plan, it is better to calculate the ramifications of your different plans before committing to one. With that framework, your calculations should not branch too broadly. In your calculations, your moves are simply following through with your plans; your opponent's moves are any and all forcing sequences that attempt to refute those plans. If they cannot easily frustrate your plan, go ahead and play the first move. } { [%cal Gc4b5] } 10. Bb5 Be6?! { (Please enjoy the rest of this unannotated Morphy miniature. Black's king remains safe for now, but the king hunt is soon to commence!) } { [%cal Gb3a4] } (10... Bd7!? $19) 11. Qa4 Ne7 { [%cal Gc1g5] } 12. Bg5 Qg6 { [%cal Gg5e7] } 13. Bxe7 { (The king hunt begins!) } 13... Kxe7 { [%cal Gb5c6] } 14. Bxc6 bxc6 { [%cal Gf3e5] } 15. Nxe5 Qf6? { [%cal Ge5c6] } (15... Qg5!? 16. Nxc6+ Kf8 { The king escapes to safety. No mate! } 17. Qa3+ Bc5! $19) 16. Nxc6+ Kf8?? { [%cal Ge4e5] } (16... Ke8! { Necessary, but scary. Amazingly, there is no discovered check that wrecks black's position. } 17. e5 Qg5! { There still is no threat. } 18. Rad1 $17) 17. e5! Qg5 { [%cal Gh2h4] } 18. h4! Qg4 { [%cal Ga4a3] } 19. Qa3+ Kg8 { [%cal Gc6e7] } 20. Ne7+ Kf8 { [%cal Ge7g6] } 21. Ng6+ Kg8 { [%cal Ga3f8] } 22. Qf8+ Rxf8 { [%cal Gg6e7] } 23. Ne7# { One of the first recorded smothered mates in history!
For more resources exploring king hunts, check out:
* ChessNetwork https://youtu.be/DL6jYi5pvqM
* kingscrusher https://youtu.be/6XDe1Hy886I
* GothamChess https://youtu.be/Apbs8auwPl0
* GMBenjaminFinegold https://youtu.be/PSOGZSPyhgA } 1-0


