{ Chapter V: Active defense

This next chapter will focus on how to defend against someone going straight after your king. The key insight is that we should not defend passively, but match our opponent's active play with our own.

PRO TIP: Active defense is nothing more than fighting for the initiative even when your opponent is trying to generate threats. }
 *


[Event "Consultation game"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1858.11.??"]
[White "Pierre de Saint-Amant / Marie Florimond de Basterot"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ECO "C54"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Classical Variation, Greco Gambit, Traditional Line"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Active defense vs passive defense"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/8lqsghjm"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ As in the Opera Game, Morphy faces off against two players discussing what moves to play together. This is known as a consultation game.

Fifteen years before this consultation game, one of the white players, Pierre de Saint-Amant, lost an unofficial world chess championship match against Howard Staunton. This loss cemented Staunton as the best player of Europe and Saint-Amant as a mere challenger.

Fast forward to 1858: Morphy toured Paris and crushed everyone, while Saint-Amant was clearly no longer near the top of the world. Saint-Amant instead admired Morphy's genius. Rather than requesting an official match against Morphy, he simply desired to play this casual game against Morphy. }
1. e4 { This game opens with an Italian. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { The Italian continues with 2... Nc6. } 2... Nc6 (2... d6!? $14 { Play Nc6 instead for the game continuation. }) (2... Nf6!? $10 { Play Nc6 instead for the game continuation. }) 3. Bc4 { We have already seen Morphy play the white side of the Italian, one of the oldest openings in chess. Now we will explore how he handles the black side of this position. } 3... Bc5 (3... Nf6!? $10 { Play Bc5 instead for the game continuation. }) (3... Be7!? $10 { Play Bc5 instead for the game continuation. }) (3... d6?! $14 { Blocks in your DSB for no reason. Find a better developing move. }) (3... Nge7? $14 { Blocks in your DSB for no reason. Find a better developing move. }) (3... h6?! $14 { Morphy would never lose time for no reason. Are you scared of Ng5? You shouldn't be! This is a chapter on active defense, so we will explore how to avoid such mental traps throughout this chapter. }) 4. c3 { White opts for the main line of the Italian, rather than the swashbuckling Evans Gambit. The point of c3 is of course to prepare d4, with tempo on our DSB. In contrast to the Evans, however, this move does not gain any time.
In view of white's incoming threat, how best should we handle the position? } 4... Nf6 { Of course, Nf6 is the most principled move in the position as it is a developing move with a threat to the e pawn. In fact, we should consider this a prime candidate move without calculating any variations or considering any consequences of the move.
But what about white's plan to play d4 with tempo? Indeed, Nf6 does not address white's threat at all. Morphy plays against their plan by ignoring it and instead pushing through his own plan.
PRO TIP: Active defense is nothing more than fighting for the initiative even when your opponent is trying to generate threats. Rather than responding directly to your opponent, you should look for dynamic moves that push through your agenda instead. } (4... d6?! $14 { This is a developing move, but not one that comes with any threat. Look for better. }) (4... Qe7? $14 { The queen is misplaced on e7, as an eventual Bg5 will come with tempo. Have you forgotten the lesson from Chapter III? }) (4... Qf6? $16 { The queen is misplaced on f6, as an eventual Bg5 will come with tempo. Have you forgotten the lesson from Chapter III? }) (4... Nge7? $16 { This is a strictly worse version of Nf6. }) (4... Nh6? $16 { Technically a developing move, but the knight on h6 looks ridiculous. Why are you misplacing your piece for no reason? As we shall soon see, Nh6 is textbook passive defense - something we wish to avoid. }) 5. d4 { d3, responding to black's threat to e4, has become the main way to play the Italian in modern times. White maintains more tension in the position but has to compromise - they will not achieve a strong center with tempo. Black wins the battle for the initiative.
In contrast, d4 is a full-steam-ahead move that tries to push black off the board immediately, and is therefore the most critical option. It is important though that white is technically behind in development, and therefore shouldn't have the right to push black off the board at such an early stage.
Morphy will show us how active defense can refute white's overeager central expansion in this game. } { [%cal Ge5d4] } 5... exd4 6. cxd4 { By including the pawn trade on d4, Morphy has opened up a new diagonal towards white's king. } 6... Bb4+! { The justification behind black's play. With this check, black regains a crucial tempo. Morphy's earlier threat to the e4 pawn drastically limits white's options. } (6... Be7? { Passively responding to white's threat. After e5, white's center pushes onwards with devastating effect. } 7. e5! d5? 8. exf6 dxc4 9. fxe7 $18) (6... Bb6? { Passively responding to white's threat. After e5, white's center pushes onwards with devastating effect. } 7. e5! d5 8. exf6 dxc4 9. d5! $16) (6... Bd6?? { Walking directly into a pawn fork! } 7. e5 $18) (6... Nxe4?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 7. dxc5 $18) (6... Bf8? $16 { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! }) (6... Nxd4?? { Oh no, your knight! } 7. Nxd4 Bxd4 8. Qxd4 $18) 7. Bd2 { Nc3 was the most convenient way white had to block this check. Unfortunately, due to black's earlier active play, black has Nxe4 in response to Nc3, winning a clean pawn. } { [%cal Gb4d2] } (7. Nc3?! Nxe4 $15) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2 { Of course, white would have preferred to recapture with the queen, since white's queenside knight is better placed on c3. However, black's threat to e4 forces this sad recapture.
The position is still sharp. Given one more move, white will run us over with their center. Both d5 and e5 are coming to scatter our knights to the side of the board. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } 8... d5! { More active defense!
Black wants to develop the LSB and challenge the center. So d5 is a top candidate move regardless of white's desires.
Yet once we consider white's threats to play d5 and/or e5, we see that this move also has the happy consequence of hindering white's plans to realize the dynamic potential of their unchecked center.
PRO TIP: The best defense is a good offense! Championing your own plans even in the face of your opponent's threats is precisely how to play active defense. } (8... d6?! $14 { Does not challenge the center directly. }) (8... Nxe4! 9. Nxe4 d5! $10 { The center fork trick is another way to equalize in the center using active defense. }) 9. exd5 { White's center has been broken up, killing its dynamic potential. } 9... Nxd5 10. O-O { The dust has settled and black has won the battle of the opening. White's d pawn is more of a liability than a strength, and thus is a static weakness. Moreover, white does not have a lead in development or other dynamic advantage to compensate for their static disadvantage. } 10... O-O { We have previously discussed that when debating between several candidate moves, we should play the most adaptable option first. This position is another example showcasing this concept.
In every continuation, black needs to castle kingside. Perhaps the bishop will end up on e6, or perhaps f5 or g4. Perhaps the queen will develop towards the kingside or perhaps it will recapture on d5. We simple don't have enough information yet to determine those pieces' optimal squares.
Indeed, castling is the most adaptable and best option. } (10... Be6!? $10 { Another sensible, albeit inflexible developing move. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) 11. h3?! { White prevents Bg4, but this is just a clear loss of time. Developing either rook to an open file was clearly better. } { [%cal Gd5f4] } 11... Nf4 { Nf4 is not the only move. In fact, Bf5 instead was a more principled and potentially stronger alternative.
However, sensing some soft light squares on white's kingside, Morphy decides to pounce and build towards an attack. Nf4 is a step in that direction.
In this position, white completely falls apart. } 12. Kh2? { An unexplainable move. White simply hangs the d4 pawn for no compensation. } 12... Nxd4 (12... Qxd4?? { Oh no, your queen! Check your move order! } 13. Nxd4 Nxd4 $18) (12... Qd6!? $17 { A good move, echoing what later happens in the game. Play Nxd4 instead for the game continuation. }) 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qc2 { White is down a pawn, but at least has finished development.
There are a variety of winning methods from such a dominant position, including trading pieces and winning with the extra pawn on the queenside. Methodical and slow methods use black's static advantage of the extra pawn to convert the full point.
Morphy opts for a different method. His one-track mind is on full display as he decides to use the dynamic potential of black's more active pieces to attack white's king. The fact that he has already won a pawn does not affect his decision. } { [%cal Gd4d6] } 14... Qd6!? { One of several good moves. Morphy lines up with white's king, setting up several deadly discovered checks with the knight (such as Nxh3+).
PRO TIP: Alignments create threats! Even when you're not completely in control of how the position will open up, lining up your less valuable pieces opposite your opponent's more valuable pieces will inevitably create tactical opportunities down the road. } 15. Kh1? { White directly responds to black's threat by escaping the alignment with black's queen. However, this move otherwise does not improve white's position; the king is not better placed on h1 except in response to black's last threat.
PRO TIP: One-dimensional defensive moves should be avoided. If all you are doing is defending your opponent's threats, the initiative swings fully to your opponent, and you will inevitably get blown off the board.
The term "passive defense" describes such soft play, and it is just as much a chess concept as it is a mentality. Constantly defending (without improving your position) and praying your opponent does not have enough to kill you rarely works out.
You must challenge your opponent and fight for the initiative even in the face of threats! Active defense!
In the previous position, Ne4! (improving the placement of the knight with tempo on black's queen) was necessary. Importantly, if black maintained the alignment of the queen and king with Qe5, white had Ng3, blocking the diagonal for good while bringing in another defender to the kingside. Textbook active defense.
Play Qh6 for the game continuation. } (15. Ne4! Qe5 16. Ng3! $17) 15... Qh6 { Alignments create threats! The queen is once again opposite white's king, and so Bxh3 is a new threat. The queen is also opposite white's d2 knight too, limiting white's options that defend Bxh3. } 16. Qc3 { Somewhat active defense. The queen defends h3 directly and is somewhat better placed on c3, where she can see the entire third rank, than on c2, where she had limited mobility. } { [%cal Gc8f5] } 16... Bf5 { There were more explosive options available to black, but this principled move finishes development and prepares to bring the rooks into the game. } 17. Kh2? { More passive defense. White is bolstering h3 further, but is once again not improving their position.
A more active defense would have been Rfe1, developing a rook to the open file, followed by Re3. Black would still be bolstering h3, but this maneuver would simultaneously improve the placement of the rooks. } 17... Rad8 { Bringing all the boys to the party! There are now two threats in the position: Rxd2, deflecting the queen from h3, and another beautiful shot we see in the game... } (17... Rfd8!? $19 { Just as good. Play Rad8 instead for the game continuation. }) (17... Rae8? $17 { This moves does not accomplish anything killer after white responds with Rfe1. }) (17... Rfe8? { This moves does not accomplish anything killer after white responds with Rfe1. } 18. Rfe1 $17) (17... b5!? $19 { A winning shot but only if black follows up as in the game. }) (17... Bxh3! $19 { Nice tactical vision! Indeed, this move order also works. Play Rad8 first for the game continuation. }) 18. Rad1 { Finally, white develops a rook. But it is too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games...
This move defends against Rxd2 but not Morphy's second threat. Can you find it? } 18... Bxh3! { The beginning of a winning sequence.
White's king is on the chopping block because all of black's pieces except the f8 rook are attacking. The only defender is the white queen on c3. Given more moves, however, white would love to play Rfe1->e3 and defend more solidly. Therefore, this is the DDD moment.
There should be no surprise that there is a tactic available in the position, as this disparity in activity is a direct consequence of white's passive defense.
If you didn't spot this move, I suggest you pause now and calculate the follow-up to justify this sacrifice. } (18... Rd3?? { The right idea but the wrong execution. After Bxd3 Bxh3, white does not have to recapture. First inserting Bxh7+! is a nice way to directly defend h3 with the queen. Active defense! After that sequence, white is the one who will emerge up the exchange.
The secret to good technique is good calculation! } 19. Bxd3 Bxh3 20. Bxh7+! Kxh7 21. gxh3 $18) (18... Nxh3? { The knight on f4 is an amazing attacker. Don't sacrifice her without a clear continuation! } 19. gxh3 Rd3 20. Bxd3 Qxh3+ 21. Kg1 $10 { The best black has is a perpetual. }) (18... Nxg2? { The knight on f4 is an amazing attacker. Don't sacrifice her without a clear continuation! } 19. Kxg2 Rd6 20. Rfe1 Rg6+ 21. Kh2 Qf4+ 22. Kh1 Bxh3 23. Qxh3 Rh6 24. Qxh6 Qxh6+ $17 { But nearly as convincing as the game. }) (18... b5!? $19 { Once again winning. But only if you follow up as in the game. }) (18... Rfe8? $17 { A sensible developing move, but you're missing a game-winning tactic! }) (18... Bg4! $19 { Nice job! Black wins an exchange because (a) moving the d1 rook anywhere allows Rxd2! followed by Bxh3!, and (b) f3 block's the queen's defense of h3 allowing Bxh3 to decide the game.
Morphy's faster kill kicks off with Bxh3 immediately instead. }) (18... Bd3! { Hitting c4, f1, and disrupting the defense of the queen and h3. A nice interference shot, but not as nice as the game. After Rfe1, we still need a move. } 19. Rfe1 b5!! 20. Bb3 Be2 $19) 19. gxh3 { So black has sacrificed a bishop. What's the follow-up? } 19... Rd3! { A beautiful interference shot! Bxd3 allows Qxh3+ Kg1 Qg2#, so white's next move is forced. } (19... Qxh3+?? { The queen on c3 still defends h3. Did you lose your grip on the board? } 20. Qxh3 $18) 20. Qxd3 { White must sacrifice the queen in order to prolong the game. } (20. Bxd3?? Qxh3+ 21. Kg1 Qg2#) 20... Nxd3 (20... Qxh3+?? $18 { White can still recapture on h3 with their queen! } 21. Qxh3 $18) 21. Bxd3 { White currently has a bishop, knight, and rook for the queen. On its own, this material imbalance is not enough to be decisive.
What's the final wrinkle to Morphy's combination that convincingly ends the game? } 21... Qd6+! { Loose pieces drop off! White's bishop falls next, when black finally achieves a winning material advantage. } 22. f4 { White's response is irrelevant. Black's next move can be pre-moved. } 22... Qxd3 $19 { Morphy has finally won a decisive amount of material, so white resigned.
In this game, Morphy's active defense gave him a chance to not only rebuff white's early aggression, but capture the initiative himself. Once he firmly grabbed the initiative, there was no more need for defense.
In contrast, white's passive defense this game was rightly punished. White failed to improve their position while responding to black's threats, so Morphy snowballed the initiative into a winning attack. Exclusively defending without improving the pieces can only end one way: disaster.
The lesson from this game is clear. We should prefer active defense over passive defense. } 0-1


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.10.??"]
[White "Napoleon Marache"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C52"]
[Opening "Italian Game: Evans Gambit, Pierce Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Beautiful finish"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/vn1S0Vvt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ We have seen Morphy play the white side of many crushing Evans Gambit attacks. Now let's see how he handles the black pieces.

This game also features my personal favorite Morphy finish. The final checkmate is truly a work of art. }
1. e4 { This game starts with another Evans Gambit. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { This game starts with another Evans Gambit. } 2... Nc6 3. Bc4 { This game starts with another Evans Gambit. } 3... Bc5 4. b4 { White opts for the Evans Gambit. } 4... Bxb4 (4... Nxb4!? { Objectively not a bad choice, but after c3 we must return our knight to c6. Why limit black's options unnecessarily?
We already know that we should play the most adaptable options first to avoid this very issue. }) 5. c3 { White, true to the Evans, builds a broad center with tempo on our bishop. } { [%cal Gb4a5] } 5... Ba5 { In our earlier Evans Gambit master class, we discussed how Ba5 is the most fiery option. At first glance, this move seems to prevent d4. However d4 is still playable, at the cost of a second pawn. No matter if black accepts or rejects the second pawn, sharp variations occur since white needs to justify the material deficit with active moves.
Morphy is not afraid of sharp variations. In fact, he invites them! } 6. d4 { Black seemingly prevented white from building their desirable broad center, but white asks the Shankland question: "What if I play d4 anyway?"
Indeed, offering this second pawn is best play. Theory has shown that white is better with best play if black captures on d4 and then again on c3. } { [%cal Ge5d4] } 6... exd4 { Morphy of course is not interested in grabbing pawns, but improving the activity of his pieces. Capturing once on d4 sets the stage for a later d5, the central pawn break that truly breaks down white's center. } 7. e5? { A bad move. White loses a tempo to prevent Nf6 or Qf6 - only one of several options for either piece. White's point is that with both moves prevented, Qb3, developing and hitting f7, is now a real threat.
Yet time is of the essence in an open position like this where white has already gambited two pawns. Instead of e5 last move, O-O or Qb3 were certainly better options.
Morphy seizes on white's slow play by responding actively. } (7. O-O! Nf6! { Active defense! } 8. Ba3! (8. e5?! d5! $15 { More active defense! }) 8... d6 9. e5 Ne4 10. exd6 cxd6 $10) (7. Qb3!? Qf6! { Active defense! } 8. O-O Bb6 9. e5 Qg6 10. cxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Nc3 Ne7 $10) 7... d5! { Active defense!
Qb3, in combination with Bc4, would have created a threat to f7. Morphy preempts this pressure on f7 by closing the diagonal with d5.
However, this move is not purely defensive. d5 also challenges white's center, gains a tempo on the bishop, and prepares to develop the LSB. Indeed, d5 was likely the best move even if white could not generate threats with Qb3. } (7... Nge7!? { A reasonable alternative since now Qb3 can be met with O-O. Play d5 instead for the game continuation. }) (7... Nh6? { Overprotecting f7, but why misplace our knight on h6 unless we are forced to? There are more active defenses instead. } 8. Bg5! $14) (7... d6?! { Challenges white's center and develops the LSB. Unfortunately, this move does not actually defend against white's threat of Qb3! } 8. Qb3 Be6! { Active defense! } 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qxe6+ Qe7 $17) (7... dxc3?! { Too greedy. After Qb3, black lacks an active way to defend f7. } 8. Qb3 d5! { Active defense! } 9. exd6 c2+! { Active defense! } 10. Nbd2 Nh6! $15) (7... Qe7? $10 { An inflexible way to overprotect f7. Where is your g8 knight going to develop now? }) 8. exd6 { White chooses to keep the a2-f7 diagonal open at the cost of losing two tempi with the e pawn. } 8... Qxd6 { White's e pawn moved three times in order to encourage black's queen to develop? White's poor play has led to black having two extra pawns and a lead in development. } (8... Nf6!? { Active defense! Black is ready to castle next and so no longer fears pressure on f7. Play Qxd6 instead for the game continuation. } 9. Qe2+! (9. Qb3? O-O! $17 { Active defense! }) (9. Ba3? O-O! { Active defense! } 10. dxc7 Re8+! 11. Be2 Qxc7 $19) 9... Be6! { Active defense! } 10. Bxe6 O-O! $15 { Active defense! The problems on the e file mean that black will regain the piece. }) (8... cxd6?! $17 { Loses time compared to the game continuation. }) 9. O-O { Since Qb3 is now conveniently met with Be6, white switches gears. Ba3 is the immediate threat. } (9. Qb3?! Be6 $17) (9. Ba3? Bxc3+! 10. Kf1!? (10. Nxc3!? Qxa3 $19) 10... Bb4 $19) 9... Nge7 { More active defense! The a3-f8 diagonal and e file are clogged, while Morphy gets on with developing.
Note how actively Morphy plays with every move. By fighting for his own plans, his army is able to handle his opponent's threats before they even materialize. In fact, if you quickly flip through this game, you might not even appreciate that white is making threats at all.
PRO TIP: Textbook active defense should not look like defense at all. When your opponent makes a threat, first consider candidate moves that improve your position as if there was no threat. Then calculate if any of those moves simultaneously deal with your opponent's threats. You might be able to conveniently defend without having to defend at all! } (9... Be6!? { Equally good since Ba3 can now be met with Qd7. Play Nge7 instead for the game continuation. } 10. Ba3 Qd7 11. Bb5 Nge7 $15) (9... Nf6? { A good square for the knight, but you aren't considering white's threat. After Ba3, black's queen now has no good squares. Moreover, Ba3 prevents black from castling kingside for the foreseeable future. } 10. Ba3! $14) (9... dxc3?! { Takes the sting out of Ba3, but we're opening up the center for white's pieces at a time when they have a lead in development. Don't get greedy! } 10. Qb3! Be6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Rd1! $10) (9... Bb6?! $10 { This move takes the sting out of Ba3, but losing a tempo purely to defend is not how you defend actively! }) 10. Ng5?! { White continues making one-move threats. } (10. Ba3!? Qf6 $15) 10... O-O! { More active defense! Again, Morphy conveniently defends white's threats with moves he wanted to make anyway. } 11. Bd3?! { Retreating the bishop just to create a one-move threat on h7... White has clearly lost the plot.
Please compare Morphy's attacks with his opponents' attacks. When Morphy attacks, every piece participates in the fight. In contrast, this opponent is attacking with a handful of pieces while neglecting the development of the entire queenside.
PRO TIP: Lower rated players tend to play with their pretty pieces. Making threats with the pieces that are furthest up the board is a good way to lose time and easily get rebuffed. Higher rated players tend to focus on their worst-placed pieces. They know how crucial it is to improve all of the pieces first in order to make coherent threats. } 11... Bf5! { More active defense! White's threat to h7 is conveniently parried by a normal developing move.
Black is now fully in the middlegame while white still needs three tempi to finish development. } (11... h6?! { Loses time. After Ne4, our queen will also have to relocate to a new safe square. Still, this move is fine. } 12. Ne4 $17) (11... Ng6?! { Walks into Ba3 and Qh5. Don't ignore your opponent's threats - refute them actively! } 12. Qh5!? h6 13. Nxf7 Rxf7 14. Bxg6 Rf6 $17) (11... f5?? { This is in no way active defense. Would you have played f5 if white was not attacking h7? Of course not - the move just blocks our LSB and weakens our king.
Moreover, After Bc4+, there is no way to avoid losing material. } 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. Nxh7!! Kxh7? 14. Qh5+ Qh6 15. Bxh6 $18) (11... g6? { This is in no way active defense. Would you have played g6 if white was not attacking h7? Of course not - the move just loses time and weakens our king. } 12. Ne4 $17) (11... Nf5!? { Improving the knight while preventing Bxh7+. This certainly qualifies as active defense. Yet what are you doing about g4? What are you doing about Ba3?
As long as you calculated a response to either of those moves before playing Nf5, give yourself full credit. Play Bf5 instead for the game continuation. } 12. g4?! (12. Ba3!? Qg6 13. Bxf8 Qxg5 $17 { Similar to the game. }) 12... Nh4 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 14. Bc2 Ne5! $17 { Black's pieces are swarming white's kingside. The h pawn was irrelevant. }) 12. Bxf5 Nxf5 13. Ba3 { This was white's point behind the last capture. By attracting black's knight away from e7, Ba3 both attacks the queen and x-rays the rook. White will win the exchange.
Unfortunately, white has lost so many tempi trying to win the exchange that black has more than enough dynamic compensation. In fact, black's dynamic potential far outweighs the exchange. Black is already objectively winning.
PRO TIP: Defending actively often requires you to move beyond materialism. Instead of bending over backwards to hold onto all of your material (like a pawn, or the exchange), you should focus on principled moves that improve your position and make your pieces more active. It may be worthwhile to transform the static advantage of extra material into the dynamic advantages that naturally arise when refuting your opponent's attack. } { [%cal Gd6g6] } (13. Qh5 Qg6 $19) 13... Qg6 14. Bxf8 { White wins the exchange for two pawns. How to continue? } 14... Qxg5! { The best capture. White will need to spend another tempo with the bishop to avoid losing it. Meanwhile, black's queen on g5 is improved since she is now opposite white's king. Black's lead in development is too much for white to handle. } (14... Rxf8?! $17 { A fine move. We recapture a piece, after which white has to spend a tempo dealing with their loose knight on g5. Yet our rook is not improved on f8, so this is one tempo slower than the game. }) (14... dxc3?! $17 { A tempting in-between capture since both of white's pieces remain hanging. This sequence is stronger by switching the move order though, once again proving the rule that we shouldn't get fancy and just recapture our pieces. }) (14... Kxf8? { The worst recapture. Our king does not belong on f8, where is is vulnerable to follow-up checks. } 15. Nf3 dxc3 16. Qb3 $17) 15. Ba3 { [%cal Gd4c3] } 15... dxc3! { This move is less about taking a free pawn and more about dominating the b1 knight. Moreover, if the knight cannot get into the game, the rook on a1 remains sidelined too. Morphy is playing with a full army, while black only has the queen and f1 rook. } 16. Bc1 { A comical position. White looks like they are setting up for the next game, not improving their pieces!
Bc1 doesn't truly gain a tempo against our queen since white has to lose a tempo with the bishop to attack her in the first place. } { [%cal Gg5g6] } 16... Qg6 17. Bf4 { White has spent 5 tempi with this bishop to play Bf4. Hopefully you can now appreciate how strong black's dynamic potential is. White's extra exchange is useless in such a position. } 17... Rd8 { The Morphy move! Black's final piece joins the game with tempo. } 18. Qc2 { White was lost in any case, but developing the queen to a square within reach of black's minor pieces was foolish. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 18... Ncd4 19. Qe4? { The final nail in the coffin. With Qe4, white allows a devastating tactical combination.
We say that "black is down the exchange for three pawns." But that is not the reality. Because white's knight and a1 rook are in purgatory, it's more correct to say that black is up two pieces. Viewing the position through that lens, it is not surprising that black has a winning tactic. } 19... Ng3!! { Alignments create threats! The knight is hanging three different ways, but the tension between the two queens ensures none of the captures are playable. } 20. Qxg6?! { White decides to trade queens since any non-queen move allowed Nxe4 or Qxe4, winning the queen, and any queen move allowed Nde2+, winning the queen or king. } (20. Re1!? Nxe4 $19) 20... Nde2# { Wow, what a beautiful finish! It's rare to mate with only two knights.
This tactic is a great counterexample to the typical advice (don't be fancy, just recapture your pieces). Mate-in-1 is more important than capturing a queen!
My annotations to this game highlighted how Morphy's active defense gave him the ability to rebuff white's heavy-handed attack and take the initiative. Indeed, this game is a classic example of the power of active defense. Yet it is worth noting that this game is famous almost exclusively for the final two moves. Many players have seen this finish without having played through the game leading up to it. } (20... hxg6?? { Finally, a position where simply recapturing the queen misses a more forcing move: checkmate! } 21. fxg3 $15) (20... fxg6?? { Finally, a position where simply recapturing the queen misses a more forcing move: checkmate! } 21. fxg3 $15) 0-1


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1857.??.??"]
[White "Hiram Kennicott"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Scotch Gambit, Sarratt Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Flipping the script"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/OvpBKEeS"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ It is interesting that Morphy has almost twice as many recorded games as white than he does as black. This is partially because he challenged others to simuls and blindfold simuls, and the host of a simul traditionally takes white. But I believe it is also partially because people were more likely to record complicated/attacking games than easy/boring games in the Romantic Era.

Since white moves first, white is more likely the side to start a nice attack. Indeed, this game follows that same script... at first. Once Morphy refutes the first wave of white's attack by defending actively, he is able to flip the script and start a nice attack himself. }
1. e4 { This game starts as a Scotch. } 1... e5 { The e5 pawn claims an equal stake in the center, thus preventing white from dominating the center with d4. } 2. Nf3 { This game starts as a Scotch. } 2... Nc6 (2... Nf6!? $10 { Play Nc6 instead for the game continuation. }) (2... d6!? $14 { Play Nc6 instead for the game continuation. }) 3. d4 { The Scotch. White breaks in the center even though black has a firm grip on the d4 square.
With black's first move, we prevented white from claiming an uncontested center. Therefore, when white plays d4 anyway, capturing on d4 is logical to avoid being overruled. } { [%cal Ge5d4] } 3... exd4 { We have already seen this same logic applied to the Open Sicilian when black plays cxd4. } 4. Bc4!? { It's the Romantic era. Rather than recapture and centralize their knight (a fine option), white opts for quick development in order to gain the initiative right off the bat. Bc4 in this position is known as the Scotch Gambit. } { [%cal Gf8c5] } 4... Bc5 { Active defense. By defending the d pawn, we force white to commit to a gambit. More importantly, Bc5 develops a piece and prepares to castle kingside ASAP.
Nf6 is the other main move for all the same reasons. Both moves are unapologetic in ignoring white's bid for activity. } (4... Nf6!? $10 { Equally playable. Also active defense. }) 5. Ng5!? { In for a penny, in for a pound. White doubles down on their early aggression and hits the weak spot in black's camp: f7.
However, black should be confident that this unprincipled aggression will not work out (White is moving the knight twice? What has black even done wrong?). Yet there are parallels between this variation and the Fried Liver Attack. Defending actively to rebuff such an attack will require skill. } (5. c3! { This move has the best reputation for white since the pawn should not be taken. Regardless, black should be fine after Nf6 - more active defense! } 5... Nf6 6. e5 d5! $10 { More active defense! }) 5... Nh6! { Developing and defending! Nice job finding this active defense. Given one more move, we are ready to castle kingside.
I hope that you asked yourself the Shankland question before playing this move though: what if white captures on f7 anyway? } (5... d5?! $14 { The other active defense move. Unfortunately, after Bxd5, black does not gain any extra dynamic options for the pawn sacrifice. }) (5... Ne5? { A worse version of the game (did you ask yourself the Shankland question?). We need to develop more pieces, not lose time trying to defend. } 6. Nxf7 Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qxc5 $16 { Black does not have as many pieces developed as in the game continuation. }) 6. Nxf7 { The Shankland question in action!
Moreover, this is the whole point of white's last move. "If you say A (Ng5), you must say B (Nxf7)!" } 6... Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 (7... Kf8? $16 { This is a worse version of the game continuation. Black's heavy pieces are slower to get into the action and the king is no safer on f8 than f7. }) (7... Ke7?? { Oh no, your queen! Bg5+ is a brutal skewer. } 8. Bg5+ $18) 8. Qh5+ { The point of white's play. Qh5+ forks our DSB and regains the sacrificed material. } 8... g6 (8... Kf8!? $14 { It's probably suboptimal to walk into Qxc5 with check. Play g6 instead for the game continuation. }) (8... Kg8!? $14 { It's probably suboptimal to walk into Qd5+ Kf8, Qxc5 with check. Play g6 instead for the game continuation. }) (8... Kf6?? $18 { Oh no, your queen! Bg5+ is a brutal skewer. }) (8... Ke7?? $18 { Oh no, your queen! Bg5+ is a brutal skewer. }) (8... Ke6?? $18 { Oh no, your queen! Qd5+ Ke7, Bg5+ is a brutal skewer. }) 9. Qxc5 { The dust has momentarily settled, but should black be unhappy with the sequence that just occurred?
Material is level. White has traded off all of their active minor pieces for black's knight on the side of the board and black's bishop that was staring at the d4 pawn. White's queen is the only piece developed. Two of black's heavy pieces are ready to enter the game next. Meanwhile the only white piece that can coordinate with the queen is the DSB.
As we have previously discussed, king safety is exclusively measured by how easily the king can come under fire. Since there are no pieces to attack black's king, our king on f7 shouldn't be a concern.
Indeed, this position is equal. But in practice black outperforms white here because of the dynamic potential of black's army. } 9... d6 { More active defense! More!
White had threatened Bg5 or Qd5+, but Morphy handles both threats by gaining a tempo on black's queen while preparing to develop the LSB. } (9... Re8?! $16 { Active defense, but after Qd5+ (defending e4) and Bg5, black's queen is out of squares. We cannot make moves based purely on principle; we still have to calculate in positions like this! }) (9... d5! $10 { Equally active defense! This is not a pawn sacrifice since white will immediately regain it after Nb4. Moreover, d5 strikes at white's center and helps develop our queenside pieces. Excellent concept!
Play d6 instead for the game continuation. }) (9... Qe8?! { Not a bad move, but Qe8 is hardly a move that black wants to make in a vacuum. Active defense entails making moves we want to make that simultaneously deal with our opponent's threats. } 10. Nd2 b6 11. Qa3 $14) (9... Qe7?! { Not a bad move, but Qe7 is hardly a move that black wants to make in a vacuum. After the queen trade, black cannot recapture and develop a piece. } 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. O-O $14) 10. Qb5 { Any queen check would have been met with Be6, developing a piece with tempo.
With Qb5, white at least pressures b7 (thus restricting black's LSB for now). But the move lacks oomph. Perhaps you can sense that the initiative is swinging towards black... } 10... Re8 { Developing with a threat. Textbook Morphy. Classic way to fight for the initiative. } (10... a6?! $10 { Not a useful tempo since a6 does not improve our position. We learned in Chapter III that attacking your opponent's queen is only worth it if you are also improving your position. }) (10... Qe7?! $14 { Tempting, but ineffective. After Nd2, there is no further way to attack e4.
Moreover, white will eventually gain a tempo on this queen with Bg5 or Re1. }) (10... Bd7?! { You have learned the correct lesson from Chapter III. White would be crazy to capture on b7. Unfortunately there are no useful discoveries on white's queen, and in the long run b7 may actually be hanging. } 11. O-O $14) (10... Qh4?! { Tempting, but ineffective. After Nd2, there is no further way to attack e4.
Moreover, white will eventually gain a tempo on this queen with Bg5 or Nf3. } 11. Nd2 $14) (10... Kg7?! $14 { Sensible, in that the king is safer on g7. But this is far from the most adaptable move in the position. }) 11. O-O! { White shows that they too understand active defense!
There was no way to defend e4 (the pawn was not only attacked but also in a pin; d5, taking advantage of the pin, refuted any direct defense of the e4 pawn). So white hurries to castle and regain the initiative while Morphy spends time capturing the e pawn. } 11... Rxe4! { A greedy capture, but black does have a slight lead in development, so losing time in order to gain this pawn is acceptable. This is a classic transformation of our dynamic advantage to a static one. } (11... a6?! { A slow option that only forces the queen to d3 where she defends e4 directly. } 12. Qd3 $14) (11... Qf6?! $14 { Develops a piece, but after Nd2, white is able to secure the e pawn for good. }) (11... Qe7?! $14 { Develops a piece, but after Nd2, white is able to secure the e pawn for good. }) (11... Bd7?! $14 { You have learned the correct lesson from Chapter III. White would be crazy to capture on b7. Unfortunately there are no useful discoveries on white's queen, and in the long run b7 may actually be hanging. }) (11... Qh4?! $14 { A reasonable option that develops a piece and avoids any Bg5 shenanigans. But after Nd2, white is able to secure the e pawn for good. }) (11... Re5?! { A tempting move that improves a piece. But you are kicking the queen to d3 where she defends e4 directly. } 12. Qd3 $14) 12. Qd5+ { Checks, captures, threats! I hope you saw a good response to this check before capturing on e4.
PRO TIP: "Broad, not deep!" When calculating variations, it is much more important not to miss candidate moves for you and your opponent than it is to calculate one line deeply. That one line might not even be the most relevant or critical variation.
A good rule of thumb is to try your best to calculate 3 ply every move. That is, the first ply is the move you want to play, the second ply would be each of the forcing options available to your opponent, and the third ply would be your responses to each. If you can clearly visualize the positions after 3 ply, and there doesn't appear to be a problem in any position, go ahead and play your move! } (12. Nd2?! Re5! $15 { Active defense! }) 12... Re6 { Passive defense, but necessary. } 13. Bg5 { Developing with tempo. White has the safer king and is now up two tempi on black. As we have already seen, three tempi is worth a pawn. So white should almost have full compensation for the pawn sacrifice. } 13... Qe8 (13... Qd7?! $14 { Blocking in your LSB? There is no chance this move is correct. }) (13... Qf8!? $10 { The queen will stand well after Kg7 next. Play Qe8 instead for the game continuation. }) (13... Qg8?! $10 { A worse version of the game continuation. }) (13... Qh8!? $10 { An interesting concept. By overprotecting d4, we prepare Ne7 to kick out white's queen. Play Qe8 instead for the game continuation. }) (13... Ne7? { Oh no, your d4 pawn! } 14. Qxd4 $14) (13... Nb4?? { Don't get fancy! Playing such a counterattack when your queen is still under attack, king is vulnerable, and rook remains in a pin is dangerous. You need to have a firm grip on the board to ensure white does not have a check, capture, or threat in this position that could ruin you.
Unfortunately, Qf3+ saves white's queen with tempo. Black will lose a queen next. } 14. Qf3+ Rf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qb3+! Be6 17. Qxb4 $18) 14. f4?! { Developing the knight and bringing a rook to the e file was more circumspect. Note that white must develop more pieces before reaching a DDD moment, when the f5 pawn break would be desirable. As-is, f4 is a bit overeager.
Still, this full-steam-ahead move is consistent with white's play so far. White is planning to play f5 next to rip open more lines against our king and involve the f1 rook in the attack.
How best to handle this position? } 14... Kg7 { Active defense!
The king escapes the f file now that f5 is about to rip it open. Additionally, this move unpins the e6 rook, simultaneously improving our position. Indeed, Kg7 was likely to be the best move even if white wasn't threatening f5.
As we have repeatedly seen, good defensive moves are multipurpose moves that deal with the opponent's threat(s) while simultaneously improving our position. } (14... Bd7?! $15 { A half-developing move that barely improves black's position. Look for better. }) (14... Kg8?! $10 { Passive defense. This move escapes the f file but does not otherwise improve the position. }) (14... Nb4?! $10 { A one-move trick. Qxd4 loses to Nxc2. But after Qc4 or Qb3, black's best option is to retreat the knight back to c6. So this move doesn't accomplish anything constructive. }) (14... Ne7?! { Not a horrible move, but not truly active defense. Moreover, after Bxe7, we will lose our d4 pawn next. f5 is still coming. } 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Qxd4 $10) 15. f5 { White follows through with their "threat." } 15... gxf5 (15... Re5?? { Active defense, but completely losing. The f pawn cannot be allowed to live. After f6+ Kh8, white has f7!, simultaneously threatening the queen, threatening to promote, and threatening Bf6#. There is no defense.
Yes, when defending actively, we first consider moves we want to make as if there is no threat. But we still must calculate our opponent's threats in response to our defensive move! } 16. f6+ Kh8 17. f7! $19 Qf8!? 18. Bf6+ Qg7 19. f8=Q#) 16. Qxf5 { Rxf5 was not possible due to white's lack of development. Black had Re1+, Rf1 Rxf1+, Kxf1 Be6, after which all of black's pieces are developed with tempo.
Qxf5 therefore had to be played.
How should we handle this position? } (16. Rxf5? Re1+ 17. Rf1 Rxf1+ 18. Kxf1 Be6 $19) 16... Rg6! { Active defense!
Any rook move should have been a candidate since they all came with a discovered attack on white's queen. With this specific rook move, Morphy safeguards his king, x-rays white's king, and rules out Qf6+ in some lines. Talk about a multipurpose defensive move! } (16... Qg6?? { Oh no, my king! Qf8 is mate in 1. } 17. Qf8#) (16... Ne7? { Passive defense, but understandable. The reason this is passive is that you wouldn't consider Ne7 except for the fact that it hits white's queen and tries to head towards the kingside to deal with white's threats.
Still, the instinct to bring pieces towards the kingside is reasonable. } 17. Bf6+! Kg8 18. Qg5+ Ng6 19. Nd2 $16) (16... Re1? { A tempting option since this is indeed active defense. Yet once again we aren't calculating white's response to our move. After Bf6+, our king is wide open and white has a devastating follow-up that wins our rook on e1. } 17. Bf6+ Kf8!? (17... Kg8?! 18. Qg5+ Qg6 19. Rxe1 $18) 18. Be7+!! Kxe7 19. Rxe1+ $18) (16... Bd7!? { Active defense. You're finishing development, overprotecting the back rank, and laughing at your opponent's threats. Indeed, black is slightly better in this position.
Play Rg6 instead for the game continuation. } 17. Bf6+ Kg8 18. Nd2 $15 (18. Qg5+?! Qg6 $17)) (16... Qh5?? { Oh no, your king! After Qf8+ Kg6, white has Qg8#. } 17. Qf8+ Kg6 18. Qg8#) (16... Ne5?! $10 { Puts the knight on a good square, while heading closer to the king. Is this truly the best we have though? Black would rather not block the heavy pieces on the e file. }) (16... Re5?? { Oh no, your king! After Qf6+ Kg8, Bh6 mates us.
Yes, when defending actively, we first consider moves we want to make as if there is no threat. But we still must calculate our opponent's threats in response to our defensive move! } 17. Qf6+ Kg8 18. Bh6 Re7 19. Qf8+! Qxf8 20. Rxf8# { The opera mate! }) (16... Re4?? { Oh no, your king! Qf6+ cannot be allowed. } 17. Qf6+ Kg8 18. Bh6 $18) (16... Re2?? { Oh no, your king! Qf6+ cannot be allowed. } 17. Qf6+ Kg8 18. Bh6 $18) (16... Kg8?! { Escaping Bf6+ is desirable, but this is the most passive way to defend possible. } 17. Qd5! $10) 17. Bf6+? { The losing move, but white continues playing consistently: attack at all costs. } 17... Kg8 { White has overcommitted to an attack without finishing development. Such an unprincipled attack should not work out.
Meanwhile, Morphy has played for activity, even while defending. The result is that his pieces are well-placed, his king is reasonably safe, and he remains up a pawn. } (17... Rxf6?? { Oh no, your rook! } 18. Qxf6+ $18) (17... Kh6?? { Oh no, your king! Qf4+ kicks off a mate in 2. } 18. Qf4+ Kh5 (18... Rg5 19. Qxg5#) 19. Qh4#) 18. Qf4 { White's attack is clearly over, and now Morphy has the initiative. By this point, it should be clear that he has already flipped the script on white's attack; who is attacking whom? } { [%cal Gc8h3] } 18... Bh3 19. Bg5 { Passive defense from white, but necessary. This was the only way to safeguard white's g2 pawn without dropping the exchange. } { [%cal Ge8e3] } 19... Qe3+! { The first example in this study where Morphy chooses to simplify into a winning endgame rather than crush his opponent in the middlegame. As the level of opposition increases in later chapters of this study, Morphy will have to simplify and convert more difficult endgames than this. } 20. Qxe3 { Kh1 would have lost to Bxg2+! Kxg2, Rxg5! among other options. } (20. Kh1?! Bxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Rxg5+! $19) 20... dxe3 21. gxh3 { White's hanging bishop couldn't move without dropping g2, so white agrees to further simplifications. } 21... Rxg5+ (21... e2!? { Equally winning. Play Rxg5+ instead for the game continuation. } 22. Re1 Rxg5+ 23. Kf2 Nd4! $19) 22. Kh1 { Morphy surely calculated to the end of the game before pulling the trigger on the earlier queen trade. But for us mere mortals, there is still a useful lesson to be learned here.
PRO TIP: When you are ahead material, a good way to convert the position is to trade pieces (but not pawns!). With every successive piece trade, the extra material becomes relatively more and more valuable. Eventually, the end goal is to make a passed pawn and get a new queen. } { [%cal Ge3e2] } 22... e2 23. Re1 { Even in the endgame, Morphy retains his signature initiative.
This game's finish is as brutal as it is instructive. } { [%cal Gc6d4] } 23... Nd4 { A classic multipurpose move. The e pawn is protected, and Nxc2 is a game-winning threat. } 24. Na3 { White defends against Nxc2 and finally develops their queenside, but it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } { [%cal Ga8e8] } 24... Re8 $19 { The Morphy move forces resignation. There is no way to prevent Nf3, promoting the e pawn or winning the exchange.
The ultimate goal of active defense is to capture the initiative. In this game, it took Morphy until the endgame to finally succeed. But he did succeed. Once in the endgame, Morphy utilized this initiative to force through his passed pawn and win the game. } 0-1


[Event "Casual Game"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1855.??.??"]
[White "Alexander Beaufort Meek"]
[Black "Paul Morphy"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Scotch Gambit, Sarratt Variation"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Reverse uno card"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/zljqdA3X"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In this game, Morphy plays his favorite punching bag, Alexander Meek. In total, their lifetime score was +8-0=0 in favor of Morphy. We have already seen Morphy crush Meek as white. Now we get to enjoy him crush Meek as black.

Once again, Morphy faces the Scotch Gambit. Once again, Morphy's opponent goes all-in on a premature attack that Morphy rebuffs with active defense. }
1. e4 { This game starts as a Scotch Gambit. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { This game starts as a Scotch Gambit. } 2... Nc6 3. d4 { This game starts as a Scotch Gambit. } 3... exd4 4. Bc4 { Just like in the previous game, white chooses to play the Scotch Gambit. } 4... Bc5! { Active defense, as before. By defending the d pawn, we force white to commit to a gambit. More importantly, Bc5 develops a piece and prepares to castle kingside ASAP.
Nf6 is the other main move for all the same reasons. Both moves are unapologetic in ignoring white's bid for activity. } (4... Nf6!? $10 { Equally playable, since it is also active defense. Play Bc5 instead for the game continuation. }) (4... Bb4+!? { Also playable, but white gets the tempo back after c3!? dxc3, bxc3! Play Bc5 instead for the game continuation. } 5. c3 dxc3 6. bxc3!? (6. O-O!? $10) 6... Ba5 7. O-O Bb6! $10) (4... d6?! $14 { Blocks in the DSB on f8 for no reason. Find a more active move. }) (4... Be7?! { A half-developing move. After Nxd4, white is in an improved Scotch game. } 5. Nxd4 $14) 5. Ng5!? { Repeating the previous game, white hammers away at the f7 weakness in black's position.
However, losing time with this knight just to attack a weakness is already slightly unprincipled. With this in mind, we must respect white's threats, but we should not fear them. } 5... Nh6! { Developing and defending! Nice job finding this active defense. Given one more move, we are ready to castle kingside. } (5... Ne5? { Did you ask yourself the Shankland question for your opponent? If you did, you would probably not have played this move! After Nxf7! Nxf7, Bxf7+ Kxf7, Qh5+ we arrive at a worse version of the previous game since black has no developed pieces. } 6. Nxf7! Nxf7 7. Bxf7+ Kxf7 8. Qh5+ g6 9. Qxc5 $16) (5... d5?! { The other active defense move. Unfortunately, after Bxd5, black does not gain any extra dynamic options for the pawn sacrifice. } 6. Bxd5 $14) 6. O-O?! { Last game, we saw white follow through with their threat by capturing on f7, ultimately taking advantage of our unprotected bishop on c5. This game, white develops more pieces before launching their attack.
However, this is inconsistent because the knight on g5 will soon end up misplaced. "If you say A, you must say B!" } 6... d6!? { Active defense! Morphy prepares to develop the LSB while simultaneously defending the DSB. Thus, white's threat of Nxf7 has been handled by not directly handling it. } (6... O-O!? $15 { Active defense! Nice job. Nxf7 has been stopped for good, while you are just getting on with castling. Play d6 instead for the game continuation. }) (6... Ne5!? { Active defense! Nice job. Nxf7 has been stopped for good, while you are improving a knight with tempo on white's LSB. Play d6 instead for the game continuation. } 7. Bb3 O-O 8. f4!? Neg4! { The point. Otherwise Ne5 would have been a water of time. } 9. h3 Ne3 $15) (6... Qf6?! { Do we really want to develop the queen this early? After e5!, white gets some annoying play on the e file. } 7. e5! Nxe5 8. Ne4! Qc6 9. Bxh6 O-O!! { An amazing example of active defense. All of white's pieces are loose. } 10. Nxc5 Qxc5! $10 { Both bishops are attacked, so black is not worse. }) (6... Qe7?! $10 { Do we really want to develop the queen this early? }) 7. c3 { A thematic move in e4-e5 gambits. White tempts black to capture on c3, losing time and developing white's knight for them. } 7... O-O { White's last move did not threaten to win d4, so there is no need to respond to it. We should especially hold ourselves back from losing a tempo by capturing on c3.
Since there was no threat, what better move can there be besides castling? } (7... dxc3?! { Loses a tempo compared to the game. Why are you developing white's army for them? White had no threat! } 8. Nxc3 $10) (7... Bg4?! { Playable but way too complicated. Your knight is now overworked defending g4 and f7. Did you consider white's reply of Bxf7+? } 8. Bxf7+! Nxf7 9. Qxg4 Nxg5 10. Bxg5 Qd7 $15) (7... Ne5? { White did not have a threat on d4 because we had two pieces defending it. We should not be tempting fate by undefending d4 here. In fact, this move is tactically flawed. } 8. cxd4 Nxc4 9. dxc5 O-O 10. Qb3 Ne5 { Passive defense, but necessary. } 11. Rd1 $16 { White's army has all developed with tempo. Black is not better developed than we were at the beginning of this variation. }) (7... Bd7?! $10 { A half-developing move that doesn't actually accomplish anything. Play the most adaptable developing moves first! }) 8. cxd4 Bxd4 (8... Nxd4!? $15 { Equally good to the game continuation. Play Bxd4 instead for the game continuation. }) 9. Nc3 { White achieves the same position as if we had captured on c3... but they have lost a tempo. Black achieved Bd4 "for free."
Due to their slow play, white's initiative has mostly evaporated. Morphy takes this opportunity to centralize the h6 knight. } { [%cal Gh6g4] } 9... Ng4 { The knight relocates from the edge of the board to e5 before white has a chance to dominate her with h3. This move also allows for h6, kicking back white's knight on g5.
Why does Morphy start with this improving move and not another developing move? Well because this is the most adaptable option!
The rook cannot undefend f7. The queen's forward moves all get hit with Nd5. The LSB has several options, but none of them are clearly good squares. Perhaps we will play Bg4 (which runs into an eventual h3), perhaps we will play Bd7 (a half-developing move), or perhaps we will find another option (as in the game).
In contrast, the knight does not want to stay on h6 in every variation. This is another example where playing the most adaptable option first is indeed strongest. } (9... Bg4!? $15 { Developing with a threat. Yet after the queen moves somewhere, the bishop is staring off into space. Perhaps this is not the best square for the bishop yet. }) 10. h3 { White kicks the knight back, but loses another tempo in the process. } 10... Nge5 { Active defense. The knight was hit on g4, so we had to respond to white's threat by moving her. Yet we don't respond by moving the knight to "just" any square. From e5, she centralizes while gaining a tempo on white's LSB and overprotecting f7. Truly a multipurpose move. } (10... Nxf2? { The two minor pieces are much more valuable than the rook and pawn. Why? Because two pieces are worth more than one! Pawns aren't people. } 11. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 12. Kxf2 $14) (10... Nf6!? $15 { Equally fine as well. Play Nge5 instead for the game continuation. }) (10... Nh6? $14 { Morphy would never lose two tempi with a knight for no reason! You must search for active moves, not passive ones! }) 11. Qh5?! { White threatens mate on h7. Of course, with a strong grip on the board, we should have already seen before moving our knight that h7 was attacked once and defended once. Thus, h7 was a possible target, and so this forcing move should not have come as a surprise. If it did, please work harder on your 3-ply calculations!
What are you going to do about white's threat? } 11... h6 { While we could classify h6 as active defense (we respond to a mate-in-1 threat by gaining a tempo back on the knight), the reality is simpler than any strategic concept. There literally was no alternative to consider. Checkmate ends the game, and we had to stop it.
White now has two pieces hanging, so black is winning a piece in every variation. } (11... Qxg5?? { Oh no, your queen! } 12. Bxg5 $18) (11... Bf5?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 12. exf5 $18) (11... Re8?? { "You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move!" Not only does this move fail to address white's threat to h7, it also creates a new target on f7. } 12. Bxf7+! Nxf7 13. Qxf7+ Kh8 14. Qh5! h6 15. Nf7+ $18) 12. Nxf7 { White had two pieces hanging. This desperate sacrifice is the best way to lose a piece. } 12... Nxf7 (12... Rxf7? { There is no reason to allow white to win a rook for two pieces. We want to cleanly win a piece instead. } 13. Bxf7+ Nxf7 $17) (12... Nxc4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 13. Nxd8 $18) 13. Qg6 { Bxh6, sacrificing a piece to open up our king, was surely the main move white was counting on to stir up trouble. However, this desperate attacking move accomplished nothing while our bishop on d4 easily protects our king.
Therefore, white chose Qg6 instead. Bxh6 is now a threat because both the g pawn and f7 knight are pinned. How should we respond? } (13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Qg6+ Bg7 $19) 13... Ne5! { Active defense! Not only are we refuting Bxh6 by gaining a tempo on the queen, we are simultaneously centralizing our knight and hitting the LSB on c4. } (13... Kh8?! { We're not technically losing the knight on f7 because of Ne5. But this is truly passive defense. The only reason you are playing your king to the h file is to defend against white's threats. Look for active defense instead. } 14. Bxf7 Ne5 $17) (13... Qf6!? $17 { Active defense, and definitely the simplest move. We are simply developing a piece but also simultaneously preventing Bxh6. Of course, since we are already up a piece, we welcome further piece trades - a concept we saw in action in the previous game.
Play Ne5 instead for the game continuation. }) (13... Bxc3?! { Further piece trades are desirable since we are up a piece. But our DSB was a strong piece! In contrast, that knight on c3 accomplished nothing. We should not go out of our way to trade a good piece for a bad piece, even when we are winning. } 14. bxc3 Qf6 $17) (13... Ne7? $17 { Another way to gain a tempo on the queen. Yet would we consider this move if white was not threatening Bxh6? Of course not! We just undefended our DSB, blocked a diagonal from our queen, and demoted the knight.
Passive defense is not the way forward. }) 14. Bxf7+ { Forced to avoid losing the bishop for free. } 14... Rxf7 (14... Nxf7? $17 { Passive defense. Why recapture while demoting your knight? }) 15. Qg3 { White's queen finally responds to the knight's threat. Once again, white threatens Bxh6.
We have fully consolidated the extra piece. From such a dominant position, there are many different winning approaches. } { [%cal Gf7f6] } 15... Rf6 { Active defense again. Bxh6 is directly defended, but Morphy also improves the rook. } 16. Nd5 { Of course, Morphy needed to calculate this forcing move before playing Rf6. There is a convenient response. } 16... Rg6 { More active defense. Black escapes white's tempo with a tempo of their own. From g6, the rook is solidly defended, gains a tempo on white's queen, and creates threats by being opposite white's king.
At this point, I hope I am belaboring the point. Morphy does not defend passively unless it is strictly necessary. He searches for active defense at every opportunity in order to take the initiative! } 17. Qb3 { Now it's white's turn to find a good defensive move. White responds to black's tempo with a tempo of their own! Any knight discovery is painful. } 17... Be6! { Active defense. Morphy plays a nice reverse uno card here: the threats along the a2-g8 diagonal now backfire. Moreover, Morphy is now inches away from finishing development.
Of course, we should not care about the measly b7 pawn from such a dominant position... } (17... Kh7?! $19 { A tidy move, but technically passive defense. The only reason to make this move is to avoid white's threat. Look for better. }) (17... Kh8?! $19 { A tidy move, but technically passive defense. The only reason to make this move is to avoid white's threat. Look for better. }) 18. Qxb7? { White wastes another tempo to snag the useless b7 pawn.
At this point, we should identify that white has transitioned from attacking our king to implementing a failed wild queen strategy. As we already know from Chapter III, the ultimate price for losing many tempi with the queen is that the opponent gets the initiative. Unfortunately for his opponent, Morphy is absolutely deadly with the initiative. } { [%cal Ge6h3] } 18... Bxh3! { Morphy converts his extra material into a winning attack. He surely calculated to the end of the game before pulling the trigger on this tempting move. But for us mere mortals, there is still a useful lesson to be learned here.
PRO TIP: When you are ahead material, a good way to convert the position is to use the extra material to launch a successful attack. With more attackers than your opponent can possibly have defenders, you should be able to overwhelm your opponent's defenses. Eventually, the end goal is to checkmate or win a decisive amount of material.
This conversion technique is in direct opposition to the conversion technique Morphy showed us last game. The decision to either trade down and win an endgame or overwhelm your opponent with a direct attack is often a matter of taste. By this point in the study, we don't need to guess which technique Morphy preferred. } 19. Ne7+ { White finds a tactic to win the exchange. Either the knight is captured and the a8 rook falls, or the knight is not captured and the g6 rook falls. Unfortunately, in either case, Morphy maintains his overwhelming attack. } 19... Qxe7! (19... Kh8? { Now the rook hangs with check! } 20. Nxg6+ $15) (19... Kf8? { Now the rook hangs with check! } 20. Nxg6+ $14) 20. Qxa8+ { We don't mind dropping the a8 rook, even if it falls with check, because that rook is significantly less active than its counterpart on g6.
Another reverse uno card! While white spends time winning the useless a8 rook, black's attack crashes through on the kingside.
PRO TIP: Active defense sometimes requires you to let your opponent follow through with their threats while you generate play elsewhere! } 20... Kh7 (20... Kf7? { There is no reason to expose your king and allow Qd5+, even though this move also wins. } 21. Qd5+ Be6 22. Qb7?? (22. Qxd4?? Nf3+ $19) 22... Nf3+ 23. Kh1 Qh4#) (20... Qf8? { Of course we should not be interested in trading queens in the middle of an attack! } 21. Qxf8+ Kxf8 22. Kh2 $19) 21. Kh2 { With five pieces attacking the naked king, black is checkmating in several different ways. Morphy chooses the most forcing sequence. } { [%cal Gg6g2] } 21... Rxg2+!! { "Oh no, my bishop!" } 22. Kxh3 { Kh1 was mated by Qh4 (threatening Rh2+! or Bg4+!). So white accepts the offered piece instead and asks Morphy to prove that there is a mate. } { [%cal Ge7e6] } (22. Kh1?! Qh4! 23. Bf4!? (23. Bd2!? Rh2+! 24. Kxh2 Nf3+ 25. Kh1 Bxf1#) 23... Bg4+! 24. Kxg2 Qh3+ 25. Kg1 Nf3#) 22... Qe6+! { "Oh no, my rook!" } 23. Kxg2 { White has no other options than to take the second offered piece.
Now its your turn to put white away. I challenge you to calculate the mate from this position before making a move on the board. } 23... Qg4+ (23... Qg6+?! $19 { Also mating, but slower than the game continuation. The queen does not cover any more squares from g6 than she did on e6. }) 24. Kh1 { Kh2 goes down similarly by switching the move order of these last two moves. } 24... Qh3+ (24... Nf3!? $19 { Also winning because Qh3+ is unstoppable. However, why allow white some spite checks when we have a more forcing way to achieve the same mate? }) 25. Kg1 { Only move... } 25... Nf3# { A common phrase about winning attacks is: "You need three attackers---one to sac and two to mate." In this game, Morphy sacrificed three pieces but still had the two necessary to weave the mate!
To conclude this chapter, it is worth reiterating that active defense is not about defense at all. When played well, active defense is nothing more than dynamic chess.
In your own games, when you spot an opponent's threat that you are "forced" to defend against, you must challenge your own assumptions. Don't accept passivity. Sometimes, looking broader leads to a new candidate move that defends without being passive. Sometimes, you can defend by counterattacking. Sometimes, you can get active while allowing your opponent to carry through their plans. Only if nothing active works out should you even consider passively defending. } 0-1


