{ Now let's summarize this chapter on active defense while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board. }
1. e4 { * Active defense is nothing more than fighting for the initiative even when your opponent is trying to generate threats. Rather than responding directly to your opponent, you should look for dynamic moves that push through your agenda instead. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. f4 { * The best defense is a good offense! Championing your own plans even in the face of your opponent's threats is precisely how to play active defense. } { [%cal Ge5f4] } 2... exf4 3. Bc4 { * Textbook active defense should not look like defense at all. When your opponent makes a threat, first consider candidate moves that improve your position as if there was no threat. Then calculate if any of those moves simultaneously deal with your opponent's threats. You might be able to conveniently defend without having to defend at all! } { [%cal Gd7d5] } 3... d5! 4. Bxd5 { * Active defense sometimes requires you to let your opponent follow through with their threats while you generate play elsewhere! } { [%cal Gg8f6] } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { * One-dimensional defensive moves should be avoided. If all you are doing is defending your opponent's threats, the initiative swings fully to your opponent, and you will inevitably get blown off the board. } { [%cal Gf8b4] } 5... Bb4 6. d3?! { * Defending actively often requires you to move beyond materialism. Instead of bending over backwards to hold onto all of your material (like a pawn, or the exchange), you should focus on principled moves that improve your position and make your pieces more active. It may be worthwhile to transform the static advantage of extra material into the dynamic advantages that naturally arise when refuting your opponent's attack. } { [%cal Gf6d5] } 6... Nxd5 7. exd5 { * "Broad, not deep!" When calculating variations, it is much more important not to miss candidate moves for you and your opponent than it is to calculate one line deeply. That one line might not even be the most relevant or critical variation.
A good rule of thumb is to try your best to calculate 3 ply every move. That is, the first ply is the move you want to play, the second ply would be each of the forcing options available to your opponent, and the third ply would be your responses to each. If you can clearly visualize the positions after 3 ply, and there doesn't appear to be a problem in any position, go ahead and play your move! } { [%cal Ge8g8] } 7... O-O! 8. Qf3!? { * When you are ahead material, a good way to convert the position is to trade pieces (but not pawns!). With every successive piece trade, the extra material becomes relatively more and more valuable. Eventually, the end goal is to make a passed pawn and get a new queen. } { [%cal Gf8e8] } (8. Bxf4?! Re8+ 9. Kf1 Qf6 10. Qf3 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3 12. Rc1 $17) 8... Re8+ 9. Ne2 { * When you are ahead material, a good way to convert the position is to use the extra material to launch a successful attack. With more attackers than your opponent can possibly have defenders, you should be able to overwhelm your opponent's defenses. Eventually, the end goal is to checkmate or win a decisive amount of material.
This conversion technique is in direct opposition to the previous conversion technique. The decision to either trade down and win an endgame or overwhelm your opponent with a direct attack is often a matter of taste. By this point in the study, we don't need to guess which technique Morphy preferred. } { [%cal Gb4c3] } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 { * Lower rated players tend to play with their pretty pieces. Making threats with the pieces that are furthest up the board is a good way to lose time and easily get rebuffed.
* Higher rated players tend to focus on their worst-placed pieces. They know how crucial it is to improve all of the pieces first in order to make coherent threats. } { [%cal Gd8h4] } 10... Qh4+! 11. g3?? { * Alignments create threats! Even when you're not completely in control of how the position will open up, lining up your less valuable pieces opposite your opponent's more valuable pieces will inevitably create tactical opportunities down the road. } { [%cal Gc8g4] } (11. Qf2! Qh5 $10 { Equal, but white has to find Kd2! just to avoid being worse. }) 11... Bg4! $19 { Black wins a piece in every variation. There are no tricks, so white resigned.
For more resources exploring active defense, check out:
* Dr. Can's Chess Clinic https://youtu.be/7e5rLZnLtNI
* Hanging Pawns https://youtu.be/aYKuiZ7D4nw
* Chessfactor https://youtu.be/MNhVWYLXmVw } 0-1


