{ Chapter VI: Opposite sides castling

We continue our theme of attack and defense by considering a particularly common type of middlegame where both players attack each other. This next chapter will focus on positions where the players have castled their kings to opposite halves of the board. That is, white's king has gone to the queenside while black's king has gone to the kingside, or vice versa.

We shall see that in such middlegames, the cost of each move goes up because time is at a premium. Additionally, the first player to launch an attack that opens up lines against their opponent's king typically comes out on top.

PRO TIP: You should think about opposite sides castling positions as a race. The first player to take over the initiative by creating decisive threats to the opponent's king typically wins. }
 *


[Event "Casual game"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1854.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Hart"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C44"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Scotch Gambit"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Off to the races"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/PjcYMYAe"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This game was played as part of a 4-player blindfold simultaneous exhibition in New Orleans. Morphy dispatches his NN opponent with a brutal middlegame attack after his opponent chooses to castle queenside. }
1. e4 e5 { This game starts with a Scotch Gambit. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { This game starts with a Scotch Gambit. } 3. d4 exd4 { This game starts with a Scotch Gambit. } 4. Bc4 d6 { A tame response to the Scotch Gambit. Morphy's choice of Bc5 is more principled since it develops and better controls the center. With black's DSB blocked by this d6 pawn, castling kingside becomes a bit harder. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3!? { Nxd4 is a strong alternative. But in true romantic fashion, Morphy opts for faster development at the cost of a pawn. If accepted, white is only up two tempi for the pawn, so this is probably not the best gambit for white. } 5... dxc3 { Taking the offered pawn is probably correct, but it does lose time. Black now needs to continue precisely to avoid falling behind in development. } 6. Qb3!? { Developing with a threat. Qb3 pinpoints f7 as a weakness at a time when black cannot defend actively. Either Qd7 or Qe7 is necessary to defend f7. Yet both moves hinder the development of one of black's bishops. } (6. Nxc3!? $10 { Equally good. Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. O-O!? $10 { Equally good. Play Qb3 instead for the game continuation. }) (6. Be3?? { Oh no, your b2 pawn! } 6... cxb2 $19) (6. Bf4?? { Oh no, your b2 pawn! } 6... cxb2 $19) (6. Bg5?? { Oh no, your b2 pawn! Taking on b2 wins the rook and makes a new queen. Talk about active defense! } 6... cxb2! 7. Bxd8 bxa1=Q $19) 6... Qe7 { Black defends f7 while attacking e4.
For the purposes of this chapter, we should also note that black has chosen to block the DSB. That implies that black is already thinking about castling queenside, which would lead us towards an opposite sides castling middlegame. } 7. O-O! { Active defense! There's no need to directly defend e4, when we can get on with our own plans instead. } (7. Nxc3!? $14 { Equally good. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (7. Bg5?? { Oh no, your b2 pawn! Taking on b2 threatens the rook while making a new queen. Talk about active defense! } 7... cxb2! 8. Bxe7 bxa1=Q $19) (7. Be3?! { Be3 takes the sting out of Qxe4 because it no longer comes with check. But cxb2 is an annoying move that we should not be allowing if we cannot recapture while developing. } 7... cxb2! 8. Qxb2 Nf6 $15) (7. Bf4?? { This move completely ignores black's active possibilities. You must calculate them, not ignore them, if you want to defend actively! } 7... cxb2! 8. Qxb2 Qxe4+ $19) 7... b6? { Black wants to develop the LSB without hanging b7. b6 accomplishes this, but loses more time.
Bd7 was a more active way to develop the queenside. Qxb7? would now be strongly met with Rb8 when black develops quickly with tempo against white's wild queen. } (7... Bd7!? { Active defense! } 8. Qxb7? Rb8 9. Qa6 cxb2 $17) (7... Qd7! $14 { Admitting defeat and trying to castle kingside is best. }) 8. Nxc3 { Morphy continues with his signature multipurpose developing moves. Nxc3 develops while recapturing, but also prepares Nd5 with tempo on black's queen.
In the event of an opposite sides castling middlegame, white can use the half-open c file towards black's king as an avenue of attack. } (8. Bd5!? { Pinpoints a tactical flaw in black's new setup. Equally good. Play Nxc3 instead for the game continuation. } 8... Bb7 9. Nxc3 $16) (8. Bb5!? { Pinpoints a tactical flaw in black's new setup. Equally good. Play Nxc3 instead for the game continuation. } 8... Bb7 9. Nxc3 $16) (8. Bg5?! { After f6, we lose back the tempo we tried to gain. Na5 is coming next to win our LSB. } 8... f6 9. Bf4 Na5 10. Qxc3 Nxc4 11. Qxc4 Bb7 $14) 8... Na5 { Black, to their credit, trades off their knight for white's strong LSB. } { [%cal Gb3b4] } 9. Qb4 Nxc4 10. Qxc4 Bb7 { Yes, Morphy has lost the bishop pair and remains down a pawn. But his massive lead in development and the open lines towards black's king in the center or queenside are more than enough compensation. } 11. Re1!? { Alignments create threats. With the rook opposite both black's king and queen, good things are sure to happen on the e file.
Moreover, given one more move, we would reach a DDD moment. Unless black acts now, the thematic e5 pawn break will blow open the center, opening lines to black's king. } (11. Rd1!? $16 { Equally good. Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. }) (11. Bf4!? $16 { Equally good. Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. }) (11. Bg5?! $14 { Develops with tempo. But after f6 (Qd7 first is more precise), this bishop is getting immediately kicked back. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! }) (11. Nd5?! { Centralizes with tempo. A good candidate move to have. Yet this is nowhere close to the most adaptable move. We should save the tempo for after we have finished development. } 11... Bxd5 12. exd5 Qd7! $14 { Black avoids castling queenside now and can quickly finish kingside development to safety.
This line showcases the problem with playing less adaptable moves before more adaptable moves. You give yourself fewer options and your opponent more! }) 11... O-O-O { Black castles their king, escaping the scary e file. We now arrive at our first opposite sides castling middlegame, so let us take a time out to discuss some fundamentals and assess this position.
White is on move and can already finish development. Black still needs at least three moves to finish development.
The c file is half-open to black's king. That is to say, white does not have a pawn on the file while black does. This means that the c7 pawn, and by extension black's king, can be targeted by white's heavy pieces (queens and rooks) on the c file. While the d file is also half-open, it is less important because there is no target at the end of the file. For black, the half-open e file provides them with a small bit of counterplay. Importantly, they don't have any half-open files on the kingside towards white's king.
PRO TIP: Half-open files are typically advantageous for the player without the pawn. Your heavy pieces often have a purpose on a half-open file: pressuring your opponent's position. Moreover, in contrast to "open" or "fully open" files, your opponent cannot challenge your control of the file.
White's pieces are also significantly more active than black's. The queen on c4 is opposite black's king. The rook on e1 is opposite black's queen. The knights and bishop are ready to jump into action. Meanwhile, black's LSB is their only strong piece.
Black is up a pawn.
In conclusion, white should already be significantly better. The dynamic imbalances all favor white, and black's extra pawn provides nowhere close to enough compensation. } 12. Bf4 { Morphy finishes development, and plants his bishop opposite what could be black's king on b8. } (12. Bg5!? $16 { Equally good. Play Bf4 instead for the game continuation. }) (12. Be3?! $14 { The bishop on e3 is biting on granite. There are better diagonals for it. }) (12. Bd2?! { A half-developing move. The bishop is not better on d2 than on c1. Look for better. }) 12... f6?! { Black continues to show that they are a beginner. One could argue that this move covers e5. One could argue this move is a prelude to a pawn storm on the kingside towards white's king. But in reality, with no pieces developed, any kingside attack will accomplish nothing.
There is no argument: this move simply loses a tempo. } 13. Rac1 { The Morphy move. As always, we must bring all of the boys to the party before launching a decisive attack. } (13. a4! $16 { A high-class move that seeks to open up further lines on the queenside with a5, and justify the rook's placement on a1. Nice job! Play Rac1 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Nd5!? $16 { Centralizing the knight with tempo on black's queen cannot be bad. Play Rac1 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Nd4!? $16 { Nice job centralizing the knight and floating closer to the king. Play Rac1 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Rad1?! $14 { A worse square for the rook than c1. The half-open d file is irrelevant because the d6 pawn is not a target. }) (13. Nb5?! { A possible move, but this doesn't accomplish much after Kb8. This is certainly not the most adaptable move in the position. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 13... Kb8 $14) (13. e5? { The only point of black's last move was to prevent this breakthrough. After dxe5, white has nothing. } 13... dxe5 $17) 13... Kb8 { In normal chess positions, you typically should only attack if there is a justification for it. For instance, if you have a lead in development while their king remains in the center, Morphy's games have shown us that an all-out attack is fully justified.
In opposite sides castling positions, the logic changes. Both sides are nearly always justified in attacking each other's kings. The reasoning is that there is no cost to opening lines against the opponent's king. Your king's shelter is unaffected as you attempt to blast open lines towards your opponent's king.
PRO TIP: You should think about opposite sides castling positions as a race. The first player to take over the initiative by creating decisive threats to the opponent's king typically wins.
In this position, white already has open lines on the queenside toward black's king. Black does not have equivalent lines on the kingside. Viewed as a race, Morphy is already at the second checkpoint, while black has yet to cross the starting line. } 14. Nd5!? { Centralizing the knight with tempo on black's queen cannot be bad, yet there were more precise continuations. } (14. Nd4! $16 { Nice job centralizing the knight and floating closer to the king. Play Nd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (14. Nb5!? $16 { Equally good. Play Nd5 instead for the game continuation. }) (14. a4?! $16 { Inconsistent. If you wanted to open up more lines on the queenside, you should have done this instead of playing Rac1, which makes the a file less relevant. }) (14. e5? { This doesn't actually open up any relevant lines for white's pieces after fxe5. } 14... fxe5 15. Bg5 Nf6 $17) (14. Qa4? { Losing tempo with the queen just to hit a7? Not fast enough. Black has Qd7 and a6 to deal with any threats. } 14... Qd7 15. Nb5 a6 16. Rxc7!! { Amazingly there is still some sauce here too. } 16... Qxb5 17. Qc2! $14 { White has play against black's king even down a piece. }) 14... Bxd5? { "You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move!"
Trading off this key defender for the knight is a horrible idea for black. Clearly, this drastic action was taken because black was afraid of losing c7. But sacrificing c7 in order to get the queens off the board, thus mitigating white's incoming attack, was the lesser evil.
Active defense requires you to fight for your ideas in the face of your opponent's threats, not implode against the slightest pressure! } (14... Qd7! 15. Qxc7+!? (15. Nxc7?! Rc8 16. Na6+! Ka8 17. Qd3 $16) 15... Qxc7 16. Nxc7 $16) 15. exd5 { PRO TIP: In opposite sides castling middlegames, king safety is the most important imbalance in the position. Therefore, opening up lines (files, diagonals, squares) to your opponent's king is crucial. Without these avenues, your pieces cannot target their king. With these avenues, your pieces can generate threats near their king and ultimately deliver a crushing blow.
As an aside, we will see in Chapter VII that this d5 pawn is in fact a "lance" pawn, spearheading a queenside attack. More on that later... } (15. Qxd5? $16 { A worse recapture. White does not open up more lines with this move. }) 15... Qd7 { Black saves their queen while trying to safeguard their king. } { [%cal Gf3d4] } 16. Nd4 { Since Morphy's entire strategy revolves around attacking black's king, bringing this knight towards the queenside (and in particular the juicy c6 square) is a simple decision. } 16... Ne7 { There was only one move to defend c6. Black desperately develops the kingside, but it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } { [%cal Ge1e7] } 17. Rxe7! { A textbook exchange sacrifice to remove a key defender. White's rook on e1 was not directly attacking black's king, while black's knight on e7 was directly defending.
Instead of viewing this as a sacrifice, consider instead that white is trading off a purposeless piece for a key defender. } 17... Bxe7 { White is attacking with four pieces, while the black king's sole bodyguard is the queen. Black's rooks and DSB are helpless to safeguard their king.
PRO TIP: One piece working on its own is ineffective as an attacker or a defender. However, if you have an overwhelming number of pieces on one side of the board, an attack on that side of the board is sure to succeed. In particular, an attackers vs defenders ratio on one area of the board of more than 3:1 is reliably enough to land a fatal blow. } 18. Qa6! { The threat of Nc6+ is stronger than the execution. Instead, Qa6 traps black's king in a mating net.
Now Nc6+ is truly threatened, kicking off a mate-in-2. } (18. Nc6+? { The most obvious move in the position, yet the threat is stronger than the execution. After Kb7, there is no knockout. We did not just sacrifice the exchange to win it back! } 18... Kb7 $16) (18. Ne6?? { Accomplishes nothing after Rc8. Once black shuts down our queenside assault, they will be able to focus on kingside operations towards our king. } 18... Rc8 $10) (18. Nb5?? { Accomplishes nothing after Rc8. Once black shuts down our queenside assault, they will be able to focus on kingside operations towards our king. } 18... Rc8 $10) 18... c5 { The only move to stave off immediate checkmate. } (18... Qc8?? 19. Nc6+ Ka8 20. Qxa7#) 19. dxc6! { Of course we should take en passant to keep open lines towards black's king.
Our rook is no longer directly contributing to the attack because the c file is temporarily closed. Yet it now supports the c pawn that controls some crucial squares around black's king. In fact, the c6 pawn is so powerful, we should view it as a fifth piece in the attack! } 19... Qc8 { Qc7 to blockade the c pawn would have easily been refuted by Nb5, when the queen has to move again.
PRO TIP: A queen is often the worst blockader of a passed pawn. Because she is the most valuable piece, attacking her with anything forces her to respond. Therefore, the blockade is easy to lift.
How do you continue the attack? } (19... Qc7?! 20. Nb5 Qc8 21. Qxa7#) 20. c7+! (20. Bxd6+?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 20... Rxd6 $17) (20. Nb5?? { Oh no, your queen! } 20... Qxa6 21. c7+ Kb7 22. cxd8=Q Rxd8 $19) (20. Ne6?? { Oh no, your queen! } 20... Qxa6 21. c7+ Kb7 22. cxd8=Q Bxd8 $19) (20. Qxc8+?? { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! We certainly don't want to trade queens in the middle of a mating attack! } 20... Rxc8 $10) 20... Ka8 { Black cannot afford to sacrifice the queen for the c pawn, so this move was forced. } 21. cxd8=Q! { Excellent find! Black's queen is temporarily pinned to the king, so neither Qxa6 nor Qxc1 are legal.
Fun fact: The pawn that just promoted did everything a pawn can do. At various points, it moved one square forward, moved two squares forward, captured normally, captured en passant, and promoted. A true martyr for our cause! } (21. cxd8=R!? $18 { Equally good. In the game, Morphy promoted to a queen. }) (21. Qxc8+?? { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! We certainly don't want to trade queens in the middle of a mating attack! } 21... Rxc8 $10) 21... Qxd8 { Necessary, unless black wanted to allow Rxc8. } (21... Rxd8?! 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Qxc8#) (21... Bxd8? 22. Rxc8#) 22. Nb5! { Pedal to the metal. Even up a piece, Morphy uses the initiative and continues delivering blow after blow. } (22. Ne6!? $18 { The threats on d8 and c7 decide the game. Play Nb5 instead for the game continuation. }) (22. Nc6? { Why block your own rook from the attack? After Qd7, your mate threat is defended, and the game continues. } 22... Qd7 23. Nxe7! Qxe7?? 24. Rc8+ Rxc8 25. Qxc8# { I doubt you calculated this entire line before pulling the trigger on Nc6. }) 22... Qb8!? { The mate threat on a7 could only be stopped with Qb8 or Qd7. Morphy's move is the same against either defense. } (22... Qd7!? 23. Rc7! $18) 23. Rc7! $18 { Morphy's queenside attack finally breaks through. Since giving up the queen cannot even prevent checkmate, black resigned.
This game truly highlights how genius Morphy was with the initiative. Even in a blindfold simul, he doesn't give his opponents a second to breathe. Ever since Morphy landed Nd5, black exclusively responded to threats, rather than making any of their own.
In the final position, Morphy is mating by force, while black has not made a single active move to generate play against Morphy's king. Morphy has already finished the race, while his opponent has yet to cross the starting line. } (23. Nc7+! $18 { Equally crushing. Black must give up the queen, and can't even slow down the checkmating attack. Play Rc7 instead for the game continuation. }) (23. Rc8?? { Oh no, your rook! I think you lost your grip on the board and forgot that this square was defended by the h8 rook too. } 23... Rxc8 24. Nxa7! $10) (23. Nxd6?? { Oh no, you lost your grip on the board! At the end of all the trades, black has Qb8 again, defending against the back-rank mate. } 23... Bxd6 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 25. Rc8+ Rxc8 26. Qxc8+ Qb8 $14 { White should not enter this position when we need to win the game all over again. }) (23. Bxd6?? { Oh no, you lost your grip on the board! At the end of all the trades, black has Qb8 again, defending against the back-rank mate. } 23... Bxd6 24. Nxd6 Qxd6 25. Rc8+ Rxc8 26. Qxc8+ Qb8 $14 { White should not enter this position when we need to win the game all over again. }) 1-0


