{ In this game, a young Paul Morphy plays his uncle, a much stronger opponent than Paul's father. While Ernest was no match for Morphy in his prime, he was strong enough to give him a non-odds game as a child.

After trading opening inaccuracies, we arrive at a highly instructive opposite sides castling middlegame. }
1. e4 e5 { The game starts with an Evans Gambit. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 { The game starts with an Evans Gambit. } 3. Bc4 Bc5 { The game starts with an Evans Gambit. } 4. b4 Bxb4 { This is not our first Evans Gambit, and indeed both Morphys play down a line we have already seen before. } 5. c3 Ba5 { A fiery option. Black's Ba5 "prevents" white from building a strong center because the c3 pawn is pinned. } 6. d4! { The most precise continuation! Morphy correctly asks the Shankland question, "what if I do it anyway?" } 6... exd4 { We have seen this exact position before. Previously, Morphy's opponent had the white pieces and went wrong with e5.
This time, Morphy plays a more accurate continuation. } 7. O-O! { Morphy gets on with development and now threatens to recapture on d4 with the pawn, achieving a strong center. } (7. Qb3!? $10 { Equally strong. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (7. Ba3?! $15 { Premature. Remember that when we have many choices, we should play the most adaptable move first. Sometimes the bishop lands on a3 in the Evans. But sometimes from c1 it is useful too, stopping Nh6. }) (7. Nxd4?! $15 { We want to get a strong center, not compromise by recapturing our sacrificed material in an inferior manner! Play more actively instead. }) (7. Bg5?! { Developing with tempo. Yet you are forcing your opponent to respond by developing and blocking with Nge7 themselves. Don't force your opponent to make good moves! } 7... Nge7 $15) (7. e5? { This is the same incorrect move Morphy's opponent played in an earlier game! Morphy correctly refuted it with active defense, kicking off with d5! } 7... d5 $17) 7... Bxc3?! { Insanely greedy. Black is now temporarily up three pawns at the cost of moving their bishop for a fourth time. } (7... Nf6!? { One of two theoretical main lines. } 8. Ba3 d6 9. e5 Ne4! 10. exd6 cxd6 11. Qe2 d5 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 f5 14. Bb3 Kf7 $10 { One sample line where black mostly consolidates the extra pawn. }) 8. Nxc3 { Active defense. We save the rook by capturing on c3 and regaining the tempo. } (8. Qb3?! { A possible alternative, sacrificing the rook on a1 but breaking through to the important f7 square. The lines to prove that there is really an attack here are insanely deep though! See the PGN after the game if you're curious.
Look for simpler. } 8... Bxa1 9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. Bxg8! Rxg8? (10... Qe8! { Warning: engine line ahead } 11. Bd5 d6 12. Ba3 Ne7!! 13. e5 Nxd5 14. exd6!! Kg8!! 15. Re1 Qc6 16. Ne5 Qe8 17. Nf3 Qc6 $10 { An engine line that ends in repetition. I recommend not going anywhere near this if you are a human. }) 11. Ng5! d5! { Active defense! } (11... Qe7?? 12. Nxh7+ Ke8 13. Qxg8+ Qf8 14. Qxf8#) 12. Qf3+ Qf6 13. Nxh7+ Kf7 14. Nxf6 gxf6 $18) (8. Bb2?? $19 { Oh no, your bishop! }) (8. Ba3?? $19 { Sometimes sacrificing this exchange but snagging the dark squares in return is a reasonable trade. Unfortunately you are not just sacrificing the exchange - your rook is undefended! }) 8... dxc3 { [%cal Gc1a3] } 9. Ba3?! { A rare Morphy inaccuracy in the opening! This move is not correct simply because it is not the most adaptable move. The bishop often stands well on the a3-f8 diagonal, but not always. From c1, the bishop still has a useful role preventing Nh6 in certain lines.
Qb3 is the more adaptable developing move. It hits f7 immediately, when Nh6 has been prevented by the bishop that remains on c1. } (9. Qb3! { The most precise move simply because it is the most adaptable. The bishop on c1 sometimes performs a useful role by preventing Nh6. } 9... Nh6? (9... Qf6!? 10. e5 Qg6 11. Qxc3 $16 { Best play. White is only down two pawns but has a massive lead in development and strong clamp on the position. }) 10. Bxh6 { The bishop on c1 serves a productive purpose! } 10... gxh6 11. Bxf7+ $18) 9... d6 { Active defense. Black prepares to develop their LSB while simultaneously shutting out white's DSB. } 10. Qb3 Nh6 { Active defense! Now we see the flaw of Morphy's earlier Ba3. From c1 it prevented this convenient response to the threat on f7. } { [%cal Gb3c3] } 11. Qxc3 Qf6?! { A step in the wrong direction. Black would love to trade queens while up two pawns, but castling the king to safety on the kingside was significantly more important. } (11... O-O! 12. e5 Re8 $10 { White has play here too, but is certainly not better. }) 12. e5! { Excellent job spotting the DDD moment! A third pawn is thrown into the wood chipper in order to blast open further lines and keep black's king in the center. } (12. Qxf6? { This capture ruins black's pawn structure, but who cares? Trading queens kills all of your dynamic potential, and white remains down two pawns! } 12... gxf6 $15) (12. Qb3?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qc2?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qd3?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qe3?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qd2?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qb2? { Accomplishes nothing except allow the same queen trade we want to avoid! } 12... Qxb2 13. Bxb2 $17) (12. Qc1?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Qe1?! { Losing a tempo with the queen allows black the chance to castle to safety. } 12... O-O $15) (12. Rac1? { With black's king so vulnerable, we certainly do not want to allow a queen trade! } 12... Qxc3 13. Rxc3 $17) (12. Rfc1? { With black's king so vulnerable, we certainly do not want to allow a queen trade! } 12... Qxc3 13. Rxc3 $17) (12. Bb2? { With black's king so vulnerable, we certainly do not want to allow a queen trade! } 12... Qxc3 13. Bxc3 $17) (12. Bb4? { With black's king so vulnerable, we certainly do not want to allow a queen trade! } 12... Qxc3 13. Bxc3 $17) 12... dxe5 { With this last capture, our DSB has just sprung to life. Black is never castling kingside. } { [%cal Gf1e1] } (12... Nxe5?! 13. Nxe5 O-O! $10 { Active defense! The engine may find lines that prove this is equal, but white should take home the full point every time in a practical game. } (13... Qxe5?? 14. Rae1 $18 { The reason black did not play 12... Nxe5 }) 14. Rae1!? c5! { Shutting down the DSB is necessary. } 15. Bb2 dxe5 16. Rxe5 Ng4 17. Rxc5 Qxc3 18. Bxc3 Nf6 $10) 13. Rfe1 Bd7 { Black recognizes they cannot castle kingside or leave their king in the center, so they take steps towards castling queenside.
To that end, this specific half-developing move is necessary. Any other bishop move would be met with Rad1, preventing black from queenside castling too. } { [%cal Ga1b1] } 14. Rab1 { The Morphy move! Of course, white's a1 rook still needed to contribute. Rab1 anticipates black castling queenside, when the rook is already targeting the tender b7 target. } 14... O-O-O { As expected, black castles queenside. Now that we arrive at a position on topic for this chapter, let's break down this opposite sides castling middlegame.
Black has successfully finished development and is up three pawns. The e5 pawn in particular is a strong center pawn. There is no attack on white's king.
White has the more active pieces. In particular, white's rooks and queen all have more scope than their black counterparts, mainly due to the open lines to black's king.
PRO TIP: Every pawn lost is a file gained! Under normal circumstances, losing a pawn is more important than gaining a file for your heavy pieces. However, when you are racing to open up lines to the opponent's king, sacrificing a pawn (or three!) can be a small price to pay.
In fact, this position would be notably worse for white if we had an extra pawn on b2. That traitor would prevent our crucial pressure down the b file. We should be thankful black captured our b pawn so many moves ago!
This position is a true battle of statics vs dynamics. Black is arguing that their three extra pawns will decide the game. White is arguing that their queenside attack will decide the game. Evaluating such a position is tricky, but with so many open lines and all but one of the pieces still on the board, we should trust in white's attack.
When you are ready, play the spectacular Ba6 for the game continuation. } 15. Ba6!! { Morphy throws in the kitchen sink in order to open up more lines on the queenside. After bxa6, the b and c files in particular are ripped open even further for the heavy pieces.
Sacrificing a piece just to open up lines is not a decision to be taken lightly. Morphy no doubt calculated several variations deeply before pulling the trigger on this sacrifice. } 15... Na5? { The losing move. bxa6 had to be played, after which the hunt for black's king kicks off with Qb3! I have included several instructive variations in the PGN of this game if you want to further explore what could have happened if the piece was accepted.
In the game, black was clearly afraid of opening up lines on the queenside. Na5 protects b7 and tries to keep a lid on white's initiative. No doubt, black underestimated Morphy's next move. } (15... bxa6! 16. Qb3 Bg4! { Active defense! Black might have missed this necessary defensive option. Now the king has the d7 square to run to, and Bxf3 is a useful intermezzo later down the line. } 17. Qb7+ Kd7 18. Rbd1+ Ke8! 19. Qxc7 $10 { The position is objectively equal, although black is obviously running for their life. } 19... Bxf3!? { An instructive engine line continues: } 20. gxf3 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Nd4! { And annoyingly white has no file for the rook to work with. } 22. Kf1!? (22. Rb1?? Qg6+! $19 { [%cal Gg6b1] }) (22. Re1?! Nxf3+ $10 { [%cal Gf3e1,Gf3g1] }) 22... Nhf5 23. Re1 Qb6 24. Rxe5+ Ne6 25. Qc8+ Qd8 26. Qc6+ Qd7 27. Qa8+ Qd8 28. Qc6+ $10 { There is no better for either side than a repetition. }) 16. Rec1! { Checks, captures, threats! With a solid grip on the board, we should instantly have spotted that c7 became a vulnerable target as soon as the c6 knight moved.
PRO TIP: Mate-in-1 threats are some of the strongest forcing moves. Besides checks, where it's illegal to ignore them, threats to checkmate your opponent necessitate a response. After all, checkmate wins the game!
While playing your games, you should constantly scan the board to make sure you don't miss a mate threat for you or your opponent. They are not necessarily the best moves, but they must be calculated to ensure they don't immediately win material or the game. This is one more aspect of keeping a grip on the board.
In this game, black has no convenient way to prevent Qxc7# while handling the pressure on b7 and a5 too. } (16. Qxa5?? { Black clearly saw this knight was hanging before playing Na5. Capturing on a5 allows Qxa6, when a queen trade dramatically lessens white's attacking potential. In fact, black's pawns are much more valuable once the queens come off the board. } 16... Qxa6 17. Qxa6 bxa6 18. Rxe5 f6 19. Rc5 $17) (16. Rbc1? { The wrong rook! We want to use both the b and c files to attack black's king. } 16... Qb6! $14) (16. Bxb7+?? { Black's last move protected against Bxb7. There is not compensation for sacrificing the bishop in this manner. } 16... Nxb7 17. Rec1 Qc6 $17) (16. Bd6?? { Oh no, your bishop! Perhaps you missed the queen also eyes d6? } 16... Qxd6 $19) 16... Bc6 { There was no convenient response to our mate threat. After Bc6, black can no longer capture our bishop on a6 with their queen. Therefore, more lines will be opened up on the queenside after all. } { [%cal Gc3a5] } 17. Qxa5 bxa6 { Clearly, black should have rolled the dice with bxa6 earlier when they were at least winning a piece. Now, black has a compromised king without even being up a piece. } { [%cal Ga5a6] } 18. Qxa6+ Kd7 { The open lines on the queenside mean that black's king must run back towards the center. Unfortunately, there is no safety in the center either. } { [%cal Gc1c6] } 19. Rxc6! { Capturing the rook with Qxc6 walks into Nxe5+ with a fork. Thus, black has neither a kingside attack nor extra material to compensate for their vulnerable king.
White has already been rewarded for the strategy of attacking on the queenside. } 19... Qf5!? { This queen move accomplishes nothing active. } { [%cal Gc6c7] } (19... Qxc6!? 20. Nxe5+ $18) 20. Rxc7+! { "One to sac and two to mate!"
Even after winning a decisive amount of material, Morphy is unapologetic about committing to the opposite side's castling strategy: break open lines on the queenside and attach the king as fast as possible.
This rook "sacrifice" is one of many winning moves, but it is definitely the most direct. } 20... Ke8 { Taking the rook would have walked into Qb7#, so black has to continue running for their life. However, with the sniper bishop on a3 cutting off any true escape, it's clear that black's king is not long for this world.
The rest of this game is mostly irrelevant since every legal move wins. } { [%cal Ga6c6] } (20... Kxc7?! 21. Qb7#) 21. Qc6+ Qd7 { Rd7 allowed Rb8#. } { [%cal Gb1b8] } (21... Rd7?! 22. Rb8#) 22. Rb8! { Morphy, ever the artist, sets up an aesthetic mate rather than take the free queen. } 22... Qxc6 { [%cal Gc7e7] } 23. Re7+ Kf8 { [%cal Gb8d8] } 24. Rxd8+ Qe8 { [%cal Ge7e8] } 25. Rexe8# { Either rook capture was mate, but of course a true artist is obliged to play a double checkmate if allowed.
We should appreciate how similarly Morphy handles positions where his opponent's king is stuck in the center and where his opponent's king is castled on the opposite side of the board of his. In both cases, grabbing the initiative and using it to execute an all-out attack is justified and indeed obligatory. In both cases, a successful attack requires active pieces and open lines to the king. } 1-0


