{ Another knight-odds game against Frederick Perrin, who we last saw in Chapter II. In this game, black escapes the opening well and ends up in a middlegame with opposite sides castling. Because both sides play the opening phase reasonably well, commentary on the opening will be light.

Let's focus on the middlegame where the theme of this chapter becomes relevant. } { [%csl Rb1][%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 2. f4 d5 { Active defense! An even better idea when facing someone already down a knight. } { [%cal Ge4d5] } 3. exd5 Qxd5 { Developing the queen early is a poor idea... if she can get hit with tempo as the opponent develops naturally. But in a knight-odds game, which white piece can touch the queen on d5? } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 4. Nf3 e4 { [%cal Gf3e5] } 5. Ne5 Be6 { [%cal Gf1c4] } 6. Bc4 Qd6 { Amusingly, Morphy still finds a way to develop with tempo on the queen. Regardless, black is happy to encourage further piece trades while already up material. } { [%cal Gd1e2] } 7. Qe2 Nf6 { [%cal Gd2d4] } 8. d4 Bxc4 { [%cal Ge5c4] } 9. Nxc4 { Qxc4 would have allowed a queen trade after Qb4+. Such a trade is unacceptable while we are already down a piece, so we should recapture with the knight, even if that means retreating. } (9. Qxc4?! Qb4+ $19) 9... Qe6!? { Black is no fool. Capturing the pawn on d4 does not win a more decisive material advantage than they already have. What it does do though is lose time, walk into more tempi with Be3, and open lines while black is already behind in development.
PRO TIP: A material advantage has diminishing returns. Winning a pawn is often enough to achieve a winning advantage. Winning two is certainly enough for a winning advantage. But winning more material does not make the advantage any more winning! In fact, while you spend time grabbing extra material, you are likely increasing your opponent's dynamic potential more than you are furthering your own advantage. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } (9... Qxd4!? 10. Be3 Qd7 11. O-O $19) 10. O-O Nc6 { Active defense! Developing and threatening d4. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 11. c3 Bd6 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 12. f5 Qe7 { Qd5 would have been met with Ne3, when the queen gets sidelined. Instead, black chooses to walk into an annoying pin. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } 13. Bg5 { Both sides have played well so far. Black has nearly finished development with a slight disadvantage in activity. They remain up a piece.
White has finished development, controls more of the center (what useful squares are controlled by black's e4 pawn?), and is building up an attack on the kingside. Indeed Morphy is ensuring that castling kingside is not without risks due to white's advanced f pawn and the pin on f6 that cannot be broken. } 13... O-O-O { Black goes queenside, where there is more security. Indeed, there are no open files for white's heavy pieces on the queenside, and white's c4 knight is the only piece within spitting distance of black's king. Moreover, Bxf6 can now always be met with gxf6, a desirable move that opens up the kingside.
Yet not all is as favorable for black as it might initially seem. Firstly, we already know the game just turned into a race to checkmate, which means dynamic factors outweigh static ones. Thus, black's extra piece is not simply game-winning as it might be in a calmer position.
Secondly, white's strong center prevents black from maneuvering pieces to the kingside from the queenside and vice versa. This means that should black shift pieces to attack, they will be cut off from simultaneously defending. In contrast, white's pieces can accomplish both. In one hop, our knight can land a vicious check or turn into a stout defender on e3. Our queen is a blink away from joining in on a queenside attack or jumping to the kingside to shore up defense.
As we shall soon explore, white has a third key advantage too. Play b4 for the game continuation. } 14. b4! { With this move, Morphy starts a pawn storm on the queenside!
PRO TIP: Pawn storms are a common strategy to break open lines on one side of the board. While the intermediate pawn pushes do not typically achieve anything constructive, a pawn storm's ultimate goal is a pawn break that your opponent cannot respond to by keeping the position closed. Thus, a successful pawn storm opens lines.
In this position, white is ultimately aiming for the b6 pawn break. Since b6 lands a fork on black's a and c pawns, black would have no way to respond to b6 while keeping the position closed. Either the a or b file will open up for white's heavy pieces. In contrast, a6 would be an ineffective pawn break; a6 is met with b6 and the queenside remains closed. As we shall soon see, this is because b7 is not a hook.
Considering black's kingside play, we see that black does not have a corresponding pawn storm. h6 is a fine start, but after Bh4, black reaches a dead end. There is no way to push the g pawn without undefending the f6 knight. Indeed, g6 or g5 are always met with fxg6, after which black loses the knight.
This is the third advantage white has: our queenside pawn storm will be more effective at opening lines than their kingside pawn storm. } 14... Nb8?! { Undeveloping the knight makes no sense on its own. Furthermore, this is the beginning of a faulty plan from black. } 15. a4 { "If you say A, you must say B!" Any other move would be inconsistent with our plan of pawn storming the queenside. } (15. b5!? $17 { Continuing the pawn storm! Equally good to the game continuation of a4. }) 15... c6?! { Black continues their faulty plan of playing on the queenside.
PRO TIP: It is rarely a good idea to meet an incoming pawn storm by pushing pawns yourself. All you will end up doing is creating weaknesses, speeding up your opponent's attack, and/or losing time. Instead you should seek counterplay elsewhere, preferably in the center of the board.
Rhe8, Qd7, or even e3 were all better ideas. They all ignore white's pawn storm and get on with improving the pieces with a focus on the center. } 16. b5 { Black's c6 move has only sped up our attack. The pawns are already making contact, whereas it would have taken us two more moves before contact if black's pawn remained on c7. } (16. a5?! $17 { A poor choice since we are not threatening a6. Get on with opening files instead! }) 16... Qc7 { Importantly, responding to b5 with c5 would not have broken down white's center or prevented queenside files from eventually opening. If black ever plays cxd4, white always responds with cxd4, and the only thing black has accomplished is opening the c file towards their king.
In the game, black chooses to sit with the pawn tension. In the meantime they are creating a one-move threat on the kingside. } (16... c5?! { Doesn't actually break down white's center. } 17. a5! { Threatening a6 b6, Nxb6! axb6, a7, when the a pawn queens. }) 17. h3 { No counterplay! Our queenside assault remains inevitable, so we can take time out to handle black's only threat. } (17. bxc6?! $17 { You are correctly opening the b file, but why rush?
Pawn storms on their own can only lead the charge in an attack (with the goal of opening lines). Active pieces must form the core of an attacking army for these newly opened lines to matter.
Considering bxc6 through that lens, all you are doing is improving the knight on b8 rather than improving any of your pieces. We need more firepower first! }) (17. g3?! $17 { Similar to the game continuation, but perhaps less solid. Both Bxg3 and h5-h4 become new ways for black to open up the kingside that they didn't have one second ago. }) (17. g4? $17 { It is rarely a good idea to push pawns on the side of the board where you have castled in opposite sides castling middlegames. In particular, g4 creates a hook that black can immediately use to blast open the position on the kingside with h5! }) (17. h4?! $17 { A worse version of the game since now the kingside is more vulnerable. }) (17. b6?! $17 { An interesting approach to open the queenside at all costs. Not a bad idea, but simply preventing black's threat first is easier and stronger. }) 17... Rde8 { [%cal Gg5f6] } 18. Bxf6?! { A questionable decision by Morphy.
Now that the f6 knight is out of the pin, Morphy captures her, preempting any offensive and defensive capabilities she would have from d5. But Bxf6 will be met with gxf6, when a kingside file will open towards white's king.
Better and more thematic would have been b6! axb6, a5! when all of the queenside files are immediately blasted open. } (18. b6! axb6 19. a5! bxa5 20. Rxa5!? (20. Nxd6+!? Qxd6 21. Rxa5 Nd5 22. c4 $17) 20... b5?? (20... Bh2+ 21. Kh1 b5 $17) 21. Nxd6+ Qxd6 22. Bf4 $16) 18... gxf6 { At least now black has a file on the kingside to work with. } 19. Rfb1 { The Morphy move! Morphy optimizes his last piece that is not yet contributing before he opens up the queenside. } (19. Rab1!? $17 { A reasonable alternative, although the pawn storm might lead to the a file opening up too. Play Rfb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (19. bxc6?! { You are correctly opening the b file, but why rush?
Pawn storms on their own can only lead the charge in an attack (with the goal of opening lines). Active pieces must form the core of an attacking army for these newly opened lines to matter.
Considering bxc6 through that lens, all you are doing is improving the knight on b8 rather than improving any of your pieces. We need more firepower first! } 19... Nxc6 $17) (19. b6!? { The right idea as long as you planned to follow-up axb6 with a5! All of the queenside files will open. In the game, Morphy brought in the final piece with Rfb1. } 19... axb6 20. a5 bxa5 21. Rfb1!? $17) (19. d5? { Increasing the tension further is tempting, but you are weakening your center too much for this to be smart. Black has Bc5+ and can next follow up with taking the free d5 pawn. The queenside does not adequately open up. } 19... Bc5+ 20. Kh1 cxd5 $19) (19. Nxd6+? { Why are you trading off pieces in the middle of a blistering attack? That bishop served no productive role in either attack or defense! } 19... Qxd6 $17) (19. Rfc1?! $17 { A poor choice. The c file cannot open up for white in any line. }) 19... b6? { Under pressure, black immediately crumbles.
We have already discussed how pawn moves on the side of the board with your king are often harmful. b6 in particular is suicidal as it creates a "hook" for us to bite at.
A "hook" is a pawn near the opponent's king that can be exploited by our pawn break to open lines. An essential trait of a hook pawn is that it is restricted from advancing in response to the pawn break (thus safely avoiding the pawn tension and keeping the position closed). In particular, the opponent's fixed or advanced pawns near their king are potential hooks.
PRO TIP: Hooks are chinks in your opponent's armor. When launching an attack at your opponent's king, exploit this immobile target with a timely pawn break to peel away the pawn shield protecting their king and open files and diagonals for your pieces. A word of warning: creating a hook in an opposite sides castling middlegame can be suicidal. If your opponent is foolish enough to do so, kindly thank them for the gift of turbo-charging your attack!
How should you continue? } (19... c5? 20. b6! axb6 21. Rxb6 $10) 20. a5! { You shouldn't have to be asked twice to bite at that hook!
With maximum tension on the queenside, all of the files are soon to open. White's heavy pieces will flood in next. } (20. bxc6? { Releasing the tension opens less lines than immediately biting on the hook. } 20... Qxc6 21. a5 Bc7! $17 { Black shores up b6 and there is no knockout. }) (20. Nxd6+? { Why are you trading off pieces in the middle of a blistering attack? That bishop served no productive role in either attack or defense! } 20... Qxd6 21. a5 Re7 $17) (20. Nxb6+?? { Oh no, your knight! Either recapture is fine for black since this sacrifice in no way opens up more queenside files. } 20... Qxb6!? (20... axb6!? $19) 21. bxc6 Qxc6 $19) 20... cxb5?! { Suboptimal. c5 was necessary to at least keep some of the queenside files closed. } (20... c5! 21. axb6 axb6 22. Ra6 $10 { White has full compensation for being down a piece. After all, what is black's knight even doing on b8? }) 21. axb6! { An exception to the rule of thumb that recapturing is typically the strongest response. This intermediate move creates two killer threats: bxc7 winning a queen, and bxa7 creating a new one. The knight on c4 is therefore immune for one move. } (21. Rxb5?! { The obvious recapture, but we are missing an opportunity to open up even more queenside files first! } 21... Nd7 22. axb6 axb6 23. Ra6 Kb7!? 24. Nxb6! Nxb6 25. Qa2! $18) (21. Nxd6+?? { Why are you trading off pieces in the middle of a blistering attack? That bishop served no productive role in either attack or defense! } 21... Qxd6 22. Rxb5 Re7! $17 { With less traffic, black can bring in more defenders. }) (21. Nxb6+?? { Oh no, your knight! } 21... axb6 22. a6 (22. axb6?! Qxb6 23. Rxb5 Qc6 $19) 22... Nc6 23. a7 Nxa7 $19) 21... Bh2+ { Black throws in an irrelevant spite check that doesn't materially change the situation. } (21... Qxc4?? 22. Qxc4+ bxc4 23. bxa7 $18 { [%cal Ga7a8,Ga7b8] }) 22. Kh1 (22. Kf1?? { The king is clearly less safe on the f file. } 22... Qf4+ $17) (22. Kf2?? { The king is clearly less safe on the f file. } 22... Qf4+ $17) 22... axb6 { The justification of inserting axb6 earlier is now clear. More queenside files have been opened for the heavy pieces. } 23. Rxb5 (23. Nxb6+? { A forcing sacrifice that doesn't throw the game away. However, with such a strong attack, we no longer need to sacrifice. Keep this knight alive for now - she'll soon contribute to our winning attack. } 23... Qxb6 24. Rxb5 Qd6 25. Qc4+ Qc7 26. Rc5 $10) 23... Nc6? { The final straw. Black needed to play Nd7 to at least force white to trade knights in the event that b6 falls.
Now, b6 will fall for free, and the queenside has been fatally breached. } { [%cal Ga1b1] } (23... Nd7!? 24. Ra6 Kd8 25. Nxb6 Nxb6 26. Raxb6 $16) 24. Rab1 Bf4 { Black may technically remain up a bishop, but they are helpless to prevent decisive infiltration on the b file.
In fact, I would argue that white is no longer down a piece. Counting the pieces doing anything constructive points us to a new material count: white is up the exchange! Black's h8 rook remains at home watching TV, so white is surely winning in a variety of ways. } 25. Nxb6+ (25. Rxb6!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Nxb6+ instead for the game continuation. }) (25. Qa2!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Nxb6+ instead for the game continuation. }) (25. d5!? $18 { Equally winning. Play Nxb6+ instead for the game continuation. } 25... Ne5 26. Nxb6+ Kd8 27. d6! $18) 25... Kd8 { Forced. } { [%cal Gb6d5] } 26. Nd5 Qd6 { The only queen move that defends the DSB. } { [%cal Ge2a2] } 27. Qa2 $18 { The final piece joins the attack. Qa8+ is as deadly as it is unstoppable.
Once more, we see that Morphy's queenside attack has broken through before his opponent has even started a corresponding attack on the kingside. This catastrophe was mainly due to black creating weaknesses and an all-important hook on the queenside rather than hurrying to attack white on the kingside. } 1-0


[Event "Morphy - Harrwitz"]
