{ During Morphy's trip to Europe, he played matches with several of the world's best, including Daniel Harrwitz - a top 5 player in the world. In this first-to-7 match, Morphy lost the first two games before rallying and winning the next four. Morphy also completed dominated Harrwitz in game 7, only to fumble the finish and draw. This was game 8. }
1. e4 e5 { Incredibly, the first 7 moves of this game follow the Opera Game. Technically, though, this game was played first. So, to be precise, the Opera Game follows the first 7 moves of this game!
Use this as an opportunity to show off your memory of the Opera Game! } 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Bg4 4. dxe5 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 Nf6 7. Qb3 Bd6?! { In the Opera Game, black defended f7 with Qe7. Here, black gives up the pawn "for compensation." } 8. Bxf7+ (8. Qxb7?! { Another free pawn available to capture. But after Nbd7, black has a lead in development, so at least they have some compensation for the pawn. Capture the more important pawn. } 8... Nbd7 9. Qb3 O-O $14) 8... Kf8 { In reality, white has the pawn and the compensation! White has a slight lead in development (it's our turn), a safer king, and an extra pawn. Black has nothing going for them.
Don't spend time analyzing the next few moves, since both players drift. Let's skip ahead to move 16, when the theme of this chapter becomes relevant. } { [%cal Gc1g5] } 9. Bg5 Nbd7 { [%cal Gf7h5] } 10. Bh5 g6 { [%cal Gg5h6] } 11. Bh6+ Ke7 { [%cal Gh5f3] } 12. Bf3 Nc5 { [%cal Gb3c4] } 13. Qc4 b5 { [%cal Gc4e2] } 14. Qe2 Ne6 { [%cal Gh6e3] } 15. Be3 a6 { [%cal Gb1d2] } 16. Nd2 Kf7 { Even though black has not technically castled kingside, they are preparing to artificially castle by safeguarding the king on the kingside and next bringing the h8 rook into the game.
White remains up a pawn and is not behind in development. How would you continue? } 17. O-O-O! { White castles long and finishes development while placing the rook on an open file.
Technically, black has not "castled" to the opposite half of the board as us. Regardless, the kings have ended up opposite each other and so strategically both sides should treat this as an opposite sides castling middlegame. } (17. O-O!? $16 { Finishing development and even aligning the rook opposite black's king. Not bad. Yet after Kg7, is this the best we can do for our rooks? }) (17. h4!? $16 { A reasonable attempt to open lines on the kingside now that black has committed their king. Let's first finish development before we attack with the game continuation: O-O-O. }) (17. a4!? $16 { A strong move to claim the c4 square for our knight. This move is not on-theme for this chapter. Play O-O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (17. g4?! { A premature lashing-out move. We still need to finish development before caveman chess becomes relevant. } 17... h6 $16) 17... Qe7 { The two main factors to consider when planning a pawn storm are center control and piece activity. Evaluating both factors will help you decide if a pawn storm will lead to a successful attack.
PRO TIP: Control over the center improves the mobility of your pieces while simultaneously reducing your opponent's piece mobility. Moreover, attempting a pawn storm on the flank without a firm grip on the center allows your opponent an opportunity to overrule your flank play with their own active play in the center.
PRO TIP: Pawn storms on their own can only lead the charge in an attack (with the goal of opening lines). Active pieces must form the core of an attacking army for these newly opened lines to matter.
In this position, both sides have an equal share of the center, with useful squares carved out by the e4 and e5 pawns. Moreover, both sides have their pieces on central squares, with rough parity in activity. Indeed, because neither side is dominating either factor, both players can and should pawn storm each other to kick off the race and try to break through first.
White's main advantage is the extra pawn: f2. The static advantage of an extra pawn is mostly irrelevant in this race, yet the dynamic potential of this specific pawn leading a kingside pawn storm is priceless.
Play g3 for the game continuation. } 18. g3!? { Perhaps this is a mysterious move at first glance. Can you come up with the ultimate goal of this move within the context of this chapter? } (18. h4! $16 { Objectively the best move. Yet h4-h5 does not bite at a hook because black can always respond to h5 with g5, keeping the kingside closed. }) 18... Rhb8!? { Black gets on with preparing the queenside pawn storm. Yet was this move necessary? Perhaps Kg7 (the most adaptable move!) or a5 (asking the Shankland question: what if I pawn storm anyway?) was stronger. } { [%cal Gf3g2] } (18... Kg7! { The most adaptable move. In every variation, black's king clearly does not belong on the f file. } 19. Bg2 Rad8!? { Noting that black will lose the race if they play down the obvious path, perhaps they should play for piece activity and central control instead? } 20. Rhf1 Bc5 21. f4?! Bxe3! 22. Qxe3 Ng4 23. Qg1 Nd4 $14 { Black's piece activity has improved dramatically, while white's pawn storm hasn't accomplished anything yet. }) 19. Bg2 a5 { Dueling pawn storms in action! Black is clearly gunning for us on the queenside, so we must hurry to open up the kingside.
Pop quiz: what ultimate pawn break does black need to achieve to open up the queenside? } 20. Rhf1 { Preparing the corresponding pawn storm on the kingside.
The "obvious" h4-h5 pawn storm is actually misguided because g6 is not a hook. The h5 pawn break can always be met with g5, keeping the kingside closed. As such, the rook on the h file was clearly the correct rook to place on f1. } (20. f4!! { Yes! This is the strongest move and another example of the Shankland question in action! f4 is hanging, but you can push past that resistance by calculating "what if I do it anyway?"
If the pawn is captured with exf4, white has e5!, ripping open the diagonal for the LSB towards the rook on a8. White will win the exchange and open lines on the kingside as well.
Play Rhf1, preparing this break, instead for the game continuation. } 20... exf4 21. e5! Bxe5 22. Bxa8 fxe3 23. Qxe3 Qc5!? (23... Bd4!? 24. Qf3 $16) 24. Qxc5 Nxc5 25. Bf3 $16) (20. Kb1!? $16 { Always play Kb1. It is a useful move whenever you castle queenside.
In this position, it is not a bad option. Look for a move that is more on-theme for this chapter instead. }) (20. h4?! $16 { Are you aware that g6 is not a hook? h5 can always be met with g5, keeping the kingside closed. }) (20. Rdf1?! $16 { A case of the incorrect rook. Clearly you are preparing f4, but why abandon the central file and trap your h1 rook in the corner in the meantime? }) 20... a4 { Black continues their plan. Have you identified the pawn break yet that black must achieve to open queenside lines? } 21. f4 { White makes first contact. e5 is an accessible hook on the kingside/center for us to bite at, and so achieving the f4 pawn break should have been a cornerstone of our strategy as soon as we entered the opposite sides castling middlegame.
exf4 is unwise due to the simple gxf4 (when white's center threatens to overrun black) and the flashy e5 Bxe5, Bxa8. Yet black need not panic: e5 is already defended, the bishop would be strong after recapturing on e5, and an open f file is perhaps not the end of the world when their king can find relative safety on g7. } (21. Kb1!? { Always play Kb1. It is a useful move whenever you castle queenside.
In this position, it is not a bad option. Look for a move that is more on-theme for this chapter instead. }) (21. a3?? { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Horrible! Not only are you playing on the wrong side of the board, but you are creating a hook for your opponent to bite at! This move doesn't prevent b4, it invites b4. } 21... b4! $15) 21... a3!? { Black follows suit with their own pawn break on the queenside. } (21... exf4? 22. gxf4!? $18 { White's center is too strong. The immediate threat of e5 is practically unstoppable. } (22. e5!? Bxe5 23. Bxa8 fxe3 24. Qxe3 $18 { All the files opened up against black's king. })) (21... b4? { The better attempt for the purposes of opening up the queenside, but white already has decisive threats. } 22. fxe5! (22. Kb1?! { This sample line shows what happens when white does not commit to the race: } 22... b3! { The correct pawn break for the purposes of opening up the queenside. The fork on a2 and c2 means either the a or b file will open. } 23. cxb3 axb3 24. a3? { This thematic way to close the queenside does not work tactically. } (24. Nxb3! $16 { Black's pieces have many open lines on the queenside. Yet the main target (a2) is not truly accessible to more than a single rook. }) 24... Bxa3!! 25. bxa3?? Qxa3 $19 { One to sac and three to mate? There is no stopping mate when white has no defenders on the queenside. }) 22... Bxe5 23. Nc4! { The open lines on the kingside spell doom for black. Black still has not created a single queenside threat. } 23... Nc5!? (23... Bd6?! 24. e5 $18) 24. Nxe5+ Qxe5 25. Qc4+ Qe6 26. Qxe6+ Nxe6 27. e5 $18 { The a8 rook and f6 knight are hanging. }) 22. b3! { Excellent job! The b2 pawn was never a hook, since a3 is always met with b3 - keeping the queenside files closed. After this simple response, both of black's rooks are now unemployed.
We can now answer the earlier pop quiz. The ultimate pawn break that black needed to achieve to open up the queenside was b3. Because b3 would have forked both the a2 and c2 pawns, there would have been no way to respond to b3 without opening at least the a or b file.
In the game, Harrwitz decided on a3, rather than b3, because achieving b3 would have taken two more moves. Before those two moves could be played, he was afraid of Morphy's kingside pawn storm breaking through. I have included a few instructive variations in the PGN showcasing the different knockouts the dueling pawn storms could have delivered to the respective kings if black pursued the b3 pawn break instead.
Finally, we should mention that b3 is now a hook for black to bite at with the c4 pawn break. Thankfully, achieving this pawn break would only be possible if we completely fell asleep at the wheel. White's pawn storm is much faster and each pawn move comes with tempo. } (22. b4!? { This also keeps the queenside files closed because Bxb4 fails to fxe5. But playing in such a style is a bit too exotic.
Play b3 instead for the game continuation. } 22... Bxb4? 23. fxe5 $18) (22. fxe5? { Perhaps you missed that axb2 comes with check? } 22... axb2+ 23. Kb1 Bxe5 $19 { Rxa2 is now a massive threat that white cannot defend against. }) (22. Kb1?! { axb2 no longer comes with check, but there is still no reason to allow black a chance to open up the queenside. } 22... axb2 23. f5 $14) 22... Kg7!? { The most adaptable move. Black safeguards their king before bad things happen to good people on the dangerous f file. } (22... exf4! { The only way to generate counterplay requires a keen tactical eye } 23. gxf4 Nxf4! { Tactically playable! } 24. Bxf4 Bxf4 25. Rxf4!? (25. e5! Bxe5 26. Kb1 $16 { Simple and strong. White opens up all the kingside files, and so has more than enough compensation for the pawn. Yet black is not lost like in the game, so this whole variation is much better than what was played. }) 25... Qe5! { The point of black's play - the fork on f4 and b2 forces white's hand: } 26. Rxf6+! Kxf6 27. Nf3! $16 { A mess is on the board, but at least black has some counterplay against white's king. }) (22... c5?! { The desirable pawn break c4 is too slow. Black simply loses the race. } 23. Nf3!? c4? 24. fxe5 cxb3 25. cxb3 Qc7+ 26. Kb1 Bxe5 27. Nxe5+ Qxe5 28. Rd5! Qc3 29. e5! $18 { White is already winning a piece before black has an attack or even any threats. }) 23. f5! { A dynamic pawn break that truly blasts open the kingside!
"Wait a second, we said earlier that g6 was not a hook!" Yes, that is technically correct. But it is important to distinguish between achieving the h5 pawn break (when black can push past with g5) and the f5 pawn break.
In this position, the g6 pawn has lost its mobility due to the fork on e6 and g6. Therefore, g6 is in fact a pseudo-hook for the f5 pawn break because black cannot respond with g5.
PRO TIP: A pawn break that is also a fork cannot be avoided. Because the pawn break hits two targets, one way or another, at least one line will open. A pawn break that is also a fork therefore achieves the same goal as a pawn break against a hook: opening lines. } (23. fxe5?! { Opens up the f file but only the f file. After Bxe5, it's unclear what newly opened lines white will be using to get to black's king on g7. Look for a more destructive way to open up the kingside instead. } 23... Bxe5 24. Nf3 Bb2+ 25. Kb1 $14) (23. c4?! { Playing on the wrong side of the board. Are you really threatening cxb5? If not, what is the point of this move? } 23... Rd8 $14) (23. Kb1!? { Always play Kb1. It is a useful move whenever you castle queenside.
In this position, it is not a bad option. Look for a move that is more on-theme for this chapter instead. }) 23... Nf8 { Now that the knight on e6 has been ousted, black can no longer ever play g5 - it just blunders the pawn for free. Therefore, g6 is now truly a hook.
Once more, we are in a position where white has achieved the correct pawn break and yet there is no direct knockout. What do you play next? } 24. g4! { The pawn storm rushes onward!
Since fxg6 hxg6 doesn't accomplish anything truly destructive on the kingside, we should prefer to keep the tension between the two pawns. Black can never release the tension by pushing (because g6 is now a hook) or capturing on f5 (which fatally exposes their king). In contrast, white's fxg6 may be truly destructive at the right moment. Yet having a pawn on f5 (or f6!) also introduces other threats that black must consider too. The immediate threat is g5 followed by f6+, a royal fork.
PRO TIP: "To take is a mistake!" Maintaining tension in a position typically favors both players. Releasing tension either trades off a more central pawn/piece for a less central one, encourages your opponent to recapture and improve a piece, or removes some of your options. You should only release tension at a moment when you have a strong follow-up or your opponent forces your hand. } (24. fxg6?! { The most crude continuation. In general, we should be looking to open lines to black's king, but releasing the tension immediately doesn't tangibly achieve anything. We want more tension on the kingside, not less! To take is a mistake! } 24... hxg6 $16) (24. Kb1!? $16 { Always play Kb1. It is a useful move whenever you castle queenside.
In this position, it is not a bad option. Look for a move that is more on-theme for this chapter instead. }) (24. Bg5!? { Atypical, but strong. By increasing the pressure on f6, we threaten fxg6 for real now. I hope you calculated a good response to h6 though!
Play g4 instead for the game continuation. } 24... h6 25. Bxf6+! Qxf6 26. fxg6 Qxg6 27. Bf3 $16 { The light squares around black's king are swiss cheese now that hxg6 was not playable. }) (24. Qf3?! $16 { There is no direct threat created by this move. We're still in a race! }) (24. Qf2?! { There is no direct threat created by this move. Moreover, what are you doing about Ng4? } 24... Ng4 25. Qf3! Nxe3?? 26. f6+ $18 { But did you really see this tactic when you played Qf2? }) (24. h4?! $16 { The h5 pawn break is still not playable due to Nxh5. So what exactly is the point of this move? }) (24. Rf2!? { Doubling on the f file in order for fxg6 to pack a big punch is a strong idea. Look for a faster knockout on the kingside instead. }) (24. Bf3!? $16 { Equally good. Play g4 first instead for the game continuation. }) 24... Qe8!? { Active defense? Qe8 avoids f6 hitting with a fork and prepares to reroute to the queenside. } { [%cal Gg2f3] } (24... c5?? { Positionally desirable - attacking the newly-create hook on b3, yet it fails tactically. } 25. g5! N6d7 26. f6+ $18) (24... Bc5?? { Positionally desirable - trading off the bad bishop for white's good bishop, yet if fails tactically. } 25. g5 N6d7 26. f6+ $18) (24... Kh8!? { Might be the safest way to avoid f6 coming with check, as it is also the most adaptable move. } 25. g5 Nh5 26. f6 Qe8 27. Bf3 $16) 25. Bf3 (25. g5!? $16 { Equally strong. Play Bf3 instead for the game continuation. }) 25... Qc6 { Black threatens Qc3, which combines well with the thorn pawn on a3 to create threats against our king.
Should we defend against black's threat or forge ahead with our own kingside assault? } 26. Nb1! { The world's most passive defense, yet totally correct!
Because black has given up on their queenside pawn storm, no lines will open towards our king. Thus, they can only attack with the a pawn and a queen. This knight move refutes that attack.
Another way to reframe things: white's single knight on b1 is holding down the fort against black's DSB, queen, and two rooks. So yes, the knight is passively defending, but what active role is any of black's major pieces playing if there is no queenside play?
Now that black's single threat is dealt with, we can continue our plan of running over black on the kingside with our remaining firepower. } (26. Qd3?! { Also defends against black's threat. Do you really want to delegate your queen to the task of defending a single square though? } 26... Rd8! { Now the queen's post is looking shaky... } 27. Nb1! $16 { As long as we find this stout defensive move, then Qd3 isn't a catastrophe - just a loss of a tempo. }) (26. c4!? { Also defends against black's threat. However, it's not smart to allow black a chance to open up the b file towards our king. } 26... bxc4 27. Nxc4 Rxb3? { Doesn't work, but why even entertain sacrifices like this? } 28. axb3 a2 29. Kb2! $18 { No threats! }) (26. Nc4?? { Oh no, your knight! } 26... bxc4 $17) (26. Qc4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 26... bxc4 $19) (26. Bc5?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 26... Qxc5 $19) (26. Bd4?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 26... exd4 27. e5 Qc3! 28. exf6+ Kh8 $19) 26... b4?! { A waste of a tempo. b4 does not contribute to any sort of attack or opening of the lines on the queenside. } { [%cal Ge2f2] } 27. Qf2?! N8d7 { Black is hoping for the cheapo of Nc5 x b3, when black's a3 pawn is unleashed.
Do not fall asleep at the wheel - we're still in a race to win on the kingside. } 28. g5 (28. Qh4!? $18 { Another fine way to attack. Play g5 instead for the game continuation. }) (28. fxg6?! $16 { This capture still doesn't meaningfully improve any of our pieces after black recaptures with hxg6. }) (28. h4?! { Tempting, but after Nc5, we still don't have a decisive kingside breakthrough. } 28... Nc5 29. Bxc5 Bxc5 30. Qe2 gxf5 31. exf5?! e4! 32. Bh1 Qa6 $10 { White has exclusively defended while black has been moving forward on the queenside and center with every move. }) (28. Bh6+?? { Tempting, with the follow-up idea of Kxh6 g5+. Unfortunately, black does not need to get greedy with Kxg5 but can instead retreat back to relative safety with Kg7. White does not achieve anything but trades. } 28... Kxh6 29. g5+ Kg7 30. gxf6+ Nxf6 $15) 28... Ng8 { Black continues running in reverse while we push them off the board. } (28... Nxe4? { Fails for several reasons. The simplest reason is: } 29. f6+ Kh8 30. Qh4 $18 { Threatening the knight on e4 and Qh6. }) (28... Nc5? { Too slow. White can already destroy black on the kingside. } 29. gxf6+ Kh8 30. fxg6 hxg6!? (30... Nxb3+?! 31. axb3 a2 32. g7+ Kg8 33. Be2! axb1=Q+ 34. Kxb1 $18 { Bc4 is a deadly mate threat. Black has opened one line to white's king, but at what cost? }) 31. Qh4+ Kg8 32. Qh6 $18 { There are too many mate threats on the kingside. Black's attack is too slow. }) 29. f6+ { Entering pure calculation mode now, Morphy decides not to directly open lines on the kingside. This strong f6 pawn both contributes to an attack and threatens to push on and become a queen. } (29. fxg6?! { A tempting capture, with the follow-up idea of Bg4 and Qf7+. Unfortunately, releasing the tension prematurely gives black more options. Rf8! is a crucial defensive move that steals the f file from us before we can land a decisive threat. } 29... hxg6 30. Bg4?! Rf8! $16) (29. Bg4!? { Also winning, but what is your response to Rf8? } 29... Rf8 30. Be2! $18 { You must spot Be2->c4->d5 if you want to make progress without the game continuation. }) (29. Be2!? $18 { The idea of Bc4->d5 is quite strong. Play f6+ instead for the game continuation. }) (29. h4!? $18 { Breaking next with h5 is a classic way to finally eliminate black's g6 pawn shelter. Play f6+ instead for the game continuation. } 29... Nc5 30. Bxc5 Bxc5 31. Qe2 gxf5 32. exf5 e4 33. Bxe4! $18 { With the knight kicked back to g8, this line finally works out for white. }) 29... Kh8 { Kf7, to blockade the pawn, was tempting. Unfortunately, it lost immediately to Be2!, when Bc4+ is a deadly threat.
Kh8 safeguards the king, but now the f6 pawn is free to continue pushing. } { [%cal Gf6f7] } (29... Kf7? 30. Be2! { Bc4+ is deadly. }) 30. f7 Nc5 { Saving the knight with Ne7 failed to Bg4, when both Bxd7 and Qf6# are decisive threats. The secret to good technique is good calculation, indeed! } (30... Ne7? 31. Bg4 Nf8?? (31... Rf8?? 32. Bxd7! Qxd7?! 33. Qf6#) 32. Qf6#) 31. fxg8=Q+ $18 { Up a knight for no compensation, Morphy went on to easily convert this game. The rest of the game is not relevant to this chapter's theme, but if you are interested in the conversion, see: https://lichess.org/rXGoEEdu .
With this win, Morphy went up 5-2, and was well on his way to winning the first-to-7 match. The next day he received a message, "Mr. Harrwitz resigns the match, on account of ill health." Repeatedly getting punched over the board will certainly do that to a man!
The dueling pawn storms allowed for many different pawn transformations throughout this game. Understanding various ways pawn tension can resolve is crucial for understanding how to open/close lines. Therefore, I have included many instructive variations in the PGN showcasing these transformations. Click "Analysis board" and flip through the annotations to view them. } (31. fxg8=R+!? $18 { Equally good. Play fxg8=Q+ instead for the game continuation. }) (31. fxg8=B!? $18 { Defends against Nxb3+ for exactly one move and is therefore good enough to still win. Play fxg8=Q+ instead for the game continuation. }) (31. fxg8=N?? { Too fancy. You forgot about black's idea of Nxb3+! } 31... Nxb3+ 32. axb3 a2 $10) 1-0


