{ In this chapter, we introduced several concepts through the lens of an opposite sides castling race. However, many of these concepts equally apply to other positions too.

Understanding pawn tension and how to open lines with a pawn storm is broadly useful. You can apply these skills to pawn breaks in the center just as much as pawn breaks on the side of the board near your opponent's king. Likewise, you can create a hook for your opponent to exploit even when both of your kings are castled on the same side of the board. Similarly, when your opponent plays on the flank, you should play in the center... regardless if your kings are castled opposite to each other.

Now let's summarize this chapter on opposite sides castling while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy.

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e6 { * Half-open files are typically advantageous for the player without the pawn. Your heavy pieces often have a purpose on a half-open file: pressuring your opponent's position. Moreover, in contrast to "open" or "fully open" files, your opponent cannot challenge your control of the file. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 2. d4 d5 { * You should think about opposite sides castling positions as a race. The first player to take over the initiative by creating decisive threats to the opponent's king typically wins. } { [%cal Ge4d5] } 3. exd5 exd5 { * In opposite sides castling middlegames, king safety is the most important imbalance in the position. Therefore, opening up lines (files, diagonals, squares) to your opponent's king is crucial. Without these avenues, your pieces cannot target their king. With these avenues, your pieces can generate threats near their king and ultimately deliver a crushing blow. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 4. Nf3 Nf6 { * Every pawn lost is a file gained! Under normal circumstances, losing a pawn is more important than gaining a file for your heavy pieces. However, when you are racing to open up lines to the opponent's king, sacrificing a pawn (or three!) can be a small price to pay. } { [%cal Gf1d3] } 5. Bd3 Be6 { * Pawn storms are a common strategy to break open lines on one side of the board. While the intermediate pawn pushes do not typically achieve anything constructive, a pawn storm's ultimate goal is a pawn break that your opponent cannot respond to by keeping the position closed. Thus, a successful pawn storm opens lines. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } 6. O-O Bd6 { * It is rarely a good idea to meet an incoming pawn storm by pushing pawns yourself. All you will end up doing is creating weaknesses, speeding up your opponent's attack, and/or losing time. Instead you should seek counterplay elsewhere, preferably in the center of the board. } { [%cal Gb1c3] } 7. Nc3 c6 { * A "hook" is a pawn near the opponent's king that can be exploited by our pawn break to open lines. An essential trait of a hook pawn is that it is restricted from advancing in response to the pawn break (thus safely avoiding the pawn tension and keeping the position closed). In particular, the opponent's fixed or advanced pawns near their king are potential hooks.
Hooks are chinks in your opponent's armor. When launching an attack at your opponent's king, exploit this immobile target with a timely pawn break to peel away the pawn shield protecting their king and open files and diagonals for your pieces. A word of warning: creating a hook in an opposite sides castling middlegame can be suicidal. If your opponent is foolish enough to do so, kindly thank them for the gift of turbo-charging your attack! } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 8. Ne5 Nbd7 { * The two main factors to consider when planning a pawn storm are center control and piece activity. Evaluating both factors will help you decide if a pawn storm will lead to a successful attack. } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 9. f4 Qb6 { * Control over the center improves the mobility of your pieces while simultaneously reducing your opponent's piece mobility. Moreover, attempting a pawn storm on the flank without a firm grip on the center allows your opponent an opportunity to overrule your flank play with their own active play in the center. } { [%cal Gc1e3] } 10. Be3?! (10. Kh1!! Qxd4 11. Nf3 Qb6 12. f5! $18) 10... Bxe5 { * Pawn storms on their own can only lead the charge in an attack (with the goal of opening lines). Active pieces must form the core of an attacking army for these newly opened lines to matter. } { [%cal Gf4e5] } 11. fxe5 Ng4! { * A pawn break that is also a fork cannot be avoided. Because the pawn break hits two targets, one way or another, at least one line will open. A pawn break that is also a fork therefore achieves the same goal as a pawn break against a hook: opening lines. } { [%cal Gd1d2] } 12. Qd2 Nxe3 { * "To take is a mistake!" Maintaining tension in a position typically favors both players. Releasing tension either trades off a more central pawn/piece for a less central one, encourages your opponent to recapture and improve a piece, or removes some of your options. You should only release tension at a moment when you have a strong follow-up or your opponent forces your hand. } { [%cal Gd2e3] } 13. Qxe3 Qxb2?! { * A queen is often the worst blockader of a passed pawn. Because she is the most valuable piece, attacking her with anything forces her to respond. Therefore, the blockade is easy to lift. } { [%cal Gc3e2] } (13... O-O! $14) 14. Ne2 Qa3 { * Mate-in-1 threats are some of the strongest forcing moves. Besides checks, where it's illegal to ignore them, threats to checkmate your opponent necessitate a response. After all, checkmate wins the game!
While playing your games, you should constantly scan the board to make sure you don't miss a mate threat for you or your opponent. They are not necessarily the best moves, but they must be calculated to ensure they don't immediately win material or the game. This is one more aspect of keeping a grip on the board. } { [%cal Ge2f4] } 15. Nf4 (15. Rab1! $14) 15... Qe7 { * A material advantage has diminishing returns. Winning a pawn is often enough to achieve a winning advantage. Winning two is certainly enough for a winning advantage. But winning more material does not make the advantage any more winning! In fact, while you spend time grabbing extra material, you are likely increasing your opponent's dynamic potential more than you are furthering your own advantage. } { [%cal Ga1b1] } 16. Rab1 O-O-O { * One piece working on its own is ineffective as an attacker or a defender. However, if you have an overwhelming number of pieces on one side of the board, an attack on that side of the board is sure to succeed. In particular, an attackers vs defenders ratio on one area of the board of more than 3:1 is reliably enough to land a fatal blow. } { [%cal Gd3e2] } 17. Be2?! (17. a4! $16) 17... Nb6 { (Please enjoy the rest of this unannotated Morphy miniature. Now that the players have castled opposite to each other, the race is on!) } { [%cal Ge3b3] } 18. Qb3 Rd7 { [%cal Gf4d3] } 19. Nd3 Nc4 { [%cal Gd3c5] } 20. Nc5 Rc7?! { [%cal Gb3a4] } (20... Nd2! 21. Qg3 Nxf1 22. Bxf1 Rc7? (22... b6 23. Ba6+ Kc7 24. Nxd7 $14) 23. Nxb7! Rxb7 24. Ba6 $18) 21. Qa4 b6?? { [%cal Ge2c4] } (21... Kb8! 22. Na6+ $16) 22. Bxc4! bxc5 { [%cal Gc4a6] } (22... dxc4!? 23. Rxb6!! axb6 24. Qa8#) 23. Ba6+ Kd7 { [%cal Ga6b7] } 24. Bb7 Rd8?? { [%cal Gb7c6] } 25. Bxc6+! $18 { The Shankland question! Black didn't actually defend against Bxc6+ because Rxc6 is refuted by Rb7+, winning the queen.
For more resources exploring opposite sides castling positions, check out:
* Dr. Can's Chess Clinic https://youtu.be/BSzyCzoWFIQ
* PowerPlayChess https://youtu.be/S--9wFOwxeI
* ChessNetwork https://youtu.be/VySMk55RYDk
* Sam Shankland's book on pawn play https://forwardchess.com/product/small-steps-to-giant-improvement } 1-0


