{ Chapter VII: The e5 lance pawn

We continue our theme of attack and defense by focusing on middlegames where white achieves a "lance" pawn, or strong e5 pawn established in black's position that cannot be easily challenged by a pawn break.

In contrast to last chapter, where the attacks were a race, lance pawn attacks can be slow and methodical. The lance pawn is a static advantage that will not easily disappear. Therefore, we may have time to optimize all of our pieces before landing the killer blow.

PRO TIP: A lance pawn often spearheads an attack on the kingside. Jousters use lances to screen their opponents in a tilt, and cavalry use lances to lead the charge in battle. Likewise, the e5 pawn prevents your opponent's pieces from reaching the defense of the kingside, while also leading the way for your pieces and pawns to join in on the action there. }
 *


[Event "Blindfold simul, 4b"]
[Site "Philadelphia, PA USA"]
[Date "1859.11.11"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Samuel Lewis"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B00"]
[Opening "Owen Defense"]
[StudyName "Morphy Simulator | Play like the legend!"]
[ChapterName "Kingside assault"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/44bSnNOe"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ After returning from his European tour in early 1859, where he dominated the best players in the world, Morphy retired from competitive chess. In fact, he even decided not to host any more exhibitions upon returning to the USA.

However, in late 1859, he made an exception for a charity event at the Academy of Music in Philadelphia and played 4 people simultaneously while blindfold. This was one of those games.

We will deeply explore how to play closed positions in Part III of this study. For now, let us content ourselves by exploring a subset of this topic. In this game, we will explain what a lance pawn is and explore how kingside attacks typically develop once a lance pawn is achieved. }
1. e4 b6 { Owen's Defense. Black fully cedes the center on move one, but plans to challenge the center with pieces and an eventual pawn break later in the game. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 2. d4 { As we well know, the opening principles tell us to develop our pieces, control the center, and get our king to safety. Therefore, when black does not prevent us from claiming the center, it is our prerogative to claim it and show them the err of their ways. } 2... Bb7 { As expected, black challenges our center from afar. Such an approach to the opening is known as "hypermodern" chess, named after the hypermodernists who came to dominate the chess scene later in the 1920s.
During Morphy's time, almost every game was played in a classical style. In contrast to hypermodernism, classical chess teaches us that the center should be occupied directly by pawns.
Neither is more correct than the other, so black's play cannot be directly refuted. However, any attempt to refute the opponent with a beautiful miniature as the Romantics loved to do requires solid control of the center. We will explore this concept deeper throughout this chapter. } 3. Bd3 { Active defense. Of course we should develop a piece while defending against black's threat. } (3. Nd2!? $14 { Equally good, even if it's a bit odd to block the DSB. Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. Nc3!? $14 { Equally good. Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. }) (3. e5?! $10 { A poor move, even though it temporarily establishes a lance pawn. We should not lose time in the opening! Importantly, this lance pawn is more of a weakness than a strength, as it can be immediately challenged with d6. } 3... d6 $10) (3. Qf3?! $10 { In no way is this the most adaptable move. You just blocked yourself from a later Nf3! }) (3. Qe2?! $10 { In no way is this the most adaptable move. You just blocked yourself developing the LSB! }) (3. Qd3?! $10 { In no way is this the most adaptable move. You just blocked yourself developing the LSB! }) (3. Qg4? { A wild queen? After Nf6, you immediately lose the e4 pawn. } 3... Nf6 $17) (3. f3?! $10 { Passive defense. It is not a good decision to lose time and weaken your king position both before and after castling just to defend e4. }) 3... e6 { Black prepares to strike at our center with d5 or c5 next. } { [%cal Gg1h3] } 4. Nh3?! { This odd developing move allows white to quickly castle without blocking the f pawn. Morphy wants to use the f pawn to better influence the center.
Unsurprisingly, voluntarily banishing your knight to the edge of the board is not best. After c5, black has enough pressure against white's center to justify their opening. } (4. Nf3 $14 { Theory shows that this is the most dependable move to fight for an advantage. }) 4... d5 { Black strikes against white's center, but now white can establish a pawn in black's position. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } (4... c5! $10) 5. e5 { With e5 on the board, Morphy establishes a lance pawn.
A "lance" pawn is a strong e5 pawn established in black's position that cannot be easily challenged by a pawn break. Typically, this means black does not have the d6 pawn break, and so the center is closed.
PRO TIP: A lance pawn often spearheads an attack on the kingside. Jousters use lances to screen their opponents in a tilt, and cavalry use lances to lead the charge in battle. Likewise, the e5 pawn prevents your opponent's pieces from reaching the defense of the kingside, while also leading the way for your pieces and pawns to join in on the action there.
If black were to establish an e4 pawn in white's position, that lance pawn would provide similar benefits for black. Moreover, in rare cases, a d5 (d4 as black) pawn planted in the opponent's half of the board could also be called a lance pawn. However, the same logic only applies if the opponent's king is on the queenside, such as in an opposite sides castling middlegame like "Off to the races" ( https://lichess.org/study/LAV8k5kM/PjcYMYAe ).
Many authors have espoused the virtues of setting up such a pawn in a position. Yet, surprisingly, I could not find anyone who formally named such a pawn. I hope you find my term "lance pawn" both evocative and memorable. } 5... Ne7 { We already see the first benefit of a lance pawn. Black's knight cannot use the f6 square, its favorite square for influencing the center while simultaneously defending the kingside. } 6. O-O { PRO TIP: A lance pawn often cuts the board in half. In particular, you now own the kingside.
Firstly, taking squares and diagonals away from your opponent's minor pieces prevents them from easily switching from the queenside to the kingside. Secondly, with the two pawn breaks d6 and f6 either impossible or too weakening, an e5 pawn ensures that the 7th rank is not open, thus impeding black's heavy pieces from performing kingside defensive duties. Finally, our pieces for the most part have easy paths towards the kingside behind the space that the lance pawn carves out.
Obviously, we still need to develop our pieces, but building up on the kingside should be top of mind. To that end, white clearly should castle kingside, when the rook can directly enter the fight after f4-f5. } (6. Be3!? $14 { Reasonable as well, although what did you have planned against Nf5? Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (6. c3!? $14 { Anticipating black's queenside play with c5 is logical, but slow. Play a more adaptable move first. }) 6... Ng6?! { A loss of a tempo. Black was better served by developing the queenside pieces with Qd7 or Ba6 (does black's LSB even qualify as developed anymore on b7?). } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 7. f4 { PRO TIP: f4 is a common follow-up to e5. Firstly, f4 supports the center in case the lance pawn is challenged with f6. Secondly, it claims more space that the rooks can use to swing over to the kingside via a rook lift. Thirdly, it prepares the f5 pawn break, which activates the heavy pieces along the f file and opens more diagonals up for the bishops. } 7... Be7 { One of many possible developing moves. However, black is in no way challenging our lance pawn or imposing center. This gives us time to plow ahead with the kingside attack. } 8. f5 { Following up with this thematic pawn break improves our LSB, h3 knight, f1 rook, and DSB simultaneously. } (8. Nc3?! $14 { The knight is often misplaced on this square because perhaps the c pawn is needed to support the center with a timely c3. }) (8. c3!? $16 { Thematic, but slow. We do not need to defend our center until black actually challenges it. While this is a good adaptable move, we can directly play for a kingside initiative instead. }) (8. Be3!? $16 { Developing a piece and supporting the center is solid. Play f5 instead for the game continuation. }) (8. Nd2?! { Where is the knight heading next? How does this play for a kingside initiative? }) 8... exf5 { Forced.
Black cannot retreat the knight and allow the f file to fully open after fxe6 fxe6. Black's king would probably die before escaping the center. } 9. Bxf5 (9. Rxf5?! $14 { A worse recapture. The rook is no better on f5 than on f1. }) 9... Bc8 { Underdeveloping, but at least black's previously horrible LSB will trade itself off for white's strong LSB. } { [%cal Gf5c8] } 10. Bxc8 { The tempo fiend move. Typically, "to take is a mistake" because the recapturing piece improves while recapturing. This is not the case in this specific position. } 10... Qxc8 { Black's queen was just demoted from d8 to c8 for two simple reasons. Firstly, she remains undeveloped on c8. Secondly, the d5 pawn has just lost its protection. } { [%cal Gb1c3] } 11. Nc3 c6?! { Black defends our threat on d5, but loses more time in the process - passive defense.
Qe6 was more accurate since the queen must be developed anyway - active defense! } (11... Qe6!? 12. Qh5 Nc6 13. Ne2 $16 { At least black forced us to make a move we didn't want to make. }) 12. Bg5 (12. Qh5!? $16 { Excellent job finding a powerful attacking move on the kingside. Play Bg5 instead for the game continuation. }) (12. Ng5!? $16 { Excellent job finding a powerful attacking move on the kingside. Play Bg5 instead for the game continuation. }) (12. Bd2?! $14 { A half-developing move that barely improves white's kingside attacking chances. Look for better. }) (12. Be3?! $14 { A half-developing move that barely improves white's kingside attacking chances. Look for better. }) (12. Qe2?! $14 { A half-developing move that barely improves white's kingside attacking chances. Look for better. }) (12. Qf3?! $14 { Developing with a threat, but you are forcing white to castle - something they want to do anyway. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! }) (12. Nf4?! $14 { The knight is better on f4, but now you blocked your DSB and rook. }) (12. Qg4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 12... Qxg4 $19) (12. Rxf7?? { Oh no, your rook! It is way too early for such a sacrifice to ever work out. What pieces do you even have to attack the king on f7 with once your rook is gone? } 12... Kxf7 13. Qf3+ Ke8 $19) (12. Bf4?! $14 { A half-developing move that barely improves white's kingside attacking chances. Moreover, this move blocks in your h3 knight and f1 rook, even temporarily. Look for better. }) (12. Ne2?! $14 { Not a terrible move, but certainly not the most adaptable move. Let's save rerouting our knight towards the kingside for after finishing development. }) 12... O-O { Black breathes a sigh of relief. At least they have castled, so their lag in development will not get punished brilliantly like the Morphy smackdowns from Chapter II.
However, they have just committed their king to the kingside. Previously, the lance pawn already dictated that we should be attacking on the kingside. Now, we have a prize at the end of that rainbow: checkmate. } 13. Bxe7 (13. Qh5!? $16 { Excellent job finding a powerful attacking move on the kingside. Play Bxe7 instead for the game continuation. }) 13... Nxe7 { Black is not pleased to constantly be recapturing pieces while retreating.
Keep up the pressure! } 14. Qh5 { Again we see a nice benefit of the lance pawn. Nf6 is never playable, so the queen's position on h5 cannot be questioned.
Our immediate threat is Ng5, hitting both h7 and f7. } (14. Ng5?! $14 { After h6, you just have to retreat. }) (14. Rf2?! $14 { Doubling on the f file. But is this the most pressing developing move for white? }) (14. Rf3?! $14 { Doubling on the f file. But is this the most pressing developing move for white? }) (14. Rf4?! { Doubling on the f file. But is this the most pressing developing move for white? }) (14. Qe2?! $14 { A half-developing move that barely improves white's kingside attacking chances. Look for better. }) (14. Qf3?! $14 { If you're getting excited about pressuring f7 with this move, don't be. The queen rarely wants to lead the charge when pressuring a pawn due to everything we previously learned when punishing a wild queen. }) (14. Ne2!? $16 { Nice job rerouting more pieces to the kingside. Play Qh5 instead for the game continuation. }) (14. Nf4?! $14 { The knight doesn't accomplish anything special on f4. What is it pressuring right now? Where is it going next? }) (14. Qd3?! { A fine developing move, but after Na6 our queen's location is already in question. Do we really want to lose time defending against Nb4? } 14... Na6! $14) 14... h6 { Black prevents Ng5, but is no closer to finishing development than they were two moves ago. White clearly has the initiative on the kingside. } { [%cal Gf1f3] } 15. Rf3 Ng6?! { Black is floundering. They again refuse to develop their queenside pieces. } (15... Qe6!? 16. Raf1 Nd7 $16 { Clearly better play from black. }) (15... Nd7? 16. Raf1 $16 { The pressure on f7 is unstoppable. }) 16. Raf1 { The Morphy move! White's heavy pieces are optimally placed.
Improving our scattered minor pieces is all that is needed in order to land a decisive blow on the kingside. } (16. Rg3!? $16 { Another strong attacking move on the kingside. First bring your last piece into the game before improving this rook. }) (16. Rd1?! $16 { In what way does this move contribute to a kingside attack? }) (16. Re1?! $16 { In what way does this move contribute to a kingside attack? }) (16. Ne2!? $16 { Bringing the knight closer to the kingside is sensible. First bring your last piece into the game before improving this knight. }) 16... Qe6 { Black finally develops a piece. Overprotecting f7 is a reasonable idea. } { [%cal Gc3e2] } 17. Ne2 { Another Morphy move! The final piece not yet contributing to the kingside attack swings over to join the fray.
After establishing the lance pawn, every single one of white's moves this game have been directed towards the kingside. With black's king situated there, Morphy is unapologetic in pursuing his goal: checkmate on the kingside. } 17... Nd7 { This position is a crystal clear demonstration of the lance pawn in action. The board is cut in half, so many of black's pieces simply cannot join in on the kingside defense. } (17... Na6?? 18. Rf6!! { A nice variation highlighting the lance pawn in action. } 18... gxf6 19. Rxf6 Qd7 20. Qxh6 $18 { There is no defense to Ng5 and e6 as follow-up attacking moves. }) 18. Nef4 { "If you say A, you must say B!" Any other move is inconsistent with our plan of improving the knight previously stuck on c3. } (18. Rg3!? $16 { A strong attacking move. Play Nef4 instead for the game continuation. }) (18. Ng3!? $16 { A strong attacking move. Play Nef4 instead for the game continuation. }) (18. Nhf4!? $16 { A strong attacking move. Play Nef4 instead for the game continuation. }) (18. g4?! $16 { The right spirit, since this continues attacking on the kingside with a mini pawn storm. However, this move is inconsistent with your last move which seeks to bring the queenside knight towards the kingside. }) (18. Rf6?? { Tempting, since this rook coordinates well with the lance pawn. Unfortunately, black's last move refutes this attacking move. } 18... Nxf6 19. Rxf6 gxf6 20. Qxh6 Qg4 $19) 18... Nxf4 { Our knight previously stuck on c3 has successfully traded herself off for one of black's only kingside defenders. } 19. Nxf4 (19. Rxf4?? { Your knight on h3 is feeling dejected after this specific recapture. Moreover, black has an opportunity to challenge the lance pawn at a moment when you have poor coordination with the timely f6 pawn break! } 19... f6! 20. exf6 { White's lance pawn cannot be maintained. } 20... Nxf6 $10 { The knight joins in the defense, and white's lance pawn is no more. }) 19... Qe7 { The lance pawn prevents black's rooks and knight from defending on the kingside. Indeed, we have four attackers to black's one defender (the queen). This ratio guarantees that we are winning in a variety of ways. } { [%cal Gf3g3] } 20. Rg3 { One of many winning moves. Black can no longer dream of queen trading with Qg5. Moreover, the threat of Qxh6 forces black's hand. } 20... Kh7 { [%cal Gf1f3] } 21. Rff3 Rg8 { Black had to defend against our threat of Rxg7+!!
Our initiative has reached epic proportions. With every move, we have improved our pieces, brought more firepower to bear on the kingside, and generated threats. Black has curled up into a ball trying to defend. } { [%cal Gf4h3] } (21... Rae8?? { A useless move to showcase white's threat: } 22. Rxg7+!! Kxg7 23. Rg3+! Kh7 24. Rh3! $18 { There is no way to prevent mate. A classic example of "one to sac and two to mate!" }) 22. Nh3 { Ng5+ and Rxf7 are both deadly threats. Black can no longer defend everything. } 22... g6!? { Black kindly asks your queen to "get out of my house!" What is the best response? } (22... Raf8?! { A visually stouter defense, but white has the simple: } 23. Ng5+! Kh8 24. Nxf7+! Rxf7 25. Rxf7 $18 { White is up material and has the compensation! }) 23. Ng5+! { Yes! There is a decisive blow on the kingside! This is a routine application of the Shankland question in action. We have way too many attackers for black to be able to boss us around.
This is also another example of an early concept we have learned: dynamics favor the side with more active pieces. With such passive pieces, black does not deserve to be able to wrestle the initiative from us. } (23. Rxf7+! { Nice tactical vision! After Qxf7, Ng5+ picks up the queen in every variation. Play Ng5+ first instead for the game continuation. } 23... Qxf7 24. Ng5+ Kg7 (24... Kh8? 25. Nxf7+ $18 { Check! }) 25. Nxf7 $18 { The g pawn is pinned, so white is just up a queen. }) (23. Qg4?? $14 { Too passive. Black does not have the right to kick us back with so many attackers generating possible threats. }) (23. Rxg6?? { Oh no, your rook! After fxg6, black's kingside defense holds strong. } 23... fxg6! $17) (23. Qxh6+?? { Oh no, your queen! This candidate move would be reasonable if you could follow-up with Nf5+. But alas, that's not how knights move. } 23... Kxh6 $19) 23... Qxg5?! { Black sacrifices their queen, desperate to end the kingside slaughter. But unfortunately the true sacrifice is black's king! } (23... Kg7!? 24. Rxf7+ Qxf7 25. Nxf7 $18) 24. Rxf7+! (24. Rxg5? { A "winning" move, since gxh5 is met with Rxf7+ and the knight on d7 ultimately falls. But why are we trading into a winning rook endgame when we have a direct win in front of us? } 24... gxh5 25. Rxf7+ Kh8 26. Rxg8+ Rxg8 27. Rxd7 $18 { Winning. But of course we should look for better than this. }) (24. Qxg5?? { After the queen trade, white has nothing. Don't mindlessly trade pieces in the middle of a blistering attack! } 24... hxg5 25. Rxf7+ Rg7! 26. Rh3+ Kg8 $19 { There is no KO. }) 24... Kh8? { The crushing blows continue.
In response to Rxd7+, Rg7 was a better defensive try. But even there, white had Rxg7+ Kxg7 and Rxg5, when white is up a queen. Black's king would not be long for the world there either. } (24... Rg7!? 25. Rxg7+! Kxg7 26. Rxg5 { The pin on the g pawn ensures that white will end up a queen. } 26... hxg5 27. Qxg5 $18) 25. Qxg5 { In the game itself, black resigned in response to this simple capture. Let's play out the finish to explain white's resignation. } 25... hxg5 { This would be the only move that doesn't resign. Anything else leaves black down a queen for nothing. } 26. Rh3# { The two rooks coordinate to provide a satisfying conclusion to the game. To make it even more satisfying, we should remember Morphy played this entire game while blindfolded!
Even in the final position, we can appreciate the strength of the lance pawn. Both d4 and e5 combine to dominate black's knight. Moreover, it is hard to imagine how black's a8 rook could ever have contributed to the defense on the kingside with no open files or ability to reach the 7th rank. } (26. Rxd7?? $18 { Yes, this is a "winning" move. But black would not be resigning if a rook endgame was the best white had... }) 1-0


