{ This next game features another lance pawn. We shall see that once the center closes, play develops on the flank.

Surprisingly, this game was played in the exact same blindfold simul as the previous game! }
1. e4 e6 { The French Defense. Black opts to stake a claim on the center on move two with d5, rather than on move one. } 2. d4 d5 { Black correctly breaks in the center, preventing white from attaining the uncontested center we achieved last game. } { [%cal Ge4d5] } 3. exd5 { The exchange French is an unambitious choice for white simply because we are forcing symmetry. Nc3, Nd2, and e5 are more popular choices in modern times to maintain richness in the position. } 3... exd5 { At the professional level, it is difficult to generate winning chances from this symmetric position. } 4. Nf3 (4. Bd3!? $10 { Equally good. Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. Nc3?! $15 { It is a bad idea to block your c pawn in d4-d5 openings. This so-called "unhappy marriage" between the knight and pawn means that you will not be able to adequately challenge black's center. After c6, black simply stands better because your knight is misplaced. }) (4. Bb5+?! $10 { Why are you walking into c6? This is a move black wants to achieve in this structure. }) (4. Bf4!? $10 { Equally good. Play Nf3 instead for the game continuation. }) 4... Be6?! { Illogical. Why is black overprotecting d5 and blocking in this bishop? There were several adaptable developing moves available instead. Regardless, this move is not outright bad, simply because the pawn structure remains symmetric and there is little dynamism in the position. } 5. Bd3 { The bishop arrives on the best diagonal.
This is certainly the most adaptable move as well, since we don't know the best squares for our queenside pieces yet. Should the knight block the c pawn or block the bishop? Should the DSB go to f4 or g5? It's still unclear. } (5. Bb5+?! $10 { Why are you walking into c6? This is a move black wants to achieve in this structure. }) (5. Nc3?! $10 { It is a bad idea to block your c pawn in d4-d5 openings. This so-called "unhappy marriage" between the knight and pawn means that you will not be able to adequately challenge black's center. After c6, black simply stands better because your knight is misplaced. }) (5. Bf4!? $10 { Equally good. Play Bd3 instead for the game continuation. }) (5. Be3?! $10 { Why would you commit the exact same mistake your opponent just made? The bishop is simply misplaced staring at the d pawn. }) (5. Be2?! $10 { A half-developing move, especially since we should not be worried about our knight getting pinned due to black's last move. A rook would rather use the e file. }) 5... Nf6 { Finally, black plays a sensible developing move. } 6. O-O (6. Bg5?! $10 { Possible. But after h6, what is your follow-up? The pin can easily be broken if we try Bh4. The insertion of h6 is useful for black if we retreat along the c1-h6 diagonal. Do we really want to take the knight and develop black's queen?
There is a more adaptable developing move instead. }) 6... h6?! { Black wastes time, unnecessarily worried about a pin kicking off with Bg5. That pin is overrated simply because black can easily break the pin with Be7 or Nbd7. Meanwhile, white has no way to pile up more pressure on the f6 knight.
Opening principles 101: black should have developed a piece instead. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } 7. Ne5?! { Seeking to take advantage of black's lag in development, Morphy jumps to the center and prepares to run the f pawn down the board.
Simple development with Re1 was stronger. } 7... Bd6 { Developing and challenging white's strong knight is best. } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 8. f4 Nc6 { Black challenges our strong knight and the d4 pawn again.
Should we capture on c6 or defend our d4 pawn? } 9. c3 { Correct! The doubled c pawns for black after Nxc6 bxc6 would be a strength, not a weakness. Both c pawns contribute to the fight for the center; indeed black would be ready to play the c5 pawn break twice - tearing down our center for good. } (9. Nxc6?! { Incorrect! Doubled pawns are irrelevant - you are simply building up black's center! } 9... bxc6 $10) (9. Be3!? $14 { Correct! Play c3 instead for the game continuation. }) 9... Qe7?! { Obviously, black should have castled kingside, after which we would have a mostly equal game.
In no world is Qe7 the most adaptable move. Black is tempting fate by not castling as well as aligning the king and queen on the same file. As we know, alignments create threats. } 10. Re1! { Alignments create threats! The immediate threat is Nxc6 bxc6, f5! winning a piece. } (10. Nxc6! $14 { Yes! Now this move is strong because after bxc6, f5! black faces difficulties on the e file. Play Re1 first instead for the game continuation. }) (10. Qb3! { Also good, but not for alignment reasons. There simply is no good way to defend b7! Play Re1 instead for the game continuation. } 10... Bd7!? (10... Rb8?? 11. Nxc6! $18 { [%cal Gb3b8] }) (10... Bc8?! 11. Qc2 $14 { Black is losing time left and right. }) 11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Nxc6! Rxb7 13. Nxe7 Bxe7 14. Re1 $14 { Up a pawn. }) 10... Bxe5?! { The pressure down the e file is too scary, so black blinks. Black did not want to capture on e5 with the bishop, but at least this move prevents white's threat. } (10... Ne4! $14 { Preventing white's threat while improving the knight, even at the cost of a pawn. Talk about active defense! }) 11. fxe5! { The lance pawn is achieved. } (11. dxe5? { A bad way to recapture, loosening our grip on the center. After Ng4, black is already threatening Qc5+ with decisive threats to our king. In general, we should recapture towards the center, especially if we are achieving a lance pawn. } 11... Ng4! 12. Qe2 Qc5+ 13. Be3 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 15. Rxe3 g6 $15 { There is no attack for white. }) (11. Rxe5?? { Oh no, your rook! This recapture loses the exchange for no reason. } 11... Nxe5 12. fxe5 Ne4 $17) 11... Nd7 { White's center is quite stable because black does not have any effective pawn breaks that can tear it down.
PRO TIP: When the center is closed and stable, play naturally occurs on the wings, or "flanks," of the board. However, premature flank play often backfires if your opponent can counterattack in the center. Strong central play can punish flank play by showing it to be at best a loss of time or at worst actively weakening.
In this position, the center is closed, and so both sides should be looking to the play on the flanks. We know that our lance pawn encourages kingside play. Meanwhile, our main concern is black achieving the c5 pawn break, chipping away at our center and initiating queenside play. If our center falls apart before we make decisive inroads on the kingside, any kingside maneuvering could simply be wasted.
Play b4 for the game continuation. } 12. b4!! { "What? Aren't we supposed to play on the kingside? Aren't we supposed to be developing rapidly?"
Yes, all of the above is true. Yet nothing beats a good move!
Firstly, this move concretely "prevents" black from castling kingside. Therefore, it is in fact related to kingside operations. Secondly, in the event that black castles queenside, we have already begun a queenside pawn storm, kick-starting the race we have seen in Chapter VI.
Overall, this multipurpose move on the flanks is not just reasonable, but concretely quite strong. } 12... O-O? { A clear mistake.
We just mentioned how white's last move "prevented" black from castling kingside. Now it is your turn to find the refutation! } 13. b5! (13. Qh5!? { The immediate threat of Bxh6, crashing through to black's king, is deadly. Black must respond with f5, after which black has created a lot of kingside weaknesses.
Play b5 instead for the game continuation. } 13... f5 14. b5 Na5 15. Ba3 Qf7 16. Qxf7+ Rxf7 $16) (13. Ba3?! { The right idea, but the wrong execution. b5 loses most of its sting after Qg5, when black escapes the alignment issues. } 13... Qg5! 14. b5 Ne7 $16 { There is no knockout, so white must continue developing next. }) 13... Na5 { Black's knight gets pushed away from the center. But what is the point of our last move? } 14. Ba3! { Excellent job. White wins the exchange in every variation. } 14... Qg5 { One of many possible queen moves. All of them lose the exchange. } (14... c5?? 15. bxc6 $18 { En passant prevents black from being able to shut down the diagonal. }) 15. Bxf8 Rxf8 { After that tactical flurry, the dust has now settled. White is up a clear exchange, but the end of this game is nowhere in sight.
Back to basics. White still has undeveloped pieces. White still maintains a lance pawn. Putting these together, what should we play? } 16. Nd2 { The knight clearly needs to head towards the kingside in all lines to emphasize the strength of the lance pawn. Therefore, this logical developing move is also the most adaptable move. In contrast, the exact route and move order for our major pieces to generate kingside play remain less obvious. } (16. Qc2!? $16 { Developing, while inching closer to the kingside. Excellent job. Play Nd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. Qe2!? $16 { Developing, while inching closer to the kingside. Excellent job. Play Nd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. Qf3!? $16 { Developing, while inching closer to the kingside. Excellent job. Play Nd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. Qd2!? $16 { Developing, while inching closer to the kingside. Excellent job. Play Nd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (16. Na3?! $16 { You're playing on the wrong side of the board! The pieces should be heading towards the kingside to build up play on the side of the board our lance pawn points to. }) (16. Qa4?! $16 { You're playing on the wrong side of the board! The pieces should be heading towards the kingside to build up play on the side of the board our lance pawn points to. }) (16. Rf1?! $16 { The rook is better on f1, but this is not the most adaptable move. Your queenside pieces should be developed first before you consider improving the rook! }) 16... Bg4?! { A one-move threat that is easily parried. Black should be playing on the queenside with the c6 or c5 pawn break instead. } { [%cal Gd2f3] } 17. Nf3 Qe7 { PRO TIP: Possessing a lance pawn is a static advantage. The benefits of the lance pawn that we have discussed so far are lasting and do not depend on the move-by-move details of the position. } { [%cal Gh2h3] } (17... Bxf3?! 18. Qxf3 $16) 18. h3 Be6 { We have only improved our position in the last few moves, while black has only retreated. Thus, we have the initiative. It should now be clear that we are better both statically and dynamically. } { [%cal Gd1a4] } 19. Qa4 { Developing with a threat. This queen is temporarily not coordinated with the other kingside pieces, but Morphy soon remedies this. } 19... b6?! { Passive defense. Nc4, bringing the knight towards the center, was clearly better.
Black surely rejected Nc4 because they were afraid of losing a7. Yet this wild queen strategy would be wholly inconsistent with the kingside attack spearheaded by our lance pawn. After Nc4, Qxa7? Ndb6! black's pieces are all coordinating with tempo, and our queen is possibly trapped. All for a measly pawn? Morphy would never be so greedy. } { [%cal Ga1d1] } (19... Nc4! 20. Qxa7? Ndb6! { White's queen is offsides. The threat of Ra8 and Na5 to trap the queen is a big problem. Black has completely taken over the initiative. } 21. Qxb7?? (21. Bxc4! dxc4 22. Qa5 Nd5 $14) 21... Na5) 20. Rad1 { To this point in the game, Morphy has largely focused on solidifying the center. He has certainly not overcommitted to a flank attack. The logic was explored in our last PRO TIP: while black could tear down our center with either the c5 or f6 pawn break, any flank attack is premature. } 20... g5? { "You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move!"
This horrible move weakens the black king. Moreover, it's also a move on the wrong side of the board; our lance pawn ensures that the kingside is our territory! Even worse, this weakening move sabotages their own central play; the pawn break f6 is now suicidal, rather than effective.
Black deserves to be punished for such a chess crime. It is up to us to deliver them to justice.
The winds have now shifted. The opponent can no longer counterattack our center with either c5 or f6, so we have a free hand to fully commit our forces to a flank attack. The lance pawn leads the charge!
What is the best way to kick off our kingside assault in earnest? } 21. Bb1!? { A beautiful attacking move. Do you see Morphy's idea behind this move? } (21. Rf1!? $16 { A great way to start the attack, activating the rook on the semi-open f file. Play Bb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (21. Qc2?! $16 { The wrong battery. Bh7+ isn't a serious threat. Qh7# on the other hand would be... }) (21. Rd2!? $16 { A great way to start the attack, lifting the rook to f2 to activate on the semi-open f file. Play Bb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (21. Re2!? $16 { A great way to start the attack, since the other rook will activate on f1 on the semi-open f file. Play Bb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (21. Qb4?! $16 { Do we really want to trade queens just before launching a kingside attack? }) (21. Nh2!? $16 { Not the most adaptable way to kick off a kingside attack. But yes the knight can reroute into the position via this square. Play Bb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (21. Nd2!? $16 { Not the most adaptable way to kick off a kingside attack. But yes the knight can reroute into the position via this square. Play Bb1 instead for the game continuation. }) (21. c4? { Actively harmful. We are only improving black's pieces while not truly breaking down black's center. You are playing on the wrong side of the board! } 21... Nxc4 $16) 21... Kg7 { What was the point behind our last move? } 22. Qc2 { Exactly! The queen+bishop battery in this arrangement creates genuine threats on the kingside. Starting with Qc2 before playing Bb1 would not have created any threats.
There were many fine moves for white, yet this is the most human continuation. "If you say A, you must say B!" } 22... Rh8 { Black defends the mate-in-1 threat.
This position is a crystal clear demonstration of the strength of the lance pawn. Convenient defensive moves like Nf6 or f5 are impossible. Moreover, white's strong center cuts off black's queenside pieces from joining the defense. } { [%cal Gf3d2] } (22... f5? 23. exf6+ Nxf6 24. Qg6+ Kh8 25. Qxh6+ Qh7!? (25... Nh7!? 26. Rxe6 $18) (25... Kg8!? 26. Nxg5 $18) 26. Qxf8+ $18) (22... Nf6?? 23. exf6+ $18) 23. Nd2 { Morphy identifies that the knight on f3 is not truly a kingside attacker. Therefore, the goal is to either convert her into an attacker or trade her off for one of black's key defenders. In either case, we increase the attackers vs defenders ratio. A step in that direction is rerouting this knight to her optimal square. } 23... h5 { Black insists on playing on the wrong side of the board.
Continue the maneuver started by our last move! } 24. Nf1 (24. Nb3?! { A step in the wrong direction. How does this knight on b3 contribute to a kingside attack? } 24... Nc4 $16) 24... h4 { Further play on the wrong side of the board.
Continue the maneuver! } 25. Ne3 (25. Nh2!? $16 { Heading to g4, now that black has unnecessarily pushed the kingside pawns is reasonable. However, when Morphy started the knight maneuver, he had a different destination than g4 in mind. }) 25... Rh6 { The rook defends laterally now along the 6th rank. Regardless, black's pieces are uncoordinated in either defense or attack. } 26. Nf5+ { After a long maneuver, our knight lands on f5 with a family fork.
PRO TIP: Knife f5! A white knight landing on f5 was Kasparov's favorite attacking piece against a castled king. In particular, she threatens several checks against a king on g8, directly hits a king on g7, and coordinates well with other attacking pieces on the sensitive e7, g7, and h6 squares all around the king. Black's knife f4 is equally deadly. } (26. Ng4?! $16 { Not the optimal square. On g4, she only hits the rook on h6. On f5, she lands with a family fork. }) 26... Bxf5 { Of course, the knight on f5 was intolerable. } 27. Qxf5 { Our queen inches closer to the king. Pressure on g5 ensures that our queen cannot be challenged. Therefore, we have more time to continue building the kingside attack. } 27... Nf8 { The knight on d7 has been dominated by white's center (in particular, our lance pawn!) for the entire game. Finally, black takes steps to bring her into the action. The same cannot be said about the poor knight marooned on a5.
Keep up the initiative! } (27... Qe6? 28. Qxg5+ $18) 28. Rf1 (28. Rd3!? $18 { A good move, preparing Rf3 and activating the dormant d1 rook. Play Rf1 instead for the continuation. }) (28. Rd2!? $18 { A fine move, preparing Rf2 and activating the dormant d1 rook. Play Rf1 instead for the continuation. }) (28. Re3!? $18 { A good move, preparing Rf3 and activating the dormant e1 rook. Play Rf1 instead for the continuation. }) (28. Re2!? $18 { A good move, preparing Rf2 and activating the dormant e1 rook. Play Rf1 instead for the continuation. }) (28. Bd3!? $18 { Preventing black's knight from even reaching c4 is cruel but effective. Improve your rooks first for the game continuation. }) 28... Nc4 { Black brings the sidelined knight into the game with tempo. Yet there are many ways to prevent Ne3. } 29. Rf3! { Active defense! Not only does this move prevent Ne3, but it involves more pieces in the kingside attack. } (29. Rd3!? $18 { Great job preventing Ne3 while improving your rook. Active defense! Play Rf3 instead for the game continuation. }) (29. Rde1?! $18 { Unnecessarily slow. You are losing a tempo on the game. }) 29... Ne6 { Black has improved their knights from the sidelined d7 and a5 squares. But it's too little too late. A common refrain when analyzing Morphy games... } { [%cal Gf5g4] } 30. Qg4 (30. Rdf1!? Nd2! 31. Qxf7+ Qxf7 32. Rxf7+ Kg8 33. R7f6!? (33. Rd7!? Nxf1 34. Kxf1 $18) 33... Rxf6 34. Rxf6 Nxb1 35. Rxe6 Nxc3 $18) 30... Qe8 { Black makes a petty threat against the b5 pawn. Yet what else should they play? Black can hardly move a muscle. The lance pawn continues to restrict any active possibilities, as it has for nearly the entire game. } 31. Rdf1 { The Morphy move! The last piece enters the attack with a threat. There is no way to defend f7 because Nd8 or Nf4 drop g5 with check.
Finally, Morphy delivers justice for black's earlier crimes. } 31... Qxb5?? { Frankly, ridiculous. The b pawn is irrelevant. Given the amount of firepower Morphy has built up on the kingside, such a greedy capture must be directly refuted.
The naive attackers vs defenders ratio is 4 to 2, which might not be immediately decisive. Yet if you look at the actual pieces attacking, white is up a queen and rook in the attack. Additionally, the lance pawn, controlling d6 and f6, is practically worth another piece in the attack.
With so much attacking power, white must have a winning shot. } (31... Nd2!? 32. Rxf7+ Qxf7 33. Rxf7+ Kxf7 34. Bf5 $18) (31... Nd8?? 32. Qxg5+ $18) (31... Nf4?? 32. Qxg5+ $18) 32. Rxf7+! Kh8 { Keep up the attack! Black's king is so vulnerable that there must be a KO. } 33. Qxe6!! { Excellent job! This beautiful queen sac forces checkmate. Morphy's opponent in this blindfold simul is gracious enough to allow the finish. } (33. R7f6! { Not the most forcing move, but certainly a winning continuation. The key to this continuation is that Rxf6 is met with Qh5+ when all of white's pieces coordinate in a mating attack. Play the more aesthetic Qxe6!! instead for the game continuation. } 33... Rxf6 34. Qh5+ Kg8!? (34... Kg7!? 35. Qh7+ Kf8 $18) 35. Qh7+ Kf8 36. Rxf6+ Ke8 37. Qg8+ Kd7 38. Rf7+ Kc6 39. Qa8#) (33. Qf5!? $18 { Nicely done. There is no defense to the threats of Rf8+ or Rh7+. This simple win is not nearly as aesthetic as the game continuation Qxe6!! } 33... Qe8 34. Rh7+! Kg8 (34... Rxh7?! 35. Qxh7#) 35. Rxh6 $18) (33. Qxg5?? { Oh no, your queen! From g5, black's knight defends the crucial f7 square. There is no mate. } 33... Nxg5 34. Rf8+ Kg7 35. R1f7+? Nxf7! $19) 33... Rxe6 { With this position on the board, we should be able to see the finish. The true difficulty lay in setting ourselves up with that queen sacrifice. } 34. Rf8+ (34. Rh7+?? $10 { After Kg8, there is no follow-up. }) 34... Kg7 { Forced. } 35. R1f7+ (35. R8f7+?! $18 { No progress. You are just repeating the position after Kh8. }) 35... Kh6 { Forced. } 36. Rh7# { It is fitting that the lance pawn led to two vicious kingside attacks in both games of this same blindfold simul.
As in the previous game, the final position showcases the strength of the lance pawn. None of black's pieces influence the kingside. Black's rook can nominally see the kingside but is irrelevant in the defense.
The strength of Morphy's center allowed him the time to optimize his pieces and build up for a kingside attack. Time was relevant, but not crucial, as it has been in other games throughout this study. Indeed, he had time to maneuver the knight to f5 and triple the heavy pieces on the f file. After g5?, Morphy slowly but surely brought justice against his opponent. } (36. Rh8# { Also mate. Play Rh7# instead for the game continuation. }) 1-0


