{ We return to the famous match between Morphy and Anderssen, one of the first unofficial world championships. At this point in the match, Morphy was convincingly leading with a score of 6 wins to 2 losses. }
1. e4 e6 { Anderssen gave up on playing solid openings after getting trounced on both sides of 1. e4 e5. We already played through a game where he essayed the Scandinavian defense. Now, he throws down the French? } 2. d4 { As before, when black does not prevent us from claiming the center, it is our prerogative to claim it and show them the err of their ways. } 2... g6?! { Anderssen feints going for the French and instead chooses to mix it up again.
However, this move is a clear waste of time. The bishop was already able to develop along the f8-a3 diagonal. Why is black spending another tempo to now develop it to g7? } { [%cal Gf1d3] } 3. Bd3 Bg7 { PRO TIP: Developing a bishop to g7 (or g2) nestled within the pawn shell of f7+g6+h7 (or f2+g3+h2) is a common way to safeguard the king and attack the center from afar. Black's bishop controls the dark squares, while black's pawns control the light squares. This constellation is known as a "kingside fianchetto," and is a hallmark of hypermodern play.
Morphy, ever the classical player, never once fianchetto'd any of his bishops across all of his recorded games. He much preferred dominating the center with pawns and developing his bishops behind it, thus preempting any challenges to his center.
Our d pawn is attacked. What is the best way to continue? } { [%csl Rg7,Bf7,Bg6,Bh7] } 4. Be3 (4. Nf3!? $14 { Equally strong. Play Be3 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. c3!? $14 { Equally strong. Play Be3 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. Ne2!? $14 { Equally strong. Play Be3 instead for the game continuation. }) (4. Bb5?! $14 { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. }) (4. Bc4?! { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. } 4... d5! $15) (4. Be2?! $10 { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. }) (4. Bf1? $10 { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. }) (4. e5?! { Too early. This pawn can be challenged with d6 at a time when our center can easily be undermined. The lance pawn should only be established if it is a strength, not a weakness! } 4... d6! 5. f4 c5 6. c3 Nc6 $10) 4... c5 { Black takes advantage of the downside of our last move. With b2 undefended, this pawn break is tactically playable. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 5. c3 (5. dxc5! { The Shankland question! "Yes, b2 is hanging, but what if I capture this pawn anyway?" In fact, the complications favor white! } 5... Bxb2 6. Nd2! Bxa1?! (6... Ne7!? 7. Rb1 $16) 7. Qxa1 { Black's only developed piece has been traded off for a rook that never moved. White is up 4 tempi for the exchange and has more than enough compensation. } 7... f6 (7... Qf6? 8. Bd4 $18) 8. Nc4 $16 { White has a massive lead in development and can already think about the DDD moment. }) 5... cxd4 { Black follows through with their play against our center. } 6. cxd4 (6. Bxd4?! { This is chess, not checkers. Black is not forced to capture on d4 a second time, gifting you a strong center. After Nf6, white's advantage is minimal. } 6... Nf6 $10) 6... Nc6 { Developing with a threat. Black piles up more pressure against our center in true hypermodern style. } 7. Ne2 { Active defense - developing and defending.
With Ne2, Morphy is anticipating achieving a lance pawn, after which it should be supported with f4 as he has in previous games. } (7. Nf3! $14 { Active defense in the most adaptable manner. This is even stronger than Morphy's choice! Play Ne2 instead for the game continuation. }) (7. d5? { Tempting. But after Bxb2, we are losing an exchange for little compensation. } 7... Bxb2 8. Nd2 Nb4! $17) (7. Bb5?! { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. } 7... Qb6! $15) (7. Bc2?! { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. } 7... d5 $10) (7. Be2?! { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. } 7... d5 $10) (7. Bc4?! { Passive defense. We should be looking to develop and defend d4 instead. } 7... d5 $10) (7. Qa4?! { This is certainly not the most adaptable way to defend d4. } 7... d5! $15) (7. e5?! { Too early. This pawn can be challenged with d6 at a time when our center can easily be undermined. The lance pawn should only be established if it is a strength, not a weakness! } 7... d6! $10) 7... Nge7 8. O-O (8. Nbc3!? $14 { Equally good. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (8. Qd2!? $14 { Equally good. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (8. e5? { Too early. This pawn can be challenged with d6 at a time when our center can easily be undermined. The lance pawn should only be established if it is a strength, not a weakness! } 8... d6! $15) (8. Nd2!? $14 { Equally good. Play O-O instead for the game continuation. }) (8. d5? { Oh no, your d pawn! } 8... exd5 9. exd5 Nxd5 $17) 8... O-O 9. Nbc3 (9. Qd2!? $14 { Equally good. Play Nbc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. a3!? $14 { A high-level prophylaxis against Nb4 is good too. Play Nbc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. Nd2!? $14 { Equally good. Play Nbc3 instead for the game continuation. }) (9. e5? { Too early. This pawn can be challenged with d6 at a time when our center can easily be undermined. The lance pawn should only be established if it is a strength, not a weakness! } 9... d6! 10. f4 Nd5 11. Bf2 f6! $15) (9. Qc2?! $15 { A suboptimal square due to Nb4, snagging your LSB. }) (9. Qb3?! $10 { Not the most adaptable move. }) (9. Qa4?! $15 { Not the most adaptable move. }) 9... d5 { Finally (and correctly!), black challenges our center. Without this pawn break, all of black's queenside pieces remain unemployed. } 10. e5 { The e pawn crosses the demarcation line, and Morphy establishes a lance pawn. The board is now cut in half, in such a way that we should play on the kingside.
Importantly, this pawn thrust is only effective after black has played d5. With f6 the only remaining pawn break against our imposing center, white will be able to maintain the lance pawn in every variation. Our center is stable. } (10. exd5?! { This capture sells our position short. After exd5, all you have done is trade our central e4 pawn for black's e6 pawn, thus equalizing the center and developing black's LSB for them. } 10... exd5 $10 (10... Nxd5!? $15 { An IQP where there is pressure against d4 is playable too. })) 10... f6!? { Playing on the wrong side of the board, but the center must be challenged if black doesn't want to get run over like Morphy's previous opponents. } 11. f4 { Supporting the lance pawn is of course our best option. If black successfully breaks down our center, any flank play is irrelevant.
PRO TIP: The main benefit of a stable center (potentially headed by a lance pawn!) is to contain your opponent's pieces. Once contained, they cannot easily create threats in your position, giving you time to build up a kingside attack.
This explanation goes hand in hand with the concept that a lance pawn often spearheads an attack on the kingside. } (11. exf6?! $10 { "To take is a mistake!" Giving up our lance pawn so easily is not ideal. Firstly, this move frees up black's pieces. Secondly, we have lost time with e5 and then exf6. }) (11. Bf4? $17 { This move doesn't even defend our lance pawn. Black has three attackers, while we only have two. You must keep a better grip on the board! }) 11... fxe5 { Again, black follows through with their play against our center. } (11... g5?! 12. exf6! Rxf6 (12... gxf4?? 13. fxe7! $18) 13. fxg5 Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 $16 { Up a pawn for no compensation. White still has the makings of a kingside attack, lance pawn or not. }) 12. fxe5 { The lance pawn is secured for good. White's center is more of an asset (shutting down black's DSB, LSB, and c6 knight) than a liability (to be feasted upon by black's pieces from afar).
Therefore, this position is a triumph for white's classical play over black's hypermodernist approach. } (12. dxe5?? { Recapturing on e5 with the d pawn is typically a poor choice for two reasons. You are weakening your control over the center. You are also shutting down several open lines you need on the kingside. For instance, your e2 knight, DSB, and f1 rook are all upset by this recapture.
In this position however, dxe5 is simply a blunder. After d4, we are directly losing a piece. } 12... d4 $19) 12... a6?! { A clear loss of tempo, and thus a sign that things have gone wrong. This move in no way controls the center, develops a piece, or gets the king to safety. } (12... Rxf1+! { A nice capture to include at a moment when white cannot recapture with the other rook. } 13. Qxf1 Bd7 14. Rc1!? Qf8 15. Qd1 $16 { The game goes on. White's attack is still far off from crashing through. }) 13. Qd2 (13. Rxf8+!? { A nice time to trade rooks while there is a disconnect in black's back rank. We can next play Qd2 and Rf1 to claim the only open file. Play Qd2 first instead for the game continuation. } 13... Qxf8 14. Qd2 $16 { Rf1 is coming next. }) (13. Qb3!? $16 { The queen does not yet coordinate with the pieces on the kingside, but next we can bring our a1 rook into the game before returning to d1 with the queen. This slow burn move should work out. Play Qd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Qc2?! { You're allowing black a chance to trade pieces with Nb4! We don't want to allow such a trade for nothing. } 13... Nb4 14. Qd2 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 $10) (13. Qa4?! { After Bd7, you are just asking for trouble. Alignments create threats! } 13... Bd7 14. Rxf8+! Qxf8 15. Rf1 Qd8 16. Qb3 $14) (13. Nf4?! { Loosening the center before we are fully coordinated is not smart. You just allowed black a nice tactic with Nxe5! dxe5 d4! with a fork.
This is yet another example of alignments creating threats. Unfortunately, this time it is our two minor pieces on e3 and c3 that are aligned. } 13... Nxe5! 14. dxe5 d4 $10) (13. Rc1!? $16 { Developing the rook to the open c file is quite principled, even if it is not technically the most accurate option. Play Qd2 instead for the game continuation. }) (13. Kh1?! { Passive defense. The king is in general safer on h1 now that you have moved the f pawn... but what black piece is going to hurt us along the a7-g1 diagonal? None.
Don't waste time defending against fake threats when you can be playing principled moves instead. } 13... Rxf1+ 14. Qxf1 Bd7 15. Qd1 Qc7 16. Qd2 Rf8 $14 { Black finishes development before us. }) 13... Nb4 { Black jumps forward with their knight at a time when we cannot conveniently save our LSB. } { [%cal Ge3g5] } 14. Bg5 { The tempo fiend move. Rather than sweat the knight for bishop trade, Morphy hurries to actualize the kingside attack instead. } (14. Rxf8+! { The best move actually! Now Bb1 followed by a3 preserves our bishops. } 14... Bxf8!? (14... Qxf8?! 15. Rf1 Qe8 16. Bb1 $16) 15. Bb1! $16 { a3 is coming, and so black's knight on b4 will simply lose a tempo. }) (14. Bb1?! { Rxf1+ at a time when our rooks are disconnected is annoying. } 14... Rxf1+! 15. Kxf1 Bd7 16. Kg1 Qc7 17. a3 Nbc6 18. Bd3 Rf8 $14) 14... Nxd3 { With relief, black snags the LSB while they can. } 15. Qxd3 Bd7 { This is another prime example of the strength of the lance pawn.
Our center clearly takes away diagonals from both of black's bishops. The DSB's sole purpose is defending, since the "pressure" on e5 is irrelevant while the d4 pawn is around; this bishop is merely "biting on granite" as GM Daniel Naroditsky used to say. Meanwhile, the LSB serves no role and indeed would love nothing more than to trade itself off for any of white's potential attackers. } { [%cal Gd3h3] } 16. Qh3 Qe8 { Black's queen escapes our pin, but black is clearly struggling to improve the pieces. } { [%cal Ge2g3] } 17. Ng3 { Meanwhile, our pieces are inching closer towards the kingside. Black's pieces have been restricted by our center this whole time, but also now must tend to potential killer shots against black's king. } 17... Rc8 { Black claims the c file, but what good is it while our knight stays on c3?
Every white piece is better than their black counterpart except for our rook on a1. } 18. Rxf8+! (18. Qh4!? $16 { A completely different plan that is also strong. After Qh4, white's pieces better coordinate on the kingside squares. Play Rxf8+ instead for the game continuation. }) (18. Rae1!? $16 { A perfectly fine move, yet the rook is not accomplishing anything killer on e1. Find a two-move plan instead that places this rook on the best square. }) (18. Rad1!? $16 { A perfectly fine move, yet the rook is not accomplishing anything killer on d1. Find a two-move plan instead that places this rook on the best square. }) (18. Rac1!? $16 { A perfectly fine move, yet the rook is not accomplishing anything killer on c1. Find a two-move plan instead that places this rook on the best square. }) (18. Rf2? $15 { Black can now rook trade at a moment when our a1 rook cannot recapture! }) (18. Rf3? $15 { Black can now rook trade at a moment when our a1 rook cannot recapture! }) (18. Rf4?! $10 { Black can now rook trade at a moment when our a1 rook cannot recapture! }) (18. Rf6? { Oh no your rook. There is not enough compensation for this exchange sacrifice. } 18... Bxf6 19. exf6 Nc6 $15) 18... Qxf8 { Yes, we traded rooks. How does that improve our position? } 19. Rf1! { Exactly! By trading rooks at a moment when black could not recapture with their rook, we are able to bring our last piece into the action with tempo. } 19... Qe8 { With our last two moves, we essentially traded white's a1 rook (a useless attacker) for black's f8 rook (a useful defender). White now has an attackers vs defenders ratio of 4 to 3 on the kingside. If we include the lance pawn as an attacking piece, it's clear that storm clouds are gathering...
Even in a closed position, Morphy has begun dictating play, thus seizing the initiative. } 20. Qh4 (20. Nh5?? { Oh no, your knight! This is a bit too crazy, especially when capturing it doesn't weaken any squares that we can next utilize. } 20... gxh5 $19) (20. Nf5?? { Oh no, your knight! This is a bit too crazy, especially when it can directly be captured by the knight, meaning black does not have to take on any weaknesses. } 20... Nxf5 $19) (20. Bxe7? $15 { "To take is a mistake!" Why are you trading your best attacking piece for black's passive knight? We want to increase the tension, not resolve it! }) (20. Nce4?? { Oh no, your knight! This is a bit too crazy, especially since our attackers vs defenders ratio doesn't improve after they take this free piece. } 20... dxe4 21. Nxe4 Nf5! $17) (20. Nxd5?? { This is a bit too crazy, especially since our attackers vs defenders ratio doesn't improve after they take this free piece. } 20... exd5 21. e6!? Bb5 22. Rf7 Qc6! $19) 20... Nf5 { Black's knight was attacked. Since there was no convenient way to defend it, black decided that clogging the f file was as good a response as any to white's threat. } (20... Nc6!? 21. Rf3 $16 { The attackers vs defenders ratio is now 4(+1) to 2... }) 21. Nxf5 (21. Qh3? { Keep up the initiative! We did not play Qh4 just to have to move her again immediately afterwards. } 21... Nxd4 $17) (21. Qg4?! { Keep up the initiative! We did not play Qh4 just to have to move her again immediately afterwards. } 21... h6 $10) (21. Qf4?! $16 { Keep up the initiative! We did not play Qh4 just to have to move her again immediately afterwards. }) (21. Rxf5? { Not the craziest exchange sacrifice, but we should first have more attackers on the kingside before pulling the trigger on such a sacrifice. } 21... gxf5 22. Nh5 Qf7 23. h3 $10) 21... gxf5 { A sad necessity. exf5 kept the king safer, but lost a crucial pawn to Nxd5!
Black reasons that, after gxf5, at least the f file is closed. White's rook is no longer controlling key squares around black's king. } (21... exf5? 22. Nxd5! $18) 22. Rf3! { Nicely done keeping up the initiative. This rook lift brings the final heavy piece back into the attack. The f file may be closed, but the g and h files sure aren't!
As we have repeatedly seen, a hallmark of Morphy's play is that he attacks with all of the pieces, not just some of them. } (22. g4? { A tempting move to bring the rook back into the action. However, exactly what decisive follow-up do you have after fxg4? } 22... fxg4 $10) (22. Rf4?! $16 { A slower version of the game. On f4, the rook does not have as many next squares to swing to. }) (22. Ne2? { Jumping the knight into the game via f4 is thematic, but incorrect. After Bb5! black is just in time to trade off their horrible LSB for our potentially killer knight. } 22... Bb5! $10) (22. Bf6?! $16 { Trading off an attacking piece for a defending piece is more logical once we have an overwhelming attackers vs defenders ratio. Right now, white is only attacking with two pieces against two black defenders! }) (22. Bh6?! $16 { Trading off an attacking piece for a defending piece is more logical once we have an overwhelming attackers vs defenders ratio. Right now, white is only attacking with two pieces against two black defenders! }) 22... Bb5 { Black is flailing. The LSB on b5 accomplishes nothing, but at least black's heavy pieces can now defend along the 7th rank. } (22... h5! $16 { Necessary. A combination of Qf7+Be8 is possible, desperately hanging onto the kingside. Still, white retains a lasting initiative. }) 23. Rg3! (23. Rh3? { Tempting, since it threatens a big check on h7. Unfortunately, black can completely shut down the h file with h5! We should not be interested in a queen trade, even if we win a pawn, since our pieces in the resulting endgame are totally misplaced. } 23... h5! 24. Qxh5?! Qxh5 25. Rxh5 $10) 23... Rc7 { Black braces for impact along the 7th rank, justifying their previous move. } 24. Bf6 { PRO TIP: The lance pawn controls the f6 square. From an offensive perspective, this is important because a knight, bishop, or rook landing on f6 often packs a huge punch. From a defensive perspective, this is important because black often wants to use the f6 square for a knight or rook when shoring up kingside weaknesses.
The threat of Qh6 is now decisive. } (24. Bh6!? $18 { Equally strong. Play Bf6 instead for the game continuation. }) (24. Nxb5!? $18 { This trade accomplishes nothing to continue our kingside attack except force matters. Find a more direct win. }) (24. h3!? $18 { Getting a flight square before swinging the hammer down on your opponent's head is often a good habit. However, Morphy is completely uninterested in slowing down from such a dominant position. }) 24... f4!? { Black is practically out of moves. The threat of Qh6, piling up even more pressure on g7 could only be delayed - not denied. } (24... Kh8!? { Morphy's line to win against Kh8 was essentially correct, although he bungled the move order to properly set up the zugzwang. } 25. Rxg7 Rxg7 26. Nxb5 Qxb5 27. Qh6 Qd7 28. h4 Qf7 29. h5 Qc7 30. a3 Qd7 31. Kf2 Qf7 32. Kf3 Qc7 33. Qxg7+ (33. g3?! { Morphy's solution wastes the reserve tempo before it is needed. } 33... Qf7 34. Qxg7+?? Qxg7 35. h6 Qxf6 36. exf6 Kg8 37. Kf4 Kf8! $10) 33... Qxg7 34. h6 Qxf6 35. exf6 Kg8 36. Kf4 Kf8!? (36... Kf7!? 37. Ke5 $18 { Zugzwang - white wins e6 and the game. }) 37. Ke5 Kf7 38. g3! $18 { Zugzwang - white wins e6 and the game. }) (24... Qf8!? 25. Nxb5 axb5 26. Qh6 Kh8 27. Rxg7 Rxg7 28. h4 $18 { Transposes. }) 25. Qxf4 Qf8 { Black is doing everything they can to defend on the kingside. Yet now we can simplify into a winning position through a series of forcing moves. } { [%cal Gc3b5] } 26. Nxb5 (26. Qh6!? $18 { A strong move. Yet black has Bd3 in this exact position since your rook now has a job pinning the g7 bishop. Switch the move order instead! } 26... Bd3! 27. Rxg7+ $16 (27. Rxd3?? Bxh6 $19) (27. Bxg7?? Qf1#)) 26... axb5 { Every legal move is winning in this position, but Morphy's continuation is precise. } { [%cal Gf4h6] } 27. Qh6 Kh8 { Black has been reduced to waiting with their king. } { [%cal Gg3g7] } 28. Rxg7! Rxg7 { This was a sacrifice only in name. Of course, we will be able to recapture the exchange whenever we want to. } { [%cal Gg1f2] } 29. Kf2! { Getting the king up in the endgame! A theme we will revisit in Part III.
We can force a winning king and pawn endgame whenever we want, so why not first improve the king in expectation of this endgame? This is a hilarious example of "to take is a mistake." } 29... Kg8 { Black escapes the deadly pin. } 30. Qxg7+ Qxg7 { Forced. } 31. Bxg7 Kxg7 { Forced. We now enter a won king and pawn endgame that we will explore further in Part III. } { [%cal Gf2f3] } 32. Kf3 b4 { [%cal Gg2g4] } 33. g4 b6 { [%cal Gh2h4] } 34. h4 b5 { [%cal Gf3e3] } 35. Ke3 b3 { [%cal Ga2a3] } 36. a3! $18 { White's king has an easy route into the queenside to gobble up all of the pawns. Since black cannot do the same on the kingside, Anderssen resigned in this position.
With this win, Morphy won the match 7-2. This dominant victory against Europe's top player convinced the chess world: Morphy was the new undisputed chess champion.
It is worth reiterating how our strong center ultimately suffocated black. Killing black's piece activity bought us enough time to maneuver our pieces to their optimal squares on the kingside. Once every piece was involved in the attack, black's only "defense" was desperately bailing out into a lost endgame. } (36. axb3? b4! $18 { White is will winning if we are careful with our kingside play. But now the win is much more difficult. }) 1-0


