{ Morphy's opponent this game is Henry Bird, an accountant by day and chess player by night. While his career prevented him from devoting much time to chess at the time of this casual game, he eventually retired and briefly entered the top 10 of the world more than 20 years later. He is famous for his opening contributions to 1. f4, the so-called "Bird opening," in which he only had mediocre results.

In this game, we will once more explore the strength of the lance pawn. However, since Morphy is black, his lance pawn crossing the demarcation line arrives on e4 rather than e5. }
1. e4 { Best by test! } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 1... e5 2. Nf3 { [%cal Gd7d6] } 2... d6 { Morphy plays the Philidor defense. } 3. d4 { Bird continues as in the Opera Game with d4: the maximalist approach to this position. } { [%cal Gf7f5] } 3... f5? { Morphy continues in the style of Philidor himself. With this move, they both argued that challenging the center is more important than developing a piece for one move.
However, f5 is a true "don't try this at home" move that asks too much of black's position. In the short term, development is objectively more important than striking at the center. In the long term, weakening your king is not ideal. Modern engines have essentially refuted this move. } 4. Nc3 { More development! } { [%cal Gf5e4] } 4... fxe4 { "To take is a mistake," but Morphy has a concrete line planned. } 5. Nxe4 { White should be pleased with their lead in development and centralized knights. But there are forcing moves available, and so the position cannot yet be assessed as-is. } { [%cal Gd6d5] } 5... d5 { This is Morphy's concrete point. First we will kick away the centralized knight, and next we will achieve a lance pawn with tempo. What could go wrong?
Morphy is playing for the static advantage of a lance pawn. Bird must seize his dynamic chances right now before they fly away. Therefore, this is somewhat of a DDD moment for white. } 6. Ng3? { Too passive. Now Morphy gets to show his idea and take over the center with tempo.
As we know, dynamics favor the side with the more active pieces! So white should embrace tactical complications at a moment when Morphy has yet to develop a single piece. Neg5 is the correct way to refute black's unprincipled opening.
Of course, playing dynamically requires precise calculation. I have included a few precise variations in the PGN showcasing how white can punish black's audacious play. } (6. Neg5! { When you have a lead in development, look to generate threats! } 6... e4 7. Ne5 { Either knight to f7 would be brutal. } 7... Nh6 { Black has to develop and defend against white's threat of Nf7. Maybe Morphy thought this position was fine from afar, but this is a textbook DDD moment. White can directly punish black's f5 move with: } 8. Nxe4!! dxe4 9. Bxh6! gxh6?? (9... Qf6!? 10. Bd2 $16 { White is a clear pawn to the good, and has thus translated their dynamic advantage into a static one. }) 10. Qh5+ Ke7 11. Qf7+ Kd6 $18 { This position looks like Morphy - NN! Nobody would believe that Morphy is black in this position. Indeed, black's king is running for his life, but there is no escape. This position is forced mate in 8. }) 6... e4 { We can nearly breathe a sigh of relief. By achieving the lance pawn and closing the center, it has now become harder for white to punish our lack of development.
The window for white's dynamic advantage to generate a decisive attack is closing, for we will soon be able to catch up in development. If we do, there will only be a static imbalance in the position: black's lance pawn. } 7. Ne5 { Precision is still required. White's immediate threat is Qh5+, a check we cannot block with the g pawn. } 7... Nf6 { Active defense!
White's lead in development is now only nominal. Moreover, our lance pawn shuts down white's LSB and knight on g3. White's window of opportunity continues to close... } (7... g6?! $16 { Passive defense. In a vacuum, we don't want to play g6 since our DSB already has an open diagonal it can use to develop. You only played this move to defend against white's threat. }) (7... Qh4?! $16 { In no way is this the most adaptable move in the position. Find a more convenient way to handle white's threat. }) (7... Qf6?! $16 { In no way is this the most adaptable move in the position. Find a more convenient way to handle white's threat. }) (7... Nh6?? { While this temporarily takes the sting out of Qh5+, what are you doing about Bxh6 followed by Qh5+? Getting mated is what! } 8. Bxh6 gxh6?? 9. Qh5+ Ke7 10. Qf7+ Kd6 $18 { A true Morphy - NN position. }) 8. Bg5!? { Developing and pinning our f6 knight. But does this pin actually matter? } (8. f3! { Challenging the lance pawn! Of course white should seek to open the position while black is behind in development. } 8... exf3 9. Qxf3 Bd6 10. Bg5 O-O 11. O-O-O $14 { White retains some play in the position due to their active pieces. Our lance pawn is no more. }) 8... Bd6 { An unapologetic developing move! White has no threat, so why not develop the bishop to the best square while preparing to castle? } (8... Be7!? $14 { Equally strong, albeit respecting white's position a little too much. Play Bd6 instead for the game continuation. }) (8... Nbd7?! $14 { Blocking in our LSB can't be the most adaptable developing move. }) (8... Bb4+?! $14 { c3, further defending their center, is a move that white is happy to play. }) (8... Be6?! { Not the most adaptable move in the position when precision is still required. } 9. Nh5! $14 { We can no longer develop our DSB without dropping g7, so white's pressure is annoying. }) (8... Nc6? { Not the most adaptable move in the position when precision is still required. } 9. Nh5! $16 { We can no longer develop our DSB without dropping g7, so white's pressure is serious. }) (8... Bg4?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 9. Nxg4 $18) (8... Qd6?! $14 { Not the most adaptable move in the position when precision is still required. }) 9. Nh5?! { White piles up on our pinned knight, but this move loses more time with a knight that has already made 3 moves.
Be2, followed by O-O, would have been far more sensible. } (9. Be2!? $10) 9... O-O { Active defense!
Now that black has caught up in development, neutralizing white's earlier dynamic advantage, our static advantage of the lance pawn stands supreme. We must be better. } (9... Qe7? { Checks, captures, threats applies to your opponent as well! After Nxf6+ gxf6, Qh5+ is once again playable for white. Devastating. } 10. Nxf6+! gxf6 11. Qh5+! Kd8 (11... Kf8?! 12. Ng6+ hxg6 13. Qxh8+ $18) 12. Nf7+ $18) 10. Qd2 { Logical development. Perhaps white is thinking of castling queenside. } { [%cal Gd8e8] } (10. Bxf6?! gxf6! 11. Ng4 f5! 12. Ne5 Nc6 $17 { Black has an imposing center. There is no attack for white along the half-open g file, so black's king remains perfectly safe. }) (10. Nxf6+? gxf6 11. Bh6 fxe5 12. Bxf8 Bxf8 13. dxe5 Bg7 $17 { Black has two pieces for the rook. For the next 20 moves, black's knight and bishop will be more useful than white's rook. }) 10... Qe8! { Any positional reasoning behind this move is mostly esoteric. But nothing beats a good move! The true justification of this odd move is concrete calculation.
Since white's knight on h5 is undefended, escaping the pin with tempo should certainly be a forcing move to consider.
There is now a crisis in white's position because the h5 knight is hanging. Retreating loses two tempo for free. Capturing on f6 loses material to gxf6. What should they do? } 11. g4?! { White finds a third option. With g4, they are sacrificing the g pawn to buy time and potentially open up a line towards black's king in the event of an opposite sides castling middlegame.
A pawn is a pawn though, and black has already seized the initiative. } { [%cal Gf6g4] } (11. Ng3!? c5! $17 { More central control! More! }) (11. Nxf6+? gxf6 $17 12. Bh6 fxe5 13. Bxf8 Bxf8 14. Qg5+ Bg7 15. dxe5 Nc6 $17 { Black has two pieces for the rook. For the next 20 moves, black's knight and bishop will be more useful than white's rook. }) (11. Bxf6!? gxf6 12. Qh6 Qe7 $17 { White's knight is trapped in the middle of the board! } { [%csl Re5] }) 11... Nxg4 12. Nxg4 { One of several forcing options in this complicated position. } (12. Nxg7!? { The best option - a spicy desperado. Such a move must be calculated precisely. } 12... Kxg7 13. Rg1! Bxe5!? 14. dxe5 Nc6! 15. O-O-O Kh8! $17 { Black is up a piece, but the position remains dicey on the kingside. }) 12... Qxh5 (12... Bxg4!? $17 { Equally good. Capture the other knight for the game continuation. }) 13. Ne5 { The dust has settled. Black has won a pawn and equalized white's earlier lead in development. We also retain the lance pawn. } { [%cal Gb8c6] } 13... Nc6!? { Black has a clear advantage after any move.
Yet Morphy, ever the tempo fiend, chooses to speedrun development. We have already won the static fight - time to win the dynamic one too! } 14. Be2 { Developing with tempo against our queen. With a good grip on the board, we should have anticipated this tempting move before they played it. } 14... Qh3 (14... Qe8?! $17 { There is no need to retreat when we have an active forward move instead. }) (14... Bg4?? { Oh no, your bishop! } 15. Bxg4 $18) 15. Nxc6 { White could not find an active way to defend the threat to Ne5. Instead, they choose to give up their centralized knight just to avoid losing a tempo. } (15. Bf4? Nxd4! $19) (15. f4? exf3! 16. Nxf3 Bg3+! $19) (15. Be3! { Overprotecting the center and preparing to castle queenside is reasonable, but black already has a killer continuation. } 15... Bxe5!! 16. dxe5 Bg4!! { The Shankland question in action! } 17. Qxd5+?! (17. O-O-O! Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Rad8 $17) 17... Kh8 18. Qxe4 Bxe2 19. Kxe2 Rae8! $19 { A typical NN - Morphy position. }) 15... bxc6 { This is a textbook position showcasing the power of controlling the center.
Black's newly fortified center headed by the lance pawn kills white's LSB and queen. Moreover, white's rooks only have the g file to work with. In fact, white does not have a single forward move with any piece except the queen.
Meanwhile, black's pieces are knifing into white's position. Every black piece has more mobility than their white counterpart. In particular, black's heavy pieces are dominant. } 16. Be3 { We have so much power attacking on the kingside that white decides to castle queenside. Overprotecting f2 is a necessary step in that direction.
Evacuating their king to the queenside avoids the thematic lance pawn kingside attack, but is not free from consequence. Going queenside enters into an opposite sides castling race.
PRO TIP: A lance pawn is a huge asset in an opposite sides castling middlegame because piece mobility is crucial in the race to checkmate. } (16. O-O-O? Rxf2 $19 { White cannot afford to give black a free pawn in such a crushing position. }) 16... Rb8 (16... Bd7!? $17 { Equally strong. Play Rb8 instead for the game continuation. }) (16... Bg4!? $17 { Equally strong. Play Rb8 instead for the game continuation. }) (16... Rf6!? $17 { Equally strong. Play Rb8 instead for the game continuation. }) (16... Rf7!? $17 { Equally strong. Play Rb8 instead for the game continuation. }) (16... Rf5!? $17 { Equally strong. Play Rb8 instead for the game continuation. }) 17. O-O-O { As expected, white finishes development by castling queenside.
This opposite sides castling middlegame is one where black has a dominating center and a lance pawn. Based purely on piece activity, we know that black must be better. But would you guess that black already has a disgusting tactical shot?
In this position, Morphy unleashes one of his most famous combinations. Play Rxf2!! to kick off this beautiful combination. } (17. c4?? Bb4 $19) 17... Rxf2!! 18. Bxf2 { "We sacrificed the rook just to clear the 3rd rank? What's the point?" } 18... Qa3!! { Amazing! The queen is immune from capture due to Bxa3#. But since she cannot be captured, white's king is suddenly under a massive attack from our heavy pieces.
This two move sequence of sacrificing the rook in order to sacrifice the queen is my personal favorite Morphy combination. } (18... Ba3? { The right idea, but the wrong execution. After Qe3, black does not have anything special in exchange for sacrificing the rook. Can you improve upon this idea with a more forcing version? } 19. Qe3 Rxb2 20. Qxh3 Bxh3 21. Rdg1! Rxa2+ 22. Kb1 Rb2+ 23. Kc1 Ra2+ 24. Kb1 $10 { Neither side can find better than repeating. }) (18... Qc3?? { Almost the correct idea. This move threatens mate on b2 and cannot be captured by the b pawn without allowing Ba3#. Unfortunately, white's queen can capture on c3 with impunity... } 19. Qxc3! $18) (18... Rxb2?? { Tempting. But after the simple Kxb2 we don't have enough remaining firepower to deliver a mate. } 19. Kxb2 Qa3+ 20. Kb1 $18 { There is no follow-up. }) (18... Qb3?? { A mate-in-1 threat, but there is no follow-up after white takes your free queen... } 19. axb3 $18) (18... Bf4?? { Unfortunately, this bishop is undefended. After Qxf4 there is no follow-up. } 19. Qxf4 $18) (18... e3?? { A fork, but after Bxe3 there is no follow-up. } 19. Bxe3 $18) 19. c3 { This move is the only way to prevent Qxb2#. White's queen now defends b2 laterally. } (19. bxa3?? Bxa3#! { What a beautiful mate. }) (19. Qc3?? { Not adequate defense. } 19... Qxa2! $19 { The first threat is Rxb2!, Qxb2 Ba3! winning the queen. The second threat is Bb4, covering the d2 escape square for white's king (thus setting up Qa1#) as well as threatening white's queen. }) 19... Qxa2 { This is not just a greedy pawn grab. We now have a new threat of Qa1+ Kc2 Qxb2#. The lance pawn performs an vital role covering the d3 escape square in that mate. } (19... Bf4?? { A clever try, but after bxa3! we are just trading queens while simultaneously hemorrhaging pieces. } 20. bxa3! Bxd2+ 21. Rxd2 $18) (19... e3?! { A fancy in-between move that doesn't ruin our position. Yet after Bxe3, what exactly have you gained? } 20. Bxe3 Qxa2 21. Qc2 $10) (19... Rxb2?? { A forcing move, but after Qxb2 there is no follow-up. } 20. Qxb2 $18) 20. b4 { Once more, white's move is forced.
Morphy clearly visualized this position before sacrificing his rook on f2, and decided that black's active pieces, strong center, open lines against white's king, and white's newly created hook on b4 justified the rook sacrifice.
Even with all these positives, believing in the rook sacrifice requires deep calculation and understanding. Don't try this at home [until you are quite strong]!
At our level, perhaps we can identify another critical factor to help justify this decision: white's pieces are devoid of activity. Pay close attention to black's center, headed by the lance pawn. How are white's bishops contributing? How are white's rooks contributing? Has white even hinted at starting an attack against black's king? } 20... Qa1+ (20... Bf4?? { A clever move to prevent the queen trade, but what is the point after Qxf4? } 21. Qxf4! Qxe2 22. Rdg1 $18 { White's pieces are finally coordinating. Black still hasn't kicked off the decisive attack. }) (20... Qa5? { Too tricky for your own good. After Qb2, there is no point to this move. } 21. Qb2 $18) (20... Qa3+? { You must keep a strong grip on the board at all times. This check only encourages Qb2, after which you must spend another tempo avoiding the queen trade. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! } 21. Qb2 $18) (20... Qb3? { You must keep a strong grip on the board at all times. This check only encourages Qb2, after which you must spend another tempo avoiding the queen trade. Don't force your opponents to make good moves! } 21. Qb2 $18) (20... Bxb4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 21. Qxa2 $18) (20... Rxb4?? { Oh no, your queen! } 21. Qxa2 $18) (20... a5?? { Oh no, your queen! } 21. Qxa2 $18) (20... Qa4? { Loses a critical tempo compared to the game continuation. Try to reach this position with black to move! } 21. Qc2 $18) (20... e3?? { Oh no, your queen! } 21. Qxa2 $18) 21. Kc2 { Forced. } 21... Qa4+ (21... Qa2+!? $10 { Always repeat. Yes, black has a perpetual, but what is the actual way to make progress? We want more than a draw! }) (21... Qa3?? { Oh no, your queen! Ra1 traps her. } 22. Ra1! $18) 22. Kb2? { The final mistake.
Kc1 was necessary, when we would have succeeded in avoiding the queen trade with tempo. Next, we would have played a5, biting on the b4 hook, to rip apart white's queenside shelter. In that position, black has sufficient compensation for the rook, but perhaps white is holding with best play.
In the game, white places their king opposite our rook, so further fireworks are already in the air. Alignments create threats! Play Bxb4 for the game continuation. } (22. Kc1! $15 { White had to hope their queenside stayed intact after a5. } 22... a5! (22... Bxb4?! 23. cxb4 Rxb4 { As opposed to the game, this move does not land with check. } 24. Qg5! $10 { White's king is escaping via d2, and we now have to worry about white's threats against our naked king. White can force a perpetual check: } 24... h6!? 25. Qd8+ Kh7 26. Qxc8 Qa2! { Preventing white's king from escaping. Qb2# and Rb1# are deadly threats, so white must bail out. } 27. Qf5+ Kg8 28. Qc8+ Kh7 29. Qf5+ $10 { Black cannot escape the perpetual. }) 23. Qc2!? Qa3+ 24. Qb2 axb4! 25. Qxa3 bxa3 26. Bg3! a2 27. Kd2 Rb2+ 28. Ke3 Ba3 29. Ra1 $13 { Four pawns for the rook. Black's pieces are good, but not nearly as dominant as they are in the game. The position perhaps is level. }) 22... Bxb4! { "One to sac and two to mate!" This final sacrifice decisively breaks through on the queenside.
With discovered checks in the air, white does not have time for anything but recapturing on b4. } 23. cxb4 { White's king is now fully exposed, so the opposite sides castling race to checkmate continues. } (23. Ra1?? Bxc3+! (23... Ba3+! 24. Ka2 Bd6#) 24. Kxc3 (24. Kc1!? Qxa1+ 25. Kc2 Rb2+ 26. Kxc3 Qa3#) 24... Qb3#) 23... Rxb4+ (23... Qxb4+?? { You should be thrown in the gulag for such a move! Why would you trade queens in the middle of a blistering attack? } 24. Qxb4 Rxb4+ 25. Kc3 $19) 24. Qxb4 { Forced. Any king move would have been immediately mated. } (24. Kc1? Qa1+ 25. Kc2 Qb2#) (24. Kc3? Qb3#) 24... Qxb4+ 25. Kc2 { Black is now up a queen. While the material is nearly level, we will explore in Part III how the evaluation of such a position is practically winning.
Morphy's next move is an instructive shot that brings in the final piece with tempo. } { [%cal Ge4e3] } 25... e3! { PRO TIP: There are rare occasions when your lance pawn provides dynamic opportunities beyond its typical static benefits. In particular, pushing onward when the lance pawn is not fixed may ruin your opponent's coordination or decisively open lines for your pieces. You should even consider sacrificing the pawn at the opportune moment purely for these dynamics.
Black's pieces are as active as they can ever be, while white would like nothing more than to develop and coordinate their scattered army. Since their king is vulnerable, this position is not any different than a DDD moment, even though we are well into the middlegame. The time to strike is now! e3 opens lines at the decisive moment. } 26. Bxe3 { White obliges us and captures the free pawn. Why did we just sacrifice the pride and joy of our position? } 26... Bf5+ { Nicely done! With the e4 pawn gone, our LSB awakens to breathe fire across the board towards white's king. } 27. Rd3!? { Blocking with the rook is the lesser evil since blocking with the bishop would have immediately lost a piece to Qc4+! } { [%cal Gb4c4] } (27. Bd3!? Qc4+! $19 { Black wins the LSB next move in every variation. }) 27... Qc4+ { Of course we are not interested in cashing in to just win the exchange. White's king deserves to get massacred. } 28. Kd2 { The only move to defend d3. } { [%cal Gc4a2] } 28... Qa2+ 29. Kd1 { Black's king must defend the e2 bishop. Therefore, the only viable alternative to the game continuation is Ke1. But Ke1 loses just as easily after Bxd3, Bxd3 Qa1+. } { [%cal Ga2b1] } (29. Ke1!? Bxd3! 30. Bxd3 Qa1+ $19 { Winning the rook on h1 again. }) 29... Qb1+ $19 { White resigned rather than allow Qxh1 or Bxd3, both of which win a rook. In either case, black would be up a decisive amount of material and maintain the raging attack.
This thrilling game truly highlights all of the strengths of the lance pawn.
Its static benefits are innumerable. White's pieces never achieved anything after the opening because our center cut the board in half and dominated their pieces. We were able to flood in on the kingside at first behind the space carved out by the lance pawn... Only to swing over to the queenside in a spectacular fashion. Thanks to our center, white's pieces could never do the same.
Yet the lance pawn also showed off its dynamic potential too. With e3! the lance pawn sacrificed itself for the greater good. e3 opened lines at the decisive moment, destroying the last vestige of hope that white could hold. } 0-1


