{ Now let's summarize this chapter on attacking with the lance pawn while playing through a fun miniature by Morphy. This game was part of another blindfold simul!

The text annotations will be repeating the most important points worth remembering from the previous chapter. Please don't get confused - each comment will have little to do with the specific moves on the board. } { [%cal Ge2e4] }
1. e4 e5 { * A "lance" pawn is a strong e5 pawn established in black's position that cannot be easily challenged by a pawn break. Typically, this means black does not have the d6 pawn break, and so the center is closed. } { [%cal Gf1c4] } 2. Bc4 Bc5 { * A lance pawn often spearheads an attack on the kingside. Jousters use lances to screen their opponents in a tilt, and cavalry use lances to lead the charge in battle. Likewise, the e5 pawn prevents your opponent's pieces from reaching the defense of the kingside, while also leading the way for your pieces and pawns to join in on the action there. } { [%cal Gc2c3] } 3. c3 Nc6 { * A lance pawn often cuts the board in half. In particular, you now own the kingside.
Firstly, taking squares and diagonals away from your opponent's minor pieces prevents them from easily switching from the queenside to the kingside. Secondly, with the two pawn breaks d6 and f6 either impossible or too weakening, an e5 pawn ensures that the 7th rank is not open, thus impeding black's heavy pieces from performing kingside defensive duties. Finally, our pieces for the most part have easy paths towards the kingside behind the space that the lance pawn carves out. } { [%cal Gg1f3] } 4. Nf3 Nf6 { * Possessing a lance pawn is a static advantage. The benefits of the lance pawn that we have discussed so far are lasting and do not depend on the move-by-move details of the position. } { [%cal Gd2d4] } 5. d4 exd4 { * The main benefit of a stable center (potentially headed by a lance pawn!) is to contain your opponent's pieces. Once contained, they cannot easily create threats in your position, giving you time to build up a kingside attack. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } 6. e5 Qe7? { (A poor move. Active defense with d5 was necessary.)
* A lance pawn is a huge asset in an opposite sides castling middlegame because piece mobility is crucial in the race to checkmate. } { [%cal Ge1g1] } (6... d5! 7. Bb5 (7. exf6?! dxc4 8. fxg7 Rg8 $15 { Black has an imposing center. White does not have a lead in development in order to create threats before black can castle queenside. }) 7... Ne4 8. cxd4 Bb6 $10 { Black has their fair share of the center and a lead in development. Our lance pawn can be challenged with a timely f6. }) 7. O-O! Ng8 { * There are rare occasions when your lance pawn provides dynamic opportunities beyond its typical static benefits. In particular, pushing onward when the lance pawn is not fixed may ruin your opponent's coordination or decisively open lines for your pieces. You should even consider sacrificing the pawn at the opportune moment purely for these dynamics. } { [%cal Gc3d4] } (7... Nxe5?? 8. Nxe5 Qxe5 9. Re1 Ne4 10. cxd4 Bxd4 11. Qe2 d5 12. Bxd5! Qxd5 13. Qxe4+ $18) 8. cxd4 Bb6 { * When the center is closed and stable, play naturally occurs on the wings, or "flanks," of the board. However, premature flank play often backfires if your opponent can counterattack in the center. Strong central play can punish flank play by showing it to be at best a loss of time or at worst actively weakening. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } 9. d5! Qc5 { * f4 is a common follow-up to e5. Firstly, f4 supports the center in case the lance pawn is challenged with f6. Secondly, it claims more space that the rooks can use to swing over to the kingside via a rook lift. Thirdly, it prepares the f5 pawn break, which activates the heavy pieces along the f file and opens more diagonals up for the bishops. } { [%cal Gb1a3] } (9... Nxe5?? 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Re1 $18) 10. Na3 Nd4 { * Knife f5! A white knight landing on f5 was Kasparov's favorite attacking piece against a castled king. In particular, she threatens several checks against a king on g8, directly hits a king on g7, and coordinates well with other attacking pieces on the sensitive e7, g7, and h6 squares all around the king. Black's knife f4 is equally deadly. } { [%cal Gc1e3] } 11. Be3 Nxf3+ { * Developing a bishop to g7 (or g2) nestled within the pawn shell of f7+g6+h7 (or f2+g3+h2) is a common way to safeguard the king and attack the center from afar. Black's bishop controls the dark squares, while black's pawns control the light squares. This constellation is known as a "kingside fianchetto," and is a hallmark of hypermodern play. } { [%cal Gd1f3] } 12. Qxf3 Qf8 { (Please enjoy the rest of this unannotated Morphy miniature. Now that white's center simultaneously dominates all of blacks pieces and cuts the board in half, Morphy begins his winning attack in earnest!) } { [%cal Ge3b6] } (12... Qe7?! 13. d6! cxd6 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Qxf7+ $18) 13. Bxb6! axb6 { [%cal Ga3b5] } 14. Nb5 Kd8 { [%cal Ga1c1] } 15. Rac1 d6?! { [%cal Ge5d6] } (15... Ra5!? 16. d6 c6 17. Qe3 c5 18. b4! $18) 16. exd6 cxd6 { [%cal Gf3e3] } 17. Qe3! Ra6 { [%cal Gb5c7] } 18. Nc7! Qe7 { [%cal Gc7e6] } (18... Kxc7?? 19. Bxa6+ $18) 19. Ne6+! fxe6 { [%cal Gc4a6] } 20. Bxa6 Bd7 { [%cal Ga6b5] } (20... bxa6?? 21. Qxb6+ Ke8 22. Rxc8+ Kf7 23. Rc7 $18) 21. Bb5! Ke8 { [%cal Gd5e6] } (21... Bxb5?? 22. Qxb6+ Ke8 23. Qxb5+ $18) 22. dxe6! Nf6 { [%cal Gc1c8] } (22... Bxb5?? 23. Rc8+ Qd8 24. Rxd8+ Kxd8 25. Qxb6+ $18) 23. Rc8+! $18 { The bishop is pinned, so losing the queen with Qd8 is black's only move. Black resigned instead.
For more resources exploring the power of the lance pawn, check out:
* ChessNetwork https://youtu.be/vj2Vvk6L5lo
* ChessCoach Andras https://youtu.be/ndd_OhGOTNw
* ChessDojo https://youtu.be/X1xu3ft3v_4
* Powerplay chess https://youtu.be/9eEMYMrP9uQ } 1-0


