[Event "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960: Introduction"]
[Date "2024.04.02"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Introduction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/hk8BBuQ3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.02"]
[UTCTime "15:30:12"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This study contains my personal annotations on the famous book by Mikhail Tal: "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960." You can use this study to learn from the games and view key variations. However, to get the most out of this study, I strongly suggest you follow along the actual book as well!

Throughout the annotations, Tal's words will be put "in quotes," while my personal comments will be plain text. }
 *


[Event "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960: Before the match"]
[Date "2024.04.22"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Before the match"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/h1pDnuUN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[UTCDate "2024.04.22"]
[UTCTime "14:04:43"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Botvinnik did not play much outside of his WCC matches. So Tal didn't have many games to analyze when preparing for the match besides the famous games already reviewed during the WCC matches against Smyslov. Still, "We were convinced that my future opponent had not recently gone in for any voluntary intensification of a struggle, and in those cases when he was caught up in a combinational 'storm,' he was less sure of himself [...] In many games, Botvinnik would agree to a minimal edge in the endgame, which as a a rule, would lead to success thanks to his highly polished technique.

"But the most important conclusion at which we arrived in examining all of his games might have been that during a game, Botvinnik gives most of his consideration to strategic questions, not being distracted by different tactical variations. This can be a plus (consistency in the realization of a plan) and a minus, since in several positions his underestimation of the tactics showed considerably in his results."

In 21st century chess, people admit that tactical complications rule over all strategic decisions. The engine has shown us countless tactical opportunities for both sides that upend overarching strategic battles that the old masters used to discuss. There are less grand plans in chess today. Chess is now dominated by move-by-move skirmishes. In that sense, Tal started the beginning of this wave, Kasparov showed higher mastery and ushered in a second wave, and many players post-engine domination have rode this wave to this very day. }
 *


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.15"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C18"]
[Opening "French Defense: Winawer Variation, Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 1: Tal - Botvinnik, French Winawer"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/r4V3pQRQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "I must confess to the readers that my spirits, right up until the beginning of the match, were not too high." Tal always lost the first game of tournaments. But this is a match, not a tournament... }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4!? { The Winawer was very much in vogue at the top level. It's positionally interesting because both sides know what to play for. But the sharp complications in the main lines would definitely favor Tal more than Botvinnik. Something that Botvinnik quickly figured out after this defeat. He never repeated the French during this (or the 1961) match again. } (3... Nf6!? { With 60 years hindsight, Botvinnik should have preferred the main line Classical systems. }) 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ (5... Ba5?! { Botvinnik chose the retreat variation in several games during the 1954 match against Smyslov. } 6. b4 cxd4 7. Nb5! { Chosen by Smyslov three times. } (7. Qg4!? { "Apparently, precisely because of 7. Qg4, Botvinnik refrains from 5... Ba5, although even here the last word has yet to be spoken."
Indeed, Nb5 is the stronger move with modern engines. However, both both Qg4 and Nb5 has a fantastic reputation, hence why black players rarely play Ba5 anymore. })) 6. bxc3 Qc7!? (6... Ne7!? { "looks more flexible[...] but the patent continuation Qg4 again causes complications, upon which chess theory has not yet given its final judgement." } 7. Qg4 Qc7 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 $14 { The main line poisoned pawn variation would have suited Tal well, although he had no knowledge of it at the time. }) 7. Qg4 { Tal chooses the sharpest move. } 7... f5?! { This entire line is not so well respected anymore. But it was the main way people used to play who didn't want to lose their entire kingside. } (7... Ne7!? 8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 $14 { transposes to the poisoned pawn main line. }) 8. Qg3 Ne7!? (8... cxd4!? 9. cxd4 Ne7 10. Bd2!? (10. Qxg7?? Rg8 11. Qxh7 Qc3+ $19) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 b6 12. Ne2 Ba6 13. Nf4 $14 { Botvinnik - Reshevsky, 1948. "White has a tangible positional plus: his DSB, although only operating on one diagonal, can strike via d2 to b4." }) 9. Qxg7 { Played after 3 minutes. "White should by no means pass up this kind of double-edged continuation" } (9. Bd2?! $14 { Smyslov - Botvinnik, 1957. }) 9... Rg8 10. Qxh7 cxd4 11. Kd1!? { "Twenty years ago, an annotator would cringe in horror at such a move." This move, originally recommended by Max Euwe keeps the g1 knight's options open. The center isn't open, so the king is reasonably safe on d1. } 11... Bd7!? { "A very artful move" played after 4 minutes. } (11... Nbc6!? 12. Nf3 Nxe5 13. Bg5! N5g6 (13... Nxf3?? 14. Bb5+! $18) 14. Bxe7!? $16 { Gligoric - Petrosian, 1959 Candidates ( https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1106469 ). The most recent French game of theoretical significance before this game. } (14. Bf6! $16 { An improvement. })) 12. Qh5+ { Played after 17 minutes. } (12. Nf3?! Ba4! 13. Bd3? Qxc3! $17) (12. Ne2?! Ba4 $10 { [%cal Gd4d3] }) 12... Ng6!? { Played after 10 more minutes. Presumably, both players are now out of theory. } (12... Kd8!? 13. Bg5?! { Tal's intention "going for an attack." Probably he was too influenced by that Gligoric game. } (13. cxd4! Qc3 14. Rb1 Qxd4+ 15. Bd2 Qxf2 16. Nf3 Nbc6 17. Rxb7 $16 { The best way to play. }) 13... Qxc3! 14. Bxe7+ Kxe7 15. Qh7+ Kf8 16. Qh6+ Ke8 17. Rb1 $14 { Maybe white is slightly better here, but there's no fast development to be seen by either side, and black's queen is just as invasive as white's queen. }) 13. Ne2!? { Nf4 is coming, hitting the pinned piece. Botvinnik spent more than a half hour on this position. } (13. Qh7?! Ne7 14. Qh5+ Ng6 $10 { "Such an agreement to a draw would be a considerable creative defeat." }) (13. Rb1!? { Probably objectively strongest. Now d3 is easily prevented, and black still can't quickly untangle and get his king to the queenside easily anyway. } 13... Nc6 14. Nf3 O-O-O?! (14... d3!? 15. Bxd3 O-O-O 16. Re1 $16 { Similar to the game, but with better development. }) 15. cxd4 $16 { White has a strong center and the better bishops. }) 13... d3! 14. cxd3 Ba4+?! { "This natural move does not seem to be quite correct. [...] He drives the white king to e1, where it is considerably more secure." } (14... Nc6?! 15. d4 O-O-O $16 { Tal seems convinced that there's compensation for black here. That really shows that he loves the initiative and clean development. This is an extremely strong position for white with the strong center and closed nature around white's king. }) (14... d4! { The correct way to "punish" white. } 15. cxd4 Nc6 16. Bd2 O-O-O 17. Ke1!? $14 { Black has a much better version of the game, since he doesn't waste tempi with the LSB. }) 15. Ke1 Qxe5 { Losing a lot of time. } (15... Nc6!? 16. d4 O-O-O $16 { Again, Tal thinks white is only slightly better when in reality this is a crushing advantage. }) 16. Bg5! { "The loss of white's e pawn has played into white's hands, since new threats can be created with the opening of the e-file." See? Even Tal knows that pawns aren't people! } 16... Nc6 (16... f4?! 17. d4 Qf5 18. Nxf4! Qc2 19. Bd3! $18 { Tal's line. }) 17. d4 Qc7 (17... Qe4? 18. Rc1! $18 { Black's queen is trapped. }) 18. h4! { Preparing a rook lift. Tal still maintains his nearly 30 minute advantage on the clock. } (18. Rc1!? Ne7 $16 { and black can castle queenside next. }) 18... e5!? { Trying to punish white for not developing and playing on the side of the board. } (18... Ne7?! 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Qg5 Qxg5 21. hxg5 $16 { "Carries the game into extremely prosaic channels." I literally have no idea what that means, but white is up a pawn and it can easily be defended by f4. }) 19. Rh3 { Tal has used just over an hour to get here, while Botvinnik, clearly struggling with king safety issues, has used more than 1 hr 45 m. } 19... Qf7!? (19... exd4? { This move was threatened, but Tal prevents it with Rh3. } 20. cxd4 Nxd4 21. Nxd4 Qc3+?? 22. Rxc3! $18 { One key point of Rh3. }) (19... e4!? $16 { "Black's position would be rather solid, but he would be threatening absolutely nothing, and white could about realizing his pawn advantage without any hindrance." }) 20. dxe5 Ncxe5 (20... Rh8?? 21. e6! Qxe6 22. Re3 Rxh5 23. Rxe6+ Kf7 24. Rxg6! Kxg6 25. Nf4+ $18 { Tal's refutation. }) 21. Re3 Kd7 (21... Rh8?? 22. Rxe5+! Kd7 23. Re7+! Qxe7 24. Qxg6 $18 { Tal's refutation. }) 22. Rb1! b6?! { Losing an important tempo, this move was played in just over 3 minutes. } (22... Bc6!? { The best try, but with his huge lead in development, Tal intended to sacrifice the exchange. } 23. Nd4 f4 24. Rxe5! Nxe5 25. Qxf7+ Nxf7 26. Bxf4 Rae8+ 27. Kd2 $16 { "the lesser of two evils for black." But yes this all objectively correct play from both sides and white will for sure be pushing here with the three connected passed pawns on the queenside and bishop pair. }) 23. Nf4 Rae8 24. Rb4! Bc6 25. Qd1! { "The queen has done her job - she is now dismissed." Tal notes how picturesque this position is (what an artist!). After many moves, the king and queen return to their starting squares.
Black is nearly lost due to the activity of white's pieces. This position is just Tal in his element. He doesn't even comment much on alternative moves here, as he feels like white's position is too dominant and the crushing moves he's about to play too straightforward for comment. } 25... Nxf4 (25... Ng4!? 26. Rxe8 Rxe8+ 27. Be2 $18 { "Black is lost." }) 26. Rxf4 Ng6 27. Rd4 Rxe3+ (27... f4? 28. Qg4+ $18 { The f pawn is falling and black's king is dead. }) 28. fxe3 Kc7 29. c4! { c4 is explosive. "This leads to a forced material advantage for white." } 29... dxc4!? (29... Ne7!? 30. cxd5 Bxd5!? (30... Nxd5!? 31. Bc4 $18) 31. Bxe7 Qxe7 32. Rxd5 $18) 30. Bxc4 Qg7 31. Bxg8 Qxg8 32. h5 { 1-0 White wins. } { "Finally the passed pawn has its say." } 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.17"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A61"]
[Opening "Benoni Defense: Uhlmann Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 2: Botvinnik - Tal, Modern Benoni"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/he1ySK4R"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Having won the first game, Tal was curious to see if Botvinnik would try to strike back with an imbalanced game or seek more positional "squeezing" territory where he was famously strong. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 { Tal opts for a benoni, and give a long 2-page explanation of the pros and cons of such an approach. Fascinating read. } 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 (5... g6? { A mistake that even Tal had known as early as 1954. Amazingly, the refutation of this line is only rarely played. } 6. d6!! Qb6!? 7. Nf3!? (7. Bg5!? { Tal's "refutation" is good too. } 7... Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. h4! $16) 7... Bxd6 8. e4! O-O 9. Be2 Re8 10. O-O $16 { White is down a pawn, but black cannot develop the queenside at all. }) 6. Nf3!? { Probably not the most dangerous move order, since this rules out the idea of a quick f4+e5. } (6. e4!? { The main way to play forces you to play directly in the center. }) 6... g6 7. Bg5!? { This move only recently came into fashion by 1960. } (7. Bf4!? { The modern way to play this position directly targets d6. }) 7... Bg7 8. Nd2!? { Botvinnik's idea is clear - a quick re-route of the knight to c4. } (8. e4!? O-O 9. Nd2! $14 { "more precise" } (9. Be2?! h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 b5!? (11... Nh5! $10 { Wang Hao - Firouzja, Alireza, 1-0, Aeroflot Open A 2019, https://lichess.org/VIodSx6C }) 12. Bxb5?! Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Qa5+ 14. Qd2 Qxb5 $10 { Tal shows this example variation as a way things can go poorly for white if he over-extends. })) 8... h6! 9. Bh4 g5! 10. Bg3 Nh5 $146 { You have to eliminate this DSB before white gets a chance to coordinate on d6 with Nc4. } (10... a6?! { The old way of playing is clearly inferior. } 11. a4 (11. Nc4!?) 11... Nh5 12. Nc4! Nxg3 13. hxg3 O-O 14. Ne4! $14) 11. Nc4 { Botvinnik spent 8 minutes on this move and "declined to refute Black's 'opening error.' " } (11. Qa4+?! Kf8 $15 { The main reason nobody had played Nh5 before this game. But already black is in the driver's seat since a6+b5 is only hitting harder. } 12. Qc2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 14. e3 Ne5 15. Be2 h5! { An engine approach to the game. Pawns aren't people, and black is justifying the king on f8 by blowing up the kingside and queenside. } 16. O-O-O!? (16. Rxh5?! Rxh5 17. Bxh5 g4 $17) (16. Bxh5?? Bg4 $19) 16... a6 $15 { With typical Benoni counterplay. The king on f8 is not a concern at all. } { [%cal Gb7b5] }) 11... Nxg3 12. hxg3 O-O (12... Bxc3+!? 13. bxc3 b5 14. Nd2 Nd7 $14 { "Immediate action at the cost of the DSB" }) 13. e3 (13. Ne4? b5! 14. Ncxd6?! f5 15. Nxc8 fxe4 $19) 13... Qe7 { Played after a 21 minute think. } (13... Na6!? 14. Be2 Nc7 15. a4 $10 { Similar to the game. Black is just slightly worse. }) 14. Be2 Rd8 { Over-protecting d6 prepares Nd7->e5. } (14... f5!? { Tal's other consideration. You can just tell that he was looking for a fight every move. } 15. Nb5!? Rd8 16. g4! $14 { I guarantee you Botvinnik would have never considered this engine line. }) (14... Nd7?! 15. Nb5! { The type of move you want to avoid, although you can still sort of make it work with: } 15... Ne5 16. Nbxd6 Nxc4 17. Nxc8 Raxc8 18. Bxc4 a6 $10 { White has won the pawn, but the OCBs favor the attacker. Here's it's a bit unclear who's attacking whom, but white does owe black a few tempi just to finish development. }) 15. O-O Nd7 16. a4?! (16. e4!? Ne5 17. Ne3! $10 { Avoiding exchanges, but sharpens up the game. }) 16... Ne5 17. Nxe5 (17. Na3?! g4 $15 { Just the type of thing black wants. }) 17... Qxe5!? { Tal criticizes his own move, but objectively this is just as fine as the other recapture. } (17... Bxe5!? { Black's "position would not have been bad at all." }) 18. a5 Rb8 19. Ra2! { The battery towards b2 has been nullified. White prepares Nb5->a3->c4. } 19... Bd7 (19... b5!! { Now that's how you stop Nb5! } 20. Nxb5!? (20. axb6!? Rxb6! 21. Qd2 Bf5 22. Rxa7 Rdb8 $10 { Benko gambit counterplay. }) 20... Ba6 21. Nc3 Bxe2 22. Qxe2 Qf5 $10 { Black can double on the b file and regain the pawn in due course. White's knight can no longer reroute to c4. This will most likely end in a queenside-only game. }) 20. Nb5 (20. Bb5!? Qe8! { Preventing Nb5 again! } 21. Qd3 Bxc3 22. Bxd7 Qxd7 23. Qxc3 Qf5 $10) 20... Bxb5!? { Removes the knight to c4 plan. But now the OCBs in the middlegame favor the attacker. Who is attacking whom? } (20... a6?! 21. Na3 b5?! 22. axb6 Rxb6? 23. Nc4 $18) (20... g4! 21. Nxa7 Ra8 22. Nb5 h5 $10 { The bishop pair remains on the board, but what exactly is black's LSB doing anyway? You'd prefer Kh7+Rh8+Kg8 in this position. }) 21. Bxb5 { Tal incorrectly offered Botvinnik a draw in this position. He had to make a move first. } 21... b6?! { Played in only 2 minutes. This desperate move to open up the queenside backfires. Now the queenside becomes blocked. } (21... a6!? { "Black should have continued" } 22. Bc4 b5 23. axb6 Rxb6 24. b3 Ra8 $10 { "queenside counterplay would have secured the draw without too much difficulty." }) (21... Bf6!? 22. b3 Kg7 $10) 22. a6! { Botvinnik declines the draw offer because now the light squared weaknesses are accessible everywhere, and the kingside is more white's playground than black's. Both players have barely used an hour so far. } 22... Rbc8 23. Qd3 Rc7 24. b3 Qc3?! { "Black, thinking the position is clearly drawn, accepts the invitation" of a queen trade. But trading off the queens makes white's grip more palpable. If the white rooks can infiltrate on any file, then white is the only one who can be pushing here. } (24... g4!? { If white wants anything here, he has to go crazy: } 25. f4! Qc3! { Now the queen trade makes more sense, as the e pawn is more of a target. } 26. Qxc3 Bxc3 27. Rc2 $14) 25. Qxc3 Bxc3 26. Rc2 Bf6 27. g4! { Botvinnik shows his class. Many pawns are being fixed on the wrong color for both sides. But white's rooks will have their say in this position, while black's rooks can do nothing. } 27... Re7 28. Rc4 { Finally Tal recognized how crummy his position is, and he begins to get restless. } 28... Rc8?! { Preventing b4. But this rook doesn't coordinate with any other piece. } (28... Kg7! 29. Kh2 Rh8 30. Kg3 h5! $10 { Similar to the game. White is just not in time to impose a firm grip on the position. }) 29. g3 Bg7!? { Getting out of the way for a possible f5 pawn break. } (29... Kg7!? 30. Kg2 Rh8 31. Rb1 h5! 32. b4! $14 { A plan that Tal goes out of his way to stop in the game. }) 30. Rd1 { Played after nearly 30 minutes. This move by itself isn't bad, but shows Botvinnik struggling to make progress. } (30. Rb1!? { The simplest way forward. } 30... Bf6 31. b4! $14 { Now b4 can be played directly. }) 30... Rf8 31. Rd3?! { Played after another 10 minutes. Botvinnik, ever the perfectionist, is playing over-prophylactically. Presumably he wants to meet f5 with f4. I suppose he just didn't see a way for Tal to make progress and thought he had all the time in the world. } (31. b4! { No matter how the pawn tension is resolved, white gets activity. } 31... cxb4!? (31... Rc8 32. bxc5?! { The timing of this capture isn't well-timed, but just to show the idea: } 32... bxc5!? { b7 is an important infiltration square for white's rooks. Advantage: white. } { [%csl Gb7] } (32... dxc5!? { d5 is a passed pawn that can be quickly escorted down the board. Advantage: white. })) 32. Rxb4 Rc8 { The best possible world for black... except for one thing. } 33. Bc6! $14 { White will eventually rule the c file. Advantage: white. }) 31... Kh7 (31... f5!? 32. gxf5 Rxf5 33. f4?! { But this makes no sense. } (33. Kg2!? $14) 33... gxf4 34. gxf4 Rh5 $10 { Black's rooks have some amount of activity here, and white has yet to achieve the desirable b4 pawn break. }) 32. Kg2 Kg6 { Tal himself just spent 20 minutes on finding Kh7->g6, and so black doesn't have a crushing time advantage. } 33. Rd1 { Botvinnik shows that the f4 idea is overrated. } (33. f4?! h5! 34. gxh5+ Kxh5 35. f5?! (35. Kf2 Kg6 $10) 35... g4! $15 { Tal refutes Tolush's recommendation for white. There's no way to take advantage of black's wayward king. }) 33... h5! { A crucial break, before Rh1 gets in and white is truly squeezing. } (33... Rd8?! 34. Rh1 $14 { Now black is actually devoid of an active plan. }) 34. gxh5+ Kxh5 35. g4+?! { "Experiencing some time trouble, white succumbs to the temptation of making an extra move with check, but in doing so, he transfers the black king to a better position."
This honestly shows one example when Botvinnik's "never play blitz" mentality comes up short. If he was a blitz maniac, he would have no issues playing 5 moves in 14 minutes, even without increment. Yet he spends almost all of his time in the next few moves and doesn't come up with anything incisive. } (35. Rg4!? Kxg4?? (35... Kg6 36. f4 Bh6 $10 { White's not doing much except trapping their own rook. }) 36. Bd3! Rxe3! 37. fxe3 $18 { Black can barely avoid mate here. }) (35. b4! { Again, this remains the most annoying move to face. } 35... Be5 36. bxc5 bxc5 37. Rb1 Rb8 38. Rcc1 Kh6 39. Kf3 Rb6! (39... f5? 40. Bd3! g4+ 41. Kg2 Rf8 42. Rb7 $18 { An excellent example of white getting the desired infiltration to the 7th rank. }) 40. Bd3 Rb4! 41. Rxb4 cxb4 42. Rc6 b3! 43. Kg4 b2! 44. Bb1 Kg7 45. Kxg5 Re8 { Black barely gets enough counterplay on the h file to not resign this position. } 46. Rc7 Rh8 47. Rxa7?! Rh1! 48. Bd3 b1=Q 49. Bxb1 Rxb1 $10) 35... Kg6 36. Rc2 (36. b4!? Be5 37. bxc5 bxc5 38. Rb1 Rb8 39. Rcc1 Kf6 { Black gets off a light square, and the b file is no longer a serious problem. } 40. Bd3 Rb2!? (40... Rb4!? $10) 41. Rxb2 Bxb2 42. Rb1 c4! { A sharp way to avoid any catastrophe's on the b file. } 43. Bxc4 Re4! 44. Be2 Rb4 $10) 36... Rh8 37. Bd3+ Kf6 38. Kg3 Ree8 { Preparing Ke7 and doubling on the h file. Now there really are no issues. } 39. Bb5 (39. b4!? Rb8 $10) 39... Re4! 40. Rc4 Rxc4 41. bxc4 { Finally the b4 pawn break is no more. The play is purely on the kingside and cannot amount to any advantage for either side. } (41. Bxc4!? Ke7 $10) 41... Ke7 42. Ba4 Be5+ 43. Kf3 (43. f4!? Bf6 $10 { No progress can be made. }) 43... Rh4 44. Rg1?! { "Not taking into account black's next move." } (44. Bc2?! Rh3+ 45. Ke4 Rh2 46. Rf1 Bg3! 47. Kf3 Bh4! $10 { White is tangled, and black has infinite king moves to pass the time. }) (44. Bb5!? Rh3+ 45. Ke4 Rh2 46. Rf1 Rh3 47. f4 Bf6 $10 { The best way to play for white still amounts to nothing. }) 44... f5! $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { After this move was played, Botvinnik offered the draw. Hilariously, this means that Botvinnik also messed up the timing of a draw offer in the same way that Tal did earlier. Regardless, Tal accepted the draw since white can no longer make further progress on the kingside. } 45. gxf5?! (45. Bd1!? $10 { The simpler move. }) (45. Rg2!? Kf6 46. Rg1 $10 { Another way to wait. }) 45... Rxc4 { If anyone, black has the advantage. } 46. Rg4! Rxg4 47. Kxg4 $10 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.19"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B11"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Two Knights Attack, Mindeno Variation, Exchange Line"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 3: Tal - Botvinnik, Two Knights Caro Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/1WGoZH9m"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

1. e4 c6 { The Caro Kann was "a solid workhorse" in the world champion's opening repertoire to get a quiet game in his matches against Smyslov. } 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 { Apparently both Botvinnik and Tal believed at the time of the WCC that the two knight's Caro was a better winning attempt for white than the main line. } (3. d4 { The main line. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { Several games between Smyslov and Botvinnik were played in this variation. }) 3... Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 (4... Bh5?! 5. exd5! cxd5 6. Bb5+ (6. g4!? Bg6 7. h4! $14 { If there is a refutation to black's move order, it might just be this variation. }) 6... Nc6 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 10. Qe2! Bb4?! (10... Bd6! $14 { The better try for black. } { Venkatesh, Marani Rajendran - Ding, Liren, 0-1, Asian Continental op, 2012, https://lichess.org/XAqc9XEH }) 11. h4! Qb6 12. O-O! $16 { A game played at the 1960 Latvian championship that Tal references. Indeed, this does appear to refute black's suboptimal play. }) 5. gxf3!? $146 { Tal's novelty was universally condemned at the time. But in the post-engine era, this very well might be a reasonable try seen at the top level. Not only is it a 0.0 variation, but the play is fundamentally different from the main lines, so you're getting both a practical advantage and playable position. } 5... e6 { Botvinnik chooses a solid continuation, keeping the light squares defended and the center reasonably closed, during the game after 16 minutes. } (5... e5?! { A training game played before the match with his second, Alexander Koblents. } 6. f4! dxe4 (6... exf4 7. exd5 cxd5 8. d4 $10 { Transposing to a favorable version of the King's gambit. }) 7. fxe5 Qd4 8. Qe2 Qxe5 9. d4! Qxd4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Bf4 Qxb2? (11... Nd7! { The only playable way to continue. } 12. Bg2 O-O-O 13. O-O $14 { With play similar to the Qd6 Scandi when black gets greedy and takes on d4. }) 12. Nd6+!! { Not played in the practice game. Would have finished him off directly. } (12. Rd1? { The game continuation. } 12... Nf6 13. Nd6+ Kf8 $10 { and we arrive at a position that was featured in the advanced section of the Woodpecker Method. Try your hand at it before checking the solution! https://lichess.org/study/H4guLgm0/7hoZiEqk }) 12... Kf8 13. Be5! Qb4+ 14. c3! Qc5 15. Nxb7! { Now this move works! } 15... Qb6 16. Bxg7+!! Kxg7!? (16... Ke8!? 17. Nd6+ $18) 17. Qg4+ Kf8 18. Qc8+ Kg7!? (18... Bd8!? 19. Nxd8 $18) 19. Rg1+ $18) (5... d4!? { This move scores reasonably well in the masters database: } 6. Ne2 c5 7. f4 e6 $10) 6. d4 Nd7!? (6... Nf6!? 7. e5?! (7. Qd3 $10) 7... Nfd7 $15 { Tal thought this would only be beneficial to white. But with such a locked position, the value of time decreases. And there's no way to quickly get in f4-f5. So black is totally fine here. }) 7. Bf4?! { Tal spent 8 minutes over the board to play a poor move. } (7. Be3! { Tal's preparation. With Qd2 and O-O-O coming next, white has some play. } 7... Bb4 8. Qd2 Ngf6 9. Bd3 $10) 7... Bb4 8. h4 { "And this is a simple blunder based on a miscalcalculation." even though the engine finds this move totally fine. } (8. a3?! Ba5?! (8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ngf6 $15 { White has a beefy center, but in typical Winawer style, we would rather play Bc1->a3 here. Black has just enough play as long as they don't blast open the center. }) 9. b4?! Bc7 { Winning a tempo. } 10. Be3 Ne7 $15) 8... Ngf6 (8... Ne7?! 9. h5 $10 { The point of h4. Black's knight is struggling to find a square. }) 9. e5?! { "After this move, white is positionally lost, since all of his hopes for an open game have disappeared and along with them any compensation for the numerous weaknesses in his camp."
Tal played this move after 23 minutes of analyzing unforced variations where he found better moves for black than for white. He should have searched broad, not deep! } (9. Qd3!? { "clumsy." } 9... Qa5 10. Bd2 $10 { It's tough to retreat like this and admit your last moves were bad. }) (9. a3?! { Tal's original idea was to "begin gambit play" } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxe4 11. fxe4 Nxe4 { This is the first position Tal should have really looked broad on rather than assume Qf3 had to be correct. } 12. Qf3!? Qa5!? { His main fear is probably not even black's best move. } (12... f5! $15 { The inhuman move refutes white's play. The knight cannot be dislodged. }) 13. Rh3!? (13. Rb1! { The c pawn is still taboo because of: } 13... Nxc3? (13... Qxc3+? 14. Qxc3 Nxc3 15. Rxb7 $16 { The position has blown open for the bishops. }) (13... Ndf6!? 14. Rxb7 $15 { Some compensation in the form of the two bishops. }) 14. Bd2! $16) 13... Ndf6 14. h5? { Also completely not forced. } 14... O-O-O 15. h6 gxh6 16. Be5 Ng5 17. Qxf6 Nxh3 18. Kd2 Ng5 19. Bd3 { "I examined this position thinking that white has a fine initiative for being down the exchange, but suddenly I felt a shiver go down my spine when I saw: " } 19... Qxe5!! $19 { Tal should have gone broad, not deep though. None of this was forced. }) 9... Nh5 10. Bg5 (10. Bd2!? Qb6 $15 { transposes to the game. }) 10... Qa5 (10... f6!? 11. f4 g6 12. Bh6 $15 { "some vague hope of creating play against the e pawn." You can already tell how desperate he sounds in his annotations. White's doing fine here. }) 11. Bd2 { A finesse to provoke the queen to be opposite the bishop. } 11... Qb6 12. a3 Be7 (12... Bxc3?! 13. bxc3! $10 { With typical Winawer play, white is doing totally fine here. }) 13. Be3?! (13. f4!? { An interesting approach to blast open the kingside even at the cost of the center. } 13... g6 14. Be2 Ng7!? (14... Qxd4!? 15. Bxh5 gxh5 16. Qxh5 $10) 15. h5! Nxh5 16. Bxh5 gxh5 17. Qxh5 $10) 13... g6! (13... Qxb2?? 14. Na4 $18) 14. Na4 (14. f4?! Ng7 15. Be2 h5! $15 { Now white is not in time to force through h5. Black retains the grip. }) 14... Qd8 { Concentrating on the original plan: the h4 pawn. But this move undevelops the queen and so gives white more opportunities to blow it all open. } (14... Qa5+?! 15. Qd2!? (15. c3!? b5 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. b4! $10) 15... Qxa4?! (15... Qxd2+!? 16. Kxd2 $15) 16. b3! Bb4! 17. Qxb4 Qxb4+ 18. axb4 $14 { The type of sharp play Tal was looking for. }) 15. Qd2?! { Tal misses his chance to truly sharpen up the position. } (15. f4! Bxh4!? (15... Ng7!? 16. h5! Nxh5 17. Rxh5 gxh5 18. Qxh5 $10 { Again, this exchange sac hits just in time. }) 16. Qg4! Be7 17. Rxh5! gxh5 18. Qxh5 $10 { Black is so underdeveloped that they can't get the king castled away to the queenside fast enough. White is blowing open the center next with f5. }) 15... Ng7 (15... Bxh4!? { "Interesting variations can arise." But that favors white who is statically worse and needs to look for dynamic complications. } 16. Bh6 $13 { [%cal Gf1h3,Gh3g4] } (16. Rxh4?! { Tal also considered this enterprising exchange sac. } 16... Qxh4 17. Bg5 Qh2 18. Qb4 f6 19. Qxb7 O-O!? (19... Rb8?! 20. Qxc6 fxg5 21. Qxe6+ (21. Nc5?! O-O 22. Nxd7 $15 { Tal's line is less convincing. This leads to a "not unfavorable game for white." }) 21... Kd8 22. Nc5 Nhf6! $10 { Petrosian's analysis after the game is more correct than Tal's. }) 20. Bh6 Rfd8 21. Qxc6 { Tal felt this was enough compensation for the exchange... but it's not after: } 21... Nf8! 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Qxe6+ Kh8 $17 { White has just been playing with the pretty pieces. Black's king is finally safe and white can't castle queenside without dropping f2 or allowing Nf4. })) 16. Bg5 (16. Bd3?! h5! $15 { Mostly plays into black's hands. }) 16... h6! (16... Nf5?! 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. h5! $10 { "white's position would have improved greatly" as the h pawn has been offloaded. }) (16... f6! $15 { The correct way to punish Tal. But Botvinnik consistently avoids these tactical melees. }) 17. Bxh6?! { Tal keeps his bishop pair, but now black can win the h pawn and once again retains some initiative. } (17. Bxe7!? Qxe7 { As long as the queens remain on the board, white has no true issues in the position. Black should be torn between getting his king to safety and attacking white's center. } 18. Bd3! (18. Qb4? b6 $17) 18... Nf5?! (18... O-O-O!? 19. b4 Kb8 20. Nc5 $10 { This remains totally playable for white. }) (18... Kf8!? 19. O-O-O $10) 19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. b4! { Once c5 is ruled out, white can utilize the f4 square for the knight! } 20... O-O-O 21. Nb2 Kb8 22. Nd3 Ka8 $10 { [%cal Gd3f4] }) 17... Nf5! 18. Bf4 Rxh4 19. Rxh4 Nxh4 20. O-O-O! { The f pawn cannot be defended. } (20. Qe3? Qa5+ 21. Nc3 c5 $17) (20. Be2? Ng2+! 21. Kf1 Nxf4 { Depriving white of the two bishops. } 22. Qxf4 Qa5 $17) 20... b5! 21. Nc5!? { "One more desperate attempt to get back the initiative at the cost of a pawn." } (21. Nc3!? a5 $15 { "Passive tactics would be absolutely disastrous for white." The engine is not impressed yet with black's attack. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 22. Kb1!? b4 23. Na4! bxa3 24. b3 { and asks black to show white the money. }) 21... Nxc5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. Be2 (23. Bg5?? Nxf3 $19) 23... Be7!? { Prevents Bg5, but it's another slow move. } (23... Nf5!? { Also takes the sting out of Bg5. } 24. Rh1!? (24. Bg5!? Qc7 25. f4!? (25. Rh1? Qxe5 $17) 25... Kd7 26. Rh1 Kc8 27. Rh7 Kb7 $17 { Another example where black doesn't dally and immediately fixes the king while coordinating the remaining pieces. }) 24... Kd7 25. Rh7 Qg8 $17 { Much cleaner coordination to accomplish the same thing done in the game. }) 24. Kb1! { Prevents black from getting the king to the queenside directly. } 24... Qc7!? (24... Kd7!? 25. c4!? bxc4 26. Bxc4 $17 { and yet this remains lost for white anyway. }) 25. Rh1 O-O-O 26. Bg3 Nf5 27. Rh7 { "Probably white's first active move in this game." } 27... Rf8?! { "Safe but passive continuation." } (27... Nxg3?! 28. fxg3 Qxe5 29. Rxf7 { For some reason, Tal doesn't even analyze this obvious move, which is best. } (29. f4?! Qf6 30. Qa5 Bc5! $17 { [%cal Gd8d7] }) 29... Bf6 30. c3 $10) (27... Rd7! 28. Rxf7!? Bb4! 29. Rxd7 Bxd2 30. Rxc7+ Kxc7 $17 { With such a locked position, both of white's bishops are dead. Still, converting this to a win will require good technique. }) 28. Bf4 Qd8?! (28... Bc5! { "Necessary." } 29. Bd3 $15 { The f pawn is defended by the queen, so Bxf5 and Bh6 don't win the f pawn. }) 29. Bd3 Rh8?! { Black has not embraced the fact that white's attempts to dynamically blow open the position would have backfired while black was positionally better.
Now, black gives up both the advantage and also spent 7 minutes to do so. He now only has 11 minutes to play 11 moves. For the slow Botvinnik, that is severe time pressure. } (29... c5! $15 { A cleaner way forward. White gets nowhere by trying to win either pawn. } 30. Bxb5?! (30. Bxf5?! gxf5 31. Bh6 Rg8 32. Rxf7 Rg1+ 33. Ka2 d4 $17 { And finally black has activated all of his pieces. }) (30. c3!? $15 { It is in no way easy to play this for either side. And Botvinnik would never play such a risky move while approaching time pressure. }) 30... g5! $17) (29... g5?! 30. Bh2? (30. Bg3!? { The better try. } 30... Rh8 31. Rxf7 $15) 30... Rh8 31. Bxf5 exf5 32. Qd3! Rxh7? (32... f4! $19 { Pawns aren't people. This is another classic example in the mold of Winter - Capablanca, 1912. White's bishop is entombed! }) 33. Qxf5+ Qd7 34. Qxh7 Qe6 35. f4! $10 { Tal's idea to get counterplay. Once again, he's too fanciful with the variations and missing tactical resources for both players earlier in the lines. }) 30. Rxh8 { Played after 21 minutes as Tal tried to calculate a full rook sacrifice. With both players now desperately low on time, this should be marked as clearly unpractical. Save the time! } (30. Rxf7?! Qe8 31. Qa5? (31. Rf6!? Bxf6 32. exf6 e5! $15 { "Insufficient compensation for the exchange" }) 31... Qxf7 32. Qxa7 { [%cal Ga3a4] } 32... Rh7! 33. a4 Bd8! 34. Qa8+ Kd7 35. axb5 Ke8! $19 { Tal refuted his own attempt at a perpetual. }) 30... Qxh8 31. Qa5! Qh1+ (31... Qd8?! 32. Qxa7 $14) (31... Kb7?! 32. Bxb5! { The only way forward. } 32... cxb5 33. Qxb5+ Kc7!? (33... Ka8!? 34. Qc6+ Kb8 35. Qb5+ $10) 34. Bd2! $10 { With a perpetual at least. }) (31... Kb8!? { The move Tal was most worried about during the game. } 32. Bxb5?? (32. Bxf5! { Tal thought this move lost but in fact it's good enough for a perpetual. } 32... Qh1+! (32... gxf5?? 33. Be3! $16 { The point. }) 33. Ka2 Qxf3 34. Be3?? (34. Qa6! { An improvement! } 34... Qxf4!? (34... gxf5!? 35. Qxc6! Qxf4 36. Qe8+ Kc7 37. Qxe7+ $10) 35. Bd3 Qxe5 36. Qxc6 Qc7 37. Qxb5+ Kc8 38. Qe8+ Bd8 39. Ba6+ Kb8 $10) 34... d4! 35. Bxd4 Qd5+! $19 { Tal found this "refutation" during the game. }) (32. a4!? { Tal's supposed improvement allows black to actually just bail with: } 32... Qd8! 33. Qa6 Qc8! 34. Qxc8+ Kxc8 35. axb5 Nd4 $15 { Not at all easy to see or evaluate. }) 32... Bd8! $19) 32. Ka2 Qxf3 33. Qa6+! Kb8 34. Qxc6! Qxf4 35. Bxb5!? { The threat of Ba6 forces black's hand: } (35. Qxb5+!? Kc7 36. Qa5+ Kb8 37. Qb5+ $10) 35... Qxe5 36. Qe8+ Kb7?! { Almost throws the game away, but black is still fine here. } (36... Kc7!? $10 { "More prudent" because now white can force a perpetual, but white doesn't have any winning chances. }) 37. Qc6+!? (37. Ba6+! { "Practically speaking this might have good chances, but white's position had been so bad throughout the game that he decided not to tempt face and therefore forced the draw." } 37... Kxa6 { Forced. } (37... Kc7?? 38. Qc8+ Kb6 39. Qb7+ Kc5 40. Qb4+ Kc6 41. Qb5+ Kc7 42. Qb7+ Kd6 43. Qb8+! Kc6 44. Qxe5 $18) 38. Qc6+ Ka5 39. c3! { The threat of b4# is so dire that black has only one move to prevent it: } 39... Qe2! 40. Qc7+ Ka6 41. Qc6+ $10 { Perpetual. }) 37... Kb8 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { With a perpetual on the board, and neither player having any time on their clock, both players agreed to a draw rather than play out the repetition. } 1/2-1/2


