1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 { The Nimzo. "From a practical point of view, its only drawback is that is has been thoroughly studied, in many variations through the 20th move, and consequently there was less probability of getting into time trouble."
You can tell that Tal has also picked up on the fact that his opponent has not handled the games correctly during time trouble. } 4. a3!? { The Saemisch is a rare move from Botvinnik's main lines with e3 and Qc2. } (4. e3!? { Much more common from Botvinnik. This also remains a main try for white in present times. }) 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 O-O!? (5... c5!? 6. f3 d5 (6... Nc6!? 7. e4 d6 $10 { My personal recommendation to avoid transposing to the f3 Nimzo. }) 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qd2?! (8. dxc5! Qa5 9. e4 $14 { The main way to play this position wasn't discovered yet. }) 8... Nc6 9. e4 Nb6 10. Bb5 (10. a4 $10 { Tal thought this line was worth considering as an improvement for white, and so avoided this whole entire line to avoid any of Botvinnik's deep prep. }) 10... Bd7 { Botvinnik - Donner, 1958. } 11. dxc5 Ne5! $10) 6. f3!? (6. e3!? { Both an extremely old and extremely new move. It was played a lot when the Nimzo was first developed in the 1920s. Then, players realized that f3 asked for more from the position. Only in the post-engine era has it been picked up again as a surprise weapon. Yes, it leads to an equal position, but there are a lot of dynamics available still, so it's nowhere near a dead draw. }) 6... d5!? { Following the famous Botvinnik - Capablanca, 1938 game. } 7. cxd5 (7. e3?! c5! 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bd2 Nc6 10. Bd3?! cxd4! 11. cxd4 e5! $17 { Known theory from the 1930s. }) 7... exd5 8. e3 Bf5!? { "Probably the most logical." } (8... c5!? 9. Bd3 $10 { Many games have been played from this position. White will achieve e4 at some point, and the question is: will black get counterplay on the queenside or while white's kingside pawn roller destroy black a la the famous 1938 Botvinnik - Capablanca game. } 9... b6!? 10. Ne2 Ba6 $14 { The aforementioned game. Tal is unimpressed with this version of the game because black is wasting a move trading LSBs with b6 compared to the immediate Bf5. }) 9. Ne2!? (9. g4? Nxg4! 10. fxg4 Qh4+ 11. Kd2 Be4! 12. Nf3 Qf2+ $19) (9. Bd3?! Bxd3 10. Qxd3 c5 11. Ne2 Nc6 12. O-O $10) 9... Nbd7 (9... c5?! 10. g4! Bg6!? (10... Be6?! $14 { "gives white an easy game with prospects for an attack on the king" }) (10... Nxg4? 11. fxg4 Qh4+ 12. Kd2 Be4 13. Rg1 Qxh2 14. Qe1 $16 { Averbakh - Khasin, 1957. }) 11. h4 h5 12. g5 Ne8 $14) 10. Ng3 (10. g4?! Nxg4! 11. fxg4 Qh4+ 12. Kd2 Be4 13. Rg1 Nb6! { The point of black's play. } 14. Rg3! $10 { takes the sting out of Nc4+, and the game continues. } (14. c4?? { Tal believed this to be the only move. } 14... Nxc4+ 15. Kc3 c5 $17 { Chernykh - Khodos, 1959. })) 10... Bg6 11. Bd3 c5 { "doubled pawns on the g file will serve as a rampart rendering any attack very difficult." } 12. O-O Re8 13. Re1 { The rook is better on the f file after the inevitable e4 dxe4 fxe4, so black shouldn't be too upset here. } (13. Ra2?! Rc8 14. Re2 Qa5!? $15 { and white will have to sacrifice a pawn on the queenside to accomplish anything active. } (14... cxd4!? 15. Bxg6! (15. cxd4?? Rxc1! 16. Qxc1 Bxd3 $19) 15... hxg6 16. cxd4 $10 { [%cal Ge3e4] })) (13. a4!? Qa5 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Qd3 $10 { One proper way to go about things. The DSB is best on d2. }) 13... Qc7 (13... Qa5!? 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Bd2 Qa6 $10 { The queen is annoyingly active here, just as in the reversed version of this position in the QGD. }) 14. Bxg6 (14. e4?! dxe4 15. fxe4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Qc3! 17. Be3 Nd5? { Tal's suggestion is too fancy. } (17... Nxe4! $17 { A clean pawn. }) 18. Bf2! $16 { and black's position is too precarious. }) 14... hxg6 15. e4 { Both sides are achieving their main goals, but black's king is totally safe as opposed to the other lines where white gets a huge attack. } 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Rac8?! (16... dxe4! 17. fxe4 Rac8 $10 { A much better version for black. White doesn't get the simple pawn roller, and the open center means there is no free kingside attack. }) 17. Bg5?! { Played after 15 minutes, this move "leads to a significant simplification of the position." } (17. e5! { "tempting." Sometimes, simple is good. This pawn roller shouldn't be allowed. } 17... Nh7 18. f4 f5! (18... Nb6?! { Ragozin's suggestion. } 19. f5 Nf8 $16 { but this is very flaccid play from black. }) 19. h4!? Qc2?! (19... Nhf6! 20. Be3!? (20. exf6? Qc3! $17 { With a fork on both rooks and the g3 knight. }) 20... Ng4 $14 { A more sensible way to play. Black's kingside remains intact, and a knight landing on e6 is a firm blockader. }) 20. Qf3 Nhf6! 21. h5 gxh5 22. Be3 Ne4 23. Nxf5 $16 { "with a very sharp game." I don't know how you could even consider such a variation. White has a connected passed pawn on e5 that is not blockaded, the h pawn is loose, white's knight on f5 is a monster, and black's pieces are doing nothing on the c file. I think this is classic Tal completely overestimating sharp positions as automatically good for him. }) (17. Ra2!? { [%cal Ga2f2] } 17... dxe4 (17... Nb6 $10 { Tal's idea during the game. But lines with e5 are still very much possible. }) 18. fxe4 Nxe4?? (18... b6?! 19. Rf2 $14 { white can refute the tactic by playing the move they wanted to play already. }) (18... Nb6! $10 { A better way to play. }) 19. Nxe4 f5 20. Nc5 Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Nxc5 22. dxc5 Qxc5+ 23. Be3! $18) 17... Qc2 { Botvinnik clearly struggled in this position, where he spent over 30 minutes thinking of how to make progress and couldn't come up with anything killer. } 18. Bxf6 Qxd1 19. Rexd1 { Leaves the other rook open to get active on the queenside. } 19... Nxf6 (19... gxf6!? { "unconvincing:" } 20. exd5 Nb6 21. Ne4 { But actually after: } 21... Red8! 22. Nxf6+ Kg7 23. Ne4 Nxd5 $10 { All of black's pieces are perfectly active and the IQP is going nowhere. Black has enough for equality. }) 20. e5 Nh5!? { Tal is already aware that his opponent has under an hour to make the remaining 20 moves, calling this "slight time pressure." Therefore, he gives him a hard choice - admit the knight on h5 isn't so bad after all or take the game into a potentially drawn rook endgame. } (20... Nd7!? 21. Rab1 Nb6 22. a4 Rc7 23. a5 Nc4 24. Rb5?! { Tal thought this was simply a great endgame for white but missed: } (24. Ra1!? $10 { If this is the correct way to play, then black has no complaints. }) 24... a6! 25. Rxd5?? Ne3 $19) 21. Ne2 { Botvinnik avoids the rook endgame after 10 more minutes. } (21. Nxh5!? gxh5 22. Rab1 (22. Rac1 Rc4 23. Rxc4 dxc4 24. Rb1 Rd8 25. Rxb7 Rxd4 26. Rxa7 Rd2 $10 { Also drawn. }) 22... Rc7 23. Rdc1 Rec8 24. Rxc7 Rxc7 25. Rb5 Kf8! $10 { Does not give white any advantage. } 26. Rxd5!? b6 $10 { [%cal Gc7c3] }) 21... Rc2 22. Kf1 g5 { The knight is no longer trapped, and black can look to activate the remaining rook. } 23. Rdc1 Rec8 24. g3!? { The knight is killed on h5, and so white's slight advantage can only be due to the difference in knight quality. } (24. Rxc2!? { Many commentators preferred this approach, but Tal refutes it. } 24... Rxc2 25. Rb1 b6 26. Rb5 Kf8! 27. g3!? (27. Rxd5?? Rxe2 28. Rd8+ Ke7 29. Rh8 Nf4 30. g3 Ng6 $19) 27... Ra2 $10 { Black prefers the queenside passed pawns to the central passed pawn(s), and thinks black is totally fine here. }) 24... f6?! { "Playing for a loss." } (24... Rxc1+! 25. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 26. Nxc1 g6 27. Ke2 Ng7 28. Ke3 Ne6 $10 { A clearly drawn endgame. }) 25. Rxc2 Rxc2 26. Rb1 b6 27. Rb5 fxe5 28. dxe5 (28. Rxd5?! exd4 29. Rxg5 d3 $15) 28... Rc5?! { "Evidently the only move" except for one thing... } (28... Rd2! { Tal assumed this move was lost after } 29. Rb3! { With the idea of Ke1 and Rd3. However, black is totally in the game here with two different variations. } 29... Rd1+!? (29... g6!? 30. Ke1 Ra2 31. Rd3 Ng7 32. Rxd5 Rxa3 $10 { The knight is getting back into the game via e6 or f5, and black is not worse. Tal feared that this type of a position is lost with the rook getting to d7, but black is fine here: } 33. Rd7!? Ne6 34. f4 gxf4 35. gxf4 Ra4 36. Nc3 Rxf4 37. Rxa7 Rf5 $10) 30. Kf2 d4 { The king is boxed out and so black is fine... if the d pawn doesn't fall. } 31. Rb4!? (31. g4!? Nf4 32. Nxf4 gxf4 33. Ke2 Rh1 $10) 31... d3 32. Nc3 Rd2+ 33. Ke3 Rxh2 34. Kxd3 Nxg3 $10) 29. Nd4! { Botvinnik only has 15 minutes. Tal has more than an hour. } (29. Rxc5?! bxc5 30. Nc3 Kf7! { Tal found this line too! } (30... d4?? 31. Ne4 $18) 31. Nxd5 Ke6 $10 { "a satisfactory endgame" }) 29... Kf7 30. Ke2?! { "Now black succeeds in bringing his knight, which had lost its way, into the game." Botvinnik played this drawing move with only 15 minutes on his clock. Once again, Tal's idea to put pressure on the clock from move one succeeds. } (30. f4! { This tactical shot is playable. } 30... g6! (30... gxf4?? 31. g4 $18) 31. fxg5 Ng7! { Tal's suggested improvement. } (31... Rxb5? 32. Nxb5 Ke6 { Tal's idea OTB. But: } 33. Nxa7 Kxe5 34. Nc8! $18) 32. Kf2?! (32. h4! { Not mentioned. The g pawn is defended, taking the sting out of Ne6. } 32... Ne6 33. Rxc5 bxc5 34. Nc6! a6 35. a4 $16 { Since black cannot bring in his king or knight, white retains a serious edge here. }) 32... Ne6 33. Rxc5 bxc5 34. Nf3 Nc7 $14 { [%cal Gf7e6,Ge6f5] }) 30... g6 31. Kd3 Ng7 32. Rb1?! (32. Rb4 $10 { More precise. }) 32... Ra5! 33. Nc2 (33. Nb5?! Ke6 $10) 33... Ne6 (33... Nf5 $10 { More precise, leaving e65 available for the king. }) 34. Rb4 Rc5 35. h4 gxh4 { White is sure to make time control, with only a few minutes left to play some obvious moves. But black simply forces a draw. } 36. Rxh4 d4 { Threatening Rc3+... } 37. Nxd4 Rxe5 38. Nxe6 Kxe6 39. a4 Rg5 40. Re4+ { White reaches the 40th move with 1 minute remaining. Tal once again incorrectly offers a draw on his own turn. Botvinnik requested Tal make his move, and only after } 40... Kf6 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { was played did Botvinnik accept the draw offer. "The board seems to be rather empty." } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.24"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B18"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 5: Tal - Botvinnik, Classical Caro Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/oRRrAjnA"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ After a rest day, Tal and his team believed that the Caro was practically impregnable. However, in a tactical game, there are dynamic chances to be had, and all dynamic games favor Tal. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 (3. Nd2!? { Transposes to the main line in the vast majority of cases. However, Yasser Seirawan believes the knight is better placed on d2 in case black tries to deviate, with something like g6. }) 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5!? { Gets the bishop outside the pawn chain, although in recent years the Tartakower has taken over as something of a main line. } (4... Nf6!? 5. Nxf6+ exf6! { "giving white a significant advantage." Incorrect! This Tartakower variation has been revived ever since the discovery of: } (5... gxf6?! $14 { "compromising the pawn structure" }) 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5! $10 { This multipurpose move, which shows white that this pawn structure isn't compromised at all. In fact, black has a majority on the kingside and can launch the pawns even if white castles queenside. }) 5. Ng3 (5. Bd3?! { "an interesting gambit variation that should be tested." } 5... Qxd4 6. Nf3 Qd8 7. Qe2 $15 { I used to face this all the time in blitz and bullet games when I played the Caro as black. It's "scary," but totally overrated. }) 5... Bg6 6. N1e2!? { Tal's idea for the game - get Botvinnik out of theory with a sideline that doesn't seem so bad. } (6. h4!? h6 7. Nf3 (7. Nh3 { "less ingenious than the game continuation." }) 7... Nd7 { Smyslov - Botvinnik, 1958. Indeed, this is one of the main lines today, with white typically having a fun time after: } 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2!? (11. Bf4!? Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Bb4 13. c3 Be7 14. c4 Qc7 $10) 11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 $10 { With the idea of Ne4, and g4-g5, black's king is not so safe on the kingside. }) 6... e6!? { An obvious move played after a 20 minute think. Clearly, Botvinnik was once again unprepared for Tal's ideas fishing around for novel territory in the main lines. Indeed, this move is probably not best (e5 in one move can sometimes be strong), and Botvinnik himself improved upon this line in games 7 and 9. } (6... Nf6! 7. Nf4 e5 $10 { The modern approved method to equalize here as black. } 8. dxe5!? (8. Nxg6!? hxg6 9. dxe5 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qxe5+ 11. Qe2 Nbd7 $10) 8... Qa5+ 9. c3 Qxe5+ 10. Be2 Nbd7 $10) 7. h4 (7. Nf4!? Qh4?! { The only real game in this position at the time was Ragozin - Flohr, 1936. Black got crushed. } (7... Bd6 8. h4 Qc7 { Tal's reasoning for refraining from this variation. } 9. h5 Bxc2! (9... Bxf4?! 10. hxg6 Bxg3?? 11. Rxh7!! $18 { White's trap. }) 10. Qxc2?! (10. Nxe6!? fxe6 11. Qxc2 Bxg3 $10) (10. Qg4? { "For his pawn, white gets a position rich in possibilities." Hilariously, this is completely lost for white if black is willing to meet fire with fire and simply develop ASAP. } 10... Nd7! { Not mentioned by Tal. } (10... f5? 11. Qf3 $16) (10... Kf8?! 11. h6? (11. Qf3 $10) 11... Nxh6 12. Rxh6 gxh6 13. Ngh5 $17 { "With a strong attack." Once again, Tal gets lost in the deep weeds of fun sacrifices instead of grounding his play. Broad, not deep. }) 11. Qxg7 { This obvious continuation doesn't work simply because black is following the rules of chess and developing their stuff... while white is not. } 11... O-O-O 12. Qxh8 Ngf6 13. Qg7 Bb4+! 14. Bd2 Qa5 $19) 10... Bxf4 $15)) 7... h6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4 { Maximum development. There is a sacrifice brewing on e6. } 9... Nf6 10. Qe2? (10. O-O $10 { Should have been played. This improvement was played later in the match. }) 10... Bd6?! { Because the sacrifices on e6 fail, Tal admits that his opening plans have failed with the next move. } (10... Qxd4!? { A pawn is a pawn. Of course, Tal continues to try and provoke Botvinnik into unclear complications. But there's nothing going on after: } 11. O-O! { Tal was going to simply castle. } (11. Nxe6?! fxe6 12. Qxe6+ Kd8 13. Be3 Qxb2 14. Rd1+ Nbd7 $17) (11. Bxe6?! fxe6 12. Nxe6 Qg4 13. Nc7+ Kd8? $10 { Tal's move is much worse because it allows O-O-O+. } (13... Kf7! 14. Nxa8 Qxe2+ 15. Nxe2 Na6 16. Bf4 Nd5 17. Bg3 Bxc2 $17)) 11... Nbd7 $15 (11... Ne4? 12. Be3!? $16 (12. Bxe6! Nxg3?? 13. Bxf7+! Kxf7 14. Qe6#))) 11. Be3?! { Given that ideas with g4+g5 and Bxg5 are played later in the game, it is better to save a tempo and not develop the bishop yet here. } (11. Bxe6? O-O! $19) (11. Ngh5! { This line is still played today with this move. } 11... O-O 12. g4! $10 { With a complicated game. }) (11. Nxe6? fxe6 12. Bxe6 Qe7 $17 { And the queens will get traded. }) 11... Nbd7 (11... Bxf4?! 12. Bxf4 Qxd4?! 13. Be5 $16 { Now winning the pawn is fraught with danger. }) 12. Ngh5 Nxh5 13. Nxh5 Rg8 { Botvinnik agrees the kingside is a bit too scary to place his king there. } (13... O-O?! 14. g4 Nf6?! 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. g5 $16 { White's earlier Nf4 and h4 are fully justified here, as white has "a strong attack." }) 14. g4 (14. O-O-O!? { Tal didn't want both players to castle on the same side of the board, after which the play is less dynamic in nature. } 14... Qe7 15. Kb1 O-O-O $14 { More of a squeezing position, where Botvinnik would prefer to have the white pieces. }) 14... Qc7 15. g5 Bg6! (15... Be4!? 16. Rg1! Bh2 17. Bf4 Bxf4 (17... Qa5+? 18. Bd2 Qf5 19. Ng3! Bxg3 (19... Qh3? 20. Nxe4 Bxg1 21. O-O-O Bh2 22. g6! $18 { "more than enough compensation for the exchange." }) 20. fxg3 $14) 18. Qxe4 $10) (15... Bf5!? 16. gxh6? (16. O-O-O O-O-O 17. Ng3! Bxg3 18. fxg3 Qxg3 $10 { "white has a significantly better position." }) 16... gxh6 17. Bxh6 Bg4! 18. Rg1! Qa5+! 19. c3 Qxh5 $19) 16. O-O-O (16. gxh6?? Qa5+! $19) 16... O-O-O 17. Ng3?! { "Now the initiative passed to black, since this move doesn't threaten anything." } (17. Bd3! { Ragozin's recommendation. } 17... Bxd3 18. Rxd3 g6 19. Ng3 hxg5! 20. Bxg5!? (20. hxg5!? f5?! (20... Rh8! $10) (20... Bxg3?! 21. fxg3 Qxg3 $14) 21. gxf6 Nxf6 22. Bg5 (22. Bd2! $14) 22... Bf4+ $10) 20... f6 $10) 17... hxg5 18. Bxg5!? (18. hxg5!? Bxg3 19. fxg3 Qxg3 $10 { The g6 bishop defends the kingside. Still, there is some compensation here too. }) 18... Bf4+ 19. Bxf4!? (19. Kb1!? Bxg5 20. hxg5 Qf4 21. Qe3 Qxe3 22. fxe3 e5 $10 { "Black maintains a small edge." So clearly Tal is already depressed with white's position in the game. However, there's nothing objectively wrong with white, because once the LSBs are traded off both h7 and f7 become good squares for a white rook. }) 19... Qxf4+ 20. Qe3 Qh6! { Botvinnik wants to trade queens on his terms. This nice move seeks to show that the rook on g8 is well-placed. } 21. Bd3 { "Better late than never!" Black's LSB is admittedly pretty strong. } (21. h5!? Bh7 22. Be2! $10 { with the idea of preventing Nd5 with c4 is the engine line. It's pretty reasonable, but you have to commit these pawns and weaken your king so much before the queen trade actually occurs. }) 21... Bxd3 22. Rxd3 Nb6 23. Qxh6 { With Nd5 coming, white was just about to be forced to trade the queens. } 23... gxh6 24. Rf3 { Tal believes black has the better endgame because the only target is on f7 and it's hard to hit it twice. } 24... f5!? { Weakens the e pawn but prevents Rf6. } (24... Rxd4?! 25. Rxf7 $10 { Heading for a draw. }) (24... Rd7!? 25. Rf6 Rg6 26. Rxg6 fxg6 27. h5 g5 28. Re1 $10 { Probably heading for a draw as well. White's knight still needs to get in the game though. }) 25. Re1 Rd6 (25... Rxd4?! 26. Rxe6 Rxh4 27. Rxf5 $10 { White's pieces are more active than black's, but this is a likely draw. }) (25... Rg6? 26. h5 Rf6 27. Ne4! Rff8 28. Nc5 $16 { The e pawn cannot be protected. }) 26. c3?! { Unnecessary. } (26. b3! { The most straightforward approach to killing the game. } 26... Rg4!? { Now this move lacks the punch it had in the game. } (26... Nd5!? 27. c4 Nc7 28. Rf4 $10 { Rg4 is prevented and the rook remains stable on this square because there's no longer an opportunity to play Nd5. }) 27. c4! Nd7!? (27... Rxh4?? 28. c5 $18) 28. d5! cxd5 29. cxd5 Rxd5 (29... exd5!? 30. Nxf5 $10) 30. Rxe6 Rxh4 31. Nxf5 $10 { All the pawns are being vacuumed off the board and there's no way black is better. }) 26... Rg4 { Black is more active than white, and so there are practical problems holding this. } 27. Ne2 Nd5 (27... Rxh4?! 28. Nf4! Kd7 29. Nd3 $14 { Nc5+ is coming, and white can't be worse. }) 28. Rh1 { Passive. But white's pieces are all worse than black's pieces, and there's no way to improve them obviously. } (28. h5!? Rg5 29. Rh3 $10 { Another way to grovel. }) 28... Rd8 29. Rg3 Rxg3 30. fxg3 (30. Nxg3!? Rg8 $15 { At the right moment, f4+Rg2 could be a problem. }) 30... Rg8 31. Kd2 Rg4!? { Keeps white bottled up. } (31... Kd7!? { Botvinnik suggested this idea instead - strengthening b6+c5, as a way to break down white's center. Tal is not convinced. } 32. Ke1 Kd6 33. Kf2 b6 34. Kf3 c5 35. c4 Nf6 36. Rd1 { "with sufficient defensive resources." }) 32. Ke1 Kd7!? { Get your king up in the endgame. But now white has time to untangle a bit. } (32... Re4!? { Smyslov's suggestion. } 33. Rf1 Ne3 34. Rf3 Kd7 35. b3 $10 { Kd2 is coming, untangling. Indeed, this is holding. }) 33. Kf2 Re4!? (33... Kd6!? 34. Kf3 b6! $15 { Another way to squeeze. } { [%cal Gc6c5] } (34... Nf6?! 35. Nf4 $10 { Tal's freeing maneuver in action. })) 34. Re1! { Trading rooks will lead to equality. } (34. Kf3? { This move is prevented. } 34... Re3+! 35. Kf2 Rd3! $19) 34... Kd6 35. Nc1 Rxe1 36. Kxe1 { Black is for choice because of how active the pieces are. But there are no accessible weaknesses. } 36... c5 37. Ke2! { The IQP is not a bother with the king so close to its defense. Without heavy pieces, it's impossible to win the d pawn. } (37. dxc5+?! Kxc5 $15 { Black's passed e pawn gives him the better chances here. }) 37... cxd4 (37... c4!? { Ragozin's suggestion. } 38. Kf3 b5 39. Ne2 a5 40. g4! (40. Nf4?! { Mindlessly wasting time with the knight is not the way to go. } 40... Nb6 41. Ne2 Na4 42. b3 cxb3 43. axb3 Nb6 { where black can create a passed pawn on the queenside, far away from white's position. }) 40... fxg4+ 41. Kxg4 $10 { White's king is activated, and he shouldn't be worse as long as there's no immediate breakthrough on the queenside. }) 38. cxd4 Nf6 39. Kd3 Nh5 40. Ne2 e5 { Both sides recognize that there's no way to attack the IQP effectively. } 41. a4!? { The last move played before the adjournment. Botvinnik is ready to seal a move. But since black needs to figure out a move right here and now, there isn't as much time to analyze this critical position vs if this position occurred during adjournment analysis. Botvinnik only has a few minutes to figure it out and Tal believes he sealed a suboptimal move. } (41. dxe5+ Kxe5 42. Ke3?? (42. a4 $10 { Tal's suggestion should hold too. The problem is that we are after move 40, after which black would have plenty of time to analyze this position after an adjournment and come up with the best way forward. }) 42... Nxg3 43. Nxg3 f4+ 44. Kf3 fxg3 45. Kxg3 h5 $19) 41... Nf6?! { Botvinnik's sealed move leads to a theoretically drawn position. } (41... e4+!? { Tal believed this to be the strongest move, but admits that it is still drawn with best play. } 42. Kc4 a5! (42... Kc6?! 43. a5! { White attains a fortress, with b4 coming next. Black cannot displace white's king. }) 43. b4! axb4 44. Kxb4 Nf6 45. Nf4 Nd5+!? 46. Nxd5 Kxd5 47. Kc3 $22 $10 { Mutual zugzwang. Both sides have two reserve tempi that cancel each other out. With black to move, b6 is met with h5 and h5 is met with a5, when black has to give ground. With white to move, a5 is met with h5 and h5 is met with b6, and white has to give ground - losing. } 47... b6!? (47... h5!? 48. a5 Kc6 49. Kc4 b5+ 50. axb6 Kxb6 51. d5 Kc7 52. Kc3! $10 { Distant opposition and black has nothing. }) 48. h5 Ke6!? { There's one last try. Black can try and win the h pawn. } 49. Kc4 Kf6 50. Kc3 Kg5 51. d5! Kf6 (51... Kxh5?? 52. d6 $18) 52. Kd4 Ke7 53. Kc4 Kd7 54. Kc3! $10 { Keeping e5 under control. White maintains opposition. }) (41... a5!? 42. b3 b6 43. dxe5+ Kxe5 44. Kc4 Ke4 45. Kb5 Kf3 46. Nd4+ Ke4 47. Nxf5 Kxf5 48. Kxb6 Nxg3 49. Kxa5 $10) 42. dxe5+ Kxe5 43. b4 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Both players had analyzed this position overnight, and so Botvinnik quickly offered a draw. The forcing line continues: } 43... Nh5 44. b5 f4!? { The only attempt to make progress is trade off the kingside pawns and break through to h4. } 45. gxf4+ Nxf4+ 46. Nxf4 Kxf4 47. Kd4 Kg4 48. a5 Kxh4 49. a6 bxa6 50. bxa6 Kg3 51. Kc5 h5 52. Kc6 h4 53. Kb7 h3 54. Kxa7 h2 55. Kb8 h1=Q 56. a7 $10 { With a known draw. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.26"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E69"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Fianchetto Variation, Classical Main Line"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 6: Botvinnik - Tal, Fianchetto KID"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/0pkkseR6"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Arguably the most famous game of the match. This is the famous piece sacrifice game in the KID.

Before the game, Tal was preparing to play the KID as the last asymmetrical opening against Botvinnik's solid 1. d4 repertoire. }
1. c4 { The English. Tal wasn't sure exactly what Botvinnik had up his sleeve, but he eventually transposes directly into a KID proper with no move order tricks. } 1... Nf6 (1... e5!? { Tal briefly considered this move. }) 2. Nf3!? { Kills several options available to white. Certainly this move is less flexible than Nc3. } (2. Nc3 e5!? { The only reason that Nc3 might not be preferred is if black decides to commit to a reversed Sicilian. Against all other lines, Nc3 is strictly better than Nf3. }) 2... g6 3. g3!? { Botvinnik goes for the older variations of the KID with a kingside fianchetto after thinking for 3 minutes. Tal was more concerned with the Saemisch and Petrosian variations of the KID instead. } 3... Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. d4 (5. d3 { Taking on a more closed position. } 5... d5 $10 { The best way to play is an improved Grunfeld, but Tal doesn't have much experience in the Grunfeld. }) 5... d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7!? { Going for the good old KID with e5 next. A rare move with Tal that he was hoping would catch Botvinnik out. } (6... c5!? { Tal has had many games from this position. }) (6... Nc6!? { Tal has had many games from this position. }) 7. O-O e5 8. e4 { Botvinnik hasn't spent any time yet, so this is still part of his overall repertoire, if not specific prep against Tal. } 8... c6 { "The most flexible." } (8... exd4 { The more common way to play today, as recommended by Daniel Naroditsky. Tal believes this "gives white a well known edge and more freedom of play in the center and on the kingside." Agree with well-known edge. Disagree that white is playing on the kingside in most of these variations. } 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. h3 Re8 11. Re1 $14 { The most precise way to play gives black a little trouble. } 11... a5!? (11... Bd7!?) (11... h6!?)) 9. h3 { Preventing Ng4, but this move wastes a tempo. } (9. Be3!? { Botvinnik's preferred move. But } 9... Ng4!? 10. Bg5 Qb6 11. h3 exd4! 12. Na4 Qa6 13. hxg4 b5 14. Nxd4?! (14. Be7! { the modern improvement. } 14... bxa4 15. Bxd6 Re8 16. e5 $14 { Jussupow, Artur - Kasparov, Garry, 0-1, Linares 10th, 1992, https://lichess.org/RW5O87mG } { And black is suffering, with this starfish bishop dominating both rooks. }) 14... bxa4 15. Nxc6 Qxc6 16. e5 Qxc4 17. Bxa8 Nxe5 $10 { Botvinnik - Smyslov, 1954 led to an advantage for black. }) 9... Qb6?! { Tal has never played this move before. While playable, it's not actually that good if white knows exactly what they're doing. At the time, this was already an extremely rare move. } (9... exd4!? 10. Nxd4 Re8 11. Be3 Qa5?! 12. Qc2! $14) 10. d5?! { Played after 5 minutes. In some sense, this justifies black's queen placement. } (10. c5!! { Is probably the way to try and refute this line completely. } 10... dxc5 11. dxe5 Ne8 12. e6! fxe6 13. Ng5 Nc7?! (13... Ne5!? 14. f4 Nf7 15. Nxf7 Bd4+ 16. Kh2 Rxf7 17. e5 $14 { Shirov, Alexei - Kasparov, Garry, 1/2-1/2, Linares 11th, 1993, https://lichess.org/wPdnSKj9 }) 14. f4 $14 { Karpov, Anatoly - Nunn, John DM, 1-0, Amber-rapid 04th, 1995, https://lichess.org/qg3B5usr }) 10... cxd5 11. cxd5 Nc5 12. Ne1!? { "During the game, I thought this was a theoretical innovation." But actually this is following Petrosian - Shiyanovsky, in the 1957 USSR Championship. The idea is simply to exchange off the c5 knight. } (12. Re1!? $14 { Sveshnikov, Evgeny - Vaganian, Rafael A, 0-1, URS-ch47, 1979, https://lichess.org/vyBAk9aA }) (12. Nd2!? $14 { The main moves. } { Khotenashvili, Bela - Ju, Wenjun, 1/2-1/2, CHN Masters (Women) 2nd, 2012, https://lichess.org/wHi9HRGa }) 12... Bd7 13. Nd3 { 10 minutes from Botvinnik, following through on this obvious move. In fact, Tal shames Botvinnik for such time management.
"The text move is the most precise, but the time spent thinking about it proved that Botvinnik had not played competitively for a long time. Why was it necessary to waste ten minutes out of an allotted two and one-half hours to play the most obvious and surely the strongest continuation of the maneuver which was begun on the previous move? How many times have these very ten minutes been insufficient for a chessplayer to make a decision at the turning point of a game!" } 13... Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Rfc8!? { Played after nearly 20 minutes. Now both players have used 30 minutes total. Tal was figuring out which plan to go for.
"Partly for psychological reasons, I decided to open up play on the queenside, lull the vigilance of my opponent, and then carry out f5 at the right moment. It should be admitted that, although I had an idea about a sacrifice of the knight on f4, it was of course, still hazy." } (14... Nh5!? 15. Be3 Qd8 16. Qe2! { Tal's line prevents f5. But: } 16... Qe8! $10 { f5 is still coming next, and black is totally fine. }) (14... Ne8!? 15. Be3 Qd8 16. Rac1 f5 17. exf5 gxf5 18. f4 $10 { Tal admits this is a reasonable way to play. }) 15. Rb1?! (15. Be3?! Qxb2 $10 { hitting the knight on c3, thus gaining a tempo and preventing either rook from reaching b1. Black is fine here. }) (15. Qe2! $14 { More flexible. Now, the b2 pawn is over-protected (thus Be3 is prepared), while simultaneously preventing the Nh5+f5 plan. }) 15... Nh5 16. Be3 Qb4 (16... Qd8?! { "Not in the spirit of the position." } 17. Nb5 Bxb5 18. Qxb5 $14) 17. Qe2 { Preventing f5. Botvinnik admits that Rb1 was imprecise because white is down a tempo. } 17... Rc4?! { A real don't-try-this-at-home move played in only 6 minutes. Not only does it feel wrong (black's queen now has a responsibility defending the rook), but it is objectively wrong as well. Tal is interested in following through on his Nf4 idea. } 18. Rfc1!? { Bf1 is coming to smoke out the rook on c4. But there were faster moves available. } (18. Bf3! { Simple enough. The threat is Bxh5. } 18... Nf6!? (18... Bxh3?! 19. Rfc1 { Black's pieces are out of wack, and white is developing normally. } 19... Bd7!? (19... Nf6?! 20. a3 Qb3 21. g4! $16 { [%cal Gg1h2] }) 20. a3 Qb3 21. Bxh5 gxh5 22. Qxh5 $16) (18... f5?! 19. Bxh5 gxh5 20. a3 Qb3 21. Qxh5 $16) 19. a3! { Removing an attacker of e4. } 19... Qb3 20. Kg2 $16 { Black has been kicked back. }) 18... Rac8 { Doubling down on his all-out kingside assault after 16 more minutes. } 19. Kh2?! { Too slow. Botvinnik is preparing something (Bf3 or Bf1) that could already be played. } (19. Bf1! { Obviously best. } 19... f5!? { Tal's idea. } 20. exf5 Bxf5 { Anti-positional, but recapturing with the bishop gets a valuable tempo against the rook to use in going for the throat. } 21. Ra1 Nf4 22. gxf4 exf4 23. Bd2 $16 { With crazy complications to follow. }) (19. Bf3!? { Once again, this normal move is good too. }) 19... f5! { Both players have used exactly half their time - 1 hour and 15 minutes - to reach this critical position. } 20. exf5 Bxf5 21. Ra1 (21. a3 Qb3 22. Ne4 Rc2 23. Rxc2 Rxc2 24. Qd1 Nf4!? { "complications defy calculation" }) 21... Nf4!! { The infamous knight sacrifice. "Suffice it to say that all the other continuations are bad and if the knight sacrifice is incorrect, then a question mark should not be placed after black's 21st move but, say, after his 17th."
Indeed, that is correct. This whole conception is complicated, but overrated. } (21... Nf6!? { With g4 coming, Botvinnik probably assumed this was forced. } 22. g4 Bd7 23. a3 Qb3 $14 { And black has been kicked back. }) 22. gxf4 exf4 23. Bd2?! { "It is possible that there will subsequently be found a way to strengthen White's defense, but in this book it is by no means claimed that a detailed analysis could be given of every variation that might be encountered in the match. Its job is ot show the moves of the struggle through the eyes of one participating in the match. And from this point of view, I am sure the double-edged knight sacrifice on f4 was a correct decision." } (23. a3! { " 'a3 would have won the game.' A critical position arises after the move:" } 23... Qb3 24. Bxa7 { "Now white's extra piece can be locked out of the game with the move b6, while at the same time both of black's bishops are extraordinarily active and can go into action on either flank. White's queenside is likewise somewhat congealed and the king's protection is weak; thus the present positional compensation and the question of detailed analysis - will black be able to make use of this - is no longer ponderable." } 24... Be5 { Tal was going to continue in this manner. } 25. f3! (25. Kg1?! b6! { [%cal Gc8c7] } 26. Qd1? (26. a4!? { The engine move. } 26... R8c7 27. Bf1 (27. Ra3?! Qb4 28. Na2 Rxc1+! $19 { Compared to the f3 line, this is killer. }) 27... f3 28. Qe3 Rxa7 29. Bxc4 Qxc4 30. Qxf3 $10 { Black is down a lot of material, but white's pieces are scattered and there is definite compensation here. }) 26... Qxb2 27. Ra2 Rxc3! $19) (25. Bf3? { Tal believed this was the most interesting variation. } 25... Ra8! { For once, the bishop is already trapped - we don't need to go to further lengths to trap it. A classic case of broad not deep, even in analysis! } (25... b6? 26. Qd1?! { Tal's analysis once more goes for this interesting queen sacrifice. } (26. a4! { Once again the engine line shows a way to punish black's coordination. } 26... R8c7 27. Ra3 Qb4 28. Na2! $16) 26... Qxb2 27. Ra2 Rxc3 28. Rxb2 Rxc1 29. Qe2! (29. Qd2? Be4!! { This amazing refutation to Qd2 was pointed out by Tal. } 30. Bxe4?? (30. Kg2?! Bxf3+ 31. Kxf3 R8c3+ 32. Ke4 Rc4+ 33. Kf3 R1c3+ 34. Ke2 f3+ 35. Kd1 Bf4 $19) 30... f3+ 31. Qf4 Bxf4#) 29... R8c3! $10 { All Tal's analysis, after which black is totally fine. }) 26. Bb6!? Qxb6 27. Qxc4?? Qxf2+! 28. Bg2 f3+ 29. Kh1 fxg2#) 25... b6 26. Qf2? (26. Qd1? { Tal's analysis forced on this move. } 26... Qxb2 27. Ra2 Rxc3 28. Rxb2 Rxc1 29. Qd2 Bxb2 30. Qxb2 R8c2 31. Qd4 Re1 $10 { White should bail out and force OCBs with: } 32. Qxf4 Ree2 33. Qg3 Rxg2+ 34. Qxg2 Rxg2+ 35. Kxg2 b5 $10) (26. a4! { The engine move. } 26... R8c7!? (26... R4c7!? 27. Ra3 Qb4 28. Qb5! Qxb5 29. axb5 $18 { The bishops isn't getting trapped after all. }) (26... Rb4! { The engine line } 27. a5 bxa5 28. Nd1 $16 { After which white's bishop is finally freed. }) 27. Ra3 Qb4 28. Bb8! Rb7 29. Na2! $18 { The queen's tenuous defense of the rook is finally exploited. }) 26... Bd4 $17) (23. Bxa7?! Qa5 $15 { and the bishop is trapped. }) 23... Qxb2? { Played after 15 minutes. Indeed, this shows that Tal's Nf4 sacrifice was mostly intuitive - he was busy recalculating other lines even after sacrificing the knight. } (23... Be5! 24. f3! (24. Kg1?? Qxb2 25. Nd1?! (25. Rab1?! Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Qc2 27. Rc1 Qf5 28. Qf3 Qh5 $19) 25... Rxc1 $19) (24. Bf3?! Qxb2 25. Nd1 Qa3! 26. Rxc4 Rxc4 { Rc2 is a threat. } 27. Qxc4?! Qxf3 $19 { "Black's attack is irresistible." }) 24... Qxb2 25. Nd1! Qd4?! { Tal, for obvious reasons, wanted to keep queens on the board. } (25... Qxa1! 26. Rxa1 Bxa1 $10 { Amazingly, this material imbalance once again is black's best bet. The bishop will return to e5, and the two rooks will dominate on the 2nd rank. }) 26. Rxc4 Rxc4 27. Rc1 Rxc1 28. Bxc1 Qxd5 29. Bf1 $10 { "Black's three pawns do not outweight white's extra piece." }) 24. Rab1 (24. Nd1?! Qe5 $17) 24... f3!? { A clearance sacrifice to make the Be5+s of the world stronger. "Black had placed all of his hopes on this move." Unfortunately, with best play, black is simply lost. Really this points more to how bad Qxb2 was rather than to how strong/bad f3 is. } 25. Rxb2? { Played after 20 minutes. Botvinnik really wanted to trade queens and simply be up a piece. } (25. Bxf3! Bxb1 26. Rxb1 Qc2 27. Rc1!? (27. Be4!! { Flohr's recommendation. } 27... Rxe4 28. Nxe4!! (28. Qxe4? Be5+ $19 { Covering the fork on e6, so now Qxd2 is unstoppable. }) 28... Qxb1 (28... Be5+!? 29. Kg2 Qxb1 30. Nxd6! Bxd6 31. Qe6+ Kg7 32. Qd7+! $18 { With a much better endgame. Everything is falling with check. }) 29. Nxd6 Rf8 30. Qe6+ Kh8 31. Nf7+ Rxf7 32. Qxf7 Qf5 33. Qxf5 gxf5 34. Kg3! Be5+ 35. Bf4 $18) 27... Qb2!? (27... Qf5?! { Botvinnik wasn't sure if he had anything here, but missed Bxc8 in the following variation: } 28. Bg4! Qe5+ 29. Qxe5 Bxe5+ 30. f4! Rxc3 31. Bxc8! $18) 28. Rb1? $10 { Tal expected a GM draw. } (28. Bg4! { Both players misevaluated that black is completely lost here. } 28... Be5+ 29. Kg2 R8c7 30. Be6+ Kh8 31. Nd1 Qd4 32. Rxc4 Rxc4 33. Ne3 $18 { For once, black does not have an attack against white's king. In fact, it's the other way around. The minor pieces are dancing all around the rook here, which no longer has any infiltration squares on the c file. })) 25... fxe2 26. Rb3 Rd4! { "Black's clumsy rook suddenly finds colossal strength in the center of the board." While Botvinnik quickly hurried to exchange queens earlier as a way to remain up a clean piece, he clearly underestimated how strong black's pieces would be afterwards, well into the endgame. The pawn on e2 is a monster. } 27. Be1 { This sad move was played only 6 minutes later. Botvinnik has 20 minutes to reach the time control, but the position is already dire. The bishop pair is just too strong. } (27. Be3?! Rxc3 28. Rbxc3 Rd1 $19) 27... Be5+ 28. Kg1 Bf4?! { Not a bad move, but misses a faster win. "The noise in the auditorium had prompted the referees of the match to carry out their threat and move the game to a closed room [...] In any case, I am not used to playing in 'nomadic' conditions." } (28... Rxc3! { Missed by Tal during the game. } 29. Rbxc3 Rd1 30. Rc4 Bb2! $19 { the blockade is broken. }) 29. Nxe2 { For the rest of the game, Tal is playing way too quickly, and missing slightly cleaner wins. } (29. Ra1?! Rxc3 30. Rxc3 Rd1 $19) 29... Rxc1 30. Nxd4!? (30. Nxc1!? Rd1 $19) 30... Rxe1+ 31. Bf1 Be4 { And Tal has a winning material advantage on top of the positional dominance. } 32. Ne2 Be5 33. f4 Bf6 34. Rxb7!? (34. Kf2!? Rb1 $19) 34... Bxd5 35. Rc7 (35. Rxa7?? Rxe2 36. Bxe2 Bd4+ $19) 35... Bxa2 36. Rxa7 Bc4 (36... Rxe2?? 37. Ra8+ Kg7 38. Bxe2 $10) 37. Ra8+ Kf7?! (37... Kg7! 38. Re8!? (38. Ra7+!? Kh6 $19) 38... d5 $19 { Simple and strong. There is no stopping the d pawn. }) 38. Ra7+ Ke6 39. Ra3 { Black's king cannot enter, and so he has to resort to another winning maneuver. Tal spent 10 minutes on this next move, while his opponent had seconds remaining, just to ensure that the win was still in hand. } 39... d5 40. Kf2 Bh4+ 41. Kg2 Kd6 { Neither player wanted to call for an adjournment because both felt the game should continue to be played out at the insanely fast speed they had been playing the endgame so far. } 42. Ng3 { Finally there is no more pin. But the rook endgame is totally hopeless. } 42... Bxg3 43. Bxc4 dxc4 44. Kxg3 Kd5 45. Ra7 c3 46. Rc7 Kd4 { Here the game was adjourned with Botvinnik sealing a move. Obviously, this is completely hopeless - the passed c pawn wins the game. } 47. Rd7+ $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } { The sealed move, but white had already resigned rather than show up to play. } 0-1


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.29"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B18"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 7: Tal - Botvinnik, Classical Caro Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/U8Eg4E2D"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ After a further two days (one rest day and one free day due to the instant resignation before the adjournment resumption), Tal and Botvinnik came together again to face off in the Caro Kann. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. N1e2 { A repetition of the last game. This time around, Tal was already committing to sacrificing a piece on e6. } 6... Nd7!? { A deviation from game 5, played after 12 minutes. The idea is to break immediately with e5, rather than defend potential sacrifices on e6. } (6... Nf6! 7. Nf4!? (7. h4!? h6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4 e6 10. O-O Bd6! $10 { Being the alternate way to play this. } { Christiansen, Johan-Sebastian - Wojtaszek, R., 0-1, World Rapid 2021, https://lichess.org/m345fRKG }) 7... Nbd7 8. Bc4 e5 $10 { is the modern approach to this position. } { Tiviakov, Sergei - Asrian, Karen, 1/2-1/2, Groningen Festival, 1998, https://lichess.org/NTjf1Mtn }) 7. h4 (7. Nf4?! e5 { shows black's idea. } 8. Nxg6 hxg6 9. dxe5 Nxe5 $10) 7... h6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4!? { Tal prepares his typical piece layout in this variation of the Caro, with violent intentions on e6 and/or f7. } (9. Bd3!? { Potentially this is a better way forward though. } 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3! { is the best recapture. White has a typical lead in development from the Caro Kann classical variations, and e5 is stopped. } (10. Nxd3?! $10 { Tal's idea to stop the e5 break. But this is clearly nothing for white. }) 10... e6 $14 (10... e5? 11. Ng6!! fxg6?? 12. Qxg6+ Ke7 13. Nf5# { The point. })) 9... e5 { The point of Botvinnik's play so far. } (9... Ngf6?! 10. O-O e6 11. Re1 $16 { And white is definitely going to be sacrificing on e6 next. } { [%cal Gc4e6,Gf4e6] }) 10. Qe2!? { Not really bad, but Botvinnik comes up with a nice retort to avoid Tal's sharpest attempts. } (10. Nd3!? { Tal's suggested improvement - sacrificing a pawn again for initiative. } 10... Qe7! { The engine "refutes" this idea by not taking the pawn and playing this artificial looking move. Hilariously, this is identical to what Botvinnik played in the game! White cannot castle without losing the h pawn and cannot take advantage of the bad queen placement. } (10... exd4?! { Opening the e file before you could possibly castle is not best. } 11. O-O! $14 { Tal's line: } 11... Ngf6 12. Nh5 Nxh5 13. Qxh5 Qf6 14. Re1+ Be7 15. Qe2 Qxh4? 16. Bf4? Bxd3 17. cxd3 $10 { where black's king remains in the center. This analysis was done after game 7, after which the variation was not repeated.
But this is another case of Tal going too deep instead of broad. As always, there are critical improvements instantly in the variation that flip the eval completely on its head. }) 11. dxe5 (11. O-O?! Qxh4 $10 { and there's no way to open the e file. }) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Be3 Bb4+ 14. Kf1 Nf6 $10) 10... Qe7! { Forcing the position into the endgame. } 11. dxe5 Qxe5 { The point of Botvinnik's last move. And yet this logical recapture took nearly 20 minutes. Once more, Botvinnik shows that he's impractical with the meta aspects of competitive chess. } (11... Nxe5?! 12. O-O O-O-O 13. Bb3 $16 { with Be3 coming, "white's edge in development would be so good that it would warrant an attack." }) 12. Be3 Bc5 { Botvinnik correctly is forcing more trades. But this move required another 20 minutes. He's already spent more than an hour only 6 moves into new territory... } 13. Bxc5 (13. O-O-O?! Bxe3+ 14. fxe3 Ngf6 $15 { "Black quietly brings his king to a safe position and, controlling e5 and the half-open e file, gradually seizes the initiative." }) 13... Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2!? { "A provocative, but hackneyed move." Except this is definitely better than Tal's suggestion. } (14. Ngxe2!? Nxc5 15. O-O-O Nf6 16. Nd4 O-O $10 { There's no lead in development or pawn structure imbalance in this equal position. }) 14... Nxc5 15. Rhe1 { Hilariously, Tal himself forgot that he had reached this exact position by transposition 5 years ago in a game leading up to the USSR Championship. } 15... Nf6 16. b4 Ncd7!? { A safer continuation. } (16... Nce4!? $10 { Ilivitsky's continutation: https://lichess.org/lKtRoznh }) 17. Kf1+!? (17. Kd2+!? { Ragozin's suggestion. } 17... Kf8 18. h5 Nb6!? 19. Bb3 a5 20. a3 a4 21. Ba2 Rd8+ 22. Kc1 Nbd5 $10 { "Black easily frees himself with Nxf4 and g5." I don't know about that suggestion, but it is true that black is not down in development, and the h8 rook can quickly get into the game. }) 17... Kf8 18. Bb3 g5! { "Unquestionably the correct continuation." Black is preparing Kg7 with tempo. } (18... a5!? { The obvious move that many commentators suggested. } 19. c3 a4 20. Bd1 $10 { This is playable too, in combination with a quick g5, as in the game. }) 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. Nh3 { The knight is bad on h3, but at least this forces the rook to have to babysit the g pawn. } 20... Rg8 (20... g4?! 21. Nf4 $14 { If white doesn't have something immediately, giving up the f4 square for the knight makes no positional sense. }) 21. Red1!? { Avoiding trades, but now the a1 rook lacks prospects. } (21. Rad1!? { The strongest move, but Tal was trying to avoid trading rooks after the obvious: } 21... Re8 22. Rxe8+ Kxe8 { Ke7 cannot be prevented, and so why would white be better in this endgame? Still, there's no need to instantly agree to a repetition after Tal's suggested line: } 23. Re1+?! (23. a3!?) (23. Ne2!?) (23. Ng1!?) 23... Kf8 24. Rd1 Ke7 25. Re1+ Kf8 $10) (21. c4?! c5! $15 { embarrasses the b3 bishop. }) 21... a5 22. bxa5 (22. a3?! a4 23. Bc4 Bxc2 $17) 22... Rxa5 23. Rd6 { Preparing to double on the d file. The rook cannot be touched by the minor pieces because of black's superfluous knights. } 23... Ke7 24. Rad1 Re5!? { Another 20 minute think by Botvinnik. He now only has 30 minutes to make 15 moves. However, Tal was impressed with this move, covering checks on the e file. } (24... Nc5!? { Tempting, but black doesn't get an edge here. } 25. R6d2 Nxb3 26. Re1+! Kf8 27. axb3 $10) (24... Rd5!? 25. R6xd5 (25. Bxd5?! cxd5! { And the rook on d6 is trapped. } 26. R6xd5 Nxd5 27. Rxd5 f6 $10 { transposes to the main line }) 25... Nxd5 26. Bxd5 cxd5 27. Rxd5 f6 $10 { Black's bishop is slightly better than either white knight. }) (24... Rc5?! 25. R6d2! $10 { Re1+ is coming and the rook on c5 does nothing. }) 25. Nh5!? { "This sudden attack by the cavalry should not get white anywhere. However, it had been prepared with several other previous moves, and now there is nothing better to be advised." } (25. Ng1!? $10 { Maybe it's just time to fix the worst-placed piece. Nf3 or N1e2 is coming. }) 25... Bg6?! { Botvinnik saw that the bishop was loose after a possible sequence kicking off with Rxd7 because Nf6+ hits the undefended bishop. So within one minute, he simply defended his bishop. But he missed that Nf6+ also hits the undefended rook on g8, so this move by itself doesn't address white's "threat." } (25... Nxh5?? 26. Rxd7+ Kf8 27. Rxf7+ $18 { The point. }) (25... Bf5!? 26. Nxf6 Nxf6 27. Nxg5! Bxc2! (27... Rxg5?! 28. f4! $14) 28. Bxc2 Rexg5 29. g3 $10 { Tal expected this line during the game. }) (25... Rh8! { Tal correctly also identified the strongest move in the game - taking the sting out of an eventual Nf6+ which no longer hits a rook on g8 or the undefended h7 bishop. } 26. f4?! { Tal wanted to lash out in order to finally free the h3 knight. } (26. f3!? Bg6 27. Nxf6 Nxf6 28. R6d2 $10 { The engine path to equality. Nf2 is coming to prevent Rh1+ and g4. }) 26... gxf4 27. N5xf4 Bf5! $15 { But once again the knight is stuck on h3, and black is starting to create threats. }) 26. Rxd7+! { The threat with white's last move is revealed. } 26... Nxd7 27. Rxd7+ Kxd7 28. Nf6+ Kd6 29. Nxg8 { If the g8 knight can return to the game before black gets queenside counterplay, then white is better. White has endgame odds in case black does not generate enough dynamic counterplay (not Botvinnik's strong suit). For now, though the position is roughly balanced. } 29... Rc5 { Going after c2 is obvious and correct. } 30. Nh6 f6!? { Defends the pawn, but loses a tempo. } (30... Ke7! { This simply retreating move might be the best option for black. White's knights are somewhat dominated on the side of the board again, and it's not clear how to free them. } 31. Ng4?! (31. Ke2!? Bxc2 32. Kd2 Bxb3 33. axb3 $10) 31... Bxc2! 32. Bxc2 Rxc2 33. Nxg5 Rxa2 $15 { The queenside pawns are running very quickly here. }) 31. Ng4 Bxc2 { Trading pawns brings the game closer to a draw, but this line requires serious precision. } (31... f5?! { Tal thought this was the most complicated way forward. } 32. Nh6! { The engine move that Tal underestimated. Now g5 is directly hit. } (32. Ne3?! { Tal was planning to go this way, but now white loses all coordination after: } 32... f4! 33. Nc4+ Ke7 $10 { But black is threatening Bxc2 next, so white still needs to play precisely. }) 32... f4 33. Ke2! Bxc2 34. Nf7+! Ke7 35. Nfxg5 $16 { There's still a lot of game to play here, but at least white's knights are finally dancing on the kingside. }) 32. Nxf6 Bxb3?! { Trading off the bishops makes the a (now b) pawn more accessible. But losing the bishop controlling e4 and h7 means the knights are finally no longer dominated. In fact, they instantly spring into motion. Tal believes that this is now winning for white with best play, but the engine shows that black has hidden resources, as always. } (32... Bf5! $10 { The correct way to play. Once more, both knights remain dominated and the g pawn is untouchable. } 33. Nxg5?? (33. g4!? Bb1 $10 { No progress for white. }) (33. Ke1!? Ke5! 34. Nh5 Bg4 35. Ng3 Kd4 $10 { Black is making progress, and white is just showing how offside the knights truly are. }) 33... Bd3+ 34. Ke1 Rxg5 $19 { Up an exchange and easily winning since the f6 knight still remains dominated. }) 33. axb3 Rb5 34. Nxg5! { The g5 knight is immune due to the fork, and so finally 20. Nh3 has been justified. The g and f pawns are about to be the heros of the game. } 34... Rxb3? { The final losing move, played instantly. } (34... Ke5!! { For one move, black can centralize the king with tempo, and prevent the f pawn from cementing the knight on g5. Obviously, Tal doesn't mention any of the following. } 35. Nh5! (35. Nfe4?! { The superfluous knights can do no harm to black's position. } 35... Rxb3 $10) 35... Rxb3 36. g4 { White has a nice wall on the kingside, but now black is in time to try and race white: } 36... c5 37. f4+ Kd4! 38. f5!? (38. Ke2!? Rb2+ 39. Kf3 Rb3+ 40. Ke2 Rb2+ $10 { There's no way to escape the checks without giving black mating nets or c1=Q with check. }) 38... c4 39. f6!? (39. Nf4!? c3 40. Nge6+ Ke5 41. Nd3+ Kf6 42. g5+ Kxf5 43. Nd4+ Kxg5 44. Nxb3 $10 { White no longer has mating material }) 39... c3 40. Ke1!? (40. f7?? c2 41. f8=Q c1=Q+ $19 { The race ends poorly for white. }) 40... Rb1+ 41. Kf2 c2 42. Nf3+ Ke4 43. Ng3+ Kd5 44. f7 c1=Q 45. f8=Q $10 { Amazingly, the knights control the checks, and so white is still able to draw this. Perhaps white remains the one pushing here, but this is sure to end in perpetual. }) 35. f4! { Pushing a pawn and preventing Ke5 to distract white's knights? Tal only spent seconds coming up with this only-move. } (35. g4? Ke5! 36. Nh5 c5 $10 { Black's dominant king position should not be allowed. }) 35... Rb1+?! { Botvinnik spent half of his remaining time to play this move which simply brings white's king up the board. It is already clear that white is winning the race. } (35... Ra3!? { This is the better attempt, preventing white's king from getting up in the endgame, but even so white is winning: } 36. Nfe4+ Kd5?! (36... Ke7 37. f5 b5 38. f6+ Kf8 39. Nd6 $18 { Nh7+ is coming and the f pawn promotes. }) 37. f5 $18 { The f pawn promotes. }) 36. Ke2 Rb2+ 37. Kf3 Rb3+ 38. Kg4 Rb2 39. g3 b5 { "Black's pawns also begin their advance, but it is too late." } 40. Nfe4+ Kd5!? { Black abandons any attempt to stop the f pawn and puts all of his hope in queening one of his queenside pawns. } (40... Ke7!? 41. f5 $18 { As we've already seen, f6+ followed by getting control of f8 leads to promotion next. }) 41. f5 b4 { Tal considered adjourning the game here, but decided to play on as he saw that the b pawn alone cannot queen. } 42. f6 Ra2 { Necessary - in order to sacrifice for the f pawn. } 43. f7 Ra8 44. Nh7! b3 (44... Kxe4?! 45. Nf6+ Kd3 46. Ne8 $18 { The rook can no longer sacrifice for the f pawn. } { [%cal Gf7f8] }) 45. Nd2 b2 { The d2 knight stops the b pawn, and the other knight prepares to queen the f pawn. White will eventually win with the remaining g pawn. } 46. Kf3! { Of course. Preventing black's king from reaching d3, which would disturb white's queenside setup. } 46... Kd4 47. Ke2! { Again, preventing Kd3. Now white's knight can always remain on d2 and there is no preventing f8=Q. } 47... c5!? { Played after 30 minutes. Botvinnik knew he was lost, but decided to really give the position a deep think just to see if there were even any remaining tricks. There aren't.
Meanwhile, Tal still hasn't spent more than 10 minutes since move 30. } (47... Kc3!? 48. f8=Q Rxf8 49. Nxf8 Kc2 50. Nd7 b1=Q 51. Nxb1 Kxb1 52. g4 $18 { The g pawn wins easily. }) 48. f8=Q Rxf8 49. Nxf8 c4 50. Ne6+ Kd5 (50... Kc3 51. g4 $18) 51. Nf4+ Kd4 52. Nb1 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { Black's pawns are blockaded, so white will simply promote the g pawn next. Finally Botvinnik resigned, going down 0-3 to Tal in only 7 games. } 52... c3!? { The only way to try and play on: } 53. Kd1 Ke4 54. Ne2 Ke3 55. Nbxc3 $18 { White easily holds onto the g pawn and the defensive setup has not been perturbed. } 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.03.31"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E10"]
[Opening "Indian Defense: Anti-Nimzo-Indian"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 8: Botvinnik - Tal, Modern Benoni"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/oUUtmywP"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Both Tal and his trainer were happy to be up 3 points in the match going into round 8. But they also both felt that Tal was not in form yet. In retrospect, Tal points to these next two games as confidence boosters going into the second half of the match, even though he lost both.

Going into this game, Tal decided to try the Nimzo Indian, having found an interesting idea that Taimanov had overlooked in a recent monograph on the Saemisch Nimzo-Indian. That idea would only appear in game 14 of the match. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3!? { "A small surprise. Botvinnik rarely avoids playing the Nimzo-Indian." } 3... c5 { After 2 minutes, Tal opts for his favorite Benoni instead. } 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 g6?! { This well-known mistake also works in the 3. Nf3 Benonis too. } 6. Nc3?! { Not the most precise. Botvinnik is letting Tal transpose into the main line Benonis. } (6. d6! Qb6? (6... Bg7! 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 Re8 9. Bd3 $16 { This is black's best. The d6 pawn is a huge pain here. }) 7. e4! Bxd6!? (7... Nxe4?? 8. Qd5 Nf6 9. Qe5+ $18) (7... Bg7?! 8. Nc3! O-O 9. e5 $18 { And the knight has no good square to jump to. }) 8. e5 Bxe5 9. Nxe5 $18) 6... Bg7 7. Bg5 { Trying to transpose into game 2 of the match. } (7. d6! $16 { Once again is correct. }) 7... O-O 8. e3 (8. d6?! { Finally, this move hits with a lot less oomph. } 8... h6 9. Bh4 b5 10. e3!? (10. Nxb5? Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Ne4 $17 { Hitting c3 and d6. Black is better. }) 10... a6 $10) (8. e4!? Re8 9. Bd3 (9. Nd2?? Nxe4! 10. Bxd8 Nxc3+ $19) 9... d6 10. h3! { Prevents Bg4, and prepares to castle. This transposes to the main lines in the Nf3 Benonis, after which white has a slight advantage. }) (8. Nd2! { The most precise setup. } 8... Re8 9. e3 $14 { Transposes. }) 8... Re8 (8... d6 $14 { "More flexible" }) 9. Nd2! { As always, this thematic reroute to c4 is strong. White prevents Bg4 directly, as well as preparing e4 on a good day. } 9... d6 { A sensible move in the Benoni. Tal prepares to simply develop the queenside. } (9... Re5?! { Tal's original intention is typically crazy-town. } 10. Bf4!? (10. Bh4!? { Tal rejected Re5 because of this move. } 10... g5?! 11. Bg3 Rxd5?! 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Nc4 $18 { Yeah this is again horrible for black. }) 10... Rxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 { "Giving black a pawn for the exchange in a good position, in view of the king's bishop range." Except this is just horrible for black after: } 12. Bd6! $16 { The LSB will remain on c8 for the foreseeable future, and white is just up an exchange. Nc4 is coming to lock in that d6 bishop. }) 10. Be2!? { Botvinnik seeks to slowly finish development before going for the d6 weakness. } (10. Nc4!? { Possibly the most critical move. } 10... Na6! { Objectively best. Black prepares b5 the normal way. } (10... Qd7!? { Tal's prepared move. } 11. Qf3! (11. Bf4?! { Hits d6 directly, but there's a snag. } 11... Nh5! 12. Qf3 (12. Bxd6? b5! $19) 12... Nxf4 13. Qxf4 Rd8 $10) 11... Ng4!? { With Ne5 coming, Tal thought he had real compensation, but he had missed: } 12. a4! Ne5 13. Nxe5 Rxe5 14. Bb5 Qc7 15. Bf4 $16 { And the rook is trapped. }) 11. Be2 Nc7 12. a4 Qe7 $14 { b6+Rb8+a6+b5 is coming. Black's queenside counterplay is slow, but inevitable. }) 10... a6!? (10... Na6!? 11. O-O Nc7 $14 { Tal notes this other line in his book and calls it "a matter of taste." }) 11. a4 Nbd7 { Now that Nb5 has been ruled out fully, black can develop harmoniously with Ne5 coming next. } 12. O-O Qc7?! { Yes, black is out of the pin. But the queen is basically always awful on this square in the Benoni - it's only job is preparing c4. } 13. Qc2 (13. e4! $16 { "White's most active move is linked with a loss of tempo. And this is not so simply resolved psychologically." Except you could point to black's waste of a move in Qc7 as a justification for white this move is now perfectly playable. }) 13... Nb6!? { Played after 10 minutes. Clearly, Tal is wriggling here, as this is not a normal setup he's going for. "A knight is always badly posted on this square" - Tarrasch. } (13... Rb8!? $16 { A more normal move, even if this doesn't yet prepare b5. }) 14. Bf3!? { As always, Botvinnik goes for a quieter continuation. } (14. e4! { "It would have been necessary to continue:" } 14... Nfxd5! 15. exd5 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 Rxe2 17. Bh6?! (17. Nc4! Bf5 18. Bh6 f6 19. Ne3! $16 { In this position, white can go for awkward rook, rather than the king, in actual fact. Black is reeling with awkward pieces everywhere. }) 17... Re5 $10 { Black's king is vulnerable, but Nxd5 is coming with adequate compensation. }) 14... c4?! { Played after 30 minutes. } (14... Re5?! { Tal was considering another artificial rook lift. } 15. Bf4 Rf5 16. g4?! (16. Nde4! $16 { Tal found the refutation to his awkward rook lift during the game - now d6 cracks. A very nice example of calculating broad, not deep. }) 16... Rxf4! 17. exf4 Bxg4 $10 { Tal successfully refuted g4 during those 30 minutes. }) (14... h6! { Correct play requires some insanely precise calculations not considered by Tal. } 15. Bh4 Bf5 { If the queen has to move, then black is totally fine. } 16. e4 g5! { I'm sure that Tal didn't consider this move during the game. } 17. Bxg5! (17. Bg3?! Bg6 $10) 17... hxg5 18. exf5 g4 19. a5 gxf3 20. axb6 Qxb6 21. Nxf3 $14 { Black is down a pawn, with a wreckage of a kingside. But c4 and b5 is inevitably coming, all of black's pieces are on good squares, and the f5 and d5 pawns can be weak. }) (14... Nfxd5? 15. Nxd5? (15. a5! $18 { "most simply refutes this idea" }) 15... Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Re5! $10) (14... Nbxd5? 15. Bxd5! Nxd5 16. Nxd5 $18 { There is no time for Re5. }) 15. Bxf6! { Instantly wins a pawn. Once more, Botvinnik chooses the responsible continuation. } (15. a5!? { Tal suggested another strong move that might even be better than winning a pawn. } 15... Nbd7 16. Qa4! b5!? (16... Ne5? 17. Bxf6! Bd7 18. Bxe5! Bxa4 19. Bxg7 $16 { Tal correctly identified that white is much better here, with 3 pieces for the queen. }) 17. axb6 Nxb6 18. Qc6 Qxc6 19. dxc6 $16 { "with a dangerous passed pawn." }) 15... Bxf6 16. a5 Nd7 17. Nce4!? (17. Qa4!? Qd8 18. Nxc4 Nc5 $16 { "getting rather active play for the pawn, as in the game." Still, a pawn is a pawn, and this gives black less than in the game. }) 17... Be5 18. Qxc4 (18. Nxc4?! b5! 19. axb6 Nxb6 $10 { "With equalizing counterplay along the c file." }) 18... Qd8 { Of course, black keeps the queen on the board. Tal saw this coming when he played c4. White has less here than in the 17. Qa4 line because white's superfluous knights in the center of the board remain a little awkward, and the queen on c4 is misplaced. } 19. Qa2!? { Getting out of any b5 tempi. Although this is a less responsible square to put the queen on given the fact that it is now a one-dimensional piece. } (19. Qb4!? b5 20. axb6 Nxb6 $14) (19. Qb3!? b5 20. axb6 Nxb6 21. Rfc1 $14) 19... f5? { "The beginning of an unjustified plan," played in only 7 minutes as a knee jerk reaction to white placing his queen in Siberia voluntarily. } (19... b5! { Clearly correct. } 20. axb6!? (20. Rac1!? $14 { Tal thought this was better for white, and it is, but that doesn't mean b5 shouldn't have been played. }) 20... Nxb6 $14) (19... Nf6?! { Tal gave this move an exclamation mark. } 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Nc4 Bh3!? 22. Nxe5?! (22. Qa4! $16 { Black has no threats, and white has time to connect the queen with the kingside next. }) 22... Rxe5 { Threatening Qxf3. } 23. Kh1 Rae8 $14 { Tal believed he had compensation for the pawn in an attack like this. }) 20. Nc3 g5 21. Nc4 g4 22. Be2 Qf6 { Going all-out for a kingside attack. } 23. Na4! { I believe this move by Botvinnik deserves an exclamation mark. He prevents Tal's attack by doing nothing at all. There is no attack. } 23... Kh8 24. g3!? { A bit unnecessary, but both players were considering Bxh2+ ideas. } (24. Rac1!? Bxh2+! { Tal was calculating this insane variation. } 25. Kxh2 Rxe3! 26. Nxe3 Qh6+ 27. Kg1 g3 28. fxg3?! (28. Bh5! { The clean refutation to the sacrifice. } 28... gxf2+ 29. Rxf2 Qxe3 30. Qc4 $18) 28... Qxe3+ 29. Kh2 Qh6+ 30. Bh5 Nf6 { "with good attacking prospects" } 31. Rc4! $18 { Except white is crushing here, with Rh4 coming next. }) 24... h5 25. f4?! { After 10 minutes, Botvinnik plays to simply shut down the kingside completely. } (25. f3?! h4 26. fxg4 hxg3 27. hxg3 Qg6 { "Black opens up the position on the kingside." And yet once more white is totally fine if he simply brings more pieces to the kingside only now that black has gone crazy. } 28. Qb1! $16 { [%cal Gb1g6] }) (25. Nab6! { Black doesn't have any threats. Best is to simply improve the pieces. } 25... Nxb6 26. Nxb6 Rb8 27. Rac1 h4 28. Qa4 $18) 25... Bd4?! { Keeping pieces on the board, but white has a strong response planned. } (25... gxf3!? 26. Rxf3 h4 27. Raf1 $16 { Black's best, after which white is totally fine. }) 26. Qa3! (26. exd4?? Qxd4+ 27. Kh1 Qxd5+ $10 { White cannot escape the perpetual without sacrificing a piece. }) 26... Rb8 { "It is very difficult to decide on such a passive move when all the preceding play had been conducted on the kingside." Tal prophylactically gets out of Nb6, allowing him to keep more pieces on the board instead.
However, this move took him a further 30 minutes to come up with. Both players are now in time pressure, and there are still 14 moves to go until the time control. } (26... Bxe3+? 27. Nxe3 Qd4 28. Kf2! $18) 27. Nab6?! { Tal shows several lines that would have won immediately. } (27. exd4! { Simply wins. } 27... Qxd4+ 28. Rf2 Rxe2 29. Qc3! Qxc3 30. bxc3 $18 { White is not up any material, but black is hopelessly passive, and white is winning on the queenside against black's trapped LSB and rook. }) (27. Rad1!? Ba7 28. Nab6 $18 { Also strong. Black's queenside pieces are shut out of the game entirely. }) 27... h4 28. Rad1!? (28. exd4!? $16 { Still wins because of the queenside bind. }) 28... Bxb6 29. axb6 Nc5 30. gxh4? { A natural move, since Qxh4 is impossible, but it throws away the advantage simply because black's queenside pieces get an opportunity to escape their bind. } (30. Rc1! { Is apparently the only move, with the idea that } 30... Bd7 31. Nxd6! { is now playable. } 31... Qxd6 32. Qxc5 Qxc5 33. Rxc5 $16) 30... Bd7! (30... Qxh4? 31. Rd2 g3 32. Bf3 $18 { Nxd6 is coming, and black has no attack. }) 31. Qc3?! { The queen trade is forced, but now black's queenside pieces have escaped their bind. White has 3 minutes left on his clock. } (31. b4!? Ne4 32. Qa1 $14 { A better way to trade queens, since now the knight no longer has the c5 square to rely upon. }) 31... Qxc3 32. bxc3 Bb5 33. Rfe1 Ne4!? (33... Bxc4! 34. Bxc4 Kg7 { A good knight vs bad bishop endgame. It's not completely obvious that white has nothing here, but it's quite important that there are no pawn breaks in the position. } 35. h5!? (35. h3?! gxh3 36. Kh2 Rh8 37. Kxh3?! Kf6 $17 { If white isn't careful, there are mates on the h file. }) (35. e4?! Nxe4 36. Bd3 Kf6 37. Bxe4 fxe4 38. c4 Rbc8 39. Rd4 Kf5 40. Kf2 Kxf4 $15 { If anything, black is the one pushing here. }) 35... Rh8 36. h3! gxh3 37. Be2! Rbe8 38. Bf3 $10 { It feels like white might have some winning chances here, even though this is 0.0. }) 34. Rc1?? { With 3 minutes on the clock, Botvinnik blunders trying to make a safe, fast move. } (34. Rd4! Nxc3?! (34... Re7! $14 { White remains in a sort of bind, and the threat of Nxc3 may hang over white's head for a while. Especially in time pressure, this is not an easy position to convert. }) 35. Bd3! { The knight on c3 is suddenly misplaced, and black needs to scramble in order to avoid being trapped. } 35... Bxc4! 36. Rxc4! (36. Bxc4?! Kg7! 37. Bd3 Kf6 $10) 36... Nxd5 37. Rd4 Nxb6 38. Rxd6 $16 { Bxf5 is coming next, and the bishop is no longer "bad." White retains real winning chances. }) 34... Rbc8?? { "I made the last move instantaneously - as if seized by the time pressure rhythm of my opponent. I had formerly seen that I would win the exchange, but I should have taken a little time to think; then I would have come up with the absolutely correct idea: Rec8! Black, as in the game, would win the exchange, but maintain his pawn on b7, after which white's position would immediately become hopeless. Here it is: the hypnotic power of 'natural' moves! It is interesting to note that the winning move Rec8 was only later found at home that evening." } (34... Rec8! 35. Na5?! (35. Nxd6!? Nxd6 $19 { There are three pawns for the piece here, but all of them are blockaded, and so black will have little difficulty converting here. }) 35... Bxe2 36. Rxe2 Nxc3 37. Rxc3 Rxc3 $19 { There is nothing going on here. White's knight is simply about to be kicked back with Rc5 since b7 is firmly defended. }) 35. Na5! Bxe2 36. Rxe2 Nxc3 { The e2 rook cannot move anywhere without falling for Ne2+! } 37. Rxc3! { Winning an important tempo. } (37. Rec2?? Ne2+! 38. Rxe2 Rxc1+ $19 { Black wins the exchange under much better circumstances - b7 can be defended next. }) 37... Rxc3 38. Nxb7 { The d pawn is defenseless. Tal thought for 6 minutes, still thinking he had winning chances, and proceeded to lose the game. } 38... Rexe3?? (38... Rb8! { "It was necessary to continue" this way. } 39. Nxd6 Rd3 { both passed pawns are stopped, and white actually needs to find some good moves to not slip into a lost position again. } 40. Rc2! (40. Nxf5? Rxd5 41. e4 Rb5! { Tal underestimated this move during his analysis. Black can fight for a win here! } (41... Rxf5?? { Both impractical and objectively wrong. } 42. exf5 Rxb6 $18 { He thought this was a drawn endgame, but in fact it's lost! }) (41... Rd1+ 42. Kf2 Rxb6 $10 { A simple way to play. }) 42. e5 a5! { A sort of zugzwang. } 43. h5!? (43. Ra2!? R8xb6 $19) 43... R5xb6 44. e6 a4 45. e7 Re8! 46. Rd2 a3 47. Rd8 Rb8 $19) 40... Rxb6 41. Nxf5 Rxd5 42. Rc8+ Kh7 43. Rc7+ Kh8 44. Rc8+ $10 { Correct play. The position is drawn. }) 39. Rxe3 Rxe3 40. Nxd6 Rd3 { Time control has been reached. Botvinnik considered this position for 30 minutes before sealing his move for adjournment: } (40... Kg8!? { "Significantly strong, but black was under the impression that all was in order." Yet it too is lost after: } 41. Nc4! Rd3!? (41... Rb3!? 42. d6 Kf7 43. h5 $18 { Again, the black forces cannot stop all three passed pawns. }) 42. b7 Rb3 43. Na5! Rb1+ 44. Kf2 Kf7 45. h5 $18 { The rook can only stop one passed pawn, and the king cannot stop the remaining wide peepos. }) 41. Nf7+! $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { A decisive transposition of moves. Now h7 is off-limits to black. Once Tal saw that this move was on the board, he instantly resigned the next day. } (41. b7?? { Tal's main considerations at the board. } 41... Rb3 42. Nf7+ Kh7! 43. Nd8 a5! 44. d6 a4! 45. d7 a3! 46. Ne6 a2! 47. d8=Q a1=Q+ $19 { Tal calculated this line during the game and felt confident. }) 41... Kh7?! (41... Kg7!? 42. b7! Rb3 43. Nd8! a5!? (43... Kf8!? 44. h5! Ke8 45. h6! Kxd8 46. h7 Rxb7 47. h8=Q+ $18 { Just in time. }) 44. d6 a4 45. d7 a3 46. Ne6+! $18 { Because Ne6 hits with check, white is queening first. }) 42. d6! $18 { As opposed to the line starting with 47. b7??, now the two queenside pawns cannot be stopped. } 42... a5?! 43. b7 Rb3 44. d7 $18 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.02"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B18"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 9: Tal - Botvinnik, Classical Caro Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/HpD3ZpQy"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Tal believes Botvinnik was extremely inspired after the last game, both because he won it but also because of the style of his victory. Rather than grinding down Tal, Botvinnik won the game in a tactical melee where Tal is supposed to be stronger than him.

Entering the 9th game, Tal once more tried to play his piece sacrifice in the Caro Kann... this time "successfully." }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. N1e2 { A repeat of this unstandard knight sortie. } 6... Nf6!? { Finally, Botvinnik takes up the most well-tested variation. More flexible than e6. } 7. h4!? { Trying to trap the bishop gains the necessary tempo to play Nf4 next. } (7. Nf4?! e5! 8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Ng4 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Ne4 Nxe5 $10 { White gets nothing here, as confirmed in Fischer - Foguelman, 1960. }) 7... h6 8. Nf4 Bh7 9. Bc4!? { This has become something of a main line, after Tal popularized this variation. In modern times, this is yet another 0.0 way to play. } (9. c3!? { I'm sure this passive move never even crossed Tal's mind during the game or analysis. But there is a point, and it might very well be white's strongest choice in this opening variation. } 9... e6 10. Ngh5 Nbd7 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Nxd3! $14 { Focusing in on the c5 and e5 breaks is another way to play. While white doesn't have much here because of the loss of tempi, black still needs to equalize white's space advantage to claim equality. This is a tempo up from the engine's suggestions on move 11. } { Demchenko, A. - Iljiushenok, I., 1-0, TCh-TUR Super League 2019, https://lichess.org/pTDpGR3P }) 9... e6 (9... e5?! { Unjustified in view of white's active setup. } 10. dxe5 Qxd1+!? (10... Qa5+!? 11. c3 Qxe5+ 12. Nfe2! $14 { Bf4 is coming next, and white has a terrible lead in development, even having to retreat the knight once. The bishop on c4 in particular is a great piece. }) 11. Kxd1 Ng4 12. Re1! Nxf2+ 13. Ke2 Ng4 14. e6! $16 { White's lead in development proves decisive, even without the queens. } { Corrales Jimenez, Fidel - Pujols, Carlos, 1-0, CUB-ch sf, 2006, https://lichess.org/aMAHCpzJ }) 10. O-O Bd6! { Absolutely correct. Black practically forces white to sacrifice on e6, or allow soothing trades. } 11. Nxe6?! { "After the game, he remarked that this sacrifice would have been very dangerous in the fifth game, that is to say, just when it was tempting to me. It was only after prolonged home analysis that he had been able to come to the conclusion that this continuation was harmless for black."
Objectively, this sacrifice isn't sound. But in typical Tal fashion, he knows there are practical difficulties lurking behind every corner. } (11. Re1?! O-O $15 { And there's no good sacrifice. }) (11. Ngh5! { The engine line. } 11... O-O 12. g3!? { The engine tries to argue that white's setup doesn't make sense and the best way to make progress is to undo the committal nature of white's setup: } 12... Nbd7 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 $10) 11... fxe6 12. Bxe6 Qc7?! { Botvinnik played this move in 2 minutes, so clearly he had spent time analyzing the sacrifice before the game. However, this is not the most precise even though this idea is correct. } (12... Nbd7 13. Re1 Qc7! { Tal correctly points out black's best defense, transposing to the game. }) 13. Re1?! { Gives Botvinnik a chance to correct his "mistake." } (13. Nh5! $10 { Tal believes that Rf8 is black's best defense here, and in fact had an opportunity to test this out against Vukic 18 years later. } { Tal, Mihail - Vukic, Milan, 1/2-1/2, Bugojno, 1978, https://lichess.org/eI6xrub7 }) 13... Nbd7! { No discovery for you! Botvinnik only played this move after thinking for another 15 minutes. Probably still home prep, but it takes some cajones to play such a move against Tal. O-O-O is a threat, so Tal needs to move the bishop right now. } (13... Bxg3?! 14. fxg3 Qxg3 15. Qe2?! { Tal's intended continuation allows black to fix his mistake with: } (15. Re3! Qc7 16. Qe2 { The engine line. Finally, black has to deal with the discoveries on the e file because the battery is the correct way around. } 16... Kd8! (16... Nbd7?? 17. Bxd7+ Kxd7 18. Re7+ $18) 17. Bh3 $10) 15... Nbd7! $17 { There is no discovery, once again. }) (13... Kd8?! $10 { "Black's king would not find refuge on the queenside." }) 14. Bg8+!? { Trading LSBs gives the g3 knight access to some tender light squares. } (14. Bh3+!? Kd8! { This was later tried, and white gets nowhere after: } 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 Bh2+ 17. Kh1 Bf4 $17 { Christiansen, Johan-Sebastian - Eljanov, P., 0-1, World Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/ygKAOVur }) 14... Kf8! { The king is much better on the kingside, allowing the queenside rook to play in some lines. The kingside rook, meanwhile, keeps its responsibility defending h7 and h6. } 15. Bxh7 Rxh7 (15... Bxg3? 16. Bg6! $16 { The light squares are a real issue. }) 16. Nf5 { Tal has only spent 20 minutes to reach this position, claiming that home analysis evaluated it as being extremely rosy. that's just not true at all though for several reasons. Firstly, black has a lead in development (and is up a piece), so both keeping on pieces and trading off them favors black. Moreover, Botvinnik shows that there is a simply remedy to force the issue and trade off the scary attacking knight: } 16... g6!? { Black is bringing his rook on h7 to bare. This might not be the most precise way to play, but it is very thematic. If you're the player up a piece, you just want that piece to be truly felt - giving up an extra pawn to activate your pieces isn't much of a concern.
Botvinnik has spent half of his time so far, while Tal has only spent 20 minutes. } (16... Bh2+! 17. Kh1 Bf4!? $17 { Simply, safe, and strong. White has nothing for the piece, with g6 coming next. } (17... g6!? { Ragozin's analysis convinces the engine, but doesn't convince Tal. } 18. Bxh6+ Kg8! { Too many pieces of white's are hanging. } 19. Ne7+!? (19. g3!? Bxg3 20. fxg3 gxf5 $19 { [%csl Gh6] }) 19... Kf7! 20. Bg5 Bd6! { and the knight is trapped behind enemy lines. })) 17. Bxh6+ Kg8 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 { Black has repulsed the attack completely, and activated his rook on h7. During the game, Tal believed that white's position without an attack was almost lost. But in analysis, he thinks that the strength of the bishop means that a 3 pawns vs a piece endgame isn't so bad for white. Tal's analysis evaluation is more correct. } (18... Rxh6!? 19. Re6 Rxh4 20. Qd3?? (20. g3!? Rh7 21. Qd3 $10 { A better path forward. }) 20... Nf8! 21. Rxf6 Qh7 $19 { A tricky line that Tal calculated. }) 19. Bg5!? (19. Qd2!? { preparing Bf4 is also sensible. } { [%cal Gh6f4] }) 19... Re7 { "I would like to cite the dialogue which occurred after the end of the ninth game between Botvinnik and myself. When I, in rapid-fire succession, began to show Botvinnik the different variations in which Black gets a good game, he said: 'At first, I thought that this position was better for white, but later I found the correct plan: I had to exchange rooks and keep the queens on the board.' At first, such an evaluation of the position seemed to be rather abstract, but when I began to go over the same numerous variations, I came to the conclusion that Botvinnik was absolutely correct: in an ending without queens, white's well-shaped active bishop guarantees him a definite edge. With the queens on the board, black can count on a strong attack in view of the weakness of g4." } 20. Qd3 (20. Rxe7!? Qxe7 21. h5 gxh5?! (21... Qf7! { White doesn't want to open the h file, exposing the white king futher. } 22. hxg6 Qxg6 $15) 22. Qxh5 Nxh5 23. Bxe7 Re8 24. Re1 $10 { Followed by Bb4. } { [%cal Ge7b4] }) 20... Kg7 21. Qg3? { "Unquestionably, the weakest move in the match." Neutering the pawn majority on the kingside and giving up control of g4 forever, effectively means that this queen trade comes at the cost of a pawn. } (21. f4?! { Tal's suggested improvement is not so much better though. } 21... Rae8 22. Re5!? { Always sacrifice the exchange! It's the right spirit, but white has no threats if black plays cautiously. } 22... Re6! $17 { Nh7 is coming to get out of the pawn fork and kick away the strong bishop. } (22... Nxe5?? 23. fxe5! $18 { [%cal Gg5f6] }) (22... Rxe5?? 23. fxe5 Rxe5 24. dxe5 Qxd3 25. exf6+! Nxf6 26. cxd3 $18)) (21. Rxe7+! { Before the rooks are connected, white needs to scramble to create counterplay. } 21... Qxe7 22. Bd2 { Re1 is coming. } 22... Rf8 23. Re1 Qd6 24. g3 $10 { White is not for choice here, but also not in any way worse. If there was time to build with b3+c4, depriving black of any central outposts for his knights, white could even be better. }) 21... Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Qxg3 23. fxg3 Rf8! { Preventing the white king from entering the game, black gets the best version of the endgame. } (23... Re8?! 24. Rxe8 Nxe8 25. Kf2 $10 { g4 and h5 are coming, when the kingside pawn majority can still be felt. }) 24. c4 (24. Re7+?! Rf7 25. Rxf7+ Kxf7 $17 { Note how important one extra tempo can be in the endgame! } 26. Kf2? Ne4+! $19) 24... Ng4 25. d5?! { Pawns aren't people. And this just lets black's knights further into the game. Tal was clearly depressed with his position. } (25. Re4?! Ndf6 26. Rf4 Re8! $19 { Once more, white's king cannot activate. }) (25. Re7+! { The most precise way to improve upon Tal's idea. } 25... Rf7 { The rook desperately does not want to be on the 7th rank. } 26. Re4 Ndf6 27. Rf4 Rd7!? (27... Re7?? { Oops - you no longer can activate the rook on the e file! } 28. Rxg4! $18 { The pin decides the game. }) 28. a4 $15) 25... cxd5 26. cxd5 Ndf6 27. d6 Rf7 { With no further progress to be made, Tal decides to give up the d pawn in order to get active with the king. } 28. Rc1!? (28. Bf4!? { Holding firm for maybe one more move might be most precise. } 28... Rd7 29. Kf1 Kf7 30. Ke2! { Another way to get the king up in the endgame. } 30... Ke6 31. Kf3+ Kf5 32. Re7 $17) 28... Rd7! 29. Rc7 (29. Bf4?! Nd5 30. Rc7?? (30. Kf1!? Kf6 $17) 30... Nxc7 31. dxc7 Rd1# { Just to highlight how strong this knight on g4 is. }) 29... Kf7! 30. Bxf6 { It's a travesty to give away the bishop for a superfluous knight, but there's just no variation where the bishop is doing anything better than the g4 knight. } 30... Nxf6 31. Kf2 { Finally, you can at least get the king up in the endgame. } 31... Ke6 32. Rxd7 Kxd7 33. Kf3 Kxd6 34. Kf4 Ke6 { Botvinnik has 6 moves to make in 13 minutes. Very doable. Meanwhile, there's no way to make progress with the king, so the best white can hope for is exchanging all the pawns and getting a drawn endgame. } 35. g4!? (35. Kg5?! Kf7! 36. Kf4!? (36. g4?! Ne4+ 37. Kf4 Nf2 $19 { Nd3 is coming and black easily handles the 3 vs 1 on the kingside with just the lone king. }) 36... Nd5+ 37. Ke4 Ke6 $17 { Black is making progress. }) 35... Nd5+ 36. Ke4 { White stays central with his king to prevent black's knight from taking all of the queenside pawns. The kingside pawns by themselves can create a passed pawn when necessary. } (36. Kg5? Kf7 37. h5 Nb4! 38. a3 Nd3 $19 { White's pawns are once again going nowhere. }) 36... Nf6+ 37. Kf4 Nd5+ 38. Ke4 Nb4 { Botvinnik, close to move 40, avoids the perpetual. } 39. a3!? { If the knight gets to c4, now both pawns are targets. This is probably not the stoutest defensive technique. } (39. a4! { The best practical chance, even if it's still lost. Now the pawns are not both targets for the knight. } 39... Nc6 40. h5 g5 41. h6 Kf6 42. Kd5!? (42. h7!? Kg7 43. Kf5 { Yes, black loses the g pawn. But white's queenside pawns are inflexible without a king around to defend them. Black can play to fix the pawns on b3 and a4 before tracking them all down: } 43... Nb4! 44. Kxg5 Nd3 45. b3 Nc5! $19 { The queenside pawns fall, and black wins. }) 42... Kg6 43. Kd6 Nd4! (43... Na5? 44. Kc7 Nc4 45. Kxb7 a5 46. Ka6 Nxb2 47. Kxa5 $10 { The same maneuver pulled off in the game doesn't work, now that the knight is unable to track down the pawn on a4 as opposed to a3. }) 44. Kc7 b5! 45. a5 Nb3! 46. a6 Nc5! 47. Kc6 Nxa6 48. Kxb5 Nb8! $19 { Black creates a wall, and white's king is helpless to penetrate to the a pawn. }) 39... Nc6 40. h5 g5 { Move 40 has been reached, but Tal doesn't want to seal a move because he believes his next move is "forced." } 41. h6 { In this position, Botvinnik considered his sealed move for more than 40 minutes... } 41... Kf6! { and chooses the most clinical response. } (41... Ne5!? 42. h7 Nf7 { Black's knight first stops the h pawn, while black's king is there to bully white's king away from the queenside. This also wins, but black need not play with a passive knight, as in the game. } 43. Kd4 Kf6 44. Kd5 Kg7 45. Ke6 Nh6 46. Kd7 Kxh7 47. Kc7 Nxg4 48. Kxb7 Ne3! { and black is just in time to win the race anyway. } 49. Kxa7!? (49. g3!? g4 50. Kxa7 Nf1! 51. a4 Nxg3 52. a5 Nf5 53. a6 Nd6 54. Kb8 Nb5! $19) 49... Nxg2 50. Kb6 Nf4 51. Kc5 Nd3+ 52. Kd4 Nxb2 53. Ke4 Kg6 $19) 42. Kd5!? (42. h7!? Kg7 43. Kf5 Na5 44. Kxg5 Nc4! { Black wins on the queenside easily. }) 42... Kg6 43. Ke6!? (43. Kd6!? Na5 44. Kc7 b5! $19 { Keeping the b pawn alive for longer secures the victory. } 45. Kb8 Nc4 46. Kxa7 Nxb2 47. Kb6 Nc4+ 48. Kxb5 Nxa3+ 49. Kc5 Kxh6 $19 { Black easily wins both g pawns and promotes on the kingside. }) 43... Na5 44. a4 { Losing a tempo compared to if 39. a4 has been played instead. Still, there were other ways to convert that position. } 44... Nb3!? (44... Nc4!? 45. b4 b5! 46. axb5 Na3 $19 { A quick victory too. }) 45. Kd6 a5 46. Kd5 { Tal has to waste time going the long way around in order to smoke out the all-powerful knight. } (46. Kc7?! Nc5! { Even in an endgame, Botvinnik is showing how to squeeze with good technique. } 47. Kb6 Nxa4+ 48. Kxb7 Nxb2 $19) 46... Kxh6 47. Kc4 Nc1 48. Kb5 Nd3 49. b3!? (49. Kxa5!? Nxb2 50. Kb6 Nxa4+ 51. Kxb7 $19 { The g pawn is going nowhere. Black easily wins. }) 49... Nc1 50. Kxa5 Nxb3+ 51. Kb4!? (51. Kb6?! $19 { Kxb7 is never even a threat because of Nc5+, trading pawns and then winning on the kingside. }) 51... Nc1! { The knight is out of range of the king, but still ready to jump back to b3 if called for. } 52. Kc3 Kg6 53. Kc2 Ne2 54. Kd3 Nc1+ 55. Kc2 Ne2 56. Kd3 Nf4+ { Botvinnik puts it away finally now that he has calculated the king is not in time to win the b pawn. } 57. Kc4 Kf6 58. g3 Ne2 $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } { White resigned. All of a sudden Tal's lead has mostly evaporated from a 3 point lead to a 1 point lead in only two days. } 59. Kb5!? { The only attempt to get something going on the queenside fails: } 59... Nxg3 60. Kb6 Ne4 61. a5!? (61. Kxb7!? Nc5+! $19) 61... Nd6! $19 0-1


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.05"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E87"]
[Opening "King's Indian Defense: Sämisch Variation, Closed Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 10: Botvinnik - Tal, Saemisch KID"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/hseELF2H"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "When the score became 5-4, it had a sobering effect on me. A new struggle with equal chances began, in which, at the same time, I had acquired newly found confidence in my abilities." Somehow, before this game, Tal had divined that Botvinnik would try the Saemisch system against his KID. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3!? { The Saemisch has been a consistent attempt against the KID since the creation of the KID itself. Fads have come and gone on the best way to play this opening for both sides, but Tal had done some homework and came in with a gameplan to play e5 and then f5, open up the f file, and get counterplay on the queenside, all while stopping white's kingside aspirations with a timely h5. Let's see it in action... } 5... O-O 6. Be3!? { Since this move doesn't actually prevent c5, some players prefer to wait on developing this bishop. } (6. Nge2!? { My personal favorite move. Be3 is not necessarily the move you want to commit to. Meanwhile, blocking your LSB happens basically every game, so this is no big commitment. }) 6... e5!? { The normal move in the KID, but no longer a well-respected line against the Saemisch. } (6... c5!? { Since Kasparov's day, most people agree that the Benoni variations against the Saemisch are the most reliable for black. }) 7. d5! { "Unquestionably the best theoretical continuation." Yet Botvinnik is already using time again in known waters...
Karpov won some stellar games against Kasparov in the late 80s and early 90s that deterred black players from trying out the e5 variations anymore. } (7. Nge2?! exd4 8. Nxd4 c6 $10 { With a Pirc setup. d5 is coming. }) 7... c6 8. Qd2 (8. dxc6?! { White is now just losing time with the d pawn. } 8... bxc6! 9. Qd2 Qe7 10. O-O-O Rd8 11. c5? d5! $17 { Ney - Boleslavsky, 1955. }) 8... cxd5 9. cxd5 (9. Nxd5?! Nxd5 10. Qxd5?! { Will win the d pawn, but white is lagging behind in development. } 10... Nc6 11. O-O-O? Nd4! 12. Bxd4 Be6! 13. Qxb7 exd4 $19 { The queenside is being blasted open. This would be great if white had played Rd1 too, simply because it takes too many moves to castle kingside to safety. }) 9... a6!? { Not the only move, but now black can safely play Nbd7 without fearing Nb5. Moreover, Nh3 has been ruled out, so white needs to come up with something right here and right now. } (9... Nbd7?! 10. Nh3! $14 { White should not be allowed to develop this knight to f2. }) 10. g4!? { Going for an all-out attack is logical, but white is still a little behind in development. } (10. Bd3!? $14 { Kamsky, Gata - Kasparov, Garry, 0-1, Manila ol (Men), 1992, https://lichess.org/G56fez65 }) 10... Nbd7 11. Nge2?! (11. h4?! h5! 12. g5 Ne8 $14 { Tal - Gligoric, 1958. White no longer can play for an attack and instead should be looking to contain black. }) (11. Nh3!? h5 12. Nf2! $14 { A reliable way to play. White is looking to finish development, while keeping kingside attacking aspirations alive. }) 11... h5! { "Patented by Gligoric." } 12. Bg5? { Botvinnik tries a new idea after thinking for 6 minutes. It's not good. } (12. g5!? Nh7!? 13. h4 f6! 14. gxf6 Rxf6! 15. Ng1 Rf4! { "worth considering is this sterotypical exchange sacrifice." } 16. Bxf4 (16. O-O-O?! Rxh4 17. Bg5?? Bh6! 18. Bxh6 Rxh1 $17 { Tal's home-cooking on the theoretical lines. }) 16... exf4 $14 { The DSB is a monster. }) (12. h3!? Nh7!? 13. h4?! (13. gxh5?! Qh4+! 14. Kd1 Qxh5 $10 { The point of Nh7. }) (13. Rg1! $14 { Timman, Jan H - Kasparov, Garry, 1/2-1/2, Amsterdam Euwe Memorial, 1996, https://lichess.org/9UFK3Gtc }) (13. O-O-O?! h4! $10 { Black's idea of Bf6->g5 to trade off the DSBs is unstoppable. } { Matlakov, Maksim - Demchenko, Anton, 1/2-1/2, Chigorin Memorial 18th, 2010, https://lichess.org/jvVU6Rcv }) 13... hxg4 14. fxg4 Nb6! $10 { An improvement Tal mentions on his game Tal - Gligoric, 1958. Nc4 and Bxg4 are threats. }) (12. gxh5!? Nxh5 13. Ng3 Nf4! 14. h4! Nf6 $14 { Tal was happy to go in for this as black. }) 12... hxg4 13. fxg4 Nc5 { The g and e pawns are both under fire. So white needs to sacrifice a pawn. "Was this pawn sacrifice found at home or over the board? Only Botvinnik and Goldberg can answer this question." } 14. Ng3! { Played after 20 minutes, Botvinnik finds the best way to sacrifice the pawn. Still, he's spent 47 minutes to barely leave theory. As always, his time management is less than impressive. } (14. b4? Ncxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4! 16. Bxd8 Nxd2 17. Be7 Re8 18. Bxd6 Nc4 $19 { The DSB is about to be felt in this position, and white is playing down most of their army. } { [%cal Ge5e4] }) 14... Bxg4 15. b4 { Another 15 minutes spent. } (15. Be2!? Bxe2 16. Qxe2 Qd7 17. h4 $15 { The engine thinks white has reasonable compensation here, with a small grip on the position in return for being down the g pawn. }) (15. h3?! Bd7 16. h4 Qb6 17. Rc1 Qb4 (17... Ng4! $17) 18. h5 $15 { and white went on to get some sort of an attack in Pachman - Gligoric, 1960 just after this WCC match. }) 15... Ncd7 16. h3 Bf3 17. Rh2 { Finally, black's forced moves are at an end, and Tal begins to think.
"White is a pawn down, but then there is a half-open file on the kingside; the black bishop on f3 is not well posted, but on the other hand, white also has several weaknesses in his position. If black can create pressure along the c file, his counterattack might become very active. In connection with this idea, black's following move is worth serious censure." } 17... a5?! { One more, Tal tries to sharpen up the game. The problem is, he's dynamically worse but statically better. In that situation, he should be looking to shore up his position first rather than go on an adventure on the board. } (17... Rc8 { This logical move is just good too, preventing white's idea in the game. } 18. Rc1 Qb6 $15) 18. b5 (18. Qe3?! axb4 19. Nb5 Nxd5! 20. exd5 Bf6 $15 { Tal was hoping Botvinnik would go for this, but of course Botvinnik chooses a quieter (and stronger!) direction }) 18... Qb6 19. Qf2!! { "An extremely profound evaluation of the position. It might seem that white, having a pawn less, should avoid simplifications wherever possible, and that his chances would lie in an attack on the king. However, Botvinnik shrewdly saw the possibility to create very interesting play on the queenside, taking advantage of the fact that most of black's forces are inactively stationed on the other side of the board [...] In spite of the fact that white is a pawn down, his position is now to be preferred."
I think Tal is overestimating how good Botvinnik's position is, but his point stands. White's not in danger of being worse anymore, simply because black's pieces are so bottled up on the kingside. } 19... Qxf2+!? (19... Bh5!? 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 $10 { Maybe this is smarter. The other knight prefers the d7->c5 reroute, but now white's c3 knight is also dominated. Moreover, b6 is stopped forever. }) 20. Rxf2 Bh5 21. b6! { A highly critical decision, made in only 5 minutes. Botvinnik's in-game sense that Nb5 was a crucial resource to take advantage of is perfectly correct. } (21. Kd2!? { Botvinnik was thinking maybe this was better. } 21... Rac8 22. Rc1 Rc5 23. b6 Rfc8 $10) 21... Rfc8 22. Nb5 Ne8 { Tal has covered all of the infiltration squares without disconnecting the rooks, but it's clear that white's pieces are more active across the board. } 23. Nxh5?! { The right idea. The wrong execution. } (23. Rb1!? { Tal's suggestion. } 23... Nxb6 24. Nxd6 Nxd6 25. Rxb6 { "is to white's advantage." Except for one thing. The rook does nothing on b6 because the knight is untouchable after: } 25... Bf8! $10 { The c file is more important than the b file. }) (23. a4! Nxb6 24. Nxh5! gxh5 25. h4 $14 { The h5 pawn is a target in the long term, and now black's king is unsafe. But timing the specifics of when to take on h5 is confusing. }) (23. Be3? Bf6! 24. Nxh5 Bh4! $17 { Tal's line is nice. }) 23... gxh5 24. Be3 Nc5 25. Bxc5 { Bailing out into an OCB endgame. } 25... Rxc5 26. Bd3 { Amazingly, this silly b pawn cannot be captured just yet. So white maintains dynamic chances well into the endgame. } 26... Rac8!? { Played after 25 minutes. Tal seeks rook trades so that his DSB can reroute to d8 and win the b pawn. } (26... Ra6?! 27. Nc3! { [%cal Gd3a6] } 27... Rxb6 28. Na4 $10) 27. Ke2 Rc1 28. Rxc1 Rxc1 29. Rf1 Rc5!? { Playing for a win. } (29... Rxf1?! 30. Kxf1 Bf6?? { Tal's suggestion flat-out loses. } 31. Na7?? (31. Nc7! Kf8 32. Bb5! Ng7 33. Ba6! $18) 31... Bd8 $10 { "secures a draw" }) (29... Bh6!? 30. Rxc1 Bxc1 31. Nc7 Nf6! 32. Ba6! Nxe4 33. Bxb7 Nc3+ 34. Kd3 Na4! $10) 30. Rb1 Bf6 31. Na3 (31. Na7?! Bd8 32. Nc6 bxc6 33. b7 Bc7! 34. b8=Q Bxb8 35. Rxb8 Kf8 36. dxc6 Ke7 37. Rb7+ Kf6 38. Bb5 Nc7! 39. a4 (39. Ba4? Rc4! $17) 39... Ne6 $17 { "Black gets the clearly better endgame." }) 31... Bd8 32. Nc4!? (32. Nc2!? f5! 33. Ne3!? { transposes to the game. } (33. exf5?! Nf6! 34. Ne3 Rc3 $17 { e4 might be a threat at any moment. Meanwhile, black's pieces are finally super active. Giving back the f pawn in order to clog the f5 hole is no bother. })) 32... f5! 33. Ne3 (33. exf5?? e4 $19) 33... fxe4 (33... f4?! 34. Nf5 $10) 34. Bxe4 { Botvinnik needs 6 moves to reach the time control but only has 10 minutes remaining. } 34... Kh8!? { Played fast and confidently. Tal is willingly going for the flag. The idea is simply Nf6 to pressure d5. } (34... Nf6?! 35. Bf5! $10 { and Nxd5 fails. }) (34... Kf8!? $10 { "Probably weaker" since the white rook can get to g8 if the king goes too far. }) 35. Kd3 Nf6 { Played after 30 minutes. So much for the flag. } (35... Bg5?! 36. Nf5!) 36. Bg2!? { Instead of playing for activity, Botvinnik is trying to make safe, sensible moves and reach move 40. } (36. Rf1!? Nxe4 37. Rf8+ Kg7 38. Rxd8 Nf6 39. Nf5+ Kg6 40. Nxd6 Rxd5+ 41. Ke3 $10) 36... Kg8 { What else to do? } 37. a4 Be7 38. Bf3 Bf8 39. Rg1+ (39. Rb5?? { Botvinnik would never play such a move with 6 minutes on his clock. } 39... Rxb5 40. axb5 a4 41. Nc4 Kf7 42. Na5 e4+! { White gets the b pawn, but the a pawn is decisive. } 43. Bxe4 Nxe4 44. Kxe4 a3 45. Nxb7 a2 46. Nd8+ Kg6! 47. b7 a1=Q 48. b8=Q Qb1+ 49. Kf3 Qf1+ 50. Kg3 Be7 $19) 39... Kh7 40. Be4+!? { During the game, both Botvinnik and Tal were impressed with this move, played with seconds on the clock. In truth, this move tempts fate just as much as waiting around would. } (40. Bg2!? { If you continue to wait around and do nothing, then suddenly the tactics explode. } 40... Bh6 41. Nf5! Nxd5! 42. Nxd6! Nf4+ 43. Ke4! $10 { White is only just not losing here. }) 40... Nxe4 { Played instantly. Hilariously, Botvinnik waited for 10 minutes before recapturing on e4, thinking that Tal would want to adjourn by sealing a move. Tal didn't even realize what was happening. } 41. Kxe4 Bh6!? { Played instantly. Tal forces Nf5, and so Botvinnik has an easy time to seal the move and calculate the concrete ramifications of this simplified endgame at home. Tal estimated that this was about 80%/20% draw vs win for black. } (41... Rc3!? $15 { Tal regrets not having played this move, which indeed seems to be slightly stronger. }) 42. Nf5 { The sealed move. } 42... Rc4+ (42... Bf8!? 43. Ng3! (43. Ne3?! Rc3 $15 { Allows Tal to make up for his 41th move. }) 43... Kg6 44. Ne2+ Kf7 45. Rf1+ $10 { Either black allows perpetual check or the king to infiltrate to f5. }) 43. Kd3 Rxa4 44. Nxd6 Rd4+!? (44... Bg7!? 45. Nxb7?! e4+ 46. Kd2 $10 { Black's bishop is finally active. Still, this is playable because black needs to go after the b and d pawns ASAP. }) 45. Ke2! { The king will blockade the e pawn on a light square. } 45... Rxd5!? (45... Rd2+! 46. Kf3 Rxd5 { Might be more precise because now white only has one option: } 47. Nxb7 Rb5 48. Ra1 Bd2 $15 { Botvinnik didn't believe in this for white, although it is still holding. }) 46. Ne4!? { Botvinnik commits to staying two pawns down, but keeping a strong knight and an excellent blockade. Nf6+ is a serious threat. } (46. Nxb7!? Rb5 47. Ra1 $15 { Botvinnik didn't believe in this for white, although it is still holding. }) 46... Kh8! 47. Nf6?? { Finally a slip in Botvinnik's home analysis. } (47. Rg6! Bg7 48. Rd6 $10 { And indeed, the knight is just able to compete with the bishop. }) 47... Rd2+ 48. Kf3 Rd8 49. Rg6 a4?? { Still home-cooking for Tal, but now this rook endgame is drawn. } (49... Bd2! { The only move! Now, black can disturb white's mating construction: } 50. Nxh5 Bc3 51. Nf6 a4 52. Ke4 Bb2 53. Kf5 e4! $19 { And white is not in time to create mating nets. }) (49... Bg7? { Tal thought this "simple" line won, but in fact } 50. Nxh5 Bf8 51. Nf6 Be7 52. Ke4 a4 53. Kxe5! a3 54. Ke6! a2 55. Kxe7! a1=Q 56. Kxd8! $10 { is enough to force black to repeat. There is simply no way to stop Rg8# or disturb white's mating net. }) 50. Rxh6+ Kg7 51. Rh7+! (51. Rxh5?? Kxf6 52. Rh7 Rb8! $19 { There is no stopping the a pawn from queening. }) 51... Kxf6 52. Rxb7 Rd3+ 53. Kg2 Rb3 54. Ra7 { Simplest. Now the pawns will get traded, after which it's an e and h pawn against h pawn. Draw. } 54... a3 55. b7 Kf5 56. Rxa3! Rxb7 { The end of Tal's home analysis. Meanwhile, Botvinnik had already thought for more than an hour.
If black were to be able to play h4, then there are some winning chances, but Botvinnik shows good technique: } 57. Ra4! { White holds as in the Philidor position. } 57... Rb2+ 58. Kf3 Rb3+ 59. Kg2 Re3 (59... e4!? 60. Ra5+! Kf4 61. Rxh5 $10 { A theoretically drawn position. }) 60. Rh4 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Tal offered a draw and Botvinnik accepted after this titanic struggle. } 60... Kg5!? { The only remaining winning attempt goes nowhere: } 61. Ra4 e4 62. Ra5+ Kh4 { Another drawn position. There is no way to improve the position after: } 63. Re5! $10 1/2-1/2


