{ Leading by three points and only needing 2.5 points to clinch the WCC, Tal was now a huge favorite to win the title. Still, his games with black were a bit shaky so far until he picked up this Ne4 idea in the Saemisch. Would Botvinnik repeat? }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Ne4 { Yes, Botvinnik continues to fight for the white side of this position. } 6. Qc2 f5 7. Nh3 { A repetition of game 16. } 7... O-O! { The better move. } 8. f3 Nf6 9. c5!? { Botvinnik tries to clamp down on black's center before it gets off the ground. The problem is that this center is also a bit over-extended. Still, if the worst case scenario is white trading off a doubled c pawn, then white is probably still fine. } (9. e4 fxe4 10. fxe4 e5 { will probably transpose to game 16. }) 9... b6 { Of course, this queenside strike is to be expected. } 10. cxb6 cxb6?! { Taking towards the center is of course correct. Instead, Tal tries to work against the c4 square and the backwards c3 pawn. Slow, and not correct. } (10... axb6! { Of course, this is the correct recapture. Tal tries to argue that this is anti-positional since there is nothing to do on the open a-file. Incorrect. White's DSB has to stay on c1 or b2 now to babysit the a pawn. Does it really fulfill a duty on either of those two squares? No. } 11. e4 fxe4 12. fxe4 d5 $15) 11. e3!? (11. e4!? fxe4 12. fxe4 Bb7?! (12... d5! $10 { If you really want to work against a backwards c pawn Tal, this is the way to go. }) 13. Ng5! { Early aggression is the name of the game here. The knight on f3 is great. The bishop on d3 is great. White has a strong and mobile center. } (13. Bd3? { Tal correctly spotted this trap. } 13... Nxe4! 14. Bxe4 Qh4+ 15. Nf2 Bxe4 $19) 13... Qc8!? (13... h6?! 14. e5! hxg5 15. Bxg5 $16) 14. Bd3 $14) 11... Qc7 { Tal is hoping Botvinnik will develop his LSB first before he commits to the Ba6 trade. } (11... Ba6!? 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O $10 { Completely fine for black too. }) 12. Bd2 { A good developing move. Meanwhile, what else is black to do before playing Ba6? } (12. Bd3?! Ba6 $15 { Now white has lost a tempo. }) 12... Ne8?! { Ridiculous and slow. Tal is really trying to commit to this Ba6 plan and is simultaneously planning Nd6->c4. This move was only played once Tal had calculated the game variation up to move 20. It took him nearly 40 minutes to pull the trigger on this move. } (12... Ba6!? 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qd3 Nb8 15. c4 $10 { "White's weaknesses on the queenside could not be exploited, and his elastic position in the center would give grounds for evaluating black's prospects as quite gloomy." Yes, but also this is what you sign up for when playing a canny system like this and taking away from the center. }) (12... d5!? $10 { Black's inelastic center and dark squared weaknesses make this look unappealing, but this is apparently as good as Ba6 according to the engine. }) 13. c4! { If black is not interested in stopping c4, it is totally correct to claim a big center. Botvinnik played this move after a 30 minute think. Now Tal's whole system comes under question. } (13. e4?! fxe4?! { Tal's idea. } (13... Ba6!? 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. e5 Rc8 16. Qd3 Qc4! $10 { The engine's idea is much more to the point. Black's knights on e8 and a6 are awful, but the light square weaknesses aren't going anywhere. There is plenty of time to maneuver them to d5 and c4. }) 14. fxe4 Nc6 $14) 13... Ba6 14. Rc1 Nd6 { Consistent as always, both sides are building up on c4. } 15. Qa4!? { Another deep think by Botvinnik. } (15. Rg1!! { The engine move is a stunner. } 15... Rc8 16. g4! { Now that black is committing hard to the queenside is exactly when the engine blows open the center and kingside. } 16... Bxc4!? (16... Nc6!? 17. c5! Bxf1 18. cxd6 Qb7 19. Rxf1 Ne5! 20. dxe5! (20. Qb1?? Rxc1+ 21. Bxc1 Nxf3+ 22. Ke2 Nxh2 $17 { with a huge attack on the weakened light squares. }) 20... Rxc2 21. Rxc2 $16 { White has too much material for the queen, and a perfectly safe king. }) 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Nf4! Nxd2 19. Qxc7 Rxc7 20. Rxc7 Nxf3+ 21. Kf2 Na6 22. Rxd7 Nxg1 23. gxf5! exf5 24. Kxg1 $16 { And white has a far superior endgame due to the activity of the rook and knight. Black's pieces are completely dominated on the queenside. }) (15. Bd3!? { The normal move. } 15... Rc8 { Following through on the threat to win the c pawn. } 16. e4! { While black is playing very hard for the queenside, white can and should break in the center. } 16... Nc6! (16... fxe4?! 17. Bxe4! Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bb7 19. Qd3 $16) 17. c5 Bxd3 18. cxd6 Bxc2 19. dxc7 Bb3 $10 { With a probable peaceful result coming next. }) (15. Qb3?! { Moving your queen twice in the opening doesn't accomplish the same thing. } 15... Rc8 16. c5 bxc5 17. Rxc5 Qb6! $10) 15... Qc6! (15... Rc8?! 16. c5! b5! (16... Bxf1?? 17. cxd6 Qxc1+ 18. Bxc1 Rxc1+ 19. Kf2 $18 { with nowhere near enough material for the queen. }) 17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Bxc4 bxc4 19. Kf2! $14 { Black's position has no prospects. Agreed. It'll be a miracle to not get run over by white's strong center. }) 16. Qxc6 { Botvinnik plays quickly here. } (16. Qb3!? Rc8 17. d5 { Tal thinks this gives black the hardest time. True. Thankfully, there is an equalizing idea here. } 17... exd5! (17... Qc7? { Tal's "wild" idea } 18. dxe6 Nxc4!? $16 { that he didn't quite trust. Correct - this is ridiculous. } 19. exd7 Nxd7 20. Qa4 Nb8 21. Kf2 $16) 18. cxd5 Qb7 $10 { A much more sound way to play. Tal believed that after a series of simplifications, black's queenside play is worth it. }) 16... Nxc6 17. Bb4 { "It was probably on this move that white placed all his hopes. Now it is clear that white's strategic plans have prevailed as his pawns threaten to significantly cramp the enemy." } 17... Nxb4 18. axb4 Bxc4! { Perhaps Botvinnik had simply overlooked this resource from afar. } (18... Nxc4!? { Tal spent 5 minutes considering this move too. } 19. Bxc4 Rfc8 20. Bxe6+ dxe6 21. Kd2 $10 { Tal believed here that the bishop is useless on a6 and that e6 could become a tangible weakness. Moreover, white has the e5 outpost too. But in order to get to e5, you have to go through d3 which allows Bxd3... }) 19. Bxc4 (19. Rxc4? Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Rfc8 21. Bb3 Rc1+ 22. Bd1 a5 $19 { Black's queenside is instantly running up the board and the extra rook is running circles around white's silly minor pieces. }) 19... Rfc8 20. Bxe6+ dxe6 21. Kd2 { "Superficially, black's chances are to be preferred since he can count on creating a passed pawn, but at the same time he has to consider his weakness on e6. The normal result of such a position would be a draw."
Botvinnik has played the last few moves quite quickly, but still only has 45 minutes to play the next 20 moves. } 21... Kf7 { After 10 minutes considering if there was an active option available to black, he decides that the best course of action is to bring the king up instantly. } 22. Nf4 (22. Ng5+ Kf6! 23. Nxh7+?? Kg6 $19) 22... a5 { "Here I come!" } 23. bxa5 bxa5 24. Kd3 { In retrospect, Tal believes this should be white pushing, but during the game he thought that he should still be the one pushing for a win because of this passed a pawn. Sounds like he's acknowledging that pawns aren't people. } 24... a4 25. Rxc8 $10 { Botvinnik played this move and offered a draw. While that's a fair take, there's still something to play for here with both colors. } 25... Rxc8 26. Ra1 Nc4!? { Tal gives this a question mark and says that now he has to fight for a draw. It is true that the position is a bit more brittle now. But if knights come off, you're still likely to get a draw here even if you lose the a pawn. } (26... g5?! 27. Nh3 { Both pawns are hanging, so black needs to go crazy to avoid losing here. } 27... g4! 28. fxg4 fxg4 29. Nf2 g3! 30. hxg3 Ra8 $10) (26... Ra8!? $10 { More careful. Now a3 is coming and black should be able to offload this pawn at least for the e3 pawn. }) 27. Rb1! { Activity! But Botvinnik has 18 minutes to reach the time control. } 27... a3 { The pawn remains scary, but also a bit over-extended. } (27... Rc7?! { The move you want to make - safeguarding your king from checks and making sure white's rook cannot get behind the pawn. } 28. d5! Ne5+?? (28... exd5!? 29. Nxd5 Rc6 $10 { Black is definitely looking shaky here. }) 29. Kd4 $18) 28. Rb7+ Kf6 29. Ra7 { Botvinnik correctly puts his rook behind the pawn. } 29... g5?! { Tal believes this is the worst move of the game. The engine still thinks this is within the drawing range, but it's certainly not a position where black is pushing, as Tal believed to be the case during the game. } (29... Nb2+! { Black can still force a draw. } 30. Kd2 Nc4+ 31. Ke2 Nb2! 32. Rxa3 Rc2+ 33. Ke1 Nc4 $10 { The pawns are coming off and black has a perpetual or equality at least. }) 30. Nh5+ Kg6 31. g4! { White is threatening at least a perpetual (or mate) with Rg7+ and then Rf7. } 31... Nb2+ { Tal recognizes during the game that he's overestimated his position and now plays for a perpetual. } (31... h6?? 32. Rg7# { One such mating net. }) (31... f4?? 32. Rg7+ Kh6 33. Rf7 Kg6 34. Rf6# { White's threat. }) 32. Kd2 Nc4+ 33. Kd3 { Always repeat. Botvinnik is getting closer and closer to the time control but only has 15 minutes remaining. } 33... Nb2+ 34. Kd2 Nc4+ 35. Ke2! { Playing for the win! } 35... Rc6!? { Defends against the mate threats with a timely e5. } (35... fxg4!? 36. fxg4 Rc6 $10 { might be very very slightly more precise, but probably will transpose. }) 36. h3! { A nice continuation. White now can meet fxg4 with hxg4 as in the game, thus keeping a stronger center and avoiding issues with having a poor h pawn at the end of the day. } 36... e5! { Activates all of the pieces. This is the perfect type of pawn break. } 37. dxe5?! { Tal is unimpressed with this move, believing that winning a single pawn is not enough to actually convert. } (37. d5! { Tal has correctly pointed out that keeping more tension in the position, avoiding pawn trades, and seeking to undermine black's coordination is more promising in the endgame than trying to win a pawn. } 37... Rb6 38. Kd3 Nd6? (38... Nb2+! { The engine finds a beautiful sequence here to keep black in the game. } 39. Kc3 Nd1+! 40. Kd2 fxg4!! 41. hxg4 Rb2+! 42. Kxd1 a2 { Black has to jump through hoops to avoid catastrophe here. Indeed, with Rb1+ and a1=Q coming, black should just be fine. } 43. Ra6+ Kf7 44. Nf6 h6!! { Saving the h pawn for exactly one turn is necessary if black wants a clean draw. } 45. Nd7 Rb1+ 46. Kd2 a1=Q 47. Rxa1 Rxa1 48. Nxe5+ Ke7 49. Nc4 $10 { The rook is not worse than the knight and pawns. }) 39. Rxa3 $16 { Black's pieces are horribly misplaced here. }) 37... fxg4 { Tal first trades off more pawns. } 38. hxg4 Nxe5 39. Rxa3 { Black's king is out of danger finally as both players reach the time control. } 39... Rc2+ 40. Kf1 (40. Kd1?! Rf2 $10 { More pawns are traded, guaranteeing a draw. }) 40... Kf7 { The game was adjourned here, with Botvinnik sealing the next move. Knight and rook endgames are incredibly hard to win. If the knights get traded, it's an immediate draw. If the pawns get traded, it's an immediate draw. If black can sacrifice the knight for all of white's remaining pawns, it's an immediate draw. The only real hope lies in converting this position into a king and pawn or knight and pawn endgame. Easier said than done. } (40... Nxf3?? 41. Ra6+? Kf7 42. Rf6+ $18 { Winning the knight is Botvinnik's trick. }) 41. e4 { Botvinnik's sealed move after 30 minutes of thought. } (41. Ra7+!? { Also playable. } 41... Ke6 42. Ng7+ Kf6! $10 { White will probably just have to repeat since the knight is dominated. }) 41... Rd2!? { Tal's prepared move. } (41... Nc4!? { Botvinnik thought this move easily secured a draw for black. His line went: } 42. Rd3 Rd2 43. Rc3 Rc2?? { with a draw. Of course, this goes against the rules of trading rooks (which Tal correctly noted!), and is in fact lost objectively. } (43... Ne5!? $10 { Not an easy draw, but this is definitely good enough too. }) 44. Rxc2 Ne3+ 45. Ke2 Nxc2 46. e5! { Only with this move does black face difficulties. } 46... Ke6 47. Kd3! Ne1+ 48. Ke4! $18 { White's king is beautifully central. Ng7->f5 is coming to centralize the knight next. }) 42. Ke1 Rg2! { Staying active. White's knight is low on squares. } (42... Rd3?! { Botvinnik was hoping for a knight endgame, but Tal was correctly set on keeping the rooks on. } 43. Rxd3!? (43. Ra5!? { A tricky try that Botvinnik had probably prepared during the adjournment. } 43... Ke6?? (43... Re3+! 44. Kf2! (44. Kd2?? Nc4+! $19) 44... Rxf3+ 45. Kg2 Nc6! { is enough to defend though. } 46. Rxg5 Re3 $10) 44. f4! Re3+ 45. Kf1! gxf4 46. Nxf4+ $18 { White cannot defend the knight or the rook. }) 43... Nxd3+ 44. Ke2 Ne5 $14 { This might be drawn, but it's best not to test your luck here as black. }) 43. Rb3 { Both the knight and rook are optimally placed, so Tal waits with his king. } 43... Ke7 44. Ng7?! { Gives up the "game." Black can immediately sacrifice the knight for all of white's pawns. } (44. Kf1!? Rc2 45. Ng7 { Perhaps this is a way to prolong the struggle. } 45... Kd6 46. Nf5+ Kc5 $10 { But now black's king is walking up in the endgame. So this too should be enough compensation for the pawn. }) 44... Nxf3+ 45. Rxf3 Rxg4 46. Nf5+!? (46. Re3!? Kf6! 47. Nh5+ Ke5 48. Ng3 h5! $10 { h4 is coming to disrupt the knight's defense of the e4 pawn. }) 46... Ke6 47. Ng3 h5! { h4 is coming to disrupt the knight's defense of the e4 pawn . } 48. Nxh5 Rxe4+ { All knight+rook vs rook endgames are drawn as long as black doesn't immediately walk into a fork. In fact, the Chess Dojo training program has that endgame as a sparring position for people 1700+. It's not hard to hold. Tal doesn't find this position challenging either.
In fact, Tal has no further annotations on this game, merely noting that the following moves are easy. He spent a total of 30 minutes for the rest of the game. } 49. Kf2 Ke5 50. Kg3 Rh4 51. Ng7 Rf4 52. Ra3!? (52. Re3+!? Kf6! 53. Nh5+ Kf5! { And the rook cannot be captured. } 54. Nxf4 gxf4+ 55. Kf3 fxe3 56. Kxe3 $10) 52... Rd4 53. Ra6 Rd6 54. Ra7 Rd4 55. Rf7 Rf4 56. Re7+ Kf6 57. Ra7 Re4 58. Nh5+ { As long as white's king cannot pass the 4th rank, black can even hold onto the pawn as well. } 58... Kg6 59. Kf3 Rb4 60. Ng3 Rf4+ 61. Ke3 Rf7 { Now, the king is cutoff on the f file. } (61... Rb4!? 62. Ne4 $10 { White can gang up on the g pawn with Ra5 next. Still a draw of course. }) 62. Ra5 Rf6 63. Ne4 Rf5 { A knight by itself cannot mate black. } 64. Ra6+ (64. Rxf5?! Kxf5 $10 { The only person with winning chances is black actually, so at this point, white should force the issue with: } 65. Nxg5 $10) 64... Kg7 65. Ng3 Re5+ 66. Kd4 (66. Kf3 { I guess white can try and win the g pawn this way. } 66... Kf7 67. Kg4 Kg7 68. Ra4 Kg6 $10) 66... Rb5 67. Ke4 Kf7 68. Nf5 Rb4+ 69. Nd4 Rb1 70. Nf3 { Black's king is cut off from the pawn, but it literally doesn't matter. } 70... Rb4+ 71. Nd4 (71. Kf5?! Rf4+ 72. Kxg5 Rxf3 $10) 71... Rb1 72. Nc6 Kg6 73. Ne5+ Kh5 74. Ra5 Re1+ 75. Kf3 Rf1+ 76. Kg3 Rf4 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Rather than continue the game a further day, a draw was agreed by both players. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.05.03"]
[Round "19"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A87"]
[Opening "Dutch Defense: Leningrad Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 19: Tal - Botvinnik, Leningrad Dutch"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/5JkGoIMt"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Botvinnik took a time-out after the last game. So game 19 occurred five days after the start of game 18. During that rest time, Tal and his trainer decided to play 1. c4 instead of 1. e4 just to get a fresh position away from the Caro-Kann. }
1. c4!? { A novelty in the match. } 1... f5!? { An unexpected choice from Botvinnik. He had played the Dutch a long time ago, but hadn't picked up the Dutch in a serious game for a while. Clearly, this choice was based on the fact that the double-edged positions that arise from the Dutch could yield a surprise victory for the player playing black. } 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 g6!? { Rather than play the Stonewall (in his opening rep), Botvinnik plays the Leningrad Dutch, something he rarely plays. This move was chosen after a 5 minute think. Probably he was upset to see that d4 wasn't played, which means that white could instead opt for d3+e4 setups against the Stonewall instead. } 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d4 d6 6. Nc3 e6!? { Preventing d5. But now if e5 is going to be played, it will have to be down a tempo. Both players appear to be out of book based on their time management. } (6... O-O $14 { By far the most common move. There are some lines where black can get in e5 in one go. } { Vidit, S. - Carlsen, M., 1/2-1/2, Aimchess US Rapid Prelim, 2021, https://lichess.org/yERFDEca }) 7. O-O O-O 8. Qc2!? { The other way to prepare e4, but black has a nice rejoinder. } (8. Re1!? Ne4! { It's necessary to prevent e4 for white. } 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 $14 { But e4 is still coming. This position favors white tremendously. } { Jakovenko, D. - Williams, Si1, 1-0, 32nd ECC Open 2016, https://lichess.org/TQnG4lGX }) 8... Nc6 9. Rd1 { Prevents e5. } (9. d5?! Nb4 10. Qb3 Na6 $10 { Black gets a nice grip with Nc5 coming next. }) 9... Qe7 (9... e5?? 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 $18 { with a pin on the d file. }) 10. Rb1! { Getting off of the long diagonal, this fine move was played in only 7 minutes. The idea of b4-b5 and Ba3 is on the cards, with white playing on the side of the board he owns. } 10... a5 { Prevents b4. } 11. a3 { Prepares b4. But now Ba3 might not be possible later. } 11... Nd8! { Not at all an obvious move. But the point is to take the sting out of b4-b5 and reroute to f7 where it fully supports the e5 pawn advance. Amazingly, there are two correspondence games in this position, both ending a draw, and both opted for this move. } 12. e4!? { Breaking in the center now that black has retreated is perfectly logical. } (12. b4!? { The obvious move is also fine, even if b5 is no longer a threat. The idea of breaking down black's position with c5 is still very much playable. }) 12... fxe4 (12... e5?! { Black has asked too much of his position. } 13. Bg5! c6? (13... Nc6!? 14. c5 $14) (13... fxe4!? 14. Nxe4 $14) 14. c5! $16 { A fire has been lit in the center of the board, and black is playing down a few minor pieces while all of white's pieces have come to fight. }) 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Nf7 { e5 is coming next. } (14... e5! 15. dxe5 Nf7! $10 { and black gets in the center pawn break he was looking for immediately. } (15... Bf5?! 16. Qd5+ Nf7 17. exd6 Qxd6 $14 { The engine thinks this is fine for black, but you have to admit that you would rather be up a pawn than not. })) 15. Bh3! { Prevents e5 for one more move. } 15... Qf6 { Black sets up the threat to win a pawn with d5 (because the h3 bishop is loose). Tal was excited at the prospect of sacrificing a pawn, so after 10 minutes played: } 16. Bd2!? d5!? { Following through with the threat. Black wins a pawn, but weakens his position. } (16... e5! { Tal correctly notes that break is more in the spirit of the position. } 17. Bxc8 Raxc8 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Bf4 $10 { Black's pieces are more active here, and the d file did not open. }) (16... c6?! 17. Bc3 e5 18. Bxc8 Raxc8 19. dxe5 dxe5 { Tal likes this position for black, but in actual fact you need to look deeper. } 20. Rd7! $14 { White's rook gets active. The e pawn is more of a liability than a strength. } 20... Nd6? { There's no time to prepare e4. } (20... Rcd8!? 21. Rc7! $14) 21. Qxe5 $18) 17. Qe2 (17. cxd5?? exd5! $19 { A double attack on h3 and e4. }) 17... dxc4!? (17... Nd6!? 18. Ne5! dxc4 19. Rbc1 b5 20. b3 $14 { The position resembles a Catalan, where white has achieved e5 and black broke at it with f6. These type of pawn sacrifices always work out for white. }) 18. Bf4?! { Arguably weaker than Bc3 because now black can and should hold onto the extra c pawn. } (18. Bc3!? { The fact that there remain two correspondence games that went like this probably speaks to the fact that a player or two is a huge fan of Botvinnik and wanted to prove that his opening choice isn't refuted. Indeed, both games ended in a draw from this position. } { Boccia, Prof. Mattia Mario - Belka, Wieland, 1/2-1/2, ITA-USA 2010, https://lichess.org/mQ9B5ubj }) 18... Nd6? { A normal looking move, but black is not fixing the rook on a8 or the bishop on c8. Tal sees his chance to strike. } (18... b5 19. Ne5 g5! $15 { and black is generating play even with a loose position. Ra6+c6 will shore up the queenside. }) 19. Ng5?! { Similar to Ne5, but Tal believed he was doing it with tempo. That's almost true: black misses a chance here to fight fire with fire. } (19. Ne5!? b5 20. Bg2 Ra6 21. a4! $16 { and the queenside explodes. Classic Catalan position. }) 19... Re8?! { These last handful of moves were played quickly (both players had already spent an hour and a half before move 20), but were inaccurate. As Magnus would say - they're playing poor moves quickly! } (19... Bh6! { You can't afford to lose any time here as black or you'll end up positionally dead on the queenside. } 20. Bxe6+!? (20. Nxe6? Bxf4 21. Nxf4 Bxh3 22. Nxh3 Rae8 $17 { White has "played with his pretty pieces." All of black's pieces are in play now while white was moving his knight all over the place. Black is doing great here to make the battle about the center and not the queenside. }) 20... Bxe6 21. Qxe6+ Rf7! 22. Qxf6 (22. Nxf7?? Qxe6 23. Nxh6+ Kg7 $17) 22... Rxf6 23. h4 Rf5 $10 { Black still is up the pawn from earlier, and the soothing trades mean his king safety is no longer a concern. }) 20. Bg2 { Redirecting to the more important diagonal. } 20... Ra6 { If black can get in b5, move his d6 knight, and then play c6, black will be well coordinated. Much easier said than done. } (20... Bd7?! 21. Ne4! Nxe4 22. Bxe4 Bc6? 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Qxc4 $16 { The c pawns are easy pickings next. }) 21. Ne4! { Striking while the iron is hot. } 21... Nxe4?! { Developing white's pieces for him. All of a sudden, white's initiative is monstrous. } (21... Qf7!? { Apparently this is an only move according to the engine. White has two good options here though. } 22. Nxd6!? (22. b3!? cxb3 23. Nxd6 cxd6 24. Rxb3 $16 { White has sacrificed a pawn for maximum activity. Black's queenside in particular is in tatters. }) 22... cxd6 23. Qxc4 $16 { Restores material equality, and white's bishops are dominating the board. }) 22. Bxe4 b5 23. b3! { In typical Catalan style, white gets massive play against the queenside with this pawn gambit. } 23... cxb3 24. Qxb5!? (24. Rxb3!? $16 { equally promising. }) 24... Rf8 25. Qxb3 { "Simple and good. The text move likewise maintains a significant edge, but in my opinion, is not energetic enough and gives black a way out." Except it definitely doesn't. } (25. Rbc1? { Tal found this move interesting during the game, since the b pawn "does not present any immediate danger." I like his "pawns aren't people" mentality. The problem is the pawn does become a problem after: } 25... Rb6! 26. Qxa5 Bb7 27. Bxb7 b2! 28. Rb1 Rxb7 $10 { when white regrets not having snagged the pawn while he had a chance. }) 25... Rb6 26. Qe3?! (26. Qc2! Rxb1 27. Qxb1 $16 { In this manner, Bb7 is prevented and black still cannot develop the queenside. } 27... Qe7!? { Tal felt that this move, which gains time on the b pawn is good for black, but } 28. Qb3 $16 { the queen on b3 hits b7, e6, and defends a3. What a great square. }) 26... Rxb1 27. Bxb1 Bb7 { Black activates his bishop pair at long last. The only cost is a measly e6 pawn. } 28. Ba2 { Keeping control, Tal plays to win the e pawn. } (28. Bxc7?! Qf3! 29. Qxf3 Bxf3 $10 { The d pawn is hit, the rook is hit, and Rc8->c1 might be a problem too. }) 28... Bd5 { Tal has 30 minutes to reach move 40, while Botvinnik once again has bled time in the complications and only has 15 minutes remaining. } 29. Bxd5 exd5 30. Bxc7 { The extra pawn is finally in the bag. } (30. Rc1!? { Taking with the rook on c7 is potentially stronger. } 30... Qxd4!? (30... Rf7?! 31. Rxc7 Rxc7 32. Bxc7 $18 { Now, white is threatening Be5 or Qe8+, and there is an attack brewing. The a5 pawn isn't safe either. }) 31. Qe6+ Kh8 32. Rxc7 $16 { White hasn't won a pawn after all but instead focuses on the weak king. Rxg7 is the threat. }) 30... a4 { Fixing the a pawn on a dark square is a sound positional idea. } 31. Rd3!? { Rather than try and maintain a measly pawn, Tal is going for the kingside initiative. Yes indeed - pawns aren't people. The extra f pawn is best used as a safeguard in terms of king safety, rather than an asset in an endgame. } (31. Be5?! Qf3! $10 { "White's a and d pawns might be liabilities in the endgame." }) (31. Bf4!? $16 { With Bh6 ruled out, h5-h5 now becomes an idea. Tal's idea to attack on the kingside is of course perfectly correct. }) 31... Qf5 (31... Bh6! 32. Qe2 Qf5 $14 { A more precise version of the game. }) 32. Be5?! { White hopes for a bishop trade, but of course black doesn't allow it. } (32. Bf4! $16 { remains the better way to attack on the kingside. }) 32... Bh6! (32... Re8?! 33. Qe2! Bxe5 34. Re3 $16 { White gets the desired heavy-piece endgame in which he torture black's king for the foreseeable future. }) 33. Qe2 (33. Qxh6?? Qxf2+ 34. Kh1 Qf1#) 33... Rc8! { Botvinnik only has 9 minutes remaining, but his active play has yielded dividends. White's "kingside initiative" is yet to be seen. } 34. Rf3! { Setting a trap. } 34... Qh3?! { Missing the trap. } (34... Rc2! { Tal notes the stronger move indeed. } 35. Rxf5 Rxe2 36. Rf6 Bg7 37. Ra6 Bxe5 38. dxe5 Rxe5 39. Rxa4 Re1+ 40. Kg2 Ra1!? (40... Kf7! $10 { The strongest way to approach this position as black: get your king up in the endgame! }) 41. Ra7 { "Of course, the rook endgame seems to be winning for white." Except it's not clear at all. All rook endgames are drawn, and black gets the desired counterplay after: } 41... d4! 42. Kf3 d3! 43. Ke3 Ra2! $10 { The pawn cannot be taken without losing f2. But if the pawn is allowed to reach d2, white will run into some problems preventing black from queening. }) 35. Bc7! { Attack and defense! } 35... Bf8?! { "Not the best defense." To be fair, this move was played with only 3 minutes remaining on his clock. } (35... Rxc7?? 36. Qe8+ Bf8 37. Qxf8# { Tal's trap in action. }) (35... Qd7! { The only move to defend. } 36. Bf4 { "wins an important tempo." } 36... Bxf4!? (36... Bg7!? 37. Be5 Bh6 38. Kg2 $16 { White's king safety is no longer a concern, while black's king is looking more and more suspicious. }) 37. Rxf4 $16 { But now we get our desired heavy-piece endgame. }) 36. Qb5! Qe6 { A good try to keep it all together. } (36... Qh5?! 37. Rf4 Rxc7!? 38. Rxf8+! Kxf8 39. Qb8+ Kg7 40. Qxc7+ $18 { With a winning queen endgame. }) 37. Be5 { "How the position has changed in a few moves!" Finally white has the initiative and the extra pawn. Tal only spent 2 minutes on his last move, while Botvinnik has nearly flagged. } 37... Qc6 38. Qa5 { Of course we don't trade queens while black has a horrible king. } (38. Qb2? Qc1+ $10 { The desired queen trade. }) (38. Qxc6? Rxc6 $10 { The a3 pawn is a target that can be poked with Rc1->a1. }) (38. Qe2? { It's no surprise that such a passive move doesn't work for white. } 38... Bxa3! $10 { Tactically winning another pawn! } 39. Rxa3?! Qc1+ 40. Kg2 Qxa3 $15 { If anyone is pushing here, it's black. The passed a pawn is difficult for the bishop to handle. }) 38... Ra8 (38... Bxa3?? { With white's queen so active, it makes sense that this pawn cannot be captured. There are two winning ideas here. } 39. Rxa3! { Tal's line is good enough. } (39. Qa7! $18 { Mate threats force black to give up the exchange. }) 39... Qc1+ 40. Kg2 Qxa3 41. Qxd5+! Kf8 42. Bd6+ $18) 39. Qd2 { Qc1+ no longer trades queens. } 39... Rc8 { Botvinnik desperately tries to trade queens again... } 40. Kg2! { No queen trade for you! } 40... Qd7 { Botvinnik plays this move with less than 30 seconds left on the clock and reaches the time control by the skin of his teeth. } 41. h4! { A textbook attack is coming on the kingside now that white is fully coordinated. } 41... Qg4 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { Botvinnik sealed this move after a long think, but decided the next morning to resign rather than continue play.
Tal considered his positional+tactical play of this game to be his "best creative achievement in the match." It really was a textbook game in the Catalan when black overextends on the queenside trying to hold on to an extra pawn. } 42. Qa5!? { Tal points out this example variation: } 42... Qd7 43. Qa6 $18 { where black can hardly move because white's pieces are too active. } 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.05.05"]
[Round "20"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E24"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: Sämisch Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 20: Botvinnik - Tal, Saemisch Nimzo Indian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/KcnnwhOJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Up four points, Tal only needed to score 1/5 in the remaining games to secure the world championship title. }
1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Ne4 { Tal repeats the same Ne4 idea in the opening, noting that his opponent for the first time in the match is playing these opening moves instantly. } 6. e3! { A theoretically important move, played instantly. } 6... f5 { Now the threat of Nxc3 is real, since the knight has the escape square on e4 if necessary. } (6... b6?! 7. Qg4! { An important nuance in the opening. As in many French positions, the loose g pawn gets targeted instantly with Qg4. } 7... f5 8. Qxg7 Qf6 9. Qxf6 Nxf6 $16 { White wins a clean pawn. }) (6... O-O!? 7. Bd3 f5 8. Qc2 { Tal did not want to transpose to this position, the Bastrikov variation. } 8... b6 $15 { "The Bastrikov variation, which, as is well known, favors white." Engines completely disagree with this assessment and actually believe white is doing nothing here! } 9. Bxe4 fxe4 10. Qxe4 Nc6 $15 { Ba6 is coming and white has been moving the queen too much in the opening! }) 7. Qh5+!! { Tal gives this move two exclams. "When such checks are made at the outset, they are usually very bad checks; when Botvinnik makes such a move - it is profound and unquestionably home preparation." } (7. Bd3! Nxc3?! 8. Qc2 Ne4 9. Ne2 $14 { A nice engine line that highlights that maybe losing a million tempi to snag white's one weakness isn't worthwhile after all. }) 7... g6 8. Qh6 { The kingside dark squares are now extremely weak without a DSB around. If Tal came to the game hoping for an easy draw and his opponent to lose the title quietly, he was sorely mistaken now! A real fight was on his hands. } 8... d6?! { Played after a 30 minute think. Unfortunately, this is a true case of long think, wrong think. He's so impressed with Botvinnik's idea that his evaluations are not objective. } (8... Qg5!? { A bit desperate. Black can try and trade into an endgame like this, but after } 9. Qxg5 Nxg5 10. h4 { Black is almost in trouble. If h5 lands, white will have a much better endgame. } 10... Nf7! $10 { Necessary. The knight is awful here, but at least h5 can be met with g5. }) (8... Qf6!? { Tal wanted to play this normal move, but wasn't happy with } 9. Nf3?! d6?! (9... Nd6?! 10. Ne5?! Nc6 11. f4?! $17 { Another line where Tal completely misses the mark. Giving up the e4 square isn't scary. }) (9... b6! 10. Ne5 Bb7 $15 { What's the problem here? Black is just developing normally. }) 10. h4 e5 11. h5 $14 { "With a sharp, but advantageous game for white." OK sure, but none of those moves are forced. Nor do they }) (8... b6! { Developing the pieces is of course fine. White can't generate any threats just yet. } 9. h4?! { The caveman approach doesn't work here. } (9. f3!? Qg5! 10. Qh3!? (10. Qg7?! Qh4+! 11. g3 Qf6 12. Qh6 Nd6 $15 { White's kingside has also been compromised. }) 10... Nd6 $10) 9... Qe7! 10. h5 g5 11. f3 Ng3! 12. Rh3 Nxf1 13. Kxf1 $10 { Black is fine here after any normal move, but just to show one cool idea available to black: } 13... Qf8! 14. Qxg5 Rg8 15. Qh4 Ba6 $15 { Counterplay on the queenside. }) 9. f3 (9. Qg7?! { Tal's bait. } 9... Qf6 10. Qxc7 { White has won a pawn, but black has a huge lead in development here. } 10... O-O $15 { This sample variation shows that you cannot move your queen 4 times in the opening without developing anything and expect to get out alive. Both Nc6 and Na6 are serious threats. }) 9... Nf6 (9... Ng5! $14 { The idea of retreating to f7 never crossed Tal's mind. But in these Dutch-like structures, the knight stands well on f7 (as mentioned in game 19!). Now, Tal can play this maneuver with tempo? Black's totally fine here. }) 10. e4! { For once, Botvinnik is playing actively in the center and willing to sacrifice material to do so! Too bad he's only playing so dynamically after he's essentially out of the running here. This style of play, along with Tal's failing health, would be the name of the game in their 1961 WCC rematch. } 10... e5 { Prevents e5 from white - kicking away the knight. } (10... fxe4?! 11. Bg5!? $16 (11. fxe4!? Nxe4? 12. Bd3 d5 13. Nf3 $18 { "Black's position is hopeless." })) 11. Bg5 Qe7 { Prevents Qg7. Black is in a lot of trouble already. "The development of black's pieces leaves a lot to be desired." } 12. Bd3 { In the right spirit of the position, white is desperate to develop all the pieces ASAP. } (12. c5!! { If we want true fire on board - this is how you play chess. White is burning down the glorious center at all costs to further highlight black's poor development. } 12... dxc5!? 13. Bd3 Rf8? (13... f4?! { Closing down the center is desirable, but } 14. dxe5 $18 { Now, black's center cannot be maintained. }) 14. exf5 exd4+?! (14... Bxf5!? 15. Bxf5 gxf5 16. dxe5 $18) 15. Kf1! $18) 12... Rf8?! { Tall believes this is forced after 15 minutes thought, but actually there are a few options available to black. } (12... f4!? { Tal believed g3 was quite scary here. While true, black has a nice response. } 13. g3 Ng8! 14. Bxe7 (14. Qh4? Qg7! $17 { h6 is coming to trap the bishop. }) 14... Nxh6 15. Bf6 O-O! $14) (12... Ng8! 13. Qh4!? (13. Bxe7?! Nxh6 14. Bh4 O-O $10) 13... Qg7! { f4 and h6 are coming to trap the bishop. White doesn't have a way to blow open the center right now. } 14. exf5!? h6! 15. Be3 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 gxf5 $10 { Botvinnik's bishop pair is no more. }) (12... Nc6? 13. exf5 exd4+?! 14. Kf1! $18 { Re1 is too strong. }) 13. Ne2!? (13. Qh4! { Tal finds an improvement for white. } 13... Qf7!? 14. Bh6 Rh8 15. Nh3 { "with a big advantage." } 15... Ng8!? 16. Ng5 Qf6 { and black is barely holding on. } 17. f4! $16 { Just the type of thing black wouldn't want to see. }) 13... Qf7 { Breaks the pin on the knight, thus enabling Ng8 and a possible h6 again. } 14. Qh4 (14. O-O?! Ng8! 15. Qh4 f4 $14 { h6 is coming next. }) (14. Bxf6? Qxf6 15. Qxh7 Bd7 $10 { White is up a pawn, but this is the best position black has had all game. After Nc6 and O-O-O, all of black's pieces are well placed. }) 14... fxe4! { Simplifying the position. } 15. fxe4? (15. Bc2!! { The engine finds a nice way to continue the fight. } 15... exf3 16. O-O! $16 { Rxf3 is coming and black is definitely not out of the woods yet. }) (15. Bxe4?! { Tal's idea tries to keep the position sharper, but simplifications are unavoidable now. } 15... Nxe4 16. fxe4 Nc6?! $14 { and black is only a little worse, since c4 is loose too. } (16... h6! { some random engine shot. } 17. Qxh6!? (17. Bxh6!? Rh8 $10 { the pin is hard to escape. }) 17... Bg4! $10 { Preventing white from castling. Qxc4 is the next idea. })) 15... Ng4! { Setting up exchanges on f2. } 16. h3 (16. Kd2!? { Tries to keep the queens on the board. } 16... h6 17. Be3 g5!? (17... Nxe3!? 18. Kxe3 Qg7 $10) 18. Qg3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Qf2 $10 { The queens cannot stay on the board. }) (16. Rg1? { Tal's crazy idea to keep more juice in white's position tactically fails. } 16... h6! (16... Nf2? { Tal apparently intended to go for this line. } 17. Bc2 Qxc4? 18. Qxh7 exd4?? { But missed of course the mate threat on e7. } 19. Qe7#) 17. Bd2 g5 18. Qg3 Nf2! $15) 16... Qf2+ { Trading queens makes black's central king less of a problem. } 17. Kd2 (17. Qxf2? Nxf2 $17 { wins at least the exchange. }) 17... Qxh4 18. Bxh4 Nf2! { Forces more trades. } 19. Rhf1!? (19. Bxf2!? Rxf2 $10) 19... Nxd3 20. Rxf8+!? (20. Kxd3!? Rxf1 21. Rxf1 Be6!? $10 { Finally black can develop the queenside. As in the game, more precise is developing the knight before the bishop. } (21... Nc6!? $10)) 20... Kxf8 21. Kxd3 Be6!? { Tal succeeds in developing his queenside and is therefore out of the woods. } (21... Nc6!? { More precise is developing the knight before the bishop. If the knight gets kicked with d5, it has a useful square to jump to. } 22. d5?! Na5! $15 { c5 is an excellent outpost. } { [%cal Ga5b3,Gb3c5] }) 22. Ng3?! { A somewhat mysterious move. Botvinnik intends to place the knight on e3 instead. But now black has plenty of time to catch up in development. White's time advantage (and therefore advantage) has finally disappeared. } (22. Bd8! { The most annoying line. } 22... Na6!? (22... c6!? 23. Bc7 Ke7 24. dxe5 dxe5 25. Bxe5?! (25. c5! Nd7 26. Bd6+ $14 { A very precise sequence where black just isn't able to finish development. }) 25... Nd7 $10 { Tal intended to sacrifice a pawn to finish development. White's central pawn mass has been shattered. }) 23. Rf1+ Ke8 24. Bg5 $10 { The position is a little uncomfortable, but black is still fine here. }) 22... Nd7 23. Nf1 a6! { Refutes white's maneuver. } 24. Bf2!? { Botvinnik takes the sting out of b5, but now we can really see that white's playing over-prophylactically. } (24. Ne3!? b5! 25. Nd5?? { White cannot follow through with the maneuver. } 25... bxc4+! 26. Kxc4 c6 $19) (24. a4?! { The tempting move to shut down black's plan doesn't prevent b5 after all! } 24... b5! 25. axb5? (25. cxb5!? axb5 26. a5 Bc4+ $10 { Black is making progress, and the passed a pawn isn't that scary. }) 25... Bxc4+! 26. Kxc4? axb5+! 27. Kxb5 Rxa1 $19) 24... Kg7!? { Getting the king off the f file. Black is finally able to finish development. } (24... b5?! 25. d5! Bf7 26. Nd2 bxc4+ 27. Nxc4 Rb8 $10 { Black is probably fine here too, but why allow white's pieces to improve while ours are worse? }) 25. Nd2 Rf8 26. Be3 b6 { Safeguarding c5 and b7. } 27. Rb1 Nf6 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Tal's plan of Nh5->f4 seems so solid to Botvinnik that he offered Tal a draw here, with both players having more than 30 minutes on the clock.
Frankly, that's a ridiculous decision to take given the match situation. Magnus would play on from this position for another 7 hours if possible. Doubly so if he was down in a WCC match! } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.05.07"]
[Round "21"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E19"]
[Opening "Queen's Indian Defense: Classical Variation, Traditional Variation, Main Line"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 21: Tal - Botvinnik, Queens Indian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/O9rhKhBC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Nearly two months after starting this WCC, Tal has a commanding lead. Botvinnik would have to win four games in a row in order to save the championship title. }
1. d4!? { For the first time in the match, Tal starts with 1. d4. He was using this as a litmus test. "If my opponent preferred a sharp struggle, then it would become clear that his intentions were to fight with all his strength 'without any remorse.' And if? The second 'if' was what happened." } 1... Nf6 2. c4 e6 { Played after 3 minutes. Was Botvinnik perhaps willing to take up the KID in this game? } 3. Nf3!? { Avoiding the Nimzo. } (3. Nc3!? { Tal was curious what Botvinnik would have played against the Saemisch Nimzo-Indian... but opted to avoid the Nimzo-Indian today since he had little energy. } 3... Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 $10 { Black has many options available to him here. I agree - this would have been interesting to see. }) 3... b6!? { Tal believes the QID signals that Botvinnik is also interested in a quick draw. I mean I disagree. As black, what can you do to play for a win here? Perhaps the Benoni is what Tal expected? } 4. g3 (4. a3!? { The Petrosian variation is a great try for an advantage here as white. Kasparov used it with great effect in the 1980s and 1990s. }) 4... Bb7 { Old theory. } (4... Ba6!? 5. b3 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 Be7 7. Bg2 $10 { At the top level, this line has taken over as the most precise way to play as black. }) 5. Bg2 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 f5 { One of the most well-known lines of the QID. White cannot be worse here, but also this is a reasonably staid attempt at an advantage. } 10. b3!? { "With only these kind of moves being made, it is impossible to lose." What a difference 60 years makes! These types of quiet moves at the current top level are more likely to lead to decisive results. This is simply because engines are so strong, and prep is so broad, that all the sharper and crazier lines have all been analyzed deeply by both players to a draw/equal position! Slow, maneuvering games though cannot possibly be analyzed that deep because the branching factor in chess is so large. } (10. d5!? $10 { Tal recommends this sharper line if you want to play for a win. Yet today, this sharper play would simplify into a draw much faster than his solid move. }) 10... Bf6 11. Bb2 d6 12. Rad1 { Simply chess by both sides. } 12... Qe7?! (12... Qe8!? $10 { "is more in the spirit of the QID, maintaining control over the light squares." }) 13. Ne1! { A theoretically well-known idea. Trading off the LSBs enables white to play for e4 and/or d5. There is no attack on the kingside. } 13... Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Nc6!? (14... Nd7!? 15. Qf3 $10 { Tall thinks that maybe white has something here. But the correspondence games disagree. } { Meyer, Klaus-Dieter - Mickevicius, Juras, 1/2-1/2, CL/2019/B2, https://lichess.org/GTTv5iAb }) 15. Qf3 Qd7 { Already, we can see a drawback of the earlier Qe7 move. Black has lost a tempo. } 16. Nf4 { Centralizing the knight and threatening Nxe6, deflecting the queen. } 16... Rae8 { White simply defends the Nxe6 threat. Black's pieces are just about as strong as white's. } (16... Nxd4!? 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 e5 { If black really wanted a simple way to equalize the position, this is about as equal as you can get. } 19. Qd5+ Qf7 20. Qxf7+ Rxf7 21. Rd5 exf4 22. gxf4 $10) 17. d5!? (17. Nh5! { The only way to actually fight for an advantage. Turning this into a good bishop vs bad knight situation might give white some play. } 17... e5 18. Qd5+ Rf7 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Qf3 $14 { It's a very slim advantage here, but white's bishop is probably the more useful minor piece as long as he refrains from d5. }) 17... Nd8 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Botvinnik plays the objectively best move after 6 minutes and recognizes that there's no chance he stands better here. After making this move, Botvinnik "made me a flattering offer. Botvinnik's 17th move was destined to be the last move in this match."
Tal won the match convincingly with a score of 12.5 - 8.5 and became the 8th world chess champion. Due to the famous rematch rule, Botvinnik had his desired rematch in 1961 and retained his title winning the rematch with a score of 13 - 8. Importantly, he crushed Tal as white with extremely dynamic play - something he utterly failed to do in this match.
After the 1961 match, Tal would only play Botvinnik two more times with white. Botvinnik held a repetition of the N1e2 variation of the Caro-Kann from this match in 1964, but got crushed by the Panov-Botvinnik attack of the Caro-Kann in 1966. } (17... Bxb2?! 18. dxe6! Ne5! 19. exd7 Nxf3+ 20. exf3 Re7 21. b4! Rxd7 22. b5 $14 { Securing a good knight vs bad bishop position. The d5 outpost is juicy. }) 18. Bxf6!? { The obvious continuation: } 18... Rxf6 19. dxe6 Nxe6 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. e3 $10 { is perfectly equal. } 1/2-1/2


