1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. e3 d5 (5... Be7 { Slightly more precise to avoid the ensuing Bb5+ option as in the game on move 7. }) 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5+ c6 8. Bd3 Be7 (8... Bd6 { But Bd6 here runs into the annoying e4 break. } 9. O-O O-O 10. e4 $10) 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Bd6 { Basically, black should have wanted to play Bd6 earlier... } 12. Nh4 Re8 13. Nf5 Bf8 { Too many bishop moves. Black needed to ensure his pieces were perfectly placed before bringing them out. } 14. Rc1 Ne4 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qg4 { [%cal Gf5h6,Gh6f7,Gg4e4] } (16. d5 cxd5 17. Nxd5 (17. Nb5) 17... Bxd5 (17... Nc5?? 18. Nh6+! gxh6 19. Nf6+ $18) 18. Qxd5 Nc5 $15 { Taimanov was hoping for such a position. }) 16... g6 17. Nxe4 Rxe4! { Always sacrifice the exchange! } (17... h5 { Tries to win a piece, but loses to a Tal-like combination: } 18. Nh6+!! Kh7 (18... Kh8 19. Nxf7+ { [%cal Gf7d8,Gf7h8] }) (18... Bxh6 19. Qxd7! { [%cal Ge4f6,Gf6d7,Gf6g8] }) 19. Qxd7!) 18. Qxe4 gxf5 19. Qxf5 Bg7 20. e4 { Inaccurate, but makes sense. White wants to play Rc3 and Rg3 or Rh3. } (20. Rfd1 Rc8 21. h3 Nf8 (21... Qe7 22. Bc3 Qe6 23. Qxe6 fxe6 24. e4 { The best black can do. }) 22. d5 Bxb2 23. dxc6 { In this variation, the rooks make themselves felt much more than the pieces. } { [%cal Gd1d8,Gc1c8] }) 20... Nf8 21. e5 (21. Rc3 c5 22. Rg3 cxd4 23. Rd1 Ne6 24. Qg4) 21... Qd5 { [%csl Gd5,Gb7][%cal Gb7g2] } 22. f4 c5 { Black has a bit of initiative now, and white's last moves haven't actually activated anymore pieces to bring into the attack. } 23. Qh3 cxd4 24. Rcd1 Qe4 25. Rde1 (25. Rfe1!? Qc2 (25... Qxf4?? 26. Bc1! { The queen is trapped! }) 26. Bxd4 { White has some semblance of the initiative back here at least. }) 25... Qd5 26. Rd1 Rc8 27. Rxd4 Qa5 { [%cal Gc8c2] } 28. Rc4 { Bronstein: "White must accede to the trade of these rooks" In actual fact: } (28. Rf2!? { Stops the Rc2 idea in its tracks. } 28... Qe1+ 29. Rf1 Qa5 $10) 28... Rxc4 29. bxc4 Qc5+ 30. Rf2 Qxc4 31. Qb3 Qe4 32. Qc2 Ne6 33. f5 (33. Qxe4 Bxe4 { An almost certainly losing endgame. The pieces will coordinate first on the queenside and then start pushing the passed a pawn. }) 33... Nc5! 34. Qd2 Qb1+ 35. Rf1 Qd3 36. Qe1 (36. Rf2 Be4 { Black's pieces coordinate beautifully. }) 36... Qd5 37. Qg3 Ne4 38. Qh4 (38. Qf3 { Necessary, but completely losing for a different reason: } 38... Bxe5 39. Bxe5 Qc5+ 40. Kh1 Qxe5 { Black is up 1 point and has the more active pieces with the attack. }) 38... Nc3 39. Qg4 h5!! { Deflecting the queen from g2 or e2! } { [%csl Gg2,Ge2] } 40. Qh3 Ne2+ 41. Kf2 (41. Kh1 Nf4 42. Qf3 Nxg2 $19) 41... Qd2 $19 { White resigned } { [%cal Gd2b2,Gd2f2] } 0-1


