1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. d4 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4 exd4 9. Nxd4 { [%cal Gd7c5,Ga7a5] } 9... Nc5 10. f3!? $146 a5 11. Be3 a4 12. Rf2 c6 13. Nc2 Qe7 14. Rd2 { Averbakh's invention for this game. } 14... Nfd7 15. Rc1 Be5? { "looks senseless: surely the bishop cannot stay here very long" } (15... f5! 16. exf5 a3! 17. b4 (17. Nxa3?? Qxe3+ $19) 17... Bxc3 18. bxc5 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 dxc5 $15) (15... a3!? 16. Nxa3) 16. Bf2 (16. f4? Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nxe4 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 19. Rxd6 $15) 16... Re8 17. Ne3 { [%cal Ge3g4] } 17... Nf8 18. Ne2 Qc7 19. Rb1 a3 20. b3 (20. b4!? Na4 21. Rb3 $14) 20... h5 21. Qc2 Be6 { Black is really quite cramped. } 22. Nc3 (22. f4! Bg7 23. Rbd1 Rad8 24. b4! Na6 25. Qb3 $16 { Continuing the squeeze was best. }) 22... Nh7 23. b4! (23. Rbd1!? { Bronstein prefers preparing b4 with this one move first. }) 23... Na6 24. f4! Bg7 25. f5!? { "The sort of move that is either very good or very bad" } (25. h3!? { Slowly improving was another option. } { [%cal Gg1h2] }) 25... Bd7 26. Qb3?! { Can't be the correct follow-up to f5. } (26. fxg6!? fxg6 27. e5 Rxe5 28. Qxg6 { This is Bronstein's improvement, but it falls flat after: } 28... Rae8! 29. Rxd6? Nf8! $15) (26. Rd3!? { Preparing Qd2 also seems sensible. }) 26... Nf6 27. fxg6?! (27. Rbd1!?) 27... fxg6 28. c5+ Be6 29. cxd6 Bxb3! 30. dxc7 Bf7 { Now there are too many weaknesses in white's camp and the trade of queens reduces the pressure from the squeeze. } 31. b5 Nxc7 32. bxc6 bxc6 33. Rb7?! Rac8?! { The pawn on a3 gives black good chances in this endgame. The rook on the 7th is temporarily tamed. } (33... Ng4!! { Missed by everyone and in the analysis. } 34. Rxc7 (34. Nxg4 hxg4 35. Ne2 Be5 $15) 34... Bxc3 $17 35. Rc2 Bb2 36. R2xc6?! Ne5! 37. Rc2 Bxa2 $19 { [%cal Ga3a1] }) 34. Rc2 { Preventing Ng4 now. } (34. e5!? Nfd5 35. Ncxd5 Nxd5 36. Nxd5 cxd5 37. Bxd5 Bxd5 38. Rxd5 $10 { A reasonable way to bail out into a draw. }) 34... Na6 35. Bf1 Nc5 36. Rxf7!? Kxf7 37. Bc4+ Kf8 38. Nf5 Ncxe4! (38... gxf5?! 39. Bxc5+ Re7 $16) 39. Nxg7 Kxg7 40. Nxe4 Rxe4 { Black is firmly in control now, and if the extra exchange can infiltrate to the 2nd, it'll be all over. } 41. Ba6 Rd8 42. h3 Rb4 43. Rxc6 Ne4 44. Rc7+ Kh8 45. Be3 Rb2 $19 { White resigned, since there's no good way to keep the a2 pawn alive. } 46. Bc4?! Rd1+ 47. Bf1 Nxg3 $19 0-1


