1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 O-O 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O Qa5 11. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3b7] } (11. a4! Rd8 12. Ba3 cxd4 (12... Bg4 13. Bxc5? (13. h3 Be6 14. Bxc5) 13... Qxc5!) 13. cxd4) 11... Bg4! { We ignore pawns in order to maximize our development! } 12. Nf4 (12. f3? Be6 13. Qxb7 (13. d5 c4 $17) (13. Qa3 Bc4 14. Qxa5 Nxa5 15. Re1 Rac8 16. Ba3 b6 17. f4 Rfd8) 13... Bc4 $17) 12... e5! 13. dxe5 (13. h3 exf4 14. hxg4 fxg3 $10) 13... Nxe5 14. h3 (14. Qxb7?? Rab8 15. Qe7 Qxc3 $19 { [%cal Gc3a1,Gc3c1,Gc3b2,Gc3a3,Gc3d2] }) (14. Bxb7?? Rab8 15. Qd5 Bf3 $19) 14... Bf3 15. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 16. Kg2 Ne5 (16... Qa6! { [%cal Gg2f3,Ga6f1] }) 17. e4 b5?! (17... c4! 18. Qc2 Rfd8! (18... b5?! 19. Rd1 Rfd8 20. Be3 $10) 19. Be3 Nd3 { Piece play is important if black wants to maximize their potential. The octopus knight landing on d3 cannot be taken due to cxd3 with a powerful passed pawn taking its place. }) (17... Qa6 { Also good. Keeps more play in the position. } 18. Qa3 (18. Ba3 b6) (18. Be3) 18... Qc4) 18. Be3 c4 19. Qc2 Nd3 (19... Rfd8 { [%cal Ge5d3] } 20. Rfd1 { Black is now simply one move too slow to take advantage of the d3 square appropriately. }) 20. Nxd3 cxd3 21. Qxd3 Bxc3 22. Rad1 Rac8 23. Qd5 Rfe8 24. Qb3 Rc4 25. Rd5 a6 26. Qxc4 bxc4 27. Rxa5 Bxa5 28. Kf3 $10 { Draw agreed. If the bishop was on g7 instead of a5, perhaps black could try and press with the idea of pushing the c pawn but here it's a dead draw. } 1/2-1/2


