1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. Bd3 (8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 $10) (8. Rc1 Bb7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. b4 $10 { [%cal Gc7c6,Gc7c5] }) 8... Bb7 (8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Qe2 c5 { How I equalized in my OTB game. }) 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Rc1 (10. Qe2 Ne4 { Attempting to force equality immediately } 11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nf6 14. e4 c5 15. d5 { With play similar to the Semi-slav Reynold's attack }) 10... c5 11. Qe2 a6?! { Too slow. } (11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 a6 { [%cal Gb6b5] } 13. a4) 12. cxd5 exd5 (12... Nxd5 13. Bg3 $10) 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfd1 Re8 15. Bc2 { Tarjan, James Edward - Karpov, Anatoly, 0-1, Skopje, 1976, https://lichess.org/40vuqUrL } 15... Qb6 16. Bb3 c4 17. Ba4 { [%cal Gh4f6] } 17... Bc6 (17... Rad8? 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5) 18. Bxc6 (18. Bc2! Rab8 19. Nd4 Ba8 20. Rb1 $16 { [%cal Gh4g3,Gd4f5] }) 18... Qxc6 19. b3 { Bronstein hates this move saying it weakens all the dark squares, undefends his knight, and makes the bishop on e7 better with Bb4 or Ba3 ideas. While this is positionally true, the computer finds tactical justifications that make this still a fine move. } (19. Nd4 Qb7 20. Nf5 Bf8 { White has interesting play here, although the computer still believes this is simply equal as well. }) 19... Rac8 20. Na4? { A step in the wrong direction. White needs to better control the center. Moving his pieces to the side of the board makes no sense only to retreat. } (20. Nd4 Qb6 21. bxc4 dxc4 22. Nf5 { Clearly a better continuation. }) 20... Qb5 21. Nc3 Qa5 22. Bxf6 Nxf6 23. bxc4 dxc4 24. Nd2 (24. Rd4 Bb4 25. Rxc4 Bxc3 26. R1xc3 Qxc3 27. Rxc3 Rxc3 28. h3 $14) 24... Rc6 25. Nxc4?! { Opening the c file while all of black's major pieces are going to be attacking down it... } (25. g3 Rec8 26. Ndb1 { Safe and solid, but white is clearly not attempting to win anymore. }) 25... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7c1] } 26. Na4 (26. Nd5? Nxd5 27. Rxd5 Rc8) 26... Rc8 27. Rd4 (27. Nab6!?) 27... Ne8! { [%cal Ge7f6,Ge8d6] } 28. e4?? (28. Qd1! Bf6 29. Rd7! { Planning to meet black's maneuver with a counter-punch is the only way out of this one. Now black has to scramble to figure out how to deal with white's pressure: } 29... Rd8 30. Rxc7 Rxd1+ 31. Rxd1 Nxc7 32. Nab6 Na8! 33. Nxa8 Rxc4 $10) 28... Bf6 29. e5 Bxe5! 30. Re4 (30. Qxe5 Qxe5 31. Nxe5 Rxc1+ $19) 30... Nf6 $19 31. Nab6 (31. Rxe5 Rxc4 32. Rxc4 Qxc4 33. Qxc4 (33. Qd1 Qxa4 $19) 33... Rxc4 $19 { [%cal Gc4c1,Gc4a4] }) 31... Rxb6 32. Rxe5 Rc6 33. Re7 Rxc4 34. Re1 (34. Rxc7 Rxc1+ 35. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 36. Qf1 Rxf1+ 37. Kxf1 $19) 34... Qc6 35. h3 Rc1 36. Rxc1 Qxc1+ 37. Kh2 Qc4 38. Qf3 Qxa2 39. Ra7 $19 { White resigned rather than continue the game down a full piece. } 0-1


