[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Welcome to another instructive study by NoseKnowsAll. This interactive study is for players 1900-2400 lichess, taking you through an advanced strategical concept: pawns aren't people! We'll see how pawn structure and material are less important than piece activity in dynamic positions. Importantly, we'll also appreciate how piece activity in the endgame is of prime importance too!

This study is part two of a two-part series on developing plans on the chessboard. Before checking out this study, be sure to master part one:

* Talk to your pieces! | Developing plans I https://lichess.org/study/kjBSgqoA

Throughout this study, I will also provide general tips that these positions showcase. Whenever this general advice occurs, I'll write it just like this:

PRO TIP: Talking to your pieces goes hand in hand with the idea that pawns aren't people.

If you find this study useful, please heart it and share it with any friends! }
 *


[Event "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II: Pawns aren't people!"]
[Date "2009.06.10"]
[White "Rafael Duailibe Leitao"]
[Black "Andre Diamant"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Pawns aren't people!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/RH6MHXo0"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "4r1k1/3n1pb1/bq1p2p1/2pP2Pp/1r2PP2/2N3QP/1P3RK1/1BB1R3 w - - 19 37"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ I hope you've mastered the ideas from part one ( https://lichess.org/study/kjBSgqoA ) because we'll be using them here in more advanced examples!

Let's move on to the strategic concept: "pawns aren't people!" Simply put, this phrase acts as a reminder to put the feelings and desires of your pieces above any concerns for pawn structure or pawn grabbing.

We arrive at a tense Benoni position. White would like to run black over in the center and kingside, while Black is making strides on the queenside. How to make progress here? }
37. e5! { This thematic break in the Benoni seems impossible at first glance because Black has more defenders on e5 than white has attackers. However, this move is only impossible if you look at this position through a "pawns are people" lens, where you are not allowed to give away pawns (seemingly for free). } (37. f5? $17 { A poor move. All of black's pieces are happy to use the newly opened e5 square. White's knight, LSB on b1, and e1 rook are all saddened to see the e4 pawn still on the board. }) 37... dxe5 { Black captures the "free" pawn and asks white what the point is. } 38. f5! { The point of white's play. In reality, white wanted to break with f5 but first wanted the e4 square free for his knight+bishop and the e file half-open for his rook. The pawn on e4 was actually a traitor to three of white's pieces! } (38. fxe5? { This move only partially improves white's pieces. In reality it activates more of black's pieces than white's after the simple recapture: } 38... Nxe5! $17) 38... e4! { Now it's black's turn to show that they also understand that pawns aren't people! If the extra pawn stays on e5, then black's knight, DSB on g7, and e8 rook are all worse off. It's crucial to instantly give back that pawn, thus freeing all of black's pieces to fulfill their important roles. } (38... Bb7?? { The actual game ended abruptly in time pressure. After: } 39. f6! $18 { Black resigned because moving the bishop allows Bxg6. https://lichess.org/skUpOqgh#77
For instance: } 39... Bf8 40. Bxg6! fxg6 41. f7+ $18) (38... gxf5?? 39. Bxf5 $18 { A key benefit of sacrificing the e4 pawn has been revealed. The previously dormant bishop on b1 now springs to life. g6 is coming next and black is busted on the kingside. }) 39. Nxe4 $10 { Both players have given away pawns solely for the purpose of activating their pieces. This tense game could still swing either way depending on the next few moves.
PRO TIP: "Pawns aren't people" applies in the opening, middlegame, and endgame. However, it is most applicable in positions where time is a factor on the chessboard. You don't want to sacrifice your static advantages without gaining dynamic advantages in return. } (39. Bxe4?? { The desirable Bxe4 now fails tactically. } 39... Bxc3! $19 { And the e4 bishop doesn't have enough protection. Note that if black had tried to maintain the extra e pawn earlier, this bishop wouldn't have been making contact with the c3 knight to begin with, and so white would have no problems here. }) (39. f6?! Bf8 { There is no longer a tactical shot for white. } 40. Bxe4 Bd6 $15) *


