[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.03.28"]
[UTCTime "17:31:35"]

{ The center is locked in this thematic French Winawer pawn structure. White's pieces (especially the rooks) are more active than black's, and black's king on d7 could come under heavy fire if the center rips opens. However, there doesn't seem like a great way to blow up the center. }
20. a5!! { A fantastic "pawns aren't people" move. No matter how the tension is resolved, lines will open up on the queenside and center in a way that benefits white's pieces. The a pawn itself is of course completely expendable. } 20... Nxa5? { The most obvious capture - why not just capture a free pawn and keep black's pawn structure intact? } (20... bxa5?! 21. Nf4! $16 { The knight re-routes to d3 and then c5 where it will land with devastating effect. Black's extra doubled isolated a pawn is irrelevant. } { [%cal Gf4d3,Rd3c5] }) (20... b5?! 21. dxc5! $16 { And now the knight has d4 to rely upon. Black's king is looking less and less safe. } { [%cal Ge2d4] }) (20... Nc6! { Probably best - black should simply bring the knight around to help support the near-crumbling queenside. } 21. Nf4 N6xa5?! { Yet the pawn remains taboo! } (21... cxd4!? 22. cxd4 N6xa5 $14 { The only correct way to take the pawn. Regardless, white's center is now rock solid, white's heavy pieces have been opened up, and black's knights are sidelined on the queenside. }) 22. dxc5! { Blowing it open further to expose the c5 pawn and improve next the knight. } 22... bxc5 23. Nd3 { [%cal Gd3c5] } 23... Qc6 24. Rg3 { [%cal Gg3g7] } 24... Rhg8 25. Qf3 $16 { At the cost of a pawn and a "wrecked" pawn structure, white's heavy pieces are now optimally placed and breathing fire across the board, while black's pieces simply cower defensively hoping there isn't a knock-out blow. Already, the threat of Bxh6 should decide the game. } { [%cal Gc1h6] }) 21. dxc5! { Blowing it open to further destabilize black's queenside piece coordination. Since pawns aren't people, white does not care that this leaves their pawn structure a complete wreck. What's important is that the white pieces are springing to life. } 21... bxc5 { Note that black's pawn structure has improved from the following transaction. However, black's static advantage is irrelevant compared to white's dynamic potential from the more active pieces. } 22. c4! { c4 is explosive! Another "pawns aren't people" move rips open the position for all of white's pieces. Note how the white rook on f3 was previously a one-dimensional piece attacking f7, but now gains access to the entire 3rd rank. Importantly, black's king "safety" in the center is now directly questioned. } 22... d4 { The only way to keep it closed for black's king. } (22... Nxc4?? { Oh no, black's queen! } 23. Rxa6 $18) (22... Qxc4?? { Oh no, black's knight! } 23. Rxa5 $18) 23. Rfa3 { White's rook is activated on the now-important a file. } 23... Nec6 24. Bd2 $18 { Black's a5 knight falls, and with it the game.
PRO TIP: Pawn structure is often overrated. More often than not, active piece play more than compensates for a bad structure. } *


