[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

23. b5 { We reach an opposite side's castling position where both sides are getting close to murdering each other's king. What do you play? } 23... c5! { Exactly. Keeping the b file closed is crucial to avoid our king safety becoming the most important factor of this position. The fact that c5 technically sacrifices a pawn is irrelevant because pawns aren't people! The game will be decided by one of the flank attacks breaking through. Now, in every variation, our attack is now much faster than white's "attack" because the b file is closed. } (23... g4?! { This thematic idea was played in the game. While it's not so bad on its own if you calculate perfectly, the counterplay that white creates on the other side of the board should first be prevented. } 24. bxc6 Nxh3! { The only way to justify this sequence. } (24... gxh3?? 25. g3! $18 { The game, after which black got murdered on the queenside. https://lichess.org/GnX1tiGR/black#49 }) 25. gxh3 Rxh3+ 26. Qxh3 gxh3 $17) (23... cxb5 { Opening up lines for your opponent cannot be correct. } 24. Na5! $10) *


