[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/784uSaAM"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1q1rb1k1/1r3ppp/1p1ppn2/p7/P1P1P3/2N2PQ1/1P2B1PP/2RR2K1 b - - 1 22"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Now let's try a problem on prophylaxis. Put yourself in white's shoes and talk to white's pieces. Is there a plan white should be thinking about after listening to white's bishop complain about how blocked in he is? }
22... e5! $10 { Exactly! We don't care about the pawn structure's feelings when we play this "ugly" move - it's all about the pieces. Looking through that lens, there's nothing ugly about this move at all!
The bishop on c6 will easily cover the d5 and b5 holes created by this pawn structure. Meanwhile, our knight can spin around to c5 (or even d4!) where it will prove better than either of white's minor pieces. Finally, we have put a stop to white's possible expansion with f4+f5 or f4+e5, after which our king may come under heat.
The backwards d6 pawn cannot be upset by you for making this move because pawns aren't people!
Be sure to check out how Fischer ended up breaking through anyway here: https://lichess.org/study/XVqy23WQ/BfmP8oaU#44 } (22... Bc6!? { Good job talking to your bishop. This is a perfectly sensible move, but due to deep calculation doesn't address a core problem in the position. Check the analysis for more information! } 23. Rd3! { Note that Nd7->c5 is always impossible without hanging the d pawn. } 23... e5?! { The desirable e5 move no longer works. } (23... h6 24. Rcd1 Rbd7 $14 { Passive, but solid defense, is best is black's only option now. }) 24. Rcd1! $14 { Once again preventing Nd7. And now black is left passively defending, for instance with Ne8. }) (22... Qc7!? $14 { A reasonable move after talking to your queen. }) (22... h6?! $14 { This is a perfectly sensible move, but not one that addresses white's main plan in the position. }) *


