[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3qr1k1/3n1pbp/3p2p1/1p1P4/2p1PPP1/1r2BB1P/1P2RQK1/R7 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ This is a Benoni gone right for black. Our queenside play has left us with pressure against the b2 pawn, active pieces, and seemingly no weaknesses. What do you play next? }
1... g5! (1... h6?! { A reasonable move, preparing g5, but white can instantly attack our only weakness with Ra6, after which there's no clear move. } 2. Ra6! Nf8 $15 { Black's still fine here, but this isn't what we wanted. }) (1... Qb8?! $15 { This slow move prevents white from breaking through with e5. But we have much stronger. }) (1... c3?! { Logical. You are breaking through and creating a passed pawn immediately. But after this trade, white's pieces remain well-coordinated and the b pawn isn't queening any time soon. } 2. bxc3 Rxc3 $10) (1... Nc5? { After Bxc5 dxc5 e5! white has an imposing center and black is getting squeezed. } 2. Bxc5 dxc5 3. e5 $16) (1... Qf6? { A reasonable move in isolation, but white is all too happy to play g5 and kick you back. Next h4-h5 is coming. } 2. g5! Qe7 $14) (1... b4?! { Logical. You are breaking through and creating a passed pawn immediately. Unfortunately, white can instantly attack our only weakness with Ra6, after which there's no clear move. } 2. Ra6! Nf8 $15) 2. fxg5 { "Thank you very much for the free pawn" white says. What is the point of your pawn sacrifice? } (2. f5? { Even worse than the game. Now white's not even up any material. } 2... Ne5 $17) 2... Ne5! $17 { Fantastic job activating the knight - now that's talking to your pieces! The fact that we sacrificed a pawn is irrelevant because pawns aren't people!
Our knight rules the board from e5 and/or d3, and our bishop on g7 will breath fire along the h8-a1 diagonal. Meanwhile, white is never getting in the thematic e5 pawn break, and so white's bishop on f3 remains a tall pawn. Black is borderline winning already.
PRO TIP: Talking to your pieces goes hand in hand with the idea that pawns aren't people. If you put the wants and needs of your pieces first, you'll find that dynamic pawn sacrifices become more natural.
This is exactly why you need to master talking to your pieces before you can fully appreciate the pawns aren't people mentality. This is your last chance to revisit part I of this series and master it! https://lichess.org/study/kjBSgqoA } (2... Be5?! { Not a horrible move, but the bishop by itself cannot hurt white. Notice how this bishop doesn't coordinate with any of black's other pieces while a certain other minor piece coordinates on d3 and f3 with the rook. }) *


