[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2r5/4bppk/p1q1p2p/B1p4P/2P3Q1/1P6/P4PP1/3R2K1 w - - 1 29"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ Talk to your pieces. In a perfect world, what move would you like to play? Now make it so! }
29. Qf3!! (29. Rd3!? { This move (with the idea of Qd1 next) isn't that bad. Unfortunately black can prevent your idea with a timely Bf6! and Bd4! } 29... Bf6! 30. Qd1? (30. Qf4 $16 { Pressure on f7 is needed if you want to claim any advantage here. Now Rd6 is the threat. }) 30... Bd4 $10) (29. Bc3!? { A playable alternative idea to the game. This one-move threat isn't bad either. However, while you get some play on the kingside, this move does relinquish your queenside bind on black. After Rg8 and Bf6, black will be fighting back. } 29... Rg8 30. Qf4 Bf6! $14) 29... Qxf3 { Excellent move! By forking f7 and c6, black was forced to trade queens. } (29... Kg8?! 30. Qxc6 Rxc6 31. Rd7 $16 { The game continued this way, after which the white rook still infiltrated, and the kingside pawns are still intact: https://lichess.org/ZAxUzc6J#61 }) 30. gxf3 Bf6 { What was the point of this queen trade? } 31. Rd7! $16 { Exactly! Once the queens have been traded, white's rook is free to infiltrate to the all-important 7th rank.
Pawns aren't people - the damaged kingside pawn structure is irrelevant compared to the activity of white's remaining pieces. } *


