[ChapterName "To take or not to take?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/ufbXnneJ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "5rk1/ppR3pp/4p3/3pPp2/1P1P4/Pr4PP/7K/5R2 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2024.03.28"]
[UTCTime "17:31:35"]

{ Now let's consider the ramifications of "pawns aren't people" in the endgame. This first example will address materialism.

White is given a choice here: do we capture the free pawn on b7 or play something else? } { [%cal Rc7b7] }
1. Rfc1! { Of course white should fully dominate the open file rather than start pawn grabbing. } (1. Rxb7? { A bad, "pawns are people" move was played in the game. Grabbing the pawn cedes the only open file to black and does not give us any decisive passed pawn to compensate. Now we are the ones struggling! } 1... Rc8! { Yes, black is more concerned with rook activity than grabbing the useless a3 pawn! } (1... Rxa3? { It's never too late for your opponent to fall captive to the same "pawns are people" illusion! } 2. Rc1! $10 { Transposes to the main line, when white is doing fine. }) 2. Rf2 Rcc3 3. Rg2 Rxa3 $15 { Black's piece activity is tremendous here, and we didn't even win a pawn after all. }) 1... Rxa3!? { Black grabs material. } (1... Rf7! { The most stable defense - trading our passive rook for either of white's rooks is a good trade. } 2. Rxf7 Kxf7 3. Rc7+ Kg6! { Get your king up in the endgame! } 4. Rxb7 Rxa3 $10 { Black is not down any material, and has a somewhat active king. The position is equal. }) (1... Rb8?! { Black really needs to avoid falling into the trap that holding onto all material is correct. The b pawn is irrelevant. What matters is that the f8 rook might as well not be on the board. } 2. Re7 Rxa3 3. Rcc7 $14 { Black is lucky they're not already lost from this position. }) 2. Rxb7 { Note that this move is not about pawn grabbing. Rather, it's about doubling our rooks on the 7th rank. Piece activity remains king. } 2... Rd3?! { Going after more pawns could lead to black's doom. } (2... f4! { This nice idea to get the f8 rook working is playable too. } 3. gxf4 Rxf4 $10) 3. Rcc7 { Now it's black's turn to turn on their "pawns aren't people" hat or immediately lose to white's pigs on the seventh. The only thing that matters is piece activity - how can black get active? } 3... Kh8! { Avoiding the pawn hanging with check. The threat is Rg8, with a passive, but solid defense. } (3... Rxd4?? { That's one pawn too many, black! } 4. Rxg7+ Kh8 5. Rxh7+ Kg8 6. Rbg7#) 4. Rxg7 Rc8! { At all costs, black has activated their last rook and barely has enough to draw the game. } 5. Rxh7+ Kg8 6. Rbg7+ Kf8 $10 { Black is threatening Rc2+, with mate, so white has to bail out into a drawn rook endgame. } *


[Event "New York 1924"]
[Site "New York City, NY"]
[Date "1924.03.23"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Black "Savielly Tartakower"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Pawns aren't people! Developing plans II"]
[ChapterName "Capablanca's endgame technique"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/dYFcDtRq/C9IIK4hZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "5k2/p1p4R/1pr5/3p1pP1/P2P1P2/2P2K2/8/8 w - - 0 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We've already seen that the pawns aren't people mantra holds true in the endgame. In fact, with less pieces on the board, it's potentially even more true in the endgame because every piece matters that much more!

Here's a famous example of proper endgame technique from Capablanca. Capablanca knows that piece activity is crucial; it doesn't matter how many pawns you have. Capablanca's rook is already the master of the 7th rank, and his next moves showcase that he is willing to activate his king in the endgame at all costs. }
35. Kg3! { PRO TIP: Get your king up in the endgame! Sometimes it's worth even a pawn or two just to get this crucial endgame piece working to his maximum. } 35... Rxc3+ 36. Kh4 Rf3 { Tartakower had seen that both the c and f pawns would fall with check. But Capablanca knows this is irrelevant - his king is walking up the board to its most active square. } 37. g6! { Clearance for Kg5. } 37... Rxf4+ 38. Kg5 Re4 { Capablanca is now down two pawns, but he's not bothered. Pawns aren't people! } 39. Kf6! $18 { Of course white doesn't capture the f5 pawn. White is using the f5 pawn as shelter against black's rook on the f file.
Now white's king has security against all checks, white is threatening mate, the g6 pawn is very scary, and white has the world's most active rook and king. Black is completely dead, as shown in the rest of the game: https://lichess.org/study/xtDSXkyi/DfIe6e9B#77 } (39. Kxf5?? { Not accurate. Are you still under the delusion that pawns are people? Now our king is less secure once we reach the f6 square. } 39... Rxd4 40. Kf6 Rf4+! $10) *


