1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 { This study will be a deep exploration from the white side of the Najdorf. I would caution lower rated (probably even me included), aka <2200 lichess, away from learning these lines because people won't necessarily play them against you. Much more important is learning the ideas for white than the specific moves. } 6. Bg5 { Black has 2 main tries here: e6 and Nbd7, which will be explored throughout this study } *


[Event "Winning attempts for white in the Bg5 Sicilian Najdorf: 6...Nbd7 Bc4"]
[Date "2021.05.14"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B94"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Najdorf Variation"]
[StudyName "Winning attempts for white in the Bg5 Sicilian Najdorf"]
[ChapterName "6...Nbd7 Bc4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/WotymApK/73aK1pyE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[UTCDate "2021.05.14"]
[UTCTime "23:30:26"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 { I have determined that this is a tough nut to crack. In many lines, black is not obliged to play e6, "wasting a tempo," and can instead focus on hitting the center and/or quickly getting their knight to c5. I'm attaching two chapters that follow to show my point. For any players out there who play the black side of the Najdorf, those lines are my recommendation. } 7. Bc4!? (7. Qe2!? { Also interesting, and should be further explored... the idea of f4 and O-O-O is still on the cards, albeit with a slightly odd queen placement. }) 7... Qb6 (7... e6 8. O-O Qb6 (8... Qa5 9. f4! Qc5? 10. Bb3 e5? { While it appears like this move is winning a piece, it actually is a huge blunder! } 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Qh5!! g6 13. Qh4 { Grandelius, N. - Olszewski, Mi, 1-0, Bundesliga 2017-18, 2018, https://lichess.org/2ZAG1rh9 } 13... Be7 14. Rxf6 Nxf6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Qxf6 O-O 17. Nd5 Qxd4+ 18. Kh1 Re8 19. Rf1 $18) (8... Qc7? 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nxe6 Qc4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 $16 { Sometimes all you need is an open e file. } { [%cal Gd1f3,Gf1e1,Gd1h5] }) 9. Qd2 h6 (9... Qxb2?? 10. Bxe6 $18 { Whenever black gets greedy, we can take on e6. }) 10. Be3 Qc7 (10... Qxb2?? 11. Bxe6 $18) 11. Bxe6!? fxe6 12. Nxe6 Qb8 13. f4 Kf7 14. Rae1 Kxe6 15. Bd4 Kf7 16. e5 $13) (7... Qa5?! 8. Qd2 e6 9. O-O-O { Play similar to the main line, but the queen is not necessarily better placed on a5. }) (7... b5? 8. Bd5! Nxd5 9. Nxd5 { [%cal Gd4c6] } 9... Bb7 10. a4 $16) (7... Qc7?! { Threatens the bishop, but brings you closer to the optimal setup: } 8. Qe2 b5 9. Bb3 e6!? (9... Nc5? 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nd5 $16 { Practically the dream setup. }) 10. O-O-O { The stage is set for sacrifices on e6, d5, or f5. } 10... Be7? (10... Nc5?! 11. Rhe1 Nxb3+ 12. axb3 Bb7 13. Bxf6! gxf6 14. Nd5! $16) (10... b4!? 11. Nd5 $14) (10... Bb7!? 11. Rhe1 $16 { Good luck finding a move here as black that doesn't allow Bxe6, Nd5, or Nf5. } (11. Bxe6?! $14)) 11. Bxe6! $16) 8. Bb3 (8. O-O!? { Wei Yi - Van Wely, L., 1-0, 79th Tata Steel GpA, 2017, https://lichess.org/8M8rM9Wb } { I won't be going this route, but GM Jacob Aagaard thinks that if there is a refutation to this line, it's 8. O-O. }) 8... e6 9. Bxf6! { White takes the knight on f6 unprovoked in order to distract the d7 knight from its ultimate destination at c5 as in the normal Fischer-Sozin attack. } (9. Qd2?! Be7 10. O-O-O Nc5 $10 { Black gets what they want here... }) 9... Nxf6 (9... gxf6?? 10. Bxe6! fxe6 11. Qh5+ Ke7 12. Nxe6!! Kxe6 13. Qe8+ Be7 14. Qxh8 $18) 10. Qd2 Be7 (10... Nd7! 11. O-O-O Nc5 12. Kb1 Bd7 13. f4 { White quickly plays for f5 to attack the e6 pawn and possibly isolate the d pawn, and Nxb3 axb3 doesn't help black's situation. SF 13 seems to think that there's still an advantage for white here, although with best play it seems to simply be a playable middlegame for both sides. } 13... O-O-O 14. f5 $10) (10... Bd7!? { See the next chapter for this line }) 11. O-O-O Bd7!? { Delaying kingside castling for a few more moves is best. You don't want to commit the king to the kingside when white has a huge attack brewing. } (11... O-O!? 12. f4 Qc7!? (12... Bd7!? 13. e5! $14 { The other thematic push works instead. } (13. g4?! Nxg4! $14)) 13. g4! $14 { This pawn sacrifice just makes sense once black has committed to castling kingside. }) 12. f4 Qc5 13. g4 $14 { Not the only move, but certainly the most principled. White has play similar to the mainline Najdorf, except black's play is slightly slower. White should have a slight advantage, and the pawn is not going to be a good one to take. } 13... Nxg4?! (13... O-O-O 14. g5 Ne8 15. Kb1 $14) 14. Rhg1 Nf6 (14... e5 15. fxe5 dxe5 16. Nf5 Bxf5 (16... O-O-O 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Qe2 $16) 17. exf5 Nf6 18. Rxg7 Rf8 $18) 15. Rg5! (15. Rxg7 { Probably easier, but why give black anything? }) 15... e5 (15... Qc7 16. Rxg7 $16) 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Nf3 Qc7 18. Rxg7 (18. Bxf7+!? Kxf7 19. Nxe5+ Ke8 { A bit unclear - no need to risk it in such a good position. }) 18... O-O-O 19. Qe3 $16 *


