1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4?! { After all the following analysis, I'm convinced that black's position is healthier than white's because of how strong h6+g5 is. I recommend Bc4 instead. } (7. Bc4!? { See the other chapters for a deeper understanding of this move. }) (7. Qe2!? { Unexplored by me, but there have been some great games in this position as well. }) 7... Qc7 8. Qf3 h6 9. Bxf6 { Important to take on f6 here, because white's pieces are misplaced if black wants to play the g5 pawn sacrifice } (9. Bh4?! g5 10. fxg5 hxg5 11. Bxg5 Qc5! { [%cal Gc5g5] } 12. Be3 Ne5 13. Qe2 Neg4 14. Bg1 Bh6 $15) 9... Nxf6 10. f5! { White stops Bg4 and takes further control of the center now that the knight cannot quickly reach the e5 hole } (10. O-O-O?? Bg4) 10... Qc5 11. O-O-O g5!? 12. fxg6 Bg4 13. gxf7+ Kxf7 14. Qd3 Bxd1 15. Nxd1 Bg7 16. Qb3+ d5 17. Nf5 Nxe4 18. Bd3 Nf6 19. Re1 Rhe8 20. Nh4 Kg8 21. Bg6 e6 22. Bxe8 Rxe8 23. Qxb7 { Best play. White doesn't really have enough here for an advantage } *


[Event "Winning attempts for white in the Bg5 Sicilian Najdorf: 6...Nbd7 f4 Poisoned Pawn (black advantage)"]
[Date "2021.05.14"]
