1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 h6 { Entering the Browne variation } (8... Qc7 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4 { I play something different against this move order, so it won't transpose. See: chapters on the main line }) 9. Bh4 Nbd7 (9... Qc7 10. O-O-O Nbd7 { Transposes to the mainline }) (9... e5?! 10. Nf5 Bxf5 (10... exf4?? 11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. Nd5 $18) 11. exf5 $14) 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. Be2! { Not the only try, but the one I'm deeply exploring. It's important to counter black's "threat" of sacrificing a pawn with g5! in order to get the e5 square for their knight. From here, black has 4 serious tries that will be explored further in the next chapters. } (11. g4? g5! 12. fxg5 Ne5 13. Qg3 Nfxg4 $15) 11... g5? 12. fxg5 Ne5 13. Qe3 Nfg4 (13... Nh7?! 14. Nf3 Nxf3) 14. Bxg4 Nxg4 15. Qd2 $16 { Here black doesn't have compensation for the pawn, and will quickly come under an attack on the f file such as in the following unforced line. } 15... Rg8 16. Nf3 hxg5 17. Bxg5 Bxg5 18. Nxg5 Bd7 19. Rhf1 Ne5 20. Qf4 O-O-O 21. Nxf7 Rdf8?? 22. Nxd6+ Qxd6 23. Rxd6 Rxf4 24. Rxf4 $18 *


