1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 h6 9. Bh4 Nbd7 10. O-O-O Qc7 11. Be2 O-O 12. Qg3 { Again we go for our Qg3 maneuver, preparing an eventual e5. } (12. g4!? { A super interesting alternative as well: white gets on with their kingside attack. } 12... b5 13. a3 Bb7 14. g5 Nh7 $14 { Salimova, Nurgyul - Ratsma, Rosa, 1-0, 30th Czech Open A 2019, https://lichess.org/HG6kMHCh } (14... hxg5?! 15. Bxg5 b4 16. axb4 a5 17. b5 $16)) 12... Nc5 (12... b5?! 13. Bf3 { [%cal Gf3a8] } 13... Bb7?? 14. e5 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 (15... Bxf3 16. exf6 Qxg3 17. Bxg3 Bxd1 18. fxe7 Rfe8 19. Rxd1 $18) 16. Bxb7 Nh5 17. Qe1 Bxh4 18. Qxh4 Qxb7 19. Qxh5 $18) 13. e5! { Not the most popular move, and one with poor win-rates, but this basically transitions into a french, where white retains most of their attacking prospects. } (13. Bf3 { Given the chance, white will break with e5 and have a great game, but black can strike first and equalize: } 13... e5! 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Rac8 17. Rhe1 Na4 $10) 13... Nfe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Qf3 (15. Qe3?! Nc3!! 16. Bxe7 Nxd1! 17. exd6 Qxe7 18. dxe7 Nxe3 19. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 $14 { Not as convincing as the easy attack white gets in the main line. }) 15... d5 (15... Bxh4 16. Qxe4 $14 { Similar to the mainline, but with more pieces on the board, favoring white - the attacker. }) (15... dxe5 16. Qxe4 exd4 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Rxd4 $14 { This is the main way black has played this position, but it's clear white is the one with the more active pieces and potential attack. }) 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Bd3 { It's a French where black has committed to h6. Normal attacking ideas in the French directly apply to this position as well. For instance: } 17... Nc5 (17... f5?? 18. g4! $18) 18. Qe3 Nxd3+ 19. Rxd3 b5 20. g4 $16 *


