1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Qc7 8. Bxf6 gxf6 { We reach a Rauzer structure, where white continues in the normal Richter-Rauzer manner. } 9. Qf3 b5 10. a3 Nc6 (10... Be7?! 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Be2 Bd7 14. f5 O-O-O 15. Rd3 $16 { [%cal Gf3h5,Gh1d1] }) 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 12. O-O-O Rb8! (12... Bb7?! 13. f5! $16 { Always an important move to pressure the central light squares }) (12... f5!? 13. Qd3 Bh6 14. Kb1 Bxf4 15. exf5 Be5 16. Be2 { [%cal Ge2f3] } 16... Rb8 17. Bf3 Qc4 18. Qe3 b4 19. Qa7! { [%csl Gb8] } 19... d5 20. Nxd5! Rb7 21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. Bxb7 $18) 13. f5 b4!? (13... Qc5!? 14. Rd3! b4 15. axb4 Qxb4 16. Nd1 $10) 14. axb4 Rxb4 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Qxf6 Rg8 17. Be2 $14 { Black has an impressive amount of counterplay, but with Bh5+ and Rhf1 on the cards, white will be playing against black's central king. } *


