1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 (6... Qb6? 7. Bxf6 Qxb2?? (7... gxf6 8. Nd5 Qxb2?? 9. Rb1 Qxa2 10. Ra1 Qb2 11. Bb5+! $18) 8. Nd5 $18) 7. f4 Be7 { These moves can transpose. White continues the same in every variation. } (7... Nbd7 8. Qf3 Qc7 (8... h6 9. Bh4 Qc7 10. O-O-O Be7 { Transposing to the Browne variation }) 9. O-O-O Be7 { Transposing to the main line } (9... b5 { Transposing to the Anand variation })) (7... Bd7?! 8. Qf3 Nc6 9. O-O-O Nxd4 10. Rxd4 Qb6 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Rd3 $14 { With play similar to the Richter-Rauzer. }) 8. Qf3 Qc7 (8... Nbd7 9. O-O-O Qc7 { Transposing to the main line }) 9. O-O-O Nbd7 (9... Nc6?! 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. e5 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nd5 (12... Qxe5?? 13. Qxc6+ $18) 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Ne4 O-O (14... Qxe5?? 15. Nd6+) 15. Qg3 Nf5 16. Qf4 $14 { White has a great attack } { [%cal Gf1d3,Gd1f1] }) (9... O-O!? { A rare move, but since black has not weakened their kingside with a rash move like h6 before committing the king, it's objectively not bad. } 10. Bd3! (10. g4?! b5 11. Bxf6 Bxf6! 12. g5 Bxd4 13. Rxd4 Nc6 $15 { The usual play is too slow here because black has not committed the queenside knight. }) 10... b5? (10... Nc6!? 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. h4 h6?? (12... Rb8! $14) 13. g4 $18 { A classic fishing pole attack. Black cannot open the h file without getting mated. }) 11. e5! Bb7?? (11... dxe5 12. Ndxb5 $16 { The usual priyome works here with the rook hanging on a8. }) 12. Qh3 $18 { [%cal Gh3h7,Gd3h7,Gg5e7] }) (9... b5?? 10. e5 Bb7 11. Qg3 Nh5 (11... Nfd7?? 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 13. Ndxb5 $18 { [%cal Ge5d6] }) (11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Qxg7 $18) 12. Qg4! { Either the knight is trapped on h5 or Nxe6 will crush black in the center. } 12... g6? (12... Bxg5 13. Qxg5 O-O 14. Qxh5 $18) 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. exd6 Bxd6 15. Qxe6+ Be7 16. Bxb5+ axb5 17. Nxb5 Qc5 18. Nd6+ Qxd6 19. Rxd6 $18) 10. g4 b5 (10... h6!? { Transposing to the Giri variation }) (10... O-O? 11. Bh4! { White gets in g5 without trading any pieces. The kingside attack is too quick. } { [%cal Gg4g5] } (11. Bxf6? Bxf6 12. g5 Bxd4 13. Rxd4 $10)) 11. Bxf6! { White trades off the bishop in order to gain a subsequent tempo with g5! } 11... Bxf6?! (11... Nxf6 { The main line } 12. g5 Nd7 13. f5 Ne5? 14. Qg3 b4 15. Nce2 $16 { White has a great position after Bg2, Nf4, etc with a lot of pressure on the central light squares (f5, e6, d5). }) (11... gxf6? 12. f5 Ne5 13. Qh3 { Again we reach a Rauzer structure, but both knights will quickly pressure the e6 square, so black's center cannot be maintained. } 13... O-O!? { Fischer's move from 1957 } (13... b4 14. Nce2 $16 { [%cal Ge2f4,Gf4e6] }) 14. Nce2 Kh8 15. Nf4 Rg8 16. Be2! { The improvement. Now d5 is stopped. } 16... Qb7 (16... d5?! 17. fxe6 $16) 17. Rhe1 Qxe4 18. Qf1 Qb7 19. fxe6 fxe6 20. Ndxe6 $16) 12. Bxb5! Rb8! { The more interesting try. Black has sacrificed a pawn for queenside play. } (12... axb5?? 13. Ndxb5 Qc6!? (13... Qb6 14. Nxd6+ Ke7 15. e5 $18) (13... Qb8 14. Nxd6+ Ke7 15. e5 $18) 14. Rxd6! { The only line in which Rxd6 is necessary. Notice how in every line we're playing e5 hitting the bishop and undefended rook on a8. Since black defends the long diagonal with Qc6, we have to first kick the queen out in order to get the same crushing attack to work out. } 14... Qc5 (14... Qb7!? 15. Rxe6+! { [%cal Gb5d6] } 15... Kf8 16. Nd6! $18 { [%cal Ge6e8,Gd6b7] }) 15. e5 $18 { [%cal Gf6e7,Gf3a8] }) (12... Bxd4? 13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Rxd4 $16) 13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. Nde2 O-O (14... Qb6!? 15. b3 $14) (14... g5!? 15. e5! Bc6 16. Ne4 Bxe4 (16... dxe5?? 17. Nxf6+ Ke7 18. Qh3 exf4 19. Rhf1 Kxf6?? 20. Qh6+ Ke7 21. Qxg5+ $18) 17. Qxe4 $16) 15. g5 Be7 (15... Bxc3?! 16. Nxc3 Qb6 17. b3 Qb4 18. Kb2 $18 { White's attack is much scarier than black's. A sample line could be: } 18... a5 19. a3 Qc5 20. h4 a4 21. b4 Rfc8 22. Rh3 Rb6 23. h5 Qc4 24. h6 g6 25. Qf2 Rbc6 26. Rd4 Qa6 27. Rhd3 Kf8 $18) 16. Rhg1 $14 { Black has some play for the pawn, but it should be insufficient. } { [%cal Gf4f5] } 16... Rfc8 17. f5 *


