1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 Nbd7 9. O-O-O Qc7 10. g4 h6!? 11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4? g5 12. fxg5 Ne5 $17 { Transitions to a bad variation of the Browne variation }) 11... Bxf6! (11... Nxf6?? 12. h4 g6 13. f5 Qc5 14. g5 hxg5 15. hxg5 Rxh1 16. Qxh1 Nh5 17. Kb1 $18 { Black's pieces are a mess, and you cannot undermine the white center with the black king stuck on e8 still. } { [%cal Gf1e2] } 17... exf5?? 18. Nd5 fxe4 19. Qxe4 $18) (11... gxf6?? 12. f5 { Typical Rauzer ideas. h6 is not helpful to black. }) 12. h4 { Against basically every move, white will continue with g5 next, even if it means misplacing the queen. Playing slowly here loses to b5+Bb7+Nc5 attacking the center. Anish Giri recommends: } 12... Nb6!? { Anish's new idea. Only possible because extensive computer analysis shows it's sound. } (12... Qb6 { The old main line in this variation. } 13. Nde2 Nc5 14. g5 Be7 (14... hxg5?? 15. hxg5 Rxh1 16. Qxh1 Be7 17. Qh7 g6 18. f5 $18) 15. Qh5! { Threatening f5, giving white the d5 square. } { [%cal Gh5h8] } (15. g6?! fxg6 $14 { Probably too soon, black is happy to castle and put the bishop back on f6 asap. }) 15... g6! 16. Qf3 hxg5 (16... h5? 17. f5 $16) 17. hxg5 Rxh1 18. Qxh1 Bd7 19. Qh8+ Bf8 $16 { Kubicki, Tadeusz - Szczepankiewicz, Dariusz, 1-0, POL/C52/final (POL), 2009, https://lichess.org/ObYZG1Wq }) (12... Qc5? { An interesting try, but one that loses tactically. } 13. e5! dxe5 14. Ne4 { With threats against e6, f6, and possible forks in the air, white is close to winning. } 14... Qb6 (14... Qc7? 15. Nxe6!! fxe6 16. Nd6+ Ke7 (16... Kf8? 17. g5 Be7 18. fxe5+ Kg8 19. Qf7+ Kh7 20. g6#) 17. g5 hxg5 18. fxg5 $18) (14... Qd5? 15. Bc4! Qa5 16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Nxe6!! fxe6 18. g5 $18) 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 (15... gxf6 16. fxe5 Nxe5 (16... fxe5 17. Ne2 Qc6 18. Qg3! Qc7 (18... Qxh1 19. Bg2 $16) 19. Nc3 $16 { [%cal Gc3e4,Ge4d6] }) 17. Qxf6 $18) 16. fxe5 Nd7 17. g5 Nxe5 18. Qg3 $16) 13. Be2!? { Keeping more tension in the position ensures that black still needs to think. } (13. g5!? { The most testing line, but one which Anish analyzed to a roughly drawn position: } 13... Bxd4 14. Rxd4 Qc5! 15. Rd2 Bd7 16. Kb1 O-O-O 17. Be2 Na4 18. Nxa4 Bxa4 19. Rhd1 $10 { Both sides have their trumps in this position, but white has more space and pressure on the backwards d pawn. Forcing a weakness from black does not seem easy. }) 13... Be7! (13... Bxd4? 14. Rxd4 Qc5 15. Rhd1 $18 { The point of Be2. Since black does not gain a tempo on the d4 rook, this entire idea with Nb6->a4 or c4 is useless. }) (13... Bd7!? 14. g5 Be7! { Correct. Transposing to the main line. } (14... Bxd4? 15. Rxd4 Qc5 16. Rhd1 $16)) (13... Nc4?? 14. g5 Bxd4 (14... hxg5 15. hxg5 Rxh1 16. Qxh1! $18 { [%cal Gh1h8] }) 15. Rxd4 $18 { [%cal Gd4c4,Ge2c4] }) 14. g5 Bd7 (14... hxg5?? 15. hxg5 Rxh1 16. Qxh1 Bd7 17. Qh7 Bf8 (17... O-O-O 18. Qxg7 $16) 18. g6 $16) 15. g6 fxg6 16. Qg4 O-O-O 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 (17... Qc6?? 18. Nxd8 $18 { [%cal Gd8c6] }) 18. Qxe6+ Kb8 19. Qxg6 { White would be completely winning here if not for exactly one resource: } 19... d5!! 20. Qxg7 (20. Nxd5?! Nxd5 21. exd5 Qxf4+ 22. Kb1 Bf6 $10) (20. exd5!? Qxf4+ 21. Kb1 Bf6 22. Qg1!? Rd6! $10 (22... Qb4? 23. a3 Qa5 24. Qg3+ { Defending the a pawn with tempo allows for b4! } 24... Ka7 25. Ne4! Rhe8?? 26. b4! Qa4 27. Nc5 $18)) 20... Qxf4+ 21. Kb1 Bf6! 22. Qg1! { This extra tempo on the knight is crucial to white's advantage. } { [%cal Gg1b6] } 22... Rd6! { Another insane move that keeps all the positives of black's position alive. I believe Anish included this move in his analysis, but regardless it's still a good position for white, albeit probably drawn. } (22... d4!? 23. Rf1 Qd6 24. Nd5 Nxd5 25. exd5 $14 { White will consolidate with Bd3, and target the d4 and h6 weaknesses. }) 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. Rxd5 Rxd5 25. exd5 Rd8! { If black doesn't immediately attack white's weaknesses, white is winning after Qh2, trading into an endgame, up two pawns. } (25... Qe5? 26. Qh2! $16) (25... Qb4? 26. Qg3+ Ka8 27. Qb3 $16) 26. Qh2 Qxh2 27. Rxh2 Rxd5 $14 { Probably equal with best play due to the opposite color bishops, but white is up a pawn and so has chances if the rooks can stay on the board. } *


