1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 Qc7 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4 b5 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. g5 Nd7 13. f5 Nc5?! { Newer engines hate this move more and more } 14. f6 gxf6 15. gxf6 Bf8 16. Rg1 h5! { Stops our queen from reaching h5. On any other move, Qh5 and Rg7 can combine for lethal threats against the f7 pawn. } (16... Bb7? 17. Bh3! { Black cannot be allowed to castle queenside! } 17... h5 (17... b4 18. Nd5 exd5 19. exd5 Nd7 20. Qh5 $18) (17... O-O-O?? 18. Nd5!) 18. Rg7 b4 19. Nd5! $16) (16... Bd7? 17. Rg7 b4 18. Nd5 exd5 19. exd5 Qa5 20. Qe3+ Kd8 21. Bh3 Qxa2 (21... Bxh3?? 22. Nc6+ $18 { [%cal Gc6a5,Gc6d8] }) 22. Bxd7 Nxd7 23. Rxf7 $18) (16... b4? 17. Nd5 exd5 18. exd5 Nd7 (18... Bb7? 19. Bh3! Nd7 20. Qh5! $16 { [%cal Gd4e6,Gg1e1] }) 19. Nc6! { Stopping Ne5 so that black can no longer clog the e file } 19... Bb7 (19... Ne5?? 20. Nxe5 dxe5 21. d6 Bb7 22. dxc7! Bxf3 23. Bxa6!! $18) 20. Qe4+ Ne5 21. Kb1 { With Bh3 coming, black needs to bail out right now: } 21... Bxc6! 22. dxc6 Qxc6 23. Rd5 O-O-O 24. Rxe5 Qxe4 25. Rxe4 $14) 17. a3 { Taking a time out to prevent b4 allows us to continue possible threats against black's centralized king } (17. Rg7?! b4 18. Nd5 exd5 19. exd5 Nd7 $10) 17... Qb6 (17... Rb8? 18. Re1! b4?! 19. Nd5! $18 { The knight cannot be taken and when the queen moves, we even have time for axb4 with a winning advantage. }) (17... Bd7?! 18. Rg7! $16 { Prevents black from castling to safety. As in https://lichess.org/study/VWxPmx2b/yp6e39pZ }) (17... Bb7? 18. Bh3 $16 { Also stops black from castling: } 18... O-O-O? 19. Nd5 Bxd5 (19... Qa5?? { One humourous way a blitz game ended. } 20. b4! $18 { The queen is trapped! }) 20. exd5 $16) 18. Kb1 b4 (18... Rb8?! 19. Bh3! b4 20. Nd5! exd5 21. exd5 bxa3 22. b3 Bxh3 23. Qxh3 $16 { With all the open lines against black's king, white is borderline winning, even in the face of black's attack. } { [%cal Gg1g7,Gd4c6,Gg1e1] }) 19. axb4 Qxb4 20. Rg7! Rb8 (20... Bxg7?? 21. fxg7 Rg8 22. Nf5 exf5 23. Nd5 $18 { [%cal Gd5f6] }) 21. b3 { Thankfully, black must spend a turn defending the Nc6 threat. } (21. Bb5+!? { Belka, Wieland - Rozenberg, Dov, 1-0, Interzonal TT/7, 2013, https://lichess.org/kRewoKmz }) 21... Bd7 (21... Qa3?? 22. e5! { Threatening Qc6+ } 22... Bb7 23. Qe3 d5 24. Ncb5! axb5 25. Bxb5+ Kd8 26. Rxf7 $18 { [%cal Gd4e6,Ge3b6] }) 22. Bh3! { The threat of e5 and/or Nd5 means that white has full compensation if Bxg7 is ever played in this crazy attacking position. } 22... Qa3?! 23. e5! d5 { Practically forced, although even here the white attack might just break through. } (23... dxe5?? 24. Nxe6! fxe6 (24... Nxb3?? 25. Nc7+ Kd8 26. Rxd7+ Kc8 27. Rd6+ Kxc7 28. Qc6#) 25. Nd5! exd5 26. Bxd7+ Nxd7 27. Qxd5! $18 { [%cal Gd5d7,Gd5f7] }) 24. Bxe6! Nxe6! (24... fxe6?? 25. Nxd5 exd5 26. Qxd5 $18 { Qf7+ and Ne6+ are mate threats. Black is busted. }) (24... Bxe6?? 25. Nxd5!! Bxd5 26. Qxd5 $18) 25. Nxd5 $16 Nxd4?? 26. Nc7+ Kd8 27. Rxd4 Kxc7 28. Rxf7 $18 *


