1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Nbd7 8. Qf3 Qc7 9. O-O-O b5 { Black saves a tempo on the mainline and immediately launches a queenside atatck. } 10. Bd3 { White quickly develops the bishop to d3 so as to play Rhe1 and Nd5 in case black pushes b4 too quickly. } 10... Bb7 (10... b4? 11. Nd5! exd5 (11... Nxd5 12. exd5 $18) 12. Rhe1! Bb7 (12... dxe4 13. Bxe4 $18 { [%cal Ge4a8,Ge1e8] }) 13. exd5+ Kd8 14. Nc6+ Bxc6 15. dxc6 $16 { Marcinkiewicz, Jan - Lybin, Dmitry Vitalievich, 1-0, WC29/ct04, 2009, https://lichess.org/l7OhAmiK }) 11. Rhe1 Qb6!? { The main move and a serious option. } (11... h6!? { Old theory from the 70s. Black tries to play like the Browne variation, but without committing the bishop to e7. } 12. Qh3 O-O-O (12... Be7!? 13. e5! dxe5 14. Nxe6! { Just as in the Browne variation mainlines. } 14... fxe6 15. Bg6+ Kf8 16. Qxe6 Qc4 17. Qh3 $14) 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. a4 { An improvement on the famous Timman - Polugaevsky, 1973 game. } (14. Nd5!? { Timman, Jan H - Polugaevsky, Lev, 1-0, AVRO, 1973, https://lichess.org/530Z0wYs }) 14... bxa4 (14... b4? 15. Nd5! Nxd5 (15... Qa5?? { Polu's blunder against Timman still works. } 16. Nb3 { The queen is trapped! } 16... Qxa4 17. Nb6+ $18) 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. Bxa6+ $16) 15. Nxa4 Kb8 16. Be2! $14 { And the queen can swing over to the queenside on b3 or c3, reconnecting with the pieces. e4 can never be captured safely. } { [%cal Gh3c3,Gh3b3] }) (11... O-O-O?! { A disreputable move according to modern theory, but black scores well here practically because white's moves are difficult. } 12. f5! e5!? (12... Ne5? 13. Qh3 $16 { Lining up with c8 and there is too much pressure on e6. } 13... exf5?! (13... b4?! { Hangs a piece in a complicated manner. } 14. fxe6! bxc3 15. e7+! Rd7 16. Bxf6! cxb2+ 17. Kb1 Bxe7 (17... gxf6?? 18. e8=Q+ $18) 18. Bxe7 $18 { Complicated, but white is up a piece. }) 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qxf5+ $16) 13. Nb3 Be7 14. a4! { The key move to remember. Now black's entire setup is called into question. } 14... b4 15. Bxf6! Nxf6 16. Nd5! Nxd5 17. exd5 a5 18. Re4! $16 { Kotronias, Vasilios - Jobava, Baadur, 1-0, EU-ch 3rd, 2002, https://lichess.org/5ChHH6zc } { A model game showing how white can use the weakened light squares. }) 12. Nd5! Qxd4 (12... exd5?! 13. Nc6! dxe4 (13... Bxc6?? 14. exd5+ Be7 15. dxc6 Nc5 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Bf5 $16) 14. Bxe4 { This variation is designed around stopping black from running to the queenside. Note the white control over d7 and d8 throughout. } 14... Nc5 (14... Nxe4?? 15. Rxe4+ Ne5 16. Nxe5! dxe5 17. Rxe5+ Be7 18. Rxe7+ Kf8 19. Qb3 $18) 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qg4 Ne6 17. Bg6!! Kd7 18. Bxf7 Kxc6 19. Qxe6 { The threat is Be8+, winning everything. } 19... Qd8 20. Qb3 { If allowed, we want to reposition the queen to d4 (with checks), and then rook lift Rd3->c3. } { [%cal Gc6b6] } 20... Rc8 (20... Qc7?? 21. Rd3 $18) (20... Kb6 21. Qe3+ Kc6 22. Qc3+ Kb6 23. Qd4+ Kc7 24. Rd3 { [%cal Gd3c3] }) 21. Be6 Ra8 (21... Rc7?? 22. Bd5+ Kd7 23. Qh3+ { [%cal Gh3c8] } 23... f5 24. Qxf5#) 22. Qb4 Kb6 23. Rd3 $16 { Komarica, Borut - Jenkins, Richard, 1-0, SLO-USA 2019, https://lichess.org/HhHhZRu8 }) (12... Nxd5?? 13. exd5 Qxd4?? 14. Rxe6+!! fxe6 15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qxg6+!! hxg6 17. Bxg6#) 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bxb5! Qc5 (14... Qa7?? 15. Nxf6+ Ke7 16. Bxd7 Kxf6 17. Qg3 { [%cal Gg3g5] } 17... Ke7 18. Ba4 $18) 15. b4! Qxb5 (15... Qc8?? 16. Bxd7+ Qxd7 (16... Kxd7 17. Nb6+ $18) 17. Nxf6+ $18) 16. Nc7+ Ke7 17. Nxb5 axb5 { A forcing line where white has won the queen for three pieces. White needs to play with the initiative and open up lines against black's king to prove any advantage here. } 18. Qd3 Ra6 19. Qxb5 Rb6 20. Qd3 Bh6 21. g3 Ra8 (21... Rc8 22. a4 Ke8 (22... Ne5?? { White gets in b5 and kills off all the queenside pieces. } 23. Qb3 { [%cal Gb4b5] }) 23. Qa3 Rbc6 24. a5 $13 { White will sacrifice the c pawn, but roll with the a and b pawns, hopefully winning a piece in the process. }) (21... Ba6? 22. Qd2 Ne5 23. a4 { If we can get in b5, our queenside pawns will roll. } 23... Nc4 24. Qc3 Rc8 25. b5 Bb7 26. Qb4 $18 { [%cal Gb4d6,Gd1d6,Ge4e5,Gc1b1] }) 22. a3 e5! { Otherwise white plays e5 and crashes through! } 23. Kb2 exf4 24. e5! fxe5 (24... Nxe5?? 25. Qd4 $18 { [%cal Gd4b6,Gg3f4] }) 25. gxf4 Bg7 (25... Bxf4? 26. Qf5 Bh6 27. Rf1 $16 { While white forces black to defend on the kingside, we will push the queenside pawns forward and win on all sides of the board. }) 26. Qxh7 (26. Kb1!? { Potentially an improvement? }) 26... Bf6 27. fxe5 (27. Re3!? { May very well be an improvement... } 27... Kf8?! (27... Rh8 28. Qf5 Rxh2 29. fxe5 Bxe5+ 30. Rxe5+ Nxe5 31. Re1 $13) 28. Kc1 { The point of Re3: Now a3 is defended. } 28... exf4? 29. Qh6+ $18 { [%cal Gh6f4,Gh6f8] }) 27... Nxe5 (27... Bxe5+ 28. Rd4 Kd8 29. Rxe5 Nxe5 $13 { White has passed pawns on either side of the board, but is down material. If black can fully consolidate, white is probably worse. If white can use the initiative to force some material concession out of black, white should be better. }) 28. Re3 Rh8 29. Qf5 Bc8 30. Qf4 Be6 31. Kb1 $10 { Sacrificing the exchange for one of black's bishops makes sense in order to better rely upon a specific color complex. } *


