{ In my opinion, this is the second hardest puzzle in this study. If you're stuck, be sure to view the hint! }
1. Rd7!! (1. Rf3 { This move is technically mating, but Qxd4 complicates matters considerably... } 1... Qxd4 2. Rxf7+ Kg8 3. Rg7+ Kh8 4. Qxd4 c5 5. Qf6 Rf8 6. Rf7+ Kg8 7. Qg7#) 1... Bxd7 { Did you see the mate if Qxd4 was played instead? } 2. Qd6+! (2. Qh6+?? { After Ke7 there is no more follow-up! } 2... Ke7 3. Re3+ Kd8 $19) 2... Re7 3. Qh6+ Ke8 4. Rg8# { One of the hardest puzzles in this study! White plays Rd7 so that in the ensuing sequence, the d7 square is unavailable to the black king and he can be back-rank mated. } *


