{ One of the hardest mates in this study. Take your time and work backwards from the mate you would like to deliver. If you need a hint, just ask! }
1. g3!! (1. Bg5+? { A logical move, played by Nisman himself, but not winning after Bg5+ Qxg5 hxg5+ Kxg5 Qf6+!? Kh6 Qf4+ Kh7 Qb4 Bxd5 Qxb5 c5! Qxb2 c4, he was happy to escape with a draw. } 1... Qxg5 2. hxg5+ Kxg5 3. Qf6+ Kh6 4. Qf4+ Kh7 5. Qb4 Bxd5 6. Qxb5 c5 7. Qxb2 c4 $10) (1. Qxg8?? { A big mistake. Black has a perpetual after Qf4+, Qg4+, etc. }) (1. Bg7+?? { Doesn't work. After Rxg7 Qf8, black has Kh7 and there is no mate. }) (1. Be7?? { Unfortunately we'll only have a perpetual check here with Bf8+. }) 1... b1=Q 2. Bg5+ Qxg5 3. hxg5+ Kxg5 4. Qf4# { Only once you've seen the idea of mating with Qf4# will you ever find the sneaky g3 move to close the net. } *


