{ Emanuel Lasker, the 2nd world champion, is the first of Silman's endgame heroes.

This is game 15 of the 1907 WCC match. Lasker won +8=7-0 }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. O-O Be7 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. Nf5 d5 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Re1 Qh4 12. Be3 f6 13. f3 fxe5 14. fxe4 d4 15. g3 Qf6 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Rf1 Qxf1+ 18. Qxf1 Rxf1+ 19. Kxf1 { This is the starting position in Silman's book. } 19... Rb8 20. b3 Rb5! { [%cal Gb5a5,Gb5c5,Gb5e5,Gb5h5] } 21. c4?! (21. Nd2!? Rc5 22. Nc4 (22. c4!? dxc3 23. Nf3 $15) (22. Nf3 Rxc2 23. Nxd4 Bh3+!? $15) 22... Ba6 23. Ke2 Bxc4+ 24. bxc4 Rxc4 25. Kd3 Rc3+ 26. Kxd4 Rxc2 $15) 21... Rh5 22. Kg1 c5 (22... Ra5 23. Nd2 c5 $15 { Engine line looks optically worse - trapping the rook on the queenside. But on a6 it can see all sides of the board and indeed this is later what black does anyway. } { [%cal Ga5a6,Ga6f6,Gc8b7] }) 23. Nd2 Kf7 { The winning plan for black: Bg4, Ke5, d3, Kd4. } 24. Rf1+? (24. a3! Bg4 25. b4 $10 { Counterplay }) 24... Ke7 25. a3 Rh6! { Reverting to the engine's original idea: Ra6. } 26. h4!? (26. b4!? Ra6 27. Rf3 Bg4 28. Rb3 Bd1! 29. Rb1 Bc2 30. Rc1 d3 $17 { Winning at least a pawn. }) 26... Ra6 27. Ra1 { No weakness on b3 but now b4 is impossible. } (27. a4?! Rb6 28. Rf4 h5! $17 { [%cal Gc8g4] }) 27... Bg4 28. Kf2 Ke6 29. a4? (29. Nf3?! Bxf3 30. Kxf3 Ke5 $19 { Rf6+ followed by d3+Kd4 (the original idea) are winning. }) (29. e5! Kxe5 30. Re1+ Kd6 $17 { At least there are dreams of activity for white. }) 29... Ke5 30. Kg2 Rf6! { "White is completely helpless." No top GM would play this endgame so passively these days. } 31. Re1 d3 { Black achieves the original plan. } 32. Rf1 Kd4 33. Rxf6 gxf6 34. Kf2 c6! 35. a5 a6! { Zugzwang. No pawn moves. Ke1 allows Kc3, and knight moves hang e4. } 36. Nb1 { Some sources give Nf1 instead. It's all the same. } 36... Kxe4 37. Ke1 Be2 38. Nd2+ Ke3 39. Nb1 f5 { Restricting white's play even further. } 40. Nd2 h5 { Zugzwang again. Kf3 is coming next. } 41. Nb1 Kf3 42. Nc3 Kxg3 43. Na4 (43. Nxe2+? dxe2 44. Kxe2 f4 $19) 43... f4 44. Nxc5 f3 45. Ne4+ Kf4 { Dominating the knight. } 46. Nd6 c5! { Zugzwang again! The king cannot move without d2 or f2 winning. Moving the knight allows Ke3 and mate. } (46... Ke3?! 47. Nf5+ $19 { No progress yet. }) (46... Kg3?! 47. Nf5+ $19 { No progress yet. }) 47. b4!? { The only try. } (47. Nb7? Ke3 $19 { [%cal Gf3f2] }) 47... cxb4 48. c5 b3 49. Nc4 (49. c6? b2 50. c7 b1=Q+ 51. Kd2 Qc2+ 52. Ke1 d2+ 53. Kf2 Qc5#) 49... Kg3! 50. Ne3 b2 $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


[Event "Moscow"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1925.11.26"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Fyodor Ivanovich Dus Chotimirsky"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C88"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Closed"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Emanuel Lasker - Fyodor Ivanovich Dus Chotimirsky"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/rOiAYnNU"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ "Though he excelled in all kinds of endgames, his ability to save poor or even lost endgame positions has never been equaled through the span of chess history."

Dus Chotimirski is the inventor of the name "Dragon" for the Sicilian Dragon. He was awarded an IM title at their inception in 1950. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 Na5 9. Bc2 c5 10. d3?! (10. d4 $10 { The mainline Chigorin is a better try. }) 10... O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Nf1 Qc7 13. Bg5 Rb8 14. a3?! Be6 15. h3 h6 16. Bd2?! { White is losing tempo left and right. } 16... Nc6 17. Qe2 Bf8 18. a4 b4! 19. c4 { Black owns the d4 square. Something has already gone wrong. } (19. Ne3!? d5! $15) 19... Nd7 20. Be3 g6 21. N3d2 f5! 22. exf5 gxf5! 23. Qh5 Nf6 24. Qg6+ Qg7 25. Qxg7+ Bxg7 26. f4 { A good practical try. Stopping black's pawn mass. } 26... Nd7 27. Rad1 Bf7 28. Nb3 exf4 29. Bxf4 Nd4 30. Nxd4 Bxd4+ 31. Kh2 b3 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
Reuben Fine: "White's LSB is stalemated, his pawn structure hopelessly weak, his other pieces (with the exception of the DSB) have little or no freedom. In such positions, Lasker's conception of chess as a struggle has valuable practical applications: Lasker makes the win as difficult as possible for his opponent, and he seizes upon any slight chance which his opponent regard as unimportant."
Indeed, we know today that with best play chess is a draw. So top level players always talk about "chances" and "probabilities," not objective evaluations. Since they know that everything is drawn everywhere you look, you have to view the game as a struggle or there is no point playing chess at all. } 32. Rxe8+! (32. Bb1? Bh5! 33. g4 fxg4 34. Rxe8+ Rxe8 35. Ng3 Bg6 36. hxg4 Nb6! 37. a5 Na4 $19) 32... Bxe8 (32... Rxe8? 33. Bxb3 $10) 33. Bb1 Ne5 (33... Bxb2?! 34. Ne3 Bg6 35. Bxd6 Re8 36. Nd5 Bd4 $19 { White has unnecessary counterplay. }) (33... Bh5! 34. Re1 Ne5 $18 { More precise, technically. }) 34. Ng3 Bg6? { Lazy. Lasker's moves are forcing his opponent to either wake up and play well or lose the advantage. } (34... Bd7!? 35. Rd2 Nf7? (35... Bxa4! 36. Nxf5 Rf8 37. Nxd4 Rxf4 38. Ne2 Rf1! 39. Nc3 Be8 $19 { Opening up the position white white has an entombed bishop has to be correct. } { [%cal Ge8g6] }) 36. a5 Re8 37. Ne2 Bf6 { Bogoljubov's line is not convincing either. } { [%cal Gf6d8,Gd8a5] } 38. d4! $15 { "White's position is far better than it initially was" -Silman }) (34... Bxb2! { Silman's solution } 35. Nxf5 Bxa4 36. Nxh6+!? (36. Nxd6!? Rf8 $19) 36... Kh8! $19 { The win is complicated and requires calculation. }) 35. Rd2 Rb4?! (35... Nc6! 36. Bxd6 Re8 $17) 36. Ne2 Rxa4? (36... Bf2! $15 { Some chances still for black. }) 37. Nxd4 cxd4 38. c5! { White gets counterplay because black wasn't calculating carefully. } 38... Ra1?! (38... Bh5!? 39. cxd6 Nd7 40. Rf2! Ra1 41. Rf1! $10) 39. cxd6! Nd7 40. Rd1 { [%cal Gb1c2] } 40... Bf7 41. Re1!? (41. Bxh6!? a5 42. Re1 a4 43. Bg5 a3 44. bxa3 Rxa3 45. Re7! Nf8 46. Rb7 Ra1 47. Rb8 Be6 48. Bh6 Rxb1 49. Rxf8+ Kh7 50. Re8?! (50. Bg5! b2 51. Rb8 $16) 50... b2 51. Rxe6 Rh1+! 52. Kxh1 b1=Q+ 53. Kh2 Qb3 (53... Qxd3?? 54. d7 $18 { [%cal Gd7d8] }) 54. Rf6 Qxd3 55. d7 Qb5 56. d8=Q Qe5+ 57. Kg1 Qe1+ 58. Kh2 Qe5+ $10) 41... a5 42. Re7 Nc5?? (42... Nf8! 43. Re1 Nd7 44. Bxh6 $16 { Transposing to the earlier line. }) 43. Be5! Ra4 (43... Rxb1?? 44. Bxd4 Ne6 45. d7! Nd8 46. Re8+! $18) 44. Rc7 Ne6 45. d7 Rb4 46. Rc8+ Kh7 47. Rh8+ Kg6 48. Re8! { [%cal Ge8e6] } 48... Rb6 49. Bf4! (49. Rxe6+?! Rxe6 50. d8=Q Rxe5 $18 { Still winning, but this requires technique. }) 49... Nxf4 50. d8=Q Rc6 51. Re7 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } 1-0


