{ A famous endgame from the famous tournament annotated by Alekhine: NY 1924. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bd7 14. Nf1 Rfc8 (14... Rac8 15. Ne3 $14 { Sutovsky, Emil - Howell, David, 1-0, Corus-B, 2010, https://lichess.org/iBWX5TJM }) 15. Re2 (15. Ne3 $14) 15... Nh5 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Nxe5! Bxh3 18. Nxf7! Be6 19. Ng5 Bc4 20. Bd3 Rd8 21. Rc2 Nf4 22. Bxf4 Qxf4 23. Nh3 Qe5 24. Bxc4+ Nxc4 25. Qe2 { Consolidating the pawn } 25... Rd4 26. f3 Rad8 27. Rac1 Bc5 28. Kh1 Bb4 29. b3 Nd2 30. Ne3 Ba3? (30... Nxe4!! 31. fxe4 (31. Nf1! Ba3! 32. Re1 Ng3+! 33. Nxg3 Qxg3 $10) 31... Rxe4 { Regains the piece. } 32. Rc8 Rf8! 33. Rxf8+ Bxf8 $17) 31. Rd1 Bb4 32. a3 (32. Nf2 $18) 32... Ba5 33. b4 Bc7 34. f4! Nxe4 35. Kh2! Rxd1 36. Nxd1 Qe7 37. Rxc7?! (37. Ndf2 $18 { The king is safer in this position. Winning the material wasn't the most important option. } 37... Bxf4+!? (37... Re8? 38. Nxe4 Qxe4 39. Qxe4 Rxe4 40. Rxc7 $18) 38. Nxf4 Qh4+ 39. N4h3 Qg3+ 40. Kg1 $18) 37... Qxc7 38. Qxe4 { White has two knights vs the rook, and black's pieces are not truly active. But this is now very hard to win. } 38... Qc4 39. Qe7 Qc8 40. Ndf2 h6 41. Qa7 Qe6 42. Qb7 Qd5 43. Qb6 Rd6 44. Qe3 Re6 45. Qc3 Qc4 46. Qf3 Qc6 47. Qd3 Rd6 48. Qb3+ Qd5 49. Qb1?! Re6 50. Ng4?! Re2! { Black has now gotten active. } 51. Nxh6+!? gxh6 52. Qg6+ Kf8 53. Qxh6+ Ke8 54. Qg6+ Kd8 55. Qg3 Re8 56. Qf2 Rg8 57. Qb2 Qd6 58. Qc3 Kd7 59. Qf3 Kc7 60. Qe4 Rg7 61. Qf5 Re7 62. Ng5 Re3 63. Ne4 Qe7 64. Nf6 Kb8 65. g3 Rxa3 66. Kh3 Ra1 67. Nd5 Rh1+ 68. Kg2 Qh7 69. Qxh7 Rxh7 70. Kf3 Kb7 71. g4 Kc6 72. Ke4 Rh8?? { This is the starting position in Silman's book. } (72... Rd7! 73. Ne3!? a5! 74. bxa5 b4 $19) 73. Ne3! { White avoids Re8+, Kd4 Rd8. } (73. g5?? Re8+ 74. Kd4 Rd8 $19) 73... Re8+ 74. Kd4 Rd8+ 75. Ke4?? (75. Kc3! { Proven to be a draw. } 75... a5!? (75... Rd6!? 76. g5 Kd7 77. f5 Ke8 $10 { with a complicated position still not quite analyzed in MGP Part 1. }) 76. bxa5 Kc5 77. g5 b4+ 78. Kc2 b3+ 79. Kb2?? (79. Kc3! $10) 79... Rd2+ 80. Kxb3 Rd3+ $19 { Ed Lasker's idea. }) 75... a5! 76. bxa5 b4! 77. a6! (77. g5?? b3 78. Nc4 Kc5 79. Nb2 Rd2 80. Nd3+ Kc4! 81. Ne5+ Kc3 $19) 77... Kc5! (77... b3?? 78. Nc4 Kc5?! (78... Kb5! 79. Nb2 Kxa6 80. Ke3 Kb5 81. g5?? (81. f5! Rf8!? (81... Kb4?! 82. g5 Ka3 83. Nc4+ Kb4 84. Nb2 $10) 82. Kf4! $10) 81... Rg8! $19 82. Ke4!? Kb4 83. f5 Kc3! (83... Rxg5?? 84. f6!! $10 { [%cal Gf6f7,Gf7f8] }) 84. Na4+ Kc2 85. f6 Ra8! $19) 79. Nb2 Rd2 80. a7! $10) 78. a7! b3?? (78... Ra8! 79. f5!? (79. g5!? Rxa7 80. g6 Rd7! $19 { Preventing Nd1. }) 79... Rxa7 80. f6!? (80. Nd1!? Rd7 81. Nb2 Rd4+ 82. Ke5 Rd2! { Fianchetto'd knights! } 83. Na4+ Kb5 84. f6 Kxa4 85. f7 Rf2 $19) 80... Rd7! { Preventing Nd1. } (80... b3?? 81. Nd1! $10) 81. g5 b3 82. g6 b2 $19) 79. Nd1! Ra8 80. g5 Rxa7 81. g6 Rd7!? (81... Kd6!? 82. Kf5?? (82. Kd4! Rc7 83. g7! Rxg7 84. Kc4 $10 { Transposing to the game. Ah. When human analysis could compete with engine analysis. }) 82... Ke7 $19 { Shown in MGP Part 1 to be winning for black. }) 82. Nb2 { One move slower than in the earlier variation with Ra8 since the extra tempo was used on b3 which had few positives and indeed has given up the c3 square. } 82... Rd2 83. Kf3! Rd8 (83... Rxb2?? 84. g7 $18) 84. Ke4 Rd2 85. Kf3 Rd8 86. Ke4 Kd6 87. Kd4! Rc8 88. g7! Ke6 89. g8=Q+! Rxg8 90. Kc4 Rg3!? { Ed Lasker assumed he was winning here since he had defended the b pawn and would soon collect the f pawn.
"I remember I left the room at this stage to stretch a little and was congratulated upon my victory by Bogoljubov and others who were in the press room and told me the story of the game was ready to be released. However when I returned to the table, a rude shock awaited me." -Ed Lasker } (90... Rb8!? { Black loses the pawn according to Shereshevsky. But there's a deep flaw in his analysis. } 91. Kc3 Kf5 92. Nd3 Rb6 93. Nb2! (93. Kb2?? Ke4 $19) 93... Kxf4 94. Nc4! (94. Na4?? Rb8 95. Nb2 Ke3 96. Na4 Ke2 97. Nb2 Ke1 98. Na4 Kd1 99. Kb2 { Nc5 supposedly wins the pawn according to Shereshevsky. But black has a winning game nonetheless! } 99... Kd2!! 100. Nc5 Rb5! 101. Nxb3+ Kd3! { A rare R vs N win. The knight is dominated and pinned. } 102. Ka2 Kc3!! 103. Nc1 Kc2 $19 { Kxc1 and Ra5# are both threatened. }) 94... Rb8 95. Nd2! b2 96. Kc2 $10) 91. Na4 Kf5 92. Kb4 Kxf4 { With a study-like draw. } 93. Nb2! { There is no way to drive white's king away.
"The first thing I did was rush back to the press room and tell the reporters that they should kill their story. I was afraid they might have already released it, for everyone had been telling them I had an easy win. Then I returned for another analysis of the position. If I could reach d2 with the king by playing him in back of my rook, I could still win. And I made a last attempt." -Ed Lasker } 93... Ke4 94. Na4 Kd4 95. Nb2 Rf3 96. Na4 Re3 97. Nb2 Ke4 98. Na4 Kf3 99. Ka3! Ke4 (99... Ke2 100. Kb2 $10 { There is no approach towards the b pawn with the king! }) 100. Kb4 Kd4 101. Nb2 Rh3 102. Na4 Kd3 103. Kxb3 Kd4+ { 1/2-1/2  wins. } { A thirteen hour game due to all the adjournments! } 1/2-1/2


