{ Akiba Rubinstein, the uncrowned champion, is the second of Silman's endgame heroes. If not for WWI, it's possible he would have been WCC.

Here he faces none other than Emanuel Lasker! }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Bg5 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nc3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6!? (7... Be7!? $14 { Lasker and modern theory show that this is much better. The engine doesn't care. }) 8. e3 Be7 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Nxd5 Bxd4 12. exd4 Qg5 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Ne3 O-O-O?! (14... Bxg2 15. Rg1 Qa5+ 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Be4 18. Rg4 $14 { "But black should be comfortable" -Lasker }) 15. O-O Rhe8 16. Rc1! { "A very subtle move. What with the threat of Rc5 and d5, white retains his advantage, and he can certainly cope with black's threat of Rxe3" as shown in the game. -Lasker } 16... Rxe3 17. Rxc6+! bxc6 18. Qc1! { A double pin! } 18... Rxd4 (18... Re5?? 19. Qxc6+ Kb8 20. dxe5 $18) (18... Rg3?? 19. Qxc6+ Kb8 20. hxg3 $18) 19. fxe3! Rd7 20. Qxc6+ Kd8 21. Rf4! { [%cal Rc6a8,Rf4c4] } 21... f5 22. Qc5 Qe7 (22... Rd1+?! 23. Kf2 Rd2+ 24. Ke1 Qxg2 25. Qa5+! $18 { [%cal Ga5d2] }) 23. Qxe7+ Kxe7 24. Rxf5 Rd1+ 25. Kf2 Rd2+ 26. Kf3 Rxb2 { This is the starting position in Silman's book. } 27. Ra5! { The most active square for the rook. Tying down black's rook to b7. } 27... Rb7 28. Ra6! { Cutting off the king. } 28... Kf8 29. e4 Rc7 30. h4 Kf7 31. g4 { "Ultimately the advance of the kingside pawns will, hopefully, create an entry square on g6 or f6 for white's king." } 31... Kf8 32. Kf4 Ke7 33. h5 h6!? (33... Kf7!? 34. Kf5 Ke7 35. g5 Kf7 36. e5 Ke7 37. g6 h6 38. Re6+ Kd7!? (38... Kf8!? 39. Rd6 Ke7 40. Ra6 Rb7 (40... Kd7!? 41. Rf6!! $18 { Transposing to the above line }) 41. Rc6! Rd7 42. Rc8 $18 { [%cal Gc8g8] }) 39. Rf6!! Ke8 (39... gxf6?! 40. g7 Rc8 41. exf6 $18 { [%cal Gf5g6,Gf6f7,Gg7g8] }) 40. Rf7! Rxf7+ 41. gxf7+ Kxf7 42. e6+ Ke7 43. Ke5 Ke8 44. Kd6 Kd8 45. e7+ Ke8 46. Ke6 a6 47. a3! a5 48. a4 g5 49. hxg6 h5 50. g7 h4 51. g8=R#) 34. Kf5 Kf7 35. e5 Rb7 36. Rd6 Ke7 37. Ra6 Kf7 38. Rd6 { Black is helpless. Always repeat! } 38... Kf8 39. Rc6 Kf7 40. a3! $18 { "At this point I enjoy saying to my students, 'And here, upon seeing this crushing move, black resigned!'" It's actually zugzwang! } 40... Kf8!? (40... Re7!? 41. e6+ Kg8 42. Kg6 Re8 43. e7! $18 { [%cal Gc6c8] }) (40... Rd7? 41. e6+ $18) (40... a6?! 41. Rxa6 $18) (40... a5!? 41. Ra6 $18 Rb5!? 42. a4 Rc5 43. Ra7+ Kg8 44. Ke6 $18) 41. Kg6 $18 { And now we see the point of a3. Rb4 is not possible! } { [%cal Gc6c8] } 1-0


[Event "Vilnius All-Russian Masters"]
[Site "Vilna (Vilnius) RUE"]
[Date "1912.08.19"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Grigory Levenfish"]
[Black "Akiba Rubinstein"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Grigory Levenfish - Akiba Rubinstein"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/QUheIIeC"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Levenfish was awarded the GM title at its inception in 1950, although his best years were in the 1920s and 1930s. He was one of the fathers of the Russian school of chess. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bf4 Ng4 11. Bg3 Qg5 12. Qxg5 hxg5 13. Bc4 Ke7 14. Rd1 a5 15. h3 f6 16. Ke2 Ne5 17. Bxe5 fxe5 18. Na4 g4 19. hxg4 Bxg4+ 20. f3 Bd7 21. Nxb6 cxb6 22. a3 Rae8 23. Ke3 Bc8 24. Bb3 b5 25. c3 Bd7 26. Kf2 Rb8 27. Ra1 a4 28. Ba2 Be6 29. Bxe6 Kxe6 30. Ke3 d5 31. g3 g5 32. f4 gxf4+ 33. gxf4 dxe4 34. Kxe4 exf4 35. Kxf4 { This is the starting position in Silman's book. } 35... Kd5 { Heading for b3 to pressure b2. } 36. Rhd1+ Kc5! { No counterplay! } (36... Kc4!? 37. Rd4+!? (37. Rd2! Kb3 38. Rad1 Rbe8 39. Kg5!? Ref8 40. Kg6 Rhg8+ 41. Kh7 Rg3 42. Rh1 Rfg8 43. Rhh2 $19 { No rook trades are possible and white's king is somewhat safe. Still hard to convert. }) 37... Kb3 38. Rb4+ Kc2 $19 { Still winning, but not easy. }) 37. Rd2 Rhf8+ 38. Kg3 (38. Ke3?! Rbe8+ 39. Kd3 Rd8+ 40. Kc2 Rxd2+ 41. Kxd2 Rf2+ 42. Kd3!? (42. Kc1?? Rf1+ $19) 42... Rxb2 $19 { Zugzwang. Ra2 or Kc4 are coming. }) 38... Rb7! { [%cal Gb7g7,Gf8h8] } 39. Kh2 Rh7+ 40. Kg1 Rg7+ 41. Rg2 Rxg2+ 42. Kxg2 Rd8! { Getting to the 2nd by force. } 43. Kf3 (43. Rf1?! Rd2+ 44. Rf2 Rxf2+ 45. Kxf2 Kc4 46. Ke2 Kb3 47. Kd2 Kxb2 $19) 43... Rd2 44. Ra2 Rd1 { White is down a rook. } (44... Kc4?? 45. b3+ Kxc3! $19 { The trick doesn't even work here. }) (44... Rh2?? 45. b4+ { This is white's one trick. } 45... axb3 46. Rxh2 Kc4! $10 { and even here it's still drawn! }) 45. Ke2 Rh1 46. Kd3 Rg1 { Zugzwang. } 47. c4 Rg3+ $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


[Event "Karlsbad"]
[Site "Karlsbad (Karlovy Vary) AUH"]
[Date "1911.09.21"]
[Round "23"]
[White "Akiba Rubinstein"]
[Black "Alexander Alekhine"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D15"]
[Opening "Slav Defense: Süchting Variation"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Akiba Rubinstein - Alexander Alekhine"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/mx2nUTTS"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Played at the famous Karlsbad tournament, although the later 1923 edition was more of a super tournament than the 1911 edition. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Nc3 Qb6 5. Qc2 Bg4 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. e3 Ne4 8. Bf4 e6 9. Bd3 Qa5 10. O-O Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nb6 14. Qb3 Rd8 15. Be2 Bd6 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 O-O 18. f4 c5 19. Bf3 Rd7 20. a4 Nd5 21. Rfc1 g6 22. Qb5?! (22. c4!? Nb4 23. d5! $16) 22... Qxb5 23. axb5 cxd4 24. cxd4 b6 25. Rc4 f5? 26. Rc6 Kf7 27. Bxd5! exd5 28. Rac1 Rfd8 29. Kf1 Ke7 30. Ke2 Rd6 31. R6c3 R6d7 32. Kd3?! (32. Rh1! h5 { First white should provoke h5. } 33. Rhc1 Ra8 34. Ra1 Rb7 35. Rc6 Kf7 $18 { Now black has over-extended his position. }) 32... Ra8 33. Rc6 Rd6 34. Ke2? (34. Rc8! Rxc8 35. Rxc8 Rd7 $16 { A better version of the game. }) 34... Rxc6 35. Rxc6 Kd7! { No infiltration on the c file. } 36. f3 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
The king and pawn endgame is lost. So either black has to play passively (rarely a good idea) or actively. } 36... Re8? { Passive defense. Akiba turns on torture mode now. } (36... Rc8?? 37. Rxc8 Kxc8 38. e4! { A lost king and pawn endgame. } 38... fxe4?! (38... h6!? 39. e5 g5 40. g4! fxg4 41. fxg4?? (41. fxg5! hxg5 42. Kf2! Kd7 43. Kg3! gxf3 44. Kxf3 Ke6 45. Kg4 $18) 41... Kd7 $10 { White's king cannot enter! }) 39. fxe4 dxe4 40. g4! Kd7 41. Ke3 Ke6 42. Kxe4 h5 43. gxh5 gxh5 44. Kf3 Kd5 45. f5! $18) (36... a5! { Active defense. } 37. Rxb6 (37. bxa6?? Kxc6 $19) 37... Kc7! 38. Rc6+ Kb7 39. Kd2 a4 40. Kc2 Re8! 41. Rc3 Kb6 $10) 37. Kd3 { More active rook. Deep freeze on the queenside. Black's king needs to stay on d7 to prevent infiltration. g4 is coming. White has to be winning. } 37... Re7 38. g4 Re6 39. Rc1 (39. Rxe6?! Kxe6 40. gxf5+! $18 { Technically this position is winning. Silman shows a wall of text proving it.
"Why did Rubinstein avoid this? Quite simply, he knew that all king and pawn endgames are confusing [...] Why take the chance that he was missing a defensive nuance in the king and pawn endgame when he could quietly dole out the slow, patient death that the rook endgame offered." }) 39... Re7 40. Rh1 Ke6 41. Rc1 Kd7 42. Re1 Rf7 (42... h5!? $14 { Trading off a pair of pawns gives black some chances here. }) 43. Ra1 Kd6 44. Rc1 Kd7 45. Rc6 Rf8 46. Ke2 { The winning plan: activate the king. } { [%cal Ge2f2,Gf2g3,Gg3h4,Gh4g5] } 46... Rf7 (46... Rc8?? 47. Rxc8 Kxc8 48. gxf5! gxf5 49. e4 $18) 47. Kf2 Rf8 48. Kg3 Re8 49. Rc3 Re7 50. Kh4 h6 { Finally, a new weakness. g6 has become a target. } 51. Kg3 h5? { The right idea. The wrong execution. } (51... Re8!? 52. Kf2 Re7 53. Rc6!? Re6! 54. Rc2 Re7! { To meet Ra2 with Kd6. } 55. Rc6 Re6 56. Rc1 Re7! 57. Rh1! Rh7 58. gxf5 gxf5 59. Rg1 $18 { Decisive penetration finally. }) 52. Kh4! (52. gxh5!? gxh5 53. Kh4 Rg7 54. Kxh5 Rg1 $18 { Black has some counterplay in this engine line too. }) 52... Rh7 (52... hxg4! 53. fxg4 Rh7+ 54. Kg5 fxg4 55. Kxg4 Rh1 $16 { Transposes to the game. }) 53. Kg5?! (53. gxf5! gxf5 54. Kg5 h4 55. Kxf5 h3 56. Rc1 h2 57. Rh1 $18 { The h pawn will be lost eventually. }) 53... fxg4 54. fxg4 (54. Kxg6?? g3!! 55. Kxh7 h4? (55... g2!! 56. Rc1 h4 57. Rg1 h3 58. Kg7! h2 59. Rxg2 h1=Q 60. Rg5 $15 { Some fortress, but black will win this 10/10 times. }) 56. Ra3 h3 57. Rxa7+ Ke6 58. Rg7 h2 59. Rg6+! Kf7 60. Rg7+ Kf6 61. Rg6+ $10) 54... hxg4 55. Kxg4 (55. Kxg6?? Rh8 56. Kg7 Rh3! $10) 55... Rh1 { Alekhine gets his activity after all. } 56. Kg5?! (56. Rc6! { Most precise. } 56... Rg1+ 57. Kf3 Rb1 58. Rxg6 Rxb5 59. Rg7+ $18) 56... Rb1! (56... Rg1+? 57. Kf6 Kd6 58. Rc6+ Kd7 59. Ke5 $18 { [%cal Ge5d5] }) 57. Ra3 (57. Kxg6?! Rxb5 58. Ra3 a5 $10) 57... Rxb5?? (57... Ke6! 58. Rxa7 Rg1+! 59. Kh4 Re1 $10 { Counterplay. }) 58. Rxa7+ Kd6 59. Kxg6 Rb3 60. f5! Rxe3 61. f6 { Technique is still required, but this is now winning for white. } 61... Rg3+ 62. Kh7 (62. Kf7?? Rg4 63. Ra4 b5 64. Rb4 Rf4 $10 { Black's rook is on the best square, while white's rook is passively defending if there is no desire to trade pawns and reach a dead drawn rook endgame. }) 62... Rf3 (62... Rh3+?! 63. Kg8 Rg3+ 64. Rg7 $18 { [%cal Gf6f7,Gf7f8] }) (62... Rg4?! 63. f7! { This is the key difference between Kh7 and Kf7. The f pawn is free to push, so white doesn't need to defend d4. } 63... Rf4 64. Kg7 $18 { Transposing to the game. }) 63. f7 Rf4 64. Kg7 Rg4+ 65. Kf6! (65. Kf8?? Rxd4 $10 { Black will return to the f file and the passed pawn generated counterplay. }) 65... Rf4+ 66. Kg5! Rf1 67. Kg6! { Similar to a variation of the Lucena. The point is that black's rook isn't on f4 pressuring both pawns now. } 67... Rg1+ (67... Rf4?! 68. Ra8 Ke7 69. Re8+ $18 { [%cal Gf7f8] }) 68. Kf6 Rf1+ 69. Kg7 Rg1+ 70. Kf8 Rd1 71. Ke8 { Exactly like a Lucena. } 71... Re1+ 72. Kd8! Rf1 73. Rd7+ Kc6 74. Ke8! Rf4 (74... Kb5? 75. Rxd5+ $18) 75. Re7! Kb5 76. Rc7! { 1-0 White wins. } { No counterplay! Alekhine resigns. } 76... Re4+!? 77. Kd7 Rf4 78. Ke7 Re4+ 79. Kf6 Rf4+ 80. Ke5 Rf1 81. Kxd5 $18 { Black cannot move a muscle still, and the f pawn remains a winning asset. } 1-0


[Event "Capablanca - Marshall"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1909.06.23"]
[Round "23"]
[White "Frank James Marshall"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D33"]
[Opening "Tarrasch Defense: Rubinstein System"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Frank James Marshall - Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/iluyOQYy"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Jose Raul Capablanca, the 3rd WCC, is the third of Silman's endgame heroes.

I have already thoroughly analyzed this endgame in my public endgame study ( https://lichess.org/study/xtDSXkyi/SclTFf1q ), so I don't do it much justice here. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Be6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bg5 Ne4 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Ne5 Nxd4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. e3 Nf3+ 14. Nxf3 exf3 15. Qxf3 O-O 16. Rfc1 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
Black already has the queenside pawn majority. } 16... Rab8 17. Qe4 Qc7 { Avoiding Bh3 threats. } 18. Rc3 b5! 19. a3 c4 20. Bf3?! (20. Rd1!? Rfd8 21. Rcc1 $15 { Lasker's suggested defense. }) 20... Rfd8 21. Rd1 Rxd1+ 22. Bxd1 Rd8 23. Bf3? (23. Rc1!? { The rook needs to get back into the game and from c3 it will only get hit with an eventual b4 with tempo. } 23... g6 24. Qc2 $17) 23... g6 24. Qc6 Qe5! (24... Qxc6?! 25. Bxc6 { Counterplay against the pawn chain although even here black has: } 25... Bh3! 26. f4!? (26. Bxb5?? Rd1#) (26. Bg2?? Rd1+! 27. Bf1 Rxf1#) 26... Rd1+ 27. Kf2 Rd2+ 28. Ke1 Rxb2 $19) 25. Qe4 Qxe4 26. Bxe4 { Now the queen trade makes sense as white's bishop is no better on e4 than on f3. The queenside pawn majority will roll next. } 26... Rd1+ { "Very important. Black must stop the approach of the white king by means of Bc2 followed by Kf1, etc" -Capablanca } 27. Kg2 a5! 28. Rc2 b4 29. axb4 axb4 30. Bf3 Rb1 31. Be2 (31. Rd2?! Ra1! (31... b3!? 32. Bd1!? (32. Be2!? Rc1 33. Bd1 c3 34. bxc3 b2 $19) 32... Ra1 33. Kf3 c3 34. bxc3 b2 $19 { An easy variation, similar to the game. }) 32. Be2 Ra2 33. Kf1 c3 34. Rd8+ Kg7 35. bxc3 Ra1+ 36. Rd1!? (36. Kg2?! bxc3 37. Bd1 Ra2 $19 { [%cal Gc3c2,Gc2c1] }) 36... Rxd1+ 37. Bxd1 b3! 38. Ke1 b2 39. Bc2 Ba2 $19 { Kasparov's variation. }) 31... b3 32. Rd2 (32. Rc3?! Rxb2 33. Bxc4 Rc2! $19 { Simple tactics }) 32... Rc1 33. Bd1 (33. Kf3?! Rc2 34. Rd4 c3 35. bxc3 b2 36. Rb4 Bd5+! 37. e4 Rxc3+ 38. Kf4 Bb3 $19 { [%cal Gb2b1] }) 33... c3! 34. bxc3 b2! 35. Rxb2 (35. Bc2? Rxc2! $19) 35... Rxd1 36. Rc2 Bf5! 37. Rb2 Rc1! { Rooks belong behind passed pawns. } 38. Rb3 Be4+ 39. Kh3 Rc2 40. f4 h5 41. g4 hxg4+ 42. Kxg4 Rxh2 43. Rb4 f5+ 44. Kg3 Re2 45. Rc4 Rxe3+ 46. Kh4 Kg7 47. Rc7+ Kf6 48. Rd7 Bg2 49. Rd6+ Kg7 $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


[Event "American National"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1913.01.22"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Black "David Janowski"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C48"]
[Opening "Four Knights Game: Spanish Variation, Ranken Variation"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Jose Raul Capablanca - David Janowski"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/bhqImKyQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Capablanca won the first 10 games of this tournament in a row, including this game against WCC contender Janowski. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 a6 5. Bxc6 { The famous exchange Ruy Lopez torture by Capablanca. } 5... dxc6 6. O-O Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. Qe2 Bd6 9. d3 Qe7 10. Nd1 O-O-O 11. Ne3 Bg6 12. Nh4 Rhg8 13. Nef5 Qe6 14. f4 Bxf5 15. Nxf5 exf4 16. Bxf4 Bc5+ 17. Be3 Bf8 18. Qf2 Rd7 19. Bc5! Bxc5 20. Qxc5 Kb8 21. Rf2 Ne8 22. Raf1 f6 23. b3 Nd6 24. Rf4 Nxf5 25. Qxf5 Qxf5 26. Rxf5 Re8 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
The position should be drawn, but white has more active rooks, a slight space advantage, and a superior pawn structure. } 27. g4 { Preparing g5. } 27... b6 28. b4! { Prophylaxis. Black is not allowed to gain space with c5! } 28... Kb7 29. Kf2 { Get your king up in the endgame. } 29... b5 30. a4! Rd4!? (30... bxa4!? 31. Ra1 { Black's queenside is shattered. } 31... Re5 32. Rxa4 Rxf5+ 33. gxf5 g6! $14) 31. Rb1 Re5? (31... a5! 32. axb5 Rxb4! 33. Rxb4! (33. bxc6+?! Kxc6 34. Ra1 a4 35. Ra5 Rb2 $10 { Counterplay! }) 33... axb4 34. Rc5 Re5! (34... Re6? 35. Ke3 Kb6 36. Rxc6+ Rxc6 37. bxc6 Kxc6 38. Kd4 $18) 35. bxc6+ Kb6 36. Rc4 Kb5 $14 { Some counterplay. White's extra pawn is not yet felt. }) 32. Ke3! Rd7 33. a5! { No more queenside counterplay for black. } 33... Re6 (33... c5? 34. bxc5 Kc6 35. d4 $18) (33... Rxf5? 34. gxf5 g6 35. Rf1! $18) 34. Rbf1 Rde7 35. g5! { Black's counterplay has been squashed. Now it's black to plan A. } 35... fxg5 36. Rxg5 Rh6 37. Rg3 Rhe6!? (37... Rh5!? 38. d4 Rh4 39. e5 $18 { Progress. }) 38. h4 g6 (38... Rh6!? 39. Rg4 $18 { Progress. }) 39. Rg5 h6 40. Rg4 { A new target: g6. } 40... Rg7 41. d4 Kb8 42. Rf8+ Kb7 43. e5 { Progress. Black is running out of moves. } 43... g5!? (43... Ree7?! 44. Rf6 $18 { Another way to lose as black. }) 44. Ke4 Ree7 45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Rf5 { More active king. More active rooks. Better pawn structure. About to win a pawn. Black is clearly lost. } 46... Kc8 47. Rgxg5 Rh7 48. Rh5! { No counterplay! } 48... Kd7 (48... Rhg7!? 49. Rfg5! { No counterplay! } 49... Rgf7 50. Rg8+ Kd7 51. Rhh8 $18) 49. Rxh7 Rxh7 50. Rf8 Rh4+ 51. Kd3 Rh3+ 52. Kd2 c5!? (52... Ke6!? 53. Ra8 Kd5 54. Rxa6 Kxd4 55. Rxc6 Rh2+ 56. Kc1 Kxe5 57. Rxc7 $18 { [%cal Ga5a6,Ga6a7,Ga7a8] }) 53. bxc5 Ra3 54. d5 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { Nothing left to play for. Every move queens and checkmates black's unfortunate king. } 1-0


[Event "Lasker - Capablanca World Championship Match"]
[Site "Havana CUB"]
[Date "1921.04.08"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D61"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Orthodox Defense, Rubinstein Variation"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Emanuel Lasker - Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/henWKmXQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ This game was the 10th round of the 1921 WCC. Capablanca was already up one game in the match. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. Qc2 c5 8. Rd1 Qa5 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bh4 cxd4 11. exd4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nb6 13. Bb3 Bd7 14. O-O Rac8 15. Ne5 Bb5 16. Rfe1 Nbd5 17. Bxd5?! (17. Bxf6! Bxf6 (17... Nxf6? 18. Ng6! $18) 18. Bxd5 exd5 $10) 17... Nxd5 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 { Trading pieces in an IQP position? Lasker clearly was no longer on his A game at age 58. } 19. Qb3 Bc6 (19... Ba6!? 20. Nd7 Bc4! { A miss by Capablanca } (20... Rfd8?! 21. Nc5 b6 22. Nxa6 Qxa6 23. d5! $10 { Capablanca's fear }) 21. Qc2 Rfd8 $15) 20. Nxc6 bxc6! { Karpov would later use this pawn recapture against Korchnoi in their 1978 match. d5 is stopped forever and is therefore fixed as a target. c6 is less of a target than d5 simply because it is harder to attack. } 21. Re5 Qb6 22. Qc2 Rfd8 23. Ne2?! { Too passive according to Capablanca. } (23. Na4!? Qa6 24. Rc5 { Counterattacking was necessary. } 24... Nf5! $15) 23... Rd5 24. Rxd5 cxd5 25. Qd2 Nf5 26. b3 { "In order to free the queen from the defense of the b pawn and also to prevent Rc4 at any stage." -Capablanca } 26... h5! { Prophylaxis against g4. } 27. h3?! { Trying to prepare g4, but now Capablanca can fix the kingside favorably. } 27... h4! { "To tie up white's king side. Later on it will be seen that white is compelled to play g4 and thus further weaken his game." -Capablanca } 28. Qd3 Rc6 29. Kf1 g6 30. Qb1 Qb4 { Preventing b4. } 31. Kg1 a5 { Black uses the minority attack to create a further weakness. } 32. Qb2 { a3 is threatened. } 32... a4! { Before white can kick the queen away with a3, Capablanca achieves the minority attack. } 33. Qd2 Qxd2 34. Rxd2 axb3 35. axb3 { This is the starting position in Silman's book. } 35... Rb6 { "In order to force Rd3 and thus prevent the white rook from supporting his b pawn by Rb2 later on. It means practically tying up the white rook to the defense of his two weak pawns." -Capablanca
"An accurate move that forces white's rook into a clumsy position." } 36. Rd3 (36. Rb2? Rb4 $17) (36. Nc1? Rb4 $17 { [%cal Gb4d4] }) 36... Ra6! { Now that white's rook is not able to infiltrate, black can get even more active. } 37. g4!? { Creates more weaknesses. But what else can white do? } (37. Rd1?! Ra2! 38. Kf1 Rb2 39. Nc1 Nd6 40. Re1!? (40. Ke1!? Ne4 41. f3 Nc3 42. Rd2 Rb1 43. Rc2 Nb5! $19) 40... Rd2 41. Ne2 Nb5 $17) (37. Nc3?! Ra1+ 38. Kh2 Rc1 39. b4 Rc2 40. Kg1 Rb2 41. b5 Rb4 $17 { Kasparov variation. } { [%cal Gb4d4,Gb4b5] }) 37... hxg3 38. fxg3 (38. Nxg3?! Ra1+ 39. Kh2 (39. Kg2? Nh4+! 40. Kh2 Rb1 $19) 39... Nd6 40. Kg2 Rb1 $17) 38... Ra2 39. Nc3 Rc2! { Threatening Nxd4. } 40. Nd1?! (40. Nb5!? { The only real chance. } 40... g5 41. g4 Nh4 42. Kf1 $17 { Similar to the game, although perhaps white's knight is able to accomplish more from b5 than d1. }) 40... Ne7 { Nc6 is the goal. } 41. Ne3 (41. b4? Rc1 42. Kf2 Rb1 $19 { [%cal Gb1b4] }) 41... Rc1+ 42. Kf2 Nc6 43. Nd1 Rb1!? (43... Nb4!? 44. Rd2 Rb1 45. Nb2 { But black does not need to trap their knight. Simple building moves like Kg7 still keep an iron grip on the position. } 45... Rxb2?? (45... Kg7 $19) 46. Rxb2 Nd3+ 47. Ke2 Nxb2 48. Kd2! $10 { Both Capablanca and Silman point out this line. }) 44. Ke2?! { Lasker deliberately walks into the trick. } (44. Ke1!? Na5 45. Kd2 Rxb3 46. Rxb3 Nxb3+ $19 { Best defense, but Capablanca wins this 9/10 times. }) 44... Rxb3! { "This is typical of Capablanca, who often made use of 'petite combinations'" } 45. Ke3 Rb4 46. Nc3 Ne7 47. Ne2 Nf5+ 48. Kf2 g5 49. g4 Nd6 { The h pawn is a permanent target as well as the d pawn. Black is already up a pawn. The position is clearly lost. } 50. Ng1 Ne4+ 51. Kf1 { Cat and mouse mode activated. } 51... Rb1+ 52. Kg2 Rb2+ 53. Kf1 Rf2+ 54. Ke1 Ra2 { I've seen Capablanca's quote "All these moves have a meaning. The student should carefully study them." several times. It remains a meme to me because there are clearly other completely winning moves that black can play. Capablanca's play was fine but not in any way forced in order to overcome Lasker's resistance. } 55. Kf1 Kg7 56. Re3 Kg6 57. Rd3 f6 { Finally Capablanca makes progress. Kd6+e5 is the plan. } 58. Re3 Kf7 59. Rd3 Ke7 60. Re3 Kd6 61. Rd3 Rf2+ { Cat and mouse mode. } 62. Ke1 Rg2 63. Kf1 Ra2 64. Re3 e5 { The sealed move after a second adjournment. } 65. Rd3 (65. Ne2!? Nd2+ 66. Kf2 e4 67. Rc3 Nf3 68. Ke3 Ne1 69. Kf2 Ng2! $19 { Capablanca's analysis during the adjournment. }) (65. Nf3!? Nd2+ 66. Nxd2 Rxd2 $19) 65... exd4 { Creating a passed d pawn. } 66. Rxd4 Kc5 67. Rd1 d4 68. Rc1+ Kd5 $19 { "The Black pawn will advance and White will have to give up his knight for it. This is the finest win of the match and probably took away from Dr. Lasker his last real hope of winning or drawing the match." -Capablanca } 0-1


[Event "World Team-ch 1st"]
[Site "Lucerne SUI"]
[Date "1985.11.17"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Vasily Smyslov"]
[Black "Xu Jun"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A08"]
[Opening "Zukertort Opening: Reversed Grünfeld"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Vasily Smyslov - Xu Jun"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/BEXp9ZSQ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Vasily Smyslov, the 7th WCC, is the fourth of Silman's endgame heroes. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 c5 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. e3 b6 9. Nbd2 Ba6 10. Re1 Rc8 11. a3 Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Ne5 f5 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. f3 exf3 16. Qxf3 Rc7 17. d5 Bb7 18. c4 exd5 19. cxd5 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. Rad1 Rd7 22. e4 Re8 23. Qd3 fxe4 24. Rxe4 Rxe4 25. Qxe4 Re7 26. Qd3 Rf7 27. Rf1 Qd4+ 28. Qxd4 Rxf1+ 29. Kxf1 cxd4 30. Ke2 Ba6+ 31. Kf3 Kf7 32. Ke4 d3 33. Ke3 Kf6 34. Be4 d2 35. Kxd2 h6 36. Ke3 Ke5 37. Bf3 Kd6 38. Kd4 Bb7 39. b4 Ba8 40. a4 Bb7 41. a5 bxa5 42. bxa5 Ba6 43. Ke4 Bc8 44. Be2 Bd7 45. g4 Be8 46. Bf3 Bd7 47. Kf4 Bc8 48. g5! Bd7 49. Be4 Bc8?? (49... hxg5+ 50. Kxg5 Be8 $10 { The wall cannot be broken. }) 50. gxh6 gxh6 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
White wants to get the king to f5 to win h6. White wants to get the king to e5 to push the d pawn. White wants to trade bishops in order to win the king and pawn endgame. There are too many winning plans, so black cannot stop them all, even though it takes Smyslov 7 moves to achieve one of them. } 51. Bf5! Ba6 (51... Bb7?? 52. Be6 { Kf5 is inevitable now unless... } 52... Bxd5 53. Bxd5 Kxd5 54. Kf5 Kc5 55. Kg6 Kb5 56. Kxh6 Kxa5 57. Kg5! Kb4 58. h4 a5 59. h5 a4 60. h6 a3 61. h7 a2 62. h8=Q $18) (51... Bxf5?? 52. Kxf5 Kxd5 53. Kg6 Ke5 54. Kxh6 Kf6 55. a6! Kf7 56. Kg5 Kg7 57. Kf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5a7] }) 52. Be6 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 52... Bd3 53. Bf7 (53. Kg4?! Bg6 { No progress. }) 53... Ke7!? (53... Bc2!? 54. Kg4! Ke7! (54... Bd1+?! 55. Kf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5f6,Gf6g7] }) 55. Be6! Bg6 (55... Kf6?! 56. Kh5 Kg7 57. d6 Bd1+ 58. Bg4 $18) (55... Bd1+?! 56. Kf5 Bc2+ 57. Ke5 $18 { [%cal Gd5d6] }) 56. Bf5! Bf7 57. Be4 Kf6!? (57... Kd6?! 58. Kf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5f6] }) 58. Kf4 Bg8 59. d6! Be6 (59... Ke6?? 60. Bd5+! Kxd5 61. d7 $18) 60. Bf3 Bd7 61. Bg4! $18 Bc6!? 62. Bc8 Bb5 63. Ke4 Bc6+ 64. Kd4 { [%cal Gd4c5] } 64... Bg2!? 65. Kc5 Kf7 66. Bd7! Kf6 67. Kb5 Ke5 68. Bc6 Bf1+ 69. Kc5 $18 { [%cal Gd6d7,Gd7d8] }) 54. Bh5 Kd6 (54... Kf6?! 55. Bg4 Bc4 56. d6 $18) 55. Bf3 { [%cal Gf4f5,Gf4g4,Gg4h5] } 55... Bc2!? (55... Bh7!? 56. Bg2 Bg6 57. Be4! Bf7 58. Kf5 $18) 56. Be4! Bd1 57. Kf5! Be2 58. h4!? (58. Kg6!? $18) 58... Bh5 59. Kf6 Be2 60. Bg2! { Avoiding Ke5 with tempo at a later date. } 60... Bg4 61. Kg6 h5 { A new weakness is fixed on a light square. } 62. Kf6 { Black's Ke5 is prevented forever. } 62... Be2 63. Be4 Bg4 64. Bh1 Be2 65. Kf5 Bg4+ 66. Kf4 Be2 67. Bf3 $18 { 1-0 White wins. } 67... Bxf3!? (67... Bb5!? 68. Kg5 Be8 69. Bxh5 $18) 68. Kxf3 Kxd5 69. Kf4 Kc5 70. Kg5 Kb5 71. Kxh5 Kxa5 72. Kg5 Kb4 73. h5 a5 74. h6 a4 75. h7 a3 76. h8=Q $18 1-0


