{ From the USSR vs UK match in 1947. USSR won 15-5. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 Nd4 7. Nce2 Ne7 8. c3 Nxe2 9. Nxe2 d6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qd2 Re8 12. d4 Qc7 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Rfd1 b6 15. Qd6 Qxd6 16. Rxd6 Ba6 17. Bf1 Be5 18. Rd2 Rad8 19. Rad1 Nc6 20. f4 Bb8 21. e5 Rxd2 22. Rxd2 Rd8 23. Rxd8+ Nxd8 24. b3 Kg7 25. c4 f6 26. exf6+ Kxf6 27. Nc3 Bb7 28. Bg2 Bxg2 29. Kxg2 Nc6 30. Kf3 Nb4 31. Bd2 Ke7 32. Ke4 Nc6 { This is the starting position in Silman's book.
A famous endgame analyzed in many books! } 33. Nd1 { [%cal Gd1f2,Gf2g4,Gg4f6,Gd2c3] } 33... Bd6 (33... e5?! 34. f5 gxf5+ 35. Kxf5 Nd4+ $16 { [%cal Gf5g4,Gf5e4] }) 34. Nf2 Nd8 (34... Nd4?! 35. Bc3 Nc6 $14) 35. Bc3 Nf7 36. Ng4 h5?! 37. Bf6+! { Preventing g5, which could free black's position. } 37... Kd7 38. Nf2 Bc7 (38... Be7 39. Bc3 g5?! 40. fxg5 Nxg5+ 41. Kf4 $16 { Silman believes this would be a better, more active, defense. SF is not impressed. }) 39. Nd3 Kc6 40. Ne1 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Ge1f3,Gf3h4,Rh4g6] } (40. Ne5+? Bxe5 41. Bxe5 $10 { No way to get in with the king. No way to attack e6 or g6 with the bishop. }) 40... Nd6+ 41. Kd3 (41. Ke5?! Kd7! $10 (41... Nxc4+?? 42. Kxe6 $18 { [%cal Ge6f7] })) 41... Nf5 42. Nf3 Kd7 43. Ke4 { [%cal Gf3e5,Gc7e5,Ge4e5] } 43... Nd6+ 44. Ke3 Nf5+ 45. Kf2 Bd6 46. h3! { Taking control over the f5 outpost next. } 46... Bc7 47. g4 hxg4 48. hxg4 Nh6 49. Kg3 Nf7?? (49... Ke8! 50. Be5 Bd8 51. Bb8 a6?! (51... Nf7! 52. Bxa7? Bc7! $10 { Trapping white's bishop. }) 52. Ne5 g5 53. Nc6 Bf6 54. Be5 Bxe5 55. Nxe5 gxf4+ 56. Kxf4 $18 { Smyslov believed this would be a tougher defense. White has an outside passed pawn in the endgame though and should win.
Of course, he missed that Bb8 earlier in the line isn't threatening to win the a7 pawn. }) 50. g5 { Nh4 is a threat now that g5 isn't playable. } { [%cal Gf3h4] } 50... Bd8 51. Kg4 Bxf6 52. gxf6 Kd6 53. Ne5! $18 { 1-0 White wins. } 53... Nd8!? (53... Nxe5+?! 54. fxe5+ Kxe5 55. f7 $18) 54. Kg5 $18 { [%cal Gg5g6] } 1-0


