{ Fischer, the 11th WCC, is the fifth and final of Silman's endgame heroes.

This game was played in Argentina in 1960 when Fischer was just 16 years old. }
1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bd6 9. Nb5 Be7 10. h3 a6 11. Nc3 Bd6 12. e4 e5 13. Be3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Bd7 15. Re1 Qe7 16. Bg5 Nxd4 17. Nd5 Qe5 18. f4 Nf3+ 19. Qxf3 Qd4+ 20. Kh1 Ng4 21. hxg4 Qxc4 22. b3 Qb5 23. a4 Qa5 24. Red1 Bc6 25. e5 Bb4 26. Qe4 Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Qb6 28. f5 Bc3 29. Rc1 Bb2 30. Rb1 Bc3 31. Rc1 Bb2 32. Rc4 Rae8 33. f6 c6 34. fxg7 cxd5 35. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 36. Qxh7 Bxe5 37. Rf4 Qe6 38. Rf1 b5 39. axb5 axb5 40. Bd2 Ke7 41. Bb4+ Kd8 42. Rxf7 Rh8 43. Rf8+ Rxf8 44. Bxf8 Qf6 45. Bc5 d4 46. Kg1 Qf4 47. Qe7+ Kc8 48. Qf8+ Qxf8 49. Bxf8 { The beginning of the adjourned position and the starting position in Silman's book.
Taimanov thought he still had winning chances (and indeed he does, although it is drawn with best play). } 49... Bg3 { Cutting off the king. } 50. Kf1 d3 { Cutting off the king. } 51. Bb4 (51. g5?! Kd7 52. g6 Ke6 53. g7 Kf7 $10) 51... Kd7 52. Be1 Bf4 { [%cal Gd3d2] } 53. Bc3 Bg3 54. g5 Ke6 55. g6 Ke7! (55... Bh4?? 56. Be5!! $18 { Preventing Bg3 means the king can run up the board next. }) 56. Be1 Bf4 57. Bh4+ Kf8 58. g3 (58. Bf6 Bg3 $10 { The king remains trapped. }) 58... Bd6 59. Kf2 Bc5+ 60. Kf3 Kg7 61. Bg5 Kxg6 62. Bf4!? (62. Be3!? Bb4 63. g4 Kf6 64. Bf4 Bc5! $10 (64... Kg6?! 65. Ke3! d2 66. Ke2 $16)) 62... Kh5 63. Ke4 Kg4 64. Kxd3 Kf3 { If the white g and black b pawns get traded, Fischer transposes to the endgame he has memorized: same color bishop vs passed b pawn. } 65. Bc7 Bf2 66. Bd6 Be1 67. Kd4 Kg4 68. Kc5 b4 69. Kb5 Kf5 70. Kc4 Ke6 71. Bc7 Kf5 72. Kd3 Kg4 73. Bd6 Bc3 74. Kc4 Be1 75. Bxb4 Bxg3 { Finally the pawns get traded. Fischer takes less than a minute for the rest of the game. } 76. Bc3 Bd6 77. Kd5 Be7 78. Bd4 Bb4 79. Kc4 Ba5 80. Bc3 Bd8 81. b4 Kf4!? (81... Kf5!? 82. Kd5 { Transposing to Capablanca - Janowski, 1916. Amazingly, in this position, Janowksi resigned! } 82... Kf4! $10 { Bringing the king behind the passed pawn to attack it (Fischer's defense in this game) would have saved Janowski's game. } (82... Bb6?? { This was the reason for the resignation. } 83. Bd4 Bc7 84. b5 Bd8 85. Kc6 Ke6 86. Bb6 Bg5 87. Bc7 Be3 88. Bd6 Bf2 89. Bc5 Bg3 90. b6 Bf4 91. b7 Bg3 92. Bb6 Bb8 93. Bc7 Ba7 94. Kb5! Kd7 95. Ka6! $18) 83. b5 Ke3! 84. Be5 Kd3! 85. Kc6 Kc4! $10 { Attacking the pawn from behind had not yet been discovered in 1916. }) 82. b5 Ke4 83. Bd4 Bc7 84. Kc5 Kd3! 85. Kc6 Kc4! { Attacking the pawn from behind is enough to draw the game... barely. } 86. Bb6 (86. Kxc7 Kxb5 $10) 86... Bf4 87. Ba7 Bc7 $10 { 1/2-1/2  wins. } { Taimanov recounts in "Taimanov's selected games": 'In this ending, where Bobby was a pawn down, one sensed that the correct decisions would not come easily to Fischer, and that he was balancing on the edge of the abyss. But then the critical, most important position was reached, and... Bobby suddenly began playing quickly and faultlessly, like an automaton---he rattled off more than a dozen difficult moves within a minute, and the draw became inevitable.
Stunned by such a finale, I asked him: "Bobby, how did you manage to find this saving path, and so quickly?"
"I didn't need to find anything" said the contented Fischer with a smile, "a few years ago your magazine Shakhmaty vs SSSR published a detailed analysis of this endgame by Averbakh, and I remembered all the variations perfectly well!" ' } 1/2-1/2


[Event "FIDE (28) 1970-1972"]
[Site "Vancouver cm qf"]
[Date "1971.05.??"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Fischer, R.."]
[Black "Taimanov, Mark E"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2740"]
[BlackElo "2620"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[ECO "B47"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Taimanov Variation, Bastrikov Variation"]
[StudyName "Silman's Endgame Course: Five Greatest Endgame Players of All Time"]
[ChapterName "Robert James Fischer - Mark Taimanov"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/XlpTz4Mu/xAPbOqa1"]

{ I have analyzed this game extensively in another study and pulled in my analysis here. See move 40 for the beginning of analysis influenced by Silman.

The 4th game of the Fischer - Taimanov candidates match. Fischer was all but guaranteed already to win the match, but theoretically there were still chances left for Taimanov if Fischer randomly fell apart. Instead, this would end up being Fischer's 11th win in a row. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qc7!? { I can't pinpoint exactly why Taimanov would play this way. But I suppose it's just a different way to get a Taimanov. } (4... e6 5. Nc3 Qc7 { The normal Taimanov move order to reach this position. }) 5. Nc3 { Far and above the most common move, but now we directly transpose to the Taimanov. } (5. c4! $14 { Ivanchuk, Vassily - Movsesian, Sergei, 1-0, EU-ch 6th, 2005, https://lichess.org/JI4LJr9R } { Technically black has allowed us to play c4 and get a Maroczy, so we should go ahead and do that. Winrates aren't that impressive here but there are some nice victories. }) (5. Nb5!? Qb8 6. c4 Nf6 7. N5c3 e6 $14 { Taimanov would hold a draw against David Bronstein later that year in this position. } { Bronstein, David I - Taimanov, Mark E, 1/2-1/2, URS-ch39, 1971, https://lichess.org/0dSfp79w }) 5... e6 { Transposing to the Taimanov. } 6. g3 { This rarer try against the Taimanov became one of my favorite ways to play a few years ago. } 6... a6 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. O-O Nxd4!? { This forcing variation has become a bit of a main line here. } 9. Qxd4 Bc5 10. Bf4! { An important theoretical inclusion. White doesn't want to block the DSB by retreating the queen. } (10. Qd3?! Ng4! $10 { Ne5 is assured and the white queen will get kicked around further. } { [%cal Gg4e5] }) 10... d6 (10... Bxd4?! 11. Bxc7 $16) 11. Qd2 h6! { Prevents Bg5, so that e5 will definitely trade the DSBs. } (11... e5?! 12. Bg5 $14 { With annoying pressure on the d5 square. }) 12. Rad1 e5 13. Be3 Bg4?! { Taimanov had sparred this position a few times in prep for this match and felt that black was totally fine here. Unfortunately, white creates some problems using the d5 square here with precise play. } (13... Ke7!! { This only started to become popular recently, but the idea is very justified. If all the pieces get traded off, we want the king in the center. Moreover, now Qd6 is ruled out for good. } 14. Bxc5 Qxc5! { A new option, previously unavailable to black because of Qxd6. } 15. Na4 Qc6!? (15... Qc7!? 16. f4 Rd8! (16... a5?! 17. c4 { With a good grip in the center. } 17... Bg4 18. Rc1 Bd7 19. fxe5 dxe5 20. Nc3 $14) 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Qb4+ Ke8 19. Nb6 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rb8 $10 { Vaibhav, Suri - Aravindh, Chithambaram VR, 1/2-1/2, Moscow Aeroflot op-A, 2020, https://lichess.org/M9l7XAXw }) 16. f4 { The knight is immune from capture. } 16... a5! $10 { Preventing Qb4+. Now the threat of Bg4 will force back some of white's active pieces. } (16... Qxa4?? 17. Qxd6+ Ke8 18. Qd8#)) (13... Be6!? { The main move looks to simply develop. }) (13... O-O?! 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Qd6 $14 { The endgame favors white because of all the weak dark squares available for the white pieces. b6 and d6 in particular. }) 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. f3 Be6 16. f4?! (16. Nd5! { The theoretically approved move. } 16... Bxd5 17. exd5 Qd6! 18. f4 { Where white's bishop will prove slightly better than black's knight. } 18... exf4!? (18... O-O 19. fxe5 Qxe5 20. d6 $14 { Transposing back to the main line. }) 19. Rde1+ Kd8 $14) 16... Rd8?! { Black's king is stuck in the center so now this is the worst of all worlds. } (16... O-O! 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Qd6 19. fxe5 Qxe5 20. d6! $14 { Adams, Michael - Anand, Viswanathan, 1/2-1/2, Corus, 2001, https://lichess.org/XClvu0Pz } { The objectively best way to play. White's bishop is felt in the position. }) 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 e4 { The only way to play, but now the e4 pawn is a target. } (18... Qd6?? { This fine blockading move now fails tactically because black hasn't brought his king out of the center. } 19. fxe5 Qxe5 20. Rfe1 $18) 19. Rfe1!? { Trading pawns in the center brings the game closer to equality but also long term leaves us with a stronger bishop. } (19. c4!? O-O 20. Rfe1 Rfe8 21. Re3 $14 { A safer way to play to milk a slight advantage. }) 19... Rxd5 20. Rxe4+ Kd8 { An odd choice by Taimanov to play this way, but because there are forced exchanges occurring, king safety isn't as bad as it looks. } (20... Nxe4?? 21. Qxd5 Nf6 22. Re1+ $18) 21. Qe2 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1+ Qd7 { Black is happy to trade queens so that the central king doesn't die. However, this leads to another problem: the infamous Fischer endgame. } 23. Qxd7+! Kxd7 24. Re5 { The start of the Fischer endgame. If black can trade off all the queenside pawns, then this is drawn. If white can keep pawns on both sides of the board and flick around with the bishop, then black's knight will be much worse than the bishop. This infamous endgame started to prove to the chess community that bishops are just better than knights. } 24... b6? { Doesn't get the king up in the endgame and weakens the light squares. Fischer pounces perfectly. } (24... Kd6! 25. b4! (25. Bxb7?! Rb8 26. Bxa6 Rxb2 { White's queenside pawns are all going to drop and black has the desired endgame situation: all pawns on one side of the board. }) (25. Bf1!? { Like in the game no longer hits with the same oomph: } 25... Re8! 26. Rxe8 Nxe8 27. Bc4 Ke7 $10 { There are less light square holes to work with and black has succeeded in trading rooks. Still, this endgame will not be pleasant. }) 25... b6!? (25... cxb4 26. Bxb7 $14 { Keeps more pawns on both sides of the board. }) 26. bxc5+ bxc5 27. Bf1 $14 { Best play is similar to the game, but black has another file for the rook to work with: the b file. } { [%cal Gf1c4,Gc4a6] }) 25. Bf1! { Forcing more pawns onto dark squares means white's bishop has more holes to rest on. } 25... a5 (25... Ra8?! 26. Bc4 $16 { f7 cannot be defended. }) (25... b5? 26. Rxc5 $16) 26. Bc4! { b5, a6, c4, and d5 are all good squares for the bishop now. The black rook has to passively defend f7 instead of challenging white's rook for the e file. } 26... Rf8 27. Kg2 { The pieces are optimized. Time to bring up the king. } 27... Kd6!? (27... Ne8!? { If the knight could reach d6, then black has a better time defending. But: } 28. Bb5+! Kd8 29. Rd5+! Kc8 30. Rd2 { And white maintains a strong grip. } 30... Nc7!? (30... Nf6!? 31. Kf3 $16 { Black hasn't made any progress yet. }) 31. Bd7+! Kb7 32. f5 $16 { The knight and rook are boxed out of the action once again. }) 28. Kf3 Nd7 29. Re3 Nb8 (29... f6? 30. Re6+ Kc7 31. Re7 $18) 30. Rd3+ { An unnecessary check, but why not? } (30. c3 Nc6 31. a4 $16 { This would also be great for white. }) 30... Kc7 (30... Ke7?! 31. Bb5! $18 { Now the knight is dominated too! }) 31. c3! { Dominating the knight. } 31... Nc6 32. Re3! { Stopping Ne7 and once again the knight is dominated. } (32. a4?! Ne7! { Nf5 is disturbing. } 33. g4 Nc8! $14 { But then black finds a way to get the knight to all-important d6 square. }) 32... Kd6 33. a4! { Fixing the pawns on dark squares so that the king and bishop can use the weakened light squares forever. b5 is now never a threat from black. } 33... Ne7 { This is finally playable, but without being able to spin back around to d6, this knight move is less effective. } 34. h3!? { I can't understand why Fischer played this move. Perhaps toying with Taimanov. Maybe he was still busy calculating the ramifications of h4-h5? } (34. h4 { Also fine. } 34... h5!? { Trying to get the f5 square for the knight and fix white's pawn structure makes sense too. Similar to the game. } (34... Nf5!? 35. Re5 g6 36. h5! $16 { Perhaps Fischer missed that he had this move here? })) (34. g4 { Also good. But now black has an easier time trying to trade off kingside pawns. }) 34... Nc6 35. h4 h5 { Fixes white's kingside pawn structure, but fixes more pawns on light squares. } (35... Na7 36. h5! $16 { More progress from white. Now g4-g5 is a plan. } { [%cal Gg3g4,Gg4g5] }) 36. Rd3+ Kc7 37. Rd5!? { Fischer is trying to force more pawns onto light squares, but black's next moves are an inevitability anyway. } (37. Ke4!? f5+ 38. Kf3 Rf6 $16 { Another way to transpose to the game. }) 37... f5 38. Rd2 Rf6 39. Re2! { Threatening to infiltrate on the 7th in case the knight goes anywhere. } 39... Kd7 40. Re3?! { A smart idea in general - now that there is a bridge on the 3rd rank, white can bring the king in on the queenside. However, it allows one last saving resource for black. } (40. Bb5! { Cleaner technique would have been to start with this move. Until g6 is played by black, we must remain wary of a timely Rg6. } 40... Rd6 41. Re5 g6?! (41... Rf6!? { Best defense might be to avoid playing g6 at all costs. But eventually white will get in on the e file at the correct moment when Rg6 doesn't offer black enough counterplay. } 42. Ke2 Kc7 43. Re3 Kd7 44. Kd3 Kc7 45. Kc4 Kd7 46. Re5 Kc7 { Every piece of white's is optimized, so now we can strike with: } 47. Re8! Rg6 48. b3! { Black should not commit with Rxg3, but then that means black has nothing going on for them. } 48... Rxg3?! (48... Rf6!? { Black can no longer sit around. } 49. Rh8 Rg6 (49... g6 50. Rh7+ Kb8 51. Bxc6 Rxc6 52. Kd5 $18) 50. Rxh5 Rxg3 51. Rxf5 $18) 49. Re6 { The point. } 49... Nd8 50. Re7+ Kc8 51. Ba6+ Kb8 52. Rd7 Ne6 53. Rb7+ Ka8 54. Kb5 $18) 42. Ke2 { Similar to how the game actually went. Now that g6 is in, there's no counterplay with Rg6, and so white can look to next trade off the rooks. } 42... Kd8 43. Re3 $16 { Similar to the game. } { [%cal Ge3d3] }) 40... g6? { The final mistake. Black should have stayed flexible with the g6 pawn to keep open the option of Rg6, with counterplay. Now that black has no counterplay on the kingside, trading rooks leads to a good bishop vs bad knight scenario which Fischer can milk forever.
This is the starting position in Silman's book. } (40... Na7! { Preventing Bb5 and remaining flexible with the g pawn is somehow enough to hold the game! } 41. Ke2 Nc8! 42. Bb5+ Kc7 43. Kd3!? (43. Rd3!? Nd6! $10 { No entry on the d file for you! }) 43... Rg6! $10 { Nd6 is an annoying resource, and now the rook is tied down on e3. }) 41. Bb5! Rd6 42. Ke2! (42. Rd3? Rxd3+ 43. Bxd3 Nd8! 44. Bc4 Ke7 45. Bd5 Kd6 46. Bg8 Ke7 47. Ke3 Nb7 48. Kd3 Nd6 $10) 42... Kd8 43. Rd3! { Fischer proves that the knight is no match for the bishop now that there are too many targets on light squares. } 43... Kc7 44. Rxd6 Kxd6 45. Kd3 Ne7 (45... Kc7? 46. Bxc6 Kxc6 47. Kc4 Kc7 48. Kb5!? (48. Kd5!? Kd7 49. c4 $18) 48... Kb7 49. c4 Kc7 50. Ka6 Kc6 51. Ka7 Kc7 52. b3 Kc6 53. Kb8 $18) 46. Be8! { Freezing the knight. Now the knight cannot reach the dream d6 square that shuts out white's king. } 46... Kd5 47. Bf7+ Kd6 48. Kc4 { Entering with the king. } 48... Kc6 49. Be8+! { Kicking away the defender of b5. } 49... Kb7 50. Kb5 { Entering with the king. } 50... Nc8 { Threatening Nd6#! } 51. Bc6+! { Kicks the king away just in time so that there's no mate. } 51... Kc7! { More centralized, following the general rule. } (51... Ka7?! 52. Bd5 Nd6+ 53. Kc6 $18 { And black's knight is dominated. }) 52. Bd5! (52. Bf3? Nd6+! 53. Ka6 Ne4! $10 { The knight cannot be captured, and g3 will fall. }) 52... Ne7! (52... Nd6+? 53. Ka6 $22 $18 { Black's knight and king are dominated, and black is in Zuzgwang. Either Kxb6 or Bf7, winning the g6 pawn must be allowed. } 53... Ne4!? 54. Bf7 Nxg3 55. Bxg6 Kc6 { White's bishop is obviously better than black's knight here. The correct way to win would be: } 56. Be8+ Kc7 57. Kb5 Kb7!? (57... Ne2!? 58. Bxh5 Nxf4 59. Bf3 Ne6 60. h5 $18) 58. Kc4 $18 { and white wins the kingside pawns. } { [%cal Gc4d5,Gd5e5] }) 53. Bf7 { Freezing the knight again. } 53... Kb7 54. Bb3!! { Recognizing that black cannot triangulate, this move loses a tempo which sets up the zuzgwang and decisive penetration. } (54. c4! { Bizarre, but this is also winning. The point is that d5 is now defended, so Bd5+ will kick away the black king just as Bf3+ does in the game. } 54... Nc8!? (54... Ka7?! 55. Bd5 $22 $18) 55. Bd5+ Kc7 56. Ka6 Ne7 57. Bb7 $18 { Zugzwang. } 57... Ng8 58. Bf3 Ne7 59. Bd5 Nc8 60. Bf7 Ne7 61. Be8 $22 $18 { Just as in the game. }) 54... Ka7 (54... Kc7?! 55. Ka6 $18 { The knight enters and Bf7 is coming again to freeze the knight. }) 55. Bd1 Kb7 56. Bf3+! { Now the black king gets kicked away from defending a6. } 56... Kc7 (56... Ka7?! 57. c4 $22 $18 { As in the other line. Black is now in Zuzgwang. Bd5->f7 will win the game. } 57... Ng8 58. Kc6!? Nf6 59. Kd6 Ne4+ 60. Ke5 Nxg3 61. Kf6 $18) 57. Ka6! { Getting the king up further. Black's king now only has c7 in order to protect b6. } 57... Nc8 58. Bd5 Ne7 (58... Nd6?! 59. c4 $22 $18 { Kxb6 or Bf7 cannot be denied. }) 59. Bc4!? (59. Bf7 $22 $18 { Immediately would have already been winning too. } 59... Kc6!? { The only move now available to black that wasn't available after Bc4. } 60. Be8+ Kc7 61. Ka7 $22 $18) 59... Nc6!? (59... Kc6!? 60. Bb5+ Kc7 61. Be8 $22 $18 { Transposes to the game. }) 60. Bf7 Ne7 61. Be8 $22 $18 { Now black has to allow Kxb6 or Bxg6 except for one move } 61... Kd8!? { The last try for black, but Fischer had already calculated the piece sacrifice was winning. } 62. Bxg6!! Nxg6 63. Kxb6 Kd7 (63... Ne7!? { Transposes to the game after: } 64. Kxc5! Kd7! 65. b4! $18) 64. Kxc5 Ne7 65. b4 axb4?! { Too easy. Now the connected passed pawns queen themselves. } (65... Kc7!? 66. bxa5! Kb7!? (66... Nc8!? 67. Kd5! Nd6 68. Ke6 { Zuzgwang again! Black cannot hold the kingside and queenside. } 68... Kc6 69. a6 $18) 67. Kd6! $18 { Black's knight gets shunted away and white will win the kingside pawns and the game. }) 66. cxb4 Nc8 (66... Kc7!? 67. b5 Kb7 68. a5 Nc8!? (68... Ng8!? 69. Kd5 Nf6+ 70. Ke6 Ne4 71. Kxf5 Nxg3+ 72. Kg6 $18 { [%cal Gf4f7] }) 69. Kd5 Na7 70. Ke6 Nxb5 71. Kxf5 Nd4+ 72. Kg6 Ne2 73. f5 Nxg3 74. f6 $18) 67. a5 (67. b5 $18 { Also wins. }) 67... Nd6 68. b5 Ne4+ { Black gets active with the knight to take out the kingside pawns, but now the queenside pawns are simply too strong. } 69. Kb6! (69. Kd5?? { Now that the knight is already committed to the kingside, this is a losing battle. } 69... Nxg3 70. b6 Ne2! { Reminding white they cannot simply run up to the queenside anymore without losing the f and h pawns. } 71. Ke5 Ng3! { The knight holds the kingside pawns } 72. a6 Kc6! 73. a7 Kb7 74. Kf6 Ka8! $10 { Black can hold the kingside pawns with the knight and the queenside pawns with the king. }) 69... Kc8 70. Kc6! { Black's king is dominated. } 70... Kb8!? (70... Nxg3!? 71. a6 Kb8 72. b6 Ne4 { Could have transposed to the game. } 73. a7+! Ka8 74. b7+! Kxa7 75. Kc7! $18) 71. b6 $18 { Taimanov resigned a second game against Fischer in a BR vs NR endgame. This infamous example of zuzgwang, the power of passed pawns on both sides of the board, and king activity in the endgame gave rise to what we now dub "The Fischer endgame."
Fischer will win with just the queenside pawns, for instance after: } { 1-0 White wins. } 71... Nxg3 72. a6! Ne4 73. a7+! Ka8 74. b7+! Kxa7 75. Kc7! $18 { b8=Q cannot be stopped. } 1-0


