{ I have analyzed this game extensively in another study and pulled in my analysis here. See move 55 for analysis influenced by Silman.

Game 13 of the 1972 WCC. Spassky fought back in game 11 to defeat Fischer in the poisoned pawn variation of the Najdorf with 14. Nb1!? Game 12 saw the return of Fischer's QGD, and although Spassky had the upper hand overall in the game, the OCB endgame was always drawn. }
1. e4 Nf6!? { Fischer opts for the Alekhine defense, something he had recently picked up against weaker opposition in the 1970 Interzonal tournament. In fact this was only the second time the Alekhine had ever been played in a WCC, Euwe having essayed it against Alekhine himself in 1935 to secure a solid draw. Besides a later game in this match, it was also the last time it was ever featured in another WCC match. } 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3!? { The so-called modern variation is the other main try for an advantage against the Alekhine. } (4. c4 Nb6 5. f4!? $14 { The four pawns attack has come and gone as the best way to try and refute the Alekhine. Recently, people consider it to be a testing line. } (5. exd6!? { The exchange is the other way to try and get an opening advantage. } 5... exd6!? $14 (5... cxd6!? $14))) 4... g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Nbd2?! { This move doesn't truly accomplish anything, and in fact gets in the way of white's other pieces. } (7. Ng5!? { The caveman approach here is actually quite powerful. } 7... e6 (7... O-O?! 8. e6! f6 9. Nf7! Qe8 $16) 8. Qf3 Qe7 9. Ne4 $14) (7. a4!? a5 8. Qe2 $14 { A more positional way to try and tackle the Alekhine. }) 7... O-O 8. h3?! { Way too passive. Now Fischer has at least equalized and can begin to try and play for an advantage. } 8... a5 9. a4 dxe5 10. dxe5 Na6! { Sometimes, greed is good! Fischer's idea is literally to ignore everything on the kingside and try and snag the a4 pawn. } 11. O-O Nc5 12. Qe2 Qe8 (12... Nxb3?! 13. Nxb3 Qe8 { The other way to try and win the a pawn isn't as critical. } 14. Nbd4! { White can and should play in the center here. } 14... Nxa4?? (14... Bd7!? 15. e6! fxe6 16. Ne5 $16) 15. Nb5! $18 { [%cal Gb5c7,Ga1a4] }) 13. Ne4?! { Spassky must have miscalculated something here. } (13. Ba2! { The correct way to go. White is OK losing the a pawn if he keeps the LSB alive. } 13... Nbxa4!? (13... Be6!? 14. Bxe6 Nxe6 15. Qe4 { At least here, the a pawn isn't dropping. }) 14. Nd4! { Stopping Be6. } 14... Nb6 15. Re1 a4 16. N2f3 $10) 13... Nbxa4 { Not only does Fischer greedily snag the a pawn, but he is also able to trade off the LSB, reducing any counterplay Spassky has on the kingside. } (13... Ncxa4? 14. Ba2 $16 { And now the knight is stranded on a4. }) 14. Bxa4 (14. Ba2?! Be6! $15 { The LSB cannot be maintained. }) 14... Nxa4 15. Re1 Nb6 16. Bd2!? { Spassky forces Fischer to push the a pawn again. Although it's unclear if this truly makes it a liability or if this is a desirable outcome for black after all. } (16. Bf4!? Bf5 17. Nd4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Qd7 $15 { A more normal line from Spassky. }) 16... a4 17. Bg5 h6 18. Bh4 Bf5!? (18... g5!? { I can imagine Fischer rejecting this line because of the possible sacrifices now or later, but once the bishop is booted to g3, black is truly solid. } 19. Bg3 (19. Bxg5?! hxg5 20. Nexg5 Bf5 $17) 19... Qc6! 20. Rad1 (20. Nd4?! Qc4! $17 { Almost forcing Spassky into a queen trade. }) 20... Qc4! 21. Qd2 $15) 19. g4 { Fischer wouldn't be unhappy provoking this weakening move out of Spassky. } 19... Be6 (19... Bxe4?! 20. Qxe4 e6!? (20... c6?! 21. Qd4! { [%cal Gd4b6,Gd4a4] } 21... Qd8 22. Qxd8 Rfxd8 23. Bxe7 $10) 21. Qxb7 { Probably Fischer rejected the line here. But Black's pieces are much stronger than white's pieces after: } 21... g5 22. Bg3 Qb5! $15) 20. Nd4!? { Spassky is jumping around with his knights looking to undermine black's position with a timely e6. } 20... Bc4 21. Qd2 Qd7?! { Yes, Fischer will not get kicked around by a rook on the d file here. But is the queen so well-placed on d7? } (21... Bxe5! { The cleanest way forward, although at first glance it looks scary. } 22. Qxh6 Bg7 23. Qe3!? (23. Qd2!? Qd7 24. Rad1 Rfe8 25. b3 axb3 26. cxb3 Bd5 27. Nc5 Qd6! 28. Ne4 Bxe4 29. Rxe4 Rad8 $17 { Black fully consolidates the extra pawn and can look to win an endgame. }) 23... Nd5 24. Qd2 b6) 22. Rad1 Rfe8?! { Fischer over-protects e7, but his pieces are a bit scattered, and Spassky had a shot here. } (22... Bxe5!? 23. Qxh6 Bg7 24. Qc1 $10 { White's queen can now retreat further away from black's pieces, so this position is less clear than before. }) (22... Bd5?! 23. Nf6+! exf6 24. exf6 { This is exactly the sort of mess that Spassky would be looking for while black is trying to catch up in development. } 24... Rfe8 25. fxg7 Kxg7 $15 { Black's king is quite vulnerable, but if there is no attack, then black remains better. }) (22... a3!? 23. b3 a2! 24. bxc4 Nxc4 25. Qe2 Nb2 { and the rook cannot defend both d4 and a1. } 26. Ra1 Qxd4 27. c3!! { However, this amazing shot keeps Spassky in the game. } 27... Qb6 28. Bxe7! Rfe8 29. Nf6+! Bxf6 30. Bxf6 Kh7 $10) 23. f4!? { White should probably not be playing for a direct attack on black's king. Instead, white needs to be fighting for the initiative all over the board while black's pieces remain scattered. } (23. b3!! { Disrupts Fischer's coordination just in time. } 23... axb3!? (23... c5!? { Giving back the pawn is always a bail out option for black. } 24. Nxc5 Qc7 25. Ne4 Bd5 $10) 24. cxb3 Bd5 25. Nc5! Qc8 26. e6! $16 { This line highlights the problems in Fischer's position. }) (23. Nc5? Qd5! $17 { No threats! }) 23... Bd5!? { Fischer is desperate to trade off some pieces, after which black should have a fine game. } (23... Qc8!? 24. f5 $10 { The attack is somewhat scary, although black does not remain worse. }) 24. Nc5! Qc8 25. Qc3?! { A clear mis-evaluation of the position. Spassky misses his last chance to burn down the position with e6 and plays a solid improving move instead. } (25. e6! { Once again, this thematic pawn sacrifice to rip open black's kingside and scatter black's defenses is best. One interesting line is: } 25... Nc4! (25... fxe6? 26. Ndxe6 Bxe6?! 27. Nxe6 Bf6 28. Bxf6 exf6 29. f5! $18 { A dominant knight on e6. Black's kingside is in ruins. The extra a pawn is irrelevant. }) (25... f6?! 26. Qc3 $14 { Compared to the game, black has no stability in the center, and his king is much weaker. }) 26. Qe2! Nxb2 27. Nf5!! Nxd1 (27... gxf5? 28. Rxd5 $18) 28. Nxg7! Kxg7 29. Qe5+ f6 30. Qxd5 $10 { Black's knight will get tracked down, and a possible attack against the king continues. }) 25... e6! { Fischer totally consolidates his extra pawn, seemingly retains the bishop pair, and should next look to play for a win on the queenside. } 26. Kh2 { A sign that Spassky doesn't see any easy improving moves left. } 26... Nd7! { Untangling on the queenside. } 27. Nd3 c5 28. Nb5 Qc6 { The dream position for black. Every piece of black's is better than every piece of white's and he's up a pawn. } 29. Nd6!? (29. Na3!? b5 $19) 29... Qxd6! { A simplification tactic that Fischer surely saw a few moves back. The knight is not allowed to stay on d6 for even a second. } (29... Reb8 $17 { This is fine too, with b5 coming next. }) 30. exd6 Bxc3 31. bxc3 f6! { Kills Spassky's bishop and knight. Next step: push the a pawn. } (31... a3?! 32. Ne5 Bc6!? $17 { No counterplay! } (32... Nxe5?! 33. fxe5 $17 { where white gets a protected passed pawn and some chances. }) 33. Be7 { Even this anchored bishop should not bother black. } 33... Ra4 34. Ra1 Rea8 $17) 32. g5! { Spassky refuses to go down without a fight. The most important square on the board (e5) must be accessible to white's pieces! } (32. Ra1?! { Or any other non-critical move. } 32... g5! 33. fxg5 hxg5 34. Bf2 b6 $19 { With total control all across the board. }) 32... hxg5 33. fxg5 f5 34. Bg3 Kf7 35. Ne5+ Nxe5 36. Bxe5 { Spassky has succeeded in making it a bit messy. Black's king isn't feeling so safe, there are too many pawns on light squares, and the a pawn still hasn't moved at all. } 36... b5!? { Fischer plays the remaining moves before the adjournment in only 30 minutes (when he had over an hour remaining). While these moves are in the spirit of the position, none of them are backed up with precise calculation, and so he misses several resources available to Spassky. On the edge of victory, he starts to drift towards equality. } (36... Red8! { The most precise move deals with any c4 shenanigans. } 37. h4!? (37. c4?! { It's important this move no longer deflect black's bishop away from anything. } 37... Bxc4 38. h4!? (38. d7? Bd5! $19) 38... Bd5 $17) 37... b5 38. Rb1 Bc6! $17 { Black can easily arrange for the bishop to return to d5, but first }) 37. Rf1?! { Spassky goes straight for the throat here, preparing Rf4->h4->h7 with at least a perpetual. Unfortunately, he misses a drawing resource. } (37. c4!! { This timely pawn break frees all of white's pieces and disrupts black's defensive strategy. Spassky presumably only sees this resource a few moves later. } 37... Bxc4!? (37... bxc4!? 38. Rf1 { Now that black's LSB is further blocked, Spassky's rook lift plan works. } 38... a3 39. Rf4 $10 { Similar to the game, Spassky can create counterplay against black's king. } { [%cal Gf4h4,Gh4h7] }) 38. d7! Red8 39. Bf6 b4 $15 { Black should sacrifice the exchange and try and promote the queenside pawns. }) 37... Rh8?! { It feels wrong to call this move a mistake because it is well-motivated. Fischer sacrifices the exchange in order to deal with any remaining king safety issues. Still, there was a much cleaner way to approach the position, and Bxh8 is not forced, so this idea remains suspect. } (37... Red8!! { A route for the king towards the queenside must be made instantly to avoid being harassed by Spassky's rook as in the game. } 38. Rf4 Ke8! 39. Rh4 Kd7! 40. Rh7+ Kc6! 41. Rc7+ Kb6 $19 { Black's king reaches safety, and the queenside pawns can push next. }) 38. Bf6! { Spassky doesn't bite and asks Fischer to decide what this rook is even doing on the h file anyway. } (38. Bxh8! { Perhaps it's objectively best to win the exchange here, but you have to find a precise sequence of moves to follow it up with. } 38... Rxh8 39. Rfe1! { Preventing Ke8 ensures that the d pawn remains scary. } (39. Kg3? Ke8! 40. Rfe1? Kd7 $19 { The king does not even need to capture this d6 pawn and allow the tricky c4 shot. Now that the d pawn is under control, Ra8 and a3-a2-a1 is a winning plan. }) 39... Ra8!? (39... Rd8!? 40. Kg3 Rxd6 41. c4 bxc4 42. Ra1 $10 { Probably a draw with best play. }) 40. Re5 a3 41. c4! Bxc4!? (41... bxc4 42. c3! $10 { Black's bishop accomplishes nothing. }) 42. Rxc5!? $10) 38... a3 (38... Ke8?? 39. Bxh8 $18) (38... Rh5?? { The rook is dead now, and white wins a rook after: } 39. d7 $18) 39. Rf4?! (39. Ra1! { Best play is to abandon the c4 tricks and focus on winning back some material. } 39... a2 40. Rfd1! Rhd8! 41. Bxd8 Rxd8 42. Rxd5! exd5 43. Rxa2 Rxd6 44. Kg3 $15 { Because black cannot create a queenside passed pawn, this position is probably drawn with best play. Still, black retains the winning chances up the extra pawn, and I can understand why Spassky did not want to enter such a dreary rook endgame just before the adjournment. }) 39... a2!? { A reasonable move from Fischer, who possibly didn't sense the danger having already stopped Spassky's rook lift plan. } (39... Bc4!! { The absolute cleanest win. } 40. d7 a2! 41. Ra1!? (41. Bxh8!? Rxh8 42. d8=Q Rxd8 43. Rxd8 a1=Q $19 { One crucial line to get right. }) (41. Re1!? e5! $19 { Similar to the Ra1 line. White's rook has a responsibility, so there's no breakthrough for white here. Black is simply queening. } 42. Rxe5 a1=Q 43. Re7+ Kf8 $19) 41... e5! $19 { Black's bishop cannot protect both d8 and e5. Finally the position is simplified, and black's a2 pawn pushes through. }) 40. c4! Bxc4!? { Fischer plays the obvious move that you want to play. } (40... bxc4?! 41. d7! c3 $15 { Perhaps there's still some chances for a win in this mess, but the position is much murkier than it could be. }) 41. d7! { But deflecting the bishop off of d5 means that Spassky has generated some counterplay on the d file. } 41... Bd5?? { The game was adjourned here, and resumed the next day. The Russian team was convinced the game was a draw, while Fischer stayed up all night also trying to figure out the evaluation of the position, unable to come to a conclusion.
Amazingly, this seemingly obvious move objectively threw away the win and leads to a drawn endgame. Though neither player could confirm this, both Fischer and Spassky play the objectively best continuation in the game, and only on move 69 does Spassky throw the game away. SF 16 doesn't recognize that this move draws the game until depth 45 or so. } (41... e5! { The correct continuation, giving a square to the king on e6. In every variation, black wins the d pawn, after which Spassky has no match to the LSB bishop and queenside pawns. } 42. Bxe5!? (42. Bxh8!? Rxh8 43. Rh4!? (43. d8=Q? Rxd8 44. Rxd8 a1=Q $19) 43... Rd8 44. Rh7+ Ke6 45. Rg7 f4! $19 { There's no disrupting the rook away from d8, and no perpetual check, so black can win directly on the queenside. }) (42. Rf2!? Rhd8 43. h4 Be6 $19 { Rxd7 is coming next. } { [%cal Gd8d7] }) (42. Rxc4!? bxc4 43. Bxh8 Rxh8 44. Ra1 Rd8 45. Rxa2 Rxd7 $19 { A winning rook endgame. }) 42... Rhd8 43. Bf6 Ke6 44. Bxd8 Rxd8 $19 { Rxd7 is unstoppable. } { [%cal Gd8d7] }) 42. Kg3! { The sealed move after 30 minutes is correct. Fischer returned from the adjournment 25 minutes late, but his time advantage from the first session meant that he was still significantly up on time for when he resumed play at the board. } 42... Ra3+! { Fischer enters a long, forcing variation, which is indeed the best try for an advantage. Objectively, this entire endgame is equal, even though no contemporary commentators nor either player could figure that out. } (42... e5?! { The active try doesn't quite work now that the bishop is looser on d5. } 43. Bxe5 Ke6!? (43... Be6!? 44. Bf6 Rhd8 45. Rh4! { Prevents black from being able to win the d7 pawn so easily. } 45... Ra3+ 46. Kh2 Rxd7 47. Rh7+ Kg8 48. Rh8+ Kf7 49. Rh7+ $10) 44. Bxh8! Rxh8 45. Rff1 Rd8 46. Rfe1+! Be4!? (46... Kd6!? 47. c4! bxc4 48. Re2! $10) 47. Ra1 $10) 43. c3 Rha8 { Black threatens a1=Q, so there really is only one option: a counterattack against black's king. } 44. Rh4! (44. Ra1?? { Too passive. Now Fischer could trivially win with: } 44... e5 45. Bxe5 Ke6 46. Bf6 Kxd7 $19 { where the two pawns and stuck rook on a1 mean black is easily winning. }) 44... e5! { Getting an escape square for the king is the only active way to avoid a perpetual. } (44... a1=Q?! 45. Rxa1 Rxa1 46. Rh7+ Kg8 47. Rh8+ Kf7 48. Rh7+ $10) 45. Rh7+ Ke6 46. Re7+ Kd6 47. Rxe5 Rxc3+ (47... Kxd7?! 48. Rexd5+ Kc6 49. Rd6+ Kb7 50. Rd7+ Ka6 { As opposed to the game, white still retains the c3 pawn, which means there is currently only one passed pawn for black. } 51. Ra1 { Passive, but solid. } 51... b4!? 52. Kf2 b3 53. c4 { [%cal Gf6a1] } 53... Ra4 54. Rc1 Rb8 55. Bb2 $10 { The bishop is not worth less than the two pawns. }) 48. Kf2! (48. Kh4?? Ra4+ $19) (48. Kh2?? Rc2+! 49. Kg1 Rd2! 50. Ree1! (50. Ra1?! Kxd7 $19) 50... Rxd1 51. Rxd1 Kxd7 52. Rxd5+ Kc6! 53. Rd1 b4 $19 { Black has totally consolidated, and the queenside pawns are worth more than the bishop. }) 48... Rc2+! { Getting out of the line of fire of the f6 bishop with tempo. } 49. Ke1! { The king inches closer to the passed queenside pawns. Meanwhile, d5 is certainly dropping. } 49... Kxd7 50. Rexd5+ Kc6 { Spassky began to double check his calculations here, using time for each move, as this was clearly near the end of his adjournment preparation. Meanwhile, Fischer continued playing instantly. } 51. Rd6+! { The threat of perpetual check forces black to run his king up the side of the board to a5/a6. Unfortunately, this blocks his a8 rook, so black is not trivially winning. } 51... Kb7 52. Rd7+ Ka6 53. R7d2 Rxd2 54. Kxd2 (54. Rxd2?! Kb6! 55. Ba1 b4! $17 { The queenside pawns are rolling here and white doesn't have a solid blockade. }) 54... b4 55. h4 Kb5 { The starting position in Silman's book. } 56. h5! { Spassky finds the only way to get active - more passed pawns for both sides! } (56. Kc2?? { The king cannot get over to the queenside without blocking the f6 bishop. } 56... c4 57. Kb2 c3+! 58. Kb3 (58. Ka1?! Kc4 $19 { Now white's king is simply in a mating net. } { [%cal Gb4b3,Gb3b2] }) 58... a1=Q 59. Rxa1 Rxa1 $19) 56... c4 57. Ra1! { Unfortunately, the rook has to be a passive blockader on a1 in order to prevent an immediate breakthrough. } (57. h6?? c3+! 58. Kc2 a1=Q 59. Rxa1 Rxa1 60. h7 Rh1 61. h8=Q Rxh8 62. Bxh8 Kc4 $19 { Black's three pawns are more than a match for the bishop. }) (57. hxg6?? c3+! 58. Bxc3! (58. Kc2?! a1=Q 59. Rxa1 Rxa1 60. g7 Ra8 $19) 58... Rd8+! 59. Kc2 Rxd1! 60. g7!? (60. Kxd1?! bxc3 61. g7 a1=Q+ $19) (60. Bb2!? a1=Q! 61. Bxa1 Rxa1 62. g7 Ra8 $19) 60... Rc1+! 61. Kxc1 bxc3 62. g8=Q a1=Q+ 63. Kc2 Qb2+ 64. Kd3 Qd2#) 57... gxh5 58. g6 h4! 59. g7! (59. Bxh4?? Rg8! 60. Rxa2 Rxg6 61. Ra8 c3+ 62. Ke2 Rg2+ 63. Ke3 Rd2! $19 { "One of the black pawns would have inevitably queened." -Kasparov }) 59... h3 60. Be7!! { Spassky finds a brilliant idea over the board and challenges Fischer's assessment of the position. Bf8 is about to be played, disconnecting the rook from the g8 square. This was the end of Fischer's adjournment analysis because, only now, 18 moves into this somewhat forcing endgame, did Fischer begin to think. } (60. Kc2?! { Perhaps this is the line that Fischer had spotted during his overnight analysis? } 60... f4! 61. Be7?? (61. Kb2! f3 62. Be5! { The h pawn is stopped, and amazingly, black can't make progress here either. } 62... b3!? (62... Rd8!? 63. Bd4! $10) 63. Rd1 f2 64. Kc3 Re8 65. Ra1 $10 { The bishop is immune to capture, and black cannot make further progress. }) 61... h2 62. Bf8 Re8! 63. g8=Q Re2+! 64. Kd1 h1=Q+ 65. Kxe2 Qxa1 $19 { White's bishop is no match for black's pawns. }) 60... Rg8!! { Played after 21 minutes. Fischer willingly traps his rook (in order to prevent Bf8 and g8=Q), and claims that his 5 connected passed pawns are worth Spassky's rook. } (60... h2?! 61. Bf8 b3 62. Kc3! { White is threatening to promote, with a clear advantage. Black is the one who has to bail out for a draw now. } (62. g8=Q Rd8+ 63. Ke2 b2 $10 { Unbelievably this is another way to play as black as well. White has no checks and black will be getting a queen next move no matter what. }) 62... Rd8! 63. g8=Q Rd3+ 64. Kb2 Rd2+ 65. Kc3 Rd3+ $10 { A trivial draw. }) 61. Bf8 h2!? { Played after 38 minutes. Objectively this position is not winning for black. Yet the Herculean effort Fischer puts into this position in order to create winning chances from a position where he's effectively down a bishop and rook deserves praise. } (61... b3!? 62. Kc3! h2 63. Rd1 f4 64. Kb2 f3 $10 { Little winning chances, with the king now on b2. Admittedly, this is similar to the game. }) (61... c3+!? { Fischer probably spent the majority of his time calculating this variation. } 62. Kd3! (62. Kc2?? Kc4 $19 { [%cal Gb4b3] }) 62... h2! { Much more double-edged. Fischer's pawns don't defend themselves, yet they better cut off white's king from the a pawn. There is no progress here either, although it is close. } 63. Rf1 f4 64. Rh1 f3 65. Rf1 f2 66. Rd1! { The only move! } (66. Rh1?? Kc6! 67. Rd1 Kd5! $19 { Black will march to g2 adn win the game. }) 66... Kc6 67. Kc4! c2 68. Rf1 Kd7 69. Kxb4 Ke6 70. Kb3 Kd5 71. Kxc2! Ke4 72. Kb2 Kf3!? (72... Kd3!? 73. Rh1! $10 { And black cannot make further progress. } 73... Ke2?! (73... Ke4!? 74. Bc5! Rxg7 75. Bxf2 $10 { Both pawns are dropping next. }) 74. Rxh2 Kf3 75. Rxf2+! Kxf2 76. Kxa2 $10) 73. Bc5! Kg3 74. Bd6+ Kg2 75. Rxf2+! Kxf2 76. Bxh2 Rxg7 77. Kxa2 $10 { A theoretical draw. }) 62. Kc2 { Finally, the king can approach the a pawn. } 62... Kc6 { Fischer tries to get his king to the kingside, where it will actually help shepherd the f and g pawns home. } (62... b3+!? 63. Kc3 Kc6 64. Rd1! { Transposes to the game. }) 63. Rd1! { Fischer's king is cut off from the queenside, and Spassky argues that the pawns alone cannot make further progress. Indeed, the game is level. } (63. Rxa2?? b3+ 64. Kb2 bxa2 65. Kxa2 h1=Q $19) (63. Kb2?! Kd5! 64. Kxa2 Ke4 { This type of scenario should not be allowed. Fischer's king is inches away from g2, after which he is winning. } 65. Rh1! f4 66. Rxh2 f3 67. Rh4+ Kd3 68. Rh2 $10) 63... b3+ 64. Kc3!? (64. Kb2!? f4 65. Rd6+ Kc7 66. Rd1! f3 67. Kc3 f2 68. Kb2 $10 { No progress can be made for either side. Gligoric drawing continuation. }) 64... h1=Q! { Distracting the rook from the d file so that Fischer can get his king up in the endgame. } 65. Rxh1 Kd5 66. Kb2 { This move has to be played eventually, so that the white rook is free to leave the 1st rank. } (66. Rd1+!? { The other try by white also works. } 66... Ke4 67. Re1+ Kf3 68. Kb2! { Stopping the a pawn so that white's rook can try and capture the f pawn. } 68... f4 69. Rc1 Kg2 70. Rxc4 f3 71. Rg4+ { with a draw similar to move 69. } 71... Kh3!? (71... Kf1!? 72. Bc5 f2 73. Bxf2! { And all the pawns get vacuumed off the board. } 73... Kxf2 74. Ra4 Rxg7 75. Kxb3 $10) 72. Rf4 Kg3 73. Rf7 Kg2 74. Bc5 { Now Fischer is on the worse side of equal. But there's nothing to do here. } 74... Kg3 $10) 66... f4 (66... Ke4?! 67. Re1+ { With the pawn still on f5, the frontal check defense is applicable to this position. } 67... Kf4 68. Rc1 Ke3 69. Rxc4 f4 $10 { Black is down a tempo from the later critical line. }) 67. Rd1+ Ke4 68. Rc1 Kd3! (68... f3?! { Objectively, this is as strong as what was played in the game. However, the following variation is practically easier to play because it is more forcing. } 69. Rxc4+ Kd3 70. Rf4 Ke2 71. Re4+ Kd3 72. Rf4 $10) 69. Rd1+?? { The losing blunder, played with only 4 minutes left on Spassky's clock. } (69. Rc3+! { Forces a draw. Spassky saw this variation immediately after the game, even playing out the moves on the board by himself after Fischer had left the playing hall. } 69... Kd4!? (69... Ke2!? 70. Rxc4 f3 71. Re4+! Kd3!? (71... Kf1!? 72. Rf4 Kg2 73. Rg4+! $10 { No progress on this side either! }) 72. Rf4 $10 Ke3?! { The last try to avoid a perpetual. But now black has: } 73. Rf7! { The threat of Bc5+ forces black's hand. } 73... Ke2 (73... f2?? 74. Bc5+ $18) 74. Re7+ (74. Bc5!? { It's probably better to not even allow this from Spassky. Honestly, white may have some winning chances here. } 74... Ra8 75. Ra7! Rg8 76. Rf7 Ra8 $10) 74... Kd3 75. Rf7 $10 { No progress can be made. }) 70. Rf3! c3+! 71. Ka1! c2 72. Rxf4+ Kc3 73. Rf3+ Kd2 74. Ba3!! { Gligoric found this drawing line. } 74... Rxg7 75. Rxb3 Rc7 76. Bb2 $10) 69... Ke2! { Fischer gains a crucial tempo here, allowing his f pawn to march forward. } 70. Rc1!? (70. Rd7!? { The critical line doesn't pan out for white with an extra c pawn still on the board. } 70... f3 71. Re7+ Kf1 72. Rf7 Kg2! 73. Bc5 { This looks similar to the line starting with 69. Rc3+, but it's crucial that black retains an extra c pawn. } 73... c3+! 74. Ka1 (74. Kxc3?? a1=Q+ $19) 74... Rb8! { And there is no way to stop b2+ and b1=Q. } 75. Bb6!? (75. Rf8?! b2+ 76. Kxa2 b1=Q+ 77. Ka3 Qb3#) 75... c2! 76. Rc7!? (76. Kb2?! a1=Q+ 77. Kxa1 c1=Q#) 76... f2 $19 { White's forces are overworked in every direction. } { [%cal Gf2f1] }) 70... f3! 71. Bc5!? { Spassky decides to delegate the task of stopping f2 with the bishop, but this lets black's rook finally escape its jail. } (71. Rxc4!? { The difference of the one tempo can be seen in these variations. } 71... f2 72. Re4+ (72. Rc1?! f1=Q 73. Rxf1 Kxf1 74. Kxb3?! a1=Q! $19) 72... Kf3! $19) 71... Rxg7 72. Rxc4 Rd7! { Fischer simply wants to check white's king away from the defense of a1=Q. } (72... f2!? 73. Bxf2 Kxf2 $19 { With a theoretically winning position. Yet this is not as convincing as the game. }) 73. Re4+ (73. Rf4?! Rd2+! 74. Ka1 Rd1+ 75. Kb2 a1=Q+ $19) (73. Bd4?! f2! { A simple deflection ensures that black's rook breaks through to white's king. } 74. Bxf2 Rd2+! 75. Ka1 Rd1+ 76. Kb2 a1=Q+ $19) (73. Rc1?! Rd1 $19 { [%cal Ga2a1] }) 73... Kf1 74. Bd4 { Spassky succeeds in stopping Fischer's rook from infiltrating to white's king... but only for one move. } 74... f2! $19 { Spassky resigned, now that the finish was apparent to both players. Fischer instantly took off from the board, while Spassky stayed in his seat, stunned at how he had just lost this game. "It is very strange. How can one lose with the opponent's only rook locked in completely at g8?"
Botvinnik called this game Fischer's highest creative achievement. } { 0-1 Black wins. } 75. Rf4!? { If Spassky had played on, Fischer wins with: } (75. Bxf2?! Rd2+! 76. Ka1 Rd1+ 77. Kb2 a1=Q+ $19) 75... Rxd4! 76. Rxd4 Ke2 77. Re4+ Kf3! 78. Re8 f1=Q 79. Rf8+ Ke2 80. Rxf1 Kxf1 $19 { and white's king loses to the two connected passed pawns. } 0-1


