1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bd3?! { Bd3 doesn't try to take advantage of my potentially vulnerable bishop. } 5... Ne7 6. Bxf5 Nxf5 7. O-O c5 8. Nc3? { The center is now successfully undermined. Nb5 is not a threat. } 8... Nc6 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxe3 11. fxe3 Bc5 (11... Nxe5 12. Qh5 Ng6 { This line wins a clear pawn, but I didn't want to deal with the potential attack due to white's active pieces. }) 12. Ncb5 a6 (12... O-O { More directly fights for the maximum advantage. }) 13. Nd6+ (13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nd4 Qc7 { I was considering this as my main line, and was confident black was better. }) 13... Bxd6 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Qf3 { There's no compensation for the pawn. Black has the more active pieces, center control, and better structure. } 15... O-O 16. b3?! { The c pawn now becomes a target after c3 is no longer an option. } 16... Rac8 17. Rac1 (17. Nxc6 Rxc6 18. c4 dxc4 19. bxc4 Qc7 $17) 17... Nb4 18. a3 (18. c4 { [%cal Gb4a2] } 18... Nxa2 $17) 18... Na2 { The knight goes on an adventure in order to reposition so as to kill all counterplay. } 19. Rce1 Nc3! { e3 and c2 remain permanent weaknesses. They'll be picked up on better circumstances. } 20. b4 b5 21. Qf4 Ne4 22. Qxd6 Nxd6 23. Rf3 Rc3 24. Nb3 Ne4! { Stops Nc5 and any hope black has of getting active. c2 or a3 now falls by force. } 25. h4 Rxc2 26. Nc5 Nxc5 27. bxc5 Rxc5 { White resigned rather than play down 3 pawns. } *


