1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 c5 3. c3 d5 { In my opinion, this is the best try for black in the delayed alapin. It will probably become a french where white has already played Nf3. } 4. Bb5+?! { White's good bishop has no business trading itself with any of black's minor pieces. } (4. e5 Nc6 5. d4 { French advanced }) 4... Nc6 5. Ne5? Qc7 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Be2 { White has now wasted 3 moves in order to strengthen black's center. The doubled pawns are a strength, not a weakness. } 7... Nf6 8. O-O?? { Hands black the pawn without having to sacrifice his structure. } (8. d3 c4!? 9. exd5 (9. dxc4 Nxe4) 9... cxd3 10. Qxd3 cxd5 $15) 8... Nxe4 9. Re1 c4 10. d4 (10. Bxc4 Bd6 { My idea - black sacrifices the pawn back in order to get a huge initiative and lots of pressure on white's king. } 11. g3 h5) 10... Bd6 11. h3 f5 12. Nd2 { With the permanent support of the d and f pawns, black's knight on e4 never needs to move. In fact, there's no way for it to pushed out because f3 would be too weakening now that h3 has already been played. } 12... O-O 13. f3?? { Never play f3. } 13... Bh2+ 14. Kf1 (14. Kh1 Nf2#) 14... Qg3!? (14... Ng3+ 15. Kf2 Qf4 16. Nxc4 Ne4+ 17. Kf1 Qh4 18. Be3 Ng3+ 19. Kf2 f4 $19) 15. Nxe4 (15. fxe4 fxe4+ 16. Bf3 exf3 17. Nxf3 e5 $19) 15... fxe4 16. Be3 e5! { With this beautiful move, black is now ready to break through to white's king on the weakened dark squares. } 17. Qd2 (17. Bf2 { The last chance for white to hold off the killer attack. I had planned } 17... Qxh3!) 17... Bxh3! 18. Bd1 (18. gxh3 Qxh3+ 19. Kf2 Rxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Qxf3#) 18... Rxf3+!! 19. Bxf3 (19. Qf2 Rxf2+ 20. Bxf2 Bxg2+ 21. Ke2 Qd3#) 19... Qxf3+ 20. Qf2 Bxg2#! *


