1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 Bg4 4. Be2 e6 5. O-O c5 6. d4?! { The reason this move isn't great is that I can gain a tempo on white's queen. } 6... Nc6?! (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 { It requires giving up the light-squared bishop, but I had already committed to doing just that with Bg4. }) 7. h3?? (7. c3 { White has time to recover towards a more normal Caro-Kann structure due to my inaccuracy. }) 7... Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Nxd4 { White gives up an extremely important pawn and therefore the game. } 9. c3 Nxf3+ 10. Qxf3 Ne7 11. Be3 Nc6 { The knight stands well on c6. But it also stands well on f5 where it eventually ends up. } 12. Qg3 Qc7 { [%csl Ge5] } 13. f4 { As soon as f4 was played, it makes sense to immediately re-route the knight to f5. Unintuitive to keep moving the knights around without finishing development, but it's best. } 13... Ne7! 14. Nd2 Nf5 15. Qf2?? d4!! { The bishop is trapped and the pawn cannot be taken because of the deadly pin. } 16. cxd4 cxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 (18. Rac1 Qb6 19. Nf3 Ne2+! { A possible variation showcasing the power of this diagonal. }) 18... Bc5 19. Qxc5 Qxc5+ 20. Kh1 O-O 21. Rfc1 Qd4 22. Nf3 Qxf4 23. Rc7 Rac8 { White resigned rather than play on down a queen. } *


