1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 { [%cal Ga7a6,Ge7e6] } 4... e6 5. Nb5 { A move that rmantf2 had originally suggested I play if black does not play 5... a6 } { [%csl Gd6] } 5... d6 6. c4 { [%csl Gc4,Ge4] } (6. Bf4 e5 7. Be3 Nf6 8. Bg5 { White is a tempo down from the mainline Sveshnikov, but it's still playable. Personally, I do not like this variation. }) 6... a6 7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Be3 Be7 9. Be2 O-O { We've entered a Maroczy bind/hedgehog with all the normal ideas, except white's knights are extremely awkward. Instead of playing solidly, I found an idea that I figured would change it up a bit, and take advantage of black's decision to castle kingside as early as possible. } 10. g4!? b6?! (10... b5! 11. g5 Nxe4!! 12. Nxe4 bxc4 { Extremely unclear, but black apparently has enough here to convince the computer that this is playable. }) 11. g5 Nd7 12. Qd2 Bb7 { [%cal Ga8h1] } 13. Rg1 { Gets the rook off the long diagonal and opposite black's king. But there are potentially more pressing pieces to develop, like the b1 knight. } (13. Na3!? Nc5 14. f3 Nb4 { But even here, white cannot castle queenside. }) 13... Qc7?! { Now the d5 break never packs that much punch. The queen is better on d8, and the more immediate b5 or d5 breaks should be forced through. } (13... b5 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Bxb5 Nc5 $15) 14. f4 Nc5 15. f5 { [%cal Gc3d5] } 15... exf5?? { While it's true that black opens up the e file to attack white's king, the more immediate issue is the gaping hole on d5 is now firmly under white's control and both knights are ready to jump in. } (15... Rfd8! 16. f6 Bf8 { Keeping the d5 square fully under black's control is crucial. This is a much improved version of the game. }) 16. exf5 Rae8?? (16... Nb4!? { The knight cannot be kicked away due to Nb3. Moreover, Nb4 says "no" to any knight jumping to d5. }) 17. f6 Bd8 (17... Nb4!! 18. fxe7 Qxe7 19. Rg3 { White is up a piece, but black's beautiful coordination and safe king make this a roughly even game. White's knights are misplaced if they cannot make use of the d5 square. }) 18. Nd5 Qd7 19. fxg7 { [%csl Gf8] } 19... Kxg7 20. Nbc3 Qe6 21. O-O-O Ne5 { White has reached a near perfect position. All of his pieces are finally in the game, but a knockout proves difficult to find. Instead of continuing the sharp, tactical game that has led us to this point, I decide to cash out and reach more positional waters where white is guaranteed to be slightly better, up an exchange and playing against the weak d6 pawn. } 22. g6?! (22. Rdf1! { The morphy move I wanted to play. But the computer proves that there is no breakthrough for at least a while. } 22... Bxd5 23. Nxd5 Qh3 24. Kb1 Kh8 25. Bd4 Ne6 26. Bc3 Rg8) 22... fxg6 23. Bh6+ Kg8 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. Rdf1 { Black resigned here, where clearly there is much more work for white to do in order to prove this is a win. } *


