1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Ngf6 9. O-O { I'm not used to seeing the combination of kingside castling and quick development without play h4 and/or h5. So I just believed this was roughly even. } 9... e6 10. Re1 Be7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Ne4?! { Normally this move makes sense, but in this case white is removing a defender with an attacker. } 12... Nxe4 13. Rxe4 Nf6 14. Re2 c5! { I was sure this position was equal now that I got my c5 break in and white cannot play d5 in response. } 15. Rd2 Qb6 { [%csl Gb2] } 16. c3 Rfd8 17. Re1 h6 18. Be5 Qc6 { Now that the knight cannot occupy the e5 square, I figured this piece rearrangement was useful. In fact, black is no longer threatening anything with cxd4 because Nxd4 now comes with tempo. } (18... Ng4 19. Bf4 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Rxd4! 21. cxd4 (21. Qxd4 Bc5 $19) 21... Bb4 22. h3 Nf6 $15 { An interesting way to prove some sort of advantage for black. }) 19. h3 Rac8 20. Qc2 Nd5! 21. Rde2 (21. c4?? cxd4 { [%cal Gc6c2] }) 21... Bd6 { Black finds a way to trade off his passive bishop for white's strongest piece. } 22. Qe4 Bxe5 23. Nxe5 { At first I thought everything was fine here for black, but then I realized that white is threatening Nxf7 Kxf7 Qxe6+ in some variations. Thus, it's crucial to defend the f7 pawn or e6 pawn. Unfortunately, I chose wrong. } 23... Qc7?? 24. a3?? { White misses his chance to capitalize. Now black can consolidate. } (24. dxc5! Qxc5 (24... Qe7 25. Rd2 Rxc5 26. c4 $18) 25. c4 (25. Nxf7?? Kxf7 26. Qxe6+ Kf8 $17) 25... Nf6 26. Qxb7 $18) 24... cxd4 25. c4?? { Unjustified sacrifice to try and get an attack that no longer exists. } (25. cxd4 Qb6 $15) 25... Nf6 26. Qf3 (26. Qf4 Rd6 27. b4 a5 28. Qf3 axb4 29. axb4 b5 30. c5 Ra6 31. g4 Ra4) 26... Rd6 27. b4 a5 28. g4 axb4 29. axb4 b5?! (29... Rcd8 { Obviously correct. I was losing patience at how slow my opponent was moving, so I went for a rushed threat instead of calming improving my position. } 30. h4 d3 31. Rd2 Qe7 32. g5 hxg5 33. hxg5 Nd7 $19 { There is no attack as long as black plays precisely. }) 30. c5 Ra6 (30... Rd5 31. h4 d3 32. Nxd3 h5!! { Black stabilizes the kingside attack and will soon win on the queenside. I missed this idea of playing h5 to stop every threat. } { [%cal Gf6g4] }) 31. Qf4 Rd8 32. h4 Ra4 33. Rb1 d3! (33... Nd5 34. Qxd4 Nxb4 35. Qe4 Nd3! 36. Qc6 Rxg4+ 37. Kf1 Qxc6 38. Nxc6 Rxh4 $19 { I missed the Nd3 tactics, but found something else that I was sure won. }) 34. Nxd3 (34. Rd2 Nd5 { [%cal Gd5b4,Gd5c3] } 35. Qd4 Nxb4 36. Qe3 Nd5 37. Qxd3 Qxe5 { White's pieces are all on bad squares and there's no way to defend the various loose pieces. }) (34. Re3 Nd5) (34. Ree1 d2 35. Red1 Nd5 { Same as before }) (34. Reb2 Nd5) 34... Qxf4 35. Nxf4 Rd4 { Black willingly gave up a pawn in order to get a monster rook raking everything on the 4th rank. } 36. c6?? (36. g5 Ne8 37. Ng2 Raxb4 38. Rxb4 Rxb4 39. gxh6 gxh6 $17 { Best play. Black is a clear pawn up, has already blockaded the passed c pawn, and is soon to push through the b pawn for a win. }) 36... Rxf4 37. Rc2 Rxg4+ 38. Kf1 Nd5 { Here white resigned rather than try a few last attempts. } { [%cal Gc6c7,Gd5c7] } 39. c7 (39. Rd1!? { [%cal Gd1d5] } 39... Ra8! { [%cal Gd1d5,Ge6d5,Gc6c7,Ga8c8] }) 39... Nxc7 40. Rxc7 { [%cal Gg4h4,Ga4b4] } *


