1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O a6 5. Ba4 Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 { Main line ruy lopez } 10... Bb7?! { c5 is the main move instead, and black gets a lot of queenside space in exchange for the center. } (10... c5 11. d4 Qc7 $10) 11. d4 exd4 12. cxd4 Nc4 13. b3 Nb6 { This maneuver is ill-advised, as the knight has now re-routed to a worse square than it was on c6 where it can transfer quickly to g6. } 14. Nbd2 Re8 15. Nf1 { [%cal Gf1g3,Gf1e3] } 15... d5!? { A well-timed strike in the center. White cannot and should not take this pawn because it would open up the entire black army. } 16. e5 Ne4 17. Ne3 (17. Ng3!? Nxg3 18. fxg3 c5 19. e6!) 17... Bb4 (17... c5! 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Bf4 cxd4 20. N3xd4 { The position I was most worried about. I couldn't tell if I still had an attack, or if black's activity on the queenside would roll me over. }) 18. Bd2 Bxd2 (18... Nxd2 19. Nxd2 { A better try - black keeps the bishop pair and can reroute his bishop back to f8 if necessary. }) 19. Nxd2 Nc3? 20. Qg4 (20. Qh5 g6 21. Qh6 Bc8 22. Nf3 { The attack is too quick. I couldn't see this far because none of the moves were forced. } { [%cal Gf3g5] }) 20... Re6 21. Nf3 h6 22. Nf5 (22. Bf5! { Obviously correct. I completely missed this move. } 22... Re8 23. e6 fxe6 24. Bxe6+ $18) 22... Rg6 { At first I thought this was impossible because of Nxh6, but then found out to my horror that Rxh6 saves the day. } 23. Qh5 (23. Nxh6+?? Rxh6 $19) 23... a5 24. N3h4 Rg5 25. Nxh6+ gxh6 26. Qxh6 { We reach the position I had been aiming for, but I immediately bungle it. } { [%cal Gh6g5,Gc2h7] } 26... Rg7 (26... Ne4 27. f3 Rg7! 28. Nf5! Rg6 29. Qe3 Ng5 30. h4 Ne6 31. Nh6+ Kg7 32. Bxg6 fxg6 33. g3 { A long, not quite forced variation where black defends the attack, but trades two pieces for the rook and two pawns. White's pieces are a little misplaced, so it's unclear compensation. }) 27. f4?? (27. e6! { I only noticed this move AFTER I played my follow-up. This is obviously better than what I came up with, and in fact is winning according to the computer. } 27... Ne4 28. Nf5! Qg5 (28... Rg6 29. exf7+ Kxf7 30. Qh7+ Kf6 31. Ng3! $18) 29. exf7+ Kxf7) 27... Ne4 { With the threat of Rh7, white's queen is trapped, and knight on h4 is falling, so white is forced to play the following, in which white is just down a piece. I resigned instead. } { [%cal Gg7h7] } 28. Bxe4 dxe4 29. Nf5 Rg6 *


