1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bg5 e6 (3... Nbd7 { This has to be a better try than what I played. I was trying to get into a french defense somehow, but it didn't work out. }) 4. Bxf6 (4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Be7 { A line in the french I have a lot of experience playing. }) 4... Qxf6 5. e4 Bb4 { Instead, we're in a Winawer-esque opening where I know no theory. } 6. Ne2 dxe4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 Qg6?! { The greedy try to hold onto the pawn. This is ultimately too greedy though... } (8... Nc6!? { [%cal Gc6d4,Gf6d4] } 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. Nxe4 Qg6 { [%cal Gg6e4,Gg6g2] } 11. Ng3 h5 { This position feels reminiscent of a reversed Winawer now based on piece positioning. }) 9. d5 O-O { At first I thought this was an interesting try, but me and my opponent missed a ridiculously obvious point here. } 10. Bc4?? a6?? (10... Qxg2 $19) 11. Qe2 f5 (11... b5!? { This was my initial idea behind a6, but I misevaluated the ensuing tactics, so I chose a different plan. } 12. Bb3 exd5 13. Bxd5 c6! 14. Bb3 (14. Bxe4?? f5 $19 { [%cal Gf8e8] }) 14... Bf5 $17) 12. O-O-O Kh8 13. Qd2 exd5 (13... e5!? { Obviously correct. I completely missed this idea, and instead started to feel the dark squared weaknesses. }) 14. Qxd5?! (14. Nxd5 { [%cal Gd5c7] } 14... Qc6 15. Bb3 Be6 { My expectations did not occur. }) 14... Nc6 15. g3 h6?! (15... Re8!? { I spotted this idea as soon as I played h6 instead. With the threat of Be6 looming, all of a sudden it's white who needs to figure out how to avoid black's threats. } 16. Ne2 (16. Qf7 Qxf7 17. Bxf7 Rf8 18. Bb3 $15) (16. f4 Be6 $17)) 16. Ne2!! Qf6 17. Nf4 g6 (17... Kh7!? 18. h4 Ne5?! 19. Qc5 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 Rf7 $10) 18. Rhf1 Kg7 19. f3 exf3 20. Rxf3 Ne5?? { I thought this was a good trade, but there's a tactic issue here. } 21. Rc3 (21. Re3! Nxc4 22. Qxc4 { [%csl Gc7] } 22... c6 $18 { Black's dark squares are completely ruined now, and the open files are owned by white. }) 21... Nxc4 22. Rxc4 c6 23. Qc5 Be6 { This was the position I envisioned when I took on f3, but I completely missed white's response which should just end the game. } 24. Rd6 Rae8 25. Rb4 Rf7 26. Qe3 Rfe7 27. h3?? (27. Nxe6+ Rxe6 28. Rxb7+ Kg8 $18 { Completely ends the game. }) 27... Bf7!! { The only move to untangle. } 28. Rxf6 Rxe3 { If any other bishop move besides Bf7 was played, then Rxg6+ would ensure that white is at least even. } 29. Rd6 R8e7 { I figured I'm now better, so I should strive for some stability instead of pawn grabbing to create a passed f pawn. } (29... Rxg3 30. Rxb7 $13) (29... g5! 30. Nd3 R8e7 { A better version of the game. }) 30. g4 fxg4 31. hxg4 Rg3 32. Nd3 Re2!? (32... Rg1+! 33. Kd2 Rg2+ 34. Kc1 Ree2 $19 { [%cal Ge2c2] }) 33. Rxb7?? { Instead my opponent fell for my main trick. } (33. b3!) (33. Kd1 { This was the main move I considered for my opponent. I envisioned that this misplaced the king and an eventual Bd5-f3+ would be good. } 33... Re7 34. Nc5 Bd5 35. Rxb7 Bf3+ 36. Kd2 Rxb7 37. Nxb7 Rg2+ 38. Kc3 Bxg4 $17) 33... Rg1+ 34. Ne1 Rexe1+ 35. Kd2 Rd1+ 36. Kc3 Rxd6 $19 *


