1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Qa5+? 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. d5 Ne5 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Be2?! (7. Bb5+! Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Kxd7 9. f4 exf4 10. Bxf4 { Also looked strong, but I figured that building up a bit more before trading would be even stronger. }) 7... e6 (7... Nf6 8. O-O e6 { I think maybe the game progressed according to this move order... }) 8. O-O Nf6 9. Bg5 (9. f4! Bd6?? { I always assumed that my opponent has this move in response, but because the queen is misplaced on a5, dxe6 simply wins a piece in this position. } (9... exf4 10. e5 Nxd5 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5+ $18)) 9... Be7 10. a4 O-O 11. Bxf6 (11. d6! Bd8 12. Bxf6 Bxf6 13. d7 Rd8 14. dxc8=Q! { I missed this final move necessary to win a piece. } { [%cal Gc8g8] }) 11... Bxf6 12. Bf3 { And now, white has to win the game all over again. I was sure I still had the advantage, but black has the bishop pair and has caught up in development, so it's only a slight pull. } 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Qd8 { [%cal Gd5f6] } 14. Qe2 a6 15. Rfd1 (15. a5 Be6) 15... Be6 16. a5 b5? 17. axb6? (17. Nb6 { How did I miss this simple win of the exchange? } { [%cal Gb6a8,Gd1d8] }) 17... Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Qxb6 19. b3! (19. c3?! { This is the standard type of move in these positions, but in reality, the b pawn on the open file becomes a target that is not easy to defend. }) 19... a5 20. Qc4 { [%cal Gc4c5,Gd5c5] } 20... Rfc8 21. Bg4 (21. Rd7 { [%cal Gc4f7,Gd7f7] } 21... Rf8 { I didn't see any real progress being made, and Rad8 is soon to follow. }) 21... Rc7 { [%cal Gd5d7] } 22. Ra4! { Stops any threats of a4 as well as the positional threat of Qb4 offering a queen trade, exchanging the defensive queen on b6 for the active queen on c4. } 22... g6 23. Qc3 { [%cal Gc3a5,Ga4a5,Gd5c5,Gc3c5,Gc3e5] } 23... h5 24. Be2 h4!? (24... Kg7!? { My initial expectation from the position. Indeed, this move is good too. }) 25. Bc4 { [%cal Gh4h3,Gc3h3] } 25... Rd8?! { Black cracks - going for active counterplay instead of passive defense. However, in this situation, White can win a pawn, and avoid any issues on his weak king, so a pawn is a pawn. } (25... Kg7 { White retains a small plus, but it's not completely clear how to improve the position further. }) 26. Rxd8+ Bxd8 27. Qxa5?! (27. Qxe5! Bf6 28. Qe8+ Kg7 29. e5!! { The move I missed in this position, which ensures white a decisive advantage. } 29... Bg5 30. e6 Qd6 31. Rxa5 Qd1+ 32. Bf1 $18) 27... Rd7 (27... Qxa5 28. Rxa5 Rd7 29. Ra1 { Best try for black. As long as white retains the rook though, the passed b pawn should still keep an advantage for white. }) 28. Qe1! { Retain the queens, and ensure there's no threat of an opposite color bishop endgame. } 28... Bg5 29. Ra6 { [%cal Ga6g6,Gc4g8] } 29... Qd8! { Defense and attack! } { [%cal Gd7d1] } 30. Bd5 { Defense and attack right back at you! } { [%cal Ga6a8,Gd7d1] } 30... Kg7 31. g3!! hxg3 (31... h3? 32. Ra8 Qe7 33. Qf1 { While at first this looks scary, it soon becomes clear that white is winning the h pawn by force. } { [%cal Gf1h3] } 33... f5?? 34. Rg8+ Kf6 $18) 32. hxg3 Qh8 33. Ra8 Qh3 (33... Rd8?? { The move black wants to play in order to take control of the h file. However, here it loses because of the f7 weakness. } 34. Ra7! Rf8 35. Qc3 $18 { [%cal Gc3c5,Gc3e5,Gc3f3] } 35... Qh5 36. Qxe5+ Bf6 37. Qe6) 34. Qe2!? { [%cal Ge2f3,Ge2a6] } (34. Qc3 { Slightly more precise. }) 34... f5?? { The right idea, but ultimately, it weakens the king way too much. } 35. Rg8+ Kf6 (35... Kh6 36. exf5! Rxd5 37. Rh8+ { [%cal Gh8h3] }) (35... Kh7 36. Qa6! { [%cal Ga6g6] } 36... Qh5 37. Qe6 $18) 36. Qa6+ Ke7 37. Qe6# *


