1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O d6 5. Re1 Be7 6. c3 Bd7 7. d4 a6 (7... O-O!? 8. Ba4 { The main line Steinitz }) 8. Bf1 { Always retreat. } (8. Bd3 exd4 9. cxd4 Nb4 10. Bf1 { I had seen this idea before, but I don't feel like the knight is that misplaced on b4. }) 8... O-O 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. h3 exd4 11. cxd4 d5?! { My opponent afterwards agreed that maybe d5 here was too early } 12. e5 Nh5 13. Nb3 { [%cal Gb3c5,Gb3d4] } 13... g6 { [%cal Gh5g7,Gg7e6,Gg7f5] } 14. Bd2!? (14. Be3 f6!? { I was considering this idea first, but decided I preferred to pre-empt f6 and N/Bb4 instead with a slightly awkward move }) 14... Bb4 15. a3 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 b6 { Makes sense to immediately block out the knight. But in this case, it leaves behind weaknesses on the light squares. } { [%cal Gb3a5,Gb3c5] } 17. Rac1 (17. Qh6!? Ng7?? (17... f5 $16) 18. Ng5 $18) 17... Ng7 18. Rc3 Re6 19. Rec1 Qe8 (19... Nf5? 20. Ng5 { Initially my opponent tried this idea, but we took it back and re-approached the game with a better defense. }) 20. Ng5 Re7 21. Qc2 Nd8 22. Rxc7 Nde6 23. Nxe6 Nxe6 24. Rc3 Ba4 25. Qd2 Bxb3! { This counter-intuitive move is directed at entering an endgame, where black is down a pawn, but in a good knight vs OK-bishop endgame. The computer recommends it even though the knight was so poorly placed on b3 because of the improved drawing chances (which shouldn't be enough anyway). } 26. Rxb3 b5 27. Rbc3 Qd8 28. g3 Qb6 { [%csl Gd4] } 29. Rd1 Rc7!? { Continuing to trade off white's active pieces for black's passive pieces. } 30. Rxc7 Qxc7 31. Bg2 Qd7?! (31... Qc4! { A better, more active try }) 32. Rc1 Rd8 33. Kh2 Kg7 34. h4 Qe7 35. Bh3 { Giving up hope on the d pawn, and admitting that black's knight is better than white's bishop. } 35... Rd7 36. Bxe6 (36. Rc6 Rc7 { I was afraid of this idea, but now I see it loses. } 37. Rxa6! Rc4 38. Bxe6 fxe6 $18) 36... Qxe6 37. Qc3 Re7 38. Qc6 Qxc6 39. Rxc6 Ra7 40. Rd6 a5 41. Rxd5 b4 42. a4! { Keeping more pawns on the board ensures that the passed d pawn will not be the only trump in white's position. } 42... Kf8 (42... Rc7! { Activity is crucial }) 43. Kg2 Ke7 44. Kf3 Ke6 45. Ke4 f5+ 46. exf6 Kxf6 47. Re5 Rc7! { Gotta get activity. But it's too little too late. } 48. Rxa5 Rc2 49. Ra6+ Ke7 50. d5? { I figured it was important to start getting my passed pawns rolling. But instead, limiting black's activity with the passed b pawn is more pressing. } (50. b3! Rb2!? (50... Rxf2 51. Rb6 { [%cal Gb6b4] }) 51. Kd5 Rxb3 52. a5 { Arrives at a position similar to the game, but where white's king is better as opposed to his passed d pawn. }) 50... Rxb2 51. d6+ Kd7 52. Ke5 Re2+ 53. Kd5 Rd2+ 54. Kc5 b3 (54... Rc2+?? 55. Kxb4) 55. Ra7+ Ke6? (55... Kc8! { Getting in front of the passed pawn is crucial. But this move also stops Rb7, so white's defense of the b pawn is put into question in a big way with this seemingly passive move. During the game, this is what I was most worried about. }) 56. Re7+ Kf5 57. a5 b2 58. Rb7 Rc2+ 59. Kd5 Rd2+ 60. Kc6? Rc2+?? (60... Ke6!! { It's crucial to stop white's king from getting in front of his passer. } { [%cal Gd2d6] } 61. d7?? (61. Kc5 Rd5+! 62. Kc4 Rxa5 { Now black's king position is much better than white's. This is most likely drawn due to the activity of black's position. }) 61... Rc2+ $19 { How unfortunate this would be! }) 61. Kd7 Rxf2 62. a6 Ke5 63. Rb5+ Kd4 64. Ke7 Re2+ 65. Kd8 Re6 66. Kd7 Re2 67. a7 { Black resigned rather than make the futile follow-up moves: } 67... Kc4 68. Rxb2 Rxb2 69. a8=Q { [%cal Gd6d8] } *


