1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Bf4 Be7 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e3 { A typical QGD setup. I recall seeing some Nakamura games with this Bf4 idea, and I thought the main way to take advantage of this not hitting my knight on f6 was to pressure the center further. Rather than going for a direct c5 strike though, I first wanted to try an a6-b5 semi-slav counter attack on the c4 bishop. } 6... a6 7. a4?! { At first I thought the inclusion of a6-a4 helped white, but after further analysis, I realized that my c6 knight would be much happier now than if these moves hadn't been included. } (7. Bd3?! dxc4 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Bd3 Bb7 { This is what I had figured could happen, and I like these structures as black. }) (7. Rc1 { Probably best. }) 7... c5 8. Bd3 { White no longer plays the waiting game. Personally I would have first played Rc1 or cxd5 before Bd3, but this can't be bad. } 8... Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nb4 { I directly head towards the isolated queen's pawn position, where blockading d5 is crucial. } { [%cal Gb4d5] } 12. Bg5 { White has now moved two pieces (both bishops) twice in the opening, and has an isolated queen's pawn. If I could simplify a little further, I felt I would be better. } (12. Re1) 12... h6 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Re1 Bd7 { [%cal Gd7c6] } 15. Ne5 (15. Qb3!? { The move I was most scared of - the queen locks in on the d5 square, and the loose b7 pawn with tempo! } 15... Nc6! 16. d5 (16. Qxb7?? Rb8 17. Qxa6 Rb6 { The queen is trapped. }) (16. Rad1 Na5 $15) 16... Na5 $17) 15... Bxe5 (15... Bc6) 16. Rxe5 Bc6 17. Ra3 Rc8 18. Rb3 Nd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Be2 Bxa4 21. Bg4 Bxb3 22. Qxb3 Rc1+ 23. Bd1 Re8 24. Rxe8+ Qxe8 25. Kf1 Qe4 26. g3 Qxd4 27. Ke2 Qxd1+ 28. Qxd1 Rxd1 29. Kxd1 Kf8 30. Kd2 Ke7 31. Kd3 Kd6 32. Kd4 b6 33. f3 a5 34. b3 b5 35. h3 a4 36. Kc3 Kc5 37. b4+ Kd6 38. f4 g6 39. g4 Ke6 40. h4 h5 41. gxh5 gxh5 42. f5+ Kxf5 43. Kd4 Ke6 44. Kc5 a3 *


