1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Ne2 { After this "slow" move, it makes sense to not go for the default plan of taking the knight and instead transition to a QGD where white's knight is arguably misplaced. } 5... d5 (5... c6!? 6. a3 Ba5 { [%cal Ga5c7] }) 6. a3 Be7 7. Nf4 b6 (7... c6 { I was unsure if going for a semi-slav would make sense with the current move order. Rather than play it fast and loose with dxc4+b5 semi-slav plans, I decided to go for a Tartakower esque setup. } 8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. O-O dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5 $10) 8. cxd5! { The critical try. White tries to show that black's pawn structure is damaged. } 8... Nxd5 9. Ncxd5 exd5 10. Be2?! { Wouldn't the bishop be better on d3? The only reason I could find for placing the bishop on e2 would be to transfer to f3 to pressure the d5 "weakness." } 10... Bb7 11. b4 Nd7 12. Qc2 c6 { Safe and solid. Black can play with the a5 idea instead of just the c5 break. } 13. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3h7] } 13... Nf6 14. Bd2 { Visually weird, but it stops a5. } (14. O-O a5 $10) 14... Re8 { [%cal Ge8e1] } 15. O-O Bd6 16. Ne2 Qe7 17. Ng3 { [%cal Gg3f5,Gf5d6,Gf5e7] } 17... g6 { As long as my bishop can retreat to f8 (always play Bf8!), this isn't a weakness. } 18. Qd1 { Now that white is less prepared to deal with an opening of the queenside, I decided it was time to strike. The engine prefers slow improving moves. } { [%cal Gg8g7,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gb7c8,Gc8d7] } (18. h3!? c5 19. Bb5 Rec8 20. Rab1 c4 21. Ne2 a6 22. Ba4) 18... c5!? (18... Kg7!?) 19. Bb5?! (19. dxc5 bxc5 20. bxc5 Bxc5 { Bb6 is safe, and the d4 break is going to liquidate black's weakness and open up the position while black is more active. }) 19... Rec8 20. Rb1? (20. bxc5 bxc5 21. dxc5 Bxc5 { Similar. }) 20... c4! { Now black has a passed pawn, queenside majority, and white has no active e4 break. } 21. Ne2 a6 22. Ba4 b5 23. Bc2 Re8 24. h3 Rad8 25. Bc3 Bc8 { As long as I maintain pressure on b4, and a4 is never really liberating white's pieces, I can regroup towards a kingside attack. } 26. Ra1 Ne4 27. Bb2 Qc7 { [%cal Gd6h2,Gc8h3,Ge4g3,Ge4f2] } 28. f4!? { A new weakness, but it's certainly double edged. On a good day, white can play f5 himself and counter-attack my king. } 28... Bf5 29. Qe1 Qd7 { [%cal Gf5h3] } 30. Rf3 h5?! { Unnecessary. Ultimately, this encourages white to play f5, when fxg6 is very weakening. } (30... Bf8! 31. Nc3) 31. Nc3 Bf8 32. Qd1 Nxc3 33. Bxc3 Bxc2 34. Qxc2 Re4 35. f5 Bh6? (35... g5! { Keeping it closed and keeping the f pawn on f7 where it belongs. } 36. f6 g4!) 36. fxg6 fxg6 37. Qf2 Rde8 38. Bd2 h4? { Trying to stop Qg3 and Qh4 ideas. But it's again a bit weakening and unnecessary. } (38... R8e7 39. Rf1 Bg7 $15) 39. Rf6 R8e6 40. Rf1 Qe7 41. a4? (41. Rf7 Qd6 42. Kh1 Bg7 $15) 41... Rxf6 (41... bxa4! 42. Rf7 Qd6 43. Ra7 { I didn't want to allow this activity while the queens are still on the board and my king is still too weak. But black has a way out. } 43... Re7! $17) 42. Qxf6 Qxf6 43. Rxf6 Bxe3+ 44. Bxe3 Rxe3 45. Rxa6 bxa4 46. Rxg6+ Kf7 47. Rh6?? (47. Ra6 { Forced if white does not want to face the prospect of a running A pawn. } 47... a3 48. Kf2 Rb3 49. b5 { Black is still better due to his active rook and temporarily stalled passed pawns. The kingside g6 pawn will not be missed. } { [%cal Gf7e7,Ge7d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b6,Gb6b5,Gb5b4,Gb4c3,Gc3d4] }) 47... Rb3 48. Kf2 Rxb4 49. Rh5 (49. Rxh4) 49... Ke6 50. Ke3 Rb2 51. Rxh4 Rxg2 52. Rh6+ Kf5 53. Ra6 (53. Rd6 Rg3+ 54. Kf2 Rxh3 55. Rxd5+ Ke4 { King activity is more important than the d5 pawn. }) 53... Rg3+ 54. Kf2 Rxh3 55. Rxa4 Ke4 { Black is winning the d4 pawn by force and will enter a rook and 2 pawns vs rook endgame. With both of the pawns connected, this is a guaranteed win. } 56. Ke2 (56. Kg2 Rb3 57. Ra5 Kxd4 58. Kf2 $19 { [%cal Gc4c3] }) 56... Rh2+ 57. Ke1 Kxd4 58. Rb4 Kd3 59. Ra4 d4 60. Ra3+ c3 61. Rb3 Rh1+ 62. Kf2 Kd2 63. Ra3 c2 64. Kg2 Rb1 65. Rg3 c1=Q 66. Rg4 Qf1+ 67. Kg3 d3 68. Rc4 Rb5 69. Rc6 Rg5+ 70. Kh4 Qg1 (70... Qg2?! 71. Rc2+ Ke3 { Black is still winning, but this stalemate trick can easily be avoided. }) 71. Rc2+ dxc2 72. Kh3 Rh5# *


