1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3 c6 5. Nc3 Nbd7 6. cxd5?! { Never a good idea to release the tension. Now we transition into a sort of reverse London. } 6... exd5 7. Be2 (7. Bd3 Bd6 $10) 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bd2 Re8 10. Rc1 Nf8 { [%csl Gc8] } 11. a3 a5 { I figured it was useful to slow down the minority attack. Here, white has wasted too many tempi with Rc1 and a3 instead of directly gunning for Rb1 and b4. } 12. Na4 Bf5 13. Nc5 Qb8 { Potentially too fancy. I wanted to stay off the semi-open c file opposite the rook in expectation of b4-b5, but Qe7 is simply a better square than c7 or b8. } (13... Qe7 $17) 14. Bd3 (14. b4 { But this nice knight remaneuver allows the minority attack to hit anyway. }) 14... Bxd3 15. Nxd3 Ne4 16. Nc5 Ng6?! (16... Ne6! { Obviously good. I kinda blanked right around here and stopped calculating any actual variations. } 17. Nxe4 (17. Nxe6 Rxe6 $17) 17... dxe4 18. Ne5 f6 $17) 17. Nxe4 Rxe4? (17... dxe4! 18. Ng5 h6 19. Nh3 Bxh2+ $17 { Easy to see and strong. }) 18. Be1 h5 19. g3 h4 20. Nd2 Re7 21. Qf3 Qe8 22. Nb3 a4 23. Nc5 Qc8 { [%csl Gf5,Gg4,Gh3][%cal Gc8h3] } (23... Bxc5 24. Rxc5 Nf8! { The knight maneuver I wanted to make work during the game makes a lot more sense here when it comes with an extra tempo. } { [%cal Gf8e6,Ge6c5,Ge6g5] }) 24. Qg2 Re8?! { Floundering a bit, I decide I should reposition my worst placed piece - the knight on g6. In a perfect world, I could arrive on g5 to eye up the weak h3 and f3 squares, but it's not practical with potential pressure down the open g file after a timely gxh4!? } { [%cal Gg6e7,Ge7f5] } 25. Nd3? (25. Bb4 Nf8 26. Nd3 $15 { Once the bishops are traded, black is only slightly better due to the space advantage. }) 25... f6? { Never play f6... Doesn't actually stop the knight from arriving at the more important square of f4. Weak play by both of us as neither is exactly sure how to improve our pieces fully. } { [%csl Ge5] } (25... Qf5! { From here, black takes completely control of the weakened light squares. I should have jumped at this opportunity, but I was too focused on improving my knight that I didn't consider all my pieces. } 26. Bb4?? h3! 27. Qh1 Bxb4 28. Nxb4 Nh4!! $19 { [%cal Gh4f3] }) 26. Nf4 (26. Bb4! { White can trade their bad bishop for my hero dark squared bishop, and the position should be roughly level. }) 26... Nxf4 27. exf4 (27. gxf4!? { Opening the g file is interesting, as a way to counterattack with Kh1 and Rg1 coming soon. }) 27... Kf7 28. Bd2 Qf5! { The weakened light squares and bad dark squared bishop prove enough for black to win. Now I find this idea of infiltrating on them, and the queen infiltration is fatal. } 29. f3?? { Never play f3... Now I can capture on g3 and cripple the kingside majority, as well as potentially attack down the newly opened h file. } 29... hxg3 30. hxg3 Rh8 { Hinting at a kingside attack. } 31. Kf2!? { The king goes for a surprising run so that Rh1 can contest the h file. But the king is not safer on f2 than g1. } 31... Rae8 32. Rce1 Qd3 { [%cal Gd3d2,Gd3d4,Gd3c3] } 33. Bc3 Bxa3! 34. Kg1 Bb4! { With this sequence of moves, black has won a pawn and transitioned play completely from the kingside to queenside. Black is now winning on all sections of the board. } 35. Bxb4 (35. Ra1!? Bxc3 36. bxc3 Re2! { And no more precision is required. } (36... Qxc3?? 37. Rxa4)) 35... Qxd4+ 36. Qf2 Qxb4 37. Rxe8 Rxe8 38. Rd1 Qe7 { Definitely not most precise, but trading queens is completely forced, and the resulting rook and pawn endgame is completely winning due to the 4 on 1 queenside majority. } 39. Qh2 Qe3+ { [%cal Ge3f3] } 40. Qf2 Qxf2+ 41. Kxf2 b5 $19 { White resigned rather than passively wait with his rook while the queenside pawns march forward. The white king is completely cut off from the queenside, so there's not any hope of stalling their advance. } *


