1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd4 7. Qxd4 d6 { B36 Sicilian Defense: Accelerated Dragon, Maróczy Bind, Gurgenidze Variation } { I've never seen this move order, but I figured it wouldn't change much and just transpose into normal accelerated dragon setups. } 8. Be3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. Qd2 { Now that his bishop is defended, he's ready to move his knight with a discovery. } 10... Ng4 11. Bxg4 { Giving up the bishop pair, but aiming for a position where I have a solid light square bind with my pawns. } (11. Bf4!? f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. O-O { Seeing as I haven't touched my f pawn, this variation actually makes sense because the g1-b6 diagonal is not an issue. }) 11... Bxg4 12. O-O Qa5 13. Bd4 h6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ (15. h3!? Be6 16. b3 Rac8 { I didn't like the pins that I felt were going to hurt me in this variation. However, white is completely fine here and still pushing for an advantage. }) 15... Qe5 16. Qxe5+?! dxe5 { Going for the queen trade leaves it in an immediately drawn position. } 17. f3 Be6 18. b3 f6 19. Rfd1 { As we shall later see, this is the wrong rook to go to d1. Rad1 is clearly better. } 19... Kf7 20. Kf2 g5 21. g4? { Giving a hook to black to attack with h5 is a non-starter. Instead I should have gone for the alternate line } (21. h3 h5 22. Rd2 Rh8 23. Rad1 g4 24. h4! { With completely solid control of the kingside entrance squares. Now my queenside 3 to 2 majority becomes relevant. }) 21... Rh8 22. h3 h5 23. Kg2 Rh7 24. Rh1 Rah8 25. Na4 Bd7 26. Nc3 (26. Nc5 Bc6 { My initial idea doesn't accomplish anything, and the knight is no better placed on d3 than c3. }) 26... Bc6 27. Rad1 Ke6 28. Ne2? { Missing a key idea black has to take control of the files. } 28... hxg4 29. hxg4 Rxh1 30. Rxh1 Rd8!! { And white's pieces are ill-equipped to deal with the active rook. Although with best play this could still be drawn, it is now clear that it is black who is pushing. } 31. Kf2 Rd2 32. Ra1 b5 33. Ke3 Rb2 34. cxb5?? { The losing move, but hard to prove why. } (34. Nc3! bxc4 35. bxc4 { Keeping the bishop out of the game temporarily. } 35... Rb4 36. Kd3 a5 37. Rc1 Bb7 { This maneuver to circle in on the c4 weakness doesn't work because the rook can first be booted off its dominant post. } 38. a3! Rb3 39. Kc2! Rb6 $10 (39... Rxa3?? 40. Kb2 $18)) 34... Bxb5 35. Nc3 Ba6 { [%cal Ga6e2,Gb2e2] } 36. Rc1 Kf7! { Announcing zugzwang. Interestingly, if black made any other move, then it would immediately be a draw. Moving the white rook allows Rc2 and the knight's position cannot be maintained to defend both a2 and e2 (Re2#). Moving the knight allows Re2# directly. And the white king cannot move. By process of elimination, it becomes necessary to move either the a or b pawn, both of which immediately lose a pawn. } (36... Kd7? 37. Rd1+ { [%cal Gd1d2] }) (36... Kd6? 37. Rd1+ { [%cal Gd1d2] }) (36... Bb7 37. Na4! { [%cal Ga4b2,Ga4c5,Gc5b7,Gc5e6] }) (36... Bc8 37. Na4! { [%cal Ga4b2,Gc1c8] }) 37. a4 Rxb3 38. Kd2 Bc4 39. Kc2 Rb8! 40. Rb1?? { An interesting idea - trying to box out the rook from entering on either the b or d files doesn't quite work because black has the following sequence. } 40... Rxb1 41. Kxb1 Bf1! { White resigned because Bg2 followed by Bxf3 is unavoidable. My opponent had 7 ACPL this game, so he was most likely cheating. However, the endgame was extremely interesting, so I decided to add this game to the study just for the learning experience. } *


