1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 { I have only recently started play this line in the Najdorf. It's extremely complicated, but a lot of fun to throw the kitchen sink at your opponents, searching for a checkmate. } 6... e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3 O-O?! { It's a bit committal to castle so quickly into this attack. } 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4 Rb8?! (10... b5?? 11. Nc6 $18) (10... Qc7 { The usual way to play b5 and get the queenside counterplay going as soon as possible }) 11. h4 b5?? { Both me and my opponent were playing this game as a 3+0 game so far, and so both of us completely missed the fact that Nc6 wins the exchange for the next sequence of moves... Frankly, terrible. } { [%cal Gd4c6,Gc6d8,Gc6b8] } 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. g5 Nd7 { [%cal Gd4c6,Gc6b8,Gc6d8] } 14. Bh3 Bb7 15. Bxe6! Nc5?? { Black doesn't take up the challenge, and now simply falls into a hopeless position. } (15... fxe6 16. Nxe6 Qa5 17. Nxf8 Bxf8 18. Kb1 { An unclear position because white's attack has gotten nowhere, but he is technically up 2 pawns and a rook vs 2 pieces. If black can drum up an attack against white's king, then the two pieces will make themselves known. But in an endgame, white is going to be better. }) 16. Bd5 b4 17. Nce2 Qa5 18. Kb1 Rfc8 19. h5 Bxd5 20. exd5 Qc7 21. Nc6 Rb7 22. Ned4! { Obviously better in retrospect. } (22. Nxe7+? { Completely unnecessary. I was seeing ghosts where the bishop could come to f6 and become a monster attacking my king, but that's simply untrue. } 22... Qxe7 23. Nd4 a5 24. Rde1 Qc7 25. g6?? (25. h6! g6 26. f5 a4 27. fxg6 fxg6 28. Rhf1 $18 { This is more like the position I wanted in the game. However, I was worried about queenside counterplay that is ultimately just too slow. } 28... b3 29. cxb3 axb3 30. a3 { Nc6 plugs up the c file, and attacks the black king. White is winning. } 30... Qf7?? 31. Qe3! Qxd5 32. Qe8+ Rxe8 33. Rxe8#) 25... h6 { A good try to keep it closed. } 26. gxf7+?! (26. Nf5! { A fantastic move that proves you don't need to open up the king in order to attack it. Piece placement is more important at the moment. } 26... f6 27. Rh2 { [%cal Gh2c2] } 27... a4 28. Rhe2 { [%cal Ge2e8] } 28... b3 (28... Qb8 29. Nxd6!! { [%cal Gb8d6,Ge2e8] } 29... Qxd6 30. Re8+ Qf8 31. Rxf8+ $18) 29. Re8+ Rxe8 30. Rxe8#) 26... Qxf7 27. Rhg1 Rf8 28. f5 Qf6 29. Rg4 Re7 30. Rxe7? (30. Reg1!? { Keeping the tension is better with the attack still to come. }) 30... Qxe7 31. Ne6?? { Blunders into an endgame where all winning chances disappear. } 31... Nxe6! 32. dxe6 Qxe6 { [%cal Gf8f3] } 33. Rxg7+! Kh8! 34. Rg1 (34. fxe6 Rxf3 35. Rf7 Rxf7 36. exf7 Kg7 $10) 34... Qxf5 35. Qg2 Qf7 36. b3 Rg8 37. Qxg8+ Qxg8 38. Rxg8+ Kxg8 { I now try and win this king and pawn endgame, but creating a passed pawn on the queenside comes at the expense of trading away two sets of pawns and simplifying the position too much... or so I thought. } 39. c3 Kf7 40. cxb4?? { Throwing away the win. } (40. a4!! { With the threat of cxb4 and a winning passed a pawn. } 40... bxa3 41. Ka2 Ke6 42. Kxa3 { White is extremely quick to take the a pawn and queen the b pawn. Notice that here, only one set of pawns has been traded, so there's no passed d pawn for black. One sample line is: } 42... Kf5 43. Ka4 Kg5 44. Kxa5 Kxh5 45. b4 Kg4 46. b5 h5 47. b6 h4 48. b7 h3 49. b8=Q h2 50. Qa8 $18) 40... axb4 41. a4 bxa3 42. Ka2 Ke6 43. Kxa3 d5 44. Kb4 Ke5 45. Kc3 d4+ 46. Kd3 Kd5 47. b4 Ke5 48. b5 Kd5 49. b6 Kc6 50. Kxd4 Kxb6 51. Kd5 Kc7 52. Ke6 Kc6 53. Kf6 Kd6 54. Kg6 Ke6 55. Kxh6 Kf6 { And it's a draw as the black king can simply follow the white king and keep him trapped on the h file. } 56. Kh7 Kf7 57. Kh8 Kf8 $10) 22... f6?? (22... a5 23. Rde1 Bf8 (23... Re8?? 24. Nf5 $18 { [%cal Gf5e7,Gc6e7,Ge1e7] }) 24. g6 $18) 23. Rde1 Bf8 24. gxf6 $18 *


