1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Qc7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. O-O Nc6 (7... Bc5!? 8. Nb3 Be7 9. f4 d6 10. Qf3 b5 11. a4 b4 12. Nd1 Bb7 $10) 8. Nb3 b5 9. Qe2?! (9. f4 { Better. White stays more flexible with his queen position, as it's not quite clear yet where it belongs. } 9... d6 10. Qf3 Bb7 $10) 9... Bb7 10. Qd1? { White rectifies their earlier mistake, but it's simply too slow in a position that demands precision. } 10... Rc8 { Fine, but imprecise. } (10... b4! 11. Na4 Ne5 12. f4 Nxd3 13. cxd3 Bc6! { I've seen this idea before in a previous game. The knight is offsided on a4 and becomes a target while other inroads are made across the board. }) 11. h3 Ne5 12. f4 Nc4! { The knight paralyzes the c1 bishop and a1 rook, and cannot ever simply be kicked away. } (12... Nxd3 13. cxd3 { The white pawn center becomes a strength, not a weakness. } 13... d5? 14. e5 $14) 13. Qe1 Be7 14. e5 Nd5 (14... Nh5 15. g4 f5!! 16. gxh5 Qc6 $19 17. Qg3 Bh4 18. Qh2 Rg8 { [%cal Gg7g5] }) 15. a4 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Qc6 (16... bxa4! { I saw this idea, but the move order is important. } 17. Rxa4?? Qc6 $19 { [%cal Gc6g2,Gc6a4] }) 17. Qg3 g6 (17... bxa4 { The pawn is much worse here because of the counter-attacking Nd4 move. } 18. Nd4! (18. Qxg7?? Bf8!! { Black wins a piece due to the mate threat. } { [%cal Gc6g2] }) 18... Qd5 19. Rxa4 g6 $10 { Similar to the game }) 18. axb5 axb5 19. Rf2 Ra8 { I thought this was a good maneuver, but in fact it invites white to reposition their rook to devastating effect on the half-open b file! } 20. Rb1!! { [%cal Gb1b5] } 20... d6?? (20... Qc8 21. Nd4 Na3 22. Bxa3 Rxa3 23. Nxb5 Ra4 { Best play loses a pawn by force, but at least we get rid of the fearsome dark squared bishop... }) 21. Nd4 { I completely missed this move - the game is now positionally lost, although white finds incredible resources to make it an immediate win instead of a slow grind. } (21. exd6? Nxd6 22. f5 Nxf5 23. Bxf5 exf5 { The position I dreamed of - yet Nd4 still brings good winning chances for white, not black. }) 21... Qc8 { Forced, but I'm glad I found the "only" move. } 22. f5!! { White has no need of the f pawn and sacrifices it in order to open lines for the dark squared bishop, and as we shall soon see b1 rook! } 22... exf5 (22... dxe5 23. fxe6 f6 24. Nxb5 $18) 23. Bxc4 bxc4 24. Bh6? { The right idea, but the wrong execution. This "slow" move allows black enough time to reposition their queen to better stall the attack. } 24... Be4?? { Trying to hold together the position, but underestimating white's follow-up } (24... Qd7! 25. Bg7 (25. exd6 Bxd6 26. Qe3+ Be4 $10) (25. Re1 Be4 26. Rxe4 fxe4 $10 { Unless white finds the amazing rook sacrifice: } 27. Rxf7 Kxf7 28. e6+ Qxe6 29. Nxe6 Kxe6 30. Qg4+ Kd5 31. Qd7 $14) 25... Rg8 26. exd6 Bxd6 27. Re1+ Be4 $10) 25. exd6 (25. Bg7?? Rg8 26. exd6 Rxg7 27. dxe7 { The line I expected. Scary, but survivable. }) 25... Bf6 { I thought exd6 was a mistake because it allows me to better take control of my dark squares. But in reality, the light square blockade is about to ripped to shreds. } 26. Re1! Qd8 27. Rxe4+ (27. Nc6 Qb6 28. Rxe4+ fxe4 29. Qf4 { The line I was expecting. The only reason it doesn't lose immediately is the surprising } 29... Kd7!? 30. Qxf6 Kxc6 { Which forces white to find the only winning move } 31. Kh2!! (31. Qxf7 Qc5 $10) (31. Bg7 Rhe8 32. Qxf7 e3 $15)) 27... fxe4 28. Qf4 Ra1+ 29. Kh2 { And black resigned because the bishop on f6 is pinned to the f7 pawn. } *


