1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. d4 Bd6 6. Bd3 Bg6 7. O-O c5?! { While this moves strives for an advantage, you can't really claim yet that black is better than white, so a calmer move like 6 or Nbd7 is more called-for. } 8. c4 dxc4 9. bxc4 Nc6 10. Nc3 { Now black can transition into a hanging pawns structure where we've traded off an active piece on d3. Black has now certainly equalized. } (10. d5! exd5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxg7! (12. Bxg6? hxg6 13. Qxd5?? Bxh2+ { Who's got the tactic on whom? }) 12... Rg8 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Nc3! (14. Bb2 $10) 14... Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Qe7 $14) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 (11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 O-O { Even better for black because now more pieces are traded off. }) 11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 O-O 13. c5?? { White was trying to clamp down on my pieces, but both strategically and tactically this is not correct. The d6 square is well guarded, the e5 square is well guarded, and the bishop is almost as good on e7 as d6. Of course, and most importantly, the queen is undefended so this pawn can simply be taken. } 13... Bxc5 { [%cal Gd8d3] } 14. Rad1 (14. Qb5 Bb6) 14... Be7 15. Ne5 Rc8 16. h4? { This move doesn't do anything except weaken white's king... } (16. f4 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Bc5 18. Qxc5 Rxc5 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 { An interesting line that could have occurred. }) 16... Nd5?! { I thought this move won a clean pawn, but since I missed some things tactically here, it's better to just keep a bottle on all counterplay with Nb4->d5. } (16... Nb4 17. Qb5 (17. Qe2 Nbd5) 17... Nbd5 $17 18. Qxb7?? Rb8 $19 { [%cal Gb8b2] }) 17. Qe4 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 Bxh4 { In this position, my opponent paused for a long time. I could see their hand moving on another monitor quite a bit, so I assume they turned on an engine at this point, upset with how they were losing this game. I had seen d5, but thought I had compensation in all lines. In fact, it gets very dicey very quickly. } 19. d5! Nxe5 (19... exd5 20. Rxd5 Qe7 21. Rd7 Qe6! 22. Qxh4 Nxe5 23. Re7 Nf3+! 24. gxf3 Qg6+ 25. Qg3 Rxc3 { I didn't see this entire line. I was scared after Re7 and decided there were better lines for black to go for. }) 20. dxe6 Rxc3? { Interesting queen sacrifice, but a mistake. } (20... Qf6 21. Bxe5 Qxe6! { In retrospect, a much safer way to go about things... } 22. Qxh4 (22. Rfe1 Bf6 23. Bxf6 Qxf6 24. Qxb7 $15 { Approximately equal. Black pawn should only matter at the highest levels of play... }) 22... Qxe5) 21. Rxd8 Bxd8 22. Qxe5 Bf6 (22... Rc7! { The solid and safe way to get what I was actually going for in the game itself. Now black retains the queenside pawns and chances for pressure on f2 and/or the white king. } 23. g3 Re7 24. exf7+ Rexf7 25. Kg2 Bf6 26. Qb5 g6 $14 { White is slightly better here, but play should be approximately level. }) 23. exf7+! Rxf7 24. Qb8+ { The move I had missed. The queen will mop up the b pawn. If the queen can mop up the a pawn as well, black is close to busted... } 24... Rf8 25. Qxb7 Ra3?? (25... Bd4?? { [%cal Gd4a7,Gd4f2] } 26. Qd5+ Kh8 27. Qxd4 $18) 26. Qd5+ Kh8 27. Qc5! { I cannot defend both rooks with one move, so I resigned. } *


