1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 (6. d4 dxc4 { I'm more comfortable with the mainline Catalan theory, having studied it in the past. }) 6... c5 { I know that c5 is the main move here, but do feel slightly uncomfortable in IQP or hanging pawns pawn structures. I figured I would give it a go. } 7. cxd5 (7. Bb2 d4 8. e3 Nc6 9. exd4 cxd4 10. Re1 Ng4 { Preparing f6-e5 to cement my central pawn structure. } 11. h3 (11. d3) 11... Nh6) 7... exd5 8. d4 b6 9. Bb2 Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 11. Rc1 (11. Ne5 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Bc5 13. Qf4 Nxe5 14. Qxe5 Re8 $10 { IQP but black has the more active forces }) 11... Re8 12. e3 { Until this moment, I've been able to make moves I would make in both the IQP and hanging pawns. Now I have to make a choice, and go for the more flexible of all the options. } 12... Rc8 13. Qe2 Bf8 14. Rfd1 { A critical moment. I was attempting my best to ensure I didn't end up in a bad IQP. Rather than allow the pawn structure to change that way, I forced white's hand to play against the hanging pawn structure instead, where my queen would be best placed on b6 (and I could later play Rcd8, going for the d4 break). } 14... Qc7?! (14... c4?! 15. Ne5 cxb3 16. axb3 a6!? (16... Nxe5?! 17. dxe5 Rxe5 18. Nb5 $14 { [%cal Gb2e5] })) (14... Qe7!?) (14... Ne4?! 15. dxc5 Ndxc5 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Rxc8 Qxc8 18. Nd4 $14) (14... cxd4?! 15. Nxd4 Nc5 $14) 15. Nb5 Qb8 16. dxc5? (16. Ne5! { Active play is a necessity. Ne5 stops me from playing Ne4. } 16... a6 17. Nxd7! { Gets the same position that we had in the game but with less support for d5 and the knight isn't blocking the g2 bishop. } 17... Nxd7 18. Nc3 Nf6 19. dxc5 bxc5 (19... Rxc5 20. Na4 $16) 20. Nxd5 $18) (16. Na3 Ne4 17. Ne5 Ndf6 $10) 16... bxc5 { Good hanging pawns! The knights on f3 and b5 are misplaced. } 17. Qc2 (17. Qf1 Ba6 18. a4 Bb7 $15 { My plan was to weaken the queenside here by taking advantage of this pin. With the pawn on a4, the b3 pawn becomes much more vulnerable. }) (17. Na3 Qa8 $15) 17... d4! 18. exd4?? (18. Na3 Qa8 19. Qe2 $17 { Best play from white, but they can never break down this massive pawn center with the queen opposite the e8 rook. Black has a pleasant position and can improve his pieces with Ng4, g6, etc. }) 18... cxd4 (18... Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Qxb5 20. dxc5 Rxc5 { Another variation where black is winning a piece. }) 19. Qd3 (19. Nc7 Be4 20. Qc4 (20. Qe2 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Rxc7 $19) 20... Bxf3 21. Bxf3 Ne5 22. Qe2 Rxc7 $19 { Similar to the game. }) 19... Bxf3 20. Bxf3 (20. Qxf3 Qxb5) 20... Ne5 21. Qe2 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Qxb5 23. Bxd4 { Black is up a piece and winning. But the conversion required some delicate care. } 23... Rxc1 24. Rxc1 Qe2? (24... Qg5 25. Rc7 { This position still requires a little bit of work to convert. }) 25. Qc3? (25. Qxe2 Rxe2 26. Rc8 (26. Bxa7 Rxa2 { The expected line once you see the forcing Rc8 doesn't work. }) 26... Rxa2 27. Bc5 Nd7 28. Bd6 f6! 29. Rd8 Ra6! { [%csl Gd6] } (29... a5 30. Rxd7 Rd2 $19 { Unbelievably there were no threats the entire time... } { [%cal Gd2d7] }) 30. Rxd7 Rxd6 $19) 25... Ne4! 26. Qc6 (26. Re1 Nxc3 (26... Nxg3 27. Rxe2 Nxe2+ 28. Kf1 Nxc3 { Another hilarious way to win. Completely unnecessary... }) 27. Rxe2 Nxe2+ 28. Kg2 Nxd4) 26... Ng5 { The knight enters in the juicy light squares around the king. } 27. Be3?? (27. Bxa7 Re6 28. Qc4 Nf3+ 29. Kg2 Ne1+ 30. Kh3 (30. Kg1 Nd3 { [%csl Gf2,Gc1] } 31. Rf1 Qf3 32. Be3 Ne5 33. Qb5 Qa8! { Nf3 is unstoppable and will be absolutely crushing. } { [%cal Ge5f3] }) 30... Qh5+ 31. Qh4 Qf5+ 32. Qg4 Rh6#) 27... Rxe3 28. fxe3 Nf3+ 29. Kh1 (29. Qxf3 Qxf3 { Prolongs the game, but is clearly resignable. }) 29... Qxh2# *


