1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. g3 { The preferred line of IM Andras. I also used to play this way as white as it's quite hard to untangle the black pieces } 6... Nf6 7. Bg2 d6 8. O-O Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. a3?! { Black's plan of a6-b5 is unaffected by this move. a4 has to be better } (10. a4 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4] } 11. Qe2 Na5 { The end of my theory }) 10... Nbd7 11. Nce2 Nc5 { [%csl Ge4] } 12. e5? (12. Nc3 { Defending again with the c3 knight seems really sad to me. Rb8 and b5 are soon to follow }) 12... dxe5 13. Nf3 Rd8 14. Nd2 { At this point, surprisingly, I couldn't find a good way to develop the light squared bishop. Rb8 can always be met with b4!? } 14... Ncd7 (14... Rb8? 15. b4 Nce4 16. Ba7 { I missed this was hanging and thought I had to go back to a8 } { [%csl Gd2] } 16... Ra8?? (16... Nxd2! 17. Bxb8 Qxb8 $19) 17. Be3) 15. c3 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6c4] } (15... Rb8?! 16. Ba7 Ra8 17. Be3 { No progress }) 16. Qc2 Bd7 $17 { Black is finally ready to finish development } { [%cal Ga8c8,Gd7c6] } 17. f4?? { A blunder, but a completely reasonable one. Falling into the same trap that Anand did against Ivanchuk in Linares 1991. } 17... Ng4! 18. Bf2 (18. Qd3 Nxe3 19. Qxe3 Bc5 $19) 18... Nxf2 19. Rxf2 (19. Kxf2 Bc5+ 20. Ke1 Ba4 21. b3 Rxd2! 22. Qxd2 Bxb3 $19 { White's king cannot survive in the center } { [%cal Gb6c4,Ga8d8] }) 19... Bc5 20. Rf1 Bb5! 21. c4 Rxd2! { Black's attack plays itself out - if the bishops are opened towards the weakened kingside, there's definitely not going to be any surviving this. Always sacrifice the exchange! } 22. Qxd2 Nxc4 23. Qc1 Ne3? (23... Qb6 24. a4 Be3 25. Qc3 Nd2 26. axb5 Nxf1 27. Kxf1 Rd8 { Another line showcasing the possible carnage }) 24. Re1?? (24. b4! Bb6 25. Qxc7 Bxc7 26. Rc1 Bb6 27. Bxb7 Rb8 { Not at all what I wanted. I missed this possibility of b4 because in every other variation (when the knight isn't on e3), there was the option of Bxf2+, winning. }) (24. Bxb7 { I thought this didn't lead anywhere, but after Rb8, white once again has this b4 resource! } 24... Rb8 25. b4! Nxf1 26. bxc5 Qxb7 27. Qxf1 $19 { Not as clean as in the game }) 24... Ng4! { Fitting that the final blow occurs on the same square that started this vicious attack earlier in the game } 25. Rf1 Bxe2 { Threatening Bxf2+ when the queen on c1 is undefended. My opponent resigned rather than continue the torture. } *


