7... Qxb2? (7... Qa6! $10 { The suggested move tries to trade queens and enter a good endgame for black, as in the Nimzowitsch - Capablanca model game. }) 8. e6! Qxa1 9. Qb3! { It's already over for black, but here's one beautiful way to go down without a fight: } 9... Qxd4!? 10. Qxb7 fxe6 11. Be3! Qa4 12. Qxa8 $18 { Perunovic, Milos - Lalith, Babu MR, 1-0, Dubai op 11th, 2009, https://lichess.org/fBFbHQps } { No development. No way to develop. Everything is undefended. This is exactly how you lose horribly. } *


[Event "New York"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1927.03.13"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Aron Nimzowitsch"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B12"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Advance Variation"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Capablanca's endgame infiltration"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/wn39rrTK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Bd3?! { As opposed to in the Tal variation, this trade here is simply a trade of white's good bishop for our bad bishop. } (4. h4 h5 5. Bd3 Bxd3 6. Qxd3 { Importantly, black has had to weaken kingside squares first here. White uses g5 to try and hurt us on the kingside while we hurry to finish development. }) 4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6 6. Nc3 Qb6 7. Nge2 c5 { Breaking down white's center now that it cannot be supported further with c3 gives black a good game. } 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O Ne7 10. Na4 Qc6 11. Nxc5 Qxc5 12. Be3 Qc7 13. f4 Nf5 14. c3 Nc6 { [%csl Gf5,Gc6] } 15. Rad1 g6 16. g4?! { The right idea for this structure. But without the LSBs on the board, white cannot really dream of attacking on the kingside. } 16... Nxe3 17. Qxe3 h5! 18. g5? { Capitulation. Now Capablanca has a dream position where the kingside is closed forever, the f5 square is a hole for black's knight, and the queenside is the sole battlefield. } (18. f5! gxf5 19. gxf5 O-O-O $15 { Black is obviously fine here too, with a relatively safe king. But at least white's last moves make sense. }) 18... O-O 19. Nd4 Qb6 20. Rf2 Rfc8 21. a3 Rc7 22. Rd3 Na5 23. Re2 Re8 24. Kg2 Nc6 25. Red2 Rec8 26. Re2 Ne7 27. Red2 Rc4 28. Qh3 Kg7 29. Rf2 a5 30. Re2 Nf5 31. Nxf5+ gxf5! { We often capture towards the center. Now white still has no breaks on the kingside. } { [%cal Gg6f5] } (31... exf5?! $10 { The e6 break gives white some activity to play for. } { [%cal Ge5e6] }) 32. Qf3 (32. Qxh5?? Rh8 33. Qf3 Rh4 $19 { Black regains the pawn and the open h file actually turns out to benefit black. } { [%cal Gh4f4,Gc4f4] }) 32... Kg6 33. Red2 Re4! { The rook cements itself on the e4 square where it can never be captured without giving black a connected passed pawn. } 34. Rd4 Rc4 35. Qf2 Qb5 36. Kg3 Rcxd4 37. cxd4 (37. Rxd4?? { The move Nimzowitsch would want to play immediately loses. } 37... Re2! { The first major piece infiltrates on the 7th rank. This move would be impossible if the king was on f3 instead of g3. } 38. Qf3 h4+! 39. Kxh4 Rxh2+ 40. Kg3 Qxb2! $19 { And the second major piece infiltrates on the 7th rank with decisive effect. Rh8 and Qh2# are impossible threats to parry. } { [%cal Gh2h1,Gh2h8,Gb2h2] }) 37... Qc4 { Capablanca takes over the c file, the e file, and looming infiltration on the 7th or 8th rank means that this game is now over. } 38. Kg2 b5 39. Kg1 b4 40. axb4 axb4 41. Kg2 Qc1 42. Kg3 Qh1 43. Rd3 Re1 { Rather than continue to target white's weak pawns, Capablanca has converted his activity on the queenside into a full-out kingside attack. An exposed king + decisive penetration = possible checkmate threats. } 44. Rf3 Rd1 45. b3 Rc1 { Zugzwang! Try and find a move for white that doesn't weaken your position or lose a pawn. } 46. Re3 Rf1 $19 { Nimzowitsch resigned rather than play on with Qe2 Qg1+, mating.
This game is a great lesson in showcasing how the major pieces require infiltration squares in order to prove their dominance against an opponent's forces. This is exactly why an open file for your rooks in the middlegame is not so important unless there is a way to actually infiltrate into your opponent's camp. } 0-1


