1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 { White gives up their strong e4 pawn for our flank c6 pawn in exchange for time and a queenside pawn majority. } 3... cxd5 4. c4 { The Panov (or Panov-Botvinnik) attack. This is an aggressive way for white to challenge our center. Rather than play structurally "sound" chess, white is hoping that their lead in development will give them middlegame attacks. } 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 { We should already imagine the c4 pawn trading for the d5 pawn, leading to an IQP structure. In that case, control over the d5 square is the most important consideration for both sides. } (5. cxd5?! Nxd5 $10 { If White releases the tension too early, then they are simply developing our pieces for us in this IQP structure. Rather than having an active attack here, white is the worse structurally and now also behind in development. }) 5... e6 { Finishing kingside development and further strengthening our control over d5. Control over d5 and quick development is more important than the typical Caro idea of getting the c8 bishop outside the pawn chain. } 6. Nf3 Bb4 $10 { Sparring Pos 4. We will play against white's IQP. d5 remains the most important square on the board by far. While will weaken our control with Bg5, Bc4, etc. We will further strengthen it with Bb4, Bb7, Nbd7, etc. } *


