1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nf3 Bb4 7. cxd5 Nxd5 { Recapturing with the piece ensures we maintain pressure against white's "weak" d4 pawn. } 8. Bd2 Nc6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Qe2 Nf6 12. Ne4 Qb6 13. a3 Bd7 { Finishing development, although this is an awkward move that temporarily halts our pressure against the d4 pawn. } (13... Nxe4!? { This move is always playable for black since piece trades are beneficial. But we shouldn't be so quick to bring white's queen into an attacking position for no reason. } 14. Qxe4 g6 15. Be3 $14 { Note the difference compared to the game. Black is not able to swing the knight to f5 or d5 in time. }) 14. Rfd1 Rad8 15. Nxf6+?! { Trading minor pieces is great if you are playing against the IQP since there is less chance of a kingside attack. } 15... Bxf6 16. Qe4 g6 17. Be3 Ne7! { Rerouting to get out of the way of white's d5 break and further pressure the pawn. } 18. Ne5 (18. d5?! Qxb2! 19. Rab1 Qxa3 20. Rxb7 Nxd5 $17 { All things being equal, being up a pawn means black is better. }) 18... Nf5 19. Nc4 Qa6 20. a4 (20. Ne5?! { White can no longer even force a repetition. } 20... Bb5! $15 { Black's idea is to trade more minor pieces, particular light square bishops, so that d5 is a stronghold for black's pieces and d4 is more of a weakness. }) 20... Bc6 21. Qf4 Bd5 { Black has a dream setup against the IQP, with pressure on d4 and d5 firmly blockaded. Moreover, keeping heavy pieces on the board ensures that the IQP is more easily targeted. } 22. Ne5 Qb6 23. Bxf5 exf5 24. Rd2 Bg7 25. h4 Rfe8 26. Qg3 Rc8 27. Nd7 Qc6 28. Nc5 b6 29. Nd3 Qd7 30. a5 Re4 31. Nf4 b5 32. Rdd1 Bc4 33. Rac1 h6 34. Rc3 b4 35. Rc2 Rc6 36. Rdc1 Bb5 37. Kh2 Kh7 38. Rxc6 Bxc6 39. Rc4 Bf8 40. Nd3 Qe6 { The d pawn is now critically weak. Moreover, it staying on d4 kills white's bishop and c4 rook. None of black's pieces are limited by the pawn staying on d4. } 41. d5?! (41. Rc1 Bd6 42. Ne5 (42. Bf4 Rxf4! 43. Nxf4 Qe4! $19 { [%csl Gf4] }) 42... Bxe5! 43. dxe5 Rg4! $19 { The d4 pawn (now on e5) finally falls. } { [%cal Ge6e5] }) 41... Bxd5 42. Rxe4 Bxe4 43. Bxa7?! { White regains material, but now black has a huge kingside attack with his bishop pair. } 43... Bd6 44. Nf4 Qe5 45. Nh3 Qe7! $19 { 0-1 Black wins. } 46. Nf4 Qxa7 $19 0-1


[Event "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS: Section 4: Exchange (3. exd5 cxd5 without 4. c4)"]
[Date "2023.06.07"]
[White "Caro"]
