[Annotator "Jesse"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Exchange Variation, Rubinstein Variation"]
[StudyName "Learn the Caro-Kann like a BOSS"]
[ChapterName "Section 4: Exchange (3. exd5 cxd5 without 4. c4)"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/8isfzJc8/b4EzCC5K"]

1. e4 (1. d4!? { Consider the positions arising from d4 d5, and compare them to the exchange Caro-Kann main line. } 1... d5 2. c4 (2. Bf4 { The London can also get you to the same Carlsbad pawn structure. } 2... Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 cxd4 6. exd4) 2... e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 { If we compare the QGD exchange variation to the main line in this variation, we see that essentially white is playing black in the exchange Caro-Kann and vice versa. }) 1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 { White gives up their strong e4 pawn for our flank c6 pawn in exchange for time and a queenside pawn majority. } 3... cxd5 4. Bd3 { The exchange variation. White will play within the structure with c3 (and not c4). This is known as the Carlsbad structure. This pawn structure can also be reached from the London and Queen's Gambit Declined move orders. } 4... Nc6 5. c3 { Sparring Pos 5. The true Carlsbad pawn structure is set up. } (5. Nf3?! Bg4 $10 { This gives our LSB a dream square from which we can next finish development. }) 5... Nf6 6. Bf4!? { This is a fancy move that Fischer used. White is hoping we block our bishop in with e6. } (6. h3!? { An alternative approach for white that stops Bg4 and next will play Nf3. } 6... g6 $10 { If we can't get our bishop to g4, at least we can get to f5! The next move is Bf5, challenging white's good bishop with our bad bishop. } { [%cal Gc8f5] }) (6. Nf3?! { This gives our LSB a dream square from which we can next finish development. } 6... Bg4 $10 { e6, Bd6, and O-O are coming next. }) 6... Bg4! 7. Qb3 { If white wants any advantage, they need to try and play against our newly undefended b7 pawn with tempo. } (7. Nf3?! $10 { Transposing to the other line gives black a good game. }) 7... Qd7 $10 { With e6, Bd6, and O-O next. All of our pieces have good squares. Black will often play for the minority attack with b5-b4. White will try and attack us using the e5 outpost. A LSB trade and/or queen trade favor us tremendously.
You don't need to memorize the following moves, but an instructive variation would be: } 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6! { We should not be afraid of losing the b7 pawn if it helps our development. } 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qxb7!? Rb8! 12. Qa6 O-O! $10 { White cannot conveniently hold onto the b2 pawn, and all of black's pieces are active. } (12... Rxb2?? { Too greedy! } 13. Bb5! $18 { If only we had finished development sooner... }) *


