1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Bd6 10. Bxd6 (10. Ne5!? Qc7! $10 { Keeping the tension and further challenging white's e5 knight. }) 10... Qxd6 11. O-O (11. Qxb7!? Rb8 12. Qa6 O-O! $10 { Black has a lot of play on the b file in exchange for the pawn. }) 11... O-O 12. Rfe1 Qc7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Rxe5 Bh5 15. a4 Bg6 16. Bxg6 hxg6 { Trading LSBs lessens white's attacking potential and increases the likelihood that black's queenside play making progress. That being said, black's doubled pawns slightly compensate for the bishop trade. } 17. g3 Rab8! { The threat is a6-b5, going for the minority attack. } 18. h4 Qa5 (18... a6!? { Also good. } 19. Re2 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Qd1 b4 $15 { The classic minority attack in action. No matter what happens next, white will be left with an accessible queenside weakness on b2, c3, or d4. }) 19. Ree1 Rfc8 20. Kg2 Qa6 21. Nf3 b5 { While this isn't the usual minority attack, it accomplishes the same goal: open lines towards a backwards pawn on the queenside. } 22. axb5 Qxb5 23. Qxb5 Rxb5 24. Re2 (24. Rxa7!? Rxb2 $10 { [%cal Gc8c3] }) 24... a5 { This is an opening success for black since the kingside is mostly irrelevant and black's play on the queenside is the focus of the game.
Now Artemiev tortures his opponent on the queenside while slowly improving his position. } 25. Ne5 Kf8 26. Kf1 Rc7 27. Ke1 Ke7 28. Kd1 Ne4 29. Nd3 g5 30. hxg5 Nxg5 31. Nc5 Ne4 32. Nxe4 dxe4 33. Kc2 (33. Rxe4!? Rxb2 $10 { [%cal Gc7c3] }) 33... f5 34. b3 Kf6 35. c4 e5 36. Rd2 exd4 37. Rxd4 Kg5 38. Kb2 Re5 39. Kc3 Kg4 40. Re1 g5 41. Re3 Rce7 42. Rd8 f4 43. gxf4 gxf4 44. Rg8+ Rg5 45. Rxg5+ Kxg5 46. Re2?? (46. Re1! Kg4 47. c5 Kf3 48. Kd4! e3 49. fxe3 fxe3 50. Kd3! e2 51. c6! Kf2 52. Kd2! $10 { After a sequence of only-moves, it's amazingly true that white's king cannot be deflected from the defense of e1. White holds a draw. }) 46... Kg4 47. c5 Kf3 48. Ra2 e3 49. fxe3 fxe3 50. Rxa5 e2 51. Ra1 e1=Q+ 52. Rxe1 Rxe1 { White's pawns aren't far enough up the board for them to stand a chance against black's active king and rook. } 53. Kd4 Kf4 54. Kd5 Kf5 55. Kd6 Rd1+ 56. Ke7 Rc1 57. Kd6 Kf6 58. b4 Rd1+ 59. Kc7 Ke7 60. b5 Rd5 61. Kc6 Rh5 $19 { 0-1 White resigns. } { Zugzwang. Kd8->c8 cannot be prevented without dropping a pawn. } 62. b6!? { The only try: } 62... Kd8! 63. b7 Rh6+! 64. Kb5 Kc7! 65. c6 Rg6! { Zugzwang again! } (65... Rxc6?? 66. b8=Q+! Kxb8 67. Kxc6 $10) 66. Kc5 Rxc6+ $19 0-1


