1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 { The Fantasy variation. White further supports the center, but at the cost of weakening their king long-term and preventing the g1 knight from developing to the natural f3 square. } 3... Qb6!? { Sparring Pos 6.
It's atypical to develop the queen so early, but since white has no easy way to finish kingside development, we can take a time-out to make a normal French move in expectation of white closing the center and transitioning into a French. } (3... e6!? $10 { A logical alternative. White has blocked their knight, and we have blocked our bishop. Now we get an interesting maneuvering game. }) 4. Nc3 e6 5. a3 Nd7 $10 { Black is always ready to meet e5?! with c5. In the meantime, we will develop our kingside pieces as if it's a French position. } *


