[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: When the exchange sacrifice is just a win..."]
[Date "1972"]
[White "Robert James Fischer"]
[Black "Borris Spassky"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "When the exchange sacrifice is just a win..."]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/iXysQZgk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "4q2k/2r1r1p1/4Pn1p/p1p2R2/P2pQ2P/1P1B1R2/6P1/6K1 w - - 9 38"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ From the famous World Chess Championship 1972 match between Fischer and Spassky. This is hardly an exchange sacrifice and more of a "just kill the guy" move. }
38. Rxf6! { White was completely winning, but this move snuffs out any hope of defense. } 38... gxf6 39. Rxf6 { [%cal Ge4h7] } 39... Kg8 40. Bc4 { Fischer merely reinforces the e6 pawn (and stops the e7 rook from ever moving due to e7+) before winning the game. } 40... Kh8 41. Qf4 $18 { With the unstoppable threats of Qxh6, Rxh6, and Rf8+, all leading to mate, Spassky resigned. The game could have continued: } { [%cal Gf6f8,Gf4h6] } 41... Kg8 42. Rxh6 Qf8 43. Rh8+ Kxh8 44. Qxf8+ Kh7 45. Bd3# *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: Another exchange sac that is just winning"]
[Date "1968"]
[White "Tigran Petrosian"]
[Black "Yakov Estrin"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "IM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "Another exchange sac that is just winning"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/tVC8XZjB"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "r2n1rk1/1ppqnpbp/3p2b1/1P4NR/4B3/2N3P1/PB1QPP2/R3K3 w Q - 3 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ From Petrosian - Estrin. To find this move, recognize that black's pieces are terrible, white has a lead in development, and the initiative is more important than material when the players have castled on opposite sides. }
18. Rxh7! Bxh7 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. O-O-O { Petrosian hasn't really sacrificed the exchange here. The open h file means that white is completely winning. } 20... Ng8 21. Rh1 Nh6 22. Nd5! { White is threatening Bxg7+ followed by Qb2+ getting on the long diagonal, so black does everything they can to stop the bleeding. This is clearly already a "win" - Petrosian just needs to find it. } 22... f6 23. Ne4 (23. Bb1 $18 { followed by Qc2 and mate threats on the h7 was probably more precise, but a win is a win. }) 23... Rxa2 24. Rxh6 Bxh6 25. Qxh6 Qg7 (25... Qxh7?? 26. Qxf8+ Qg8 27. Qxf6+ Kh7 28. Qh4+ Kg6 29. Qg5+ Kf7 30. Qf6+ Ke8 31. Qe7#) 26. Qh4 { Black resigned rather than face the following crush: } 26... Qxh7 27. Bxf6+ Rxf6 28. Qxf6+ Qg7 29. Qxd8+ $18 *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: The quintessential exchange sacrifice"]
[Date "2020.11.29"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "The quintessential exchange sacrifice"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/5OOguTH3"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2n1r1k1/2qbr1b1/pp1p1p1p/2pP1Pp1/P1P3P1/1PNQ1BBP/8/R3R1K1 w Q - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]

{ Now let's talk about REAL exchange sacrifices. You're sacrificing your rook for pure positional compensation - not to win the material back immediately. }
1. Re6! { [%csl Re8,Re7,Rd7,Rc8] } (1. Kg2?! { If you're not willing to sacrifice the exchange in this position, then notice how quickly your lead can disappear... } 1... Rxe1 2. Rxe1 Rxe1 3. Bxe1 $16 { White is no doubt still a little bit better, but there's no immediate breakthrough and this game will take a lot of work in order to convert. }) 1... Bxe6 2. dxe6 { Black: 👍up an exchange, 👎d6 pawn is weak and accessible, 👎g7 bishop is completely trapped, 👎rooks on e7 and e8 are doing absolutely nothing, 👎knight on c8 is not contributing. White: 👍passed e pawn on e6, 👍amazing knight about to land on d5, 👍g3 bishop and queen are targeting the weak d6 square, 👍space advantage on the kingside. These positional positives > the material. } { [%csl Gd5] } (2. fxe6!? { Also good, but the d5 square is more accessible to our pieces than the f5 square. } { [%csl Gg7,Ge7,Ge8] }) 2... Na7 (2... Qd8 3. Nd5 Ra7 4. Rd1 Ne7 5. Nxe7+ Rexe7 6. Bxd6 $18 { If black tries to hold onto their material, the passed e pawn will quickly win the game. }) 3. Nd5 { I've included the rest of these moves to showcase how quickly things can go wrong if black tries normal looking moves. I encourage you to try out your own ideas and see how quickly white wins! } 3... Qb8 4. Rd1 Nc8 5. h4 { White does not ever need to take back the exchange - the knight on d5 is better than either rook! Only once white has built up the position to its maximum will they go for the material. } 5... Kh8 6. hxg5 fxg5 7. Kg2 Kg8 8. Be1 Qa7 (8... Kh8 9. f6! Rxe6 10. fxg7+ Kxg7 11. Bc3+ $18) 9. Bc3 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 $18 { The knight and queen will both soon infiltrate on the weak dark squares around black's king. The engine suggestion is Rxe6, giving up an entire rook just to avoid immediate disaster. } { [%csl Gf6] } *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: A common Sicilian exchange sacrifice"]
[Date "2020.11.29"]
[White "blindbandit99"]
[Black "NoseKnowsAll"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "A common Sicilian exchange sacrifice"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/WnmImhnb"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "2rq1rk1/1b1nbppp/p2p1n2/1p2pP2/4P3/PNNQB3/1PP1B1PP/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]

{ This position is from a Sicilian Najdorf, although this setup can occur from many Sicilians. With so much pressure on e4 and the c3 knight being the key defender, this exchange sacrifice should come as no surprise! }
1... Rxc3 2. Qxc3 (2. bxc3 Bxe4 3. Qd2 Nb6 $19 { A worse version of the game. } { [%cal Gb6c4] }) 2... Bxe4 { White: 👍up the exchange, 👍good pawn structure, 👎down a central pawn, 👎potential weakness on c2. Black: 👍incredible bishop on e4, 👍two central pawns and d5 cannot be stopped, 👍up a pawn, 👍no pawn weaknesses. More nuanced than last position, but black has incredible compensation! } 3. Nd2 Nd5! (3... Bb7 4. Rad1 Qa8 $17 { Even if black doesn't see Nd5 winning the bishop pair, black has extremely active pieces and retains the central pawn majority. Black remains better. }) 4. Qb3 Nxe3 5. Qxe3 Bb7 $17 { Black finds a way to deprive white of the bishop pair too! After Bg5 and Nc5, it is clear that all of black's pieces are more active than white's. The "extra rook" white has is stuck on a1 still doing nothing. Black is down 1 point of material, but engine says -1 purely because of positional compensation! } { [%cal Ge7g5,Gd7c5] } *


