[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/TXAYV179"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]

{ Feel free to skip to move 14 if you just want to see the exchange sacrifice. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 { [%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4] } 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg7a1] } 8... Nc6 9. Nb3 Be6 10. f4 { [%cal Gf4f5] } 10... Na5 { [%cal Gb3a5,Gd8a5,Gf4f5,Ga5f5] } 11. f5 Bc4 { [%cal Ga5c4] } (11... gxf5?? 12. exf5 $18) 12. Nxa5 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qxa5 14. g4 { This scary move was once thought to give white an advantage. However, black players soon found the following cure... } { [%cal Gg4g5,Gf5f6,Ge4e5] } (14. fxg6?! hxg6 $10) 14... Rac8! 15. g5 Rxc3! 16. gxf6 { [%cal Gg7f6] } (16. Bd2?? Qc5+! 17. Kh1 (17. Be3 { [%csl Gc3,Gc5][%cal Gc3e3,Gc5e3] } 17... Qxe3+ 18. Qxe3 Rxe3 19. gxf6 Bxf6 $19) (17. Kg2 Rxc2 18. gxf6 Bxf6 $19) 17... Rxc2 { [%cal Gg5f6] } 18. gxf6 Bxf6) (16. bxc3 Nxe4 { This position is reminiscent of the previous example. Black is not just equal - they are much better. } { [%csl Gc3,Gc2][%cal Gg7a1] }) 16... Rxe3 { [%cal Ge3e2] } (16... Bxf6 17. bxc3 Qxc3) 17. Qxe3 Bxf6 { [%cal Gc2c3] } 18. c3 $10 { Once this sequence was discovered in the 1980s, people realized this line was not scary for black at all! Black is again down the exchange for a pawn, but has full compensation due to their amazing bishop on f6 which pressures c3 and b2, perfect pawn structure, and soon-to-be active rook. Black is not better because white also has no accessible weaknesses, but is certainly not worse. } { Lukin, Andrei M - Georgiev, Krum, 1/2-1/2, Naleczow, 1981, https://lichess.org/wCBkQQ48 } *


[Event "Always sacrifice the exchange!: Reshevsky - Petrosian, 1953"]
[Date "1953"]
[White "Samuel Reshevsky"]
[Black "Tigran Petrosian"]
[Result "*"]
[WhiteTitle "GM"]
[BlackTitle "GM"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Always sacrifice the exchange!"]
[ChapterName "Reshevsky - Petrosian, 1953"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/h3ccaYFE/YNI3sgTZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "3rq1k1/4rppp/2n3b1/pp2P3/2pP1QB1/P1P1R3/1B4PP/4R1K1 b - - 3 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One of the most famous exchange sacrifices ever played, Petrosian is defending against a fearsome attack from Reshevsky. With things looking bad, he uncorked the amazing defensive move: }
25... Re6!! (25... Kf8? 26. Bf3 Kg8? 27. d5! $18 { If black sits around, white plays d5 and wins the game by blasting open the center files and creating a mobile passed pawn. }) 26. a4 (26. Bxe6 { Not played immediately, but similar to the game } 26... fxe6 27. Rg3 Ne7 28. Rf1 Nd5 $14) 26... Ne7! 27. Bxe6 fxe6 28. Qf1 Nd5 29. Rf3 Bd3 { Compare this position to the position at move 25. Black's knight is impressive on d5, constantly pressuring the c3 square. Black's bishop is certainly more powerful than white's bishop locked behind the pawn chain. The white rooks, once so powerful in the center, are now staring at nothing. } 30. Rxd3! { Reshevsky has to sacrifice the exchange back! } (30. Qf2? { In fact if white plays poorly here, he can actually be worse! } 30... b4 31. cxb4 axb4 $17 { The two passed pawns on the queenside more than compensate for the exchange! }) 30... cxd3 31. Qxd3 b4 32. cxb4 axb4 $10 { The game continued and ended up in a draw } *


