[FEN "r2q2k1/3nb2p/p2p2pB/1p1Ppr2/4N3/6Q1/PPR2PPP/5RK1 w - - 3 19"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]

{ Two 1600 lichess players reached this position. White, afraid of Nc5 played b4?! and went on to win a chaotic game }
19. Rfc1 { The most natural move in the position is also extremely good! } (19. b4?! Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Rc6 $14 { White is slightly better, but this is far from a clear position. }) 19... Nc5?! 20. Rxc5!! (20. Nxc5? dxc5 { This variation is much worse for white. Note how the knight on e4 controlled the d6 square, rested on a beautiful light square outpost and therefore could never be kicked away, and allows an immediate breakthrough. }) 20... dxc5 21. d6! (21. Rd1?! { Even if white does not see this tactic and cannot push d6 immediately, the d6 blockade is uncomfortable by black because they are dooming their bishop to passivity. } 21... Bd6 22. Bg5 Qf8 23. h4 $16 { White can continue to make progress even here. } { [%cal Gh4h5] }) 21... Bf8 (21... Bxd6?? 22. Rd1 $18 { [%cal Gd1d8] }) 22. Bxf8 Qxf8 23. Rxc5 $16 { White's f pawn is never a weakness because of the hero knight on e4 which defends f2, threatens Nf6+ in some variations, supports the d6 pawn, and blockades the e pawn. White is much better. } *


