[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "b2r2k1/2q3bp/1r4p1/p2nPp2/2pP1P2/2P4P/R1B1NQ1K/2B2R2 b - - 1 31"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2020.11.29"]
[UTCTime "06:12:13"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ In the candidates tournament 1959, Smyslov's a pawn is being attacked by Gligoric' rook. What should we do? }
31... Rb3!! (31... Qf7 { This move is also ok, but it does give up the a pawn. Smyslov comes up with a much more active plan. } 32. Rxa5 Bc6 33. Qe1) (31... Ra6 { This move is also ok, but after h4-h5, white's kingside attack gains real steam. Note the a pawn is still firmly blockaded by the bishop and rook. }) 32. Bxb3 cxb3 33. Ra4 { Not forced, but white is trying to get their own passed pawns rolling too. } (33. Rb2?? a4 $18 { The passive Rb2 would have been an immediate disaster. } { [%cal Ga4a3] }) 33... Bf8 (33... Rb8 { Also a good move, but what was your plan after Bb2? }) (33... Bc6 { Also excellent. Smyslov didn't want to allow Ra3 a4 c4 where white's pawns start rolling. }) (33... Nb6? { Interesting. But after Rxa5 Nc4 Rb5! white stops the b pawn's progress. } 34. Rxa5 Nc4 35. Rb5) 34. Bb2 Bc6! $17 { Bc6 was not played in the game because Smyslov was worried about c4!? giving back the exchange and getting counterplay with their own passed pawns. However, Bc6 c4 Nb6 is simply winning for black, so this really was the cleanest way forward. If the rook moves immediately, then a4-a3 quickly decides the game. } (34... Nb6!? { Interesting, but allows white a chance to give back the exchange with Rxa5 Nc4 Rxa8! Rxa8 Ra1! Rxa1 Bxa1. Black is slightly better. } 35. Rxa5 Nc4 36. Rxa8 Rxa8 37. Ra1 Rxa1 38. Bxa1 b2 39. Bxb2 Nxb2 $17) *


