{ In this game between Anatoly Karpov and Ulf Andersson, black just blew open the center with d5 and needs to find a way forward to fully equalize. }
26... Bd6 (26... Rxe3? { Too early! After Qxe3 Bd6 Qg1, white is up the exchange with no issues. } 27. Qxe3 Bd6 28. Qg1 $18) (26... Nxd5!? { White retains some edge after Nxd5 Bxd5 Bxa6 } 27. Nxd5 Bxd5 28. Bxa6) 27. Nf1 { [%csl Gh2] } 27... Rxe3! 28. Nxe3 { Did you find Bf4 after Qxe3? Black wins back the exchange and trades pieces which is good when black lacks space. } (28. Qxe3 Bf4 $14) 28... Bxh2 { White is living on a razor thin margin here. The only move that gives white an advantage is Bxa6, allowing Bg3, when white will eventually sacrifice back their exchange. In the game, Karpov immediately misplays the position. } 29. Nf1?! Bf4 30. Rc2 b5 $10 { Black's bishop pair and extra pawn give him full compensation for the exchange. Andersson went on to win a chaotic game. } (30... Bb7 { Also good, but not as precise as in the game. Why block your own queen? }) *


