1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 (5... e6 6. g4 { The mainline Keres }) 6. Be3 e6 7. g4 e5 8. Nf5 g6 { [%cal Gf1g2] } 9. g5 (9. Bg2 gxf5 10. exf5 { [%cal Gg2a8] }) 9... gxf5 10. exf5 d5 11. Qf3 { Still theory. This might be the earliest game where this became known as theory? } { [%csl Gf5] } 11... d4 12. O-O-O Nbd7 13. Bd2 { [%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5,Gc3e4] } 13... dxc3 14. Bxc3 { White is down 2 pieces. But the knight on f6 is trapped. Black's king is never going to be safe. The pawn on e5 is currently "free" so we're quickly able to open up the e file. } { [%cal Gh1g1,Gf1c4] } 14... Bg7 (14... Rg8 15. gxf6 Qxf6 16. Bh3 Be7 17. Rhe1 Kf8 18. Kb1 { The stockfish line. Bh3 is a novelty that has never been played before, but in this position only a5! gives black any advantage. }) 15. Rg1 O-O 16. gxf6 Qxf6 17. Qe3 { [%cal Gf2f4,Gc3h8] } 17... Kh8 18. f4 Qb6 (18... exf4 19. Bxf6 fxe3 20. Bxg7+ Kg8 $18) 19. Qg3 Qh6 20. Rd6!! f6 (20... Qxf4+ 21. Qxf4 exf4 22. Bxg7+ Kg8 23. Bf6#) (20... Qxd6 21. Qxg7#) (20... Nf6 21. Bxe5) 21. Bd2 { Now that black has blocked their own diagonal, we can reroute to the more important diagonal (threatening fxe4 with tempo). } 21... e4 22. Bc4 b5 23. Be6 { [%csl Gd7] } 23... Ra7 24. Rc6 { [%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c7] } (24. Be3 { A bit premature due to } 24... Rc7) 24... a5 { [%csl Gb5,Ga5][%cal Gc8a6] } (24... Bb7 25. Rc7 { [%cal Gd2e3] } 25... Rd8 26. Be3 $18 { [%csl Gb7,Ga7] }) 25. Be3 Rb7 26. Bd5 { [%cal Gc6c8] } 26... Rb8 27. Rc7 b4 28. b3 Rb5 29. Bc6 Rxf5 30. Rxc8 Rxc8 31. Bxd7 Rcc5 32. Bxf5 Rxf5 33. Rd1 { [%cal Gd1d8] } 33... Kg8 34. Qg2 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { Material has been restored, but black is completely tied down and is losing e4 (and therefore his king) by force. } { [%cal Gg2e4,Ge4e6,Ge4a8,Gd1d8] } 1-0


