1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 8. Bc4 O-O (8... b5 9. Bd5 Nxd5 10. Qxd5 { [%cal Gd5a8,Ge3a7] } 10... Qc7 11. Qxa8 Bb7 12. Qa7 $18) 9. O-O Be6 10. Qe2 b5 11. Bb3 Bxb3?! { giving up further control of d5 is not best. } (11... h6 $10) 12. axb3 Nbd7 13. Rfd1 Qc7 14. Bg5 { Announcing to black that her strategy will now completely revolve around the weakened d5 square. If we can put a knight on d5 and leave black with their bad dark squared bishop, white will be positionally winning. } { [%cal Gg5f6] } 14... Rfc8 { [%csl Gc2] } (14... h6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 { [%cal Gf3h4,Gh4f5] } 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 g6 18. c3 Kg7 { The knight cannot be denied d5 long-term. } { [%cal Gf3d2,Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Ge3d5] }) 15. Ne1 Qb7 { [%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5] } (15... b4 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 { transposing }) 16. Bxf6 (16. g3 h6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. Nd5) 16... Nxf6 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Rc5 19. Rad1 { White has a strategically winning good knight vs bad bishop endgame... if only the knight can arrive on d5. } 19... Rxd5?! (19... a5 $14) 20. Rxd5 Rc8 21. c3 b4?! { An interesting try - trying to prevent the knight getting to d5 via the normal route. But it backfires on Anand. } (21... Rc5 { [%cal Ge2d2] } 22. Qd2? (22. Rd1 { [%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5,Gc2b4,Gb4d5] }) 22... Rxd5 23. Qxd5 Qxd5 24. exd5 { [%csl Gd5] }) 22. c4 g6 23. g3 Rc5 24. Rd1 { We want to keep as many pieces on the board as possible in order to threaten the kingside too in case black starts playing there. } 24... a5 25. Nc2 { [%cal Gc2e3,Ge3d5] } 25... Kg7 (25... Bg5 { [%csl Ge3] } 26. Rxd6) 26. Qd3 (26. Ne3? Qxe4 $17) 26... Rc6 27. Ne3 Qc8 28. Kg2 Qe6 29. Qe2 Bd8 30. Nd5 { Polgar has reached the dream position. } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gd1h1] } 30... Rc5 31. Qe3 Be7 32. Rd3 Bd8 33. Qd2 Rc6 { With the battery formed in this manner, black's pieces are now forced to defend the d pawn forever. } 34. Qd1 Kg8 35. h4! Kg7?! { Possibly the decisive mistake. } (35... h5 36. f3 $14 { Now g4 will be the pawn break to achieve. But it weakens white's king a bit more than one would want, so the position might become double-edged. }) 36. h5! { Opening a new route into the position for white's major pieces. } 36... Bg5 (36... g5? 37. Ne3 $18 { [%cal Ge3f5] }) 37. Qf3 Rc8 38. Rd1 Rc6 39. Qe2 Rc8 40. Rh1 Kg8 41. f3 { [%cal Ge2f2] } 41... Rb8 42. Qf2 Rb7 { The white queen cannot enter the queenside, but now black's rook is stuck. } { [%csl Gb6,Ga7][%cal Gf2b6] } 43. hxg6! { Now is the time to exchange! } 43... fxg6 { Black's king is weaker, the d and h pawns are now targets, and white should be breaking through. } (43... hxg6?? { The move you want to make fails tactically. } 44. Qg1! Bf6 45. Qh2 Kf8 46. Ra1! $18) 44. c5! dxc5 45. Qxc5 Bd8 46. Rc1 Kf7 47. Qe3 { If only the rook could infiltrate to c6... } { [%csl Gc6] } 47... Kg7 48. Rc4 Rd7 49. Qc1 h5 50. Rc6 Rd6 51. Rc8 { The rook has penetrated, and black's king is in trouble. } 51... Qd7 52. Qc5 Kh6? 53. Rb8 (53. Ra8! Bb6 54. Qc1+! Kg7 55. Qg5! $18) 53... Bf6? { [%cal Gc5a5] } (53... Kg7 { [%cal Gd8b6] } 54. Rb7 Qxb7 55. Qxd6 { [%cal Gd6e5,Gd6d8] }) 54. Qe3+ (54. Qxa5?? { No such thing as free lunch } 54... Rc6 { [%cal Gd7h3,Gc6c2] }) 54... Bg5? (54... Kg7 55. Ra8 { Winning at least a pawn. } { [%cal Ga8a5] } 55... Rc6? (55... Qb5 56. Nc7 $18 { [%cal Gc7b5,Gc7e8] }) 56. Ra7! $18 { [%cal Ga7g7] }) 55. f4!! exf4 56. Rh8+!! { 1-0 Black resigns. } 56... Kg7 57. Qd4+ Bf6 (57... Kf7 { [%cal Gh8h7] } 58. Rh7+ $18) 58. Qxf6+ (58. Rg8+ Kxg8 59. Nxf6+ { [%cal Gd6f6,Gd4d7] } 59... Kf7) 58... Rxf6 59. Rh7+ Kxh7 60. Nxf6+ Kg7 61. Nxd7 $18 { A cleanly winning final position. } 1-0


