1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3 a6 7. Na3 Be7 { I had never seen this move before, so I tried to play typically with Nd5. Theory shows that Nc4 into e3 immediately is stronger so as to keep control over d5 with a piece. } 8. Nd5 (8. Nc4 b5 9. Ne3 Nf6 10. Ned5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 O-O) 8... Nf6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Be3 Be6 { b5 was much stronger than Be6 because it prevents my idea of trading off the light squared bishops on white's terms. } 11. Bc4 b5 12. Bd5 Rc8 13. c3 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Ne7 { If I would play this position again, I would go with Qb7 and go pawn hunting. } { [%cal Gd5b7] } 15. Qd2 (15. Qb7 d5 16. Qxa6 d4 17. Qxb5+ Nc6 18. cxd4 exd4 19. Rd1 O-O 20. O-O Qc7) 15... d5 16. exd5 Qxd5 17. O-O O-O 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. Qe2 Qb7 20. g4 { Running low on time, I played g4 trying to prevent Nf5 and get a flight square. I expected him to get in h5 eventually when I would reinforce g4 with h3. I completely missed Ng6 though. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge7f5] } (20. c4 b4 21. Nc2 b3 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Ne1) (20. f3 Nd5 21. Bf2 Nf4 22. Qe4 Qxe4 23. fxe4) 20... Ng6 21. h3 Nh4 22. f3 Nxf3+ 23. Kf2 Bh4+ 24. Kf1 f5 25. Nc2 fxg4 26. hxg4 Rf8 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


