1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Qc7 6. Nc3 b6 7. a3 Bb7 8. Be3 Nf6 9. f3 d6 10. Be2 Nbd7 { I knew we were still in theory here, but I was getting to the end of where I know. I figured Qd2 was more solid than O-O because then I could meet Ne5 with b3 } 11. Qd2 (11. O-O Ne5? 12. f4!! Nxc4 13. Bxc4 Qxc4 14. Rc1! { Down a pawn but white is winning because the Queen has no way to get out of the pin. }) 11... Rc8 12. Rc1 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Kh1 h5 15. b4 Qb8 16. Nb3 h4 17. Rfd1 h3 18. gxh3 Ne5 19. Na4 b5 20. Nb6 { At this point, I was already under 30 seconds. } 20... Nxc4 21. Nxc4? (21. Nxc8!! Rxc8 (21... Nxd2 22. Nxe7+ Kh7 23. Rxd2 $16 { A beautiful queen sacrifice I missed. })) (21. Bxc4 bxc4 22. Nxc8 Rxc8 23. Na5 d5 { Aman said this was his plan - sacrificing the exchange in order to get in d5. I have to admit, this looks scary, but I at least get the chance to trade off the beautiful light squared bishop before trying to break down the center. } 24. Nxb7 Qxb7 $14) 21... bxc4 22. Rxc4 d5 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 24. Bf4?? { I completely missed that e5 was a possibility. I thought he had to play Qa8 in which case I was preparing e5 to try and shut down the center. } 24... e5! (24... Qa8 25. e5) 25. Bg5 dxe4 26. Bxf6 exf3 27. Bxe7 f2+! 28. Qd5 Bxd5+ 29. Rxd5 Qb7 { White resigned with no way to stop the f pawn or the rook from dropping. } *


