1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2... d5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 3. Bf4 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 3... e6!? { [%clk 0:02:56] } (3... c5 { For some reason I decided not to play my mainline weapon against the London, fearing some specific preparation by my FM foe. }) 4. e3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 4... c5 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 5. c3 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 5... Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 6. Nbd2 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 6... Qb6 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 7. Rb1!? { Because Bf5 is not available, white has the added option of Rb1 to defend the b pawn. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } 7... Be7 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 8. Bd3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 8... O-O { [%clk 0:02:52] } 9. O-O { [%clk 0:03:00] } 9... h6 { [%clk 0:02:39] } 10. h3 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 10... Bd7 { [%clk 0:02:29] } 11. Ne5 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 11... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 12. Bxe5?! $10 { White plays carelessly and black is immediately able to equalize by trading off his bad d7 bishop for the beast on d3. } { [%clk 0:02:43] } (12. dxe5! { A more testing line } 12... Nh7!? (12... Ne8 13. Qg4 Kh8 14. Qh5 Bb5 { Black cannot get away with the same bishop maneuver in this variation (what I was going to play in the game) } 15. Bxh6! Bxd3 16. Bg5+ Kg8 17. Bxe7 $18) 13. Qc2 f5 14. exf6 Nxf6) 12... Bb5! { [%clk 0:02:24] } 13. Qe2 { [%clk 0:02:34] } (13. c4!? dxc4 14. Nxc4 { White insists that he keep the light squared bishop } 14... Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Rfd8 16. Qe2 Rac8 $10 { but the remaining piece coordination by black is perfect, so the game is still equal. }) 13... Bxd3 { [%clk 0:02:21] } 14. Qxd3 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 14... Rfc8 { [%clk 0:02:09] } 15. Kh1 { [%clk 0:02:19] } 15... Ne8 { [%clk 0:01:55] } 16. g4 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 16... Bd6 { Seeing the attack coming, I again recognize the need to trade pieces. My advantage lies on the queenside, not the kingside. } { [%clk 0:01:57] } 17. f4 { [%clk 0:02:12] } 17... f6 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 18. g5! { [%clk 0:02:03] } 18... hxg5 { [%clk 0:01:30] } (18... fxe5?? 19. fxe5 Bf8 20. Qg6 hxg5 21. Qf7+ Kh7 22. Nf3 $18) 19. Bxd6 { [%clk 0:02:03] } (19. fxg5! fxe5 20. Qg6! Rc7 21. Nf3!! { The only triple exclamation mark move I've ever seen. White sacrificed a piece in order to perform a slow motion reposition of his knight with a deadly finish. } 21... Re7 22. Nh2! { [%cal Gh2g4,Gg4h6] } 22... exd4 23. Ng4 Rc8 (23... Rc7 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. Ne5 Bxe5 26. Rf8+ Kh7 27. g6+ Kh6 28. Rh8+ Kg5 29. h4#) 24. Nh6+ { And the eagle has landed. } 24... Kh8 25. Rf8#) 19... Nxd6 { [%clk 0:01:32] } 20. fxg5 { [%clk 0:02:04] } 20... f5 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 21. g6 { [%clk 0:01:59] } 21... cxd4? { [%clk 0:01:17] } (21... Qd8 22. Qe2 { If black did not trade on d4, then there's no pressure on the e6 pawn, and black can safely play the desired move } 22... Qg5 { [%cal Ge2h5,Gg5h5] } 23. Rg1 Qh6 { The white queen cannot enter black's position. } { [%csl Gh5] }) 22. exd4 { [%clk 0:01:57] } 22... Qd8! { The queen repositions to d8 in order to better control the kingside squares for the incoming attack } { [%clk 0:01:15] } 23. Qe2! { I didn't spot this queen move. She eyes h5 for a devastating check on h8 as well as the loose e6 pawn. } { [%clk 0:01:52] } 23... Qf6 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 24. Qh5 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 24... Ne4?? { [%clk 0:00:25] } (24... Kf8!! { The perfect time to run. There is no pressure on the e file, and the g7 pawn is defended, so black can dart towards the queenside and play Rh8 to evict the white queen his his own attack on the loose white king. } 25. Rbe1 Ke7 26. Qe2 Rh8 27. Rf3 Rh6 28. c4 Rxg6 29. cxd5 Qxd4 $17 { Still a very difficult position to convert. }) 25. Nxe4 { [%clk 0:01:48] } 25... dxe4 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 26. Rbe1 { e4 cannot be defended. } { [%csl Ge4] [%clk 0:01:50] } 26... Kf8 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 27. Rxe4 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 27... Rd8 { [%clk 0:00:11] } (27... Ke7?? { It's too late to run. } 28. Rxf5 $18) 28. Rxe6! { [%clk 0:01:32] } 28... Qxe6 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 29. Rxf5+ { [%clk 0:01:33] } 29... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:20] } 30. Re5 { [%clk 0:01:32] } 30... Rd6 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 31. Qh7 { [%clk 0:01:14] } 31... Qxe5 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 32. dxe5 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 32... Rd1+ { [%clk 0:00:19] } 33. Kg2 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 33... Rad8 { A desperate bid to get the rook on a8 actually participating, but white doesn't give black any time. } { [%clk 0:00:11] } 34. Qxg7+ { [%clk 0:01:16] } 34... Ke6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 35. Qf6+ { [%clk 0:01:17] } 35... Kd7 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 36. Qxd8+ { "There are many different wins here - I'll choose the most aesthetic" } { [%clk 0:01:08] } 36... Kxd8 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 37. g7 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 37... Rd2+ { [%clk 0:00:09] } 38. Kf3 { [%clk 0:01:06] } 38... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:02] } 39. g8=Q { [%clk 0:01:03] } 39... Rd3+ { [%clk 0:00:02] } 40. Ke4 { 1-0 White wins on time. } { There are no stalemates to try for. } { [%csl Gd7,Gb7,Ga7] [%clk 0:01:03] } 1-0


