1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 1... c5 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 2... d6 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 3. d4 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 4... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 5. Nc3 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 5... a6 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 6. Bg5 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 6... Nc6 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 7. Qd2 { Through a weird move order, we now enter the Richter-Rauzer attack. } { [%clk 0:02:59] } 7... e6 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 8. O-O-O { [%clk 0:02:53] } 8... Bd7 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 9. f4 { [%clk 0:02:31] } 9... b5 { I had a recent classical game in this position and played the slightly inaccurate but very interesting Nxc6 Bxc6 Qe1. I reviewed a little more theory after the game and discovered the following idea is mainline: } { [%clk 0:03:07] } 10. Bxf6 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 10... gxf6 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 11. Kb1 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 11... Qb6 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 12. f5?! { Andras immediately commented that playing f5 is inaccurate in the situation where black can trade queens. Better was Nxc6 Bxc6 f5. } { [%clk 0:01:45] } (12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. f5 b4 14. Ne2 e5 15. Ng3 h5 16. h4 { I have seen a very similar professional game recently. }) 12... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 13. Qxd4 { [%clk 0:01:45] } 13... Qxd4 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 14. Rxd4 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 14... Ke7 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 15. Be2 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 15... Bh6 { White must stop the bishop from reaching e5. } { [%cal Gh6f4,Gf4e5] [%clk 0:02:51] } 16. g3 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 16... Bc6 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 17. Rhd1 { [%clk 0:01:21] } 17... Rad8 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 18. Bf3 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 18... Be3 { [%clk 0:02:32] } (18... exf5?! 19. Nd5+ $16 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 fxe4 21. Bxe4 { [%csl Gd6,Gf6,Gf7] }) 19. R4d3 { [%clk 0:00:52] } 19... Bc5 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 20. Bh1? { I wanted my bishop to be defended in case my knight was kicked with b4. Sadly this move didn't help matters. } { [%clk 0:00:32] } (20. e5! d5 (20... Bxf3 21. exf6+ Kxf6 22. Rxf3 { A much better version of the tactic I spot later in the game. }) 21. exf6+ Kxf6 22. fxe6 fxe6 23. Rf1 { Best play. The position is equal, but white has an easier time due to the threats against the weak e pawn and black's unsafe king. Long term, black should have the easier time of it due to the bishop pair and the passed e pawn. }) 20... h5 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 21. Ne2 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 21... Rdg8 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 22. Nf4 { [%clk 0:00:23] } 22... h4 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 23. e5 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 23... Bxh1 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 24. exf6+ { [%clk 0:00:16] } 24... Kxf6 { [%clk 0:01:42] } 25. Rxh1 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 25... hxg3 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 26. fxe6 { [%clk 0:00:14] } (26. Rxg3?? Rxg3 27. hxg3 Rxh1#) 26... g2 { 0-1 Black wins. } { [%clk 0:01:34] } 0-1


