 } 16... exf5 17. exf5 Qxf5 $17) (16. Kb1! { Always play Kb1. }) 16... Nc5 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 17. Kb1 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 17... Nxb3 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 18. axb3 { White is now threatening Nd5 } { [%clk 0:01:03] } 18... Rfe8 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 19. h4 { [%clk 0:00:37] } 19... Qb4? { At the time I didn't understand this move. Now that the queen won't be headed for e5, I'm free to play the f5 pawn break I've wanted to play for a while now. His actual idea was to prepare playing d5 (which previously would have lost a pawn to Nxd5!) } { [%clk 0:01:07] } (19... d5?? 20. Nxd5 Qxd2 21. Nxe7+ Rxe7 22. Rxd2 $18) 20. f5 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 20... exf5 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 21. exf5 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 21... d5 { [%clk 0:01:02] } 22. f6 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 22... Bf8?? { [%cal Gg7b2,Gf8g7] [%clk 0:01:02] } (22... Bc5! 23. Rh1 { Black can remain sort of equal here by showing that my Rhg1 move was actually a loss of tempo too. }) (22... d4 23. h5 dxc3 { [%cal Gb2c3] } 24. bxc3 Qc5 25. Qd7 Bf8 26. g6 $18) 23. h5 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 23... d4 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 24. g6!! { No backing down now. It's kill or be killed and there's no way I'm moving my knight to somewhere passive and allow black to trade queens... } { [%clk 0:00:13] } 24... gxf6 { [%clk 0:00:18] } (24... dxc3?? 25. gxf7+ Kxf7 26. Qd7+ Kxf6 27. Rdf1+ $18 { "Where's the mate?" }) (24... hxg6 25. hxg6 fxg6 26. Qd3! { Not sure I would have found this quiet killer. } { [%cal Gd3g6] } 26... dxc3 27. Qxg6 $18 { [%cal Gf6f7,Gg1h1] }) 25. gxf7+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } (25. gxh7+?! Kh8 { I thought at first this capture would allow black to keep it quasi-closed near his king, but actually I can force things open: } 26. Qf2 { [%cal Gf2f6] } 26... Qe7 27. Ne4! $18 { [%cal Ge4f6] }) 25... Kxf7 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 26. Qf4 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 26... dxc3 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 27. Qc7+?? { With 3 seconds on my clock, I throw away all the advantage, missing black's coordination on the e7 square. } { [%clk 0:00:04] } (27. Qf5 { The move I needed to see! Now the threats of Rd7+ and Qxh7+ are decisive. There's no defense: } { [%cal Gf5h7] } 27... Qe4 28. Rd7+ Re7?? (28... Qe7 29. Rb7!! Qxb7 30. Qxh7+ Ke6 31. Qxb7 $18) 29. Qxe4 $18) 27... Re7 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 28. Rd7 { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gf8e7,Gb4e7] [%clk 0:00:05] } 28... Re8 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 29. h6 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 29... Bxh6 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 30. Qxc6 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 30... Rxd7?? { The rest of this game was played with seconds on each player's clocks and so was a blunderfest... } { [%clk 0:00:04] } 31. Qxd7+ { [%clk 0:00:08] } 31... Re7 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 32. Qd5+ { [%clk 0:00:09] } 32... Re6?? { [%clk 0:00:06] } (32... Ke8 33. Qh5+ Kd7 34. Qxh6 Qd4 $10 { [%cal Gc3b2,Gd4g1] }) 33. Qd8?? { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gd8g8] [%clk 0:00:07] } (33. Qh5+ Ke7 34. Qxh6 { Black's king is more vulnerable than mine, so white still attacks even here. }) 33... Qe7?? { [%csl Ge7,Ge6,Gf6] [%clk 0:00:08] } 34. Qg8# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } { Gauri expected me to play Qd7+ instead of Qd8, in which case this move would block the check... oops :P } { [%clk 0:00:05] } 1-0


