1. e4 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 1... e6 { [%clk 0:03:02] } 2. d4 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 2... d5 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:04] } 4. e5 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 4... Nfd7 { [%clk 0:03:05] } 5. f4 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 5... c5 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 6. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 6... Nc6 { [%clk 0:03:08] } 7. Be3 { [%clk 0:03:04] } 7... cxd4 { [%clk 0:03:09] } 8. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 8... Bc5 { [%clk 0:03:10] } 9. Qd2 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 9... O-O { [%clk 0:03:10] } 10. O-O-O { [%clk 0:02:59] } 10... a6 { I firmly believe this is one of the best ways for black to play this line for an advantage. I haven't found any great ways forward as white, as the pressure on e5 means the f5 pawn break is near impossible. } { [%clk 0:03:11] } 11. h4 { [%clk 0:02:53] } (11. Nb3!? { Probably the improvement I need to research more. }) 11... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:03:11] } 12. Bxd4 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 12... b5 { [%clk 0:03:12] } 13. h5 { [%clk 0:02:45] } (13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Qd4 Qc7 15. h5 { The engine line appears to be equal too. Regardless, I prefer this to the way I played. }) 13... b4 { [%clk 0:03:12] } 14. Ne2?! { [%clk 0:02:44] } (14. Na4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Qa5 16. b3 { I didn't want anything to do with this position, but with my queen on d4, my a4 knight cannot be challenged except by Bb7-Bc6 which is quite slow. } 16... Bb7 17. Kb1 Bc6 18. Nb2 $10) 14... a5 { [%clk 0:03:13] } 15. h6?! { Premature. I need to be getting in f5 first, so that on f6!? g6 is impossible due to hxg6. Now the position around black's king cannot be peeled further open. } { [%clk 0:02:43] } 15... g6 { [%clk 0:03:13] } 16. g4 { [%clk 0:02:30] } 16... Ba6 { [%clk 0:03:07] } 17. Kb1 { [%clk 0:02:19] } 17... a4 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 18. Bxc5 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 18... Nxc5 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 19. Nd4? { [%clk 0:02:08] } (19. Qxb4 Ne4 { This looked suicidal to me. During the game, Jesse also said "that seems like a pawn you don't want to be taking, buddy." }) 19... Qc7? { [%clk 0:03:01] } (19... Qb6! { Now the threat of a3 is that much stronger. }) 20. Bxa6 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 20... Rxa6 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 21. Qe2?? { I wanted to protect the e5 pawn in order to push through with f5. } { [%clk 0:01:36] } (21. Nb5! Qc6 22. Nd6 f6 23. Rhf1 { A missed opportunity - the files remain closed for a little while longer, and my knight shelters the soon-to-be "weakness" on e5. }) 21... a3!! { A brilliant move that immediately punishes my last queen move. } { [%clk 0:02:51] } 22. f5? { [%clk 0:01:00] } (22. b3? Na4! 23. bxa4 Qc3 $19 { I saw this line and I realized why the queen was better placed on e3, not e2. The dark squares are more important than the "tempo" on the rook! }) (22. Nb5 Qa5 23. b3 { My last chance, but after Ne4, it's clear I'm lost. } 23... Ne4! $19 { [%cal Ge4c3,Ga5b5,Ge2b5] }) 22... axb2 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 23. Qb5 { Stopping Qa5 which would immediately mate me. Regardless, black is breaking through first. } { [%clk 0:00:24] } 23... Rxa2! { [%clk 0:02:17] } 24. Kxa2 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 24... Qa7+ { [%clk 0:02:17] } 25. Kxb2 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 25... Qa3+ { [%clk 0:02:18] } 26. Kb1 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 26... Ra8 { [%clk 0:02:14] } 27. Nb3 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 27... Ne4?? { [%clk 0:02:14] } (27... Nxb3 28. cxb3 Qxb3+ 29. Kc1 Qc3+ 30. Kb1 Ra1# { I saw this line, but what else could I do? }) 28. Rd3 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 28... Nc3+ { [%clk 0:02:15] } 29. Rxc3 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 29... bxc3 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 30. fxe6?? { Pre-moved. I still thought the only available check was Qa2+... } { [%clk 0:00:09] } (30. Na5! { An amazing defense that I missed with a few seconds left on my clock. Amazingly, white can hold! } 30... Rxa5 (30... Qxa5 31. Qxa5 Rxa5 $15) 31. Qb8+ Qf8 32. Qxf8+ Kxf8 33. fxg6 fxg6 34. g5 $15 { Black is only up a pawn in this rook endgame, and my "unsafe king" is now totally fine with only a single rook left on the board. }) 30... Qb2# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:02:16] } 0-1


