1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:03:06] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 0:03:09] } 3... d5 { [%clk 0:03:11] } 4. g3 { [%clk 0:03:14] } 4... Be7 { [%clk 0:03:17] } 5. Bg2 { [%clk 0:03:20] } 5... O-O { [%clk 0:03:23] } 6. O-O { [%clk 0:03:27] } 6... dxc4 { [%clk 0:03:28] } 7. Qc2 { [%clk 0:03:29] } 7... a6 { [%clk 0:03:34] } 8. a4 { [%clk 0:03:35] } 8... Bd7 { [%clk 0:03:40] } 9. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:03:39] } 9... Bc6 { A reprisal of this line from my game with Jesse, just one week later! } { [%clk 0:03:45] } 10. Bg5 { The "old" main move. } { [%clk 0:03:44] } 10... Bd5 { [%clk 0:03:48] } 11. Qc2 { [%clk 0:03:50] } 11... Be4 { [%clk 0:03:52] } 12. Qc1 { [%clk 0:03:55] } (12. Qc4?! Nc6 { Black is not obliged to repeat: } 13. Nc3 Na5! $15) 12... h6 { [%clk 0:03:34] } 13. Bxf6 { [%clk 0:04:00] } 13... Bxf6 { [%clk 0:03:40] } 14. Nc3 { [%clk 0:04:01] } 14... Bxf3 { [%clk 0:03:41] } 15. Bxf3 { [%clk 0:04:08] } 15... c6 { Following along with Bareev-Anand, 2000. I knew this was reasonably fine because the extra tempo on the d4 pawn means I have time to get the pawn structure I want with a5. } { [%clk 0:03:47] } 16. Rd1 { [%clk 0:04:12] } 16... a5! { The b4 square is black's forever. This was the end of any prep I had. } { [%csl Gb4] [%clk 0:03:51] } 17. Qf4 { [%clk 0:04:04] } 17... Na6 { [%clk 0:03:31] } 18. h4 { [%clk 0:04:04] } 18... Nb4 { [%clk 0:03:33] } 19. e3 { [%clk 0:03:57] } 19... Qe7 { [%clk 0:02:58] } (19... Be7!?) 20. Rac1 { [%clk 0:02:38] } (20. Ne4!? { A try for an advantage, but white just doesn't have enough here with their bishop biting on granite on the queenside. } 20... Nd5 21. Qg4 (21. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $10) 21... g6 22. Nxf6+ Qxf6 23. h5 g5 $10) 20... Rfd8 { [%clk 0:02:29] } 21. h5 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 21... e5! $10 { With the central pawn break achieved, it's clear that black is now completely fine. } { [%clk 0:02:07] } 22. Qf5?! { [%clk 0:02:15] } (22. dxe5 Bxe5 23. Qe4 $10) 22... exd4 { [%clk 0:02:10] } 23. exd4 { [%clk 0:02:06] } 23... Qd7! { [%clk 0:01:10] } (23... Rxd4? 24. Be4! $16 { I saw the threats on the kingside due to the advanced h5 pawn, and didn't want anything to do with this. }) (23... Bxd4!? 24. Be4 Qf6 25. Qh7+ Kf8 $10 { Apparently this is equal, but I was not convinced. }) 24. Qxd7 { Basically forced. Black should have the better of it in this endgame because of the IQP. } { [%clk 0:00:28] } (24. Qb1?? Bg5! $17 { [%csl Gc2,Gc1][%cal Gg5c1,Gb4c2] }) 24... Rxd7 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 25. Bg4?? { [%clk 0:00:35] } (25. Ne4 Be7 26. Bg4 Rdd8 $10 { This was Gauri's idea, but he said on stream he mixed up his move order. } (26... Rd5 $10)) 25... Rxd4 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 26. Bf5 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 26... Rad8 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 27. Kg2 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 27... Rd2!? { [%clk 0:00:35] } (27... Nd3! { The revenge of the octopus knight. I need to learn to watch out for this move as it literally hits everything. }) 28. Rxd2 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 28... Rxd2 { Up a pawn, and with more active pieces, it's clear that I should be borderline winning now. } { [%cal Gd2b2,Gd2f2] [%clk 0:00:42] } 29. Ne4 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 29... Rxb2 { [%clk 0:00:30] } 30. Nxf6+ { [%clk 0:00:12] } 30... gxf6 { [%clk 0:00:37] } 31. Re1 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 31... Kf8 { Stopping any rook penetration. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge1e7] [%clk 0:00:35] } 32. Bd7 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 32... Nd3! { Finally I find Nd3! f2 cannot be defended unless white essentially gives up with Rf1. } { [%cal Gd3f2,Gb2f2] [%clk 0:00:27] } 33. Re8+ { [%clk 0:00:21] } 33... Kg7 { [%clk 0:00:33] } 34. Re7 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 34... Rxf2+ { [%clk 0:00:34] } 35. Kg1 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 35... Rf3 { [%cal Gf3g3] [%clk 0:00:29] } 36. Kg2 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 36... Rf2+ { Always repeat. } { [%clk 0:00:32] } 37. Kg1 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 37... Rb2! { It took me a while to find this regrouping. The knight on e5 will defend f7, while the rook on b2 defends b7. } { [%clk 0:00:29] } 38. Bc8 { [%clk 0:00:19] } (38. Be6 Ne5 $19 { [%cal Ge5f7] }) 38... Ne5 { [%clk 0:00:26] } (38... b5!? { The alternative didn't seem so appealing to me because his rook gets even more active: } 39. Ra7 bxa4 40. Rxa5 Ra2 $19 { But this construction cannot be disturbed. }) 39. Bxb7 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 39... c5 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 40. Rc7 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 40... c4 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 41. Kf1 { [%clk 0:00:15] } (41. Rc5?? Rxb7 $19) 41... Rb4 { [%cal Gb4c4,Gb4a4] [%clk 0:00:21] } 42. Ke2 { [%clk 0:00:09] } (42. Bc6!? { [%cal Gc6a4] } 42... Nxc6 43. Rxc6 Rxa4 44. Rc5 Ra3 45. Rxc4 Rxg3 46. Ra4 Rg5 $19 { This rook endgame is probably white's best. But there's just no way that I shouldn't convert this. }) 42... Rxa4 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 43. Bd5 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 43... Rb4 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 44. g4 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 44... a4 { [%clk 0:00:12] } 45. Kd2 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 45... a3 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 46. Ra7 { [%clk 0:00:23] } 46... Rb3 { Finally, Gauri misses my threats after a long task of helplessly defending these passed pawns. } { [%clk 0:00:17] } 47. Ra4?? { [%clk 0:00:12] } (47. Kc2 Rg3 48. Ra4 Rxg4 49. Rxa3 f5 $19 { The way forward. Black can walk their king up the board and now promote these 3 "connected" pawns on the kingside. } { [%cal Gg7f6,Gf6g5,Gg5h5] }) 47... Rd3+ { [%clk 0:00:22] } 48. Kc2 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 48... Rxd5 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 49. Rxa3 { 0-1 White resigns. } { [%clk 0:00:24] } 0-1


