1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 3... Bb4 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 4. Qc2 { [%clk 0:02:56] } 4... O-O { [%clk 0:02:57] } 5. Nf3 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 5... c5 { [%clk 0:02:55] } 6. dxc5 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 6... Na6 { [%clk 0:02:54] } 7. g3 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 7... Nxc5 { [%clk 0:02:51] } 8. Bg2 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 8... Nce4 { [%clk 0:02:41] } 9. O-O { [%clk 0:02:51] } 9... Nxc3 { [%clk 0:02:40] } (9... Bxc3 { pd159's recommendation } 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. Nd4 (11. Bf4 d6 12. Nd4 e5 13. Bxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Qxc4) 11... d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Bf4 Qc5 14. Rac1 Bd7) 10. bxc3 { [%clk 0:02:51] } 10... Be7 { [%clk 0:02:39] } 11. e4 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 11... d6 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 12. e5 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 12... dxe5 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 13. Nxe5 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 13... Qc7 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 14. Qe2 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 14... Bd6 { [%clk 0:02:20] } (14... Nd7 { A slightly more accurate defense. Black shouldn't have any problems here. } 15. Bf4 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bd6 $10 { Topalov, V. - Dominguez Perez, L., 1/2-1/2, Champions Showdown Blitz, 2019, https://lichess.org/1kvY7VFk }) 15. Bf4 { All theory until here, and I knew it gets tricky, but black should be equal with best play. } { [%clk 0:02:40] } 15... Nd7 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 16. Rfe1 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 16... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:02:16] } 17. Bxe5 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 17... Bxe5 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 18. Qxe5 { [%clk 0:02:13] } 18... Qxc4 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 19. Red1 { [%clk 0:02:08] } 19... a5 { I also vaguely remembered this position, but I have two major issues: (1) I can't develop my bishop and (2) there's no way to control the dark squares e5, d6, c7, e7. } { [%clk 0:01:55] } 20. a3 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 20... f6 { Heading in the right direction: to take control of the dark squares. } { [%clk 0:01:41] } 21. Qd6 { [%clk 0:01:56] } 21... Ra6?? { I thought this was nice to further take control of the d6 square. But when the queen infiltrates on e7, it's immediately lights out. } { [%clk 0:01:29] } (21... Re8! { Stopping Qe7 is crucial. } 22. Rab1 h6 23. Bxb7 Bxb7 24. Rxb7 Qxc3 25. Qd7 f5 { [%cal Bc3g7] } 26. Qf7+ Kh8 27. Rdd7 Reb8! 28. Qxg7+ Qxg7 29. Rxg7 Rxb7 30. Rxb7 Kg8 $10 { A very tough defense to find, and the resulting position still has potential winning chances for white. This is the type of position that makes me think that the Dominguez game is a better defense. }) 22. Qe7! { Black is already busted. There's no satisfactory response to Rd8 or Bd5. } { [%clk 0:01:55] } 22... Rc6 { The best move, but it's hopeless. } { [%clk 0:00:19] } 23. Bxc6 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 23... Qxc6 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 24. Rd8 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 24... Rxd8 { [%clk 0:00:18] } 25. Qxd8+ { [%clk 0:00:47] } 25... Kf7 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 26. Qxa5?? { Amazingly, this natural move, blunders away the advantage. } { [%clk 0:00:38] } 26... e5?? { [%clk 0:00:14] } (26... b5!! { Now white's queen is trapped in Siberia and after Bb7, it's black that has the better coordination! } 27. Re1 Bb7 28. Kf1 Qc4+ 29. Kg1 Qc6 $10) 27. Rd1 { [%clk 0:00:31] } 27... Bh3?? { [%clk 0:00:05] } (27... b5?! { This same idea is now one move too late. } 28. Qd8 Bb7 29. Qd7+ Kg6 30. Qxc6 Bxc6 $19) (27... Be6 { The only move to fight on: stopping the queen trade. } 28. Qd8 Qxc3 $18 { But white should still be able to convert this. }) 28. Qd5+ { [%clk 0:00:28] } 28... Qxd5 { [%clk 0:00:03] } 29. Rxd5 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 29... Ke7 { [%clk 0:00:01] } 30. Rb5 { [%clk 0:00:26] } 30... Bc8 { [%clk 0:00:01] } 31. f4 $18 { 1-0 White wins on time. } { I lost on time because I forgot it was 3+0, but even so the position was hopeless. } { [%clk 0:00:25] } 1-0


