1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 (4... c5 5. Ne2 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. a3 Be7) 5. Ne2 Ne4!? 6. f3!? Nxc3 7. bxc3 Be7 8. e4 (8. Ng3 { Shirov, Alexei - Adams, Michael, 1-0, Las Palmas, 1994, https://lichess.org/yxI7bsMy } 8... Nc6 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. O-O Na5 11. Qe2 c6 12. f4 d5 13. cxd5 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 exd5 15. Kh1 (15. f5 h5) 15... Nc4 16. e4) 8... Nc6 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc6a5,Gc8a6] } 9. Ng3 Ba6 10. Bd3 Na5 11. Qe2 d6 12. O-O Qd7 (12... h5?! 13. f4 h4 14. Nh5 g6 15. Ng7+ Kf8 16. Nxe6+ fxe6 17. f5 Kg7 (17... exf5 18. exf5 Bf6 19. Bg5 Kg7 (19... Bxg5 20. fxg6+ Bf6 21. Qe6 $18 { [%csl Gf7,Gf6] }) 20. Bxf6+ Qxf6 21. fxg6)) 13. Rb1?! (13. f4! Qa4 14. f5 Bxc4 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Nh5 Rg8 17. Nf4 O-O-O 18. Nxe6! Bxe6 19. Bb5 Bc4 20. Qg4+ $18) 13... h5! 14. Re1?! { Sokolov: In the game I
definitely saw the possibilities associated with 13. f4!, but
playing White against some under-2500 Australian guy, I
thought 'regular' moves should suffice, and the win should
arrive without any risks involved. This is perhaps a
reasonable way of thinking when you play some Catalan line
with white, but not in this type of Nimzo. White is about to
learn this lesson soon. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gg3f1,Gf1e1] } (14. f4 h4 15. Nh5 g6 16. Ng7+ Kf8 17. Nxe6+ Qxe6 18. d5 Qd7 (18... Qf6 19. e5 Qg7 20. Be3 dxe5 (20... f5 21. Bd4 Re8) 21. fxe5 Qxe5 22. Bh6+ { [%cal Ge2e5] }) 19. f5 gxf5 20. Rxf5) 14... h4 15. Nf1 c5 $15 16. Be3 Rc8 17. Nd2 e5 18. f4 (18. d5 Qa4 19. f4 Bf6 20. f5) 18... Bf6 19. dxe5 (19. Nf3 h3 (19... cxd4 20. cxd4 exd4 21. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 22. Nxd4 $16)) 19... dxe5 20. Nf3 Qe6 21. fxe5 Be7! { Sokolov: Looking at my horrible pawn structure and slowly
becoming aware of the long and difficult defence that lay
ahead, I could not help but wonder abut the speed of my
positional collapse: in a mere 20 moves, playing White against
an opponent I had never heard of and not having made any clear
mistake - except that my whole concept was a positional
blunder } { [%cal Ga5c6,Gc6e5] } 22. Rf1 Bxc4 23. Bg5 Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Nc6 25. Bxe7 Qxe7 26. Rbd1 O-O 27. Qd7 Qxd7 28. Rxd7 h3 29. gxh3 Rce8 30. Kg2 Nxe5 31. Rxa7 Nc4 32. Rf2 Rxe4 33. Ng5 Re5 34. Nxf7 Ne3+ 35. Kg3 Rf5 36. Re2 Nf1+ 37. Kg2 R8xf7 38. Rxf7 Kxf7 39. Kg1 Kf6 40. Kg2 b5 41. Kg1 c4 42. Kg2 Kg5 43. Kg1 Kh4 44. Kg2 Rf4 45. a3 g6 { Sokolov: And White resigned. A painful defeat and a
positional lesson that I have taken to heart } 0-1


