1. e4 e6 2. c4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] } 6... Bg4 7. Qa4+ Bd7 8. Qe4+ Be6 (8... Qe7 { So many different pins make this the tactical solution. } { [%cal Ge7e1,Gd5e7] } 9. Qxe7+ Nxe7) 9. Nd4 Nxc3 10. dxc3 Qd5 11. Bd3! { White keeps winning the tempo battle. Every developing move comes with a threat. If the queens are traded then b7 comes under fire. } 11... Be7 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. O-O Qxe4 14. Bxe4 c6 15. Re1 Nd7 16. Bf3 Kf7 17. Bg4 Rhd8 (17... Nc5! 18. b4 h5 19. Bh3 Nd3 20. Bxe6+ Kf8 21. Re3 Nxc1 22. Rxc1 Rd8 { While this is a cramped position, the presence of the opposite colored bishops makes this seem reasonably drawable as black. This sequence was much stronger than what happens. }) 18. Bxe6+ Kf6 19. h4 h6 20. Bf4 Nf8 21. Bb3 Bd6 22. Be3 c5 23. Rad1 Be7 24. Bf4 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. Be3 Rxd1+ 27. Bxd1 { Successfully trading bishops, black's plan now is to trade his knight for the light squared bishop - reaching a drawn end game. } 27... Ng6 28. g3 Ne5 29. Be2 b6 30. Kg2 Bd6 31. f3 Kf5 32. g4+ Ke6 33. f4 Nc6 34. Bc4+ Kf6 { Now that black has been pushed back repeatedly, the only thing left for white to do is to push through a passed pawn on the kingside. } 35. Kf3 Na5?? { Allowing white to trap the knight with Bd5! I had only seen Bb5 in response where after Nb7-d8-e6, the knight returns to play on the kingside. } 36. Bd5 *


