1. e4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 Bd6 5. Bd3 Ne7 6. O-O Bf5 (6... O-O 7. Bxh7+ Kxh7 8. Ng5+ Kg8 9. Qh5 Bf5) 7. Bg5 f6 8. Bh4 O-O { We had played several drawn exchange French games, so white decided to mix it up and play for a win. } 9. c4 dxc4 10. Bxc4+ Kh8 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. fxg3 Qd7 13. Nc3 c6 14. Qb3 a5 15. a4? { Giving up the b4 square ends up being a mistake because the knight landing on b4 becomes an shuts down almost all queenside play. } 15... Na6 16. Rad1 Nb4 17. Rd2 (17. Nh4 Bc2 { The first iteration of this game }) 17... Rad8 { Trying to get control of this isolated pawn and play Ned5 with a perfect blockade. } 18. h3 h6 19. Nh4 Bh7 (19... Bc2!? 20. Rxc2 Nxc2 21. Qxc2 Qxd4+ 22. Kh2 Qxc4 { Winning the piece back ensures that this line is good for black. }) 20. Be6 Bg8!! { Counter-pin on the queen. Bg8 prevents white from taking over the light squares around black's king. } 21. Bxg8 Rxg8 22. Re1 Ned5 23. Qd1 { The most active try for counterplay. Without any kingside attack attempt, white will have to sit back and watch as black builds up pressure on the weakened queenside pawns. } 23... Rge8 24. Rxe8+ Rxe8 25. Qh5 Re1+ 26. Kh2 Ne3! { A beautiful move. Even with white's kingside attack raging, Nf1 is unavoidable. } 27. Rf2 Nf1+ 28. Rxf1 Rxf1 29. Ne4 Nd5?? { Doesn't give enough weight to Nc5 - forcing the queen away from the light squares around black's king. } (29... Qe6! 30. Nc5 Qe1 31. Ng6+ Kh7 32. Nf8+ Kg8 33. Qf7+ Kxf7 34. h4 Rh1# { The direct line that shows black's advantage. }) 30. Nc5 (30. Nd6 Qxd6 31. Qe8+ Kh7 32. Qg6+ Kg8 33. Qe8+ Qf8 34. Qe6+ Qf7 35. Qc8+ Kh7 { The initial try by white to get a draw. White missed Qf8 defending the perpetual. }) 30... Nf4!! { The only saving move. Sacking the knight allows black to enter with his queen. A perpetual is white's best try now. } 31. gxf4 Qxd4 32. Qe8+ Kh7 33. Qg6+ Kg8 34. Qe8+ Kh7 35. Qg6+ *


