1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 O-O 5. Nf3 b6 6. e3 Bb7 7. Be2 c5 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 d6 11. Bd3 f5 12. dxc5 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 dxc5 14. Rg1 Qf6 15. Ne5 Nc6 16. Nxc6 Qxc3+ 17. bxc3 Bxc6 18. Ke2 Rad8 19. Bc2 Rd7 20. Rgd1 Rfd8 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. g3 Kf7 23. f4?! Kf6 24. a4 Rd6 (24... a5 25. Rb1 Rd6! { Active defends of b6. Allows black to push through on the kingside with h6-g5 and maybe even e5. }) 25. a5 b5!? { The most active try to prove that black has the advantage. } 26. Bd3 b4! 27. cxb4 cxb4 28. Rb1 (28. c5 Rd5 29. Rc1 b3 30. e4 (30. Ba6!? { The idea is to sit and wait. If black can't make progress in some tangible way, white is happy to take a draw. } 30... e5 31. Ke1 h6 32. Rb1 Rxc5 33. Rxb3 Rxa5 34. Be2) 30... b2! 31. e5+ Ke7 32. Rb1 Rxd3 33. Rxb2 Ra3 { This was the second attempt by white. The same tactic comes up again, even in a different position. }) 28... Rxd3! { White cannot take back because Be4+ wins a full piece. } 29. Rxb4 Ra3 *


