1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bd3 Bb4 8. Qd2 (8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qxc3 10. e5 Nd5 11. Qg4) 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nc6 10. h3? { A weak move that is aimed at expanding with f4. It is misguided because black's d5 strike in the center hits much too quickly. } 10... d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bh4 Ne5 15. Bg3 { Realizing the idea behind Bg5. The bishop is much better placed on g3 than on e3. } 15... Nxc3 16. Rfe1 Rd8 17. Qf4 (17. Rxe5 fxe5 18. Re1!! Rd5 19. Nf3 Bd7 20. Bxe5 Rxe5 21. Rxe5 { White wins the pawn back and has the better bishop in a very interesting endgame. }) 17... Nd5 18. Qh4 g6 19. c4! { While not necessarily best, c4 ensures that black's kingside will be ripped open. } (19. Bxe5!? fxe5 20. Nf3 Qe7 21. Qg3 Qf6 22. Re4 { And the attack continues with the c8 bishop never able to enter the defense }) 19... Nb4 20. Bxg6 hxg6 (20... Rxd4! { A very interesting try to keep the position alive. White would have to find Qxf6 to keep the advantage. } 21. Qxd4 (21. Bxh7+ Qxh7 22. Qxd4 Nbc6) 21... hxg6 22. Bxe5 fxe5 23. Qxe5 Qxe5 24. Rxe5 Kf7) 21. Qxf6! { The knight on d4 is immune from capture because of Bxe5. The white pieces will swarm in unless Rf8 is played. } 21... Rf8 22. Qxe5 Qxc4?? { Black falters under the pressure. } (22... Qxe5 23. Rxe5 { And white is up a pawn with the much more active pieces. }) 23. Rac1 Nd3?? 24. Rxc4 (24. Qe4 Qd5 25. Qxg6+ Kh8 26. Rc7 { A quick mate follows. }) 24... Nxe5 25. Bxe5 Bd7 26. Rc7 Rad8 27. Rxb7 Bc8 28. Rg7+ Kh8 29. Re4 Rxd4 30. Rxd4 { And black resigned before mate was delivered. } *


