1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Nf6 6. d3 d6 7. c3 Bg4 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. h3 Be6 10. Nf1?! { As white, I need to be more proactive about striking first in the center. I'm too happy to play Nf1-g3 every Ruy Lopez before attempting to open it up. But now black is the one who strikes first! } 10... d5 11. Ng3 dxe4?! { Surely maintaining the tension benefits black. } 12. dxe4 Qxd1+ 13. Bxd1 O-O 14. O-O Rad8 15. Be3 (15. Bc2 { The move I wanted to play. Somehow I mixed up the lines in my head and played Be3 first. }) 15... Bc4 16. Re1 Bd3 17. Bd2 { While very awkward, thankfully this move holds the pawns together. Rc1, Bc2 next and white should be doing alright again. } 17... Rd7 18. Rc1 Bc4!? 19. b3!? Ba3 20. bxc4 Rxd2 21. Rb1 Rxa2 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Rxb5 Bd6 24. Bb3 Ra3 25. Rc1 { White has activity, but I was fearful that none of my pieces have stable squares to work with. The game has opened up and become quite tactical when black is slightly more stable. } 25... g6 26. Nd2 { Going for the stable c4 square. } 26... Na5 27. Bd1 Rd8 28. Kf1 Nd7 (28... Bf8 29. Rc2 Ra1 30. Ke2 Bh6 { The positioning of the white pieces here looks very suspect. }) 29. Nf3 Bf8 30. Nxe5 Nxe5 (30... c6 31. Rxa5 Rxa5 32. Nxc6 { I saw that this deflection tactic did not work out well for black. }) 31. Rxe5 Bd6 (31... c6!! 32. Be2 f6 33. Re6 Kf7 { And the rook is completely trapped }) 32. Rd5 Re8 33. Bf3 Bf4 34. Rcd1 { And finally, the white pieces are coordinated effectively. I disagree with the evaluation here. But white immediately goes astray... } 34... c6 35. Rc5?! { I saw that the rook couldn't be trapped with Bd6, but missed the idea of Bc7-b6! } (35. R5d3 Nc4 { I analyzed this line and didn't like Ne5 here shutting down any hopes of activity. }) 35... Bc7! 36. e5!? { Trying to at least take down another pawn before giving up the exchange. } 36... Bb6 37. Bxc6 Re6 38. Bd5 (38. Rxa5 Bxa5 39. Bd5 { My initial plan, but I didn't like how I lose the e pawn in this line. So instead of giving up the exchange, I gave up a piece. }) 38... Bxc5 39. Bxe6 fxe6 40. Ne4 { 2 pawns is not enough for the exchange, but I was banking on the activity of my knight and rook on d7 and d6 or f6 to give me some chances. } 40... Bb6? { Giving up an immediate perpetual. Nf6+ wasn't played because I thought the king could escape to h6. But indeed he cannot. } 41. Rd7 (41. Nf6+ Kg7 42. Rd7+ Kh6 43. h4 g5 44. h5 g4 45. Rxh7+ Kg5 46. g3 { And white is the one who's ahead in this line! }) 41... Ra1+ 42. Ke2 Ra2+ 43. Kf3?? { Satisfied with the inevitable perpetual, I went to the square that I thought was safest from checks. But precision is needed. } 43... Nc4? { Thankfully, black missed the save. } (43... Kf8!! 44. Kg4 (44. Kg3) (44. Kf4 Nc4) 44... Nc4 45. Nf6) 44. Nf6+ { And a draw was agreed. The game could have ended as follows. } 44... Kf8 45. Nxh7+ Ke8 46. Nf6+ Kf8 47. Nh7+ Ke8 48. Nf6+ *


