1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. O-O Bd7 5. Re1 a6 6. Bf1!? { Trying something new in the Steinitz. I'm going to fianchetto my kingside bishop and go for a KIA-like setup. } 6... Nf6 7. g3 Bg4 8. c3?! { The right idea: building the center and stopping Nd4. But it's too slow. d5! hits immediately. } 8... Be7 (8... d5 { Striking in the center before white's pieces get coordinated. } 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Bg2 e4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3) 9. Bg2 O-O 10. d4 b5 11. d5 Na7!? (11... Na5 12. Nbd2 Rb8 13. b4 Nb7 14. a4 { This was what I was analyzing. Na7 surprised me. }) 12. b3 { With the idea of supporting my pawn chain from any c6 breaks. } 12... c6 13. c4 c5?! { Releasing pressure on my center and clogging up the c5 square cannot be correct. Now I simply have to stop b4-a4 breaks. } 14. Qd3 Qa5 15. Bd2 b4 16. h3 Bh5 17. a4! { Cannot take en passant which means the kingside (where all my initial aspirations and current pieces are) is where the remaining action will take. Note how the knight cannot easily get to a5 to pressure my b3 base pawn. } 17... Qc7 18. Nh2 Qd7 19. f4 exf4 20. gxf4 h6 21. e5 dxe5 22. fxe5 { Pushing through with a very scary attack. } 22... Ne8 (22... Nc6 { I saw this idea only one move later. }) 23. Qg3 f6? 24. Bxh6 Bg4?? { Presumably trying to block up the g file so that gxh6 is possible. But it fails to Nxg4! } 25. Nxg4 fxe5 (25... gxh6 26. Nxf6+ Kh8 27. Nxd7 { And the double check wins the black queen. }) 26. d6! { Opening up lines further (the a1-g8 diagonal towards the king and the h1-a8 diagonal towards the rook). } 26... Bxd6 (26... Nxd6 27. Bd5+ Kh7 28. Nxe5 { What I was expecting. }) 27. Bxa8 e4 28. Qg2 Rf3 29. Rxe4 Rxb3 30. Rxe8+! Qxe8 31. Nf6+ Kf7 32. Nxe8 Kxe8 { And tactics based on the open g file finish off the black king. } *


