1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 4. c3 { [%cal Gg8f6] } 4... Nge7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4 8. Nc3 (8. a3 Ba5 9. d5!) 8... d5 { We had previously played a game in this line and I liked the resultant game for white. But this was perhaps not best play to take advantage of a slightly different move order. } 9. e5 Bg4 10. Be3 Nf5 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. a3?! Be7 13. b4?? { [%cal Gf5h4] } 13... Nxe3?? { After mutual blunders we're back to an even game. } (13... Nh4! { Taking advantage of the pin, and completely winning. }) 14. fxe3 f6!? { Breaking down the center is the correct idea, and c5 is already ruled out. } 15. Qd3 Qc8 16. e4! { Give my c3 knight activity now! } 16... dxe4 17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Qc4+ { [%csl Gc8] } 18... Be6 (18... Qe6 19. Qxe6+ Bxe6 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Nxf6+ Rxf6 22. Ne5 { The variation I calculated. White ends up with a strong knight vs a bad (but active!) bishop. But perhaps it's not enough to win. }) 19. Qxc6 Rd8 20. Rac1!? { Ignoring the fork on d5 and focusing on the weaknesses in black's camp instead. } 20... Bd5 21. Qxc7 Qe6 { [%cal Ge4c5,Gd8c8,Ge6f7] } (21... Qxc7 22. Rxc7 Bxb4 23. Nxf6+ gxf6 24. axb4 { And white remains comfortably ahead. }) 22. exf6!! { I had missed Qe6, but I found the strongest reply: exf6! Although the knight on e4 is doubly hanging, the threats on e7 and/or g7 prevent it from being captured, and its influence on f6 is certainly felt. } 22... gxf6 (22... Bxf6 23. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { The natural variation leads to a very strong position for white. }) 23. Qg3+ (23. Nc5?? Qe3+ 24. Kh1 Bd6 { And the queen is trapped. } 25. Qa5) 23... Kh8 24. Nc5 Qe3+ 25. Kh1 Bd6? { Although it looks natural and good, undefending f6 ends up being crucial. } 26. Qh4 { [%csl Gf6] } 26... Kg7?! { The king isn't the defender you want on f6. } 27. Rce1 { [%cal Ge3h6] } 27... Qxa3 (27... Qh6 28. Qxh6+ Kxh6 29. Nh4 { The last try to avoid catastrophe. Even though the queens are traded, white is clearly superior due to the piece activity and extra pawns. }) 28. Ne5!! (28. Ng5 { The fastest win. } 28... fxg5 (28... Rh8 29. Nge6+ Bxe6 30. Qxf6+ Kg8 31. Qg5#) 29. Qxg5+ Kh8 30. Qf6+ Kg8 31. Rf5) 28... fxe5 (28... Rf8!? 29. Rf3!! Bxf3 (29... fxe5 { [%cal Gf3a3] } 30. Rxa3) 30. Ne6+ Kh8 31. Qh6 Bxg2+ 32. Kg1 Rf7 33. Nxf7+ Kg8 34. Qg7#) 29. Qf6+ Kg8 30. Rf5 { [%cal Gh7h6] } 30... Bxg2+ (30... h6 31. Qxh6 (31. Qg6+ Kh8 32. Qxh6+ Kg8 33. Qg6+ Kh8 34. Rh5#)) 31. Kg1! { There is not a single check on the white king and Rg5+ or Qg6+ are unavoidable. } 31... Qd3 (31... Be4 32. Nxe4) (31... h6 32. Qg6+ Kh8 33. Qxh6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ Kh8 35. Rh5# { The initial try I thought black had to stay in the game before I sacked the knight was h6. But I had missed Qg6+ leading to a mate in 4. }) 32. Nxd3 Be4 33. Rxe4 h6 34. Rg4+ Kh7 35. Qg7# *


