1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 Bd6 5. Nc3 c6 6. Bd3 Ne7 7. Bg5 f6 8. Bd2 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Bxf5 Nxf5 11. Re1 Qc7 12. Ne2 Nd7 13. c3 Nb6 14. b3 a5 15. h3 (15. Qc2 g6 16. Ng3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 { It looks a little airy around my king, but this is what I had prepared against Qc2. }) 15... a4 16. g3 Rfe8 (16... Nxg3 17. fxg3 Bxg3 18. Nxg3 Qxg3+ 19. Kf1 { I was analyzing this position and couldn't find the win. Once I saw there were no more kingside pieces left to continue an attack, I gave up on the sacrifice. } 19... axb3!! { And white cannot recapture because otherwise the f3 knight falls. } 20. Rb1 bxa2 21. Rxb6 a1=Q 22. Qxa1 Qxf3+ 23. Kg1 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Qg3+ 25. Kf1 Qxh3+ 26. Kg1 $17) 17. Bf4 Bxf4 18. Nxf4 Nd6 { Rerouting to the juicy e4 outpost. } 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. bxa4?! { Giving up the c4 square should not be worthwhile. } 20... Ne4 21. Ne2 Ra8 22. Nd2 Nxd2 23. Qxd2 Rxa4 24. Nf4 (24. Qf4 Qxf4 25. Nxf4 Nc4 26. Ne6 Ra3 { I figured I had enough here to win, even without the queens. }) 24... Nc4 25. Qe1 (25. Qc2 { I had mainly considered Qc2 instead. } 25... Ra3 26. Re1 Qd7) 25... Qd7 26. Ne6 b6 { Defending the important c5 square. Doesn't allow white to find as nice an outpost for his knight as mine. } 27. Rb1? { Somehow white missed that Rxb6 and/or Nc5 shenanigans never amount to anything. } 27... Rxa2 28. Nc7?? (28. Rxb6 Nxb6 29. Nc5 Qf7 $17) (28. Nc5 bxc5 29. Rb8+ Kf7 30. Qb1 Ra7 $17) 28... Kf7! { Traps the knight. But black played this with the intention of Nd2 into f3. } 29. Ne6 Qxe6 30. Qxe6+ Kxe6 31. Re1+ Kd7 32. f3 Rc2 33. h4 Rxc3 34. Kh2 Rxf3 35. Kg2 Rd3 36. Kh3 Rxd4 37. g4 Rd3+ { White ran out of time, but this was a simple conversion at this point. } *


