1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. Bd3 Nbd7 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 e5 { Needed so as to avoid white from taking over the center. } 9. e4 Re8 { Continuing to pile pressure on e4 (after a possible exd4). } 10. Re1 b6 11. a4 Bb7 12. Qc2 h6 { Finally putting to rest any possible pin. I didn't think this was the best move, because Nh4-f5 possibilities and a4-a5 scared me, but I decided that the pin and activation of white's terrible dark squared bishop would be the hardest to deal with. } 13. Bb2?! { This move doesn't accomplish anything. } 13... a5 { Clamping down on the queenside. If I can stop white's c5 break (by provoking d5, for instance), then play will only be on the kingside. } 14. h3 Nh5 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gh5f4] } 15. Bc1 { [%cal Gc1f4] } 15... Nf8 { Maneuvering to get control of the f4 square. } (15... Qf6! { Ensures a piece will land on f4, by preventing g3 as well! }) 16. Rb1 Bc6 17. Nh2 Ng6 18. g3 Qd7!? 19. Ra1?? { The h pawn is much more important than the a pawn. } (19. d5!? Bxa4?! 20. Qa2 Nf6 21. Ra1 b5 { The bishop on a4 is so terribly placed that desperate measures must be called for. This looked so bad, I was more considering Bb7 in response to d5. }) 19... Qxh3 20. Nf1 Nf6 (20... Nhf4!! 21. gxf4 Nh4 22. f3 Nxf3+ 23. Kf2 Nh4!! 24. dxe5 dxe5 25. Re3 Qg2+ 26. Ke1 exf4) 21. Ne3 exd4 22. cxd4 Bxe4 23. Bxe4 Rxe4 24. Bb2 Rae8 25. d5 Ng4 (25... Nh4 26. gxh4 Rxh4 27. f3 Qh1+ 28. Kf2 Rh2+ 29. Kg3 Nh5+ 30. Kg4 Rh4+ 31. Kf5 g6#) 26. f3 Qxg3+ (26... Nh4 27. gxh4 Nxe3 28. Qf2 Rxh4) 27. Qg2 Qxg2+ 28. Nxg2 Rxe1+ 29. Nxe1 Ne3 *


