1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. b3 O-O (6... Bb4 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nf3 c5!! 9. dxc5 Ne4 10. Rc1 Qa5 11. Qc2 Re8 12. Be2 Qxa2 13. O-O Bxc3 14. Bxc3 Qxc2 15. Rxc2 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Rxe2 { And black just wins a piece. I saw the first few moves of the variation, but saw that I couldn't add more pressure to the pinned knight... completely missing c5! }) 7. Nf3 Re8 8. Be2 { I tried making the least committal moves of the variation just to see if I could probe for a more favorable exchange, but I missed my last chance to pull the trigger here. } 8... c6?! 9. O-O Bf5 10. Bb2 { This bishop isn't exactly on its dream diagonal. } 10... dxc4 11. bxc4 { I figured going into a hanging pawn-esque structure here would favor black, but it turns out I am just a little too cramped for space to justify it. dxc4 now is the correct time because it doesn't allow my Nbd7 move from blocking the all-important d5 square. } 11... Nbd7 12. h3 (12. d5? cxd5 13. cxd5 Nb6 (13... Qb6 14. Nb5 Bc5 15. a4 a6)) 12... Nb6 13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Bd6 15. Rfd1 (15. c5?? Bxc5 { The d pawn is pinned to the queen. }) 15... Bc7 16. Re1 Qd7 17. Rad1 Rad8 18. Bc1! { This beautiful repositioning move repurposes the poor bishop to a better diagonal. } 18... h6 19. Be3 Re6 { I felt that my pieces were on their optimal squares at this point. It was difficult for me to find an improvement for my pieces without allowing the all-important d5 break from crushing me. } 20. Ne2 Re7 { Avoids Nf4 with tempo. I didn't want to depart the d file just yet. } 21. Ng3?! { I thought Nf4 looked more natural. This allows me to trade off more pieces and reach an endgame where I continue to have pressure on the c and d pawns. } 21... Bxg3 22. fxg3 Rde8 23. Bf2 (23. Ne5 Qc8 24. Bf4 Nfd7 25. Qc3 Nxe5 26. Bxe5 { The variation I was most concerned about. It turns out to not be a bother though after... } 26... Qe6! { Who's pinning whom? }) 23... Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 (24. Bxe1!? { Keeping more pieces on the board is certainly worth a consideration by the side with the space advantage. }) 24... Rxe1+ 25. Bxe1 Qe6 26. Ne5? { Looks natural, but it is a mistake due to the text. } (26. c5?! { The computer suggestion. } 26... Nbd5 27. Ne5 Nd7 { And black must certainly be better because of the beautiful knight vs bad bishop ending. }) 26... Nfd7! { [%cal Ge1c3] } 27. Bc3 (27. Nxd7?? Qxe1+ 28. Kh2 Nxd7) 27... Nxe5 28. dxe5 Qxc4 { Wins the pawn and a tempo. White can now must keep the queens on the board to threaten perpetuals. } 29. Qd8+ Kh7 30. Be1 { There was no time for Qc7 targeting the 7th rank because of the pressure on the bishop. } 30... Qc5+ 31. Bf2 Qxe5 32. Qd3+ (32. Bxb6 axb6 33. Qxb6 Qe1+ 34. Kh2 Qe7 { I was happy to play this ending because my queen activity, pawn structure, and pawn advantage should be enough to win. }) 32... f5! { Black must block the diagonal for good. } 33. g4!? Qe4 34. Qa3 fxg4 35. Qxa7 gxh3 36. gxh3 (36. Qxb6?? Qxg2#) 36... Qb1+ 37. Kh2 Nd5 38. Qd4 Qf5 { My queen stays on the all-important diagonal, and cannot be kicked from its central perch. } 39. Be3? (39. Bg3!? Nf6 40. a4 c5 { This alternative will be similar to the game but with an extra piece on the board, white has slightly better chances. }) 39... Nxe3 (39... c5!! 40. Qxc5 (40. Qd2 Qe5+ 41. Kg1 Qxe3+ 42. Qxe3 Nxe3) 40... Qe5+ 41. Kg1 Qxe3+ 42. Qxe3 Nxe3 { The only tactical sequence I missed in the game. }) 40. Qxe3 c5 41. a4 c4 42. a5 Qd3 { And the queen can escort the d pawn forward. } 43. Qb6 (43. Qe5!? c3 44. h4 c2 45. Qf4 h5!! { And white is in zugzwang! } 46. Kg2 Qe2+ 47. Kh3 (47. Kh1 Qe1+ 48. Kg2 c1=Q 49. Qf5+ Kh6) 47... Qg4+) 43... c3 44. Qxb7 c2 45. Qc6 Qd2+ 46. Kg3 Qe3+ 47. Kg2 c1=Q { Every checking square is covered, so white resigned. } *


