1. e4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3?! { Allowing an endgame that is roughly even, but still rich in possibilities for black. } 3... dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 Nf6 6. Nc3 { [%csl Ge4] } 6... Bg4 7. Be2 Nbd7 8. Bd2 O-O-O { Black's king will find a nice home on c7. } 9. Kc1 e5 { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gf4c7] } 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 Bg6 { After a sequence of poor moves, white now needed to tend to the weak e4 pawn. } 12. Rd1? (12. Bd3 Bc5 13. Rf1 Bd4! 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Ne2 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Nxd4 Rhe8 $17) 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bc3 f6 { Black achieves the idea pawn setup. Now, placing a knight on d5 or d4 will automatically lead to a good game, ignoring the fact that black is already up a pawn. } 15. Nh4 Bc5 (15... g6!? 16. f3 Bd5 { I didn't want to retreat like this, and instead tried to solve my issues tactically. But ultimately, this would have been the stronger attempt. }) 16. f3 Be3+ 17. Kb1 Bg6 { Covering Nc5 is important. } (17... Bf2?! 18. fxe4 Bxh4 { This was my original idea, but why would I trade off my best bishop and voluntarily misplace my bad bishop? }) 18. b3 Bf2 { Forcing a decision to be made with this knight before committing further on the queenside. } 19. Nf5 Bxf5 20. gxf5 g5! { Ensuring that black is not left with a backward g pawn. Taking en passant only activates black's pieces. } 21. Kb2 Nb6 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Rd1 Nd5 (23... Rxd1! 24. Bxd1 Bd4 25. Bxd4 exd4 { I wanted to leave the rooks on the board so that I had more opportunities to win this game, but it's clear that this would have been a textbook great knight vs a bad bishop endgame. }) 24. Bc4 Kc7 (24... Nxc3? 25. Rxd8+ Kxd8 26. Kxc3 { The opposite color bishop endgame looks to be drawn. }) 25. Bxd5 cxd5 { Now that there's no fear of opposite colored bishops, I was happy to freeze up the queenside before infiltrating and attacking the weak pawns on the kingside. } 26. Be1?? { Trading these bishops makes white's defensive task impossible. } 26... Bxe1 27. Rxe1 Kd6 28. Rd1 Rc8 29. c4 d4 { Black now acquires a protected passed pawn. } 30. Rd3 (30. h4 h6 { Black wants to open up a second flank. This way the weak f pawns can be targeted. }) 30... Kc5 31. a3 a5 { Stopping white from playing b4 and pushing his majority. } 32. Kc2 (32. a4 Kb4 { I initially thought this would be good for black, but underestimated that a file needs to be opened up in order to win this game. Therefore, Re8, aiming for e4 would be more immediate. }) 32... b5!! { Opening up a file for penetration. } 33. cxb5 Kxb5+ 34. Kb2 Rc5! { Zugzwang. Black will penetrate. } 35. Rd1 Rc3 36. Rf1 a4!! { Giving a passed pawn to white but allowing further (and decisive) penetration. } 37. b4 Rb3+ 38. Ka2 (38. Kc2 Rxa3 $19) 38... Kc4 39. Rc1+ Rc3 40. Rf1 (40. Rxc3+ Kxc3 41. b5 d3 42. b6 d2 43. b7 d1=Q 44. b8=Q Qd5+ 45. Ka1 Qb3 $19) 40... Kd3 { Black has made decisive penetration and will pick up the f3 pawn before marching the e and d pawns to victory. } 41. Kb2 Ke3 42. b5 Rb3+ 43. Kc2 Rxb5 { The rook isn't even inconvenienced here. } 44. h4 h6 45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Re1+ Kxf3 47. Rf1+ Ke2 48. Rd1 Rb2+ { Strong and good, but missed the better Rc5+. } (48... Rc5+ 49. Kb1 Kxd1) 49. Kxb2 Kxd1 *


