1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3?! { A passive opening that tries to immediately get out of any theory while simply getting a playable game. } 3... Nf6 4. b3 Bg4 { Developing the bishop is no problem now that b3 is played (so Qb3 is ruled out). But this pin isn't very annoying. A simple Bf5 puts the bishop on what appears to be a better diagonal. } 5. Bb2 e6 6. Be2 Nbd7 7. O-O Be7 (7... Bd6!? { I was envisioning an eventual d3-e4 push when I would have to watch out for e5 with a fork. }) 8. Ne5? { Why trade these sets of pieces? This only gets rid of black's worse knight and "bad" bishop for no gain. } 8... Nxe5 9. Bxe5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 O-O 11. f4?! { This was the point of the previous moves, but there will be no threats after f5 hits, so white's attack does not come to anything. } 11... a5 12. f5 exf5 13. Rxf5 Nd7?! { Black is too focused on trading off in order to avoid an attack that is simply not there. } (13... Qd7!? 14. Qf3 dxc4 15. bxc4 Qe6 { This line highlights white's lack of development and simultaneously keeps more pieces (and therefore play) on the board for black to claim an advantage. }) 14. Bb2 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. d4? (16. Nc3 { This was white's last chance to develop naturally, but even now it's too late. } 16... d4! 17. exd4 a4! 18. Nxa4?? Qxd4+ { [%cal Gd4a1] }) 16... a4! { Taking advantage of white's lack of development. } 17. Nd2 axb3 18. Nxb3 { The knight is poorly placed on b3 and in no way contributing to an attack. Now black can target white's backward e3 pawn. } 18... dxc4 19. Qxc4 Re8 20. Raf1 Rxe3 21. Nc5 (21. Rxf6? gxf6 { White's original plan goes nowhere. There's simply not enough pieces to try for any attack. }) 21... Qe7 (21... b5! { This move weakened the c6 pawn too much for my liking. But if I had seen 2 moves ahead, I would have seen that black is next taking on d4 with a huge advantage. } 22. Qc2 Qxd4) 22. Nd3 Re2!? (22... Qa3 23. Ne5 Qxa2 { With very real threats on my king now that I've voluntarily misplaced some defenders, I discounted the strength of this line. }) 23. a4 (23. Ne5? Raxa2 { My active rooks are much stronger than any of white's threats. }) (23. Re5! Rxe5 24. Nxe5 { The most accurate play by white. Black is still forced on the defensive, even though he is up a pawn. }) 23... Qe4! { The threats on g2 force more trades that only benefit black. } 24. R5f2 Rxf2 (24... Qe3 { [%cal Ge3g1] } 25. Kh1 Rxf2 26. Rxf2 Rd8 { The other line I was considering. }) 25. Rxf2 Qd5 (25... b5! { Breaking open the a file in order to get at the white king! } 26. axb5?? cxb5 27. Qxb5 Ng4) 26. Qb4 Ng4?? { Completely missing the threat on b7... } 27. Qxb7 (27. Rf4 Qe6 { The line I expected. I was only analyzing my own threats instead of considering my opponents' }) 27... Re8 28. Re2?? { A cute move but ultimately a blunder. White missed that Qxd4+ allows Qa1 in some lines, and black breaks through first. } (28. Rf4 h5 29. Ne5 Nxe5 30. dxe5 Rxe5 { The line I was envisioning. }) 28... Qxd4+ 29. Kf1 (29. Kh1 Qa1+ 30. Re1 Qxe1+ 31. Nxe1 Rxe1#) 29... Qxd3 { Here, white resigned. } 30. g3 Qxe2+ 31. Kg1 Qxh2+ 32. Kf1 Qf2# *


