1. d4 d6 2. c4 { Already possibly a step in the wrong direction. You kinda need to play the Pirc if you want a true advantage here. } 2... e5 3. d5?! { Releasing the tension gives black a good KID. } (3. Nf3 $10) (3. dxe5?! dxe5 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $15) 3... f5 { Claiming kingside space } 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bg5?! { Also probably not best to give up the bishop pair so quickly. But white's going for full light square control then. } (5. e4 fxe4) 5... Be7 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e4 { White gives up the good bishop in order to get a strong center. This now resembles a KID, but white is missing their dark squared (good) bishop. } 7... O-O 8. Nf3 (8. Bd3!?) (8. exf5?! Bxf5 9. Bd3 e4! $17) 8... Na6!? { Going for the strong c5 square and preventing white from playing their c5 break. } { [%csl Gc5] } (8... g6!? { Securing a KID. }) 9. Bd3 f4?! { Too early. Since white hasn't committed the king yet, the center tension should be maintained. } (9... g6!? $15) 10. h3?! { Seeking to avoid a Bg4 pin, but this move gives black something to bite at when they play an eventual g5-g4 push. } (10. Nd2!? Nc5 11. Bc2 g5 12. Qe2 $15 { This sequence of moves makes more sense to me as white. You still have time to castle queenside if black really wants to go all-in with g5-g4-f3. }) 10... Nc5 11. O-O? { Suicidal. Castling into the attack. Black now has a monster KID. } 11... a5! { Creating a support point on c5. In order to push this knight back, white must now play b3-a3-b4 which comes at a snail's pace. } 12. Na4 Nxa4!? { Not my personal preference, now it becomes a little easier to get play started on the queenside. } (12... b6!? 13. Nxc5 (13. a3 Bd7 14. Bc2 g5 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 Na6! (16... Nxa4? 17. Bxa4 Bc8 $16 { White will still eventually kick the knight out. This pawn transition favors white. }) 17. Qb1 h5 $17 { White's queenside play is irrelevant. Black is just going to mate on the kingside. }) 13... bxc5 $15) (12... Nxd3!? 13. Qxd3 b6! $15 { [%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5,Gg5g4] }) 13. Qxa4 Bd7 14. Qc2 Kh8? { Preparing Rg8 and the g pawn advance. But missing a crucial idea to stall white's play. } (14... b6! { Stops white's queenside aspirations and now the attack can play out. } 15. b3 Kh8 16. a3 g5 17. b4 h5 $17) 15. c5! { Now or never - white needs to get the play going. } 15... Qe8 16. c6!? (16. cxd6!? { Makes less sense with the queen on the c file. } 16... cxd6 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. Qb3 $14 { Still. Black's attack hasn't kicked off yet. }) 16... bxc6 17. dxc6 { [%cal Gd7c6,Gf1c1] } 17... Bc8 { Black is temporarily kicked back, but the c file is now blocked from white's rooks. Play will quickly transition to the kingside. } { [%cal Gc2a4,Gd3c4,Gc4d5] } (17... Bxc6? 18. Rfc1 Bd7 19. Qxc7) 18. Rab1?! { Very slow. } (18. Qa4!? { [%cal Gd3c4,Gc4d5] }) 18... Qg6!? { Piece play instead of pawn play. Interesting choice by black. } { [%cal Gc8h3] } (18... g5! $17 { The normal thing is probably correct. } { [%cal Gh7h5,Gg5g4] }) 19. Kh1 Qh6 { [%cal Gc8h3] } 20. Qe2 (20. Nh2!? $10 { Saves a tempo on the game since it's not clear the queen belongs on e2. }) 20... g5 (20... Bxh3?? 21. gxh3 Qxh3+ 22. Nh2 $18 { Qg4 is coming next and there is no attack. }) 21. Nh2 Rg8 22. Ng4 { Desperately trying to block the g file, but this is only a temporary block. h5 is coming. Meanwhile no queenside improvements have been made. } 22... Qg6 { Black returns to the pawn storm, and is probably now better. } 23. b4 axb4 24. Rxb4 Be7! { Maintaining the bishop so h5 cannot be stalled with Nxf6. } 25. f3 h5 26. Nf2 g4 { Pushes through. But the mass exchange of pieces ends up favoring white because now black at least cannot checkmate. } 27. fxg4 hxg4 28. Nxg4 Bxg4?! (28... Qh5! { A clear improvement. } 29. Nh2 Qxe2! 30. Bxe2 d5! $17 { [%cal Ge7b4,Gd5e4] }) 29. Qxg4 Qxg4 (29... Qh6!? 30. Qe2 Rg3 31. Rb7? Rag8! 32. Rxc7? (32. Rb2!? d5!! { Engine line } 33. exd5 f3! 34. Rxf3 Rxf3 35. Qxf3 e4! 36. Bxe4 (36. Qxe4 Qc1+ $19) 36... Qc1+ $19) 32... Qg5! 33. Rf2 Rxh3+! $19) 30. hxg4 Rxg4 31. Rb7 Bd8? { Passively defending yes, but this is just not the way to win a chess game. } (31... d5!! { Engine move though refutes this Rb7 idea. } 32. Rf3! (32. exd5?? Rh4+ 33. Kg1 Bc5+ $19) (32. Rxc7?? Rh4+ 33. Kg1 Bc5+ $19) 32... Rh4+ 33. Rh3 Rxh3+ 34. gxh3 Bd6 35. exd5 Rxa2 $17) 32. Bc4 Kg7 33. Rfb1 Kf8? (33... Rg3!? 34. Rb8 Rxb8 35. Rxb8 Rc3 36. Bd5 Bh4 $10 { Note the difference between putting the king on the back rank. The bishop is free to move with no fear of a deadly pin on the 8th rank. }) 34. Rb8! { Highly committal to trade the great b7 rook for the bad a8 rook. Played with the intention of suffocating black's pieces on the back rank. } 34... Rxb8 35. Rxb8 Ke7 36. a4 Rg3! { Black is just in time to prevent the pawn from queening. If white blocks as in the game, we get to a drawn opposite colored bishop ending. } 37. Rb3?? { I can't believe white would trade into OCBs and instantly allow black to equalize. } (37. a5! { The obvious move is completely winning: } 37... Ra3 38. a6 d5!? (38... Ra1+?! 39. Kh2 Ra4 40. g4!! $18 { Black is basically in zugzwang as he cannot take the c4 bishop. Just get your king up and the game is over. } (40. Kh3! $18)) 39. exd5 e4 40. d6+! cxd6 41. Rb7+ Kf6 42. c7 $18) (37. Bb3!? Rc3 38. Bd5! (38. a5? Rxc6! 39. Ra8 Rc3 $15) 38... Ra3 39. Ra8 $16) 37... Rxb3 38. Bxb3 d5! { The only way to activate the king and allow him to stop the a pawn. Otherwise, Bd5 would have allowed white to win. Presumably white missed this idea when he traded rooks. } 39. exd5 Kd6 40. a5 Kc5 41. a6 Kb6 42. Bc4 { The opposite colored bishop ending is hopelessly drawn. } 42... Be7 43. Kg1 Bd6 44. Kf2 Ka7 45. g3 fxg3+ 46. Kxg3 $10 *


