1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 b6 3. e3?! { Why block your bishop's natural diagonal? } (3. c4!? $10) (3. Bf4!?) 3... Bb7 4. Bd3 e6 5. Nbd2 { Instead of c4, white is aiming for e4. } (5. c4 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 $10 { Transposes directly into a Nimzo, I believe. }) 5... c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. O-O Bd6? { Too fanciful. Either d5 or Be7 was much better. There is no immediate attack on white's king. } (7... Be7!? $10) (7... d5!? $10) 8. e4! cxd4 9. cxd4 { White threatens e5, so there is no time for Nb4. } 9... Be7 10. a3 { Maintains white's killer bishop in case black castles. } 10... h5? { Black is still under the delusion they they are the ones attacking. But now black's king is stuck in the center without any shelter. White's center is imposing. } (10... O-O 11. e5 Nd5 $14) 11. b4 Qc7?! { Open file... you're going to get hit with Rc1. } 12. Bb2 Rg8? { Further compounding black's problems. } (12... d5!? { Probably black's best try is to make a claim in the center. } 13. e5! { But now we're in a French with a poor LSB on b7. }) (12... O-O-O? 13. Rc1 Kb8 14. b5 $18) (12... d6!? { Holding firm and going for a hedgehog makes some sense, but the queen is misplaced on c7. } 13. Rc1 $16) 13. Rc1 { [%cal Gb4b5] } 13... a6 14. Re1 { White's pieces are maximized and so must do something to open up the center immediately so as to punish black's play. } 14... g5 15. g3? { White blinks. This is unnecessary, and allow black to open up white's king immediately with h4. } (15. d5! { Certainly thematic. } 15... g4 16. Nd4 exd5 (16... Nxd4? { [%cal Gc1c7] } 17. Rxc7 $18) 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Nf5! $18) (15. b5!? axb5 16. Bxb5 g4 17. Ne5 { Another interesting way to react to black's pseudo-threats on the kingside. }) 15... h4 16. e5 Nd5 17. g4 $14 { Presumably this is white's idea. But now the center is not going to be opened up any time soon. White still maintains an advantage, but it's not as much as it was a few moves back. } *


