{ NN - Pam, 1997 }
1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 3. e4 d6 4. d4 Bg7 5. Be2 { Black transitions from the English into a mainline KID } 5... O-O 6. Bg5!? { The Averbakh variation. Temporarily stopping e5 } (6. Nf3!?) 6... Na6 { The knight heads to c5. The hole on c5 doesn't exist yet, so e5 is needed to utilize this move effectively. } 7. Qd2 e5 8. d5 Qe8 { Gets out of the pin, but the queen is somewhat awkward on e8. Black guns immediately for f5. } 9. f3 { Played in expectation of the incoming f5 strike. } 9... Nh5 10. Be3 f5 11. O-O-O { White was already hinting that he would castle queenside by not developing the kingside knight. However, now black has a well-defined target with this king on the queenside. c6 (and maybe b5) will be used to open up the queenside and attack white before white can get in h4-h5 ideas himself. } 11... Nf4! { Black does not mind sacrificing a pawn in order to get rid of white's dark squared bishop and open up the eyes of his own bishop. } 12. g3?! (12. Bf1! $14 { The other alternative to defend g2, and prepare g3, seems safer. }) (12. Bxf4? exf4 13. Qxf4?? { Even if this doesn't lose the pawn back, this type of pawn grab would be unthinkable. The poor dark squares are fully black's forever. } 13... fxe4! 14. Qxe4 $17) 12... Ng2!? (12... Nxe2+!? 13. Ngxe2 fxe4 14. fxe4 Bh3 $10 { Another alternative where the light squares end up really hurting white on the kingside. I don't think white can be better here. }) 13. Bf2 { White tries to maintain the bishop, but it won't be possible. } 13... f4!? { The point of Ng2. Closes down the center, but giving the e3 square to the knight is crucial to avoid losing a piece. } (13... fxe4!? 14. Nxe4 Bf5 15. Bd3! (15. Bf1?? Qa4! 16. Kb1 Bxe4+ 17. fxe4 Rxf2! 18. Qxf2?? Qxd1#) 15... Qa4 16. Nc3 Qa5 17. Bf1?! (17. Bxf5! Rxf5 18. Kb1 $16 { The remains trapped, even though it cannot be attacked. }) 17... Nb4! 18. g4 Qxa2!! 19. gxf5 (19. Nxa2?? Nxa2#) 19... Qa1+ 20. Nb1 c5! { Defending the knight, fixing c4 as a hook, and preparing e4! bringing more pieces into the attack. } 21. Bxg2 e4! 22. fxe4 b5! 23. cxb5 Nd3+ 24. Kc2 c4! $19) 14. Bf1 Ne3 { The knight is now simply too strong to ignore. At least this doesn't open up the g7-bishop's eyes as well. } 15. Bxe3 fxe3 16. Qxe3 { The dust has settled, and white is a clear pawn up, but with no dark squares. If black can activate the dragon bishop on g7, or use the bishop pair to launch a queenside attack, they will be standing well. As-is, the position is probably slightly better for white. A pawn is a pawn. } 16... Nc5 { The knight reaches the beautiful outpost on c5 } 17. Bh3! { White seeks to trade off his terrible bishop caught inside the pawn chain with black's good bishop. Also gets rid of the bishop pair. } (17. h4!? { Just getting on with h4-h5 and playing this position as if white isn't up the extra pawn makes sense too. }) 17... Na4?! { Black trades off their great knight for white's strong defender. This trade allows b5 to come quickly. Personally I think I would have favored a6 immediately as a way to open up the queenside. } (17... Bxh3!? 18. Nxh3 a6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 19. Ng5 Bh6! 20. h4 b5 $10) (17... a6!? 18. Bxc8 Qxc8 19. h4 b5 $10) 18. Kb1!? { It makes sense to place the king on the safer square of b1. It also makes sense not to invite the queen close to your king. However, the white queen is doing a good job stopping Bh6 and simultaneously influencing the queenside from its e3 post. So I'm not sure if this is the most precise move. } (18. Nxa4!? Qxa4 19. Qb3 $14 { is the other main alternative. Trading queens favors white, so this probably was a better choice, winning a tempo over the game continuation. }) 18... Nxc3+ 19. Qxc3 Bh6! { Black now has a free hand to activate their bishop. } 20. Bxc8 Rxc8!? (20... Qxc8!? { Swinging out to a6 after a6+b5 is achieved. }) 21. h4 c6 { Black continues the queenside assault. } 22. Nh3!? { Heading for g5 where it will block the diagonal of black's strong bishop. } (22. dxc6!? Rxc6 (22... bxc6? 23. Rxd6 $16) 23. Rd5 a6 24. Nh3 b5 $10) (22. Ne2!? $14 { A la Shirov's dragon game in 2021. White can use the knight to better defend on the queenside, and allocate the rest of the major pieces for more exciting tasks. }) (22. Qd3!? { Just getting out of the pin is smart too. }) 22... cxd5!? { A contentious move, trying to get in play immediately on the c file. } (22... b5? 23. cxb5 cxd5 24. Qb3! $16 { Unfortunately this doesn't rip open the files for black fast enough to matter. White is just up a pawn here. }) 23. exd5? { Pawns aren't people... this move kills all of white's play in the center and gives black two interesting pawn breaks to choose from. } (23. Rxd5! $14 { Clearly superior. Pressures the backward d pawn, prepares to double, and stops b5. } { [%cal Gd5d6,Gh1d1] }) (23. cxd5?? Rxc3 $19) 23... e4!! { Black insists on ripping open the long diagonal. While the bishop is good on h6, it's even better on the long diagonal aiming straight for white's king. } (23... b5!? $10 { The other thematic break in the position is also probably strong. }) 24. f4!? { f4 seeks to keep things closed and utilize the knight more effectively on g5. But does white really want to keep the kingside closed? } (24. Rde1!? Rxf3! (24... Bg7!?) 25. Qxf3 exf3 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Rf1 Re3 28. Ng5 $10) 24... b5! { Black insists on opening up the queenside as well. This idea is only possible because of the earlier Na4 maneuver. } 25. Qb4?! { Aiming for the d6 pawn, but now white is just playing with their pretty piece. } (25. c5?! Rxc5 $17 { Keeps the b file closed, so b2 is less of a target. But now it's clear that white cannot claim any advantage. }) (25. Ng5!? { The knight heads to e6, where it might honestly be better than the g7 bishop. } 25... Rxc4 (25... bxc4?! 26. Ne6! $14 { The octopus arrives! }) 26. Qe3 { Another variation where the b file remains closed. The immediate threat of Ne6 prevents black from keeping the bishop. } 26... Bxg5!? (26... Qc8? 27. Ne6 Rf7 28. h5! $16) 27. hxg5 Qf7 $15) 25... bxc4! { The b file is the actual file black wants to attack on. } 26. Qxd6 { White has a strong passed pawn, but their king is incredibly exposed to black's major pieces. } 26... Qb5! { Logically eying the weak b2 pawn and preventing white's queen from defending. Black is ready to generate a strong attack with the bishop and remaining pieces. } 27. Qe6+ Kh8 28. Ng5!? (28. Rh2!? Bg7 29. Qxe4 Rb8 30. Qc2 $17 { White is still holding on, but not allowing c3 as a fork. But every black piece is better than every white piece. }) 28... Rb8! { Black is ready to sacrifice the exchange because every remaining black piece is killing white's king on b2. } 29. Rd2 Bg7 30. Nf7+ (30. Rhh2?! c3 31. b3? cxd2 $19) 30... Rxf7 { The obvious continuation. White is toast. } 31. Qxf7 Bxb2 { Black cashes in now and the white king is too exposed to survive. } 32. Rc2 Bc3+ $19 33. Kc1!? (33. Rb2!? Qxb2#) 33... Qb1# *


