1. b4! { Takes advantage of the pin in order to get rid of white's weakest pawn. } 1... c4 (1... Kf8!? 2. bxc5 bxc5 3. Kd3 $14) 2. b5!? { White transitions from isolation to destruction. The c4 pawn is the target. } 2... Kf7 (2... Ba3! { Averbakh's suggested improvement does appear to almost draw by getting all of black's pieces as active as possible. } 3. Rc2 c3! { Ditching the pawn for maximum activity. } 4. Bxc3 (4. Nxc3?? Nb4! $19) 4... Bb4 5. Kd2 (5. Kd3?! Bxc3 6. Nxc3?? Nb4+ $19) 5... Rc4 6. Bxb4!? (6. Kd3!? Rxe4 7. Kxe4 Nxc3+ 8. Kd4 Nxa4 9. Rc4 Bc5+ 10. Ke5 Nb2 11. Rc2 Nd3+ 12. Kxe6 Nb4 13. Rd2 a5 14. bxa6 Nxa6 $14) 6... Rxe4 7. Bd6 Rxa4 8. f3 g5 9. e4 $14 { The bishop remains stronger than the night here though. And temporarily, white's one b pawn is holding up black's two. }) 3. Bc3 { Cuts off the king. Moreover, white is fine entering into a good knight vs bad bishop endgame due to the structural weaknesses on the board. } 3... Ba3 4. Rc2 Nxc3+ 5. Rxc3 Bb4 6. Rc2 Ke7 7. Nd2 { Seeking to win the c4 pawn directly. Again, there's no issues for white entering a purely rook endgame because of the two weaknesses on e6 and c4. } 7... c3 { Now that the pawn has been goaded forward, the white king can help out in destroying it. } (7... Kd6?! 8. Rxc4 Rxc4 9. Nxc4+ Kd5 10. Kd3 $16 { White is much better. }) (7... Bxd2?! 8. Kxd2 Kd6 9. Kc3 Kc5 10. Rd2! $16 { Rd7 or Rd4, wins the game. }) 8. Ne4! { Blocks the black king from entering the position further and allows for Kd3. } 8... Ba5 (8... Kd7?? 9. Nf6+) (8... Kf7? 9. Ng5+ { White will win a pawn either way if black tries to activate their king. }) (8... Rc7!? { I think this is a stronger waiting move than Ba5. Once white transitions to the kingside, black will want to have a more active bishop that can return to the action immediately. } 9. Kd3 Rd7+ 10. Kc4 { But perhaps it loses a pawn immediately, regardless. }) 9. Kd3 Rd8+ 10. Kc4 Rd1! { Black tries to get active in exchange for the c pawn. } (10... Rd2!? 11. Kb3! { Black's temporary flash doesn't amount to anything as long as white keeps his cool. } 11... Kd7 12. Nxc3 $16) (10... Rc8+?! 11. Kb3 $16 { Now, Nxc3 is unstoppable. }) 11. Nxc3 Rh1?! (11... Bxc3! 12. Kxc3 Rh1? (12... g5! $14 { "all rook endgames are drawn" - here, white is struggling to get the rook active since black keeps white's king away from the center. }) 13. Kd4! { Clinical, as in the game. } (13. h3?! { I played this move 4 years ago, but it's a real "pawns are people" move } 13... Rg1? (13... Rd1! $14) 14. g4 Rh1 15. Kd4! Rxh3 16. Ke5 Kd7 17. Rd2+ Ke7 18. Rd6 $18 { White's active king and rook spell black's doom. }) 13... Rxh2 14. Rc7+ Kd6 15. Rxa7 Rxg2 16. Rxh7 Rxf2? (16... Rg4+! 17. e4 e5+ 18. Kd3 Kc5 19. Re7 $16) 17. Rb7 $18) 12. Ne4 Rxh2? { Greedily snags a pawn, but now white's king enters with anger. } (12... Rd1! $16 { Everyone is falling for the lie that pawns are people. }) 13. Kd4! Kd7 (13... Rxg2? 14. Rc7+ Kf8 15. Rxh7 $16 { Black cannot allow his king to get cutoff so completely. }) 14. g3!? (14. Ke5! Rxg2 15. Nf6+ Ke7 (15... Kd8 16. Kxe6 $16 { Going for mate next! }) 16. Rc7+ Kd8 17. Rd7+! (17. Rxh7!? Bc3+ 18. Kd6!! Bxf6 19. Rf7 { [%cal Gf7f8,Gf7f6] } 19... Kc8 20. Rxf6 $18) 17... Kc8 18. Kxe6 Rxf2 19. Ne4! Rf8 20. Nd6+ Kb8 21. Rb7+ Ka8 22. Rxh7 $18 { Morin's winning line. }) 14... Bb4 { Trying to activate the bishop and return it to the action. } 15. Ke5 Rh5+ 16. Kf6! { The white king penetrates completely. } 16... Be7+ 17. Kg7 e5 18. Rc6 { Stopping Ke6. White has a compact structure on the kingside with the strong knight defending everything, so he transitions to winning a piece/going after the queenside pawns now. } 18... Rh1!? { Looking for counterplay against white's queenside pawns. But it's too slow. } 19. Kf7 Ra1 20. Re6 { [%csl Ge7,Gf6,Gg5,Gh4] } 20... Bd8 21. Rd6+ Kc8 (21... Kc7?? 22. Ke8! $18) 22. Ke8 { [%csl Ge7,Gf6,Gg5,Gh4] } 22... Bc7 23. Rc6 Rd1 (23... Rxa4? 24. Ng5! h5?! (24... Kb7!? 25. Ne6 Bb8 26. Nd8+! Ka8 27. Rc8 a5 28. Nc6! $18 { [%csl Gb8] }) 25. Ne6 $18 { White tracks down this piece so quickly. } { [%csl Gc7] }) 24. Ng5 { [%csl Ge6] } 24... Rd8+ 25. Kf7 Rd7+ 26. Kg8 { Black resigned here as trading pieces allows a completely winning king and pawn endgame. } 26... h5!? 27. Ne6! Kb7?! (27... e4!? 28. Ng5! (28. Rxc7+?? Rxc7 29. Nxc7 Kxc7 { White can no longer play f4 and freeze the kingside pawns! } 30. Kg7 g5! 31. Kg6 h4! $19) 28... Rd5 29. Rxg6 $16 { Good enough for a win though. }) 28. Nxc7 Rxc7 29. Rxc7+! (29. Rxg6?! Rc2 30. Rg7+ Kb8 31. Rg5 Rxf2 32. Rxh5 Rf3 33. Rxe5 Rxg3+ $18 { Winning, but potentially holdable. }) 29... Kxc7 30. f4! exf4 31. exf4 $18 { A clear victory for white. No passed pawn can be created for black, so white simply munches on the kingside pawns and pushes the f pawn for a touchdown. } *


