{ Petrosian - Spassky, 1969. }
1. c4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nf3 Be7!? { Avoids the Bg5 exchange lines. } (3... Nf6!? 4. Nc3!? { Main line QGD, going for Bg5 next. } (4. cxd5!? exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Bg5 { QGD exchange })) 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bg5 { The main line QGD } 5... O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 (7. Bh4!? b6 $10) 7... Bxf6 { Avoids the Tartakower variation. } 8. Qd2 { A move that came to the forefront due to the Karpov - Kasparov match in 1985. Ben Finegold always liked this move. The most testing tries for black rely upon achieving e5 pawn break now instead of c5. } 8... b6 { As soon as a move is "wasted" to activate the light squared bishop, white is fine exchanging on d5 } 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4! { Clamps down on the freeing c5 break. As long as white can stop that break, there will be a perpetual weakness on the queenside for the major pieces to target. } 10... Bb7!? { Does the bishop really belong on this square? Black needs to watch out for b5 and a clamp on the c file. } (10... Ba6?! 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. b5 Nb8 $14 { In this circumstance, black is still too passive. White's pressure on the backward c pawn will be too quick. }) (10... Be6!? { A la the famous Tartakower game between Fischer and Spassky is probably best. }) 11. Rb1 c6! { c6 is needed to prevent white's b5. Now, b5 can be met with c5 and black will have hanging pawns instead of a backward c pawn. } 12. Bd3 (12. b5?! c5 13. dxc5 bxc5 $10 { Black's bishop pair is active here. }) 12... Nd7 13. O-O Re8 14. Rfc1 { [%csl Gc6] } 14... a5!? { Fearing perpetual pressure on c6, black lashes out with a5. That being said, this move doesn't necessarily stop said pressure. And it also allows pressure on the b pawn as well now. The benefit is that there is guaranteed pressure on a2 from black too. } 15. bxa5 (15. a3?! { Petrosian tried this earlier in the match. } 15... axb4 16. axb4 b5! $10 { Nc4 will come and there's no chance for white to be better. } { [%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] }) 15... Rxa5 16. Bf5 { Threatens b6. } 16... Ra6 17. Rb3 g6 18. Bd3 (18. Bh3!? $14 { Suggested as an improvement after the game. Maintaining pressure on the knight and therefore b6. }) 18... Ra7 19. Rcb1 { From here, black is trying to get in the freeing c5 break while trying to maintain the c and b pawns. e4 can be good for white under some circumstances as well. White on the other hand is trying to exert maximum pressure on both b6 and c6, while stopping the c5 break and any pressure on a2. White wants to trade off all minor pieces but black's dark squared bishop. } 19... Bg7?! (19... Kg7!? $10 { Also allows for a possible Bd8->c7 reroute in the future. }) 20. a4 Qe7 21. Bf1 Ba6?! { Black is happy to trade off its bad bishop for white's good bishop. But it comes at the cost of perpetually weakening c6. Probably this trade doesn't benefit black though who needs to generate some counterplay on the kingside. } { [%csl Gc6,Gb6] } (21... Rea8!? $10 { Leaving more tension in the position. }) 22. h4! Bxf1 23. Rxf1 h5!? { Stopping white from clamping down on the kingside with h5 themselves, but now white gets the g5 square to mess with too. } (23... Raa8!? 24. h5 g5 (24... gxh5?! $14 { Knife f5 is gonna hurt at some point. }) 25. Nh2 $10 { [%cal Gh2g4] }) 24. Re1!? { Playing with the idea of an e4 break too. } (24. Rfb1!?) 24... Raa8 25. g3 Qd6 26. Kg2 { I imagine this position remains level. At this point, black needs to find more active ways to generate counterplay against a4 or on the kingside. } 26... Kf8?! (26... Ra5!? 27. Reb1 Qb8 28. Qd1 Bf6 29. R3b2 Bd8 30. Rc2 Qa8! 31. Ne2!? Rxa4 32. Rbc1 c5 $10 { One sample line where black is playing actively. }) 27. Reb1 Kg8?! { The knight on d7 stabilizes the b6 pawn, while the c3 knight blocks any pressure on c6. But this passive defense cannot work with so many pieces on the board. } 28. Qd1 Bf8 29. R3b2 Bg7 30. Rc2 Ra7 31. Rbc1 Nb8 32. Ne2! { Direct pressure on the c pawn. } 32... Rc7?! { The most passive way to defend though... } (32... Rxa4? 33. Rxc6 Nxc6 34. Qxa4 $16 { White is more than happy to trade their a4 weakness for the heart of black's queenside structure. }) (32... Rc8!? $10 { At least white needs to be kept honest about the a4 pawn here. }) 33. Qd3 Ra7 34. Qb3 Ra6 35. Nf4 Rd8 36. Nd3 { White has achieved the dream setup in the Carlsbad, so the position is probably already gone now for black. } 36... Bf8 37. Nfe5 Rc8 38. Rc3 Be7 39. Nf4 Bf6 40. Ned3?! { White does not want to change the pawn structure and allow Bxe5, but misses a winning shot. } (40. Nxc6! Rxc6 41. Rxc6 Nxc6 42. Qb5! $16 Nb8?! (42... Nb4!? 43. Rc8+ Kg7!? (43... Bd8!? 44. Qe8+ Qf8 45. Qxf8+ Kxf8 46. Rxd8+ $16) 44. Qe8 $18) (42... Ra5!? 43. Qxc6 Qxc6 44. Rxc6 Kg7 45. Rxb6 Rxa4 $16) 43. Rc8+ Kg7 44. Rxb8! Qxb8 45. Qxa6 $18) 40... Ra5?! { Black believes they will be fine trading off the a and b pawns. But in reality, this leads to tactics on black's undefended pieces that only favor white. } 41. Qxb6 Rxa4 42. Rc5 Ra6 43. Rxd5!! Qxf4!? (43... Rxb6!? 44. Rxd6 $16) (43... Qxd5+?! 44. Nxd5 Rxb6 45. Nxb6 $18) 44. Qxa6! Qe4+ (44... Nxa6 45. Nxf4 $18 { [%cal Gc1c8] }) 45. f3! Qe6 (45... Qxd5?? 46. Qxc8+ Qd8 47. Qxd8+ Bxd8 48. Ne5 $18) (45... Qxe3?? 46. Qxc8+ $18) 46. Qc4! Qxe3 (46... cxd5? 47. Qxc8+ Kg7 48. Qxe6 fxe6 $18) 47. Ne5!! { [%cal Gf6e5,Gd5e5] } 47... Rf8 (47... cxd5? 48. Qxc8+ $18) 48. Rc5!? { Finally white saves the rook. } (48. Rd6!? Kg7 49. Rxf6! Kxf6 50. Rb1 $18 { [%cal Gb1b8] }) 48... Be7 49. Rb1!! { [%cal Ge3d2,Gg2h3] } 49... Bxc5 50. Rxb8 $18 { Black resigned here. } 50... Rxb8?? (50... Bxd4?? 51. Qxf7+! Kh8 52. Nxg6#) (50... Qd2+!? 51. Kh3 $18 { The checks run out and white clearly wins in all variations. } 51... Kh7 52. Rxf8 Bxf8 53. Qxf7+ Bg7 54. Qxg6+ Kg8 55. Qe8+ Kh7 56. Qxh5+ Qh6 57. Qxh6+ Bxh6 58. Nxc6 $18) (50... Qxd4?! 51. Qxf7+! Kh8 52. Nxg6#) 51. Qxf7+ Kh8 52. Nxg6# *


