1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Be7 (4... Bc5!? { probably the more common main move }) 5. O-O O-O 6. c3 d6 7. Re1!? Bg4?! { This walks into the thematic h3+Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver, after which white gains a tempo. Especially because white is not gunning for d4 in this variation, Bg4 will prove to be a waste of a move. } (7... Na5! 8. Bb5 a6 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bc2 c5 $10 { Directly transposing to the Ruy Lopez d3 main lines, where black has been doing reasonably well. }) (7... a6!? { Threatening Na5, } 8. Bb3! $10 { Keeping the two bishops. }) 8. h3 Bh5 9. Nbd2 Re8 10. Nf1 a6 { With the threat of Na5 to win the light-squared bishop. Instinctively I would have played Bb3 so that on Na5 I have Bc2. Only then would I play Ng3. } 11. Ng3?! { Rushing to win the bishop pair, but this is mistimed. } (11. Bb3! Na5 12. Bc2 c5 13. Ng3 Bg6 $14 { The aforementioned tempo. }) 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Na5! { So white does not retain the bishop pair after all. } 13. Bg5?! { Allowing the "weakening" Nxc4 does have some perks. d5 will remain very difficult for black to achieve, and there might be pressure down the d file if the c pawn ever moves. But this bishop move doesn't threaten anything and can immediately be answered with h6. } (13. Bd5!! c6?! (13... Nxd5!? 14. exd5 $16 { And the a5 knight is trapped, unless concessions are made on the queenside. }) 14. Bxf7+! Kxf7 15. b4! $16 { A brilliant way to avoid losing the bishop for nothing. }) (13. Bb3!? Nxb3 14. axb3 { This is a better pawn transformation than what happened in the game. } 14... Bf8 { [%cal Gd6d5] } 15. Bg5 $14) 13... Nxc4!? { Committal, but probably not bad. } (13... h6! 14. Bxf6 (14. Be3 $10 { According to Silman, this was the point of Bg5, provoking h6 which might be a weakness. I don't really buy it. }) 14... Bxf6 $14 { Black has almost equalized, but the signs are all there to achieve the good knight vs bad DSB endgame. }) 14. dxc4 Qd7?! { Slowly inching the queen into the defense on the kingside. Not a fan. } (14... h6!? { Probably the last chance to remove white's kingside attackers before they destroy us. But now white is happy to achieve a good knight vs bad bishop endgame. } 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nf5 $14 { Nd5 is playable if desired as well. }) (14... Nd7!? 15. Be3 Bg5! $10 { Trading the correct minor piece off is also better. }) 15. Nf5 Qe6 { At least the queen is off the d file, but white has some amount of threats on the kingside. And h6 can now always be met with Bxh6! } 16. b3 { Solidifying c4, and asking black - how are you going to untangle? } 16... Bd8? { This move accomplishes worse than nothing. Now there's no Bf8 in order to defend the kingside. } (16... b5!? 17. cxb5 axb5 $14 { Getting more play on the a file. }) (16... h6?? 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18. Qg3+ $18) 17. Bh6! { Launching a huge kingside attack, now that the safe Bf8 is off the cards. } 17... gxh6 (17... g6? 18. Ng7 $16 { [%cal Gg7e6,Gg7e8] }) 18. Qg3+ Ng4 { Forced. } (18... Kh8?? 19. Qg7#) (18... Kf8?? 19. Qg7#) 19. Qxg4+ Qg6 20. Nxh6+ Kf8 21. Nf5 Qxg4?! { Black does better to maintain the tension as a queen trade on black's terms would repair the kingside weaknesses. Opening the h file doesn't seem smart. We now end up in a good knight vs bad bishop endgame, where white's up a pawn. Completely winning. } 22. hxg4 Bg5 23. Rad1 Rad8 (23... b5!? 24. Rd5! (24. cxb5?! axb5 25. Re2 { Too much activity for black. }) 24... bxc4 25. bxc4 Rab8 26. c5! $16 { Using the doubled pawns as a force for good. White's already breaking through. }) 24. g3 Rd7 25. Kg2 Red8 { Already, black should be on the lookout for their bishop being trapped. It's incredibly low on squares. } 26. Rh1 Kg8 27. Rh5 f6 { The bishop is now trapped. Once f4 is supported, black will be forced to lose the piece. } (27... Bf6?! 28. Rdh1 $18) 28. Rhh1 c6 29. Rhf1 $18 { f4 is unstoppable, and the bishop is trapped. } 29... Re8!? 30. f4 exf4 31. gxf4 Rxe4 32. Kg3! (32. fxg5?! Rxg4+ 33. Kf3 Rxg5 $18 { And a little more work must be done. }) 32... Bxf4+ 33. Rxf4 Re2 34. Rf2 Rxf2 35. Kxf2 $18 { Cleanly up a piece. } *


