{ The game played by Silman's friend in 1974 that he ended up putting into the 4th edition of Reassess Your Chess. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 (5. c4!? { My personal preference is to force black into a Maroczy bind. }) 5... Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Be2?! { The old, slow move. } (7. Bc4! { The only critical try } 7... O-O 8. Bb3 Re8!? (8... d5!? $14 { This crazy pawn sac was played by agedwhitecheddar in the Austin 90+30 tournament. }) 9. f3 e6 { Preparing a quick d5, but: } 10. f4! d6 11. Ndb5 Re7! 12. Qd2! (12. Nxd6? Rd7 $15) 12... Rd7 13. O-O-O d5 14. e5 Ng4 15. Nd4 (15. Bg1?! Bh6! $10) 15... Bh6!? (15... Nxe3!? 16. Qxe3 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 $14 { Gets us into a French where it's a bit unclear if black is doing well or not. Both sides pieces are misplaced. }) 16. h4!! Ncxe5 17. h5! Nc4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. hxg6 fxg6 20. Qe2 e5 21. Rxh6 exd4 22. Qxg4 Qe8 23. Bxd4 Rxd4 24. Qf3 Rxd1+ 25. Nxd1 Qf7 26. Rh1 Be6 27. Re1 Bd5 28. Qf2 Re8 29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. Qd2 Bc6 31. g4 $10 { Potrata, Janko - Ingersol, Harry, 1/2-1/2, WLS/SRCCC/19/D1 (WLS), 2019, https://lichess.org/P5iEH8wG }) 7... O-O { [%cal Gd7d5] } 8. Qd2?! { The whole point of the accelerated dragon is that they wish to get in d5 in one go. Now black is totally fine here after the thematic: } (8. Nb3! { Correct. Preventing d5. } 8... d6 9. O-O Be6 10. f4 Na5 11. f5 Bc4 12. Nxa5 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qxa5 14. g4?! Rac8! 15. g5 Rxc3! 16. gxf6 Rxe3 17. Qxe3 Bxf6 $10 { A line given by Silman showcasing the power of sacrificing the exchange. }) 8... d5! (8... d6 { Transitions back into the normal dragon. }) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 Ng4 { And black is more than fine here. } 11. Bxg4 Bxg4 12. h3 Bf5 13. g4 Be6 { White is now committed to an all-out attack on the black king, but his own king isn't yet safe. } (13... Bxe5! 14. gxf5 d4 $17) 14. Qd4?! { Centralizes the queen and defends the e5 pawn, but does nothing about the king being in the center. } { [%cal Gg7d4] } (14. f4 $10 { Clearly correct. }) 14... f6! { Cracks at the center while white's king is stuck in the center. } 15. f4 Qc7! 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Qc5 Bh4+! { White's king never had time to castle and must now stay stuck in the center for good. } (17... d4! { A more direct way to go in straight for the kill. } 18. Bxd4 Qxf4 19. Bxf6 Rxf6 20. Ne2 Qe4! $19 21. O-O-O?! Qxe2 $19) 18. Ke2 Bc8! { Retreating move to activate the bishop on a better diagonal in an all-out attack on the king. } { [%cal Gc8a6] } 19. Nxd5 { Takes an important pawn due to the undefended queen, but opens up the center more... } 19... Ba6+ 20. c4 Qb7! { Gets out of the pin and targets b2 with check, "forcing" this clumsy retreat } { [%csl Gb2] } 21. Nb4 e5!! { The king deserves to die in the center. } 22. Nxa6 (22. Qxe5? Bxc4+ 23. Kd2 Qxb4+ $19) (22. fxe5? Be7! $19) 22... exf4!! (22... Qxb2+! 23. Bd2 Rxf4 $19 { Also good, but much less pretty. }) 23. Bd4 (23. Nb4?? fxe3 { [%csl Gf2] }) 23... Rae8+ { All pieces are participating in the attack now, even though black is temporarily down a piece. } 24. Kf3 Re3+!! { The rook cannot be taken because it opens up the king too much. } 25. Kg2 (25. Bxe3?! fxe3+ 26. Kxe3? (26. Ke4!? Re8+ 27. Kd3 Qxb2! $19 { [%cal Gb2d2] }) (26. Ke2!? Qxb2+ $19) (26. Kg2? Qxb2+ 27. Kg1 Qf2#) 26... Bf2+ $19) 25... f3+ 26. Kf1!? (26. Kg1!? Rfe8! $19) 26... Rfe8! 27. Kg1 (27. Bxe3? Qxb2! { White's king dies if white tries to take that rook again. } { [%csl Gg2,Ge2] }) 27... Bg3! { Bg3 covers any Rh2 lateral defense ideas in case white takes the rook. } { [%cal Ge3e1] } 28. Rf1 (28. Bxe3? Qxb2 $19 { Same mate threats. }) 28... Re1! { Removing the defender of the back rank. } 29. Bc3!? (29. Rxe1? Rxe1#) (29. Qa5!? Rxf1+ 30. Kxf1 Qe7! $19 { [%cal Ge7e2] }) 29... Qxb2!! $19 { The bishop is overloaded, and mate is unstoppable. } *


