{ Without even looking at the game itself, after 3 moves I could tell that this was going to be Morphy Opera game. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 Bg4?! { In order to maintain the central pawn, black has to give up the bishop pair in an open position and help white develop. } 4. dxe5 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 dxe5 6. Bc4 Nf6 (6... Qf6!? { Not what you want to do, but perhaps a better way to keep the position held together? } 7. Qb3 b6 (7... Nd7?! 8. Qxb7 Rb8 9. Qa6 Qxa6 10. Bxa6 $16 { Morphy is not a pawn grabber. }) 8. Nc3 c6 9. Nd5! cxd5 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Bg5! Qg6 (11... Qxg5 12. Bxc6+ Ke7 13. Bxa8 $18) 12. Qxd5 Rc8 13. O-O-O! $18 { [%cal Gd5d8] }) 7. Qb3 { Focuses in on both f7 and b7. } 7... Qe7 { Qe7 defends the more important f7 square, and plans to meet Qxb7 with Qb4+ (trading queens) and only going down a pawn. } 8. Nc3! { Never be greedy! More development and white is already way ahead in development ready to attack. } (8. Qxb7!? Qb4+ 9. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 10. c3 Bc5 11. f3 $16) 8... c6 { Black holds on to all the pawns now, but is way behind in development. } 9. Bg5 b5?? (9... Na6 { Maybe the last chance to keep it all together. Would Morphy really go in for a structural advantage of Bxa6? }) 10. Nxb5! cxb5 11. Bxb5+ { White happily sacrifices a piece in order to open up black further while his king is stuck in the center. } 11... Nbd7 12. O-O-O!! { The last pieces are now ready to play in this position as well. } 12... Rd8 13. Rxd7! Rxd7 14. Rd1 Qe6 15. Bxd7+ { White finishes off his opponent with style } 15... Nxd7 16. Qb8+! Nxb8 17. Rd8# *


