{ Larsen is white. }
1. g3 g6 2. Bg2 Bg7 3. e4 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O Nf6 6. d3 O-O 7. Re1 d6 8. Nbd2 Rb8! { Gets off the long diagonal (opposite the bishop) and prepares a b5 or b6 push. } 9. a4 { Stopping the more aggressive choice. } 9... b6!? (9... a6!? $10 { preparing b5 anyway }) 10. Nc4 Bb7 11. h4 Qc7 12. Bd2 { A passive developing move, but prepares to play Qc1 and Bh6 in a way that cannot be stopped (due to Nh5 or Ng4). } 12... Rbd8 13. Qc1 d5! { Black takes advantage of white's slow opening to break in the center with d5. } (13... Ng4!? { Black can play to calmly stop white's nonsense on the kingside too. } 14. Bh3?! f5 $17) 14. Bf4!? Qc8 { The queen is inconvenienced before the bishop trade occurs. } 15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Bh6 Rfe8 { Activates black's last piece and hopes to get in e5. } (16... Nf6!? $10 { Preventing h5 for good. }) 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. h5! { Now white cracks at black's kingside structure. } 18... Nf6?! (18... Ndb4!? 19. h6+ Kg8 $10 { The queen cannot so easily slide into the attack while the c pawn is falling. }) 19. h6+!? { Releases the tension, but allows for a huge thorn pawn to be installed near black's king. Attention is immediately turned to the queenside where progress can hopefully be made. } 19... Kg8 20. Qf4 Nh5 21. Qd2 { [%cal Gd2c3,Gc3g7] } 21... f6? { This ugly move is made with the hope of getting in e5 and further blocking in the long diagonal. But there's no way opening the light squares near your king can be correct. } 22. a5! b5 23. a6!! Ba8 (23... Bxa6?! 24. Na5 Nxa5 25. Qxa5 Bb7 26. Qxa7 { White wins back the pawn and has active queenside play on the a file. }) 24. Na5 e5 (24... Nxa5 25. Qxa5 { [%csl Gb5] } 25... Bc6 26. b4! { White continues to tear down the queenside. }) 25. Qc3 Nd4 { Black hopes to hold together the queenside (and trade off pieces) to reach a safe endgame. } (25... Nxa5?! 26. Rxa5 $16) (25... c4!? 26. dxc4 Nxa5 27. Rxa5 Qxc4 28. Qxc4+ bxc4 29. Rc5 Rc8 30. Rxc8 Rxc8 31. Rd1 $16) 26. Nb7!! { But white doesn't give black a moment to spare; Sacrificing the a pawn in order to open up the a file and g2 bishop with continued queenside play. } 26... Bxb7 27. axb7 Qxb7 28. Nxd4 cxd4 29. Bxb7 dxc3 30. bxc3 { When the dust settles, white has the superior minor piece, the queenside targets, and the more compact pawn structure. } 30... Re7 31. Rxa7 { And a pawn too! } 31... Kf8 (31... Rb8? 32. Bd5+! Kf8 33. Ra6 $18) 32. Rb1! $18 { Winning a second pawn and eventually the game. } *


